<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, May 3.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Kukes, Albania) _ It lasted no more than three
minutes, three minutes of savagery unleashed without even a word.
``They just started shooting and I got hit in the shoulder. The
dead bodies behind me pushed me over the cliff and into the stream.
I was lucky because all of the dead bodies fell on top of me.''
Isuf Zheniqi, who said he survived when 58 men died in a massacre
in southwestern Kosovo more than a month ago, speaks out
hesitantly, fearing Serbian forces might take revenge on members of
his family still in Kosovo. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK (Washington) _ The general running the campaign to
end the murder and expulsion of Kosovo's Albanians learned as an
adult that his grandfather was a Russian Jew who fled the pogroms a
century ago. A profile. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ Russia puts its prestige on
the line in trying to mediate the Kosovo conflict. By Michael
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REBELS (Bogota) _ Nearly six months ago, the Colombian
government ceded control of a Switzerland-sized area to the
country's main Marxist guerrilla group. But now with a
make-or-break talks scheduled for Monday, the rebels appear
reluctant to leave the zone. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CORSICA (Paris)_ Bombs and fires have long been common
tools for Corsica's separatists, but a recent explosion at a beach
restaurant appears to have been the work of the very crack police
squad that was created to stem the guerrilla violence. By Marlise
Simons.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-WOMEN-POLITICS (Chijarasi, India) _ Almost a million women
have been elected to village governing panels since India adopted a
constitutional amendment in 1993. Still expected to veil their
faces and submit to male elders, more and more women are now
challenging centuries-old, feudal hierarchies. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-INTERNET (Undated) _ Reports that the two students
involved in the shootings in Littleton, Colo., had played violent
computer games and that one of them had posted descriptions of
making pipe bombs on a Web site appear to have sharpened parents'
concerns over the online activities that are often the most
mysterious corners of their children's lives. For many, it was the
one checked item on a mental list of comparisons to those
responsible for the Colorado massacre. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-WORKERS (Washington) _ A study shows that low-wage
workers at companies with many high-wage workers are more likely to
have employer-provided health insurance than low-wage workers at
companies with few high-wage workers. That is, it's better to flip
hamburgers in the General Motors cafeteria than at McDonalds. By
Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-BALL-PROFILE _ Profile of Robert Ball, old lion and voice
of traditionalism in the Social Security debate. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHARITY-ADS-CRACKDOWN (Undated) _ Nonprofit organizations take
in roughly half a billion dollars a year for lending their good
names to the marketing of everything from nicotine patches to pain
relievers. The proliferation of such pitches, and the fact that
consumers may mistakenly believe they are endorsements, has come to
the attention of state regulators, and now 16 state attorneys
general want to stem the tide of ads. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   DISASTER-INDUSTRY (Undated) _ When a disaster like the Kosovo
crisis strikes, humanitarian agencies race to provide aid.
Supplying many of these groups is a growing disaster industry, a
loose network of brokers, wholesalers and companies who, for a
profit, can supply anything from drugs to cooking kits to armored
personnel carriers to concertina wire. It is a curious industry in
which salesmen drumming up business may stalk aid workers in
refugee camps and a good year in terms of disasters can mean
hundreds of millions of dollars. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-REFORMS (Undated) _ The year 2000 problem has cast in sharp
relief for the general public how dependent society is on computers
and how potentially dangerous programming errors can be. And that,
say some experts, could lead to reforms in the way computer
programs are written and maintained, just as a big earthquake often
leads to stronger building codes. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   VARIETY-REPORTER (Los Angeles) _ With its snappy headlinese and
vacuum-like reporting, Variety has owned the entertainment-news
turf for decades. Not anymore. Hollywood Reporter is making a
strong challenge. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-MUSIC (San Francisco) _ In a move involving two of the
leading digital-audio formats for the Internet _ MP3 and Real
Networks' G2 _ Real Networks on Monday will announce an alliance
with RCA to create music players that would further blur the
distinction between conventional audio CD's and computer files. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SEYMOUR-HERSH (Undated) _ The trial of the man accused of
selling the fake Kennedy papers has provided an unusually close-up
look at an investigative reporter, the celebrated and villified
Seymour Hersh, who testified at the trial. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-SECURITY (Undated) _ Analysts and executives agree
that a vast majority of E-commerce sites are secure, but some say
the trend may actually be heading in the opposite direction, as
companies rush past security issues in their zeal to establish a
Web site. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-VOTING (Undated) _ Though no states allow Internet
voting _ and few are even in the earliest stages of contemplating
it _ a handful of companies are hard at work building systems to
enable voters to cast ballots on line. By Rebecca Raney.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TRADEMARKS (Washington) _ The World Intellectual
Property Organization issues its report on protecting trademarks
against Internet domain-name squatters. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-BOOKSELLING (Los Angeles) _ Despite the boom in online
booksites, the sale of consumer books declines by 3 percent, the
first decline since 1990. Plus, other developments at the American
Bookseller's Convention. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-MEDIA (Undated) _ Column on the network coverage of
the Littleton massacre. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-AD-COL (Undated) _ Two agencies are joining the
growing chorus along Madison Avenue singing ``That's
Entertainment.'' By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-FOUNDATION (Undated) _ A new nonprofit foundation is formed
to finance innovative art shunned by the NEA. By Judith H.
Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KINGSLEY-PROFILE (Hollywood) _ Profile of Pat Kingsley, the
doyenne of Hollywood publicity. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   BERGER-RACE (Undated) _ Conversation with Maurice Berger, author
of a much-discussed new book on race. By Felicia R. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   DANGEROUS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
reviews ``A Dangerous Friend,'' by Ward Just (Houghton Mifflin
Co.).
</P>
