<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MILOSEVIC'S PEACE OVERTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 3:
</P>
<P>
   After more than a month of grim tidings from Yugoslavia, the
release of three captive American soldiers is heartening. But
Slobodan Milosevic's good-will gesture alone is not sufficient
reason to suspend the air war. As President Clinton rightly noted
yesterday, Christopher Stone, Andrew Ramirez and Steven Gonzales
are headed home after 32 days in Serbian custody, but more than
600,000 ethnic Albanians expelled from Kosovo cannot yet return to
their homeland. NATO leaders should intensify their diplomatic
efforts, but until Milosevic takes the steps necessary to restore
peace to Kosovo, there should be no bombing pause.
</P>
<P>
   That is not meant to belittle Milosevic's decision, or the Rev.
Jesse Jackson's role in gaining freedom for the three soldiers and
his appeal for a bombing moratorium. Clearly, Milosevic is
signaling that he would like to find a way to end the war. Jackson,
once again defying diplomatic convention, has brought at least a
moment of hope to an otherwise depressing conflict. The propaganda
benefits Milosevic may harvest from Jackson's trip are easily
outweighed by the safe return of three young Americans to their
families, and Jackson deserves the nation's thanks.
</P>
<P>
   But the weekend's developments do not change the larger picture.
The Serbian assault has not abated, and tens of thousands of
displaced ethnic Albanians continue to stream into Albania and
Macedonia, many with credible accounts of Serbian atrocities. While
Milosevic has modified some of his peace terms, he has so far
offered allies an unacceptable deal. His proposal to meet with
Clinton is diplomatic grandstanding and was properly rejected by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's idea of a political settlement still falls well
short of the minimal conditions that must prevail in Kosovo when
the war ends. Though he has invited the refugees to return home,
Milosevic has so far refused to accept the presence of a well-armed
international peacekeeping force, which would be required to
prevent further ethnic bloodshed. Nor has he clearly offered to
call off his attack on Kosovo and start withdrawing his forces in
return for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   There is reason to think these and other disagreements with NATO
can be narrowed with intensive diplomacy. Milosevic in recent weeks
has shifted from a flat refusal to consider any foreign military
presence in Kosovo to acceptance in principle of an unarmed or
lightly armed force with some NATO representation. Russia, which is
now playing a central and constructive peacemaking role, seems
willing to approve an adequately armed force under U.N. authority.
NATO troops will need to play some role in peacekeeping, as will
Russian forces, and it ought to be possible to find a balance
acceptable to all parties.
</P>
<P>
   With improving weather allowing NATO to escalate the air war,
Milosevic may eventually prove more flexible on other issues as
well, including a restoration of the substantial degree of
political autonomy Kosovo enjoyed until 1989. Boris Yeltsin has
drafted his own proposals, which are to be presented to Clinton
today by Viktor Chernomyrdin, Moscow's special Balkan envoy.
Certainly every diplomatic opening should be pursued. But the
bombing provides the incentive for Milosevic to give up his deadly
game in Kosovo, and it should not be suspended until he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
