<SLUG> BC-CAR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON HAS STUMPED CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM GAZZOLO  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Jeff Gordon lives.
</P>
<P>
   The much-talked-about, much-hyped and, by many, much-hoped-for
death of Gordon's racing career is on hold. Talk that Gordon's
better days were behind him can rest in peace. That was just the
wishful thinking of his detractors, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR fans will have to put up with him for a long time to
come. Gordon proved that there is nothing wrong with him, his car
or his crew that an easy Sunday drive around Fontana couldn't cure.
The man racing fans love to hate, whose victories they boo and
defeats they cheer, simply drove away from the field to win his
second California 500 in three years.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it in a way that will cause those who dislike him to
dislike him even more. Gordon won by having the fastest car, by
being the best driver and by having the best pit crew. There was no
one even close. He made a mockery of the race, tearing up the
California Speedway as if it were his own personal driveway.
</P>
<P>
   That fact, more than anything else, will stick in the craw of
many good ol' boys who had hoped Gordon's domination of the sport
built from bootleggers' runs from the law was over. Guess again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting,'' said Gordon. ``We were able to put our
troubles behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Those troubles include three wrecks and three races where he was
left standing in the garage when kisses were being given to the
winner. Those woes also had many believing Gordon's best was no
longer good enough to win. They saw the setbacks not as chinks in
the armour, but deep cuts to his flesh. More important, they saw it
as the end of putting up with the young gun who had stolen their
sport from southern gentlemen who spit tobacco, drink beer and
whittle wood. Those are folks who are not dealing in reality.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the facts: Gordon's win Sunday was his third of the
season, more than any other driver. That's three victories in 10
races. Gordon lurks fourth in the points standings, just 200 behind
leader Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is still the most recognizable figure in Winston Cup and
is the crossover star to mainstream sports fans. And most
importantly, he is still the best race car driver around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Gordon is the man to beat, no question about it.'' That's
from somebody who should know, Dale Jarrett, who started second
Sunday. By the way, Jarrett's words came before the race. It became
obvious that he was still the best with about 50 laps to go when
Gordon pulled away from the field after his final pit stop. He
stopped for gas and tires with other leaders, up by almost two
seconds; he returned to the track ahead by over four seconds.
That's a full-service station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went perfect on that stop,'' said crew chief Ray
Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   That has not been the case recently, as Gordon has seen more
than his share of problems. Still, the crew and driver never got
down even as the buzzards circled above.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win, you can't go around and pat yourself on the
back, and you can't slit your wrists when you lose,'' said
Evernham. For Gordon, it was just a matter of things coming
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just have things go our way, if we just have some good
fortune instead of misfortune, we can win races,'' said Gordon.
``That's what happened to us today. ``If we can get some
consistency, we'll be a factor in this championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement from a man who has won three of the
last four points titles, including the last two. It is also not the
type of thing those who consider Gordon an overexposed punk like to
hear. But once again they had better get used to it. Sunday only
proved that Jeff Gordon is still the man when it comes to Winston
Cup. Just don't consider it any type of rebirth. Rather, call it a
return to the norm.
</P>
</TEXT>
