</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIFT-GIVING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CORRUPT GIFT-GIVING MADE EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 3:
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with ambiguous language in the federal criminal
statute that outlaws gratuities to public officials, the Supreme
Court responded last week with a 9-to-0 ruling that, while not
unreasonable in the abstract, will have the practical effect of
making it hard, if not impossible, to prosecute cases of improper
gift-giving.
</P>
<P>
   Before the court was an appeal by the independent counsel Donald
Smaltz, who three years ago obtained a conviction of an
agricultural cooperative, Sun-Diamond Growers of California, for
bestowing $5,900 worth of tennis tickets, luggage and other gifts
on then-Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy. There was ample evidence
to show that these gifts were meant to curry favor with Espy, who
was acquitted on related charges by a federal jury.
</P>
<P>
   The gratuities law makes it a crime to ``give anything of
value'' to a federal official ``because of any official act
performed or to be performed in the future.'' But last week, the
Supreme Court unanimously ruled that the law provides criminal
sanctions only where prosecutors can prove a link between a gift
and a specific official act _ in essence imposing the same sort of
quid pro quo requirement that makes the more serious offense of
bribery so hard to prove.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate danger is that gift-loving members of Congress
will try to use the new decision as a wedge to weaken existing
House and Senate rules restricting gifts to lawmakers. Instead,
Congress should concentrate on strengthening those rules, and
amending the illegal gratuities statute to cover all but the most
trivial gifts to high officials _ taking a lot more care this time
in the drafting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
