<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HARDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAL HARDY, 84, HEADED FHA UNDER KENNEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Kan., Calif., Wash., Mo., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neal Hardy, who headed the Federal Housing Administration in the
Kennedy administration, died on April 15 at My Country Home Adult
Congregate Living Facility in Osteen, Fla. He was 84 and had
previously lived in Orange City, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy was an executive of the National Association of Home
Builders when President Kennedy nominated him to head the FHA in
1961. The agency was a predecessor of the Department of Housing and
Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy became known as a progressive administrator, shifting the
emphasis of federal housing to the cities from the suburbs,
promoting low-income housing and helping to plan an executive
order, issued in November 1961, that barred discrimination in
federally subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   The housing agency and the Veterans Administration both issued
rules against racial and religious discrimination in housing. At
that time, the two agencies together were insuring or guaranteeing
mortgages on about a quarter of the private housing built in the
United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy also began a program providing mortgage insurance to
nonprofit and limited-profit organizations for the construction and
rehabilitation of homes for low- and moderate-income families.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned in January 1963 and moved to New York City, where he
worked in the public affairs program of the Ford Foundation. In
1964, he was named deputy administrator for rehabilitation in the
city's Rent and Rehabilitation Administration, which was mounting a
drive to rehabilitate slums.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy was an assistant administrator in the city's Housing and
Development Administration from 1968 to 1972. He was executive
director of New York City Rehabilitation Mortgage Insurance Corp.,
a government concern, from 1972 until he retired in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Ottawa, Kan., the son of Cleo Hardy and the
former Irene Johnson. In 1936, he received a bachelor's degree from
the University of Kansas. He served in the Army in World War II,
did intelligence work and became assistant military attache at the
U.S. Embassy in London.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Hardy began working for the Housing and Home Finance
Agency, the parent of the FHA, in Washington. He stayed there until
he moved to the home builders' association in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   His 1938 marriage to Dorothy Margaret Cortelyou ended in
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 38 years, Sallee, of De Land,
Fla.; two sons, Neal Jr. of Marina Del Ray, Calif., and Van of
Redmond, Wash.; a stepson, Scott Lee Bashaw of St. Louis; five
grandchildren, and a sister, Polly Roehm of Weston, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
