<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LABONTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABONTE PLEASED WITH PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HELMS  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Bobby Labonte said he knew what was coming
after Saturday's practice sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon looked dominating then, too. Labonte just hoped he'd
be somewhere near the front when the California 500 neared its
conclusion. He got his wish because he was the main one chasing
Gordon for a good stretch late in the race before he was overtaken
by second-place finisher Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   But third-place was more than enough to make Labonte pleased
when the race was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Gordon would be tough to beat after practice,'' Labonte
said. ``(Gordon and Jeff Burton) were the class of the field, and
we were able to hang in there with them towards the end. (Team
owner Joe Gibbs) should be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who started in the fourth position, said his car got
better as the race went on, but that the top two cars were simply
better.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte led two times during the race for a total of 14 laps,
but he knew Gordon and Burton had their cars running better for
most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My car wasn't as good on a long run early on. I got about a
half-lap down and we made a lot of adjustments under yellow and got
the car a lot better,'' Labonte said. ``We came away with a good
finish, a top-five, and hey, that's good. They (Gordon and Burton)
just beat everybody everywhere. At the beginning, heck, I couldn't
even see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who is fourth in the points race, has had mixed results
in Fontana. He was sixth in 1997 and wound up 38th last year in
what he considered to be a faster car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first Cup race here, we didn't run that good, but we got a
good finish on fuel mileage, so we were lucky with that,'' Labonte
said. ``Last year, we had a better car, but we actually blew the
motor up on the first lap.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a much better run in this year's race. Labonte had the
second-fastest practice lap Saturday, and he led early in Sunday's
race. He said his car ran the best just past the halfway point of
the event _ he led for three laps until Gordon passed him on Lap
141 _ but his car's performance fell off a bit after his last pit
stop. That's when he fell far behind Gordon and couldn't hold off
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get passed, there's usually a reason why you got
passed,'' he said. ``We were better with the set of tires before
that last run. We lost some grip there at the end of the race
compared to the last set of tires before that. We were really good
on about a 15-lap run, but after that we'd typically fall back.
Towards the end, we made some adjustments so we got better toward
the end of our runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is enjoying a successful season and Sunday's third-place
finish was his sixth top-five placing in 1999. He remains fourth in
the points race after a career-best sixth-place finish last year.
He won a pair of races last year and has won a pair of poles this
year, but is still looking for his first win of '99. He made a good
run at it Sunday, but fell short for a very good reason. The two
cars ahead of him were better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no complaints,'' he said. ``I'm happy with our
finish.'' Gordon and Burton were, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
