<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WARREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES WARREN, 92, PHYSICIAN AND MOUNTAINEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Warren, a British physician who tried three times to
scale Mount Everest in the 1930s, died on March 30 in his home in
Essex, England. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Warren brought the sherpa guide Tenzing Norgay to the attention
of British mountaineers. Norgay made history in 1953 when he and
Edmund Hillary became the first men to reach Everest's peak.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, whose death was first reported last weekend, himself
came to the attention of those organizing the British Everest
expeditions after a successful 1933 climb to the summit of
Bhagirathi III, in the Gangatori district of the Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
   His initial attempt to reach the top of Everest, in 1935, led by
the explorer Eric Shipton, was notable mainly for the discovery of
the body of Maurice Wilson, a soldier-turned-mystic who believed
prayer and dedication would lead him to the top of the world.
Warren helped bury Wilson in a crevasse.
</P>
<P>
   That first failed mission was also noteworthy because Warren,
the physician for the expedition, was impressed by Norgay and
invited him to stay in the doctor's home in Felsted in Essex.
Norgay served as a porter for Warren on all three of his attempts
at Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, a cautious climber, also served as physician to British
expeditions that were turned back, mostly by weather, in 1936 and
1938.
</P>
<P>
   Warren was born in London and educated at Eastbourne College and
Emmanuel College, Cambridge, where he studied medicine. He
specialized in pediatrics, helping to develop ultraviolet
treatments for infants suffering from jaundice.
</P>
<P>
   His wife died before him, and he leaves no immediate survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Though Warren never tried to climb Everest again after his three
attempts, he kept scaling mountains around the world, even when he
was past 70. A hike to the top of Cuillin Ridge on the Isle of Skye
in Scotland when he was 72 and his last rock climb, in the Lake
District on his 80th birthday, were both capped with champagne
toasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
