<SLUG> BC-SLUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTOYA CAPTURES BOSCH SPARK PLUG 200 FOR SECOND STRAIGHT CART WIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Pa. _ Juan Montoya's quick rise to Champ Car
prominence is reminiscent of another aggressive and confident
driver who seemingly came from out of nowhere to win consecutive
championships in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably not too early to start comparing Montoya to his
predecessor, the two-time champion Alex Zanardi, who left Chip
Ganassi Racing after last season for the twists and turns of the
Formula One circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya and Zanardi are similar on many levels. Behind the
wheel, they are precise and calculating. Both are self-confident,
sometimes even cocky. And now, they have something else in common:
success very early in their CART careers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, with the assistance of Chip Ganassi Racing's famously
fast pit crew, Montoya dominated the Bosch Spark Plug 200 at
Nazareth Speedway from start to finish, taking the FedEx Series
points lead with his second straight CART victory.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year old rookie, who put his Honda-Reynard on victory
lane two weeks ago in Long Beach, Calif., started Sunday's race
from the pole and led for 210 of the 225 laps, finishing more than
five seconds ahead of P.J. Jones, in a Ford-Swift, and Paul Tracy,
in a Honda-Reynard.
</P>
<P>
   After rubbing tires with Helio Castro-Neves on Lap 145, Montoya
came onto pit lane under caution after Jones' car spun out of
control. Montoya's pit crew pulled off their tires-and-gas stop
nearly three seconds faster than Castro-Neves', giving Montoya all
the advantage he needed to win the race. The bumping incident
between Castro-Neves and Montoya was the only excitement in what
was a ho-hum finish to a ho-hum race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they do, but they are pretty quick,'' said
Montoya, who won consecutive victories as a rookie for the first
time since Nigel Mansell won at Michigan and Loudon in 1993.
Mansell went on to capture the PPG championship that season and
earn rookie of the year honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had quite a good car today,'' said Montoya, who averaged
120.225 miles an hour around the mile tri-oval. ``I lost the lead
twice to Helio in traffic, but both times my guys in the pits got
me back out front. They got this win for me. I was just trying to
keep it on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, who was born in Bogota, Colombia, made a name for
himself on Europe's road courses. So like Zanardi, Montoya left
Europe for Chip Ganassi Racing's team, which has dominated CART in
the 1990s and has won the last three series titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be on top of the points,'' Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Sunday's race lacked the wheel-to-wheel
action that is normally found in CART races was due to the
aerodynamic changes the teams were required to make on the cars.
</P>
<P>
   All week, drivers complained about the sanctioning body's
mandate that the cars use smaller aerodynamic wings on CART's short
ovals, like the one here at Nazareth. The shorter front and rear
wings are designed to slow the cars down by creating less
down-force, thus making the drivers slow down in the turns, as the
cars now tend to lose traction.
</P>
<P>
   The cars did run slower and more loose. Montoya's qualifying
time of 173.755 m.p.h. was more than 11 m.p.h. slower than Patrick
Carpentier's record speed of 184.896 mph set at last season's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really single file,'' said Tracy, who finished in the
top three for the fifth time in nine starts at Nazareth. ``The cars
were really spread out. It wasn't much like Champ Cars are all
about. We have to figure out how to make the cars better when they
are in close to one another, wheel to wheel, to make passing
easier. It's definitely hurting the sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIFETEEN-AZR &LR;      05-03 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFETEEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO TEEN RETREAT TURNS TO HEALING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The teenagers who lost 13 friends in the
Columbine High School murders danced and sang ``The'' ``Happy
Song'' on Sunday morning at St. Frances Cabrini Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   As the band jammed, the 75 or so teens sang out: ``Everybody's
singing now, 1-2-3, `cause we're so happy . . . And unseen angels
celebrate, for joy is in this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Joy, for the first time since April 20, had replaced sadness,
fear, anger and myriad other emotions for many of the teenagers who
took part in the retreat that began Friday night at the church,
which is only two miles from Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat was supposed to be for the 91 members of the 1999
confirmation class. Daniel Mauser, who died at Columbine, was
supposed to be there.
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings, the church opened the retreat to any teen
who wanted to come _ nearly 200 took part _ and changed the theme
to ``We survived. We will prevail. We have hope to carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Frances' high school group, Life Teen, is part of the
national Life Teen program that began in Mesa. Seven adults from
the East Valley flew to Littleton to help with the retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the St. Frances teens know the victims, but several
_ Mauser, Lauren Townsend, Rachel Scott and Matthew Ketcher and two
others who were wounded _ were in their Life Teen group. Nearly
everyone at the retreat knew someone who died and some knew them
all.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday morning, the teenagers cheered and hugged and
laughed and began to heal, they said. The funerals are over and
they have been reminded of the presence of Jesus in their lives and
in the lives of their friends who died, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brain has just been a mess,'' said 16-year-old Caitlin
Whitney. She was in the courtyard when the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to focus enough to pray more than `God,
please help me, please help me get through this,' '' she said.
``Just being here this weekend, I was able to focus and able to
make a connection. I actually felt like I was talking to God, and
he was hearing me. It made me feel satisfied, like I'm OK. I will
be fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers have a lot to be happy about, said Jessica Mestas,
15. The community is closer, more people are seeking God, and fewer
people died than the killers intended, the teens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was the devil's great plan, it's all back in his
face,'' Mestas said. ``I think a lot of good has come out.''
</P>
<P>
   When the retreat opened Friday, the teens, who came from several
area high schools, ran the gamut of emotions. Some were sick of
hearing about Columbine. Others hadn't come to terms with their
feelings. All needed a breath of fresh air. The weekend was a mix
of fun _ pickup basketball games in the gym, rowdy music and
humorous skits _ and serious talks and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   There was time to spend with one or two friends tucked away in a
quiet stairwell, talking and consoling each other and time to
giggle and eat cookies. Counselors were on hand for private and
group sessions, and the confirmation class continued its work,
preparing for Tuesday when its members will be confirmed into the
faith.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers reminded the teens that God was there in the midst
of the evil. Law enforcement officials have said they don't
understand why 200 or 300 didn't die, said Steve Angrisano, a
national Catholic speaker and a member of St. Frances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were flown by angels out of that school. Don't miss that.
Make your life count,'' Angrisano said.
</P>
<P>
   They were reminded of the martyrs of the faith, including Cassie
Bernall, the 17-year-old who was shot and killed after saying yes
when asked, ``Do you believe in God?''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Schnurr, who worships at St. Frances, was in the library
when the shooting began. She was hit and began to pray. She also
was asked by one of the shooters if she believed in God, and she
said yes. It appeared she was going to be shot again, but something
distracted the shooter and she survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a miracle,'' said Bobby Ratzi, 16, who was in
the same confirmation group as Mauser. ``People say God never does
miracles. That was a smack in the face. You can't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three walls in the St. Frances Life Teen room are covered with
posters and cards of condolence from Life Teen members around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The posters have hearts and angels drawn on them. Many quote the
Bible: ``We believe that Jesus died and rose again and so we
believe that God will take back with Jesus those who have died
believing in him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the St. Frances teenagers believe, they said, and
that is their hope and their joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends who don't believe in God. For them, it's over.
They'll never see their friends again. I don't know what I'd do if
I wouldn't be able to see my friends again,'' Whitney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to have patience,'' added Sarah Arzola, 17, who
was good friends with victim Rachel Scott. ``When I do die, I'm
going to see Rachel again. We all say we are lucky to be here. In a
way, they are even luckier to go to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholics believe the real presence of Christ is in the bread of
the Eucharist, called the blessed sacrament. On Saturday night, the
lights were dimmed and Father Fred Gaglia brought out the blessed
sacrament, encased in glass, and the teens and adults fell to their
knees for adoration and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Music played softly as Gaglia touched the sacrament to the
forehead of each teen, asking for God's blessing on them. He asked
that each one be filled with whatever gift of the spirit was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Some cried. Some appeared to faint. Others had their tears
turned to laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way that God could show them visibly his great love
and concern for them. Now it is a living reality for them,'' said
Gaglia, the western regional Life Teen coordinator who is based in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Kuenstler, 15, had left the class of Dave Sanders, the
teacher who was killed, just before the shooting started. She heard
shots in the hall and has had a difficult time since, she said. The
weekend, and especially Saturday night, were a help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relief for me because of all the stuff we've been
going through,'' she said. ``I could just feel the holy spirit in
me. It was really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bell, 15, couldn't stop laughing Saturday night. She felt
happy, she said. Bell had buried her face in her hands and cried
after they had prayed for Mauser the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was God's way to tell me to stop mourning and to go on from
here,'' she said. ``The whole weekend calmed everyone down and made
everyone feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beckman, the Life Teen director at the church, challenged
the teenagers to forgive the killers, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, and be examples to the community in finding forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do walk away from this and don't embrace forgiveness
and God's mercy, you become Eric and Dylan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has chosen us for a mission and he is going to give us
every tool and every weapon we need to bring glory and honor to him
through this. Go rock your world!'' Beckman said on Sunday at the
end of the retreat. The teenagers cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Then, T-shirts were handed out. On the front were the words
``Survive, prevail, hope'' and ``70X7.'' On the back, ``We
survived. We will prevail. We have hope to carry on!'' and the
symbol of a cross.
</P>
<P>
   In the gospel of Matthew, a man asks Jesus how many times he
should forgive his brother. Seven times? Jesus says, ``Seventy
times seven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As Christians, we are called to forgive always. That's got to
be a rallying point for us,'' Beckman said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the teenagers pulled the T-shirts over their shirts
immediately. The rallying had begun. &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at (602) 444-4877 or at
kelly.ettenborough(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
