<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1736 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-03 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE WOODLANDS _ He still wears his wedding ring. Of course he does.
Why wouldn't he? Renay's gone, but she's not really gone, not from
his heart, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Golf, meanwhile, fills some of the tangible void. It keeps him
going. You can't stop living.
</P>
<P>
   You can't stop loving, either, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renay,'' Stuart Appleby said, ``will be with me forever, no
doubt, in anything I do. And she'll be there to help, nothing but
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby lost his wife of less than three years last July.
Sunday, he won his first PGA Tour event since that unfathomably
tragic accident outside of London's Waterloo Station. While his
victory in no way cancels out his personal loss, it at least
provides a respite, a fleeting break in the relentless monotony of
his sadness.
</P>
<P>
   The Shell Houston Open may have had greater champions in its
history, both bigger names and guys who fashioned flashier scores.
Remarkably, Appleby's final-round 71, a mere stroke better than
par, would be sufficient to erase a three-shot deficit when the
blustery afternoon began.
</P>
<P>
   But, with no offense intended toward Hal Sutton, whose
tournament it was to lose _ and he did _ Houston's often
star-crossed stop on the golf circuit has never had a champion the
swarming, teeming masses at the TPC should have pulled any harder
for than Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   See, he won't be the same again even if he wins 100 golf
tournaments. Nothing can scrape away his memory of seeing Renay
die. One minute she was carrying suitcases; the next she was a
crumpled, comatose form on the grimy asphalt, having been
accidentally crushed between two vehicles as the couple were
preparing to leave London for a holiday.
</P>
<P>
   He had just missed the cut at the British Open and was still
feeling sorry for himself. As with his peers, golf defined him, so
playing golf badly always left him in a funk. But he was about to
find out how a real funk felt.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Championship in August marked his return to competition.
He cried his way through a historically poignant news conference,
then failed to recompose himself sufficiently to earn a weekend tee
time. It has been a weekly, daily, hourly struggle since to clear
his mind enough to let his motor skills function as they did before
July 23, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although a year-end victory at a small tournament in his native
Australia gave him hope, it didn't repair his battered mental
state. Coolum only reminded him how much he missed Renay. The event
was one he had played largely at her behest because she would go to
the beach there, or ride her bicycle. As much as anything, it was a
vacation destination more than it was a business trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a victory where I played by pure relaxation,'' he
said. ``This was work. Real work.''
</P>
<P>
   The capricious gusts kept the field from scoring Sunday. None of
the 54-hole leaders bettered Appleby's 1-under-par round. In fact,
Clarence Rose skied to 79, Joey Sindelar to 77, Frank Lickliter to
76, Loren Roberts and Sutton to 75. Hal's bogeys at 16 and 17
opened a window for Appleby, who found within himself the
wherewithal to climb through.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-foot birdie putt he rammed home at 17 effectively sealed
the deal. But he had told himself early in the morning he would
win, no two ways about it. Was Renay with him all the way? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave me the strength,'' Appleby said. ``Yeah, I mean, why
not? I just felt strong. I sort of walked like I wanted this
tournament. I knew this was going to be mine, that I was going to
get this thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be Renay (and) try to talk to myself about what I had
to do to win. The answer was: Get your act together. Try and stay
positive on the course. Believe in yourself. Believe that practice
is going to work. All the stuff I've been through is not for any
reason at all, (not) because I'm a bad person. It's not that.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby's piercing blue eyes appear to water frequently when he
speaks of Renay, but he maintained a taciturn demeanor on the
wind-whipped Woodlands track. Although he didn't bring his ``A''
game, he did bring his brain, without which, he said, ``you can
pack your bags and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great victory,'' he suggested, ``in the sense that my
mind got me around more than anything else _ the opposite of the
last few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was Appleby's 28th birthday. Renay would be 26. Just
kids still, the two of them, with so much to look forward to. Now?
One life is done; the other must, damn the pain and the injustice
of it all, continue. To honor Renay's memory, Appleby needs to do
his job to the best of his ability. There's no profit in anything
less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you lose someone you love so much,'' he said,
``but you've got to turn it around. And you have to make sure that
if anything happens, for good or bad, you have to find out in the
end that everything was for the good.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, to be sure, not an iota of good in Renay's untimely
passing. It did not happen to punish her, or him. But it happened,
so he has to cope. Winning seems as effective a means as any,
certainly better than the alternative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
