<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ANYBODY WANT A SLIGHTLY USED FOOTBALL TEAM? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New England Patriots have decided there is not enough money
in the world to make them move to Hartford, Conn. The Patriots'
owner, Robert Kraft, agreed back in December that Connecticut could
have the privilege of building him a $375 million stadium,
guaranteeing the sale of all the luxury seating and underwriting
virtually every other team expense except the Gatorade. But now
Kraft seems to be planning to stay in Massachusetts, even though
its offer of financial assistance is the major-league equivalent of
pocket change. We have seen this story in dozens of teen-age
movies, and Connecticut is stuck playing the spoiled cheerleader
who gets dumped at the prom.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we hope that this could be the beginning of the end for
major-league stadium extortion? Smaller cities lusting after the
cachet of big-time sports are going to think twice before they get
into a bidding war that could end in this kind of humiliation. The
Massachusetts House speaker, Thomas (``No tribute or ransom'')
Finneran, who took the heat for driving the Patriots away, now
looks like the Patrick Henry of football, if only because he had
the temerity to call Kraft ``a whiny millionaire looking for a
bribe.'' Finneran is even demanding that the Patriots reimburse the
state for part of the cost of fixing the roads and utilities around
a stadium Kraft would have to build for himself. Team owners have
always regarded these sorts of infrastructure improvements for
their sports meccas as an inherent responsibility of American
government, like schools and firefighting.
</P>
<P>
   In backing out of the Hartford deal, Kraft cited uncertainty
over a stadium completion date, but a big factor seemed to be his
fellow team owners' contempt for the size of the local TV market.
Your heart has to go out to Hartford, which has been sinking into
the status of a snakebit money pit for decades now, littered with
failed development projects of the past_ the abandoned jai alai
fronton, the near-empty indoor mall, where a hamburger stand is now
the lead tenant. The Hartford Whalers hockey team has gone South,
preferring to play before fans whose experience with ice is limited
to their refrigerator freezers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby Providence, which Hartford had always regarded with
disdain, somehow developed a lively downtown while Hartford's began
looking more and more like a ``Blade Runner'' set. To add insult to
injury, Providence got its name on the title of a TV series _ a
series with good ratings! No wonder the Connecticut state
legislators sat there salivating while Kraft told them he could put
the Hartford skyline on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something pathetic about the eagerness of Gov. John
Rowland and the Connecticut Legislature to believe that Robert
Kraft really meant it when he enthused ``we want to partner with
Hartford!'' even as he devised a contract that gave him more escape
hatches than Houdini. It is easy to make fun of them in hindsight,
but it is' also easy to imagine New York doing the same thing,
forking over great piles of money while burbling about bringing
``Monday Night Football'' to Albany. New York's lawmakers have, by
my count, approved subsidies for at least 20 professional sports
facilities over the last half-decade, from tennis courts in
Schenectady to 10 fields for minor-league baseball. One of them was
built in Watertown for an AAA team that has already jumped ship for
a new publicly financed stadium in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford now stands as a warning about what can happen when a
city plays ball with the whiny millionaires. ``This has to be `The
Music Man,' with Kraft in the Robert Preston role,'' said William
Curry, who ran against Rowland in 1994. ``The sports guy blows into
town and tells everybody the wonderful things he's going to do for
you. Then you give him all the money, and you don't even get the
band uniforms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
