</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS' PLUMMET AUDIBLE LONG BEFORE THUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The final week of the 1999 Sonics season: Bellyache,
heartbreak and an elimination loss to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't that how the 1997-98 Sonic season ended?
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the Sonics wasted 48 games and a lot of fans'
entertainment dollars to get back to where they were.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not exactly the same spot. This season, the Sonics
commenced their self-sabotage earlier, and their annual
season-ending loss to the Lakers came Sunday, three games before
the end of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics are virtually as dead as they were a year ago at
this time, when the Lakers wasted them 4-1 in the playoffs' second
round. Sunday's 91-84 loss at KeyArena left the Sonics with a
postseason hope thinner than team camaraderie, if that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to use the term `mathematically alive,''' said Hersey
Hawkins, ``because that pretty much means you're almost dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, deadness began to set in in January, when the NBA and
the players' union settled their preposterousness and agreed to
play the most invalid and esthetically absurd sports season since
the 1987 NFL scab games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were destined to fare worse than most of their
high-end contemporaries merely by having to fill six roster spots
and the head coach position with new faces.
</P>
<P>
   But miss the playoffs? With Gary Payton, Vin Baker, Detlef
Schrempf and Hersey Hawkins? In a league in such poor shape that
the Teletubbies could average 75 points a game?
</P>
<P>
   No way.
</P>
<P>
   But where there's little will, apparently there is a way.
</P>
<P>
   By reporting grossly cherubic, Baker and free agent signee Billy
Owens not only committed professional fraud, they nearly took down
the Sonic season by themselves. Add coach Paul Westphal's multiple
dubious strategic maneuvers as well as president Wally Walker's
inability to stock quality veteran help thanks to the Jim McIlvaine
fiasco and reliance on rookie draftees, and the recipe for pro
basketball futility was writ large.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite all, the playoffs were still attainable until the
developments of this last desultory week.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the springtime bellyaching was confined mostly to
George Karl, who almost coached himself into another first-round
upset and then talked himself out of the job anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was the co-captains, Payton and Baker, whose
ill-considered oral geysers helped push the Sonics to the
precipice.
</P>
<P>
   After Payton bellowed his dismay in the locker room Wednesday,
it was Baker's turn Friday to hold the franchise momentarily
hostage. Pouting to Westphal and Walker, with Payton and agent in
tow, Baker had the audacity to complain about his playing time in
his first game back after bruising his knee.
</P>
<P>
   If the lockout didn't sufficiently sicken an NBA fan, and the
level of play didn't induce nausea, then the snits by Payton and
Baker are the kinds of moments under pressure that make easier the
abandonment of interest in pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Sunday the Sonics finally had the tandem
contribution from Baker and Payton that they long had sought:
Payton had 29 points, five rebounds, five assists, and Baker off
the bench had 19 points, 12 rebounds and three blocks. Except for
Schrempf (21 points, 11 rebounds), it was the rest of the team that
failed in the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   All involved will deny that the week's tumult had anything to do
with Sunday's season-killing result. But that's the same kind of
denial engaged in a few weeks ago by the Lakers regarding the
distractions of Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers are clearly doing better without the headaches.
So would the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal takes almost a perverse pride in never revealing his
emotions to the media _ known in the hoops biz as a full reverse
George _ but Sunday's loss dragged him close to some public dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer not to have the stuff out there,'' Westphal said,
referring to the Payton/Baker histrionics. ``Unfortunately it's a
big part of what this game is all about in the '90s. Whether it's
the increased visibility, or the WWF factor, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I try to do is still enjoy the game. I don't enjoy the
losing, and I don't enjoy being the target of occasional unfair
criticism, but the game itself makes the circus worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunno about that, Paul. It must help greatly to be paid more
than $1 million to attend the circus, but this season's NBA game,
and this season's Sonics, who are better in a shouting match than a
shooting match (26th in field goal percentage, 27th in free throw
percentage), would severely test even the deepest of NBA loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   As Hawkins was saying, the only possibilities around the Sonics
these days are mathematical. Hope and joy were long ago eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
