<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-LAKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS TO LAKERS LEAVES SONICS ALL BUT OUSTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was more coincidence than anything that Olden
Polynice wore black.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his postgame attire and mood Sunday epitomized the Sonics
following their devastating 91-84 loss to the Los Angeles Lakers at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   When players start tossing around phrases like ``almost dead''
and ``killed us,'' you have to believe their season has officially
reached its morbid point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slim just hopped on the train,'' said Polynice, talking about
the team's playoff chances. ``None is left.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Sonics have two regular-season games left to hold
off the passing of their season. Sunday's loss did not
mathematically eliminate them from the postseason. However, the
outlook is bleak when you consider:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Sonics have won two games in a row only twice in the past
28 games.
</P>
<P>
   -- The seventh-seeded Minnesota Timberwolves are two games ahead
of Seattle in the Western Conference playoff standings. Even if the
Sonics finished tied with Minnesota, the Timberwolves own the
tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   -- Eighth-place Sacramento also has a two-game lead on the
ninth-place Sonics. The Kings must lose their final two games
against Denver and Vancouver, and the Sonics must sweep Dallas and
the Los Angeles Clippers to have a chance. If the Sonics finish
tied with Sacramento, they would go into the postseason based on a
better conference record.
</P>
<P>
   In other words. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have a minuscule chance of getting in (the
playoffs),'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``We have to hope for
all kinds of help from other people. ... We won't give up as long
as there is a ray of hope, and that's all there is right now. ''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to blame the Lakers for the Sonics' dire
circumstances. A more fitting assessment perhaps would be that the
Sonics just shot themselves in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Seattle probably would miss.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics turned in a flat-line performance in the most vital
game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They missed easy shots.
</P>
<P>
   They missed open shots.
</P>
<P>
   They missed. They missed. They missed, and ended up shooting 37
percent at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to win many games that way,'' said Hersey
Hawkins, one of the main culprits after a 1-for-8 performance.
``The effort was there. We played hard. We just couldn't make shots
for some reason. For the most part the ones I shot felt good, and I
think the other guys will say the same.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Gary Payton's 29 points on 11-for-24
shooting, the rest of the Sonics starters shot 6-for-26 (23
percent) from the field. Detlef Schrempf put together 21 points
with the help of 15-for-16 shooting at the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker came off the bench for a second straight game and
scored 19 points in 38 minutes. He used his quickness to slither
his way to the basket, and when it was time to use muscle on the
low block, he had that, too. In his second game back from a deep
bone bruise in his right knee, Baker gave the Sonics the effective
inside play they desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't come in and feel myself out,'' Baker said. ``I had
to play aggressive to stay in the game. ... There is no tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baker was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' starting five outscored the Sonics' starters 76-59.
</P>
<P>
   Laker guard Kobe Bryant did the most damage. He hit eight
straight baskets in a decisive third quarter and ran amok on the
Sonics' defense to the tune of 19 third-quarter points. He missed
just one of 10 shots in the period, which ended with the Lakers
ahead 70-57.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics went into a tailspin after relinquishing a 44-40
halftime lead, making just 4 of 16 shots in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting to within 81-78 with 2:18 left in the game, the
Sonics were 8-for-20 in the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help that they turned the ball over 17 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Baker said. `` ... There's no doubt about it.
The playoffs are just out of our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Like they have been all season, the Sonics were reaching for
anything to work during the stretch of this game.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal resorted to a strategy of using a much-smaller Dale
Ellis on mammoth Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal. Ellis hacked
O'Neal every time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal responded by making five of his 10 free throws in the
game's final three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never understand that one,'' Polynice said. ``We're doing
things we normally wouldn't do. ... They went to their strengths.
They went to their advantages. I guess we didn't think they were
going to see it was a mismatch.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is turning out to be a season of conflict for
the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   They are on the verge of missing the playoffs for the first time
since the 1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to prepare for Dallas and root like crazy for
anybody Minnesota and Sacramento plays,'' Westphal said. ``As long
as there is a chance, our guys will be motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance, however, is now slight for a Sonics team that has
already begun to mull what could have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
