</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ATTACK DARKENS BELGRADE AND AREAS OF SERBIA 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new updating 3rd graf)  By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Serbia _ All of Belgrade and parts of Serbia were
plunged into darkness just after 10 o'clock Sunday night, when NATO
warplanes hit a major hydro-electric power station west of the
capital, in Obrenovac, said a Serbian Cabinet minister, Goran
Matic.
</P>
<P>
   As anti-aircraft fire filled the skies over Belgrade, lights all
over the city suddenly went dark, leaving the eerie sight of cars
speeding across Belgrade bridges. The official Serbian radio later
reported that power had been restored in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity was restored to central Belgrade shortly before 5
a.m. on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The strike at the power station was hinted at in some of the
recent propaganda leaflets dropped by NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
   One leaflet, which may have been a warning of the strike Sunday
night, showed a picture of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
with an arrow pointing backward. Above the president's name it
said: ``No gasoline, no electricity, no trade, no freedom, no
future.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side it said: ``As long as Milosevic is going to
continue his program of destruction, rape and murder in Kosovo,
Serbia will go deeper into isolation. Don't be prisoners of
Milosevic's awfulness.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier foreshadowing apparently came late last month from
Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman. Referring to several
protests staged by citizens of the capital and the Yugoslav
government since the NATO bombings began, he said, ``You can have
your rock concerts, but pretty soon it's going to be Belgrade
unplugged.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbs reacted immediately with anger. A woman who works for a
Western news agency said: ``This really makes me annoyed. This is
not a military target. This is just trying to demoralize ordinary
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the power station seemed a clear rejection of the
Rev. Jesse Jackson's request that the White House consider a halt
to bombing after Milosevic released three captive American soldiers
early Sunday. The attack on what appeared to be a civilian target
came less than 12 hours after Jackson and his party of religious
leaders flew with the three soldiers to freedom in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we make a gesture of good will, they respond with
escalation,'' said a senior Yugoslav official. ``Someone has
decided to keep using the stick, and why?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about politics, but pure power,'' he added. ``It's
just to show muscle, it doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO has vowed to intensify its air attacks against Yugoslavia,
vowing to force a change in Belgrade's policies toward Kosovo,
where tens of thousand of ethnic Albanian have been forced from
their homes. The heaviest NATO bombings since the air war began 40
days ago have occurred in the last few days. NATO planes have been
flying more than 600 sorties a day, last week hitting Milosevic's
official residence in an exclusive area of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of sorties has increased so has the number of
accidents. In the last week NATO has bombed residential areas of
Belgrade, Prizren and Surdulica _ all by mistake. NATO sent a
missile into Bulgaria, a prospective alliance member, where it
sliced the roof off a house.
</P>
<P>
   The intention clearly seems to be to try to force Milosevic to
yield by increasing the pain on ordinary citizens, with the
mounting discomforts ranging from a severe shortage of cigarettes _
which should not be underestimated in the Balkans _ to a monthly
ration of gasoline that is now only five gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Different parts of Belgrade have been blacked out by previous
raids, but never the entire city at once, and transportation has
been increasingly difficult, with much of the country's bridge and
rail network destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs have proved resilient improvisers, however,
usually patching together repairs that allow basic services to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all NATO's effort to drive Serbian state television off
the air _ by striking at transmitting stations and offices _ it has
been able to keep broadcasting to most parts of the country. Now
NATO has apparently decided to cut power to the television sets
themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
