<HEADLINE>
CHARLES DAWSON, 88, LED IN STUDY OF POISON IVY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., N.Y., S.C., R.I., Idaho, Maine)  (mk) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Dawson, a longtime chemistry professor at Columbia
University who played the leading role in the discovery of the
toxic compounds in poison ivy, died on Wednesday in a hospital in
Wolfeboro, N.H. He was 88 and lived in Wolfeboro.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson taught at Columbia from 1939 until he retired in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, he and David Wasserman, a Columbia graduate student
then, began to carry out experiments involving poison ivy. They
collected 80 pounds of poison ivy bark, from which they extracted
two teaspoons of the poisonous oil. The oil was used in preliminary
chemical experiments, and then the scientists began work on
developing methods of synthesizing compounds similar to those found
in poison ivy oil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Dawson told reporters that he and Wasserman had
developed a synthetic compound resembling the chemical structure of
poison ivy and producing the same physiological effects. At that
time, the compound, which was considered better than poison ivy as
an aid in the diagnosis and possible treatment of the effects of
contact with the plant, was being tested by Dr. Harry Keil of the
Skin and Center Unit of the New York Post-Graduate Medical School
and Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, it was announced that Dawson and his research students
had isolated the toxic agent in the sap of poison ivy and had
broken it down into four distinct parts.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson's son, John, a chemistry professor at the University of
South Carolina, said Sunday that the least toxic of the four was
one of a family of chemical compounds, called alkyl catechols,
which cause allergic responses in most people.
</P>
<P>
   With researchers from the National Institutes of Health, Charles
Dawson set about trying to discover a treatment or vaccine based on
that least toxic compound.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, tests carried out at the University of Pennsylvania on
a vaccine developed by Dawson for the prevention of the adverse
effects of poison ivy were reported to have been successful.
Thousands of volunteers had submitted to a series of injections
intended to desensitize them to poison ivy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, it was reported that the poison ivy vaccine, which
could be taken orally or intramuscularly, would soon be on the
market. John Dawson said that it was his understanding that the
vaccine had been on the market for some years, and that eventually
it had been supplanted, as the chief anti-poison ivy treatment, by
steroid-based anti-inflammatory ointments.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dawson was born in Peterboro, N.H. He received a
bachelor's degree in 1933 and a master's degree in chemistry in
1935, both from the University of New Hampshire, and a doctorate in
1938 from Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, Dawson is survived by his wife,
Dorothea; a daughter, Patricia Dawson Runner of Tiverton, R.I.;
seven grandchildren; a sister, Ruth Taylor of Boise, Idaho, and a
brother, Robert, of Leeds, Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
