<HEADER>
A1750 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THIEL-ELWAYCOLUMN     05-03 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-ELWAYCOLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE OTHERS SAY GOODBYE, SEATTLE SAYS GOOD RIDDANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With Michael Jordan and Wayne Gretzky, it was more of
a cerebral appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway is different. It's visceral. Personal.
</P>
<P>
   To veteran followers of Seattle sports, John Elway has been the
acme of sporting villainy.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, in the cruelest ways, Elway taunted the
Seahawks, then crushed them.
</P>
<P>
   To him, for the players and Seattle fans, let it be said now:
</P>
<P>
   Good freakin' riddance.
</P>
<P>
   That is meant in the nicest way. Which is another problem: Elway
is not only the ultimate gladiator, but a sportsman and gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   For the Seahawk fan, how does it get more aggravating?
</P>
<P>
   If Elway had a little more Snidely Whiplash in him, his
departure would be more cathartic in these precincts. But Elway
never seemed to enjoy taunting or trash talking. He seemed pleased
enough simply to reach into the Seahawk chest and fetch out the
beating heart.
</P>
<P>
   If he just had a DWI, or cursed a reporter, or packed heat, or
smoked dope ... the worst thing he ever did was fire Dan Reeves,
and every superstar fires a head coach at least once.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Seahawks who chased him across the Northwest have
nothing but respect and admiration for the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one thing that made him stand out, it's that he
kept getting the first down, some kind of way,'' said Dave Brown,
who flailed against him as a Seahawk defensive back as well as a
Seahawk assistant coach. ``It seemed like almost every time it was
third and long, he found a way to get the ball in the right hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coaching a game in the Kingdome, I think it was
'93, when we had been doing a great defensive job on Denver. We had
'em stopped, it was third-and-15 around the Seattle 40 and we ran a
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Broncos sent everybody out and we were all over Elway. But
somehow he ducked under a lineman, went almost to his knees. Our
safety on (tight end) Shannon Sharpe, Robert Blackmon, thought
Elway was sacked and hesitated just a second. All of a sudden Elway
straightens up and throws this bullet to Sharpe. Hits him in the
numbers at the goal line before Blackmon knew what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best throw I ever saw a quarterback make.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it's been for most of the 16 years Seattle has been
under Elway's hegemony. The Seahawks' 9-20 record in his starts
with the Broncos is the worst among Seattle's frequently played
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with one possible exception, no other opponent in
Seattle's modern big-time pro sports history has tortured this town
so much. From 1983 to 1998, Elway was the grounds in our collective
latte.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 20 greatest individual passing games against the
Seahawks' in their 23 seasons, Elway has the most, five, including
his last one _ 335 yards in December, when the Broncos ended the
Seahawks' regular season and another Seahawk coach's NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Broncos' sixth straight win over the Seahawks and
11th in the last 13 games (one of the two Seattle wins, 31-27 in
1995, required staging the greatest comeback, from 20-0, in club
history).
</P>
<P>
   If Elway played one more season, the NFL would have to sell what
remained of the Seattle franchise to Bronco owner Pat Bowlen, who
already owned most of it.
</P>
<P>
   In the category of perennial Seattle nemesis, Elway has no peer
from baseball. Perhaps the best long-term batting career against
the Mariners was Cal Ripken Jr., whose .294 average (plus 28 homers
and 110 RBI) is his highest mark against any AL foe. He also went
7-for-16 in the 1997 AL Division Series to help eliminate the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitcher against Seattle probably was Dave Stewart, 20-6
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The one rival Elway has as Seattle nemesis was a longtime
unmatchable for the Sonics: Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   In his career from 1969-70 to 1988-89, the Sonics had a record
of 30-88 against his teams in Milwaukee (7-27) and Los Angeles
(23-51), a miserable 25.4 winning percentage. In the playoffs, the
Sonics fared little better, going 7-14 (33 percent) in five playoff
series against his Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Seahawks won 31 percent of their games against Elway's
Broncos, it might be argued that Abdul-Jabbar helped wreak more
devastation. But the Sonics were expansion fodder in Abdul-Jabbar's
dominant early years. And as a Laker, Abdul-Jabbar was almost
always surrounded by superlative talent.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, on the other hand, was a rookie when the Seahawks were at
their best, and later often was hampered by the ordinariness of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the beginning, Elway haunted. The first playoff game
in Seahawk history was in 1983, a 31-7 win over the Broncos when
rookie Elway came in for injured Steve DeBerg and hit 10 passes in
15 attempts _ a percentage he reached in only one other of his 22
postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, he threw for 432 yards against the Seahawks, the
second-highest Seahawk opponent total.
</P>
<P>
   About the only time the Seahawks had much of an edge on the
Elway-led Broncos was 1987-88, when haircut/linebacker Brian
Bosworth personalized the rivalry to wonderfully silly proportions.
With a large photo of Elway pasted to his locker, Bosworth publicly
taunted Elway, calling him ``Mr. Ed'' and helping the Seahawks beat
the Broncos in three of four meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But Bosworth turned out to be as temporary as the Seahawk sack
that Brown described. Long after Boz started getting paid to be a
bad actor instead of doing it free, Elway endured, enraged and, to
a more enlightened, less provincial point of view, enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   To Seattle eyes, he was the greatest, most aggravating, rival
ever. And we haven't even mentioned his brilliant Stanford career
against the Washington Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, he's a native son, born in Port Angeles where his
dad, Jack, coached high school.
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention John's wife is from Tacoma?
</P>
<P>
   For his entire athletic life, he's been coming back to town,
beating up the local boys, getting the girl and stealing all the
horses and the whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   A weepy farewell? The only dry place in Seattle is sports fans'
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
