<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-570&AMP;ADD-NYT     05-03 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI TESTS NATIONAL WATERS, BUT BARELY A RIPPLE IS SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki had just finished a 50-minute speech
at Georgetown University about the Balkans when a student
interposed a question that had little to do with Pataki's views on
foreign policy: Why was a New York governor offering a major
address in Washington on global problems in the first place?
``Normally, those are handled by presidents and vice presidents,''
Matthew Payne, a government major, observed dryly.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki paused as a rustle of laughter rose from the seats. ``I'm
sure that we have many New Yorkers involved in the airstrikes,'' he
said. Besides, the governor asserted, ``The national policy debate
_ the decisions that are made here in Washington _ have an enormous
effect on New York.''
</P>
<P>
   As the question posed at Georgetown last week suggests, Pataki's
campaign to establish himself as a leading influence within his
party _ shaping the Republican Party's platform and earning
consideration as a top-tier candidate for national office _
apparently has yet to take hold. Three months after Pataki began
offering his views of the world beyond Albany, his state capital,
with a series of speeches across the country, Republican
politicians and strategists say he remains largely a New York state
figure, respected for his accomplishments in that state, but still
not considered among the leading forces in his party.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's signature argument that his party should turn away from
such issues as abortion rights and embrace the Reagan-era platform
of cutting government spending and taxes has yet to inspire the
kind of debate that the governor might have envisioned. Even
Republicans who praise his record say he is rarely mentioned in
discussions these days about potential presidential or vice
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that he is not a serious candidate,'' said Mike
Murphy, a Republican strategist who worked for Bob Dole's
presidential campaign in 1996. ``His presidential ambitions are
writing checks that his political muscle can't cash. There is no
opening for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bailey, a former Republican consultant who is now the
publisher of a daily political digest and tip sheet, said: ``I
don't think he's on anybody's list. I don't think anybody seriously
thinks that he's planning to run. I don't think he's a household
name anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding his apparent lack of success to date, Pataki has
a history of emerging unexpectedly at the top of the political
heap. He was, after all, the little-known Republican legislator
from Westchester who toppled former Gov. Mario Cuomo, and he is
nothing if not a persistent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   His nomination in 1994 came after years of steady if unnoticed
work in New York political circles, traveling the state and giving
speeches, preparing himself should the political opportunity arise,
as it did when Republican leaders recruited him to run against
Cuomo. He is now executing the same kind of strategy on a national
level, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki said that he was satisfied with his success so far,
asserting in an interview that his speeches on national politics
and the future of the Republican Party _ in Illinois, Missouri and
New Hampshire, among other places _have drawn attention both to his
record in Albany and to his views on how his party can become more
competitive in national elections. ``I really believe this stuff,''
he said. ``I really believe in these principles.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I am amazed at the level of attention,'' Pataki said. ``When
you have seven or eight candidates _ and I'm not a candidate _ to
have obtained the level of attention that we've gotten is, to me,
very surprising. I didn't expect it to be as widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a view, though, that is not widely shared among
Republicans these days. Several contrasted Pataki's trips with
those of his predecessor: In particular, Cuomo's 1984 speech about
abortion rights at the University of Notre Dame, when he was a
first-term governor, which drew extensive national attention and
helped stir the talk among some Democrats about Cuomo as a
potential presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's advisers describe what he is doing as, in effect, a
should-lightning-strike strategy: establishing his credentials in
case one of the Republicans more commonly mentioned for national
office should falter. But that is an eventuality that even Pataki's
advisers see as increasingly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's attempt to use the 2000 presidential campaign to
raise his own profile _ following a long line of governors from New
York who have done the same thing to great success, whether Thomas
Dewey or Cuomo _ has been, to some extent, undercut by events
beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   When Pataki began earlier this year, it was far from clear who
the Republican Party might nominate for president. That has changed
with the rise of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas as the party's
leading presidential contender, to Pataki's clear disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's actually looked at as a candidate by very
many people because the movement to Bush is unabated,'' said Gov.
John Engler of Michigan, an early supporter of Bush. ``There is a
settling in that's taking place that in all likelihood, George W.
Bush is going to be our nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki's hopes of being considered for vice president are
complicated by, among other things, his support of abortion rights,
which will certainly be a contrary position at the next Republican
convention, and the fact that he is from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing Republicans are concerned about is reinforcing
their base in the South and the Southwest,'' said Adam Goodman, a
Republican consultant. ``The Northeast is not at the top of the
priority list.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pataki has succeeded in distinguishing himself
ideologically in his party, with his emphasis on economic issues
combined with his support for abortion rights and gay rights.
Several advisers said that such ideological positioning could prove
fortuitous in future presidential elections if the Republican Party
moves to the center. In that event, what Pataki is doing now could
pay dividends in 2004 or 2008, much the same way his work in New
York in 1990 paid off in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Pataki said he intends to continue traveling
the nation, presenting himself as a noncandidate concerned about
the future of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is doing what you can do when you are the governor of New
York, which is to monkey around in the primary season,'' Murphy,
the Republican consultant, said. ``There is no such thing as too
much exposure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
