<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLEMAKING INMATEFORCES EXTRA SECURITY AS EXECUTION DATE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The career of one of Arizona's most notorious
criminals is expected to end Wednesday when Robert Wayne Vickers is
set to be executed at the Arizona State Prison in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers, who has kept prison officials busy for the past 20
years with a series of murders, assaults, threats and escapes, is
expected to be executed at 3 p.m. for the 1982 murder of fellow
death row inmate Wilmar ``Buster'' Holsinger.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers also was sentenced to death for the murder of his
cellmate, Frank Ponciano, in 1979. He carved the word ``Bonzai,'' a
misspelling of the Japanese war cry, in Ponciano's back.
</P>
<P>
   He came to be known thereafter as ``Bonzai Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is far from the first time that Vickers has come close
to death. He escaped execution after death warrants were signed on
five earlier occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Department of Corrections officials say they are taking
unprecedented security steps for the execution, some of which they
won't talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Camilla Strongin, a Corrections spokeswoman, said Vickers is
being shuttled between two cells that are equipped with heavy
plastic glass and with reinforced welds connecting the beds to the
walls. Vickers has made weapons in the past by breaking welds on
beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he leaves one cell for the other, it is searched
extensively before he returns to it,'' Strongin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ben Cooper, a Phoenix attorney who represents Vickers, said
he feels he has fertile psychological grounds to win a stay of
execution.
</P>
<P>
   After a long juvenile history of petty crime, he said, Vickers
was originally sentenced to three to nine years for grand theft in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections records, Cooper said, show a pattern of inadequate
mental health care and ``reflect the history of an inmate who came
to prison on a robbery charge and psychologically deteriorated
until he ended up on death row.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident with Holsinger is a major point in Vickers' appeal
seeking a stay of execution, Cooper said, because the attack was
not premeditated.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers attacked Holsinger with a firebomb he fashioned in his
jail cell after Holsinger had made lewd comments about Vickers'
11-year-old niece. Vickers was the porter in death row at the time
and had shown Holsinger a picture of the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy (Vickers) with a flash point about sexual
molestation of children,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's kind of a noble impulse. I fear that the state and
DOC just want to see him dead because he hasn't been a choirboy in
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he was sent to prison, Vickers has been cited for more
than 160 major disciplinary violations, including more than 35
counts of making weapons, more than a dozen assaults and numerous
threats. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
