<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG GONE, BUT NOT TO YARD IN SKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Grega owns what sound like perfect dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Dartanian, part malamute and part shepherd, and Alyosha, a
Samoyed, don't climb on the furniture. Barking is not a problem.
Cleanup is non-existent, and the dogs never threaten the postman.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they're dead.
</P>
<P>
   Which cuts down on their usefulness as guard dogs considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Grega had both dogs preserved; they lie, seemingly asleep, in a
bedroom of his New York apartment. Forever.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, Fido, too, must shuffle off this canine
coil. But even the most devoted pet lover might wonder: What's the
point of keeping him around after he's gone?
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few years, it has alleviated the pain of losing
those animals,'' explained Grega, who works at a software company.
``I see them every day. . . . It's not like they're in the ground
decomposing. I can touch them. My kid actually likes to pet them.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. Four-year-old Dion doesn't think all dogs lie stone
still.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets along well with live dogs,'' Grega said, laughing.
``He'll even tell me we have two dogs, and they're both dead.'' &QL; 
`After-death pet care'
</P>
<P>
   Grega had his dogs preserved in Phoenix at Pet &AMP; Animal Lovers
Service, or PALS. The company specializes in after-death pet care.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting more emotionally attached to pets,'' said
Katherine Heuerman, PALS founder. ``Everyone's going to (the option
of) getting their pets back.''
</P>
<P>
   Often in the form of ashes: Cremations make up the bulk of her
business, Heuerman said. PALS cremates 60 to 65 animals a week (the
crematoriums are open for pet owners to inspect).
</P>
<P>
   But preservation is growing; one or two people a month now
request it.
</P>
<P>
   Preservation is a form of taxidermy, Heuerman explained, only
more detailed. You didn't gurgle baby talk for 10 years to the
white-tailed buck mounted above the mantel, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fox or deer is wildlife,'' Heuerman said. ``People see them
once, they shoot them, they kill them. There is no emotional
attachment. We have to capture the personality.''
</P>
<P>
   So PALS requires at least three photos of the pet. Preservation
is not cheap; it starts at about $500. (Cremations start at $100,
and burials run $750 to $1,000, Heuerman said.) It's also slow,
taking six to 12 months. But to some, it's worth it. &QL; 
Peanut's place
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said to Peanut, `You'll never leave me,' '' said
Sandra Wade of Scottsdale. And so he hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut, a chocolate-brown poodle no longer among the living,
lies atop a red satin pillow in a cherry-wood bed on top of the
entertainment center in Wade's bedroom. He's encased in a
custom-made glass case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep him with me,'' Wade said. ``I didn't want to
cremate him, and I didn't want him rotting in the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Peanut soon will be joined by Buddy, a white bichon frise, who
died in March and is being preserved, and, eventually, by her seven
other dogs. ``It's well worth the investment,'' Wade said.
``(Preserving Peanut) helped me. I cried when I saw him, but it was
happy. I feel very comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't. A dead pet sitting on a shelf staring back at me
sounds creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Grega understands that, noting that if he didn't know and love
Dartanian and Alyosha, he might find their presence weird, too. But
he did, so he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like they're asleep,'' he said. ``They're where
they've always been. They slept in these poses when they were
alive. If you imagine hard enough, you can imagine them sleeping
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He even talks to them, saying things like ``I miss you guys''
and ``I wish you were alive'' and ``I'm glad you're here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unusual things going on in this world,''
Grega said. ``While that probably is unusual, there are a lot of
things going on you could look at a lot more cross-eyed than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. I'm willing to let eternally sleeping dogs lie.
Someone else's dogs, that is. In someone else's house. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
