The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, May 3. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ Dennis Grega owns what sound like
perfect dogs. Dartanian, part malamute and part shepherd, and
Alyosha, a Samoyed, don't climb on the furniture. Barking is not a
problem. Clean-up is non-existent, and the dogs never threaten the
postman. On the other hand, they're dead. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ.
Story will move in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTIFY - (TEMPE, Ariz.) The house near the middle of East Driftwood
Drive looked just like any other on the block, save for the
perfectly manicured pansies, petunias and geraniums that beckoned
the attention of passersby. But that was before police showed up in
this idyllic south Tempe neighborhood, papering it with bright pink
fliers, knocking on some 500 doors and inviting residents to a
community forum. The man who had cultivated such beautiful blooms
was a convicted sex offender. Things in the Lakes community
changed. At the grocery store, a mother grabbed her young son's arm
and pointed to ``the bad man.'' Women veered off the sidewalk into
the middle of the street when they reached the block where the man
lived. Families stopped letting their children play in the front
yard without supervision. Across the nation, more and more
neighborhoods are being alerted when a sex offender moves in. The
year-long experience of the Lakes shows how such news can pit
neighbor against neighbor, with some camped firmly against sex
offenders like Glenn, saying their pasts automatically make them a
danger, and others arguing that they should get another chance. By
JUDY VILLA. Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LIFETEEN - (LITTLETON, Colo.) At the Catholic parish, the teenagers
who lost 13 friends in the Columbine High School shootings danced,
clapped and sang ``The Happy Song'' on Sunday morning to a jammin'
band. They have spent practically every waking minute since Friday
night together at a retreat at St. Frances Cabrini Catholic Church,
only two miles from Columbine High School. This retreat was
supposed to be for the 91 members of the 1999 confirmation class.
After the shootings, the retreat was opened to any teen who wanted
to come. The retreat doubled in size. St. Frances' high school
group, Life Teen, is part of the national Life Teen program that
began in Mesa, and Life Teen leaders, including seven adults from
Mesa and Gilbert Ariz., flew in as reinforcements. By KELLY
ETTENBOROUGH. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
VICKERS (PHOENIX) The career of one of Arizona's most notorious
criminals is expected to end Wednesday when Robert Wayne Vickers is
set to be executed at the Arizona State Prison in Florence.
Vickers, who has kept prison officials busy for the past 20 years
with a series of murders, assaults, threats and escapes, is
expected to be executed at 3 p.m. for the 1982 murder of fellow
death row inmate Wilmar ``Buster'' Holsinger. By MARK SHAFFER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
