<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HN     05-03 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Not so long ago, Shane Reynolds couldn't win at Pro Player
Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, he can't seem to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds became the first starter in the National League with
five wins Sunday as the Astros extended their winning streak to a
season-high four games with a 3-2 victory over the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won for the sixth time in seven games and completed
their first-ever road sweep of the Marlins. Carl Everett and Tony
Eusebio paced the Astros' 13-hit attack with three hits apiece,
with Everett driving in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who entered with only one career victory in Miami,
held the Marlins to two runs and eight hits in 7 innings. He struck
out six and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterful. He really is,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``He's the kind of guy that is a perfectionist in everything he
does. If you watch him in his day-to-day routine his truck is
always washed, and his clothes are always tailored. Everything _ he
does it to a T.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros built a 3-0 lead, then held on after the Marlins
rallied with a two-run eighth. The Astros didn't help themselves,
stranding 12 runners to match a season high. They left 30 on base
during the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one scared the heck out of me,'' said Dierker, whose team
was 10-20 against the Marlins on the road before the weekend.
``About the sixth inning, all those hits, walks and baserunners,
and nobody was coming home. Usually when we're on the other side of
that, I think we're going to win when the other team keeps missing
too many chances. If you blow that many opportunities to extend the
score, it usually comes back to haunt you.''
</P>
<P>
   But not when your No. 1 pitcher takes a shutout into the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (5-1) has won his last two starts at Pro Player
Stadium, which had been his personal ballpark of horror. He entered
Sunday's series finale 1-5 with a 9.10 ERA in seven games here.
During a game in 1997 in Miami, Reynolds hurt his right knee after
sitting through a rain delay and was forced to spend time on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know (what it is about pitching here),'' said
Reynolds, who tied New York Mets reliever Dennis Cook for the
league lead in wins. ``It's one of those things somebody starts and
gets in your head. The credit goes to our offense and defense. They
picked me up with some good plays. If you keep the game close, we
can put up some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was cruising, up by three with two out in the eighth
inning before allowing a single to Alex Gonzalez and a double to
Mark Kotsay that dropped inside the left-field foul line. Jay
Powell replaced Reynolds and surrendered a two-run double to Cliff
Floyd that bounced over the center-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Floyd) hit it in the only place for us it didn't go out of
the park (for a home run),'' Reynolds said, referring to the
434-foot distance to the center-field wall, one of the deepest in
the majors. ``Anywhere else, and maybe it's a tie ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The two runs marked the first given up by Reynolds since April
21, a span of 19 innings. Powell redeemed himself by striking out
Derrek Lee to end the inning, Lee's NL-leading 31st of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really want to give Floyd anything to hit, because he
can hurt you,'' Powell said. ``My slider is something I don't
really have a lot of command of right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner notched his ninth save by retiring the side in
order in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   How bad are things for the Marlins? They own the worst record in
the majors (6-19) and have scored the fewest runs (86). And if that
isn't enough, Sunday's starting pitcher, Alex Fernandez, left after
only seven batters with a pulled right groin.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez (1-2), making his third start since returning from the
disabled list, had to leave in the second inning. He winced in pain
when he came off the mound awkwardly after throwing a 2-1 pitch to
Eusebio. After missing all of last season following rotator-cuff
surgery, the righthander was once again placed on the DL after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored one run off Fernandez in the first inning.
Craig Biggio and Bill Spiers led off with consecutive singles, and
Jeff Bagwell drove home Biggio with a sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who entered the game in a 2-for-20 slump, had hits in
his first three at-bats, which included a pair of RBI doubles. He
doubled off reliever Brian Edmondson in the third and added another
double in the fifth to make the score 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to come in here, (against) a young team like this
and a little inexperienced, and go in and try to take all three
games,'' said Everett. ``You don't want to lose to this type of
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Though their pitchers pretty much did their job, the Marlins
just couldn't come up with the big hit they needed. Of their 33
hits in the three-game series, 29 were singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take (winning) three games anywhere,'' Biggio said. ``It
was a tough game. That's a tough field during the daytime. Both
teams played well, and it came down to the last batter. We were
fortunate to get a couple of runs early and hold on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
