<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1764 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTIFY-AZR &LR;      05-03 2465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTIFY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARFUL EYE: KEEPING WATCH ON SEX OFFENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDI VILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The house near the middle of East Driftwood Drive
looked just like any other on the block, save for the perfectly
manicured pansies, petunias and geraniums that beckoned the
attention of passersby.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before police showed up in this idyllic south Tempe
neighborhood, papering it with bright pink fliers, knocking on some
500 doors and inviting residents to a community forum. (Tempe is
near Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   The man who had cultivated such beautiful blooms was a convicted
sex offender. Things in the Lakes community changed.
</P>
<P>
   At the grocery store, a mother grabbed her young son's arm and
pointed to ``the bad man.'' Women veered off the sidewalk into the
middle of the street when they reached the block where the man
lived. Families stopped letting their children play in the front
yard without supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a natural reaction,'' said Roger Glenn, 57, the
man who had altered the dynamics of the neighborhood. ``But if they
talked to me, they'd get a different opinion. I'm not a danger.
Just give me a chance and I'll prove it. I don't need to go back.
I'm too old for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, more and more neighborhoods are being alerted
when a sex offender moves in. The year-long experience of the Lakes
shows how such news can pit neighbor against neighbor, with some
camped firmly against sex offenders like Glenn, saying their pasts
automatically make them a danger, and others arguing that they
should get another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, both sides find themselves forced to to confront
their fears, their prejudices and their notions of forgiveness. And
both sides ultimately change the way they live.
</P>
<P>
   Front gates in the Lakes were locked more than they weren't.
Doors got second deadbolts. Annette Capuchino got up three or four
times a night to check her house and make sure it was secure. She
bought a gun and obtained a concealed weapons permit. Pat Akey no
longer went outside after dark, yet she refused to buy
pepper-spray.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind notification is to create safer neighborhoods by
arming potential victims with the knowledge they need to protect
themselves. But is notification merely creating unnecessary
hysteria and hampering offenders from becoming productive members
of society?
</P>
<P>
   Fear is pervasive in newly notified neighborhoods, from the
mother who stands on the porch and watches her children walk two
doors down, to the dads who dust off their bikes to accompany
tikes, to the lady down the street who starts shooing kids toward
home when the sun goes down.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, Capuchino could be watching a movie when ``all of a
sudden I get this fear he's right there.'' She drove her daughter,
Alicia, to school each morning, even though it was a five-minute
walk, and Alicia had to call and check in the minute she got home
in the afternoon. She wasn't allowed to walk up to the store or to
ride her new 10-speed bike alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm getting a phobia,'' Capuchino said. ``But I need to
do everything I can to feel safe and I don't. I don't like living
next to this man.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't slip up. You can't be comfortable. Not with the
person this close. I'm mad and I'm scared. I had to change my life
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Capuchino saved $2,200 over three years to be able to move to
the Lakes with 15-year-old Alicia. She had been living in south
Phoenix but figured the Lakes, with its prestige and its better
schools and nicer houses would make her feel safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong,'' Capuchino said simply.
</P>
<P>
   She is moving when her lease expires at the end of the month.
(May) Capuchino said it's wrong that area residents had to change
their lifestyles around one man, and it's not fair that they had to
live always ``on our guard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever saw him, I'd probably spit on him,'' Capuchino said.
``Maybe he is a nice man, but I wouldn't want to know him like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   She is looking for a home in north Phoenix. Her first question
to any leasing agent, she says, will be ``Do you know of any
registered sex offenders in the area?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that homeowners have to answer honestly, and one
where a ``Yes'' likely means their property values will be
significantly affected.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakes is generally a friendly area, with tree-lined streets,
well-traveled bike lanes and man-made lakes. It's a mix of retirees
and families, but the people moving in seem to be getting younger.
The homes and townhouses are well-kept, and some people dock boats
to their back patios. Rover Elementary School, Fees Junior High
School and Marcos de Niza High School are minutes away on foot.
There are two day care centers within a mile or so and parks, one
at the end of Glenn's street.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing anyone expected was to hear that a sex offender
had moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Most found out about Glenn when they arrived home on a cold
December day to the pink flier stuck in their doors. ``SEX OFFENDER
NOTIFICATION,'' it said in bold black letters.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn served 10 years in prison after he pleaded guilty in 1987
to attempted sexual assault and attempted kidnapping. The victim
was a 33-year-old woman who met Glenn when she was looking for a
job at his bar.
</P>
<P>
   The woman told police that Glenn became violent when she shunned
his sexual advances after a night of drinking and that he pulled
off her sweater and punched her in the mouth, fracturing her jaw.
Glenn insists that the woman persisted in calling him even after he
filled the bartending position and that she took off her own shirt
and injured her jaw when she fell and hit her head on a table while
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn hasn't had a drink since then and he maintains that the
woman leveled the charges in the hopes of getting a financial
settlement. He says that he pleaded guilty because he thought he
would get probation. He was 44 years old and didn't have any
history of sex crimes. His past convictions were mainly for
white-collar crimes stemming from his ownership in Detroit of a
mortgage and real estate company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you think,'' Glenn said of his past, ``but I know
myself. I'm not really a bad person. . . I'm going forward. I'm not
going backwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to dwell on the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn would have moved quietly into the Lakes last May, but he
made a mistake in registering after he was released from prison two
years ago: He listed his address as a P.O. Box. Police tracked him
down in August and arrested him for failing to register as a sex
offender. He is now on three years' probation for that.
</P>
<P>
   The community notification was done at the Lakes in early
December. Glenn, residents were told, was ranked Level 3, meaning
he was in the group considered most likely to reoffend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Educational materials, including information about community
notification, registration requirements, sex offender facts and
personal safety rules for children, were provided to Lakes
residents at a forum held three days after the notification.
Residents also were reminded that it's against the law to threaten
or harass a sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   That warning may have spared Glenn the harassment that has
occasionally popped up across the country: vandalism, picketing,
beatings and verbal assaults. A single incident of a house burning
has been documented. And an Oregon offender had a gun pointed at
him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In September 1996, someone burned a Scottsdale man's bushes
after his conviction for statutory rape and child rape was revealed
in anonymous fliers. The man slipped away from the neighborhood, in
the dark, four days later. His neighbors said they were proud of
what they'd done, hugged each other and watched their children
cheering that ``the bad man's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More commonly, neighbors rally against sex offenders, making it
so uncomfortable for them that they either move away or decide not
to move in at all. Some offenders find themselves evicted or
repeatedly turned down for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``It used to be a societal value that you pay your debt to
society then go about trying to rebuild your life,'' said Eleanor
Eisenberg, executive director of the Arizona Civil Liberties Union.
``. . . I really don't understand the mentality that is more
interested in vengeance and punishment than in trying to remedy the
problem. We're not letting them move on and get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's just not realistic to expect society to give sex
offenders warm welcomes, equal privacy rights and immediate
acceptance, says David Beatty, the director of public policy for
the National Center for Victims of Crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because they have paid their debt to society doesn't mean
they have earned the trust of society. That is not instantaneous
just because they walked out of the prison gates,'' Beatty says.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Glenn tried to fit in. He kept his home immaculate
and planted fresh flowers as soon as the old ones wilted. He and
his girlfriend kept to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy doing what I'm doing now,'' Glenn said. ``I'm very
comfortable where I'm at. I like my freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn didn't see his neighbors much. He got up every morning in
the dark and strolled through the neighborhood streets. With two
Diet Pepsis and two bananas, he reported to work at a Tempe travel
agency at 9 a.m. He took a two-hour lunch and worked, setting
appointments over the phone, until 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a responsible person, in my eyes, in our society,'' said
Bill Fautsch, Glenn's boss. ``He pays his taxes. He just bought a
new car. He jogs. He's physically fit. This is not the animal they
typecast him as.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But a few neighbors initially wanted to circulate a petition
forcing Glenn to move. In the end, they changed their own lives
instead and learned to co-exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the idea of forgiving is there,'' said Akey, the block
watch captain on Glenn's block. ``. . . If he's on the level now,
if this is what should be, then maybe we should let it be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, forgiving is not an easy thing in neighborhoods where sex
offenders have moved in. Many find themselves unable to look past
the crime, especially if it involves children. And while some say
they are willing to dole out second chances to thieves or drug
addicts, sex offenders are held to a different set of standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been proven in a court of law as a sex offender and you
should be treated like one,'' Capuchino said. ``You should be
feared. He wants to walk around free and live a normal life, and I
don't think he should. I won't accept him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Geffen represented the other side of the debate. She's
``not a bleeding heart liberal,'' but Geffen prefered ``to believe
the best of him, that that night was a one-time thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I think everyone can make one mistake,'' Geffen said,
expressing an unpopular viewpoint. ``Any one of us, given the taste
or the temptation, might do something that we bitterly regret. I'm
sure there's not one of us who hasn't done something that we wish
we could take back, something that we say we'd give a year of our
life to take back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He sat out his 10 years and he deserves a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Statistically, there isn't any difference in the recidivism
rates of sex offenders who had been subject to notification and
those who had not, according to a 1995 study by the Washington
State Institute of Public Policy. However, the study did find that
offenders subject to community notification were arrested much more
quickly than comparable offenders who hadn't been subject to
notification.
</P>
<P>
   Of 125 of the most dangerous sex offenders released from
Washington State prisons between March 1, 1990 and Dec. 31, 1993,
18 of them, or 14 percent, were arrested for new sex offenses
within 54 months. And 63 percent of the new sex offenses occured in
the same jurisdiction where notification took place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Geffen said she never felt threatened or scared by
Glenn's presence. In fact, she still would greet him if she saw him
on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not condoning what he did. I think it's utterly
disgusting,'' Geffen said. ``If I had my druthers, of course, I'd
rather he not live down the street from me, but I just think the
poor guy has to live somewhere. And until he does something to
prove the opposite, he deserves a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   If he reoffends, she said, lock him up and throw away the key.
</P>
<P>
   Others found themselves unable to separate the intellect from
the emotion, the acceptance from the fear, the forgiveness from the
lingering prejudices. Although willing to concede that Glenn might
someday be able to prove himself to society and earn a second
chance, Akey steadfastly refused to be naive and say this
definitely wouldn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   In her most liberal days 20 years ago, Akey would have
befriended Glenn. She used to say, ``Hello'' to him, but once she
knew who he was, Akey admitted, ``I would put my head down, look
away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people feel he should have a second chance but on the
way is he going to hurt somebody who doesn't deserve to be hurt?''
Akey said. ``There's still that little bit of a fear. It is too
bad. I would hate to have that happen to me. I wouldn't want people
to hate me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fautsch, Glenn's boss, said he understands society's
apprehension about sex offenders, but he said that Glenn completed
the sentence that society handed down and it doesn't seem fair that
people judge him so harshly and won't let him move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we draw the line?'' Fautsch asked. ``It's OK for
Clinton to do what he did. Here I've got a fellow who comes to me
and is open and tells me about his crime, and he's persecuted for
it. It stung Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To make everything black and white and not make anything a
grey area, it's sad. He's a genuine and sincere individual. He has
changed. . . He just wants to finish his life in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn says he has everything to lose if he doesn't toe the line,
and he's not willing to throw it all away. Rather, like many
others, he just wants to do his job, pay his bills and put
something away for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need any trouble,'' Glenn said. ``I just want to fit
in. I just work hard and try to be a good person, and it'll all
take care of itself, right?''
</P>
<P>
   But on an overcast day late last week, (THURS 4/29. GLENN TURNED
IN THE KEYS TO HIS LANDLORD ON FRIDAY 4/30.) moving vans pulled up
to the house on Driftwood Drive and Glenn packed his things inside.
Neighbors let out a big hoorah: Glenn is buying a house somewhere
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   And another neighborhood will be notified about a sex offender
in its midst. Another neighborhood will be forced to confront its
intolerance. Another neighborhood will change the way it lives. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0049EDT &QL; 
