<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STRUGGLE EXPOSES CRACKS IN NEW YORK CITY POLICE UNION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Patrolmen's Benevolent Association has long
served as the unified voice and jut-jawed defender of New York City
police officers, the architect of a blue wall of solidarity that
supports them, right or wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But as the union prepares to elect a president this month, the
campaign is revealing deep divisions within its leadership, even as
many officers look to the organization for help in reviving the
force's flagging morale.
</P>
<P>
   The dissension is apparent everywhere, from the vitriol of stump
speeches to the gaping disagreements among the candidates about how
the union should deal with the Police Department and the public.
</P>
<P>
   In station house appearances and campaign attack advertisements,
the four candidates often billy club one another with the relish of
professional politicians, using terms like liar and ``captain's
water boy.'' to disparage their opponents. Two have even sued the
union, asserting that it has acted unfairly to help the incumbent
president, James Savage, hold onto his job.
</P>
<P>
   The very fact that there will be an election is evidence of a
splintered, weaker union. For the last two decades, the PBA has
used the ballot box to pick a leader about as often as the Vatican
does.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Caruso held the office unchallenged for 15 years, and
when he resigned in 1995, he bequeathed the job to a handpicked
successor, Louis Matarazzo. The last time the city's largest police
union had a contested election for president was in 1980, when
America's image of the police was formed by television series like
``Starsky and Hutch.''
</P>
<P>
   But there has been no seamless transfer of power this time.
</P>
<P>
   Many union dissidents complained last December when Matarazzo
resigned with six months left in his term, allowing Savage, the
union's first vice president, to serve as president until the next
election.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he took office, it was clear that Savage would have to
fight to hold the job as challenger after challenger emerged,
warning of the malaise that was spreading through the union's
27,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The mood has only darkened since. Though police officers have
been widely credited with causing the city's historic drop in
crime, many are walking their beats with drooping shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Their accomplishments have been overshadowed by accusations of
police brutality, racial insensitivity and excessive violence.
Their pay has fallen below that of many of their suburban
counterparts. And the union itself has been buffeted by a federal
investigation that has produced no indictments but has led to page
after page of unfavorable publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Savage has until May 21, when balloting begins, to convince
members that recent initiatives on his part, including a
no-confidence vote in the police commissioner that he engineered,
are evidence of a strong hand that will steer the union away from
the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   How he is doing is anyone's guess. Although the race has been
awash with the paraphernalia of modern politics, such as campaign
consultants and expensive fund-raisers, none of the four candidates
_ Savage; the union's recording secretary, James Higgins; the
Manhattan North trustee, Edward Mahoney, and a Brooklyn delegate,
Patrick Lynch _ have done any polling. They do not think officers
would be kindly disposed toward someone who called them at home to
pry into their political leanings.
</P>
<P>
   But the challengers, including the two longtime board members,
Higgins and Mahoney, have concluded that it is wise to talk about
reform in a union where power has long been closely held.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for reform stems in part from a two-year-old
investigation by the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan into
possible corruption in the union's financial dealings. Though the
investigation appears dormant, three of the union's old lawyers
were convicted last year of racketeering in a kickback scheme
involving a different police union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent events have led cops to believe that prosecutors are
against them, that the community doesn't understand them and that
their leadership in the Police Department and City Hall doesn't
support them financially,'' said Aaron Rosenthal, a former police
chief who teaches at John Jay College of Criminal Justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
