<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMCAST-MEDIAONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE CARRIER IS SAID TO PREFER AT&AMP;T MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board of MediaOne Group Inc., the big cable television
carrier, sent a letter on Saturday to Comcast Corp. informing the
company that MediaOne wanted to proceed with a proposed merger with
AT&AMP;T Corp., people close to the discussions said Sunday. In effect,
the letter began a five-day timetable under which Comcast has until
Thursday to come back with a counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has been in intense discussions with America Online Inc.
and Microsoft Corp., which is already an investor in the cable
company, about those companies supporting its bid. Paul Allen, a
founder of Microsoft who left the company in 1983, has also
expressed interest in joining Comcast.
</P>
<P>
   Fashioning a bid is difficult and several options are being
explored, people close to the talks said. Microsoft has no obvious
motive for antagonizing AT&AMP;T, though it does have huge cash
reserves, which would make Comcast's $53 billion stock offer more
competitive with AT&AMP;T's $58 billion stock-and-cash bid. America
Online has motivation because it wants assurance that cable
operators will offer its service to their customers, though they
have no legal obligation to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who owns cable systems with 4 million subscribers, might
want the alliance because it would let him swap some of his cable
systems for other more contiguous systems, one person close to the
talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast needs a cash infusion because offering more Comcast
stock would not only depress its price but would still be less
appealing than AT&AMP;T's cash-and-stock offer.
</P>
<P>
   For any player joining Comcast's bid, one issue will be who gets
control of Comcast. When Brian Roberts, the president of Comcast,
originally announced the proposed acquisition of MediaOne, Comcast
orchestrated a deal in which it would have retained control of the
merged company even though MediaOne was a larger company.
</P>
<P>
   A person who has long followed Comcast said he could not imagine
that the Roberts family would be satisfied with any arrangement in
which the giant cable operator gave up control to an outsider.
Whether that would appeal to America Online, Microsoft or Allen is
unclear, but it is certainly likely to be an issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
