<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-ELECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOW OF FORMER PRESIDENT WINS RACE IN PANAMA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: UPDATES lede with Moscoso victory; ADDS 7th graf for quotes) 
(ATTN: Fla., Texas)  (rk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Mireya Moscoso, the widow of a Panamanian
president who stepped out on her own politically to become the main
opposition leader here, narrowly defeated her main opponent Sunday
night,making her the country's first woman president.
</P>
<P>
   With just 55 percent of the vote counted, official tallies
showed Ms. Moscoso, 52, with 43 percent. Martin Torrijos, the
35-year-old son of the late Panamanian strongman, Gen. Omar
Torrijos, followed with 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moscoso will lead the administration that acquires the
Panama Canal from the United States at the end of the year under
the 1977 Canal Treaty negotiated by the general with President
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Vallarino, 47, of a third political alliance, trailed
with 17 percent. He conceded shortly after 8 p.m. and wished Ms.
Moscoso ``success in leading this country in one of the periods of
major challenges but also of major opportunities in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, Torrijos publicly congratulated the winner
and announced to his supporters that he would seek to become
secretary-general of the Revolutionary Democratic Party, reorganize
the party and prepare to run again in the 2004 elections ``for the
benefit of the motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure that we have a future and that time does not
stop at this moment,'' he said to wild cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 10 p.m., Ms. Mos-H coso was welcomed by
supporters at a hotel here with shouts of ``Mireya! Mireya!'' while
caravans of honking cars could be heard around the city. She then
promised to given an ad- dress from her party's headquarters later
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Mireya Moscoso didn't win,'' she said. ``The Panamanian
people won. We have a commitment with this country and thousands
and thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The president is elected by a simple majority for a five-year
term starting Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanians also chose two vice-presidents, 71 legislators for
the unicameral Legislative Assembly and 74 mayors in tranquil
elections that appeared to be the third clean election of recent
years, solidifying a break from the country's history of massive
election fraud and political coups.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among the 1.7 million registered voters was 74 percent,
and in many polling places the mood was relaxed, with little
partisan euphoria evident in or outside the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moscoso, owner of a coffee business inherited from her late
husband, Arnulfo Arias, for whom the Arnulfista Party was named,
ran on a populist platform that promised to end government
corruption and privatization policies that have left Panamanians
grumbling about higher rates for telephone and other services. This
was her second try at the presidency after losing 1994 elections to
the current president, Ernesto Perez Balladares.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This time, Ms. Moscoso had to overcome early polls that showed
her behind, criticism over her lack of college degrees and
government experience, and the ghost of the late general. Memory of
the general still resonates with many voters and his name was
constantly invoked by her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   To retaliate, she often referred to Torrijos, the candidate, by
the diminutive ``Martincito.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos, an economist with degrees from Texas A&AMP;M University
who served as deputy minister of government and justice in the
Perez Balladares administration, did not differ widely with Ms.
Moscoso on policy.
</P>
<P>
   The main thrust of his campaign was to offer a cleaner, less
arrogant image for the party once led by Gen. Manuel Noriega, who
was ousted in the American invasion of Panama in 1989 and is
serving a prison sentence in the United States on a drug-related
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In her campaign, Ms. Moscoso drew on the memory of another
charismatic politician: her husband. Arias died in exile in Miami
in 1988 after a long career in which he won three elections as
president, but each time was removed from office by opponents, the
last time in 1968 in a military coup that installed the general as
ruler.
</P>
<P>
   While some Panamanians quipped that the campaign was thus a race
between ``two corpses,'' many voters expressed a desire to break
with the past, which Ms. Moscoso said she would offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the selfish leadership in the government has
appropriated the riches and national assets while the great
majorities are increasingly impoverished,'' she said in a fiery
speech at her own campaign closing rally last week. ``I promise you
a different government.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting Sunday morning at a school here, Jose Aparicio, 54, owner
of a business that does electrical work, said he voted for Ms.
Moscoso because he believed in alternating the parties in power.
``It was the Arnulfistas' turn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repeated winners could think the country is theirs,'' he said.
``She has life experience and a strong character. You don't need
college to make good, logical decisions and think about the
country, not yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   With poverty and unemployment widespread, and a judicial system
in need of serious reform, many Panamanians also hope for a break
with the government corruption and nepotism of the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
