<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE-KNUCKLE TIME FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-A'S-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It might not rank with a locust invasion or
the killing of male first-borns, but for Jim Corsi, prince of
Newton, what is afflicting the Red Sox these days is something
straight out of the Old Testament, or a Steven Spielberg cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A plague,'' Corsi said after the Red Sox fell, 7-5, to the
Oakland A's, who in one weekend accomplished what it took them all
of last season to do _ beat the Red Sox twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pitching when we weren't hitting, when we scored eight
runs in seven games,'' Corsi said, ``and now the plague is we're
not pitching well, except for the little short guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pedro Martinez can only work every five days. In the
meantime, knuckleballer Tim Wakefield took another early powder
Saturday, failing to make it out of the fourth inning for the third
time in his last four starts, and Corsi couldn't hold a lead for
the second time in three games after he replaced reliever Tim
Harikkala with two on and one out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen's not doing too hot,'' acknowledged Corsi, who
walked the first batter he faced, Matt Stairs, gave up a two-run
single to the next batter, Jason Giambi, then a run-scoring double
to the Panamanian mystery man, Olmedo Saenz, who pronounced his hit
an act of sweet revenge after taking a Martinez bullet in the back
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wasted was a three-run home run by third baseman John Valentin,
his first homer in 70 at-bats and only the second three-run home
run by the Sox this season in 24 games, a dozen apiece in the
won-and-loss columns.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin's fifth-inning home run came off A's starter Tom
Candiotti in the first matchup of fellow knuckleballers Wakefield
has had since facing Dennis Springer of the Angels almost three
years ago (Aug. 16, 1996). It gave the Sox a 5-4 lead in a game in
which Wakefield faced only five batters before returning the 2-0
lead the Sox presented him on a double by Jose Offerman, Valentin's
infield out, Brian Daubach's misplayed triple, and Nomar
Garciaparra's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who has allowed 18 earned runs in just 15 innings
(10.80 ERA) in his last four starts, went single, double, single,
double, RBI infield out before getting out of the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   He loaded the bases in the third but escaped with just a yield
of one run (Scott Spiezio's sacrifice fly) when the A's ran into
outs in two rundowns on one comebacker to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   When Wakefield walked the first two batters he faced in the
fourth, he was done for the day. In his last four starts, he has
pitched a total of 15 innings. Even counting his days in
Pittsburgh, where he was released by the Pirates, he's never had a
stretch in which his starts were so short-circuited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a very good mood,'' Wakefield said quietly after
dressing. ``I don't have a whole lot to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The message from manager Jimy Williams was simple: He still
plans on giving Wakefield the ball, even though Wakefield has a 3-7
record, 7.00 ERA, and six starts of four innings or less in a dozen
starts dating back to Aug. 30. That includes the inning and a third
he lasted in a Game 2 playoff loss to the Indians last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just keep pitching him,'' Williams said. ``He's going to
start. He's going to turn this thing around. He could turn it
around real quick. His next start, he could pitch a shutout.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the knuckleballer's lot to endure such droughts. Last
season, Wakefield also got off to a slow start (0-1, 6.00 ERA in
five starts), then reeled off six wins in a row en route to a
career-best 17-win season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening with him right now is he's throwing 10 great
knuckleballs in a row, then the one he leaves up gets whacked,''
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``Every time he's making a
mistake, he's paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puzzling thing with him is that he's had good side
sessions and good warmups. Maybe he needs to use a little more of
that swagger, that confident feeling on the mound. It may be more
of a mental thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going through a tough spell right now, but he'll get it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had one last chance to come back when A's closer Billy
Taylor walked the first two batters he faced, putting the tying
runs on base in the ninth. But Daubach struck out, Garciaparra
popped to short center, and Troy O'Leary tapped to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing that a lot,'' said Garciaparra, who slammed
his bat down after just missing making solid connections. ``I've
got to keep swinging the bat. It's not like I'm trying to hit a
home run every time I'm up there.''
</P>
<P>
   He can't, because he seldom sees a pitch that he can drive.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, just file it under plagues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
