<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1774 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-BLUEJAYS     05-03 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-BLUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS RALLY FOR VICTORY AS HUSKEY SINGLE CAPS TWO-RUN NINTH 
</HEADLINE>
 JAYS-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Butch Huskey has seen what Robert Person does to
hitters with an 0-and-2 count. So with two outs in the ninth inning
Sunday, the Mariners right fielder figured his former roommate in
the minor leagues might throw a fastball well out of the strike
zone, then come back with high heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how I throw,'' Person said.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey had struck out three times off Toronto Blue Jays starter
Pat Hentgen, and he did not want to fan again. So he choked up,
hoping he could stay alive against Person with a foul ball.
</P>
<P>
   Person tried to come up and in, but missed in the strike zone.
It was a fatal mistake as Huskey lined the pitch into left field to
score Ken Griffey Jr. with the winning run in a stirring 3-2 win at
the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's mad,'' Huskey said, smiling. ``I'm sure he's
calling me every name in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Mariners side, there was only joy after a victory manager
Lou Piniella called one of his team's best. For the third time in
four days, the M's came from behind to win. The comeback was made
possible by pitchers Mac Suzuki and Ken Cloude, who together gave
up 15 runs to the Texas Rangers April 13 but had much different
results teaming up Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While Suzuki and Cloude kept the M's close, Hentgen enjoyed his
usual dominance in Seattle. The former Cy Young winner is 4-1 with
a 1.85 earned run average in six starts here. Sunday, he allowed no
hits to the last 17 batters he faced, striking out eight in 71/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed after Hentgen left the game. Reliever Peter Munro
got a double-play ball to end the eighth, but allowed a game-tying
homer to David Bell leading off the ninth. It was Bell's seventh
home run of the year _ more than Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, Albert
Belle and every member of the Colorado Rockies _ and it set up
Huskey's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's got more pop than Mac does,'' said M's catcher Tom
Lampkin, a former Cardinal. ``He's lucky he's not on the same team,
or (McGwire) would be taking a lot more flak than I'm giving him
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, whose career high is 10, isn't thinking about home runs.
The more important thing about the homer, he said, is that it came
on a 3-and-1 count. That's symbolic of the new approach Bell has
taken since Piniella called him into the manager's office during
the last road trip and stressed patience at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Since that meeting in Chicago, Bell has walked nine times. Prior
to the meeting, he had walked once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so happy in my life to walk as I've been the
last week,'' Bell said. ``Lou took the time to call me in, and not
only has it helped the team, it's helped me, too. To be able to
pull that off over the last week is a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki and Cloude (3-1) can share in those good feelings. Suzuki
made the team in part because he was out of minor-league options,
and his first three outings this season came in relief in blowout
losses. The last was the Texas rout, and Suzuki did not pitch again
for 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   He started Sunday because Brett Hinchliffe, who has options, was
sent to Class AAA Tacoma to make room for new outfielder Brian
Hunter. But Suzuki performed so well, he earned a place in the
rotation and will start Friday at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's start was broadcast live in Japan, where the first
pitch came at 5:40 a.m. The early risers saw the Kobe native retire
the first seven Blue Jays before allowing a homer to Mike Matheny.
Suzuki got another out, then allowed a single and consecutive
walks.
</P>
<P>
   With Eric Weaver warming in the bullpen, Suzuki fell behind
3-and-0 to the dangerous Carlos Delgado. But he escaped harm by
getting Delgado to ground to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, the pitches that Mac threw had enough movement that
he didn't get the good part of the bat on the ball,'' Lampkin said.
``But those are not situations you like to find yourself in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, though, Suzuki found himself in a similar
spot against a different Toronto slugger, Shawn Green. With two out
and two on, Suzuki struck him out on a pitch so nasty it couldn't
be defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to throw me a fastball, but I don't think that
was a fastball,'' Lampkin said. ``I came in the dugout and Lou
said, `What was that?' I said, `I don't know.' It was almost like a
split-finger or something that fell down pretty sharply at the end.
I almost didn't even get a glove on it. Whatever it was, it was a
good pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki left after allowing consecutive singles to open the
sixth. One of the runners scored, but Cloude followed with four
shutout innings. In five relief outings since starting that game
against Texas, Cloude is 3-0 with a 1.64 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki has claimed one rotation spot and John Halama is next in
line, but Cloude is content where he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pretty much accepted it from the beginning,'' he said.
``I just approach it as if every pitch was my last one. I think my
trouble in the past has come when I out-think myself and give the
hitters too much credit instead of worrying about what I can do and
what I can make happen. There's no doubt I'm a lot more
confident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
