<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN FIELDS CRITICISM, FIRES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-VALENTIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ John Valentin doesn't dispute the empirical
evidence. The fans' eyes are not deceiving them.
</P>
<P>
   It's true he failed to run out a ground ball last weekend at
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   It's true he was tagged out at the plate two weeks ago without
attempting to slide, also at home.
</P>
<P>
   It's true he let a popped bunt drop in front of him without
attempting to make a diving catch here the other day.
</P>
<P>
   And it's true that he hit just .195 in April while scoring only
seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   But it's how people choose to spin those facts that Valentin
challenges. The Red Sox third baseman, aware that he has become a
target of criticism, disputes anyone who questions his desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, it's been very frustrating, that's all I can say,''
Valentin said before driving in four runs Sunday with a three-run
home run, his first homer in 70 at-bats, and an infield out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fans should know this. This is my eighth year here,
and I bust my butt for them because they pay my salary. I play hard
for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I may not have run a ball out because of frustration
that I'm not playing well, but for someone to question my work
ethic when they haven't even seen me practice or how I prepare is
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin does not defend his failure to run out a ground ball
against the Indians last weekend. Had he run through the bag, he
may have been safe, because the throw pulled first baseman Jim
Thome off the bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no excuse for that,'' he said, ``but I probably was
disgusted with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   On the play at the plate against the Devil Rays, when he was
thrown out attempting to score from second, Valentin said he got a
late read on the play and consequently a poor jump, and the throw
from center field was up the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that it looked bad that I didn't slide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bunt attempt, which went foul Friday night, Valentin waved
off. ``If I thought I had a play, I probably would have dove,'' he
said. ``But in the spectator's eyes, I can see where someone might
have questioned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slow starts are nothing new, of course, for Valentin. Two years
ago, he hit just .160 in April. Last season, he hit .264 in April,
but followed that with a .216 average in May.
</P>
<P>
   He is showing signs of coming out of his slump, with hits in
seven of his last eight games, including two doubles and a single
Saturday and Sunday's home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the field, obviously, I'm not hitting,'' he said. ``I'm
trying to get that going, and it's been somewhat frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field? Those frustrations, Valentin keeps to himself. He
has nothing to gain talking any further about the absence of Mo
Vaughn, how it has impacted him both personally and professionally,
robbing him of a friend while weakening a lineup that needed
another righthanded bat even when Vaughn was here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to understand,'' he said, ``that I'm still
here, busting my butt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
