<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCHA BLASTS OFFSIDE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRANSTON, R.I. _ David Socha viewed the Revolution's 2-1 loss to
Colorado Saturday and, like coaches Giuseppe Galderisi and Walter
Zenga, he was not impressed by the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Socha has a different perspective than the Revolution leaders.
Socha was the top referee in the United States in the 1980s, the
only American to be selected for two World Cup finals and an
Olympic Games tournament. In fact, Socha retired soon after
refereeing Italy's 3-2 win over South Korea in the Mexico '86 World
Cup, a game in which Galderisi played.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were upset by the method of determining offside,
arguing that the linesmen were slow in signaling the violation.
According to Socha, the linesman, or referee's assistant, should
immediately raise the flag if offside occurs, but the referee has
the final say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the trouble with offside is that FIFA has confused the
linesmen,'' said Socha, who was inducted into the New England
Soccer Hall of Fame Sunday. ``They tell them not to call offside if
the players are even. But it is a split-second judgment and you
can't stand there and think it over. But how are you going to do it
when you've never played at that level? How are you ever going to
have the reactions?''
</P>
<P>
   Socha believes that MLS referees are at a disadvantage because
they are lacking top-level experience. The North American Soccer
League, which produced several FIFA referees, had a much higher
standard of play than the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were veteran players, but there were also great young
players,'' Socha said. ``Hugo Sanchez went on to become the top
goal-getter in Spain (with Real Madrid) and Bruce Grobelaar played
for years with Liverpool. Where are those type of players now?
</P>
<P>
   ``The NASL was producing some very good players and the New York
Cosmos were the Real Madrid of the Western Hemisphere and they were
drawing big crowds. The NASL was the most difficult league in the
world to referee because of the different nationalities and styles
of play. That made it a great training ground for referees at the
international level.''
</P>
<P>
   Socha understands the gamesmanship and cutthroat politics of
international soccer. Yet, after a dispute with the US Soccer
Federation he has not been used even in an advisory role by the
USSF or MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the professional game in this country is that
the people in charge are not qualified,'' Socha said. ``So many of
the inspectors never played the game at that level and don't
understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go from the college system to refereeing at the pro
level. That system is wrong. Where can they get experience? In the
ethnic leagues, where people are passionate and really know the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Revolution coaches pursuing the officiating crew
after the game, Socha said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The referee has to get respect from everyone. Once they know
where you are coming from, they won't do things like that. Listen,
these guys (Galderisi and Zenga) are coming from a place where they
go to school to learn how to bait the referee. They are very
refined about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, many of the referees are too young, and that is
because FIFA lowered the mandatory age of retirement, so they don't
have the experience. It's like a player; if you understand the game
you don't have to run needlessly. You pace yourself, like a player.
If you can read the game, you don't have to run all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In soccer, the referee is the maestro, the conductor. And the
game can be either a beautiful symphony or a catastrophe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0104EDT &QL; 
