<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER MAY HAVE RUN OF THE PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Over the past fortnight, he has been a
spectator. We've seen Antoine Walker cheer, coax, and wear some
serious threads. Monday night, he plans to be wearing something
different: A green-and-white uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' captain went through what coach Rick Pitino termed
``a walk-through-type'' practice Sunday at Healthpoint and said his
sprained left ankle felt fine. Barring a blowup, Walker said he
will be ready to go Monday night against the Knicks in Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have predicted this 15 days ago when Walker left MCI
Arena on crutches? Certainly not Pitino, who has been telling
everyone that Walker would not make it back. But we never heard
that from Walker. He vowed to return and it appears he will for the
final two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wait and see how it reacts,'' he said Sunday before
heading for the team plane. ``I went through the whole practice and
I did everything. We'll see how it feels, but I'm going to try to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said, ``He's out of shape, but he's moving well. He moved
well, he's not limping or anything. He's just out of shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Being out of shape, of course, is a no-no in the Pitino system,
but with only a couple games left, and with an opportunity to delay
the likely Knicks' playoff clincher, why not? It's not clear if
Walker would start, but the guess is that he will if he makes it
through the night without further pain or swelling.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics haven't missed Walker (or Kenny Anderson, for that
matter) as much as one might have thought. Boston won the game in
Washington after Walker went down five minutes into the game. Since
then, the Celtics have been 3-5, but only 1-4 at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Celtics have had some of their most efficient
offensive performances in that stretch. They shot 55 percent in a
still-astonishing 107-96 victory at Miami. They shot 54 percent in
a home bludgeoning of the Wizards and also won a wire-to-wire
thriller by 29 in Chicago. Since Walker went down, Paul Pierce has
averaged 21.5 points a game to lead the team in the last nine
games. He's been the top scorer in seven of the games.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting hurt, Walker appeared to be rounding into form.
In the game before the Wizards game, he had scored 29 against
Miami, including an improbable game-winning trey with 7-10ths of a
second to play. That more than made up for his 6-point performance
two nights earlier, one in which he was again booed by the
FleetCenter fans and subsequently offered that he might not be the
kind of player that Celtics fans embrace.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Walker also should give Pitino some manpower,
something he's sorely lacking. On Saturday against Milwaukee, his
bench consisted of Walter McCarty, Eric Riley, Marlon Garnett,
Damon Jones, and Dwayne Schintzius. All but Schintzius played. Only
McCarty (7 points) scored. The Bucks bench produced 44 points from
players such as Sam Cassell, Armon Gilliam, Vinny Del Negro, and
Michael Curry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics will have a say in who gets the last playoff spot in
the East. The Knicks got smoked Sunday by the Pacers (94-71) which
dropped them to 4-2 since Dave Checketts jettisoned general manager
Ernie Grunfeld. With Charlotte losing Sunday night to Miami, the
Knicks could clinch a playoff spot with a win Monday night because
they hold the tie-breaker over the Hornets . . . Anderson did not
make the trip. When asked why he wasn't going, especially since the
game was in his native New York, he smiled and cracked, ``because I
love Boston so much.'' . . . This will be Boston's ninth appearance
on network television, including NBC. They are 3-5 in big-time TV
games, with three of the losses coming to Indiana and two of the
wins coming against Miami. The other win was against New York Feb.
26 at the FleetCenter . . . One of the benefits of Walker's injury
has been a dearth of technical fouls. There've been only two
against Boston in the last nine games. One was for an illegal
defense violation and the other was assessed to Tony Battie for
hanging on the rim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
