r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-GRIEF-2takes-L     05-03 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-GRIEF-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER SHARES IN PERSONAL GRIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT and GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ This area's grief in the wake of the Columbine High
School shootings is as broad as a country mourning a national hero
but as personal as a family struggling with its most intimate pain.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Denver area, with more than 1.5 million residents,
is emotionally broken and still bleeding from the April 20 massacre
in suburban Littleton. People are struggling to regain a sense of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, while Coloradans joined with other Americans in
celebrating the release of three prisoners of war in Yugoslavia,
they also had to cope with yet another memorial service for the
Columbine students _ the final service, as it was billed.
</P>
<P>
   Across Greater Denver, billboards that would normally blare
sports slogans or National Rifle Association advertisements read,
``Pray for the Kids.'' And the marquee outside a Hooters restaurant
tells the children, ``Columbine, Our Prayers Are With You.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations play over and over the song ``Columbine,'' a
rallying cry written and sung by two classmates of the 12 students,
two killers and a teacher slain in the April 20 massacre.
</P>
<P>
   A Nordstrom store has shrouded its windows in silver and blue,
the school colors.
</P>
<P>
   Froggy's Flowers in Littleton has been flooded with requests for
colombine, a purple flower not yet in season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood Brother,'' a musical just in from London about a double
murder, has transformed from light entertainment into an operatic
tale of morality, with refunds offered to those who just couldn't
bear to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from being the Super Bowl champions to being a city
where we wonder if our children are safe, from a place where
everyone wondered whether Elway would retire to a worried city
filled with grief,'' said Dr. Robert Freedman, a Denver-based
national expert on mental disorders in children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole city changed in one week,'' added Freedman, whose
son once participated in a debate in the Columbine library, which
was turned into a bloody battlefield by Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community has lost its innocence,'' he sighed.
</P>
<P>
   As mountains of wilting flowers in Clement Park hallow the
nearby Rockies, a deeply religious community is turning its weeping
eyes inward and asking, What is wrong with our soul? What have we
done wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Denver's Archbishop Charles Chaput told nearly 2,000 mourners at
the funeral for sophomores Kelly Ann Fleming and Daniel Mauser that
a culture of killing in America, which permits abortion, euthanasia
and the death penalty, is very much to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be cut to the heart by what has happened, so that
we might personally convert and work for changes in society,''
Chaput said.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on the Family, a powerful religious organization in
Colorado Springs, has placed full-page ads in newspapers around the
metropolitan area. The ads urged readers to observe a moment of
silence on behalf of all those victimized by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening in Denver is people are putting their arms
around everyone, regardless of whether they believe or don't
believe in God,'' said H.B. London, vice president of Ministries
for Reach and Pastoral Ministries for the religious group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all lost children, we all suffered pain, and each of us
will deal with it with the resources we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The hauntingly personal nature of the killings, where students
were singled out and killed, has thrust a new layer of horror on
top of what has become an all-too-common phenomenon of kids killing
kids in American schools over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Shoels was gunned down because he was African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Cassie Bernall was killed after she professed her faith when
asked by a gunman if she believed in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion and faith are not at fault,'' said the Rev. George
Kirsten, Cassie's pastor at West Bowles Community Church. ``The
kids are really getting strength and hope in the same Christ Cassie
believed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Hummel, a grief counselor and clinical social worker at the
Denver Hospice, cautions the most profound grieving hasn't even
begun.
</P>
<P>
   Students from Columbine High School and people in the immediate
area are still in shock and will soon experience nightmares,
flashbacks and other types of post-traumatic stress as their lives
slowly regain normalcy, Hummel said.
</P>
<P>
   The grieving is going to be complicated because the killings
were sudden and unexpected, violent and destructive, random and
possibly preventable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of this, this event does not make sense. It has
blind-sided everyone,'' Hummel said. ``There is an inability to
grasp the meaning of this and has knocked everyone for a loop. You
feel secure about what your city stands for and its great quality
of life, and then it's like your secure base has been attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Hummel warned that maxims like ``God will provide for the
victims'' or ``God must have needed another angel'' are not
particularly helpful for those struggling to cope with a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The only real rules of grief support are to ``not tell people
how to be or how to view their loss,'' she said. ``Remember to
listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of others, Los Angeles musician Mark Spiegel says
he cried when he saw the vivid television footage of prostrate,
bleeding bodies lying on the pavement; rag-doll forms carried by
paramedics to waiting ambulances; and terrified teen-agers,
crouching next to walls before racing to safety with an awkward
gait.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel wrote a song and sent it to the Denver Post, hoping it
would find its way to survivors:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be with you, you'll be with us. ... We all have ways to
deal with grief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do something, just something. I have a 13-year-old
son,'' Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Marino, a 17-year-old senior, missed the gunmen by
minutes on his way back from lunch. His best friend Patrick Ireland
wasn't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland will be forever remembered as the boy who galvanized the
nation when he broke out a library window and tumbled _ limp and
bleeding _ into the arms of a SWAT team below on live TV.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hurtful,'' Marino said quietly yet so stoically, last
week as he left Centura St. Anthony Hospital, that it made the
grown-ups by his side weep.
</P>
<P>
   In an agonizing procession of eulogies for the dozen students
killed and for teacher Dave Sanders, as well as at a private
service attended by a handful of people for one of the killers, the
only question that mattered was, Why?
</P>
<P>
   Pastors struggled for the right words.
</P>
<P>
   ``God holds us in the palm of God's hand,'' said the Rev. Dwight
Blackstock of Grace Presbyterian Church, as he stood before the
coffin of 15-year-old Daniel Lee Rohrbough.
</P>
<P>
   What else can one say when the pallbearers aren't even old
enough to drive?
</P>
<P>
   Columbine senior Nick Foss still trembles when he speaks of
Danny, wishing he could have comforted the boy who died by his
side. ``But he was already gone,'' Foss said.
</P>
<P>
   Foss' friend Kevin Aberd, a Columbine senior, said it hurts to
see how hard his classmates are taking it all. A week after the
shooting, he worries whether Foss is moving on. But grief is such a
private matter, and he respects that.
</P>
<P>
   Aberd was barricaded in the choir room for three hours, praying
for help, as gunfire and exploding pipe bombs replaced the sound of
baritones. Now he flings his grief into the sky with every flip of
his Frisbee. ``We're trying to move on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the marrow of the matter, where the desire for revenge meets
the hope for healing, moving on can be nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I wish to God they'd catch the other kids,'' Aberd said,
speculating with deputies that other teen-agers may have been
involved in planting bombs inside the school. But what should
happen then, what is just and fair and right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I really don't,'' Aberd said after hesitating.
</P>
<P>
   A world of pep rallies, proms and adolescent anxieties poses
inherent limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the teen-agers are trying to pick themselves out of a
morass of hate with the confidence of youth and the last shreds of
innocence that remain in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Columbine! We are Columbine!'' The cheer rumbled
through the crowd of at least 70,000 at last week's memorial, an
inexorable, defiant chant of solidarity and of a promising future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give people a hug, say hi to everyone, say, What's up?'' Aberd
suggested. ``Make sure you say it to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But after all the hellos and goodbyes, the healing must begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a heck of a lot of loneliness in the Denver area,''
said Dick Berger, a Jefferson County resident and executive
director of a small, volunteer-based suicide, depression and crisis
hotline based in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency in suburbia to cover things up or to not
acknowledge problems and those who are different. In my estimation,
that can be a goddamned pain in the tush,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Garbarino, a Cornell University professor and author
of ``Lost Boys,'' a book about troubled teens, stressed there can
be no simple, easy or formulaic answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we persist in calling these just senseless killings by
wacko kids, then we are almost guaranteeing this kind of thing will
happen again,`` Garbarino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are, then the social factory that produces this
product will continue. The answer is to stop the factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurting and troubled boys crash to Earth _ sometimes taking
others with them _ when the stresses of their lives pile up
intolerably. Shame, abuse, mental illness and appealing but dark
subcultures all contribute, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine, a boy building a tower of blocks out of those
things,'' Garbarino said. ``Then it falls, and which block do you
blame?''
</P>
<P>
   Adults have not found effective ways to penetrate the mask of
normalcy that so many at-risk teens wear while living in a kind of
parallel universe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Easily available guns, point-and-shoot video games, deadly codes
of silence among teen-agers, and an obsession with material
possessions affect troubled teens in ways that today's parents,
teachers and mental health providers often can't counteract.
</P>
<P>
   Too often adults withdraw and simply ``cross their fingers,''
Garbarino said.
</P>
<P>
   Outcast juveniles are more likely to adopt deadly roles as their
fascination with darker aspects of culture increases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are prone to the melodramatic,'' Garbarino added.
``And these boys have a tremendous sense of righteousness, of a
higher purpose and of legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the truth may be that the grief will never
entirely disappear in Denver, said Robert Kladifko, the Reseda High
School principal who in 1993 carried dying senior Micheal Ensley in
his arms to the school nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you learn to handle it,'' Kladifko said. ``You learn to
cope.''
</P>
<P>
   The school has developed a nationally recognized violence
intervention program, Weapons Are Removed Now, where, starting in
elementary school, kids are taught to report weapons on campus. It
also has a ``unity council,'' where schoolteachers act as watchdogs
and conflict counselors. Now students are writing letters of
encouragement to Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the hurt so fresh, there are signs that hope is
beginning once again to bud at the high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be OK,'' Aberd said.
</P>
<P>
   Then expressing one hard-learned lesson of the tragedy, he
added, ``We're not just a school. We're a family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
