<HEADLINE>
LUKAS'S EYES TRAINED ON ANOTHER DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
 DERBY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Trainer D. Wayne Lukas already has won four
Kentucky Derbys, but his quest has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   When Charismatic crossed the finish line first in Saturday's
125th Run for the Roses at Churchill Downs, it tied Lukas with H.J.
Thompson, who won the Derby twice in the 1920s and twice in the
'30s. The only one in front of Lukas now is Ben Jones, legendary
trainer of Calumet Farm, who won six, one in the '30s, four in the
'40s, and one in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why I can't break the record,'' said the
63-year-old Lukas Sunday. ``I like what I'm doing, I have the
clientele, and I could win a few more. I've got 60 2-year-olds, and
some of them we like.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who first participated in the Derby in 1981, has started
a record 35 horses in America's greatest race, and his winners
before Charismatic were Winning Colors (1988), Thunder Gulch ('95),
and Grindstone ('96). Lukas also has won the Preakness four times.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Derby, in which he was 31-1 ($64.60 to win) under
Chris Antley, Charismatic had run 14 races and won only three
times. Until he captured the Grade II Lexington at Keeneland April
18, his only two victories had come in claiming races. Charismatic,
a true distance horse, outlasted the others in the Derby, while
running 10 furlongs in a slow 2:03 1/5, but it is highly unlikely
he will be favored in the Preakness at Pimlico May 15, an event
much more conducive to speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK, the horse doesn't know,'' said Lukas. ``Charismatic
was a claimer because I misread him very badly. That's when the
experience factor as a trainer came into play. I changed up on him,
giving him long, fast gallops, and it worked. It could have gone
the other way, and he'd have been running for a $35,000 claiming
tag. But I've learned you have to take your shot.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Charismatic, who was astutely kept wide
by Antley, took advantage of the crowding, bumping, and blocking
that went on in the 19-horse field. The roughness of the race
eliminated several logical contenders, most notably the Bob
Baffert-trained entry of Excellent Meeting and General Challenge,
which was favored at 3-1. Not surprisingly, Lukas is not in favor
of reducing the Derby field from the allowed maximum of 20. The
Preakness, for example, allows only 14 (determined by overall
earnings), the number that can fit in one starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask the people who put up the money for the
high-priced yearlings not to run in the Derby,'' said Lukas. ``You
can't take away their dream. What should we do, make the Indy 500 a
six-car race?''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic's triumph concluded a sensational week for Lukas,
who was elected into the Hall of Fame Tuesday, and he has, at least
temporarily, regained his position atop the training leaderboard
from Baffert, who had saddled the previous two Derby winners. There
is some rivalry between the two, especially where owners Bob and
Beverly Lewis are concerned. The Lewises employ both as trainers,
and allow Baffert and Lukas to pick the yearlings they buy. Baffert
came up with Silver Charm, who won the Derby for the Lewises in
1997, for $120,000, and Lukas recommended Charismatic, who cost
$200,000. And, Sunday, Lukas couldn't resist a good-natured shot at
Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat everybody who showed up, that's all we can do,'' said
Lukas. ``Did I out-train the other guys or what? That sounds like
Bob Baffert.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing is a money game, and Lukas freely admits he likes to
count his cash. When he spoke about his election to the Hall, he
mentioned that the fact his stable is on the verge of becoming the
first to earn $200 million in purses was his proudest
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he was asked, other than the history involved, what
thrilled him most about taking the Derby. ``The $886,200 that goes
to the winner.'' he replied. ``Old Wayne has a lot of bills to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The list of horses whose connections are considering the
Preakness numbers 18, including 11 who contested the Derby. In
addition to Charismatic, who will seek the Triple Crown; Menifee,
who was second; Cat Thief, trained by Lukas and third; Prime
Timber, trained by Baffert and fourth; Kimberlite Pipe, sixth;
Worldly Manner, seventh; K One King, eighth; Lemon Drop Kid, ninth;
Stephen Got Even, 14th; Adonis; 17th, and Vicar, 18th, are being
pointed to Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven horses who did not run in the Derby, but appear
headed to Baltimore, Silverbulletday, who won the Kentucky Oaks for
Baffert at 1-10 in a tour de force, would be the biggest threat.
Also in that group are: Patience Game, impressive winner of the
Derby Trial; Talk's Cheap, winner of the the Tesio Stakes, a
Pimlico prep for the Preakness; Millions, third in the Tesio as the
choice, Torrid Sand, third in the Arkansas Derby; Forty One Carats,
second in the Flamingo at Hialeah; and Badge, fourth in the Wood
Memorial as the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot written about Valhol, who was allowed to enter
the Derby only after a court ordered the purse he won in the
Arkansas Derby released following controversy over whether his
jockey used an electrical device during the race. However, Valhol,
who won the Arkansas Derby as a maiden, performed poorly, as most
observers suspected he would, fading to 15th after taking the lead
under Willie Martinez. ``I don't know where he'll go, but there are
some good races coming up right now,'' said trainer Dallas Keen.
``I don't think that we are going to the Preakness. We'll go to
Lone Star (outside Dallas) for a while, and see how he does. Hey,
he's eligible for non-winners of two races at Lone Star. I
definitely did not want him on the front end. He jumped tracks the
first time past the wire, and when the jock reached up to grab him,
he just took off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
