<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It had been almost a year since the Anaheim
Angels had gotten a complete game from their pitching staff. It has
been a lot longer since any of their pitchers has received much
respect.
</P>
<P>
   But when Omar Olivares went the distance Sunday night to defeat
the Chicago White Sox 6-3 in front of 34,737 at Edison Field, the
Angels had the look of a team that had found a missing ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive game, their starters pitched at least
seven innings. Sure the Angels got home runs from Garret Anderson
and journeyman Tim Unroe. But it was Olivares' night that gave the
Angels (12-13) their fourth victory in five games and represented
what the rotation can mean to the team's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what is going to make the difference in this season,''
manager Terry Collins said. ``We have an excellent bullpen, but you
have to take the load off them. Guys are starting to come up big.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares (3-2) needed just 102 pitches to get through a White
Sox lineup that battered closer Troy Percival for five ninth-inning
runs Saturday night. Percival, who had pitched in three of the four
previous games, warmed up Sunday but wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was important to me,'' said Olivares, who also pitched
the Angels' last complete game, on May 22. ``Every night,
(Percival) is up. Every night, the offense is doing big things. But
we know we have good starters. Now it is showing.''
</P>
<P>
   Today will be another test when the struggling Tim Belcher faces
the White Sox in the final game of an eight-game homestand. Belcher
blew a 10-run lead to Toronto in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares allowed five hits and two earned runs, including Chris
Singleton's first major-league home run. He got 16 ground-ball
outs, two on a dazzling stop by third baseman Troy Glaus that
started an inning-ending double play in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Plays like that kept the White Sox, one of the league's surprise
teams, from getting to Olivares. The Angels roughed up Chicago
left-hander Jim Parque (3-2) for eight hits and four runs in five
innings, but Collins said if the game had been close, he would have
used Percival in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if he could go and he said, `Yes,''' Collins said.
``That's what we pay him for.''
</P>
<P>
   Parque, the former standout at Crescenta Valley High School and
UCLA, has been the top left-hander on a White Sox staff that leads
the American League in ERA.
</P>
<P>
   But after Singleton's homer gave Chicago a 1-0 lead in the
third, the Angels immediately got the run back on an RBI single by
Salmon. They added two more in the fifth when Parque walked the
bases loaded and Salmon and Glaus had back-to-back sacrifice flies.
Parque was done after just two batters in the sixth. Unroe opened
with a home run to left, his first in the majors since 1997 when he
played with Milwaukee, and Matt Walbeck walked.
</P>
<P>
   In came right-hander Keith Folkes, who appeared to get out of
trouble when he retired Mo Vaughn and Tim Salmon with the bases
loaded to end the sixth. But Glaus opened the seventh with a double
and Anderson hit his fifth homer to give the Angels a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was all Olivares, who was coming off his worst outing
of the season, a 10-1 loss to Toronto last Monday. He retired 10 of
the final 11 batters. The only one to reach was catcher Mark
Johnson, who got on when Olivares bobbled his comebacker to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we have been playing on defense, I guess I had to be
the one to mess things up,'' Olivares said. ``But I could tell by
the second inning that things were going well. My sinker was
working inside and out.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley knows that is not always enough. He pitched seven
strong innings Saturday only to lose a chance for the victory when
Percival blew the save opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley knows the Angels might be onto something good.
Beginning last Thursday when Ken Hill allowed one run in seven
innings, Angels starters have given up eight runs in 302/3 innings,
a 2.40 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is going to hit,'' Finley said. ``It always seemed
the starters couldn't string anything together. Now it does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
