<HEADLINE>
PETTY TUNES UP FOR MOTORCYCLE TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Kyle Petty finished six miles shy of the full
distance during Sunday's NAPA California 500 at the California
Speedway. That was just a tuneup for the trip he's going to embark
on this morning from Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth consecutive year, Petty will lead a motorcycle
caravan cross-country to his home in North Carolina. The Kyle Petty
Charity Ride Across America, sponsored this year by Hot Wheels,
will get under way at 10 a.m. This year's route will cover 2,863
miles and is expected to draw more than 250 riders.
</P>
<P>
   Participants for the week-long ride include members of the
racing Petty family, Richard and grandson Adam and Winston Cup
drivers Steve Park, Kenny Schrader, Joe Nemechek, Geoffrey Bodine
and Robert Pressley.
</P>
<P>
   Petty has raised more than $1 million for various children's
charities and the Winston Cup Racing Wives Auxiliary Trust Fund.
The group will stop along the route to visit several children's
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun thing to be associated with,'' said Petty. ``I
really enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Sunday's race, Petty finished 26th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just never ran. We had a good, basic race, we just didn't
run good,'' said Petty, who unveiled a new paint scheme that
featured the charity ride's logo. EARLY EXIT: Johnny Benson didn't
get much time on the track. On the third lap, the driver of the No.
26 Cheerios Ford made contact with the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what happened,'' said Benson. ``It got a little
loose in one, but that was my fault for getting too high and then
it was fine. I went down in turn three and it came around so fast I
don't know if something broke or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much a junked car.''
</P>
<P>
   AIR CONTROL: It did not seem nearly as crowded on the two-mile
speedway as it did in the airspace above. Nine airplanes towed
various signs over the crowd, while three helicopters hovered in
and around that traffic. The Goodyear blimp, based in Carson, also
made an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Overcast skies in the morning prevented the crowd from viewing a
pair of F-16 jets from the 144th Fighter Wing at March Air Force
Reserve Base in the traditional fly-by. Major John Cotter called
for two passes, but the jets couldn't get under the cloud cover for
safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The low ceiling also prevented a 30-person skydive.
</P>
<P>
   BONUS MONEY: A total of $55,500 in bonus money was not awarded
on Sunday, including the NASCAR Winston Leader bonus worth $50,000.
If Jeff Gordon, winner of the race, had also led the points he
would have cashed in. Runner up Jeff Burton maintained the points
lead. The remaining $5,500 was dependent on qualifying, which was
rained out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Burton did cash in on the Gatorade Front Runner Award, worth
$10,000 for leading at the halfway point. Gordon crew chief Ray
Evernham picked up $7,200, which was more than his driver.
Evernham's pit strategy was worth $4,200 and being the winning crew
chief netted him another $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   OVERNIGHT WORK: Long before the first fan arrived at the
speedway on Sunday, speedway maintenance crews had worked long and
hard on painting the walls. According to operations director Ed
Straub, Jr., the crews used 30 gallons of white paint to remove the
various marks made by Busch Grand National and Winston West cars
during their races on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
