<HEADER>
A1790 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STEWART-LADN     05-03 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STEWART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART TAKES BIG STEP TOWARD ROOKIE OF THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM GAZZOLO  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Despite a foot fault that cost him pain all
day, Tony Stewart kept a leg up on most of the field. Sure, he
showed his rookie status a couple of times Sunday, but by the end
of the California 500 he was the only one who noticed. And he
noticed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old, who is driving up a storm in his first season
on the Winston Cup circuit, took a huge step toward winning Rookie
of the Year honors. That step, however, landed on two very painful
feet. Stewart forgot to put on his heel pads before the race, only
realizing the mistake when he pulled out of pit row for the parade
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them hanging on my mirror,'' he said. ``That was my
fault, no question about it. It started bothering me at about lap
50, but I had a job to do, and I had to hang with it.''
</P>
<P>
   While his feet soaked in ice water, Stewart reflected on a day
of highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the way we ran,'' said Stewart. ``I made a lot
of mistakes out there and they showed, but we hung tough. I learned
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished the race fourth, best of his young career in Winston
Cup. He also made his car owner, Joe Gibbs, happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day for Tony,'' said Gibbs. ``He fought through
some troubles and made the needed adjustments to finish the race.
He is coming on strong as a driver and learning every week. We
can't ask for much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart showed he can survive near-disaster as well. After
starting the race from the seventh spot, he quickly moved up the
field, reaching third once. He was in fourth place when he got
caught in traffic coming out of turn two on lap 147.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck behind Rusty Wallace, among others, he was trying to pass
and nearly lost control of his car. Instead, he avoided spinning
out by hitting the brakes, a move that saw his car begin to slide
and eventually cost him seven positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your heart skips a beat when you start to lose a 3,600-pound
car, that's for sure,'' said Stewart. ``It reminded me of my days
on the dirt tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart recovered, regained his poise and ultimately his
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That showed what kind of a driver Tony is,'' said Gibbs. ``He
learned from that and was able to get back into the thick of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The move also impressed his crew chief, Greg Zipadelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has a ton of talent,'' said Zipadelli. ``He is smart and
aggressive. Those things got him out of trouble and kept him
racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fine line between being aggressive and being stupid,
and Tony seems to know where that line is and doesn't cross it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-place finish marked the ninth time in 10 races that
Stewart has been the fastest rookie. It also topped his career-best
Cup showing of fifth, which he set last week at Talladega. Stewart
also improved a spot in the Winston Cup standings, moving from
seventh to sixth. He is trying to become the first rookie since
Jody Ridley (7th) in 1980 to finish in the top 10 in the final
points standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a great showing,'' said Zipadelli. ``I think we
are ahead of schedule. He is still a rookie and still has a lot to
learn, but he is learning quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell Stewart how good he is, he doesn't want to hear
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see guys like Jeff Gordon and Jeff Burton out there, and
you see what they do week in and week out. That's where you have
got to go to win consistently out here. You have to be consistent
and that's what we are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be happy with the way we raced today. The team did a
great job, but we have a lot more work to do, and we all know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's feet are firmly planted on the ground, but they are
just a little sore right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
