<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-ROCKETS-     05-03 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Every now and then, a team just needs to slap around the Clippers.
Having failed to do it then, the Rockets desperately needed to now.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No team might have needed to enjoy itself more. Winning would
not be sufficient. The Rockets needed to run and have fun. It
didn't matter to the Rockets that it was the Clippers. The Rockets
needed to strut again.
</P>
<P>
   So with Charles Barkley and Scottie Pippen forcing the break and
pledging to press the accelerator the rest of the season, the
Rockets ran and laughed to a 110-84 rout of the Los Angeles
Clippers on Sunday night at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   The win could not repair the damage in the standings or to the
ego wrought over the past two weeks. But so desperate were the
Rockets to win, and enjoy themselves after they handled the
Clippers, who were playing out the string in the second game of a
road back-to-back, Pippen declared: ``It was a great win. We needed
a win like this for our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Barkley said he and Pippen decided to run and
enjoy themselves. They forced tempo from the outset, rarely went to
the usual half-court, low-post game and scored easily. They had the
most prolific first half of the season and finished with a flurry
of 3s. Along the way, they led by as many as 30 points and never in
the second half allowed the Clippers to get closer than 14.
</P>
<P>
   And though their 19 fast-break points were fewer than in recent
wins over the Lakers and SuperSonics, and for that matter their
loss to the Clippers, they seemed more active, aggressive and
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the mentality we have to have going to the
playoffs,'' Barkley said. ``We just have to build upon that.''
</P>
<P>
   With two regular-season games left, and reeling from losses in
five of their past six games, the Rockets rolled from the outset to
keep pace with the Lakers, 91-84 winners in Seattle on Sunday. The
teams are tied in the race for the fourth seed and home-court
advantage in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets face Minnesota on Tuesday and are at Denver on
Wednesday. The Lakers, holding the tiebreaker over the Rockets, are
home for Dallas tonight and Portland on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Rockets clinched at least the fifth seed. With
the Rockets' recent slide, until Sunday Phoenix had remained in
range to catch the Rockets for the fifth seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a much-needed win,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``It got us off the schneid and keeps us in the race for the
home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do the best we can, and somebody has got to help
us. If it (reclaiming the home-court advantage) doesn't happen,
we'll deal with the hand we're dealt and go from there. We've done
that before.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, Sunday's win was not about home-court
advantage or next week. It wasn't even about feeling like a
contender again. The Rockets said they needed to enjoy themselves
on the court, to get get their rookies running and their defense
moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody enjoyed that game,'' said guard Brent Price, who
came off the bench for 15 points and five assists in 21 minutes.
``We have not played well lately. We had that monkey crawling on
our backs. To go out there and relax, have fun out there and play
some ball, to enjoy that experience, is big. We need to build on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   They seemed to build on it as the game progressed. As if to
demonstrate that they would not rely on the post-up game and
3-point shooting, they ended the third quarter with a run without
posting Barkley or Hakeem Olajuwon (20 points) inside or taking a
3.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley scored on an alley-oop inbounds pass from Pippen
to beat the shot clock, then set up Barkley for a layup. Michael
Dickerson had his second dunk in three minutes, before Mobley
scored on two drives and a 22-footer, pushing the lead to a then
game-high 20, 80-60.
</P>
<P>
   But before they would settle for a solid but unspectacular win,
they found the touch outside to turn it into a rout. Leading by 18
after a Pippen 3, the Rockets went three minutes without scoring as
the Clippers moved within 86-72 with eight minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next four minutes, the Rockets found the range
outside. Pippen, who finished with 14 points, seven rebounds and
seven assists, pulled up for another 3 before Sam Mack, who had
made just one of his first five shots, hit a 3 from the corner and
got on a roll. Price hit a trey, and when Pippen missed on a fast
break, Olajuwon was there to put in the follow.
</P>
<P>
   Price missed a 3, but Pippen grabbed the rebound and hit another
3, his third of the quarter. And when Mack nailed another trey with
2:50 left, the Rockets had a 17-6 run and a 25-point margin.
Leading 103-78, Tomjanovich had his first chance in weeks to clear
his bench with enough time to let them get sweaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starters have been carrying a lot of heavy minutes. It's
always good when everybody gets the opportunity to get into the
ballgame,'' Pippen said. ``We haven't played great ball over the
last five or six games. We needed to come out strong, take this
team out early, not let them have any confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Rockets reclaimed enough of their confidence
to put their recent past behind them, even to expect more of the
same when they are not sharing the court with the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty important for us to get out and play with
intensity,'' Rockets forward/center Antoine Carr said. ``That is
something we've been lacking. We need this same type of intensity
until this season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt good to win the way we did. We still have a long
ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But they knew though it might have been a small step, they took
it at full speed and in the right direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
