<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BURTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON CONTENT WITH SECOND-PLACE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HELMS  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ It was tough to see Jeff Gordon by the end of
the California 500 Sunday, but Jeff Burton had as good a view as
anybody. And he knew any hopes of catching the winner at the end
were futile.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won the race for the second time in three years and all
Burton could do was settle for a distant second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 24 car got out ahead of us a little bit too far,'' Burton
said. ``All you want is to have a chance to win at the end and we
didn't quite get that chance. Once he got half a straightaway in
front of us, we were pretty much done.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton appeared to be closing the gap at the end, but Gordon's
winning margin was still more than four seconds. Burton wondered if
Gordon wasn't just coasting a bit with such a large lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know that he was running as hard as he could run (at
the end),'' Burton said. ``I suspect that he wasn't. All day long
we were pretty much equal to him, and you don't just all of a
sudden, unless they're running poorly, start picking up three or
four tenths a lap. I don't know how we would have been with him.
Our car was good at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton was more than happy to take his second-place finish,
especially considering the way his car ran earlier in the week.
There was no qualifying for Sunday's race because of Friday's
persistent rains, and Burton got the pole because of his standing
in the points race. He considered that a blessing because the
practice laps he took around the track on Saturday were less than
scintillating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't been rained out, we probably would have qualified
30th,'' Burton said. ``We didn't like the way the car was running
in practice. We were the third-fastest car, but we weren't the
third-best car by any means. After about 15 laps, our car was
really bad. We had to make huge improvements to the car if we were
going to compete with the 24.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton felt better about his chances once he got out on the
track Sunday. Although he immediately lost the lead to Dale
Jarrett, he was able to run with the leaders all afternoon. He and
Gordon battled fairly evenly in the early stages of the race. The
turning point came when Ricky Rudd hit the wall on lap 133, drawing
a caution flag, and Burton was caught in the pits. By the time he
returned to the track, he was a lap down from the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Gordon, who was also in the pits, was able to get
out just in front of the pace car so he stayed on the same lap.
Burton got the lap back later in the race and was able to quickly
fight his way back into the top five. He eventually ran down Bobby
Labonte for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``To battle back from being a lap down that late in the race and
getting second was pretty good,'' Burton said. ``I got a little bit
loose at the end and couldn't make up enough ground (to catch
Gordon).''
</P>
<P>
   The second-place finish did enable Burton to increase his points
lead over second-place Jarrett to 55 points. Gordon moved up to
fourth, 200 points behind. Third place belongs to Labonte, 154
points behind Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burton is hanging in there strong,'' Gordon said. ``He's
running well; that's why they're where they're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who wound up fifth last year in points with career-highs
in top-five and top-10 finishes, is getting the job done with
consistency. He has finished 11th or better in nine of the 10 races
this year, including a pair of victories. He also recorded his best
finish at California Speedway. He was 10th here last year and 30th
in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
