<SLUG> BC-POW-JACOBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. RABBI MEMBER OF JACKSON DELEGATION TO BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Rev. Jesse Jackson tapped religious
leaders for his bold effort to free three American soldiers held
captive in Yugoslavia, Rabbi Steven Jacobs of Woodland Hills was
honored to join the humanitarian mission.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Jewish leader has traveled abroad to aid Cambodian
and Laotian refugees and Russian refuseniks, but the journey into
the heart of a nation bombed daily by NATO forces was his most
dangerous challenge yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew this was a dangerous mission. They made the choice to
put themselves in harm's way. This was the window of opportunity
that they saw to get these men out,'' said his wife, Linda Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have faith as well and I believed he would be safe, though I
was realistic to know they were in a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Jacobs and the others in the 19-member interfaith
delegation were returning to the United States on Sunday after
Jackson convinced President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to
release the soldiers a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation left with freed soldiers on a bus to Croatia and
then were flown to a U.S. military base in Ramstein, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud. For someone who has a passion for humanity and
civil rights, this is what it's all about,'' Linda Jacobs said &UR; , &LR; 
after speaking with her husband by phone from the base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi's involvement was a good omen for the mission, said
Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, who joined a congressional
delegation to Italy, Albania, Macedonia and Brussels, Belgium over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been involved in the moral issues of our country,''
Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly the U.S. position that these soldiers were
held immorally and illegally,'' Sherman noted. ``Having a
delegation made up of people who are known for their human rights
was important to the successful mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi and the reverend have joined for a variety of
interfaith efforts over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, rabbi of Kol Tikvah, a Reform congregation, attracted
Jackson's attention with his efforts to create new bonds between
Jewish and African-American congregations. Jackson spoke at the San
Fernando Valley Interfaith Council celebration of Martin Luther
King Jr.'s birthday last year.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Jacobs and Jackson laid a wreath for three civil
rights workers who were slain near Philadelphia, Miss., in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the call to join the mission to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very excited about it and really wanted to be part of
this because he believed a humanitarian approach might be a way to
get these men home,'' Linda Jacobs recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Yugoslavia on Wednesday, the delegation met with the
Yugoslavian foreign minister and a Yugoslav interfaith clergy
group.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and his delegation met with the three soldiers Friday in
Belgrade. Rabbi Jacobs told his wife they appeared generally
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But gaining their release was far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a chance that they would leave
empty-handed,'' Linda Jacobs noted. ``They did have some
frustrating moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts were raised after Milosevic told Jackson after their
first meeting that he would speak to his government officials. But
the two met again and Milosevic committed to the soldiers' release.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the three U.S. servicemen, including Staff Sgt.
Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, were headed to Germany for
reunions on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich., and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas, were
taken captive March 31 while patrolling the Yugoslav-Macedonia
border as part of a peacekeeping mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
