r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BOSTON-AZR &LR;      05-03 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BOSTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP PICK HURTS LEFT SHOULDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tempe, Ariz. - Cardinals first-round draft pick David Boston
suffered a fractured bone in his left shoulder less than 30 minutes
from the end of the final workout in a three-day minicamp on Sunday
and will be unable to work out for at least one month.
</P>
<P>
   ``No surgery is required,'' said Russell Chick, the Cardinals
orthopedic surgeon, who made the diagnosis after Boston was x-rayed
in the training room. ``Treatment will be immobilization in a sling
for four to six weeks. After that, he should be 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The fracture is to the scapula, or wing bone, on the back of the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, who in three years broke nearly every pass-receiving
record at Ohio State before the Cardinals made him the eighth
player chosen in last month's draft, emerged from the training room
and refused to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The injury was suffered when cornerback Corey Chavous collided
with Boston while Boston, who is not yet under contract, was
attempting to catch a pass in the no-pads workout at the team's
training facility in Tempe. The blow from the collision knocked
Boston to the ground. He landed on the back of his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scapula is part of the structure of the shoulder that
elevates and moves the shoulder,'' Chick said. ``There are a lot of
muscles attached to it. It's not near the shoulder joint, which
means it should heal quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``David cannot lift his arm above his shoulder at this point.
It's too painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, medical personnel thought the injury was only a
bruise. Chick said that Boston told him that he had ``had this
maybe 50 times before.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was learned that the injury was more serious, the
Cardinals' reactions ranged from disbelief to anger that Boston,
whose speed is expected to stretch opposing defenses and make the
Cardinals offense more explosive, had flirted with disaster at the
hands of a teammate in a no-pads drill.
</P>
<P>
   Minicamps are conducted primarily as off-season vehicles for
training and implementation of systems. By league rules, the only
protective gear permissible is a helmet. Some coaches have
circumvented the rules in the past by allowing shoulder pads to be
worn. They have been fined by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having something like this happen is the line you walk when
you have a minicamp,'' said Bob Ferguson, the Cardinals new general
manager. ``Players get carried away in the spirit of competition.
You've got to be careful. You want them going full speed in these
drills, but you've got to be mindful that you're without pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unintentional, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavous and Boston shook hands and talked for several minutes
afterward in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man, never in a million years did I think something like
this could happen on the last day of minicamp,'' Chavous said. ``I
really hope he's going to be OK. I was just sick. You don't want
anybody getting hurt in minicamp, especially someone who means as
much to our future as David does.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's an athlete, I'm an athlete, and we were going for the
ball, competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jake Plummer, who threw the pass, said his heart
also sank when he saw Boston land hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A quarterback can't stand to watch a defensive back throw a
receiver down,'' Plummer said. ``It was not Corey's fault. If it
had been on purpose, like he was trying to teach a rookie a lesson,
that would be B.S. But he was playing ball, and that's just the way
things go. I know David will be all right, but I know ownership
doesn't want to watch David Boston limp off.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Coach Vince Tobin was led to believe it was no more
than a bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after getting the bad news, an obviously angry Tobin
refused further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said that Boston will not run until the fracture begins to
unite. Boston will be limited in the team's two-week rookie and
free-agent camp in Tempe next month but should be fully healed for
the start of training camp in Flagstaff at the end of July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
