<HEADER>
A1796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES     05-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY GOES TO THE FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Au revoir, sayonara, see ya later, goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins bid farewell to the valiant Carolina Hurricanes
Sunday night, knocking them out in six games and the 2-0 victory,
their third in a row, was punctuated by goalie Byron Dafoe's second
shutout of the series (No. 3 of his playoff career) and his first
postseason series win.
</P>
<P>
   The victory in the Eastern Conference quarterfinal series was
Boston's first in a series since defeating Montreal in seven games
back in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now the team must wait to find out its opponent for the
conference semifinals. Boston would face seventh-seeded Buffalo if
Pittsburgh knocks off New Jersey in Game 7 Tuesday night. If New
Jersey wins, Boston will face fourth-seeded Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said he was grateful the series was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lost, a Game 7 would've been very, very difficult for us
to win there,'' said Burns. ``I didn't tell (the players) that. But
you didn't want to go back for a Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's over, Burns said they haven't won anything. Nobody
is satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't accomplished nothing yet,'' he said. ``You get
greedy, that's what happens. We're greedy right now. We've got one
step, anything's possible. It's a step for the young players that
they really learned what it takes to get this far. Now we have to
try to teach them to get one more step further.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina was a game and difficult opponent throughout, including
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. The Bruins got on the board midway through the first
on Joe Thornton's first goal of the postseason. With Boston on the
power play, Jason Allison dished the puck between the legs of
defenseman Curtis Leschyshyn to right wing Dmitri Khristich.
Khristich relayed it to Thornton, who slid his shot past goalie
Arturs Irbe at 8:58. It was just Boston's third shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of heavy hitting in the period with the best
one coming from one former teammate to another. Defenseman Don
Sweeney knocked the stuffing out of Carolina rearguard Glen Wesley,
a former Bruin, at the Boston blue line during a Hurricanes power
play.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Kyle McLaren also rattled some bones when he drilled
Robert Kron in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   The wild second period was, depending on what team you were
rooting for, a comedy of errors for Carolina or some wonderful luck
for Boston. The Hurricanes missed a boatload of scoring chances and
the Bruins managed to build on their lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes thought they had tied it at 2:10 when Bates
Battaglia fired a pass to Kron. Kron, driving toward the right
post, had the entire net to shoot at but couldn't control the pass.
Battaglia went so far as to raise his arm in celebration only to
realize the pass didn't translate into a goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes had another scoring opportunity at 7:29 when Gary
Roberts got to a rebound but missed the empty net. Kent Manderville
also had a good one from the left circle but he couldn't cash in
and that immediately preceded the second Boston goal. Mattias
Timander chipped the puck out of the Boston zone and Anson Carter,
the hero of Game 5, skated it up the ice, through the neutral zone,
and gained the blue line. He threw it over to Steve Heinze in the
left circle and Heinze backhanded it right back, with Carter
beating Irbe from right in front at 8:13 for the 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the second period belonged to Carolina, which
began putting heavy heat on the Bruins in their own end and outshot
them by a whopping 16-3 in the period. But Dafoe, as he's done all
season long, held the fort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They missed a lot of open nets that could've really changed it
around,'' said Burns. ``The third period was probably the best
third period we played in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said he considered himself very fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some saves when I had to,'' he said. ``But I also had a
couple of empty nets and they put some plexiglass up or something.
I don't know what happened. Obviously with them not getting a goal
and us going into the third period up, 2-0, I liked our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's Keith Primeau said Dafoe was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we have any more chances in this locker
room,'' he said. ``But he turned us down time and time again. It
was just that Byron Dafoe played out of his mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
