<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-KINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS LOSE GAMBLE WITH SLOPPY PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Suns are thinking about first-round playoff
opponents. San Antonio? Portland? Utah? It's roulette. Round and
round it goes.
</P>
<P>
   The spinning array of NBA possibilities will stop on one of the
three this week. On Wednesday, the Suns will know their first foe.
On Sunday, they simply knew they were lucky. Even in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings won't be there. If they were, this game of
roulette might be deadly. The Suns simply had no chance against the
Kings this season.
</P>
<P>
   That point was hammered home with a 111-100 victory over the
Suns that gave the Kings a sweep of the regular-season series
between the Pacific Division teams: three Sacramento victories by a
average margin of 13.3 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns struck out in any and every attempt to derail the
entertaining whirlwind of an attack launched by an improbable team
that is one game from clinching a playoff spot for only the third
time since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any team that says, `Oh good, we get to
play Sacramento,' '' said Suns Coach Danny Ainge, whose club nailed
down a playoff spot Saturday in a victory over Vancouver. ``I feel
the same way about us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Utah, Portland or San Antonio are really looking
forward to one team or another. I think there is a lot of parity
out there. The Kings have a chance, and I think everybody knows
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' chances to avoid the sweep in the series finale before
a lively crowd at ARCO Arena were limited by their own plans.
Before tip-off, Ainge planned on cutting the minutes for his key
players.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kidd is the league leader in average playing time. On this
night, he played only 36 minutes. In the second half, he sat for
seven minutes, a stretch during which the Kings gained control.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gugliotta didn't play at all in the fourth quarter. In part,
Ainge rested him because he still is troubled by a bruise to his
right calf. Gugliotta hit a jumper for two of his 21 points with
4:31 left in the third quarter. The 17-foot shot tied the score at
71. He left the game for good 1 minute, 22 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Kings had pushed their advantage to six. They would
never look back, as they raced to a lead that grew to 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the substitution pattern coach had planned on,''
Gugliotta said. ``It's no big deal. I accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kidd sounded almost relieved at the diminished time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us before tip-off that we were going to have
limited minutes,'' said Kidd, who narrowly missed another
triple-double with 15 points, 10 assists and nine rebounds. ``We
clinched a playoff spot. That's what we wanted to take care of. Now
the key is to make sure everybody is rested.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Kings, there would be no such luxury. They are still
battling for one of the Western Conference's two remaining playoff
spots. There is a sense of urgency in Sacramento, and it was
evident with repeated bursts of energy, especially from rookie
playmaker Jason Williams and veteran forward Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Williams finished with 24 points. For every Suns threat, he had
a counter. Midway through the fourth quarter, Suns forward Clifford
Robinson cut the Kings' margin to seven with a three-point goal.
Williams followed with one of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Webber. He played despite back spasms that forced
him to the locker room in the first half. He also was saddled with
foul trouble. The NBA's rebounding leader was charged with his
third in the first half. Yet, he managed 13 points and 13 rebounds
in only 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite it all, the Suns still had chances. In the end, they
only had to look at the box score for the reason they lost. Twenty
total turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The turnovers were no reason to panic. Still, they sounded an
alarm. They are a sign of sloppiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we came out with a lot of the passion and energy
that we have been playing with,'' Ainge said. ``But then, I saw the
intensity and concentration level fade in the second quarter. We
were in and out for the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little scary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
