<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1799 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-B     05-03 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' EFFORT REALLY SOMETHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Five years later, the Hub got its hockey team back
Sunday night. The Bruins found their game. They won a playoff
series. Monday morning they are one-quarter of the way to the
Stanley Cup _ talk about your unbridled optimism _ and the truth
is, that doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   What matters? Just that they can look in the newspapers, watch
the sportscasts, most importantly look in the mirror and finally
say they've won something. They aren't just a bunch of whoevers and
wannabes dressed in Black 'n Gold uniforms. They've got an
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a while,'' said Steve Heinze, one of the veterans
who was in uniform when the Bruins won their first-round series in
'94, back in the Planet Iafrate era. ``Something like this brings
you together when you know you can do something this good.''
</P>
<P>
   From here, who knows? The Bruins will face either Toronto or
Buffalo in Round 2. Neither of those clubs will bang away and
barrel in on the forecheck the way Carolina did, but both can
finish better around the net and both have superb goalies.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that's for later in the week. The Bruins can look
back at a first-round triumph in which they trailed, 2-1, and
rattled off three straight wins. Once they figured out that the
Carolina offense consisted of: 1. A dump in the corner; 2. A pass
behind the net; and 3. A centering pass from behind the post, they
all but punched their ticket to Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were making a lot of flip dumps,'' said Boston netminder
Byron Dafoe, who picked up a pair of shutouts in the six-game
series. ``I told our guys, `Look, I can get out there and handle
the puck, if you can hold them up on the way in.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Voila. If only every playoff series were so simple to fathom and
then unfold. There was more to getting by the 'Canes than that, of
course, and one of the key elements was luck.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget OT in Greensboro Friday night when Martin
Gelinas was left staring at 24 square feet of open net as he stood
at the top of the crease. Gelinas didn't blink, but he swung and
hit the puck twice, a double hit that would be tantamount to
striking out twice on the same at-bat in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, old friend Glen Wesley rang a potential winner off
the crossbar (at least his shots are getting lower).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins haven't won a Stanley Cup since '72, and in that
quarter century-plus drought they've had more than their fair share
of bad breaks, both regular season and postseason. Thus far in the
spring of '99, they have fate patting them on the back instead of
slamming down on their toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some bounces here in the last couple of games,'' said
Ray Bourque, the aging captain, who totaled nearly an hour of ice
time in the Game 5 double-OT victory. ``That's what you need to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe did his usually reliable job in the series. Bourque, the
other given, did everything that was expected of him, and a little
bit more (isn't that what's really expected of him, too?). They got
a huge series from Anson Carter, who popped in the second goal
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night with an eye-popping dash down the slot. And their
ever-reliable checking line of Rob DiMaio, Tim Taylor, and P.J.
Axelsson more than stood up to the ferocious 'Canes charge that was
led by behemoth Keith Primeau. All of that, with some luck mixed
in, defeated the 'Canes.
</P>
<P>
   If they're going to get to Round 3, though, the Bruins are going
to have to step up their offensive attack. Dmitri Khristich, who
had one shot in the first three games, got slightly better in the
next three games. He still isn't the guy who popped in a team-high
29 goals from October to April. Jason Allison and Sergei Samsonov,
his other linemates, also have to be more involved in the offense.
Allison had some prime opportunities, but kept hitting Arturs Irbe
in the chest as if there were extra points to be had for hitting
some invisible bull's-eye. To keep the good times rolling around
here, the No. 1 trio has to play like a legitimate first-line
force.
</P>
<P>
   The first round, essentially a postseason qualifier, allows a
team to move on when not all the parts are working. The Bruins have
yet to find their `A' game.
</P>
<P>
   But they have found their team, their confidence, their
self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we have in here, I think we've always known
that,'' said DiMaio. ``Now, the further you go, everything gets
intensified, the attention, everything. We always felt like a team.
Now we're winning, and the goals just expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo is saying the same thing. Toronto, too. There will be a
Stanley Cup parade somewhere in late June and by Tuesday night
we'll know the eight teams that are still vying for that raucous
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Bruins twice drew monstrous crowds downtown when they
won the Cup in '70 and '72. Those were the days of Bobby Orr and
Phil Esposito, of Gerry Cheevers and John Bucyk. If not for Ken
Dryden, there might have been three consecutive parades. It looked
like the parties and the celebrations would last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing lasts forever, of course. But Sunday &UR;  &LR; night a little of
that feeling came back. Hockey has come back to the Hub.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
