<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1800 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIREMENT-     05-03 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIREMENT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK RUNS OUT  
 FINAL DRIVE TAKES ELWAY OUT OF FOOT BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ John Elway already has found out that retirement can be
costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) night, John went down to have dinner with several
of his teammates,'' Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen said. ``There
was a no-parking sign that said nobody can park there except
(maybe) John Elway. They towed his car .
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't get a cab. So he had to walk three miles through
an industrial area to get his car. The lady said, `That will be
$100.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So, John, welcome to being a retired quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Elway, the only NFL player ever to start five Super
Bowls, officially retired after 16 seasons. Recovering his car was
easier than getting through his retirement speech.
</P>
<P>
   Not even humor could keep him from breaking down several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys told me (Saturday) night, there was an over-and-under
(bet) in the locker room how many times I'm going to cry,'' Elway
said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, his wife, Janet, needed to bring him a bottle of
water and Kleenex. The tears still flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the line is, but I lost my bet,'' Elway
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was flanked by Bowlen, who called him ``the greatest to ever
play the game,'' and Coach Mike Shanahan, Elway's close friend and
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   All of his family was in the audience. Many of his current and
former teammates also attended.
</P>
<P>
   `'I've learned so much from John _ how to handle the locker
room, the media, when to shut up,'' tight end Shannon Sharpe said.
``The guy has been Mr. Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the players who placed the (over) bet on how many
times he'd cry. You can't go 16 years and all of sudden not do that
anymore without being emotional. There's not an over-40 or over-50
league for him to play. He was saying today that the last time you
saw me play football was in the Super Bowl, and it was hard for
him. I knew (the tears) would happen. That's why I bet and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, 38, goes out on top. The Broncos have won back-to-back
Super Bowls, and he was selected the Most Valuable Player in last
January's victory over Atlanta in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   He said he made his decision to retire in early April after
consulting his wife and his father, Jack Elway, Broncos director of
pro scouting who told him that he was getting ``prone to
injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has a deteriorating left knee that hurts so badly he can't
walk 18 holes of golf, and the knee will eventually have to be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to stop competing, but I can't compete at the
level I want to compete anymore,'' said Elway, whose 51,475 passing
yards trail only Dan Marino in NFL history. ``The second reason
came down to my family. They've been great for 16 years. It's time
I focus around them.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that trying to help the Broncos become the first
team to win three consecutive Super Bowls was intriguing. But he
said before last season that he was 99 percent sure it would be his
last, and he never really wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chance for a three-peat seemed great, but I just wanted to
give myself a chance to think about it,'' he said. ``The only way I
could do that was to get away. When it was time to get ready for
the off-season program, I needed to see where my head was. About
the time the program was ready to begin (April 5), I said, `I can't
do it anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Elway said Shanahan had ``left the door open'' for him to return
on almost any terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You can play half a season. We'll make sure you're
healthy. If you're not healthy, you don't play,' '' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Mike, that's not me. I'm all in or all out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There will have to be a 100 percent, total catastrophe for me
to come back. If Mike came to me and said, `The only guy who can
take a snap is (guard) Mark Schlereth.' Other than that, I'm
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway doesn't know how he will spend his retirement. He's
interested in Bowlen's standing offer to become a minority owner of
the team, but the two haven't discussed specifics. He confirmed
that he has some national broadcast opportunities, including being
part of ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' team, but said he was ``not
overly excited about it because of the time commitment away from my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know I'm going to be the biggest fan of the Denver
Broncos of all time, and they're going to continue to win,'' Elway
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said he would remember Elway as an intense competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you did, he had to beat you,'' Shanahan said.
``If you did beat him, he had to play you until he won.''
</P>
<P>
   He also will remember Elway for his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Shanahan, a San Francisco assistant at the time,
interviewed for the Broncos head coaching job but didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``John said, `What's the problem?' '' Shanahan said. ``I said,
`It's more salary than anything else.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I embellished the story a little bit and said there was a
difference of about $200,000 a year on a three- or four-year
contract. He said, `That's done. I'll take care of that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him there also were some perks involved. He said, `I'll
give you four cars, one for each of your family.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Elway was known for his great comebacks. In fact, he
led the Broncos to 47 come-from-behind victories. ``I wonder how we
got in that situation so many times,'' Elway said. ``But (the
comebacks) sort of tells you what I'm all about.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also had been known for embarrassing Super Bowl losses.
The Broncos were outscored by a combined 96 points in Elway's first
three Super Bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances are if we hadn't won that Super Bowl (XXXII), I'd
be back playing right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd miss the huddle and telling Sharpe ``to be quiet. I
know you're open. I know you're open. I know you're open.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows not to ignore any more parking signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said, `No Parking. Postal Customers Only.' I said, `This
must be OK,' '' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look up and think, `Oh, no. The car's gone.' I start
walking. I think I'll run into a cab. I run into six limos of high
school students going to a prom. They drive by and point at me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
