<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MANN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANN GETS CHANCE TO MINE FOR GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The morning practice was over, only Shawn Bates and
Cameron Mann left behind for what amounted to on-ice skeet
shooting. Assistant coach Jacques Laperriere stood in one circle
and shuttled pass after pass to the opposite side, Bates and Mann
taking turns cocking back their sticks and leveling blazing
slappers at an open net.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting is only half the drill. Knowing when to shoot, what to
look for, is equally important. ``You've got to read off the
defenseman if you're in a one-on-one situation,'' Mann said. ``Cut
to the middle, take what he gives you and hit it _ ideally use the
defenseman as a screen.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the theory, anyway, and until Sunday &UR;  &LR; night Mann had
only theory to dwell on in Boston's first-round series against the
'Canes. He wasn't asked to suit up in the first five games, coach
Pat Burns electing to go with a more seasoned lineup against the
older Carolina club.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night, with the Bruins facing the chance to clinch
their first postseason series since '94, Burns told Mann to pull on
a sweater and join the show. It was Mann's first Stanley Cup game,
the first postseason match of his professional career. He made two
appearances in Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's victory for a total of 1 minute 48
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Just as timing is important when pulling back and teeing up a
slapper, it can be key, too, elsewhere in life. Warren Mann came to
town two weeks ago in hopes of seeing his son wear the black and
gold in a playoff game. His ticket home to northern Ontario was
punched in advance, and he was on a 6 p.m. flight out of Logan,
some 90 minutes before Mann suited up to face the 'Canes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' said Mann. ``He wanted to be here, but he's got
to be home for work.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Mann lives a black and gold life, too. He's a
supervisor in a gold mine in Cochenour, Ont., some 1,500 miles
north of Toronto. He spends his shift, 6 p.m. to 4 a.m., some 26
levels below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taken me down there with him a couple of times,'' said
Mann. ``If you're claustrophobic, it's probably not something you
want to do. But it didn't bother me. It's actually really something
to see. If they hit a sleeve (of gold), everyone gets pretty
excited and comes running to see it. Most of the time, you can't
even tell there's gold. They have their ways of getting it out of
the rock. But when they hit that big sleeve, you can see it, touch
it _ it's actually kind of soft _ and the guys get going.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering, there are no free samples in the gold
mining business. When the shift is over, workers file through
security and are checked by what Mann described as a metal
detector. If you're caught trying to take the job home, in all
likelihood you'll be told to stay home for good.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Mann, who turned 22 last month, is one of Warren and
Darlene Mann's three sons. Dallas, two years older than Cam, played
briefly for Binghamton last season in the United Hockey League, but
had his season shortened by a knee injury. Shane, two years younger
than Cam, is back home in mining country.
</P>
<P>
   The mining life often pulls generations of a family into the
tunnel. It can be a grueling existence. Cameron never wanted to
follow in his dad's footsteps, because he had it in his head at an
early age that he'd rather look for gold in an ice rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it a lot, how lucky I am to play a game like
hockey to make a living,'' he said. ``I mean, it's a game, it's
fun, and when you've grown up to see people work the mines, well,
you definitely respect people who work 8 to 5.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann's father wasn't always a miner. The family moved from
Manitoba to Saskatchewan and then eventually to Ontario as Warren
looked for work. He labored for years in grain elevators before
finding work underground as a means of supporting his family.
Darlene Mann augmented the family funds by giving piano lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had her own piano, until my dad had an accident,''
recalled Mann. ``It was one of our moves _ I can't remember which,
because I was young _ and my dad fell asleep, or something, and
cracked up the U-Haul. The piano was ruined. Like I say, a long
time ago, but he hasn't lived that down.''
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Mann was in Winnipeg Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, awaiting her
husband's arrival on the flight from Logan. The drive back to
Cochenour, Cam figured, would take about four hours. By 6 p.m.
Monday, Warren Mann will be back supervising his shift, looking for
the earth to give up its treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked hard for me to play hockey . . . he's worked hard
for all his sons to have a good life,'' said Mann. ``I always knew
what I wanted to do and my dad always encouraged me to follow my
dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
