r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-GAM     05-03 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-GAME-6-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOENFELD ON A LIMB AFTER BLUES TIE SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Was it the act of a desperate man, or a case of a
blind optimist whistling past the graveyard?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld raised a lot of
eyebrows with some bold words Sunday after the St. Louis Blues
evened the best-of-seven Western Conference playoff series at three
games each with a 5-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   It means the Coyotes, having squandered a 3-1 series lead, will
return to America West Arena on Tuesday night for Game 7 wearing
the forlorn look of distant cousin Wile E. Coyote moments before
another boulder crushes his melon.
</P>
<P>
   But Schoenfeld tried to paint a different picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win Game 7,'' he said. ``Both teams have played
extremely well, and it probably should come down to seven (games),
if justice is served.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell you I would stake my job on it, but that's
already been done, so I'll just say we're going to win Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld was referring to speculation that his job is history
if the Coyotes don't reach the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can say it, it doesn't matter,'' Blues defensemen Al
MacInnis said, reflecting the mood in the Blues' locker room.
``We're not concerned about what they say or do. We're just going
about our own business and try to win one more game.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Coyotes are now in a situation where the home-ice
advantage won over 82 regular-season games can pay dividends,
although it hasn't meant much in this series. Each team now has two
road wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter now what happened in the first six games. It
doesn't matter,'' Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said. ``It comes
down to one game. It doesn't matter if they won eight games in a
row. Just one game for 60 minutes. We'll find out if home-ice
advantage means anything on Tuesday night.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a series of words and wild momentum shifts. In the
past two games, too many words from the Coyotes about closing the
series and not enough action. If ever there was a day when Blues
goalie Grant Fuhr was beatable, it was Sunday. He surrendered three
goals on a paltry 21 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix goalie Nikolai Khabibulin faced 34 shots and saw enough
odd-man rushes to think he was facing the ``Charge of The Light
Brigade''.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a lot of battles down low,'' Schoenfeld said. ``They
established a much stronger forecheck. That has been a concern the
last few games, with the people we have out of the lineup, to
sustain some kind of offensive pressure, which does two things for
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates scoring chances and gives our defensemen a
breather. The last few games, we've spent far too much time in our
defensive zone, which isn't the strength of our defense. Our
defense is at its best when we are moving the puck and breaking
plays up the neutral zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were without forwards Greg Adams, who has a groin
injury, and penalty killer Mike Sullivan, neither of whom are
expected to play Tuesday night, causing Schoenfeld to shake up his
lines.
</P>
<P>
   He moved Rick Tocchet and Robert Reichel to the No. 1 line with
Tkachuk and started a second line of Dallas Drake, Shane Doan and
Stephen Leach. The two lines had one shot between them in the first
period, causing Schoenfeld to reconfigure them again in a search
for offense.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a team should have entered a game with a sense of
urgency, it was Phoenix. Yet it didn't. Fourth-line center Mike
Stapleton even gave the Coyotes a 1-0 lead at 2:20 of the first
period. Instead of increasing the tempo, they fell back on their
haunches, stopped forechecking and allowed Craig Conroy to score
the first of his two goals to knot the game at one just 36 seconds
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it,'' Stapleton said of the lack of
first-period emotion. ``It's just like we're not getting momentum
going. It's like we're playing content when we shouldn't be. A
sense of urgency? We didn't play like it. We should have but
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Phoenix play smart, twice throwing away power-play
opportunities in the first period by taking silly penalties _ 35
seconds into one, and 32 seconds into another.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues, however, chose to cash in their power plays, which
they have done with regularity in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Young put St. Louis up, 2-1, at 8:25 on a first-period
power play, and Chris Pronger erased an improbable 3-2 Phoenix lead
with a power-play goal with three-minutes left in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Improbable lead?
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Coyotes took only three shots on goal in
the entire second period, very improbable. Somehow, they managed to
score two goals in 93 seconds, one by Leach and one on a power-play
goal by defenseman Teppo Numminen.
</P>
<P>
   But it was former Coyote Jeff Finley who stuck the dagger into
the Coyotes' heart, taking Pierre Turgeon's centering pass in the
slot and ripping it past Khabibulin at 8:59 of the third. Conroy
completed the scoring, driving home the second rebound on a
three-on-one rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had too many turnovers in our own end and gave them
three-on-ones, three-on-twos,'' Phoenix's Dallas Drake said. ``You
can't do that against them. The penalties we took tonight were not
aggressive penalties. They were stupid penalties.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
