r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TRACK-LADN     05-03 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON LIKES FONTANA TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ 
and KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ So, is Jeff Gordon the king of California
Speedway?
</P>
<P>
   One would think that after the three-time NASCAR Winston Cup
champion won here for the second time in the three-year history of
the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory, seen my an estimated 117,000, was Gordon's
third top 5 victory in Fontana. Beside winning Sunday and the
inaugural event in 1997, he finished fourth last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy Penske tracks,'' Gordon said. ``California, Michigan
... we seem to run well. Maybe our Michigan package kind of helps
us here. This track is similar to Michigan. It's a beautiful
facility and an awesome place to run a race. We're excited about
coming here. It's my home state and I get a lot of fans out here
and that helps my motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was one of several laps to praise the three-year
facility, which seems to be developing a wider racing groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great track,'' said Bobby Labonte, who finished
third. ``I don't think I ran many laps on the same line over and
over. I was outside and inside. The groove moved way up during the
race. It really made for good racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Bodine's bad luck continued Sunday. Bodine, whose had
several good runs during the first part of the season, was running
up front before engine problems dropped him to 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something broke,'' Bodine said. ``We came from a long way
back. I'm proud of the crew. This is a new team and our first time
here with a Chevrolet and the first time here with this team. To be
competitive, you can't feel anything but good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
