<HEADER>
A1812 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HURRICANES-BOS &LR;      05-03 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWN CHANCES FOR HURRICANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Perhaps they feared that the FleetCenter Jumbotron
would fall on their heads. Perhaps they were suffering a lingering
hangover from the bewildering near misses two nights earlier.
Perhaps they had all come down with hockey's equivalent of the
yips.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the fans who showered the ice with
black-and-gold pompoms at the end of Sunday night's game came
closer to hitting the empty net than did the Carolina Hurricanes.
And that's why the end of the game also marked the end of the
series and the season for the Hurricanes, who dropped a 2-0
decision to the Bruins but were darned if they knew how.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a series that tight-checking, you can't miss those
chances,'' said Carolina coach Paul Maurice, whose team bowed out
of the best-of-seven Eastern Conference quarterfinal in six
nail-biting games. ``Those weren't empty nets, those were line
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Maurice's metaphor was confounding, so were the platinum
opportunities that escaped the Hurricanes in their futile battle
for survival. Byron Dafoe was unyielding in the Boston net, but he
wasn't the only reason the Hurricanes outshot the Bruins, 31-21,
including 16-3 in the second period, and had nothing to show for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt for the first time in six games he gave up some big
rebounds,'' said Carolina's thunderbolt center, Keith Primeau, who
must think his last name is ``Sucks'' after three games of
incessant serenading by the Boston fans. ``We couldn't put 'em in.
I can't even count the number of solid chances we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he could think of a couple in particular.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:47 of a scoreless game in the first period, Primeau walked
out of the corner and sent a shot that caromed off Dafoe's pads.
Then the black magic started. With the net as empty as the
Hurricanes' fortunes, Primeau fired a rebound _ and watched it
glance off defenseman Kyle McLaren's skate. Carolina defenseman
Glen Wesley then flashed into the play, corraling a second rebound
_ and watching in horror as Dafoe knocked it wide by the width of
his skate blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it just kept going from there,'' said Primeau.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, less than three minutes later, Primeau was primed to
answer a goal by Boston's Joe Thornton when he set up dead in front
of Dafoe _ and missed.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse in the second period even as Carolina besieged
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:32, Robert Kron was stationed just to the right of the
crease, salivating to cash in a pass. But he was perhaps a step too
deep and mishit the puck.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30, Sami Kapanen slammed a slap shot from the left that
kicked off Dafoe's pads and rebounded to onrushing Gary Roberts on
the right. The onetime 50-goal scorer launched his bid into the
ozone.
</P>
<P>
   And at 9:25, desperate after Boston built the lead to two goals,
Ray Sheppard drilled a shot from the right that glanced off Dafoe's
pads to Glen Wesley, who misfired from the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances in the second and couldn't capitalize,''
lamented Wesley. ``I don't believe they're the better team. We're
evenly matched. They cashed in on their opportunities and we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns would second that. ``Byron made some big saves and
they missed a lot of open nets,'' said the Bruins coach. ``Things
could've swung either way easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice felt as if he were swinging from a noose as he watched
the gallery of unscathed targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think you can put them in the missed-opportunity
category,'' he said. ``It's not like Dafoe was pulling shots out of
the air on three-on-twos. When I'm standing on the bench and I can
see both posts and there's no goalie between them, that's what I'm
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Hurricanes merely were performing a variation on
the theme that killed them at Greensboro Friday, when Wesley hit
the crossbar and Martin Gelinas's wide-open bid in front struck
either Ray Bourque's stick or a gremlin, enabling Boston to escape
with a 4-3 victory. But Carolina wasn't subscribing to the theory
of cursed karma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a carryover,'' said Primeau, whose
fortune was so wretched that he satisfied the fans' bloodlust by
getting cut in the lip for stitches _ by a teammate. ``It would
have been one thing if we'd been trying to carry the puck through
the neutral zone. But we were right on them and had the chances
right in front.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's any consolation, at least Maurice doesn't have to
scramble for an introductory theme next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to work on it from day one in training camp,'' he
said. ``We're going to leave the goalies in the locker room and
practice hitting empty nets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
