<HEADER>
A1813 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-A     05-03 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH'S GUARANTEE A DIVERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS - The words were almost comical, received with a
collective shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, you can rest easy. The Coyotes coach has
guaranteed a victory in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would stake my job on it,'' Jim Schoenfeld said. ``But
that's already been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are no guarantees in life, much less in sports.
So what to make of Schoenfeld's voluntary stroll to the edge of the
ledge?
</P>
<P>
   You might call it a sign of panic. After all, a man who is
convinced he's going to win doesn't need to tell the world about
it. Or you might call it confirmation, that regardless of player
testimonials, Schoenfeld knows he is gone if the Coyotes don't
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can call it what it really is: A calculated diversion, an
attempt to take all the focus off his beleaguered hockey team.
Because, in the wake of a 5-3 thumping from the Blues on Sunday,
there is a grim reality beginning to surface.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are undermanned. And maybe they're just not good
enough to win this series.
</P>
<P>
   It's not daring if you have nothing to lose, but Schoenfeld's
remarks did the trick. The moment the guarantee left his lips,
every media type in the building had swallowed the hook, off with a
sucker's story, off on a frenzied journey for reaction.
</P>
<P>
   In the Coyotes' corner, stoic faces backed their coach. In the
Blues' dressing room, the words carried the ring of a cheap
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees, I'll guarantee that,'' Craig Conroy
said. ``But we've put ourselves in a perfect spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Words that made Chris Pronger smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he's in trouble if they don't (win),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Words that bounced off Grant Fuhr like a weak backhand, a man so
worried that he's wondering whether he'll get a chance to golf with
Valley resident and traitor Phil Mickelson in the next couple of
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good for them,'' Fuhr said. ``But we've got 25 guys in here
that don't think that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, these things work out. Joe Namath and Mark Messier
made good on their guarantees, but they were in a position to
influence the outcome. Jimmy Johnson once put his neck on the line
and came off as a prophet. But most of the time, a guarantee from a
coach means less than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the last time a coach in our parts guaranteed a
victory, Danny Ainge predicted the Suns would rally from an 0-1
deficit last year against the Spurs. He ended up with a plateful of
crow.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld could look like a genius. Or he might resemble the
village idiot. But if his future is predetermined, this is a
no-lose proposition.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think for a moment that his boast has infuriated the
Blues, so much that it will throw them off their game. They have
seized the series, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can say it, it doesn't matter,'' Al MacInnis said. ``We're
not concerned about what they say or do.''
</P>
<P>
   And really, that's the problem. With a full cast, the Coyotes
would've already won this series and moved on. With a decimated
lineup, there is little for the Blues to fear.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sullivan is limping like he has a leg full of shrapnel.
Greg Adams has missed four games with a sore groin. Yuha Jlonen and
Jeremy Roenick are gone. And sheer talent is starting to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Blues were in control from the start, outskating,
outhitting and outwilling the opponent. They won 14 of the first 21
faceoffs. They held the Coyotes to 21 shots on goal. It was a
miracle that the Coyotes entered the final period with a chance to
win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come out to play in the first 20 minutes,'' Mike
Stapleton said. ``And they jumped on us.''
</P>
<P>
   So throw the guarantee out the window. It was an attempt to draw
all analysis to Schoenfeld's bravado, to suck the pressure out of
the room and place it squarely on his shoulders. For one day, it
worked. But in reality, it's pointless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's job is on the line here,'' Keith Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the real story. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
