<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-03 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets' plan off and running
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first quarter, Charles Barkley pulled a defensive
rebound off the glass, lowered his head, gained momentum going up
the court like a tractor trailer on the open road and rolled all
the way to the hoop for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   Very late in the fourth quarter, Barkley wrapped his mitts
around one more rebound, turned and fired a long, would-be
touchdown pass to a galloping Scottie Pippen, who might have wasted
an easy scoring opportunity if not for his racing buddy Hakeem
Olajuwon trailing the play for a follow-up dunk.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the Rockets did more running than a late-arriving
plane load of Cancun vacationers with Montezuma's revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Charles charged. Scottie sped. Hakeem hustled. Michael motored.
Cuttino cruised. Sam streaked.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like they were shooting a TV commercial for one of the
long-distance phone carriers. You know, Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   At times it appeared to be a track meet. At other times it
looked a little like the Kentucky Derby with so many thoroughbreds
racing to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Message is clear
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, it may have seemed like just an ordinary
beating of the LA Clippers, the unofficial punching bags of the
NBA. But to the Rockets, who have been on the receiving end of too
many wallops themselves lately, it was a much-needed tonic. And to
Barkley, it was a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to go down in this thing anywhere short of a
championship, then at least we're going to go down taking our best
swing,'' Barkley said. ``And that means running with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means getting the ball off the boards and running. It means
taking the ball out of the basket when the other team scores and
running. It means picking up any loose ball or seeing any
opportunity and running. It's the only chance we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it's better than the option the Rockets had been
putting on display lately in losing five of their previous six
games _ standing around and watching each other shoot 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a talk with Scottie before the game, and I told him that
we might as well get out there and run with the ball and try to get
things moving,'' Barkley said. ``I mean, what do we have to lose?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the way things are with people getting the blame. I
told Scottie that he and I are going to be blamed here if we don't
win it all, so let's just try to do what we can. My grandmother
told me, `If you have a gun, shoot it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets shot the ball at a 51 percent clip and drilled 11 of
21 from behind the 3-point stripe, which does cover up a lot of
sins. But they also made sharp, crisp cuts on offense, had
excellent ball movement, bounced all over the floor on defense. The
way they flew all over the floor, they looked like, well, Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   How different was this picture than the staid, conservative
portrait of defeat that couldn't get out of its own way on Friday
night in losing to the Jazz?
</P>
<P>
   Well, consider that there were just over three minutes left in
the first half when the Rockets first dumped the ball down low to
either Barkley or Olajuwon in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   This was a completely different, more upbeat look. It was
Olajuwon making himself available for medium-range jumpers from all
around the lane. It was Pippen filling lanes on the fast break. It
was the two kids, Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley, getting to
race all over the playground like a couple of kids.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with Charles
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it was Barkley, pushing, prodding, urging, goading them
to run at every single opportunity. He ran through traffic, and he
ran sometimes ahead of the fast break. He would kick the ball out
to one of the guards to move the ball ahead, and then he'd kick it
into a higher gear himself and beat the ball to the other end,
where he converted follow-up hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had 19 points and 12 rebounds, five of them on the
offensive boards. Olajuwon went off for 20 points, Brent Price for
15, Pippen for 14, seven rebounds and seven assists. It was even a
night when a ``Pig'' could fly as Anthony Miller hustled up and
down the floor for eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is part of the upcoming Nike ad campaign that will
once again feature Barkley. After all, you can hardly be hawking
sneakers if you never run in them. More likely, it really is the
best chance the Rockets have in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unrealistic to ask people to stand around the 3-point
line watching, take maybe five shots a game and then bust their
(tail) on defense,'' Barkley said. ``We have to run no matter what,
and that's what we're doing from here on in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got Scottie here now to take some of the heat. He's my
Steve Austin, the $67 million man, and we're together on this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. You have all these guys making all this money. But
when it comes down to it, you know all the blame is gonna be put on
poor, measly, million-dollar Chuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm running till I drop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
