A1820 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-BOS     05-03 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER'S LITTLE THRILLS GO ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's been a whirlwind two days for Anson Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday morning, he put the Bruins on the brink of
winning their first playoff series since 1994 with a goal at 14:45
of the second overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night he helped push them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   His goal at 8:13 of the second period gave the Bruins some
breathing room, while at the same time seemingly bursting the
Carolina bubble, and helped advance him and many others on this
team into unchartered territory.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-0 win over Carolina, before a roaring FleetCenter crowd,
gave the Bruins the series, 4 games to 2, and sent them into the
Eastern Conference semifinals against an opponent yet to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   As often happens, Carter's goal came just seconds after Gary
Roberts missed a golden opportunity to pull Carolina even when he
rifled a rebound high over the glass with Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe
out of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Carter picked up the rebound, weaved his way down the right
wing, and then cut towards the net, where he was met by Carolina
defenders Steve Halko and Paul Coffey. He flicked the puck to the
left to an open Steve Heinze, and then Heinze fed it back to him
and he had Carolina goaltender Arturs Irbe down and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just saw the highlights and we couldn't believe how many
empty nets they missed,'' said Carter, who had three goals in the
series. ``I think someone upstairs wanted us to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these things happen. How many times do you see one team
miss a great opportunity and then the other team come down and
score? It seems to happen all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the Bruins were confident, but not overly so, after
taking a 2-0 lead into the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we were confident, but at the same time, we knew exactly
what we did in their rink, coming back from a 2-0 deficit. We knew
one goal wasn't a big lead and two goals is the worst lead in
hockey. A team scores one goal to cut that lead in half, and then
the other team tightens up. We didn't want that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the fans played a key role in this win and he tipped
his hat to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the energy, I felt the electricity,'' he said.
``I usually don't hear the crowd, but tonight was one of those rare
cases where you could feel the excitement just walking into the
rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we wanted to go back down (to Greensboro) and
face that hostile crowd there in a Game 7. The fans let us know
they didn't want us to, either. They really jacked us up. It was
nice to hear their approval. We used the crowd as a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter likened the past 48 hours to a thrill ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great experience, but a roller coaster type
experience,'' he said. ``After that big goal the other night you're
sky high, but then you have to come right back down to earth and
get ready for the next game. The older guys on the team were great
and helped me get through that emotional high I was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me that during the playoffs there would be a lot of
ups and downs. That overtime goal was a high point, but earlier in
that game there was a low point when I missed my coverage on the
point man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, Carter was back on a high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
