<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BREWERS-AZ     05-03 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BREWERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLY IN THE 9TH FALLS FLAT AFTER BULLPEN BLOWS LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The Diamondbacks had the bases loaded with no outs
in the ninth inning Sunday and their three hottest hitters coming
to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell, Luis Gonzalez and Matt Williams, who have 24 home runs
among them, couldn't get a ball deep enough to score a run, and the
Milwaukee Brewers held on for a 6-5 victory at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody told me we'd have the bases loaded, nobody out and
Jay, myself and Matty coming up, I would have bet the farm we'd get
a run,'' Gonzalez said. ``But that's why this is baseball, and
strange things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have gotten much stranger than during a wild eighth
and ninth in a roller-coaster game that saw Williams launch two
home runs and the Diamondbacks' bullpen revert to opening week
failures and blow two leads.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Olson, recalling Los Angeles and Atlanta where he blew
three save opportunities in the first week, gave up a three-run
homer to pinch-hitter Marquis Grissom with two outs in the eighth
that gave the Brewers the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses,'' said Olson, who saved two games in as many days,
coming into Sunday. ``I just failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers' closer, Bob Wickman, wasn't much steadier during
his turn in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks seemed to have the right-hander flustered,
after they twice pointed out to the home-plate umpire that Wickman
was going to his mouth with his fingers. That's an automatic called
ball, and pinch-hitter David Dellucci reached base on a walk to
start the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mad at us for calling the umpire's attention to it,''
Manager Buck Showalter said. ``That's a rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley, pinch-hitting, then singled, and Wickman walked
leadoff man Tony Womack on four pitches to load the bases for Bell,
who hit his eighth home run on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bell bounced meekly to Wickman, who got the force out at the
plate. The throw to first was in the dirt and Sean Berry wasn't
able to scoop it up, leaving the bases jammed for Gonzalez, who had
doubled in the fourth to extend his hitting streak to 16 games and
walked twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get something up, to stay out of a double play,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   He got something up _ a pitch that went up in his hands.
Gonzalez hit the ball into right. Finley was halfway between third
and home, as right fielder Jeromy Burnitz, known to have one of the
strongest arms in the league, charged and caught the ball, sliding
on his knees before getting up to throw.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Finley got back to third, it was too late to tag and
try to score.
</P>
<P>
   Burnitz said, ``if he's tagging, no,'' he doesn't get Finley at
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't forecast him sliding on his knees as he gets up to
throw,'' said third-base coach Brian Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   Said Finley, ``That's one of those Catch-22 balls. If he short
hops it and you're tagging, you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter called it ``a good read by a good base runner and a
good third-base coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks (14-12) had one more chance at a three-game
sweep of the Brewers with their most dangerous hitter at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-0 pitch, Williams hit a sharp line drive that Wickman
snagged to end the game and the Brewers' five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it off the end of the bat,'' said Williams, whose
two-run homer in the eighth gave Arizona a 5-3 lead. ``I thought it
might have a chance. He made a good play.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasted in the three-hour, 37-minute marathon was a decent effort
by starter Armando Reynoso, who left at the end of six innings with
the score tied at 1. He threw 116 pitches, 38 of them in a rocky
fifth, when he was fortunate to escape with just one run.
</P>
<P>
   Wasted was catcher Damian Miller's seventh-inning, two-run
homer. Wasted, too, was Williams' third lifetime multihomer game in
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Brian Anderson gave up four singles and two runs in
the seventh when the Brewers tied it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
