<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-FRAUENHE     05-03 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-FRAUENHEIM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEUD HURTS THOSE WITH NO OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A growing feud between a longtime Phoenix
trainer-turned-promoter and the Arizona State Boxing Commission is
beginning to shrink an already limited number of opportunities for
the state's youngest fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer/promoter  &UR; Willy Borchert and  &UR; John Montano, the
commission's executive director, are involved in a tug of a war
over control.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines are familiar. Businessmen and regulators are
often at odds, regardless of whether they're selling bouts or
bagels. From one perspective, regulation is interference. From the
other, it's protection for customers and participants alike.
</P>
<P>
   Compromise keeps everybody in business. Trouble is, there's been
no apparent move toward compromise in the Borchert-Montano
struggle. Borchert canceled a card scheduled for May 11 at Midnight
Rodeo out of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much hassle,'' Borchert said.
</P>
<P>
   The losers? Young fighters who are looking for a chance to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   Borchert complains that Montano has taken on the role of
matchmaker. He said Montano exercises arbitrary power in
sanctioning bouts. Montano has asked to see some of Borchert's
proposed fighters either train, spar or run a couple of miles just
a few days before the opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gov.  &UR; Jane Hull, Borchert accuses Montano of
``rude and abusive behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Montano counters that he is simply fulfilling his
job description.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must ensure the safety of the boxers,'' Montano said. ``It's
my responsibility to guarantee the safest possible atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now federal provisions that require me to do that.
The commission provides scrutiny of matches, including approval and
denial. By law, we have to do that. Ethically, we must do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate aspect in this standoff is that Borchert and
Montano are two of the best people in Arizona boxing. They
genuinely care about the sport and the young men who go into harm's
way.
</P>
<P>
   Borchert jumped into the promotional wars, simply because he
wanted to give apprentice fighters a chance.
</P>
<P>
   In boxing's increasingly big-time, pay-per-view atmosphere,
there are fewer and fewer opportunities for kids who didn't make
the Olympic team or couldn't find backing from a major promoter.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner, there's Montano, who watches controversy
tear apart a sport he has loved all his life. The sad spectacle
stretches from  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Tyson's bite to the inexplicable scoring in the  &UR; Lennox
Lewis-Evander
 &UR; Holyfield draw.
</P>
<P>
   Montano has to look at the tattered national scene and say to
himself:
</P>
<P>
   Not here. Not in my state.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Montano has become more involved with federal
legislation sponsored by Sen.  &UR; John McCain of Arizona &UR; . Montano is
vice president of the National Association of Boxing Commissions,
which is trying wrest the powers of assigning judges from the
various ruling acronyms.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem here is personal. Borchert and Montano are
headstrong. If both can get beyond their stubborn pride, they might
discover they have a mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of young fighters, there is no other option. &QL; 
Briefly . . . &QL; 
Open scoring was dismissed by  &UR; Mark Johnson, who won the
International Boxing Federation's junior-bantamweight title a week
ago when scores were announced after the fifth and eight rounds.
``Why should I go out and take a chance?'' said Johnson, who knew
he was way ahead after the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's move to junior bantam means he has vacated the IBF's
flyweight title. That might open the door for  &UR; Michael Carbajal in
his comeback hopes for a major flyweight crown.
</P>
<P>
   Information from other media sources included. Norm Frauenheim
can be reached at (602) 444-8259 or norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
