A1831 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR     05-03 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SPOILED SUNS SEASON IN 1981 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Kings are the journeymen. In name. And fact.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise has gone from Rochester, to Cincinnati, to Omaha
and Kansas City, and now Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there has been a consistent intersection:
</P>
<P>
   The Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' last memory of better times came at the expense of
Phoenix. As the Kings close on what would be only their third
playoff appearance since 1985, they remember the last time they won
a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1981. In the second round, the Kings upset the Suns, then
the Pacific Division champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings coach?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cotton Fitzsimmons, now a Suns vice president. Fitzsimmons'
Kings won Game 7 at Veterans Memorial Coliseum despite an
injury-wracked roster. He slowed down the ball and confused the
more talented Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of special teams, but that was the best
coaching I ever did,'' Fitzsimmons said. ``We won Game 7 on Easter
Sunday. I know someone up there must have loved me that
afternoon.'' &QL; 
Sideline chatter &QL; 
There's no respect, not even for a former King.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter, a Sacramento fan got a smile from
Suns Coach
 &UR; Danny Ainge when he yelled:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Danny, you're just a tall  &UR; Bobby Hurley,'' in reference
to a former Kings guard who struggled throughout his stay in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge, also a former Kings guard, looked up into the crowd and
countered:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't I a little better shooter than him?'' &QL; 
Bench assist &QL; 
Former Arizona State guard  &UR; Byron Scott works as a Kings assistant
coach alongside former Suns Coach  &UR; John Wetzel.
</P>
<P>
   Scott brings experience to the Kings that includes three
championship rings as a starter for the Los Angeles Lakers in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told all the guys I keep my rings in a safe deposit box in
Los Angeles, and I only pull them out when I want to see them
again,'' he said. ``Usually, that's in the summertime, but once we
get to the playoffs, I might go back home and pull them out and
show them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why you play in this league. It's not for the money
and all the other accolades. It's for the rings, for the
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you win these, nobody can ever take these away from
you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott said time does take away some other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time my hair grows a little, I cut it back off, just so
I don't have to see if it's turning white up there or not,'' he
said. &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
Odd couple: Former ASU Coach  &UR; Bill Freider was in the ARCO Arena
crowd with &UR; Steve Fisher, his former assistant at Michigan. Fisher
took over for Frieder and won an NCCA title for the Wolverines a
decade ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
