<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-FINLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY ENJOYS MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Jeff Finley's worlds were colliding.
</P>
<P>
   There he stood, sharing the ice with a team that didn't want him
badly enough and a team that, at this particular moment, needed him
desperately.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the juxtaposition is what inspired the St. Louis
defenseman, who took a corner feed from center Pierre Turgeon and
slapped in what proved to be the winning goal in the Blues' 5-3
victory over the Coyotes in Game 6 of the first-round playoff
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``To score is always exciting, especially when you don't do it
often,'' the former Coyote said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't kidding. Finley's goal was only his second in 18
months and his first since March 22. It was also his first playoff
goal ever.
</P>
<P>
   His timing was perfect. The game was tied at 3 in the third
period, with St. Louis on the brink of elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes goalie Nikolai Khabibulin stopped Finley's first
attempt, but the puck found Turgeon in the corner, who fed it back
to the wide-open Finley. He sent it higher and over Khabibulin's
pad to make it 4-3 at 8:59. Center Craig Conroy scored nearly seven
minutes later to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest goal of my career, definitely,'' Finley
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a career that started with the New York Islanders and had
stops with Philadelphia, Winnipeg/Phoenix and the New York Rangers
before he came to St. Louis on Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   He played in 65 games for the Coyotes, scoring three goals and
seven assists, but when he became an unrestricted free agent in
1997, the better offer came from the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no hard feelings,'' Finley said. ``In fact, when I
look back, I remember it as a tremendous experience. So many people
had many doubts at the time about how people would react to hockey
in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the people responded and treated us and to be part of
that experience the first time out was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's agent, Art Breeze, was less kind at the time,
criticizing the Coyotes for not re-signing Finley or another
client, winger Jim McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, as witnessed by the recent loss of two
high-profile free agents, someone in Phoenix management should
learn that winning teams treat their players with dignity and
respect,'' Breeze said.
</P>
<P>
   Finley emphasized that he remembers his experience as positive.
But he did find irony in his team's future being affected by the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a trying season at times for the 32-year-old. It
began with the Rangers but also included three months with Hartford
of the American Hockey League. He was traded to St. Louis on Feb.
13 and has played in all but one game since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to see players like Finley and Conroy, who
work so hard, get the big goals and help us win,'' Turgeon said.
``That's exactly what we needed today. We're the kind of team, at
least during the season, that gets contributions from everyone.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
