<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1833 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-PENALTY-K     05-03 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-PENALTY-KILL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' PENALTY KILLERS PLAY DEAD AGAINST BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ This killing time is killing the Coyotes. And if
they aren't careful, it could kill everything.
</P>
<P>
   The head coach. The Los Arcos arena vote. Maybe a star player
such as Jeremy Roenick, Keith Tkachuk or Robert Reichel.
</P>
<P>
   But first, it would simply kill their first-round playoff series
against the St. Louis Blues, now knotted at three games apiece with
everything on the line Tuesday night in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because the Coyotes' penalty killers, at one point the best
bunch in the entire NHL, are getting killed by the Blues' power
play.
</P>
<P>
   It was the difference once again in Game 6 of the series Sunday
at the Kiel Center. St. Louis scored two more power-play goals,
including the tying score late in the second period, that resulted
in a 5-3 victory and prevented the Coyotes from wrapping up the
series for the second straight time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our penalty killing has killed us in this series, and their
power play has killed us,'' Phoenix center and penalty killer Mike
Stapleton said. ``We're just not getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues have a league-high nine power-play goals after six
games, the most ever scored in one series against the Coyotes'
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the Blues' 18 goals in the series have come with at
least one Phoenix player sitting in the penalty box. Can you see a
trend developing here or what?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the same thing all series long,'' Coyotes defenseman
J.J. Daigneault said. ``It's the one thing we wanted to avoid, and
we were unable to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault was whistled twice Sunday, both for hooking. The
first one broke up a two-on-one St. Louis rush, which was
acceptable, especially since the Blues didn't score on the ensuing
man-advantage. But the second one, which tripped up Pavol Demitra,
was critical.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes had just scored on a power-play goal of their own by
Teppo Numminen to take a 3-2 lead with 6:09 left in the second.
Three minutes later, Chris Pronger banged in a rebound with a
dejected Daigneault in the box to steal the momentum, not only in
the game, but in the series as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, our power play's been the difference. It hasn't skipped
a beat,'' said Blues forward Scott Young, who scored on a
first-period power play for St. Louis in which the Coyotes never
once could clear the puck out of their zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues' power play ranked third in the league during the
regular season at 20.3 percent. The Coyotes' penalty-killing unit
ended up fifth-best at 87.1 percent. To be fair, however, Phoenix
has been without two of its penalty killers, injured forwards
Roenick and Juha Ylonen. On Sunday, they also were missing Mike
Sullivan, out because of a bruised leg after getting hit by a shot
in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it probably would be tough to stop them even if we had
those guys,'' Coyotes forward Dallas Drake admitted. ``Our penalty
killers were exhausted out there, but sometimes, you've got to
sacrifice a little bit more. Dive headfirst in front of a shot if
you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   They've thrown themselves in front of Al MacInnis and his
howitzer of a slap shot, which has been timed at more than 100 mph.
But the St. Louis defenseman still has six of his nine points on
the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're scared of Al's shots, and they're trying to take it
away,'' Demitra said of the Coyotes, ``but that just leaves more
room for the other four guys out there to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes can't play like a collection of Lady Byngs and stay
away from any physical contact. That's not their game. But
penalties could be the death of them. And a whole lot more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
