<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS BACK SCHOENFELD'S VICTORY PROM ISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN, TIM TYERSAND PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It didn't take long for  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld's postgame
comments to filter back into the Coyotes' locker room Sunday after
their 5-3 loss in Game 6 of their first-round playoff series to the
St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win Game 7,'' the head coach predicted. `` . .
. I would tell you I would stake my job on it, but that's already
been done, so I'll just say we're going to win Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld's prediction, however, went over well with most of
his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that. Did he really say that? I'm backing him up
then,'' defenseman
 &UR; J.J. Daigneault said. ``I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   So did center,  &UR; Bob Corkum, who said, ``I'm right behind him on
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I loved that guy,'' chimed in  &UR; Jeremy Roenick, who has
missed the series with a broken jaw and fractured thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain  &UR; Keith Tkachuk, however, was a little bothered
by Schoenfeld's job-status reference, which further fuels questions
about the coach's future in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who starts that stuff, you (media) guys? Does somebody tell
you that?'' Tkachuk said. ``I'm not worried about that. He's our
coach. He's done a great job this year. We can't worry about that.
Everybody's job is on the line here. We're all in it together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with Shoney saying that. He's a great guy, but
you have to win for each other. I don't believe in that. It's out
of my control. We're all in it together as an organization. We
don't need any of that before Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 7 is Tuesday night at America West Arena. As of Sunday,
3,000 tickets remained. &QL; 
What if . . . &QL; 
If the Coyotes win Tuesday night, the second-round series probably
will start Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes would play Dallas if Colorado beats San Jose in that
first-round series, which the Avalanche leads, 3-2. If San Jose
wins Games 6 and 7 to advance to the second round, the Coyotes
would play Detroit in a Western semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes would open on the road regardless of the opponent. &QL; 
Memory power (play) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has scored a playoff-high nine power-play goals in the
series, including two more on Sunday by  &UR; Scott Young and  &UR; Chris
Pronger. It's already the most power-play goals the Coyotes have
had scored against them in a single series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but think back to the time Minnesota went to the
Finals,'' Young said, referring to the 1990-1991 North Stars.
``Their power play was unbelievable. It was on fire. That's why
special teams are so important. Especially in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Stars scored a playoff record 35 power-play goals in
23 total playoff games, but lost to the Pittsburgh Penguins in a
six-game series. Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith played for
the North Stars that season and scored both of Minnesota's
game-winning goals in the two games the North Stars won. &QL; 
Sitting out &QL; 
Although it was St. Louis' most balanced effort of the playoffs,
one player who wasn't a big factor was left wing  &UR; Geoff Courtnall,
who played less than seven minutes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Courtnall, who has played in 16 NHL seasons, missed 57 games
this season with post-concussion syndrome. He returned April 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' he said. ``I don't know what the reason is, but
when you get to the playoffs, you can't complain about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting a taste of what it's like to sit out for a long
stretch, Courtnall said he can find the patience, knowing how lucky
he is to still be competing. &QL; 
Fore and Fuhr &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golfer  &UR; Phil Mickelson must have had a vision about this series.
After the Blues' win on Friday in Phoenix, Mickelson told St. Louis
goalie  &UR; Grant Fuhr not to worry about signing a stick the golfer
had for a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do it Monday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two are expected to play golf together today, which might
stir up the rumor mill again after Fuhr was accused of playing 36
holes the day before he allowed the Coyotes to score five goals in
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Fuhr once again laughed at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you turn 25, 36 is out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr, 36, insisted he played 18 and will do the same today. &QL; 
What advantage? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Al MacInnis, the Blues' leading playoff scorer with
9 points, has played on teams that blew 3-1 leads in seven-game
series and were eliminated, and he thinks he has a good idea what
the Coyotes are thinking as they try to circle the wagons for Game
7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough and frustrating when you get up like that,'' he
said. ``I'm sure they are thinking about Game 5 (3-2 overtime loss)
and letting it slip away like that. The only thing I can say is
going into Game 7, I'd rather be going in having won two rather
than losing two. Momentum is a funny thing, but we have it now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
