<HEADLINE>
SLOW START BE WILDERING TO BENES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ After beginning his workouts earlier than usual,
after losing body fat and increasing his strength, Diamondbacks
pitcher  &UR; Andy Benes envisioned a better start than this, even for a
traditional slow starter.
</P>
<P>
   After five outings, he is 2-2 with an 8.76 ERA. He closed last
season without yielding an earned run in his last 27 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Since his last start Wednesday, when he gave up four earned runs
in six innings to Houston, Benes has been watching film of his last
five starts from last season. Included in the movie classics was
his no-hitter for 8 innings Sept. 13 against the Cincinnati Reds at
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Benes hopes the trip back to the site of his greatest
achievement will help. He'll start today's opener of a three-game
series against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to get too irritated,'' Benes said. ``You try to
find out what you're doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes, who won seven of his last nine decisions last year, said
his main problem is feeling comfortable on the rubber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been in good position to throw the ball,'' he said.
``I think I'll get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach  &UR; Mark Connor said he's been working on mechanics
with Benes since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going uphill on his delivery some,'' Connor said. ``His
fastball is closer to his slider. There's only 5 to 7 mph
difference. There's no variance in velocity. We want him to be at
92 to 93 (mph). No doubt, he'll get there. His command is the
biggest thing.'' &QL; 
Climate control &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Luis Gonzalez, who extended his franchise-record
hitting streak to 16 games Sunday, usually starts the season
slowly, but feels the change of scenery did him good.
</P>
<P>
   He played last year for the Detroit Tigers, where he hit 23 home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel more comfortable with the surroundings,'' Gonzalez
said. ``In Detroit, I hit some home runs, but it was a young team.
Here, it's more relaxed. Guys aren't as intense (in the clubhouse).
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were on pins and needles (in Detroit). Instead of
worrying about being in the big leagues, they were worried about
staying in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez had a career-best 23-game hitting streak with the
Houston Astros two years ago. He says he doesn't think about
streaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out with the same approach every time to have a good,
solid at-bat,'' he said. &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reliever  &UR; Greg Swindell had his first plate appearance since
1996 on Saturday. He flied to right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make contact and not look stupid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only three second basemen in the major leagues have hit 40 or
more home runs in a season:  &UR; Rogers Hornsby, Ryne Sandberg and
 &UR; Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four after this year,'' third baseman  &UR; Matt Williams said loud
enough for second baseman  &UR; Jay Bell to hear. ``How's that for
pressure?''
</P>
<P>
   Bell has eight homers, but says he's no threat to win a home run
title. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
