<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1837 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ORIOLES-GOMEZ-AZR     05-03 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ORIOLES-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBANS' VISIT INCITES EMOTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE - This lunch-pail-in-hand, blue-collar city where
people work hard for a living figures to be transformed into one
huge ratings-gathering network news event today.
</P>
<P>
   In the eye of what figures to be a hurricane will be, of all
things, a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   However, this will be no simple Sunday-in-the-park ballgame.
This event will mark the first time a team composed solely of
Cuban-born players will play against a major league club on U.S.
soil.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Baltimore Orioles' turn tonight to host the final game
of a goodwill two-game exhibition series between the long-sparring
nations at the gem of a stadium called Camden Yards, where tickets
have been long gone for the historic game.
</P>
<P>
   The two clubs met in Cuba in late March, when the Orioles eked
out a 3-2 victory in 11 innings. Critical comments were many after
it was learned the 50,000 tickets to ``Estadio Latinoamerica'' were
distributed by invitation to government employees only.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Orioles are facing criticism of their own for strict
guidelines being imposed for the game.
</P>
<P>
   For those who believe the laughable Orioles, bearers of the
worst record in the majors, were incapable of electrifying this
baseball-mad area this season, here's proof of the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the 1999 Baltimore Orioles actually have little to do
with the rousing emotions building for this game.
</P>
<P>
   The always hot-button issue known as politics is taking the
staring role for this monumental game. Basically, the Orioles have
done very little _ which may be the best way to describe their
season _ other than schedule the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-American groups from Miami to New Jersey, most of them
strongly obstinate, are ready to stage countless protests. Many
will occur outside Camden Yards in designated areas. Some groups,
however, are ready to defy the Orioles' ban of allowing them inside
Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet these groups will have no problem taking on whatever
authority is inside Camden Yards, and tangling with guards is
almost a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban exiles living here are emotional when it comes to the
politics surrounding U.S. relations with their former homeland.
It's the single-biggest reason busloads of people, some who don't
know the first thing about baseball, will caravan to a city that
sits a leisurely 40-minute drive from Washington, the bastion for
freedom around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles are so worried about what might happen that they
successfully petitioned to the Federal Aviation Administration to
have a three-mile radius around the stadium be off-limits to
aircrafts flying below 1,500 feet. Such aircrafts generally tow
banners or drop leaflets over sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the club will enforce a ban on flags and musical
instruments and will ask fans who chant to leave if it is deemed
they are disturbing others.
</P>
<P>
   The previous paragraph could have been written about communist
Cuba, not the land where free speech is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles can do this because they lease the publicly financed
Camden Yards from the state of Maryland and can set any guidelines
inside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   While Cuban-American groups will be busy protesting what they
believe is a feather in President Fidel Castro's cap, it very well
could become a black eye instead, if even one of the Cuban
ballplayers manages to defect during the team's stay in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past seven years, more than a dozen Cuban ballplayers
have managed to defect, among them New York Yankees pitcher Orlando
``El Duque'' Hernandez, his half-brother Livan Hernandez, who
pitches for Florida, New York Mets shortstop Rey Ordonez, Tampa Bay
pitcher Rolando Arrojo and Rene Arocha, who began the list of
defections when he walked away at the Miami airport in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It would instead turn into a coup for Cubans living here, and
agent Joe Cubas, who has helped more than a dozen ballplayers
defect in the past six years and has always been known as someone
capable of pulling off the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   There are strong rumors that Cubas, who has been in Baltimore
since Thursday, may already have lined up the defections of at
least two players who may be on the Cuban roster. This is one of
the reasons the Cubans have been so secretive in releasing the
names of the 25-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the hotel where the Cubans are staying will not
allow incoming phone calls to the players. Also, the floors where
the Cuban delegation is staying are cordoned off from the public.
In short, it's similar to a police state.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in tonight's game, the events surrounding
it will be of greater magnitude that any run-scoring double Albert
Belle or Omar Linares may hit.
</P>
<P>
   This is a game of political chicken, where Cuba stands to be the
only loser, even if the team wins tonight. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
