<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-CALIF.-500-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON COASTS IN CAL 500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Ho-hum. Jeff Gordon again.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed as if Gordon's viselike grip on the NASCAR
Winston Cup throne might be loosening, thanks to three
uncharacteristic DNFs through the season's first nine races,
stock-car racing's dominant driver delivered another sparkling run
into victory lane Sunday at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 27, who has won a remarkable 45 races in just 199 career
starts, easily captured the California 500 by 4.492 seconds over
runner-up Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least it seemed easy.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon led 151 of 250 laps, including 86 of the final 87, and
won for the third time this season.
</P>
<P>
   What slump?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some rough (races) lately, but I knew we could get
back to victory lane, and we proved it today,'' said Gordon, a
victim of three crashes in the past four races.
</P>
<P>
   Proved it?
</P>
<P>
   Heck, the Rainbow Warriors, the nickname given to Gordon's
hearty band of Mr. Fixit crew members, put their seal of approval
on it.
</P>
<P>
   With crew chief Ray Evernham barking signals, Gordon was able to
double a tenuous two-second lead over Bobby Labonte with a
lightning-quick, green-flag pit stop on Lap 207.
</P>
<P>
   Need an analogy? Think of it as Cardinals quarterback Jake
Plummer completing a fourth-and-10 pass to Rob Moore with less two
minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to crunch time, when the pressure is on and it's
time to make a great pit stop, that's what these guys do,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham credited Gordon as much as the fueler, jackman and tire
changers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff did a great job making a clean stop on pit road and the
(pit crew) guys were flawless,'' Evernham said. ``Plus, I'm not
sure (Labonte's) guys maybe didn't have one of their best stops.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gordon returned to the racetrack, a two-second lead had
become nearly 4.5 seconds over Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Lap 215, it grew to 5.081. By Lap 216, it was 5.166.
</P>
<P>
   On Lap 229, it reached 5.594 seconds, and the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   Except Burton had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Burton passed Labonte on Lap 235 and began to slice ever so
gingerly into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon was going to win, Burton reasoned, he wasn't going to
do so without having to keep an eye peeled on the rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, however, Burton realized all hope was lost, even
after cutting the deficit to an even three seconds on Lap 246.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure (Gordon) was running as hard as he could there at
the end,'' said Burton, who increased his lead in the drivers
standings to 55 points over Dale Jarrett. ``I suspect he wasn't. I
started doing the math in my head, and knew I couldn't (catch him).
So I backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Tony Stewart capped another impressive race with a
fourth-place finish. Dale Jarrett was fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton, Jeremy Mayfield, Wally Dallenbach and Terry
Labonte, who finished sixth through ninth, were the only other
drivers to finish on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   For Gordon, the win was a terrific pick-me-up after last week's
miserable showing at Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway, a race in
which he departed early after a crash and a 38th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Ugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels so good,'' Gordon said. ``We had a little bit of
bad luck here lately, but we're only human, and we're going to have
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just have things go our way, if we just have some good
fortune instead of misfortune, we can win races. If we can get that
consistently, we'll be a factor in this championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happened today, and it helped that we had an awesome race
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Stick an awesome race car underneath Gordon and Sunday's result
in front of 117,000 spectators is what you usually get.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's luck even seemed to take a turn for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gordon made a green-flag pit stop seconds before Ricky
Rudd produced a caution after a crash in Turn 3, he was able to
return to the wide two-mile oval so quickly, he still remained atop
the pack while the rest of the front-runners pitted under yellow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
