<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENALTY, FLAT TIRE DON'T KEEP JARRETT FROM GOOD FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Beaten down with an ill-timed pit stop, a flat
tire and a stop-and-go penalty,  &UR; Dale Jarrett still managed a
top-five finish in Sunday's California 500 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett fell a lap down at one point, but he rallied and
remained runner-up to  &UR; Jeff Burton in the NASCAR Winston Cup
drivers standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came down pit road too soon, and I don't understand why you
get a penalty when you don't stop, but I guess that's the rule,''
said Jarrett, who was penalized for coming onto pit road before it
was open following a caution. ``Then, we go back to racing, and we
cut a left-rear tire down. I don't know why we didn't wreck, but we
got lucky and didn't hit anything.'' &QL; 
Numbers game &QL; 
There were five cautions for 23 laps, three of which were for
accidents. There were no serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jeff Gordon's average winning speed was 150.28 mph.
</P>
<P>
   $155,890: Gordon's winner's check. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon now has won two of the three races here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers and NASCAR officials should be happy. Of the nine
cars finishing on the lead, Chevy, Ford and Pontiac each had
three. &QL; 
Tony the tiger &QL; 
Rookie  &UR; Tony Stewart has been terrific.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart finished fourth and now has two top-five and four top-10
finishes in 10 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Gordon had the same statistics his rookie season.
Gordon, however, also had four DNFs. Stewart has none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm finally starting to catch up to the capabilities
of my crew, and it's starting to show,'' Stewart said. ``If we can
keep running in the top five, I'll be tickled to death.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
