<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTTIS NOT MESSING AROUND, RUNS FULL SPEED AT MINICAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -  &UR; Brad Ottis has an unusual souvenir of his career
with the Cardinals. A screw.
</P>
<P>
   A surgical screw that didn't work. It was replaced with an even
larger one last September, causing Ottis, a defensive lineman, to
be placed on injured reserve and miss the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Ottis saw considerable action as the first substitute across the
defensive line two seasons ago. Now he is back and, like the screw
in his left foot, even bigger than before. Intensive weight lifting
has helped him add eight pounds, making him 289. With it comes
reduced body fat, causing him to appear to be bigger yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ottis suffered a fractured foot while working out shortly before
minicamp last year. A screw was implanted surgically to help it
heal.
</P>
<P>
   Then during preseason, Ottis had the foot stepped on and
suffered a refracture that bent the screw. A new one, ``about five
inches long and about as big around as a ball-point pen,'' was
inserted to help the fracture heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've run full speed since I broke my
foot,'' Ottis said Sunday at the conclusion of the Cardinals'
three-day minicamp. ``It feels great. I'm not worried about it
happening again. The doctors said I definitely won't bend this
screw. I've got the first one. It's at home. I just wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's insurance, just as the return of Ottis is insurance
against injury of a front line defender. While Ottis prefers to
play end, his bulked up body will lend itself to his playing
tackle. Left tackle  &UR; Eric Swann is coming back from two knee
surgeries on his arthritic knee and right tackle  &UR; Mark Smith
skipped camp because he wants a larger contract offer. &QL; 
Lonesome ends &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the undrafted rookies, one who caught the eyes of both
Tobin and General Manager  &UR; Bob Ferguson is  &UR; Clarence Williams, a
5-9, 202-pound running back from Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For being undrafted, he certainly has a lot of quickness,''
Tobin said. ``He has what I call juice. He can shake and bake. He's
a little off-size, but he catches well, and he can return kicks.
He'll be an interesting guy in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Another will be linebacker  &UR; Aaron Collins, who was in camp last
year as an undrafted rookie from Penn State before he was cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more mature and more confident,'' Tobin said. ``He has
excellent quickness. If he continues to show what he showed here,
he will be hard-pressed not to make the team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
