<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 08:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-DIARY-REVIEW     05-03 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-DIARY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A HARROWING FLIGHT FROM KOSOVO, AN ALBANIAN LOSES HIS
PATRIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ March 24, the day NATO jets first dropped bombs
on Yugoslavia, was hardly the beginning of troubles for the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, or the starting point of their sorrowful
exile. In the months leading up to the assault, the Yugoslav army
and local police, often working in tandem, forced thousands of
Kosovars to flee their homes. Refugees in their own land, they
wandered from village to village in search of safety and shelter.
With the bombing, the Serbian government stepped up its tactics,
and , some 700,000 Albanians eventually left Kosovo outright, about
half of them crossing into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The camps and shantytowns that have sprung up here are filled
with refugees who can tell stories of a traumatizing odyssey that
has lasted months. Among them is Skender Vehapi, a 47-year-old
farmer from the ancient village of Zatric in the mountains of
southwestern Kosovo, who left his home with his seven children and
extended family eight months ago. His account follows.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANTHONY DePALMA
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long our family has lived in Zatric. My
grandfather was born there and his father before him. We have been
there many, many years. Longer than anybody can remember.
</P>
<P>
   We had a very full life. We had two fields and part of another
with very fertile soil. We grew corn and wheat, and we had a
vineyard. I made a little wine for myself, but most of the grapes
were sold to the state winery nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there were 25 people living on our farm, in two stone
and cement houses that I built myself. We had television, radio and
three djeps (Albanian cradles that are the symbol of Albanian
family and life). It was very beautiful. The village of Zatric is
near a great mountain. The Serbs have renamed it Gradiste, but in
Albanian it was always known as Shipe i Madh.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The closest Serb enclave to Zatric is in
Orahovac, about five miles away. Rolling a cigarette that he would
smoke in a long metal holder, Vehapi said he never knew any Serbs
personally, and only saw them passing on the road. (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago was the first sign that there was going to be
real trouble for Zatric.
</P>
<P>
   The police came to my house and also to the houses of my
relatives. They ordered us to give them our arms. But we didn't
have any guns. They came into the house and started searching for
guns. Then they beat me, right in front of my family, screaming at
me to give them my guns. But I didn't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The Serbs singled out many Kosovar villages
because they harbored the Kosovo Liberation Army, a sometimes
ragtag, often disorganized group fighting for Kosovo's freedom.
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``The K.L.A. was there in Zatric starting in March 1998. The
Serbs knew that. Their offensive in our region began on Sept. 3 and
lasted until Sept. 5. First they shelled the village, shooting the
bombs from other villages nearby. The shells started falling at 8
o'clock in the morning and continued until 5 in the afternoon
without pause. I remember it very clearly. It was a Thursday. We
left Zatric that day.
</P>
<P>
   We loaded a wagon and hooked it to our tractor. We left the
village and went into the mountains. On that night, the Serbs
entered Zatric. They stayed all night and they killed three people
who hadn't left. They took everything they could take and then they
burned our houses.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The next day Serb forces scoured the
mountains looking for the villagers. Vehapi and others left behind
all their belongings and their tractors and headed to the village
of Ponorac where they joined refugees from several other villages.
Serb forces soon surrounded them. Some of the men _ about 200 _
decided it would be safest for their families if they separated.
The men walked to the village of Crnovrana. For Vehapi and the
others it was a difficult decision.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't describe how I felt at that moment. I was thinking
that maybe they would kill my wife and all my children. But, I tell
you, I was afraid. When the Serbs came, they were carrying big
knives and scythes that they were sharpening right in front of the
children. They had kerchiefs on their heads. There were regular
police and army but also many paramilitary forces and mercenaries.
It was very frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
