u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-DIARY-REVIEW     05-03 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-DIARY-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 KUKES: It was very frightening.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (END ITALICS HERE)Those left behind were separated _ the old
men, women and children were allowed to go, while the men of
military age were herded into a school and kept for 24 hours.
Vehapi returned to his home. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it with my own eyes. It had been burned from the inside,
like all the others. Two of the walls had collapsed. There was
nothing left inside, nothing. In Zatric there used to be 78
families, each with its own farm and houses. Only three of them
were not burned.
</P>
<P>
   The tractors were also burned, along with most of what we had
taken from the house. But the djep was about six feet away because
one of the children was playing with it and it was saved. My
tractor was left without tires. But I was able to repair it later
and get it going again.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)His home destroyed, Vehapi moved to the
village of Pastacel. March 24, the initiation of the NATO attacks,
was an ordinary day. But on March 30, Serbian forces entered the
nearby village of Pecovic and burned it. The villagers and refugees
of Pastacel knew they were next. They gathered to discuss what to
do. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``The local people said we cannot go anywhere, we don't know
where to go. We must stay here. But I said to the villagers that we
must leave. But they refused to go.
</P>
<P>
   I took my family and my father-in-law and went to Ratkovac.
After we left Pastacel, the Serbian forces came in and surrounded
the people. It was a massacre. There were 106 people who were
killed, including 14 people from my own village of Zatric who had
taken refuge in Pastacel. The next day, after the Serbs had gone, I
left my family in Ratkovac and came back to Pastacel and helped to
bury the victims.
</P>
<P>
   What we saw was terrible. It was a nightmare. They had separated
all the men into groups of 15 each and killed them all in one
place. The bodies fell in groups into a small stream. The stream
was running with blood. The bodies were piled one on top of the
other.
</P>
<P>
   We spent three days trying to bury them. We took the bodies from
the stream and brought them to the field. When the police came
back, we ran. Then we came back and, using shovels, we buried them
in the field next to the mosque. They were not buried very deep,
just enough to cover them. We couldn't hold a ceremony or even put
up a marker for them. The head of the mosque said a brief prayer,
but that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)On April 2 or 3, Vehapi can't remember, Serb
soldiers came to Ratkovac with tanks and ordered the villagers to
leave their houses immediately. That began the final leg of his
wandering in Kosovo. He would be on the road for 20 days, finally
crossing the border into Albania at 4:30 a.m. April 22.(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain what it felt like to cross the border. I
couldn't believe I had been forced to leave Kosovo. I was very
happy to be here, and thought ``My God, now my family is safe.''
But at the same time leaving Kosovo broke my heart. Until the
moment I crossed the border, my head was turned back over my
shoulder and I kept looking at Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Vehapi spent his first days in Albania in a
plastic tent that he erected alongside his tractor. (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do now is close my eyes and try to put it all out of
my head. I think about Zatric. And I think that everything would be
all right if I could just see Shipe i Madh one more time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
