<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 08:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-WARCOSTS-REV     05-03 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-WARCOSTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT COSTS A LOT MORE TO KILL FEWER PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For an air war that many U.S. generals believe has
been run on the cheap, tactically, the bombardment of Yugoslavia
could go down as the most expensive military campaign, bomb for
bomb, in history.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton,
likes to brag that 90 percent of the bombs dropped in the 40-day
operation have been precision-guided, compared to only 9 percent in
the 1991 Persian Gulf war, reducing risks to civilians on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of keeping the civilian casualties low is steep.
Cruise missiles fired from ships and submarines run $1 million
apiece, and their heftier cousins launched off B-52s cost twice
that. A laser-guided, 2,000-pound bomb dropped from a radar-evading
F-117 costs $26,200, compared to unguided bombs pitched from B-1
and B-52 bombers, which run about $600 each.
</P>
<P>
   When asked the other day if NATO was using million-dollar
weapons to bomb $10,000 targets, like military trucks and small
bridges, Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's military commander, bristled.
``This is not a war that we're running on a checkbook budget,'' he
snapped. ``We're running this war to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the armaments money can buy, though, the air war
has yet to achieve its goal of forcing Yugoslavia to withdraw its
troops in Kosovo and allowing refugees to return with international
military escorts. Politics and the elements have conspired to level
out the allies' technological edge. Bad weather trumps a pilot's
ability to aim a laser-guided bomb, and Defense Secretary William
Cohen said last week there have only been about half a dozen days
free from rain and fog.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the skies cleared, NATO pinpoint accuracy didn't stop
the 40,000-strong Yugoslav army and special police from purging
most of the 1.8 million ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, or from
avoiding gruesome civilian casualties, like the two convoys and a
passenger train that were accidentally blasted to bits by allied
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, NATO's political leaders have restricted the targets
pilots could hit and the tactics they use to hit them. Low-flying
ground-attack planes like the A-10, ideal for blasting tanks, have
flown few bombing runs for fear they are still too vulnerable to
Yugoslav missiles. Other high-flying jets have picked up many of
those missions, but it's difficult to distinguish a farmer's truck
from armored infantry vehicle at 20,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's driving me nuts,'' said Gen. George Joulwan, Clark's
predecessor as supreme commander of the allied forces in Europe.
``We're better than this. I really don't understand, unless someone
thought we could drop a few bombs and get off cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Half-hearted tactics, perhaps, but the costs have been anything
but. Entering the sixth week of a campaign many NATO commanders
thought would last only a few days, the Pentagon is running up
bills that approach $1 billion, and Congress is preparing to
approve the Clinton administration's request for $6 billion to
finance the war through September, if needed. It's far less than
the much larger Persian Gulf war, which lasted 44 days and cost $61
billion (most of which allies like Saudi Arabia paid for). The
Pentagon says this war is costing about $37 million a day, and
that's not counting the relief operation for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Congress prepares to add billions of dollars to the
administration's war tab to buy new bombs, missiles and other
weapons the Defense Department didn't request, some lawmakers are
criticizing the Pentagon's spendthrift ways in the Balkans. It's
costing $700 million to send 24 Apache helicopters and long-range
artillery from Germany to Albania, said Rep. John Murtha of
Pennsylvania, a senior Democrat on the Appropriations Committee. He
said he's angry that every night, NATO launches 300 to 600 missions
to bomb perhaps two dozen targets or so. With clear skies predicted
for the next few days, both numbers are likely to increase. ``I
need to hear why so many planes are up and there are so few
targets,'' said Murtha, a gruff former marine.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that NATO hasn't had enough bases for the
more than 700 allied aircraft joining the air war. Only recently
did NATO negotiate with Hungary to allow fighter-bombers and,
equally important, the refueling planes that keep them aloft. Now,
the aerial refuelers have to fly from as far away as Spain, England
and France, burning up precious fuel that could keep fighters
flying.
</P>
<P>
   One seasoned F-16 pilot, stationed at Aviano air base in Italy,
said in an interview that the air space is so crowded that the most
dangerous part of flying in the Balkans is circling at night, along
with dozens of other fighter jets, at 500 miles per hour in
thunderstorms and lightning to get more gasoline from airborne
refueling planes. ``It's kind of like New York City traffic up
there,'' the pilot said.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Pentagon officials said, the Air Force
didn't plan ahead, as the Navy and Army did, to equip all its
aviators with night-vision goggles that cost $7,000 a set. ``It's
the difference between driving with your parking lights or
headlights,'' said the F-16 pilot, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   There are other mismatches between the high-cost mission and
tactical common sense. The combat debut of the B-2 bomber has been
notable, if for nothing else than its 31-hour (at $5,719 an hour)
round-trip flight to the Balkans from its base in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon might have stationed the stealthy B-2 in a friendly
country like Britain, and saved about $270,000 per mission, except
that the Air Force is squabbling with a California company over the
details of a contract to produce a mobile, climate-controlled
hangar that is needed to protect the bomber's sensitive,
radar-absorbing skin.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, NATO commanders are hoping just a few more of their
costly bombs will be needed to force Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no interest in destroying more targets in Serbia than
is absolutely necessary,'' said Denmark's chief of defense, Gen.
Christian Hvidt, a former F-16 fighter pilot. ``We dislike using
power, really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
