<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1965 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CHINA-PARTY-REVIEW-     05-03 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-PARTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE COMMUNISTS SAY THE PARTY ISN'T OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ That the Communist Party is losing touch with the
masses is an open worry to leaders here. The latest shock to the
system came last week with the sudden demonstration by the
spiritual cult called Buddhist Law, a movement claiming tens of
millions of Chinese members. So what is party chief Jiang Zemin
doing to create a more relevant Communist Party for the 21st
century?
</P>
<P>
   Old habits, it seems, die hard: Jiang's top aides have been busy
mounting an old-fashioned ``rectification'' campaign to promote
ideological conformity among the millions of cadres who purportedly
run the country, to re-invigorate the party and, not incidentally,
to assure Jiang a place in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Three Stresses campaign, as it is known, is being waged in
party offices, government agencies and the army. The senior ranks
at universities, research centers and publishing houses are next.
Under the command to ``stress study, stress politics and stress
rectitude,'' officials are required to read specially prepared
textbooks including works by Mao Tse-tung, Deng Xiaoping and, of
course, Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt officials will read and reread Jiang's speeches, which
are filled with abstruse rationalizations for economic reforms as
well as demands for social stability and party unity. A typical
Jiangism: ``Unwaveringly upholding the party's general line
requires properly handling the relationship between reform,
development and stability at all times.'' Such words hold the key,
or so officials hope, to discerning the proper line in a confusing
period.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of weeks, high officials in a given workplace must
participate in group discussions and write critiques of their own
errors in thought and deed _ whether they have put the interests of
the party ahead of personal gain. They are also instructed to write
anonymous critiques of their organizations and bosses for use in
additional group sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But even if party discipline improves, it is unclear how the
change will help China's rulers govern an increasingly diverse and
demanding society. Officials seemed bewildered by the giant
demonstration by the Buddhist Law movement, which wants official
acceptance, not Communist regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's campaign lacks the ferocity of drives dating from the
1940s, and participants describe the sessions as boring. But he is
using traditional methods to corral wayward cadres that are prone
to corruption and ideological wandering. According to a retired
official, he also hopes to identify loyal, promising officials for
future leadership positions.
</P>
<P>
   With 21 traveling inspection teams monitoring compliance, the
Three Stresses campaign is going national. Supervising them is Vice
President Hu Jintao, who appears to be Jiang's favored successor if
he retires from party leadership as expected in 2002, and Zeng
Qinghong, Jiang's close adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang has shown every sign that he aspires to enter the pantheon
of great Communist philosopher-leaders like Mao and Deng. Among
other things, three times in recent weeks he has had his
calligraphy printed, Mao-style, on the front page of the People's
Daily _ something he would never have dared to do a few years ago
when his status was less secure.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang was widely dismissed as a caretaker when Deng installed
him as party chief in 1989, after the traumatic crushing of mass
protests in Tiananmen Square. But he seems to want credit as a
masterful contributor to the progress of the party and its guiding
thought _ the ``third generation'' titan whose essays and speeches
will find a place alongside Mao Tse-tung Thought and Deng Xiaoping
Theory.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's aides are now at work compiling his speeches and
writings, possibly in time for October's celebration of the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
