<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1966 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SOCSEC-POLITICS-REV     05-03 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SOCSEC-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IDEOLOGY GOES WHERE ACTUARIES TREAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As legislation, the plan to overhaul the Social
Security system announced last week by two influential Republican
congressmen is going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have concluded that their party cannot touch
Social Security without getting burned politically, and they have
made clear that they have no intention of allowing any Republican
legislation making fundamental changes in the popular retirement
system to come to a vote before the next election.
</P>
<P>
   But as a case study in politics and the development of
government policy, the new Social Security plan belongs in the
textbooks. It shows how when politicians dig beneath the surface of
a complicated topic, they often learn that their ideological
preconceptions are unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, particularly the most conservative ones, have never
much liked Social Security. Their feel the country would be better
off if the government's role in the pension system were minimal and
if workers could invest their retirement money at will in the
financial markets, draw benefits based on how well their
investments performed, and pass on to their heirs what was left of
their retirement savings when they died.
</P>
<P>
   So when the main Republican entry in the Social Security reform
sweepstakes was announced last week, many in the party who had not
been involved in its preparation were flabbergasted. Far from the
free-market approach that most Republicans say they favor, the
measure would strictly limit private investments, pay the same
benefits to retirees no matter where they invested their money and
leave nothing at retirees' death that could be willed to the next
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was lambasted by the conservative policy purveyors at
the Heritage Foundation and the Cato Institute and denounced by
many Republicans in Congress. ``I could never support anything like
that,'' said Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, a committed conservative who
is chairman of the Budget Committee and a long-shot candidate for
the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsors of the plan _ Reps. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, and E. Clay Shaw Jr.,
R-Fla., chairman of the Social Security subcommittee, both
conservatives to the core _ almost seemed surprised at the way
their proposal had turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it would work: The government would give workers
money through tax rebates and require them to invest it in private
retirement accounts. So far so good, from the conservative
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   But get this: The measure would also require that the
investments be precisely 60 percent in stock index funds and 40
percent in corporate bonds. When workers retire, they would have to
give their retirement accounts to the government, which would
convert the money into financial instruments called annuities that
would pay retirees a fixed monthly sum for the rest of their lives
and expire when they died. Workers would be guaranteed that their
monthly check would be at least as large as what they would get
under the current Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   This means workers would have nothing from the accounts to leave
to their heirs unless they and their spouse died before either
retired. And because the monthly payment retirees would be entitled
to under Social Security would almost always be larger than what
they would receive from their annuity alone, retirees' benefits in
practice would be the same no matter how the investments they had
made during their working lives had performed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had included such rigid government controls in his
plan, given his predilection for an investment-based approach to
Social Security, Shaw replied, ``There is no other way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose Archer and Shaw had not mandated that investments be
exactly 60 percent in stocks and 40 percent in bonds. Then workers
might as well put their money in the riskiest ventures imaginable.
After all, their retirement benefits would be guaranteed if the
investment failed. In such a situation, the Social Security
actuaries would not have certified, as they did last week, that the
Republican plan would preserve the solvency of the system for the
next 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   What if the plan did not require workers to surrender their
accounts for annuities when they retired? Then long-lived people
might exhaust their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be absolutely certain that no one, no one in
America, would become a ward of the state when they got old,''
Archer said. ``What became very clear as we went along was that as
long as the government is providing the money, it doesn't work
without government standards.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the Republican dream of turning Social Security into
a mostly private system. Like countless other radical departures
(communism in Europe; Prohibition in the United States),
privatization of Social Security turns out under scrutiny to have
more drawbacks than benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what keeps those of us who study policy in business,''
said Donald Kettl, a political science professor at the University
of Wisconsin. ``Policy is almost always more complicated than what
it looks like in the headlines. If you worry about the mechanics,
then you lose the headlines,'' Kettl continued. ``And if you lose
the headlines, then you lose support.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the lesson of Bill Archer and Clay Shaw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 0906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SOCSEC-POLITICS-REV     05-03 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SOCSEC-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IDEOLOGY GOES WHERE ACTUARIES TREAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As legislation, the plan to overhaul the Social
Security system announced last week by two influential Republican
congressmen is going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have concluded that their party cannot touch
Social Security without getting burned politically, and they have
made clear that they have no intention of allowing any Republican
legislation making fundamental changes in the popular retirement
system to come to a vote before the next election.
</P>
<P>
   But as a case study in politics and the development of
government policy, the new Social Security plan belongs in the
textbooks. It shows how when politicians dig beneath the surface of
a complicated topic, they often learn that their ideological
preconceptions are unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, particularly the most conservative ones, have never
much liked Social Security. Their feel the country would be better
off if the government's role in the pension system were minimal and
if workers could invest their retirement money at will in the
financial markets, draw benefits based on how well their
investments performed, and pass on to their heirs what was left of
their retirement savings when they died.
</P>
<P>
   So when the main Republican entry in the Social Security reform
sweepstakes was announced last week, many in the party who had not
been involved in its preparation were flabbergasted. Far from the
free-market approach that most Republicans say they favor, the
measure would strictly limit private investments, pay the same
benefits to retirees no matter where they invested their money and
leave nothing at retirees' death that could be willed to the next
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was lambasted by the conservative policy purveyors at
the Heritage Foundation and the Cato Institute and denounced by
many Republicans in Congress. ``I could never support anything like
that,'' said Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, a committed conservative who
is chairman of the Budget Committee and a long-shot candidate for
the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsors of the plan _ Reps. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, and E. Clay Shaw Jr.,
R-Fla., chairman of the Social Security subcommittee, both
conservatives to the core _ almost seemed surprised at the way
their proposal had turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it would work: The government would give workers
money through tax rebates and require them to invest it in private
retirement accounts. So far so good, from the conservative
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   But get this: The measure would also require that the
investments be precisely 60 percent in stock index funds and 40
percent in corporate bonds. When workers retire, they would have to
give their retirement accounts to the government, which would
convert the money into financial instruments called annuities that
would pay retirees a fixed monthly sum for the rest of their lives
and expire when they died. Workers would be guaranteed that their
monthly check would be at least as large as what they would get
under the current Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   This means workers would have nothing from the accounts to leave
to their heirs unless they and their spouse died before either
retired. And because the monthly payment retirees would be entitled
to under Social Security would almost always be larger than what
they would receive from their annuity alone, retirees' benefits in
practice would be the same no matter how the investments they had
made during their working lives had performed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had included such rigid government controls in his
plan, given his predilection for an investment-based approach to
Social Security, Shaw replied, ``There is no other way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose Archer and Shaw had not mandated that investments be
exactly 60 percent in stocks and 40 percent in bonds. Then workers
might as well put their money in the riskiest ventures imaginable.
After all, their retirement benefits would be guaranteed if the
investment failed. In such a situation, the Social Security
actuaries would not have certified, as they did last week, that the
Republican plan would preserve the solvency of the system for the
next 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   What if the plan did not require workers to surrender their
accounts for annuities when they retired? Then long-lived people
might exhaust their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be absolutely certain that no one, no one in
America, would become a ward of the state when they got old,''
Archer said. ``What became very clear as we went along was that as
long as the government is providing the money, it doesn't work
without government standards.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the Republican dream of turning Social Security into
a mostly private system. Like countless other radical departures
(communism in Europe; Prohibition in the United States),
privatization of Social Security turns out under scrutiny to have
more drawbacks than benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what keeps those of us who study policy in business,''
said Donald Kettl, a political science professor at the University
of Wisconsin. ``Policy is almost always more complicated than what
it looks like in the headlines. If you worry about the mechanics,
then you lose the headlines,'' Kettl continued. ``And if you lose
the headlines, then you lose support.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the lesson of Bill Archer and Clay Shaw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
