<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONGRESS-WAR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY CONGRESS CAN DECLARE WAR, BUT IT ALMOST NEVER HAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was the bombing of Cambodia and the national
anguish over Vietnam that spurred Congress, over Richard M. Nixon's
veto, to enact a law that it hoped would prevent any other
president from waging undeclared war.
</P>
<P>
   The War Powers Resolution of 1973 was a masterpiece of deadlines
and trip wires, all carefully constructed to keep a president in
check. It called for consultation with Congress in matters of war.
It required the commander in chief to notify Congress quickly when
U.S. troops were being sent to face possible hostilities. And it
said troops had to be removed from foreign territory within 60 to
90 days unless Congress explicitly approved their mission.
</P>
<P>
   But the law could do nothing to change the essential nature of
Congress. Lawmakers rarely like to take an assertive stance on war
_ and most particularly not before the chances of success or the
poll ratings become clear. If anyone wanted proof of this it came
last week when Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., ignored the entreaties
of the House leadership and used the Vietnam-era legislation to
force the House to take a stand on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The result? A philosophical muddle devoid of practical effect.
</P>
<P>
   The House refused to declare war. It would not ratify the
bombing already underway against Yugoslavia. Nor would it pull out
the troops in order to stop the bombing. Then it demanded the right
to vote again before President Clinton could widen the conflict to
ground troops. The next day, a House committee proposed to give the
president more than twice as much money as he wanted for the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signals being sent around the world are confusing,'' said
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
fumed that the House action was a ``low moment in American foreign
policy and the history of this institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Debate over how the president and Congress should share power in
matters of war is as old as the Republic. Presidents have sent
forces abroad more than 100 times; Congress has declared war only
five times: the War of 1812, the Mexican-American War, the
Spanish-American War, World War I and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Article II of the Constitution makes the president commander in
chief. But Article I puts responsibility for declaring war solely
in congressional hands, and Congress, most notably in 1973, has
spasmodically tried to keep it there. But in practice, it has long
been content to cede most of that authority to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' war powers were rarely seriously challenged until this
century. But the nuclear age and the Cold War led presidents to
assume more power. In 1950, Harry S. Truman found a new way to
side-step Congress: he used United Nations resolutions instead of a
declaration of war by Congress to send troops to Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for the past quarter of a century presidents and
Congress have almost seemed to conspire to find ways around the war
powers law.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents, after all, have never conceded that the law is
constitutional. And Congress, for fear of being accused of giving
aid and comfort to the enemy, has always shied away from pulling
back troops once confronted with a fait accompli by a president.
``Even though the law is still on the books it has basically been
ignored,'' said Peter Spiro, an associate professor at Hofstra
University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   So, for example, presidents have used semantic tricks to
minimize the role of Congress in military engagements and get
around the deadlines for congressional ratification. Troops are
sent into foreign conflicts that presidents insist are not
``hostilities'' under the definition of the war powers law.
Presidents assert they have satisfied the requirement to
``consult'' Congress by informing a select circle of Congressional
leaders of actions already underway.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan told Congress of the invasion of Grenada two
hours after he had ordered the landing. He told congressional
leaders of the bombing of Libya while the aircraft were on their
way. And he did not report formally to Congress when he increased
the number of military advisers in El Salvador in 1981 because he
argued there was no imminent threat of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Though Congress did vote on the Persian Gulf war, it did so only
in January 1991, just days before U.S. bombs began to fall on Iraq.
For months as half a million U.S. troops assembled in Saudi Arabia,
Congress was slow and cautious, taking little action beyond
complaining to President Bush that he needed congressional
approval. And when Clinton sent troops to Haiti, his administration
argued that no congressional approval was needed because there was
no war _ the troops had been invited.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who acknowledges ``there's a natural inclination not
to want to go on record on a controversial matter until and unless
you have to,'' believes that the war powers law may have actually
done the opposite of what its drafters intended, actively
discouraging Congress from taking stands on wars. He said
presidents and Congress often view the 90-day time limit the law
sets for a deployment without congressional approval as a grace
period during which Congress does not have to take a stand.
Afterward, with U.S. soldiers under fire, a vote against war is
politically untenable.
</P>
<P>
   Across the years, some dissident members of Congress have turned
to the courts to try to test the president's power to wage war
unilaterally. But they have been rebuffed because in each case
Congress had failed to pass a resolution ordering the president to
remove the troops.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the House on record against declaring war in
Yugoslavia, Campbell is taking another stab at recapturing
Congress' theoretical war-making authority by seeking a court
ruling to stop U.S. participation in the air war against
Yugoslavia. He may or may not get a decision before the fighting
stops.
</P>
</TEXT>
