<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1986 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COPYCATS-COX     05-03 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPYCATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado massacre spawns copycats, fear
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ SWAT teams and bomb disposal squads are
showing up on school grounds with the regularity of visiting
football teams.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are wondering whether the school year is effectively
finished. Teachers watch warily for bulging back packs. Students
look over their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Colorado high school massacre 13 days ago, more than a
dozen Florida middle and high school students have been questioned
by police after making specific threats to blow up or shoot
teachers and students. Several were suspended, a few arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, hundreds of bomb threats have been reported
at schools. A monotonous litany of copycat calls and written
warnings kept thousands out of class. On Friday, many schools
closed because of rumored violence, some tied to the anniversary of
Hitler's suicide.
</P>
<P>
   All of these incidents are news because they affected families
and educators in communities coast to coast. Still, questions must
be asked about how direct a connection there is between each
incident and the shootings at Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   If there are connections, what are they? Are other, important
lessons from the Colorado carnage being ignored because the media
and students and parents are all caught up in a national hysteria?
</P>
<P>
   Is reason being applied to fact, or is fear flowing from rumor?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumor and fear are now the enemy,'' says David Cantley,
principal of Lake Worth High School. ``It's so quiet here it's
scary. We've had a quiet year, just the usual friendly fistfights
between willing participants. But the rumors since the Colorado
shootings are causing chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go onto the P.A. system to say, `No, I have not been
threatened; no, there is no gang on the way to shoot it out with
Mexican students; no, there has been no face-off between Haitian
and white students.' Even then, a student misunderstood and his
father called me at home, upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Cantley finally had to call police to Lake Worth High to
help him quell rumors, not because of any actual incident.
</P>
<P>
   Are today's schools are out of control? Or are the perpetrators
this year's model of the wise guys who have pulled fire alarms for
as long as there have been alarms to pull? Are they angry kids?
Idle kids? Evil?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have far, far fewer false alarms and bomb threats than 15
years ago. I've heard that back in the desegregation era of the
early '70s, it was just crazy _ bomb threats, rumors. Years ago,
the Lake Worth police used to rotate through this building 20 times
a day it seems, for fights, threats, trouble. Schools are safer
now, and we'll keep them safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Drop in gun crimes
</P>
<P>
   Statistics back up Cantley.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the U.S. Department of Justice released a report on
strategies to reduce gun violence. The report states: ``Gun related
crime peaked in the late 1980s and early 1990s. Since that time,
the United States has made steady progress in reducing gun-related
violence. Between 1992 and 1996, handgun homicides declined 35
percent. Murder rates declined by 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also states that schools are the safest place for
children, especially those from high-crime neighborhoods _ safer
than streets, playgrounds, work places, and, safer than the home.
</P>
<P>
   Among the conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   Violent deaths in school settings declined 27.3 percent between
1992 and 1996. Less than 1 percent of all violent crimes against
youths take place in schools.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year study by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention found that the incidence of school-related violent death
was less than one in a million.
</P>
<P>
   During school year 1996-1997, more than 54 million students
attended U.S. schools; 40 were killed in school.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, according to Barry Glassner, a professor of sociology
at the University of California, the number of murder stories on
network newscasts increased 600 percent since 1990, ``not counting
stories about O.J. Simpson.''
</P>
<P>
   Glassner says in his book, FEAR, Why Americans are Afraid of the
Wrong Things, ``Valid fears have their place; they cue us to
danger. False and overdrawn fears only cause hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   He stresses one point throughout the book: TV violence, whether
news or fiction, sometimes causes fear but does not cause violence.
He advises adults and parents to sift through misinformation for
the rational nuggets that can help solve real problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cantley agrees. ``My advice to students is turn off the TV.
These kids have active imaginations. What they see on TV, over and
over and over again, does nothing but scare them. They need to be
active, play their sports, do their homework, talk to their parents
about news that troubles them. But turn off the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Glassner goes Cantley one better. ``Kids shouldn't have to turn
off the TV,'' he says. ``They should be able to watch well
reasoned, informative coverage that explores facts and debunks
myths. They ought to learn from TV, not become afraid, except of
those things they should be afraid of.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the Colorado footage over and over again on TV and you
begin to feel that this type of incident is more frequent than it
is. Then you ask why, but your question is based on paranoia,
faulty information. Of course it seems that way, you're seeing the
same scene over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``And count the times you hear words like `cult,' `Marilyn
Manson,' `epidemic.' These are words that put you on a path to
nowhere. The question should be: What does it take to commit mass
murder? The answer is: weapons of mass destruction. Guns. And
bombs, even though nobody in Colorado died from a bomb. As long as
the media talk about epidemics of violence, real questions will go
unanswered. All you'll get is fear. The wrong fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools are safe. Statistic: A student is three times more
likely to be hit by lightning than be killed in school.
</P>
<P>
   But how to prevent the lightning strike? And what to do when
lightning strikes?
</P>
<P>
   Cantley says he and his teachers are always on the lookout for
behavioral changes in students, a sudden drop in grades, hints of
trouble at home.
</P>
<P>
   Cantley's biggest fear after Colorado is police response time if
there were a real hostage situation or shooting at his school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt the Lake Worth police would show up fast and
go into this school like bulldogs,'' he says. ``They've been to the
school for walk-through assessments. They have the blueprints. But
as I watched the coverage of the Colorado shootings, I found myself
thinking, `Am I supposed to stand outside my school for three hours
while SWAT teams tiptoe around the bushes and my kids are inside?'
Not on your life. I'm going back into my school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a credible fear,'' says Glassner. ``Why did it take
Colorado police three hours to get kids out? That's a good
question, one that can offer a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't there, so I'm not going to criticize the Colorado
response,'' says Capt. Jack Maxwell, head of the Palm Beach County
Sheriff's Office Special Response Team. ``But if kids are watching
those tapes, I don't blame them for being afraid. I hate to say it,
but I can see myself in the near future at schools lecturing
students and teachers on the proper response to a terrorist-style
incident. Everybody has a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team's job in a hostage taking or shooting is to isolate
and contain the suspects quickly. We'd look for signs of what sort
of weapons they have, how many wounded, how many suspects. Every
situation is different, but the focus remains the same _ isolate
and contain.''
</P>
<P>
   The former head of an FBI SWAT team in New England added: ``We'd
head for the shots, the smoke, the screams. You don't want your
people hurt, but you go in _ fast. Colorado wasn't a hostage
situation where you get the pizza guy there and everybody talks on
the phone. It was a mess, but you have to step over the bombs and
hope they don't explode. You keep moving. Your target is the bad
guys. Find them. If they're still shooting, shoot them. Shoot to
kill. That's the best way to save the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparedness is key
</P>
<P>
   Colorado police spokesmen say the scene at Columbine High School
was chaos _ tiles falling, sprinklers flooding halls, bombs all
over the place, a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was chaotic,'' says the Boston FBI agent, who
asked not to be identified. ``But it wasn't a crime scene until it
was over. Then the lab guys and bomb guys go in. Two lessons can be
learned from Colorado. You save lives by taking out the shooters
fast. Second, kids and teachers must be prepared to help
themselves. Look out the door, listen for the direction of shots.
Go out the way the police came in. Make a break for it if the good
guys haven't shown up. You can't sit under a desk for three hours
and wait your turn to be shot. Have a plan. If anything halfway
good comes out of this, it's the need for everyone to have a plan
and know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantley agrees. ``We had, years ago, a plan to respond to gunmen
in the school, a c
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
