<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Presidents at their worst
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have a theory about the U.S. presidency. It goes something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. presidency has been going from bad to worse for 40
years, and the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following, all of whom helped put the hiss in
history.
</P>
<P>
   _ JFK assassinated in his first term, which turned out to be a
good career move. As it was, the worst of Kennedy's private life
would remain blacked out for another generation.
</P>
<P>
   _ LBJ was going to nail the coonskin to the wall, he said of
Vietnam. He ended up a casualty of his own making, along with
58,000 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nixon was forced to resign in the wake of the Watergate
scandal, such was his disgrace. What a liar. He even tried to tell
the American public he was not a crook.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ford was our stand-in president who had trouble standing on
his own two feet. After he pardoned Nixon, a majority of voters in
the next election were quick to trade him in.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carter is best remembered as the malaise president, the man
Iran had running scared. Let it be said in his favor: He's probably
the best ex-president we've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reagan acted the part well enough, reading the lines they gave
him. Too bad we couldn't read between the lines. His legacy was a
$3 trillion national debt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush lost the presidency even though he won the war, doing
what we should have done in Vietnam _ declaring victory and pulling
out. Never mind Saddam's still on his throne, and we're still
suffering casualties from Gulf War syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton, the Comeback Kid who can't help coming on to the
women, turned out to be an embarrassment with a capital ASS. If he
ever visits war-torn Kosovo, he'll probably arrive with his pockets
stuffed with nylons.
</P>
<P>
   That takes us up to today, and beyond that, tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Next president? How about the worst-case scenario for the worst
yet?
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting on Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   What convinced me was a list of Quayle quotes making the rounds
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, here's a sampling of responses reported during
his term as vice president:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love California, I practically grew up in Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A low voter turnout is an indication of fewer people going to
the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Illegitimacy is something we should talk about in terms of not
having it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready for any unforeseen event that may or may not
occur.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For NASA, space is still a high priority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, teachers are the only profession that teach our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't pollution that's harming the environment. It's the
impurities in our air and water that are doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a waste it is to lose one's mind. Or not having a mind is
very wasteful.'' He was trying to recite, ``A mind is a terrible
thing to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``May our nation continue to be the beakon of hope to the
world.'' The Quayles' 1989 Christmas card, not exactly a beacon of
literacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have the best-educated American people in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on and on. But suffice it to say, the following
says it all:
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by all the misstatements I've made.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe I'm wrong. Maybe choosing a rotten log as presidential
timber isn't inevitable. Maybe things will improve.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Dan Quayle once said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are on an irreversible trend ... but that could
change.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
