<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GEEWAX-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time capsules fulfill urge to preserve
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since ancient hunters started drawing pictures on cave
walls, human beings have been trying to pass along their life
stories to future generations. Over the ages, we have gotten better
at preserving our drawings, writings, clothing, tools and other
objects to inform descendents about our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Now as the millennium winds down, this urge to preserve is
growing. Individuals, families, schools, clubs, churches and
corporations are creating lots of new time capsules to be sealed up
Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most people define a ``time capsule'' as a container filled with
items chosen to reflect daily life at a particular time. The
original experts were the ancient Egyptians. They built enormous
pyramids to serve not only as vessels to the afterlife but also as
bridges to the future. They filled their stone pyramids with
jewelry, furniture, urns, garments, cuneiform inscriptions and
other objects that tell about life some 4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, we generally have stuffed our objects into the
cornerstones of important buildings, such as schools, churches and
government offices. For example, a cornerstone in an 1851 extension
of the U.S. Capitol lies undisturbed since it was filled with
coins, newspapers and historical parchments.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, the desire to preserve information and
objects for posterity has gotten a boost from the creation of tough
new materials.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1939 World's Fair, for example, Westinghouse Electric
built a time capsule from a new alloy of copper, called Cupaloy.
The durable capsule was buried in Flushing, Queens, in a crypt that
incorporated Pyrex glass, water repellents and preservative gases.
</P>
<P>
   Should the capsule last its intended 5,000 years, our
descendents will find an array of goods including a Sears Roebuck
catalog, a Mickey Mouse cup, cigarettes, a fountain pen, a slide
rule and an electric lamp.
</P>
<P>
   Today, one small company in Morgan Hill, Calif., is selling
aluminum capsules designed to last for hundreds of years without
rusting or becoming brittle.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the clubs and corporations buying the cylindrical
devices, which look a little like a Thermos bottle, are thinking
particularly long term, said Gillian Barr, co-owner of Barr
Technologies Inc. ``We're getting sororities that want to bring
people back together in 25 or 30 years for reunions,'' Barr said.
``They want to be present when it's opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Some college students can't wait even that long. This year, a
group at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology sealed up a 1999
digital time capsule containing information drawn from the
Internet. It's set to be opened in the distant year of ... 2004.
That's the same year many of today's journalists will get around to
opening the Dunkin' Donuts boxes they on left on their desks this
week. But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end of the time continuum is a group of would-be
preservationists in New York led by French artist Jean-Marc
Philippe. They are raising money to create a time capsule to orbit
the Earth for 50,000 years. Participants are being asked to write a
message of up to 6,000 characters and submit it through a Web site
(http://www.keo.org). According to the plan, the messages will be
stored on special, glass-tempered CD-ROMs and sent into outer space
in a satellite that will fall back to Earth in 50,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that CD players haven't gone the way of
eight-track tapes by 52,000 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Y2K, visit these Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.bytewise.com/atlyear2000/
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.igc.org/millennium/
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.4themillennium.com
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.everything2000.com
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.keo.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
