<SLUG> BC-MAC-NEWS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stock analyst uses PC, touts Apple
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even some of those who don't use Macs are falling in
love with Apple Computer. Take Kevin Prigel, a confirmed PC user
and investment analyst at StreetAdvisor.com.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent analysis published on StreetAdvisor's Web site,
Prigel says he's learned to love Apple Computer because of its
soaring stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the Apple Computer story keeps getting better,''
wrote Prigel. ``After beating earnings estimates by a sound 7
percent when every other box maker has been missing estimates, this
company looks poised for a great run.''
</P>
<P>
   Prigel based his comment on seven analytical points.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Prigel said that, since the rollout of the iMac
last August, Apple Computer's sales have increased roughly 10
percent every quarter. That adds up to a whopping 46 percent jump
in sales on an annualized basis, Prigel calculated.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of computer companies increase sales only to see their
profit margins fall through price cutting. Not Apple Computer. Its
gross profits increased 121 percent in the first quarter from the
same period a year earlier, concluded Prigel.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a company that lost nearly $2 billion two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prigel contends that users no longer care what operating system
is running on their computers _ as long as they can run the
programs they want or need. With Microsoft's commitment to keep
making current versions of its popular software for Macs, Apple's
computers are now on a level playing field with Windows machines,
says Prigel.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Microsoft's Office 98 for the Mac includes features not
yet included in the Windows version of the leading business package
of software titles.
</P>
<P>
   Another Apple Computer strength, says Prigel, is the ease with
which its computers connect to the Internet. He says that no
computers connect faster. ``With an iMac, an inexperienced user can
plug in a power cord and phone line and be online in minutes,''
writes Prigel.
</P>
<P>
   In conclusion, Prigel says, ``Since (Steve Jobs) took over with
Apple Computer floundering, the company has done nothing but
innovate. Believe in Steve Jobs as you would believe in Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Prigel makes several other points, which you can read for
yourself. His article is fairly easy to follow, even for someone
who is neither a businessman nor an investor.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the article on the Net at
www.streetadvisor.com/spot/042299/01.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Prigel, by the way, uses a Dell computer and says has no
intention of changing. At least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
