<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mission impossible: Summer visitor just can't stay away
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``Fish gotta' swim...birds gotta' fly....''
and beavers have to build dams. Makes little difference to them if
the raw material they're harvesting happens to be the famous cherry
trees in Washington's Tidal Basin. To a beaver, they all look
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Bucky and his buddies could care less whose yard
they're in. They're just busy doing what comes naturally. Beavers
in the Basin? A red-tailed hawk munching on White House lawn duck?
Even though this is a
</P>
<P>
   different kind of ``wildlife'' from what we have come to
associate with our nation's capital, it is a bit worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   What if this sudden onslaught of nature is the basis for a
cleverly concocted subversive plot? The president can't handle any
more distractions. He has enough on his plate without having to
worry about Godzilla swooping down and hauling Socks away. Come to
think of it, why isn't Buddy outside barking at something?
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I'd offer to help, but right now I have problems of my
own. The raccoon is back.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up a couple of nights ago outside my office windows _
the ones overlooking the front porch roof. The hour was late and
the town had pretty much shut down. I was deep in concentration at
my desk when I heard a resounding WHUMP! on the attic roof above my
head. In a flash, my alert mind and superior reasoning powers
enabled me to pinpoint the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Aliens had landed.
</P>
<P>
   Two more thumps, and a bit of scurrying later, the creature was
gawking at me, daubing noseprints all over the office windows. It
was the same kohl-eyed, furry-suited fellow who'd bugged me all the
previous summer. I recognized his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the moonlight marauder doesn't show up this early in
the year. Usually, he waits until the nights have warmed up and the
cats and I have settled into our summer sleeping quarters on an
upstairs back porch. That's when he begins hanging out in the
eaves, driving the cats nuts and involving me in odd conversations
in the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You back again?'' is my standard opener. He loves it when I
talk to him. He fidgets and cocks his head to one side like he's
really listening to me as I explain that he ought to be out with
his friends doing raccoon stuff like
</P>
<P>
   climbing trees and getting stuck in chimneys.
</P>
<P>
   As long as I keep talking, he'll dangle there a few feet from
the hammock, occasionally shifting his fuzzy self for a more secure
hold on the gutter. If I stop the chatter and try to roll over and
ignore him, he quickly shifts into
</P>
<P>
   his version of an arboreal jitterbug, bouncing to an unheard
beat and taking swipes at the screen from time to time just to
remind us he's out there.
</P>
<P>
   Late last summer, just after I'd caught him up to his elbows
coming through my bedroom screen, the raccoon and I had a serious
talk. As I eased the glass casement closed, careful not to pinch
any toes, I tried to explain that it was nothing personal, but the
time had come for him to accept that we were not going to invite
him in for the winter. I was hoping he'd check out some new digs,
but I underestimated his attachment to the family. It looks like
we're in for a long summer.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday morning dawned fair and unusually warm for the time
of year, so in a fit of spring euphoria, I threw open the office
windows and took a deep breath. Then I gagged. THEN, I noticed the
flies. Jillions of them. My striped friend had left his calling
card _ three piles of it.
</P>
<P>
   So that's how I happened to be on the porch roof with a broom
this morning. Some folks, no doubt on their way home from church
and filled with a kindly spirit, waved politely. Then George rode
by on his bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey! Whatcha' doin' up there?''
</P>
<P>
   I waggled the broom at him and answered, ``Practicing takeoffs
and landings.'' He pedaled on.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, folks, I hated lying on a Sunday morning but there was
just no nice way to explain my mission.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH, 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
