<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Site gets credit for its advice
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's May, and that New Year's resolution to eliminate
your credit debt is sucking wind.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's help online: www.creditpage.com is a Web site
devoted to managing and mitigating your credit debt, brought to
you, in part, by credit card companies and banks.
</P>
<P>
   CreditPage starts with an online test to help gauge the depth of
your credit card addiction. From there, you check your credit
report, find a local credit counselor, read up on your rights as a
borrower and view answers to frequently asked questions.
</P>
<P>
   The site was launched last month, in time for National Credit
Education Week, which was April 18-24.
</P>
<P>
   The site is sponsored by the National Foundation for Consumer
Credit, Debt Counselors of America, the National Council on
Economic Education, the JumpStart Coalition for Personal Finance
Literacy, Genus Credit Management, Money Management International,
Personal Debt Solutions, the Forms Group, Bank of America,
MasterCard International and Visa.
</P>
<P>
   Bill-paying blues
</P>
<P>
   It might be the wave of the future. But for now, the people who
pay their bills with their PCs are a byte on a floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   A bill-payment study from Synergistics Research shows that 79
percent of the people polled pay their bills the old-fashioned way:
They mail them. Thirty percent of the people asked also pay bills
in person, at the biller's office. An almost equal amount _ 29
percent _ arrange for an automatic deduction from their bank
account. Six percent pay at an ATM, 5 percent transfer funds by
telephone and 2 percent use their PC.
</P>
<P>
   The study concludes that billers need to start marketing the PC
option a bit more aggressively, because paying bills by PC has
little appeal if you can't get your bills by PC.
</P>
<P>
   Synergistics Research, based in Atlanta, surveyed 1,100 people
in March.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the study found 40 percent of consumers asked had
some sort of problem with their regular bill-paying method: usually
delays in mail delivery, the time and effort used, and the cost of
postage.
</P>
<P>
   The study found 40 percent of consumers had PCs in their homes.
Of those, 70 percent are on the Web an average of 10 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   For sale by owner
</P>
<P>
   You've decided to bypass real estate agents and their hefty
commissions and sell your own home. But there are still a few
questions left. Like, how much should you sell it for? And what are
some quick and simple things you can do to create a good first
impression?
</P>
<P>
   Check out www.audrie.com, a site designed to guide a
do-it-yourself home seller through the process without a real
estate agent. The site covers everything from touch-up painting to
what to expect from an inspection to creating a ``for sale'' flier
with the help of an online composer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
