<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shoot-'em-up games teach about killing
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The events at Columbine High School appear to have
sent the nation into the deepest sort of soul-searching. Why did it
happen, and how can it be prevented?
</P>
<P>
   If the answers were easy, the problem would have been dealt with
long ago. And that's part of the answer _ the problem didn't exist
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a boy, you could mail-order guns. I had several. I
was also pretty miserable, but it never occurred to me that it
might be cathartic to wipe out my classmates. If it occurred to any
other kid in the 1950s, he didn't act on it.
</P>
<P>
   What's the difference, and what's that got to do with computers?
</P>
<P>
   I think those looking for answers would do well to read a book
called ``On Killing,'' by Lt. Col. Dave Grossman. Grossman is a
psychologist and military historian, and this rather dry and
scholarly book studies the act of killing and its effects on
soldiers at war.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman recounts how, in the waning days of World War II,
studies were conducted which showed that roughly 80 percent of
infantrymen in battle either never fired their weapons at all, or
fired them over the enemy's head. They could not bring themselves
to kill another human being.
</P>
<P>
   This, obviously, is an unsatisfactory state of affairs in the
military, so the Army's psychologists set about trying to find ways
to teach soldiers to overcome their distaste for killing. A few
years later, when hostilities broke out in Korea, the rate of
willing killers had gone up to about 50 percent. In Vietnam, it was
around 90 percent. This was accomplished, Grossman says, by making
a game out of killing.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II, soldiers were taught to shoot by firing at
paper bull's-eyes. Thirty years later, they were shooting at
humanoid silhouettes that popped up, moved around, and fell over
gratifyingly when hit. Soldiers found it a very small step from
this training to the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman concludes his book with a chapter pointing out how well
the entertainment industry is applying these concepts. Nowadays a
single movie will waste more extras in the first 15 minutes than an
entire film studio wiped out in a year when I was a boy; the
killing is even choreographed in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   Computer and video games are even worse. ``Doom'' inaugurated
the flood of first-person shooters. Everybody loved it. I loved it.
It seemed OK to me; our opponents were, after all, nasty-looking
aliens and monsters. It wasn't long, however, before the rush of
rip-off games presented perfectly human targets. Bad people,
presumably, but bad is often in the eye of the beholder. Games
proudly claim to have more blood and gore than their competition;
body parts are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A policewoman told me just last week that she went out to buy
some Nintendo games for her son and was unable to find a single one
that didn't glorify violence. I can't speak for video games, but
there are plenty of fine computer games available with either no
violence at all, or violence reduced to abstract historical
battles.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest that we need to pay close attention to our
children's computer entertainment. I think it's part of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
