<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Include your car in spring cleaning
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wax on; wax off. No, I'm not auditioning for the next
``Karate Kid'' movie. Recent mild temperatures provided the perfect
opportunity to indulge in one of those traditional rites of spring
_ spring cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   The task I performed was not exactly what you'd classify as the
Martha Stewart treatment. Cobwebs will continue collecting dust and
the silver will have to stay tarnished for another weekend or so,
but my little Saturn looks and runs as well as she did four years
ago when I drove her out of the dealership.
</P>
<P>
   She got lots of neat presents for her birthday: new oil and
filter and special transaxle oil (I decided to treat her to Amsoil,
a synthetic lubricant). Her tires were rotated; the brakes, fluids,
belts, hoses, wiper blades and bulbs were inspected; door, hood and
trunk hinges were lubed. I added a can of fuel system treatment to
her gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   Once her mechanical needs were attended to, the real work began:
wax on, wax off.
</P>
<P>
   I attribute my Saturn's healthy good looks to this spring and
fall ritual. Although pine sap, bird mess and acid rain do their
best to destroy her glossy finish, we foil their attempts with our
special beauty treatment. I apply two coats of good paste wax to
the horizontal surfaces (hood, top and trunk) and a liquid wax on
the side fenders and doors. The bumpers and rubber trim receive a
liberal dose of vinyl protectant, and the windows are treated with
Rain-X.
</P>
<P>
   I've found the best applicators and polishing cloths to be
squares torn from old cotton flannel nightgowns and sheets. This
inexpensive source of soft rags allows me to change them frequently
so I don't risk scratching the paint with little flecks of dirt. I
don't know if there is any real scientific advantage to using two
coats of wax, but I figure it works on the same principle as
fingernail polish. Two coats wear longer.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of the car got its own personal spa treatment. The
windows and mirrors were washed. The upholstery, door panels and
carpets were vacuumed and spot-cleaned. I use a hose, laundry
detergent and a scrub brush on the mats and let them dry in the
sun. This scrubbing really attacks the accumulation of ground-in
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite cleaning tool for the A/C vents and those other
hard-to-reach nooks and crannies is a 2- or 3-inch paintbrush. The
long, soft bristles can get into crevices.
</P>
<P>
   A thorough wipe-down of the dash and the rest of the plastic
trim with a damp cloth, followed by an application of vinyl
protectant, completed the job.
</P>
<P>
   While I was sitting in the car, I checked to make sure my
current registration and insurance card were in the glove
compartment. We were stopped in a police road check a couple of
weekends ago in a car without these documents. What a mess, and a
ticket to boot!
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted after a day of rubbing and scrubbing, I gathered up my
cleaning supplies and paused to take a last look at my handiwork.
My little car looked beautiful. And you know what? I swear I could
see her smiling. I glanced over at our truck. He looked sort of
forlorn and forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the cobwebs will have to wait another week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
