<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School violence: A pledge not to tease
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   High school students in Nashville created a pledge to help stop
violence in schools. But instead of promising not to use guns,
they're asking kids not to tease others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it'd be good just to encourage people to be nice
and not make others feel like outcasts, because (the killers in
Colorado) apparently felt like everybody was against them,''
Hillsboro High junior Rebecca Hunter says.
</P>
<P>
   Kids from around the country have signed. The pledge says:
</P>
<P>
   ``As a part of the community I WILL ...
</P>
<P>
   I will pledge to be a part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   I will eliminate taunting from my own behavior.
</P>
<P>
   I will encourage others to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   I will do my part to make a safe place by being more sensitive
to others.
</P>
<P>
   I will set the example of a caring individual.
</P>
<P>
   I will eliminate profanity toward others from my language.
</P>
<P>
   I will not let my words or actions hurt others.
</P>
<P>
   ... and if others won't become part of the solution,
</P>
<P>
   I WILL.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO attacks increase
</P>
<P>
   The United States, along with its allies in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, increased attacks last week on Yugoslavia's
capital city, Belgrade. NATO jets blasted the Yugoslavian army
headquarters, government offices and neighborhoods close by.
</P>
<P>
   These were the strongest attacks on the capital since the NATO
bombings began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   NATO wants the president of Yugoslavia to make peace with
Kosovo, a region of his East European country. The Kosovar people
want to be independent, but Yugoslavia doesn't want them to secede.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, an American civil rights leader, and a
Russian leader are negotiating peace between NATO and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Smog season bad for kids
</P>
<P>
   Besides being baseball and pollen season, it's also officially
smog season in Georgia. Scientists at the Georgia Environmental
Protection Division have declared that May 1 through Sept. 30 is
when the pollution in our air can be worst for our health.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution, emitted by cars, factories and other sources, cooks
in sunlight, turning into smog. Because sunny days are often calm,
the smog sits above the city, making it difficult for people to
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Kids are often affected the most because they play outdoors. For
children with asthma, smog can be especially bad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
