r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-CHECKITOUT04-COX     05-03 0277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-CHECKITOUT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't forget Mother's Day
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mother's Day is Sunday. Do you have a plan? You don't
have to buy expensive things to make your Mom feel special. You can
draw her a picture, write her a poem or sing her a song. You can
clean your room, help make dinner or wash the dog. And there's
always Mom's favorite gift: Saying you love her and you appreciate
all that she does! For a special Mom award, check
www.billybear4kids.com/holidays/mother/mom.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Shorter showers help the Earth
</P>
<P>
   For years you've told your parents you really can get clean in
less than three minutes. Now, you've got proof. The U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency recommends taking a shower that is
five minutes or less to help preserve our water supply. This week
is National Drinking Water Week and there's more you can do to
protect this natural resource. Turn off water while you're brushing
your teeth, turn water on and off while washing your dog or your
parent's car and water your plants at night.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry for knowledge
</P>
<P>
   Ever eat your homework? Now you can with the edible science
experiments at www.madsci.org/experiments. There are dozens of
experiments broken down into Earth Sciences, Mathematics, Chemistry
and more. You can taste such things as Cheese Fractures, The Cat's
Meow and Food Batteries. Many of the experiments require common
household items. Click on a file to find age requirements and
safety measures. Some of the experiments are inedible (which means
don't eat them!).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
