<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovo children, families flee homes to find safety
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Camping out in tents with no school for weeks may
sound like a dream come true. But for more than 300,000 Kosovo
kids, it's a nightmare that just won't end.
</P>
<P>
   These kids and their families are refugees _ people who have
left their homes for safety. They began fleeing Kosovo, a region of
Yugoslavia, a month ago. The Yugoslavian army and Serbian police
entered their towns and forced them out.
</P>
<P>
   With no time to pack, they ran for safety to neighboring
countries like Macedonia, Albania and Montenegro. They traveled any
way they could _ in cars, on tractors, by foot _ and battled
freezing weather and treacherous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, many kids got separated from their families and
some were orphaned. Those who escaped are living in refugee camps
waiting to return to what's left of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The really lucky ones have clean water nearby, but all of them
are stranded in foreign countries at the mercy of relief workers
and local residents.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone wonders what's going to happen next, many of the
children still are struggling with what happened. They don't know
why they had to leave home, why their families were beaten or
killed or why they now have to live in tents with few supplies.
</P>
<P>
   These refugees are the latest casualties of disputes that have
been raging in this part of Europe, known as the Balkan Peninsula,
for 600 years. The mostly Muslim ethnic Albanians make up 90
percent of Kosovo's population. They want their independence from
Yugoslavia. Orthodox Christian Serbs make up the other 10 percent.
However, Serbs are the majority in the rest of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The groups practice two very different religions, speak two very
different languages and celebrate different cultures. But they both
believe that Kosovo belongs to them. The bombings, the other
violence and the losses can have a long-lasting impact on children.
Relief organizations like UNICEF are doing their best to make life
in the refugee camps as comfortable as possible for the kids. Some
camps have set up schools, while others have pitched tents where
kids can come to draw, talk, get counseling or medical help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about fancy stuff, just getting them to hold
hands and sing, to play games, little running exercises,'' Carol
Bellamy, executive director of UNICEF, told reporters after she
returned from the region a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   News services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
