 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2539 - May 3, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2539 -- May 3, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. TOURISM IN SPACE : NOT SUCH A FAR-OUT IDEA Honeymoons on the
moon may still be some time off, but vacation trips to an orbiting
hotel are much nearer to reality. Participants in a recent
conference on space tourism learned that plans are well advanced
for such a sky-high hotel, where a week's stay (transportation and
meals included) could cost $250,000. Work is already under way on
an international space station, a step toward space tourism, and
both governmental engineers and private firms are developing
reusable launchers that could bring the cost of a space trip down
to the (almost) affordable -- about the cost of a luxury car.
Ladies and gentlemen, fasten your seatbelts! From Der Spiegel.
1,000 words. (English translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
``BE MORE CAREFUL WITH THE BALKANS'' Yevgeny Yevtushenko, a poet,
professor of literature at Queens College and a former member of
the Soviet Parliament, writes about the solidarity between many
Russians and the people of Serbia. New York Times Op-Ed. 1,000
words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
WHAT'S DOING IN WEIMAR Anyone who imagines the former East Germany
as grim, grey and dominated by Stalinist architecture is in for a
surprise in Weimer. Even during the four decades of Communism, this
small city in Thuringia was protected as a cultural jewel. Ideas on
events, sightseeing, hotels and restaurants. By Edmund L. Andrews.
From The New York Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos. 4.
EX-PRIEST TAKES THE BLASPHEMY OUT OF EVOLUTION A conversation with
Dr. Francisco J. Ayala, who is known in the science world as the
Renaissance man of evolutionary biology. He discusses ways of
teaching evolution to students who are resistant to the concept. A
former Dominican priest, Ayala is also an authority on genetics and
a professor at the University of California at Irvine. By Claudia
Dreifus. From The New York Times Science Times. 1,600 words +
photo. Q&AMP;A format. 5. FRAILTY MYTH HAUNTS WOMEN IN SPORTS If not
for a history of medical myths and a lack of athletic opportunity,
it is at least possible, suggests Dr. Ellis Cashmore, a professor
at Staffordshire University in a medical journal article, that in
all sports that demand skill as opposed to pure brawn, women might
have been competing at levels comparable to their male
counterparts. The article has become a lightning rod for
controversy. By Mary Duffy. From The New York Times Science Times.
930 words.
