<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, May 3, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-PROFILING (San Francisco) _ Christopher Darden,
co-prosecutor in the O.J. Simpson murder trial, found himself
facing cops who stopped his car for no apparent reason. ``I just
have to believe that the first black guy to own a Model T got
stopped without probable cause,'' said Darden, referring to the
police practice of ``racial profiling'' _ disproportionate stopping
of male motorists who are black or Latino. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-CASH (San Francisco) _ Saying they want to keep poor
people from spending their welfare checks on drugs and alcohol,
some local merchants want to put a plan on the ballot to cut cash
benefits for San Francisco's general assistance recipients, giving
them only 15 percent of their benefits in cash _ while the
remaining 85 percent would go for services like housing, addiction
treatment and job training. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   SEA-OTTERS (San Francisco) _ The population of sea otters along
the California coast is dropping so quickly that scientists fear it
could be approaching extinction. The most recent count, late last
year, estimates that only 1,937 survive. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ In the largest class action
lawsuit to go to trial against an automaker in U.S. history, Ford
Motor Co. is accused of fraudulently covering up a potentially
dangerous stalling problem in 22 million cars and trucks. The class
action suit is set for trial May 11. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YEARS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco has launched a massive
planning effort to prepare for an estimated 1.5 million people
expected to celebrate in the city as the clock strikes 2000. The
city has begun special training, is plotting sites for MASH-like
medical centers and expects employees from cops to street sweepers
to work overtime on the New Year's Eve celebration. By RACHEL
GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD-PRESSURE (Albany, N.Y.) _ New research is showing that
diet can play a direct role in lowering blood pressure and risk for
hypertension, a major risk for heart disease and stroke.
Considering that one in four adult Americans, or 50 million people,
suffer from high blood pressure, those findings have the potential
to address one of the nation's most serious health problems. By
SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SYMANTEC-CEO (San Francisco) _ ``I will not be a poster boy.''
John W. Thompson, the new CEO of Cupertino-based Symantec Corp., a
software company, is trying to hammer home that he refuses to
become, in his words, ``the poster boy for African Americans in
Silicon Valley.'' By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (San Francisco) _ ``Star Wars'' fan Khari Crowder set
up camp over the weekend on the sidewalk near the city's UA Coronet
Theater. Next to him was a big banner that declared: ``I'M FIRST.''
He hopes to snag tickets to the long-awaited ``Star Wars: Episode I
_ The Phantom Menace'' that opens May 19. Advance tickets go on
sale May 12. By JASON LLOREN.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-NIGHT (Undated) _ ``Sports Night'' is a
behind-the-scenes look at the characters who run what is
essentially ESPN's ``SportsCenter.'' You are there, on the floor,
as the dialogue races between anchors, producers, editors, makeup
people and network suits. Everybody who walks onto that set is
interesting in some way. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-COUNTRY (Penngrove, Calif.) _ Gerald Haslam, a retired
Sonoma State University professor, has made a crusade of fighting
the white-trash image of ``Okie'' music. In his new book, ``Workin'
Man Blues,'' published by UC Press, Haslam argues that this state
had a strong country music tradition even before the Okie migration
of the 1930s and the influx of Hollywood cowboys in the '40s. By
EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LISTS (San Francisco) _ The Modern Library's list of the
100 best English-language works of non-fiction this century begs
for argument. But rather than hem and haw over the list, how about
just throwing together another list, a quick list of 50, easily
found in most libraries or yard sales or in the sale bin at used
book stores, and well worth a read? By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The '90s have been a pathetic
decade. Or so we gather from the U.S. Postal Service whose greatest
advance in the '90s was to give us candidates for stamps to
represent each decade of the century. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-SEEDS (San Francisco) _ Monsanto Corp. is trying to
bolster its bottom line by selling suicide seeds that don't grow
again after sprouting the first year. By KEN ALEXANDER.
</P>
