<HEADER>
A2135 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HDTV-COMING-SOON-LIFE     05-03 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-COMING-SOON-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH DEFINITION TV COMING INTO FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a HDTV in a store and a sidebar of the
history of TV 
 By JAY HANDELMAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when everyone gathered around the neighbor's new
television set to see what Little Joe looked like in ''living
color?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, some 40 years later, television is taking another
technological leap.
</P>
<P>
   High-definition television, with its sharp focus and
three-dimensional feel, debuted in last November when network
affiliates in the nation's 10 biggest cities were mandated by the
federal government to begin digital broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   At its digital-signal best, HDTV will provide the kind of
picture quality that can make you feel as if you're sitting on the
50-yard line of a football game or on the sidelines of a parade.
</P>
<P>
   But not many consumers are going to be taking advantage of these
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers with ordinary, analog sets will see no change in their
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   And, like all new electronic devices, the outsized HDTV sets are
expensive, costing anywhere from $4,000 to $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who take the plunge will have to wait a while for
HDTV programming to become widely available.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, satellite customers are the only ones who can
make regular use of the improved signals, along with those who
watch movies in a new digital format called DVD.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say that the HDTV revolution will be as dramatic as
the switch from black and white to color, and will sneak up on
America's television-addicted populace.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's coming sooner than you think,'' said Stephen L. Rogers,
president and chief executive officer of WEDU-Ch. 3, the public
television station in Tampa, Fla. ''We have until 2003 to be
broadcasting in high definition, and the commercial stations in
(most cities) have to do it by 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   The changeover is the first upgrade to the broadcast television
standard in more than 40 years. While it will eventually make
obsolete an estimated 240 million television sets, the new standard
also will increase the quality of communication and bring the
information superhighway into every home, even those without
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The new sets and digital signals will bring CD quality sound and
restore the at-home viewer's peripheral vision.
</P>
<P>
   Most stations are scheduled to turn off their analog signals in
2006. Consumers who haven't bought a new TV by then will need a
converter box to watch their old (or non-HDTV) sets.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two stations across the country were the first to begin
high definition broadcasts in October with the launch of the space
shuttle Discovery carrying John Glenn back into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between analog TV, which exists now, and digital
TV is in the nature of the signal used to beam the TV channel. An
analog transmitter turns light and sound into radio waves. A
digital transmitter turns light and sound into a series of 1s and
0s, the same kind of coding that computers use to process data.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said his station will have to raise about $10 million to
install all new equipment ''down to every last cable and plug'' to
handle the new format.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers don't have to go that far, but they will have to get
at least two pieces of new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   One is a conversion box that will adapt the signal coming into
the home (via satellite, over the air or, eventually, via cable)
and turn it into a much richer, sharper and more colorful picture,
along with a higher quality of sound. The box resembles a
videocassette recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the new television set, which at the moment runs
large but will eventually come in all sizes, said Tom Cannon, a
salesman at a Sarasota, Fla., Sound Advice store. Because of the
improved sound, many customers may also want to get more advanced
speakers or surround-sound setups.
</P>
<P>
   On a display at his store, Cannon can show customers clips of a
football game on a 50-inch Mitsubishi set so clear it seems as if
you're transported to the stadium. On a nearby wall is a 50-inch
letterbox-shaped plasma television set that is about 4 inches deep
and hangs on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ''These televisions are going to change the way people set up
their homes,'' said Cannon, who also has an 80-inch high definition
television on display.
</P>
<P>
   The price of HDTVs is expected to decline markedly over the next
decade, much as the cost of calculators, PCs, video cassette
recorders and camcorders did after several years on the retail
market.
</P>
<P>
   Color televisions, introduced in the 1960s, first sold for the
equivalent of $2,100 in today's dollars. Now, an average color TV
runs about $500.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers with high definition sets and converter boxes will be
able to pick up the signals from local broadcast stations directly
over the air with an antenna.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll either get a sharp, clear and crisp signal or you won't
get anything. There won't be any snow or fuzzy pictures in HDTV,''
Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   But most television viewers now watch through cable, and the
National Cable Television Association estimates that companies will
spend $33 billion over the next few years to upgrade their systems
to handle the greater band width required by HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   Cable systems haven't rushed to upgrade because there aren't
clear standards out there about what converter boxes for HDTV will
be like.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will HDTV offer consumers high quality pictures and
sounds, but it also offers the potential for even more channel
choices because the signals use a greater band width.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a television station may choose to use all its band
width for one channel, or it could divide the signal, with lesser
quality, to provide programming options.
</P>
<P>
   WEDU, Rogers said, may offer children's programs on part of its
signal and public affairs on another, or contributors to the
station may be able to watch a channel without pledge-break
interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of options open to us,'' Rogers said. ''And
for the consumer, the possibilities are really amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 0 _
</P>
<P>
   (JAY HANDELMAN is television writer for the Herald-Tribune in
Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
