w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACHEL-WEISZ-IN-THE-M     05-03 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACHEL-WEISZ-IN-THE-MUMMY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUMMY'S' GIRL: RACHEL WEISZ HEADS FOR ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Rachel Weisz with Brendan Fraser in a
scene from ``The Mummy.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Making movies can be a real pain in the ...
 &HT;    Well, let Rachel Weisz tell it.
 &HT;    ``I've still got a scar there,'' the actress says with a laugh.
``You can get incredibly sore bouncing up and down on a camel.''
 &HT;    Camel-bouncing was only one of many new experiences endured by
Weisz _ an art-house regular whose films include ``Stealing
Beauty'' (1996) and ``The Land Girls'' (1998) _ in making
writer/director Stephen Sommers' ``The Mummy.'' For the film, which
will open May 7, Weisz _ it's pronounced ``vice'' _ also found
herself acting opposite dubbed-in-later special effects, performing
hair-raising stunts and, oh yes, having rats crawling on her chest.
 &HT;    Yet, despite the popcorn-movie trappings, the 28-year-old
British actress swears by her character _ Evelyn, a prim and
proper, albeit clumsy librarian who joins legionnaire Rick
O'Connell (Brendan Fraser) on a quest across Egypt that involves
treasure seekers, archaeologists, locusts, man-eating scarabs,
ancient curses and a certain slow-walking creature (Arnold Vosloo)
inadvertently awakened from a 3,000-year-long slumber.
 &HT;    ``The women in these action/adventures are so often marginal,
and that wasn't the case here,'' she says. ``Stephen Sommers
created a wonderful character.
 &HT;    ``Evelyn is smart, funny and sexy, and she gets to be a real
part of this adventure,'' Weisz adds. ``It was for that reason
that, going in, I thought `The Mummy' could be a good experience.
I've gotten a lot of ridiculous scripts where there was no thought
whatsoever given to creating an original, unusual, real-life woman.
 &HT;    ``For `The Mummy' to work, for any comic-book-genre movie to
work in 1999, you can't just have a pathetic damsel in distress
floating about. It would be silly.''
 &HT;    ``The Mummy'' was filmed in England and on location in the
Sahara, where temperatures soared to 130 degrees. Some days she
fled invisible sand storms, bugs or mummies to be added later,
while others were spent kissing Fraser or lying manacled to a stone
table.
 &HT;    ``Somehow I didn't feel like a cog in a machine,'' Weisz says
during a conversation at the Intercontinental Hotel in London.
``There were a lot of effects in the film, for sure, but several of
us shared those scenes ... When you're doing so much with other
people, with the camera right there, you can't really feel like a
cog.''
 &HT;    Weisz particularly enjoyed conveying Evelyn's burgeoning
sexuality.
 &HT;    ``It's in the vein of Lois Lane,'' says the actress, equal parts
fetching and demure in a bright-pink T-shirt, cream cardigan and
gray-lace skirt. ``She takes off her glasses and she's suddenly
sexy.
 &HT;    ``That's archetypical comic-book stuff, to go from hair in a
bun, spectacles and a buttoned-up shirt to a more sexy woman in a
nightdress running around the desert. It was really fun.''
 &HT;    Evelyn's metamorphosis won't surprise Weisz fans. The actress
turned up the heat as a bitchy anti-virgin in ``Stealing Beauty,''
starred in the barely released ``I Want You'' (1998) as a woman in
a ``sick, obsessional relationship'' and is currently heading the
cast of a steamy West End revival of Tennessee Williams' ``Suddenly
Last Summer.''
 &HT;    ``I'm only too comfortable with sexuality,'' Weisz says
unashamedly. ``I was brought up on black-and-white movies. I grew
up with Elizabeth Taylor, Bette Davis and Katharine Hepburn, who
were witty, sexy and glamorous, often at the same time.
 &HT;    ``Women do themselves harm when they think they can't be sexy
and be taken seriously,'' the actress says. ``Obviously, some of
the concerns about people's reactions cross my mind. I think, `God,
must I clamp my breasts down to be taken seriously in this part?'
 &HT;    ``I think everybody uses their sexuality, to some extent, to get
what they want in life,'' she adds. ``Personally, I don't go to the
lengths of some of my characters _ I've played several unhealthy,
not wholesome women.''
 &HT;    Weisz leans forward.
 &HT;    ``But they are fascinating characters to explore,'' she says.
``I do not want to play those roles all the time. They can be
upsetting to have in your head.''
 &HT;    Just because her best previous work has been in independent
films, Weisz says, is no reason to assume that she won't turn up in
Hollywood epics.
 &HT;    ``The only things I want from any film are a character, script,
director and actors that interest me,'' she says. ``That may be a
lot to ask, big or small budget!''
 &HT;    She laughs.
 &HT;    ``Really, the only difference between a big-budget film and a
small one is the craft services and your trailer's size _ which are
not that fulfilling _ and the amount of time you have to shoot,
which can be important.
 &HT;    ``What I've done so far is just a reflection of what I like.''
 &HT;    Weisz has ventured onto action-movie turf once before. ``Chain
Reaction'' (1996), co-starring Keanu Reeves and directed by Andrew
Davis, director of the smash hit ``The Fugitive'' (1993), was a
prototypical blockbuster wannabe. But it received a critical
thrashing and bombed at the box office.
 &HT;    The actress starts to try to be diplomatic, fumbles for words
and then shrugs. ``The hell with it,'' the gesture seems to say.
 &HT;    ``I had no idea what was going on,'' she says candidly. ``It was
my second film. I was running around with Keanu in the snow.
 &HT;    ``It was an interesting script,'' she adds, ``and the concept of
trying to find a new energy source was of interest to me.
Unfortunately, they cut the movie's first 20 minutes, where they
set up my character and Keanu's character _ apparently the studio
decided the explosions had to happen sooner.
 &HT;    ``So you didn't give a f--k about these characters,'' she says
bluntly. ``You didn't know who they were, and it was senseless.''
 &HT;    If they had made the movie they set out to make, she suggests,
it might have fared better.
 &HT;    ``When we were making it, Andrew Davis said he wanted the movie
to be about real people and a real event,'' she says. ``He wanted
the characters to be in danger, and didn't want Keanu or me to be
superhuman. It worked on `The Fugitive,' but it somehow didn't work
on `Chain Reaction.'''
 &HT;    Weisz, who is committed to ``Suddenly Last Summer'' through
July, will next be seen on screen opposite Ralph Fiennes in a
drama, ``A Taste of Sunshine.'' Another art-house film,
``Sunshine'' follows three generations of a Hungarian Jewish family
from the 1860s to the 1950s.
 &HT;    It's very much in the vein of Weisz's pre-``Mummy'' movies,
ample proof _ if any were needed _ that the London resident has no
plans to go Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``I can fly into Hollywood to meet directors,'' she says. ``I'm
very happy for Hollywood to take the films I'm in, but I don't have
to live there.
 &HT;    ``I've never even made a film in Hollywood.''
 &HT;    Her greatest interest, the self-confident Weisz makes clear, is
to ensure the longevity of her career. This entails making good
movies, even at the cost of the chance to do successful movies, she
believes.
 &HT;    ``I hope to be acting when I'm 70,'' she says. ``I don't know if
living in L.A. and going to the openings of envelopes wearing
low-cut dresses are what take you through for the long run.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I'm just too practical and I'll be proven totally
wrong.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
