<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-WARS-CELEBRATION     05-03 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-CELEBRATION-QUIZ-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR-QUIZ: THE QUESTIONS ARE OUT THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jake Lloyd in a scene from ``Star Wars:
The Phantom Menace.'' 
 By S. BURELISON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It didn't start with ``Star Wars.''
 &HT;    In fact, the science-fiction craze of the last 20 years actually
began by looking backward, when novice director George Lucas, still
working on his first film, turned to composer Lalo Schifrin and
said, ``I want to do Flash Gordon.''
 &HT;    Ultimately he couldn't get the rights to the famous 1930s
science-fiction serial, but he caught a lot of its spirit in three
subsequent films. You may have heard of them _ ``Star Wars''
(1977), ``The Empire Strikes Back'' (1980) and ``Return of the
Jedi'' (1983).
 &HT;    Now, as the long-awaited fourth ``Star Wars'' movie, ``The
Phantom Menace'' _ it's a prequel, so they're calling it ``Episode
1'' _ swoops toward theaters, there's never been a better time to
check your knowledge of classic film science fiction.
 MOONSTRUCK  
 &HT;    The first movie spaceship took off in French filmmaker George
Melies' 1902 film ``Le Voyage dans la Lune (Voyage to the Moon).''
Space travel was faster then _ its astronauts take only 14 minutes
to cover the round trip.
 &HT;    In 1904, Melies directed the first two-reel movie, ``Voyage a
Travers l'impossible (Impossible Voyage).'' The title was
well-chosen _ a group of people travel to the sun by train, with no
need for special training, equipment or clothing.
 &HT;    Since then, of course, space travel has become a staple of film
science fiction. Test your star-trekking knowhow with these
relatively simple questions:
 &HT;    1. What catchy turn-of-the-century American song is HAL-9000,
the deranged computer of ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968), singing
as ``he'' dies?
 &HT;    2. In the popular ``Flash Gordon'' serials, who was Flash's
adjective-enhanced nemesis?
 &HT;    3. ``In space, no one can hear you scream'' was the
scientifically accurate but dramatically irrelevant tag line used
to promote what 1979 space-going thriller?
 &HT;    4. In ``Dune'' (1984), characters travel to the sandy planet of
Arrakis to recover what precious commodity?
 GUESS WHO'S COMING TO DINNER?  
 &HT;    In 1947, an American pilot named Kenneth Arnold spotted nine of
what he called flying discs over the state of Washington. An
enterprising journalist referred to them as flying saucers, and
soon bug-eyed monsters were under every bed.
 &HT;    The classic film in the genre is, of course, ``Invasion of the
Body Snatchers'' (1956), in which aliens grown in giant pods
replace the residents of a California town _ picture-perfect but
devoid of personalities. Widely recognized as a metaphor for the
Red-hunting, ultra-conformist 1950s, the film has been remade
several times in various guises, but never so well.
 &HT;    Until the next wookkie rings your doorbell, test your knowledge
of visitors from outer space with these brain-teasers:
 &HT;    5. What finally defeats the aliens in the classic ``War of the
Worlds'' (1953)?
 &HT;    6. How does the awesome Klaatu (Michael Rennie) demonstrate his
power to world leaders in ``The Day the Earth Stood Still'' (1951)?
 &HT;    7. Where is ``The Blob'' (1958) finally cornered and captured?
 &HT;    8. How does young Elliott (Henry Thomas) lure a reluctant alien
out of hiding in ``E.T. _ The Extra-Terrestrial'' (1982)?
 HOW I LEARNED TO STOP WORRYING AND LOVE THE BOMB  
 &HT;    The dropping of atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki set the
whole world quivering _ most parts of it in fear, but Hollywood in
excitement at the glimpse of a new plot staple.
 &HT;    Radiation gone wild was the theme of choice for the 1950s, and
not only in America. In fact, the classic of the genre may be a
product of Japan _ the definitive giant-dinosaur movie,
``Godzilla'' (1954).
 &HT;    But nature has been striking back ever since. Try your hand at
these bigger-than-life questions _ and don't worry, none of them
concern the genre's nadir, the rampaging-bunnies epic ``Night of
the Lepus'' (1972):
 &HT;    9. What are _ or is it ``is?'' _ ``Them!'' (1954)?
 &HT;    10. What title monster was played by two men sharing a latex
suit _ Ricou Browning under water and Ben Chapman on land?
 &HT;    11. In ``The Day of the Triffids'' (1963), what are triffids and
what's especially dangerous about them?
 &HT;    12. What made ``The Incredible Shrinking Man'' (1957) shrink?
 THE SOURCE OF THE FORCE ... OF COURSE  
 &HT;    From the very beginning, a science-fiction film has been only as
good as its special effects. Sci-fi audiences want to see things
they've never seen before, and from cardboard rockets on strings to
computer-synthesized, digitally enhanced space creatures, Hollywood
has been only too eager to oblige.
 &HT;    George Lucas' ``Star Wars'' changed the rules, however, and his
company Industrial Light and Magic has seen to it that they stayed
changed, providing breathtaking effects for scores of movies in the
intervening decades.
 &HT;    How well do you know the ``Star Wars'' universe? Try these
questions on for size:
 &HT;    13. What's so unusual about the sky on Luke Skywalker's home
planet of Tatooine?
 &HT;    14. Where did Han Solo (Harrison Ford) get his spaceship, the
star-spanning Millennium Falcon?
 &HT;    15. Besides the three ``Star Wars'' feature films, there was one
television movie based on the series. What was it?
 &HT;    16. Who played Darth Vader in all three ``Star Wars'' movies?
 &HT;    17. Where did Luke Skywalker (Mark Hamill) first meet Han Solo?
 &HT;    18. What does Yoda tell Luke he must do in order to become a
true Jedi knight?
 &HT;    19. Only one actor in the original ``Star Wars'' films won an
Oscar, before or since. Who?
 &HT;    20. Where on earth would you go to find a place that looked like
Tatooine? 
 -0- 
 THE STAR-TLING ANSWERS  
 &HT;    1. HAL renders ``Daisy,'' with its all-too-true chorus, ``I'm
half crazy ... ''
 &HT;    2. Flash Gordon dueled the interplanetary tyrant Ming the
Merciless.
 &HT;    3. ``Alien'' reminded us that sound doesn't travel through outer
space _ but took place mostly aboard a starship, where an
artificial atmosphere made possible ample screaming.
 &HT;    4. Arrakis is the source of a rare spice, melange.
 &HT;    5. The Martian invaders in this H.G. Wells adaptation are immune
to earthly guns, bombs and even atomic weapons _ but not to human
germs, which wipe them out.
 &HT;    6. Klaatu gets his audience's attention by causing a 30-minute
power failure _ worldwide.
 &HT;    7. The Blob is finally trapped in a diner. In the 1988 remake,
incidentally, it's a skating rink.
 &HT;    8. Elliott made friends with the lost E.T. by plying him with
Reese's Pieces candy.
 &HT;    9. ``Them'' are radiation-mutated giant ants.
 &HT;    10. It took the combined efforts of Browning and Chapman to
embody ``The Creature From the Black Lagoon'' (1954).
 &HT;    11. Triffids are carnivorous plants _ think immense venus
flytraps. Unlike flytraps, however, triffids can move from place to
place.
 &HT;    12. Most sci-fi radiation seems to make small things huge, but
Grant Williams' character encounters a cloud of radioactive mist
and finds himself incredibly shrinking.
 &HT;    13. Tatooine is located in a binary system, with two suns.
 &HT;    14. Solo won the Falcon in a bet with Lando Calrissian (Billy
Dee Williams), the raffish governor of Cloud City, as revealed in
``The Empire Strikes Back.''
 &HT;    15. ``The Ewok Adventure'' aired in 1984 on ABC, and focused on
the furry, tree-dwelling creatures who first appeared in ``Return
of the Jedi.''
 &HT;    16. It's a trick question: While James Earl Jones supplied the
voice, the man in the Sith Lord's costume was actor David Prowse.
Actor Sebastian Shaw was the face of Darth Vader, but appeared only
in ``Return of the Jedi.''
 &HT;    17. Luke first meets Solo in a cantina on Tatooine _ think a
waterfront bar frequented by some seriously weird sailors.
 &HT;    18. To become a Jedi knight, Luke must confront Darth Vader _
enough reason for the average student to drop out.
 &HT;    19. Alec ``Obi-Wan Kenobi'' Guinness won the Best Actor Oscar
for ``The Bridge on the River Kwai'' (1957).
 &HT;    20. ``Star Wars'' _ and the new ``Phantom Menace'' _ were filmed
in part in the north African nation of Tunisia.
 c.1999 S. Burelison  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (S. Burelison is a Greenfield, Ind.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
