<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROD-STEIGER-CARRIES-O     05-03 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROD-STEIGER-CARRIES-ON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEGEND IN WINTER: ROD STEIGER ON MOVIES, HOLLYWOOD AND
ELIZABETH TAYLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Rod Steiger in a scene from ``Crazy in
Alabama.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    One of Hollywood's longest-running feuds is over.
 &HT;    For 45 years Rod Steiger hated Marlon Brando's guts, and that's
the way he liked it.
 &HT;    It all stemmed from one of the most famous movie scenes of all
time, the ``I coulda been a contender'' scene in ``On the
Waterfront'' (1954).
 &HT;    ``You know that taxi scene in `On the Waterfront?''' Steiger
says. ``Well, Marlon wasn't there when I did my close-ups. And
because acting is reacting, I never got over it.''
 &HT;    But last year Steiger was in Montreal to receive a
lifetime-achievement award and received a ``wonderful telegram''
from ... Brando.
 &HT;    After his speech, Steiger was handed a note with an invitation
and directions to a small Chinese restaurant on the outskirts of
town.
 &HT;    ``And who is sitting there at a table but Mr. Brando,'' Steiger
recalls. ``I said to myself, `I guess you've got to go over there
and thank him for his damn telegram.'
 &HT;    ``So I walked up to the table and said, `Marlon!''' he says.
``We gave big hugs, and I rubbed his bald head against my bald
head.
 &HT;    ``And then I said, `I'm really sorry you sent me the telegram,
because now I can't say any more rotten things about you!'''
 &HT;    Steiger laughs. It's a sparkling spring day in Los Angeles, and
the actor is sitting on his back patio, overlooking the Pacific
Ocean.
 &HT;    If the man notorious as the most ornery guy in Hollywood seems
uncharacteristically mellow, it's no wonder. He's happy to be here
today, working and alive, after an eight-year bout with crippling
clinical depression that rendered him all but bedridden.
 &HT;    ``I was sick for eight years,'' he says, ``and I never thought I
would make it back ... I just didn't care anymore.''
 &HT;    Five years ago, and with the aid of new medication, he began to
feel better.
 &HT;    ``There wasn't a major turning point where you think, `I've got
this thing licked,''' he says. ``You come back as gradually as you
left. I just found that one day I was more interested in life.
 &HT;    ``One of the first things that dies in a clinical depression is
your curiosity,'' he adds. ``I'm talking about everything from
watching how an ant crawls across a piece of wood to greater and
more important things. I finally got my curiosity back.''
 &HT;    Which was all well and good, but a far cry from acting in major
motion pictures.
 &HT;    ``I wondered if I could still act,'' Steiger admits. ``It was
like starting all over again for me. I worried that I wouldn't be
able to remember a line.''
 &HT;    For the Oscar-winning actor, veteran of such film classics as
``On the Waterfront,'' ``Oklahoma'' (1956), ``The Pawnbroker''
(1965) and ``Dr. Zhivago'' (1965), the stakes were high. There was
nothing he could take for granted, including the response of a new
Hollywood generation which had mostly forgotten him or assumed him
dead.
 &HT;    ``The only thing that saved me is that I did pretty good work in
the past and my movies were on television,'' the actor says. ``The
younger people began to say, `Hey, he's pretty good. Who is
that?'''
 &HT;    The result is a revived career that in recent months has
included work on the upcoming Arnold Schwarzenegger action film
``End of Days,'' as well as roles in Antonio Banderas' directorial
debut ``Crazy in Alabama'' and in ``Lazarus and the Hurricane,''
Denzel Washington's biopic of controversial boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter.
 &HT;    He's also completed a straight-to-video sequel to his 1997 film
``Shiloh,'' and even signed to direct his first movie,
``Thanksgiving.''
 &HT;    Not bad for a 74-year-old.
 &HT;    ``I have two cars,'' he explains. ``My license plate on one car
says `Courage,' and the other car says `Keep Moving.' And that's
what you've got to do. You've got to get out of the bed. You've got
to force yourself at any age.''
 &HT;    ``End of Days'' casts Steiger as a priest _ ``the nice guy for
once,'' he says _ facing a visit by Satan to New York at the turn
of the millennium.
 &HT;    He didn't have to research the role of a priest, the actor adds,
or delve into Satanism.
 &HT;    ``I hate to bring it up,'' he says, ``but I did do a terrible
movie called `The Amityville Horror'' (1979), where I did the most
difficult scene in my entire life. I had to sit still while they
poured beer and sugar on me. And then they unleashed all these
flies. Because, you know, when the devil comes, I guess flies are
supposed to arrive, too.
 &HT;    ``I could only hold the scene for a minute,'' he adds. ``The
tickling drove me nuts.''
 &HT;    ``Thanksgiving'' is a different kind of ticklish project _ a
low-budget drama about three aging gay men who have differing
Thanksgiving dinners.
 &HT;    ``It's rather funny,'' Steiger says, ``but it's not campy. But
then it gets to be tragic.''
 &HT;    He'd hoped for a cast that would include himself, James Garner
and Sidney Poitier, his co-star in his Oscar-winning ``In the Heat
of the Night'' (1967).
 &HT;    ``But Jimmy is busy,'' he says, frowning. ``Sidney is an
ambassador to something, so forget it.''
 &HT;    In other words, casting gay roles isn't easy, which came as no
surprise to Steiger.
 &HT;    ``I remember when I did `The Sergeant' (1968) many years ago,
about a master sergeant in the army who falls in love with this new
young guy he has working in the office,'' he recalls. ``I heard,
`You better be careful, Rod. Oh my God! You won't work again.' And
I yelled back, `I know what goes on in my bedroom, my friend. I'm
not worried about it.'''
 &HT;    The ornery Steiger of old resurfaced earlier this year, when it
was announced that Elia Kazan, his director for ``On the
Waterfront'' and a former friendly witness before the House
Un-American Activities Committee, would receive an honorary Oscar.
 &HT;    ``I didn't think he should get anything,'' Steiger snorts. ``If
I killed somebody when I was 13, when I was 93 I still killed them.
He killed careers.
 &HT;    ``I knew people during that time who didn't survive,'' the actor
adds angrily. ``Kazan hurt people to the point where people's
children couldn't go to school or college. No way did he deserve an
award.
 &HT;    ``He sacrificed other people's happiness for his ambitions.''
 &HT;    It isn't Kazan's name that most often turns up linked with
Steiger's in the news, of course. That would be Elizabeth Taylor,
the actress he insists is just a ``good friend.''
 &HT;    ``They've tried to make us a romance for years,'' he says. ``As
I said to somebody, `If you can have a romance with a woman in a
brace from her breasts to her hips, tell me how you did it.'''
 &HT;    Well, but Taylor isn't wearing the brace anymore.
 &HT;    ``Liz is getting better and better,'' Steiger concedes, ``but
that still doesn't mean we're having a romance. I've had four
marriages, thank you very much. My romantic days are over. I am now
a clinical advisor on love.''
 &HT;    Or is he?
 &HT;    ``I'm not really giving up,'' he says, chuckling. ``I mean, how
can you write off love when you're as physically attractive as I
am?
 &HT;    ``I'm more attractive than Liz,'' he adds with a laugh. ``When
we go out for lunch, I get all the attention.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
