<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO GIRDS FOR 2000 CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco has launched a massive planning
effort to prepare for tens of thousands of people expected to
celebrate here as the clock strikes 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The city has begun special training, is plotting sites for
emergency medical centers and expects employees from the police to
street sweepers to work overtime for the New Year's Eve
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning for the worst, but hoping for the best,'' said
police Sgt. Daniel Linehan, who is helping to organize the
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Linehan and others dug into the archives to look at what
happened when San Francisco became the center of celebration on the
West Coast at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   With the benefit of that hindsight, city officials are
intensifying their New Year's Eve planning.
</P>
<P>
   A spontaneous three-day, street fete to mark the end of the war
in 1945 left 11 celebrants dead, thousands injured, streetcars
overturned and much of the downtown in shambles. Some 3,000
soldiers were called in to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are hoping for less chaos as revelers greet the
new year, and hope that planning will achieve their goal.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known how many people will show up. When the Golden
Gate Bridge turned 50 in 1987, organizers of the official birthday
party expected 50,000 people to walk across the span _ an estimate
that turned out to be a major miscalculation. At least 10 times
that many people showed up, giving the bridge the test of its life
and a noticeable, albeit temporary, sag in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the authorities estimate an extra 750,000 people will
be in town on Dec. 31, doubling the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a major event,'' said Lucien Canton, the
director of the Mayor's Office of Emergency Services.
</P>
<P>
   The city's 15,000-plus hotel rooms are being booked at a good
clip already, with eight months left until the holiday. Many hotels
are requiring a three-night minimum stay.
</P>
<P>
   Kandace Bender, a spokeswoman for Mayor Willie Brown, promised
that ``San Francisco will have a world-class celebration at the
turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   The city also is preparing for potential problems relating to
the year 2000 computer glitch that could affect older computers and
software that only read the last to digits in dates.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities say there is a chance the computer glitch could
disrupt traffic signals, automated fire truck ladders, elevators,
sprinklers, bank machines, data processing systems and air traffic
control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
