<HEADLINE>
`DASH' DIET MAY COMBAT HIGH BLOOD PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In 1989, David Kidd had a heart attack. His blood
pressure was higher than normal and so was his cholesterol level.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his recovery program, he heard about the benefits of
diet and exercise. ``I became an instant believer,'' said Kidd, a
retired school superintendent living in Niskayuna, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Today, after making some diet and exercise changes, his blood
pressure is an optimal 110 over 65 and his cholesterol is 157. ``I
just do it to stay alive and feel good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that a healthy diet is important for good health.
New research, however, is showing that diet can play a direct role
in lowering blood pressure and the risk for hypertension, a major
risk for heart disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that 50 million Americans suffer from high blood
pressure, those findings have the potential to address one of the
nation's most serious health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``High blood pressure is frequently referred to as the silent
killer,'' said Janis Swain, a researcher and registered dietitian
at Brigham &AMP; Women's Hospital in Boston and a co-investigator on
the study, known as DASH or ``Dietary Alternatives to Stop
Hypertension.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, researchers had tested various single nutrients,
such as calcium, magnesium and potassium, to find clues about what
affects blood pressure, which measures the force of blood against
artery walls.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded as two numbers, the top digit represents the force of
blood when the heart contracts. The bottom one represents the force
of blood in between heart beats.
</P>
<P>
   A normal blood pressure is considered less than 130 over 85.
</P>
<P>
   When blood pressure is too high, the heart is working harder
than it should. Although no one knows exactly what causes high
blood pressure, left untreated it can lead to heart and kidney
disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are medications to treat high blood pressure,
scientists supported by the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute in Maryland tested nutrients as they occur in food to see
if they could affect blood pressure. The results were dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Among those 459 adults with higher than normal blood pressure,
the DASH eating plan lowered blood pressure. For hypertensive
patients, the reduction was even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's your typical low-fat, no-added-salt diet,'' said Sheila
Musco, the cardiac rehabilitation coordinator at Ellis Hospital in
Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Yet DASH is also different in some specific ways, with a
high-fiber regimen that almost doubles the usual number of
recommended fruit and vegetable servings. It is also high in low or
no-fat dairy products rich in calcium, including skim milk and
yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an eating pattern,'' Swain said. ``It's not one
particular food. There's no magic bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many Americans are buying into gimmicky diets,
that's good news for dietitians who are trying to promote the idea
that good food is fundamental to good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is out there,'' said Joyce Bagyi, a clinical
dietitian at the Albany Medical Center in Albany, N.Y. ``What you
eat can change your medical course of disease.''
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution: if you are already being treated for high
blood pressure, don't stop taking your medication. Consult your
physician about what diet changes may be right for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, who is in his 70s, has come up with his own healthy eating
and exercise plan over the past decade with help from Ellis
Hospital and its specialists. ``What you don't eat is probably as
important as what you do eat,'' said Kidd, who stays away from
butter, red meat and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has no doubt the investment in eating right has paid off.
He has plenty of energy to volunteer, play golf, exercise and keep
up with the yard work. ``It was an easy decision to make,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (To learn the specifics of the DASH eating plan, contact your
dietitian, or visit the DASH Web site at
http://dash.bwh.harvard.edu. To learn more about the prevention and
treatment of high blood pressure, call 800-575-WELL.)
</P>
</TEXT>
