<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NAZARETH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITHS CLASH IN NAZARETH OVER LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Israel _ Along Paul VI Street in the center of this
town where Jesus came of age, the smashed windows in the Christian
shops were being repaired and owners of looted stores were trying
to assess their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Nazareth, a community of Christian and Muslim Arabs packed
together on a steep hillside, has long prided itself on tolerance.
But now, in the aftermath of several days of rioting that erupted
on Orthodox Easter Sunday between members of the two faiths, the
city is struggling to come to terms with the violence.
</P>
<P>
   As it senses itself fraying along religious lines, this
once-cohesive community of 65,000 has begun to fear the future.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the shattered glass and toppled shelves of his shoe store,
Raed Hakim, 29, a Christian, asked, ``How did this happen? How
could people who used to live together with us do this?''
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop to the violence is a simmering two-year dispute
over a half-acre plot of land. The Christian mayor wants to build a
public plaza at the foot of the massive Church of the Annunciation
as part of a ``Nazareth 2000'' project. Leaders of the militant
Islamic Movement, who control the municipal council, say the
proposed project would violate an Islamic shrine, and they want to
build a mosque on the site, with a towering minaret capped by a
laser-lit Muslim crescent.
</P>
<P>
   As the tension built in recent months, Israeli government
officials did little to intervene. Witnesses said Israeli police
stood and watched when violence erupted. Compared with past
episodes involving Arab Muslims in violent land disputes, the
police passivity was unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli reluctance to get involved has the Christian mayor
and Israeli journalists questioning whether forces in Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud Party are siding with Muslims
in a cynical ploy to pick up Arab votes in this month's election,
playing a political game that exploded in violence less than one
month before what is expected to be a very close vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an old game of divide and rule, but it has become a
dangerous game,'' said Nazareth Mayor Ramez Jeraisi, a member of an
old-line Communist party and a Christian. ``Likud sided with
Muslims here to get their votes. And now look what has happened.
I'm afraid the damage to our community, the way we get along, will
be long term.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netanyahu government dismisses any notion that it was
stirring trouble to win Arab votes as ``conspiracy theories.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the claims and denials, there is no mistaking the
destruction caused by the volatile mix of politics and religion. It
has left Nazareth fretting over its international reputation on the
eve of the millennium, when millions of Christian tourists are
expected to flock to the Holy Land and the pope is expected to make
a historic visit.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon traveled to the Vatican
last week to meet Pope John Paul II about his visit, and reportedly
discussed the simmering tensions in Nazareth. Eager to find a
compromise, the Israeli government has offered to allow the Muslims
to build a small mosque. The Vatican has criticized the Muslim
plans as ``a provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is politics and religion colliding,'' said Nahum Barnea,
a reporter for the Israeli newspaper Yediot Ahronot. ``It started
as petty politics, but now people are worried it has spun out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began in late 1996, when the Christian mayor
proposed building a public plaza at the foot of the Church of the
Annunciation, where Christians believe the Angel Gabriel appeared
to the Virgin Mary to announce she was going to bear a son, Jesus.
The plaza was part of an $80 million project of city improvements
geared toward handling the wave of tourists in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But a militant group of Muslim activists saw the municipal plan
as a holy war against their faith. The land once housed a school
dating to 19th century Ottoman rule, which Muslims say housed a
small mosque. The city tore it down in November 1997 to build the
plaza.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the lot still stands a small shrine to Shahab
el Din, a martyr in an 11th-century battle against Christian
crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   Barnea, the journalist, has written extensively on the tensions
in Nazareth, and said that at the onset of the dispute, a Likud
adviser on Arab affairs, Danny Greenberg, landed in Nazareth.
Greenberg, he said, promised the Islamic movement that Netanyahu's
government would not stop them from taking the land by force. In
December 1997, they did just that, descending on the vacant lot in
the dead of night. They created a makeshift mosque by erecting a
tent and loudspeakers to call prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Under Israeli land laws, the police had to remove them from the
property within 30 days or the Muslims would have a legal claim to
the lot. But the police did not act, saying the seizure took place
during Ramadan, the Muslim holy month.
</P>
<P>
   The militants have been occupying the land for more than a year
while the case lingers in court.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute gave the Islamic movement a cause and helped the
Muslim Unity Party win a 10-seat majority on the 19-seat municipal
council in November. Muslims represent a roughly 65 percent of
Nazareth's population.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Salman Abu Ahmed, the head of the Unity
Party, dressed in a blue suit, came out from noon prayers under the
cool shade of the tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do Christians want this specific piece of land?'' he
asked, as supporters gathered. ``This is holy land, so why should
they be entitled to build a tourist park? Build it somewhere else.
The church owns a lot of land.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Abu Ahmed had proposed that the land be used for a new
municipal building, according to the council's minutes. Asked why
he now sees it as holy land, he replied, ``I didn't know it then.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the tent, a group of several hundred Muslim worshipers
were milling around on the hot afternoon. One, Mohammed Abu Rahal,
40, shaking with anger, said, ``We will die here for this mosque.''
When the tent mosque first went up, Friday prayers drew only a few
dozen militants. Since the eruption of violence, as many as 1,500
Muslims have been attending, and hundreds have been going to daily
services.
</P>
<P>
   Barnea and Jeraisi said Likud's keen interest in the dispute
revolves around two political benefits they can derive from it.
Likud, they say, is trying to win Arab votes in what is expected to
be a very close election on May 17. Knowing that the hard-line
Likud has no natural constituency among Arabs and received only 5
percent of the Arab vote in the last election, the party has
targeted certain Arab towns to win votes by making political
promises on issues that matter to them. Picking up even 1,000 votes
out of Nazareth's 35,000 registered voters would be a considerable
gain in this election.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the two observers said, Netanyahu's Likud may have
wanted to permit the militant Muslims to rampage to show Christians
worldwide, including the Vatican, a frightening image of what would
happen to Christian holy sites if Jerusalem were divided and part
of it placed under Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Moti Zaken, Netanyahu's adviser on Arab affairs, acknowledged
that Likud's Greenberg had ``played some foolish games there'' and
was reprimanded for it.
</P>
<P>
   He made the Muslim Arabs ``think they might gain something, but
they are wrong if they think that,'' said Zaken.
</P>
<P>
   Zaken denied a Likud plot, saying, ``First of all, Muslims
wouldn't vote for Likud even if we paid them. This is good for
newspapers and conspiracy theories, but it has nothing to do with
reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
