<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-LESSONS-BOS &LR;      05-03 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-LESSONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I AM COMLETELY CHANGED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fleeing war or persecution is becoming a way of life worldwide.
Before Kosovo, the world had 22.3 million refugees _ one for every
264 people on earth; now there are 700,000 more. How have those
other refugees, from places like Ethiopia and Cambodia and Sierra
Leone, fared in their new lives? How did their uprooting experience
change them? Focus writer Matthew Brelis talked with six refugees
who landed in America. Their answers provide some insight into what
may lie ahead for hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians. &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HASSAN KOROMA, 32, a senior assistant secretary in Sierra
Leone's ministry of youth and sports, fled his West African
homeland in June 1997 when a coup d'etat resulted in mass murder of
government officials. Today he does odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am completely changed. I have lost my self-esteem. I am very
guilty of things I never thought would affect me. I completely
regret leaving my family. At first, I thought I was very clever (to
have escaped). But my wife was shot. My children are in another
country and I cannot get to them, my extended family _ I do not
know what has happened. It has been traumatic and I feel very, very
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now . . . I try to convince immigration officials I should
have permanent refugee status and that would qualify me for a
program to help bring my kids here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just alone now, just trying to get along. Everyone I know
is dead or not seen. Rebels went to my village in the north and
killed my grandmother and my cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see Kosovo, I feel like the whole thing is happening to
me again. . . .'' &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FARAH MOHAMED, 34, fled Somalia at the end of 1986 after being
arrested several times because of his opposition to the government.
Today he is a family counselor for Catholic Charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a refugee camp for more than a year. It was quite an
experience . . . actually, most of the problems were psychological.
My biggest fear was the lack of understanding, the lack of vision
about my future, what was to become of me . . . and being worried
about family members in Somalia. It is something that stays with
me, even though I consider myself lucky when I see what is
happening to other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the United States in 1988 and I am a citizen now. I
think the question of going home will take time to answer. It is
really a Catch-22. I would like to go back and help my people, but
I have a different understanding about life today. I have worried
that things can go wrong so easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is really sad. It is like it is happening to me. I
started reducing my time watching TV because I cannot really take
it. It is not only the death and dying, but actually that I know
more about being a refugee. . . . I think many people don't really
understand what being a refugee means. It is losing everything.
Some people only think about losing life. Some think that is the
biggest thing to lose. But besides your possessions, your family,
you lose your identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about ending up in America. Everyone in my
neighborhood knew my name, what tribe I came from, and what I stood
for. Here, I am only a black guy around the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am relatively educated. I got a master's degree, I am a
working professional, but I cannot redefine myself, my role. I am
missing something and that is the reality of being a refugee.'' &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELAI HABTE-YESUS, 44, left Ethiopia in 1976 to study medicine
in India. In 1985, he chose not to return home when the government
started killing students. Today he works for the Ethiopian
Community Development Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the situation on the tube, I am reminded of what
happened in Ethiopia in 1977, people displaced internally because
of famine. I have not been sleeping in the past few nights. I feel
this will be the challenge of the 21st century: There is not enough
sympathy for the plight of simple, ordinary people who are victims
of political terror. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Going home again is a challenge; I think about it every day of
my life. It has been almost 23 years and I have not seen my family
and friends. I pray and hope that I will be able to go back one
day. I always thought it would be a temporary thing, a year or two,
at most five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, mental-wise, I am well informed, but emotionally I am
fairly disconnected. I don't think I could say I am a complete,
full person, having gone through what I have _ and I have not seen
anything physical like torture.'' &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIDA IBISEVIC, 16, left Bosnia-Herzogovina with her parents in
1995 because of the conflict there. Today she is a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard leaving everything. The material stuff is nothing,
but we had family and friends and a sense of belonging somewhere.
Here, you have to go on proving yourself _ learning a new language
and trying to fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has helped my confidence because I had to go through a lot
to find friends, learn a language, and fit in. I know nothing can
hurt me. All the bad things that are supposed to happen have
already happened. The war made me stronger, but changing the
environment and starting all over from the beginning helped a lot,
too. I think I became a stronger person and raised my
self-confidence up and helped me understand myself and my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, I feel I lost some of my identity, but this
has given me so much self-confidence. I ask myself sometimes if I
belong to any country, and I want to belong to both. I am an
American, but I have not stopped being a Bosnian. I feel like I am
losing some identity, but I am not letting it go and it is all
about what you feel like inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I wish the war never happened. I would never have
left Bosnia where we have friends and everything. I would not want
to go through it again, but I would not change it. It does not
matter as long as I feel loved, but I would not wish it to anyone
else.'' &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RACI SAY, 48, was rounded up with millions of other Cambodians
in 1975 when the Khmer Rouge took power. After two years, she fled
to refugee camps in Thailand. Today she an administrative
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here in 1981 and we all try to heal our souls. We go
to temple to try and get the nightmare over, and then, boom! All
these things come up. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovo thing is being addressed much faster than what
happened in the killing fields (of Cambodia, but) Kosovo strikes me
so hard, I feel like I am again running at gunpoint. Everyone in my
family is taking it personally, reliving old memories. All these
years later and things still happen the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I came here, make a decent life, have a good house
_ much better than in Cambodia _ nothing is the same. You still
miss the one you grew up in. Life for refugees is never the same,
even if you have much more than you had before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the Kosovars go back, it will not be the same;
everything is destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wish to go back and I plan, but I don't know if the
situation allows it, security-wise. I have been here 17 years and I
never feel settled. I still feel something is missing. You have
Christmas, but we had New Year's.'' &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHIMAN ZEBARI, 37, fled Iraq in 1974 as a Kurdish refugee. She
came to the United States in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was just temporary, but now I know I cannot go
back unless we have our own country. When my husband and I became
American citizens, I knew that was it. I was happy to become an
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I gained, I don't feel I lost my identity. I am still
Kurdish, but I found another identity. At home I am Kurdish. When I
come to work I am American. I don't feel I have lost at all. The
more you know about other cultures, you are learning. How could you
be losing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a refugee made me a better person, a tougher person, I
know I can take the worst situation and make it livable. It really
taught me a lot. I have learned to work harder. I have learned to
get to know other cultures, other languages and to accept all
people equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo breaks my heart. I hope America does something to stop
this. I cannot turn on the TV at dinner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
