<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF GRILLING: LAUER DESERVES ROASTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's former girlfriend Monica Lewinsky is being
criticized these days because she bailed out on some interview
commitments after an unfortunate encounter with Matt Lauer on NBC's
``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   The news reports and commentary about the incident mostly say
that Lewinsky couldn't handle the ``tough questions'' that were
asked during her chat with Lauer and that she canceled the
remaining interviews on her U.S. book tour because she feared the
prospect of further ``grilling'' by other TV inquisitors.
</P>
<P>
   Tough questions? Grilling? Matt Lauer?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like one of those test questions where you're given a
grouping of words or phrases and asked to pick out the one that
doesn't fit. If Lauer ever did any grilling, it must have occurred
in the backyard and involved some hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer was the guy throwing the softballs on that fateful day
when Hillary Rodham Clinton declared that allegations regarding her
husband's affair with Lewinsky were the product of a vast
right-wing conspiracy. He let that slide by as if he'd asked the
first lady about the weather and she had accurately reported that
the sun was shining.
</P>
<P>
   Tough questions, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Koppel probably gives the information operator a tougher
grilling when he calls for directory assistance than Lauer has ever
given a public official or celebrity in a TV interview. Lauer
doesn't specialize in tough questions _ but he does specialize in
questions that are irrelevant, rude and just plain dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Monica. The interview on ``Today''
started going downhill when Lauer demanded that Lewinsky justify
her attendance at moviedom's Academy Awards and her post-Oscar
partying way back in March.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky seemed taken aback by the question _ not because it
stumped her but because it was so stupid. She obviously wondered
what on earth her party-hopping with movie stars had to do with her
book, or even with her role in the White House sex-and-lies
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But she answered the question competently and politely,
explaining that after everything she'd been through, she thought
she was entitled to a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer's reaction to her answer _ an answer that could have and
perhaps should have been, ``Why shouldn't I go to the Oscars, you
jerk? _ was the body-language equivalent of ``Harrumph!''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to quasi-sanctimonious pomposity, Lauer may be in
a class by himself. And he was just getting warmed up.
</P>
<P>
   Having asked Lewinsky, in effect, what gave her the right to
parlay her unfortunate notoriety into a night on the town, Lauer
next wanted to know if she had suffered a suitable amount of guilt
and self-loathing for the pain that her dalliance with the
president might have inflicted on his wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the question suggested that Lauer considered
Lewinsky to be primarily responsible for the marital vow-breaking
that took place in and around the Oval Office. Lauer evidently
bought Clinton's under-oath explanation of the relationship:
Lewinsky had sex with him, but he didn't have sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer then read a passage from Lewinsky's book in which she
describes in somewhat explicit detail her anticipation of an
intimate encounter with the president. Lauer followed up the
dramatic reading by asking Lewinsky how she could show such
insensitivity to Clinton's family. Why, Hillary and Chelsea could
pick up that book and read this trash, he huffed.
</P>
<P>
   The look on Lewinksy's face as Lauer read indicated _ in order _
surprise, alarm, annoyance, anger. But she didn't miss a beat,
throwing the accusation right back at him: How could he be so
irresponsible and insensitive as to read this passage on network
television, thus exposing her words to millions of viewers who
never have and never will read her book _ including, perhaps, the
president's wife and daughter?
</P>
<P>
   The media can rip Lewinsky all they want. I say she emerged from
the interview with a lot more dignity than Lauer did.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Is that what's known as damning with faint praise?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
