u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MRI-BOS &LR;      05-03 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MRI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU NEED AN MRI, TAKE A NUMBER AND GET IN LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tried to schedule an MRI lately?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you probably had to wait two to six weeks, or were told
to come in the middle of the night. And if you were lucky enough to
land an immediate daytime date, chances are it was on Super Bowl
Sunday, Easter or some other occasion when no one in their right
mind would want to squeeze inside a donut-shaped machine with
magnets pounding in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech diagnostic devices are in such demand at hospitals
across the state that they're up and running 15 to 24 hours a day,
with considerable waits for anyone without a life-threatening
condition. That's why, even though they're one of the most
expensive machines in the hospital, many facilities are lining up
to buy more, and most are running the ones they have as often as
they can.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is a dramatic development considering that just a
dozen years ago few doctors and fewer patients knew what a magnetic
resonance imaging machine was. Over that time, and especially in
the last several years, the MRI has become the test of choice to
diagnose orthopedic injuries as well as problems in the brain and
spine. And it's increasingly being used to pinpoint potential
strokes and heart attacks, as well as to guide surgeons operating
on the liver and prostate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have patients on the phone every day asking to be moved up,
begging to have their scans done sooner rather than later,'' says
Dr. Clare Tempany, director of clinical MRI at Brigham and Women's
Hospital in Boston. ``It's five to seven weeks now for an elective
outpatient procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine is a great job to have because there's something new
happening with MRIs all the time. . . . The technology is
improving, the magnets are getting faster, and we're able to do
different things with them that we didn't dream about when they
first came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors aren't the only ones turned on by all the new things
MRIs can do. ``They saved my life, definitely,'' says Thomas
McArdle, a retired electrician who has had six of them in recent
years, including one last month at Brigham that found an aneurysm
in his aortic artery and another in March that helped doctors there
insert radioactive seeds in just the right place to attack his
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have come quite a way in just the quality of the
picture,'' he says, adding that it more than makes up for the fact
that it now takes weeks to schedule a test.
</P>
<P>
   To understand all the hoopla about MRIs, it helps to understand
what the machines do, and how they have been transformed since they
first started showing up in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   MRIs contain powerful magnets that make the positive-charged
proton particles in the body line up in the same direction. Radio
waves are then transmitted towards the protons, which absorb the
energy, tilt and, as the waves are switched off, emit a signal that
the MRI measures and transposes into a picture.
</P>
<P>
   Those pictures used to be fairly crude, but now they're getting
better and better at zeroing in on everything from soft tissue and
bone marrow to all organs of the body. And as the pictures
improved, so did the uses of the tests, moving from the brain to
the spine to the entire musculoskeletal system.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms that means that orthopedic surgeons can, for
the first time, get a clear look at whether cartilage is missing
from the joint surface in a patient's knee without having to go in
with an arthroscope, which means the patient is less likely to end
up needing surgery or having to be on crutches. They also can
detect subtle bone fractures that are too tiny for x-rays to pick
up.
</P>
<P>
   Progress has been equally spectacular in other areas of the
anatomy, with MRIs now used to unmask and sort out lesions in the
liver, to determine how bad a ruptured disk is and to see whether
everything is going right with a pregnancy. A new type of magnetic
imaging machine also has found a place in the operating room,
giving surgeons a real-time roadmap of where they are going in
cutting tissue, attacking a tumor and performing other parts of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the heart, ``which is going to be the real
gangbuster with MR technology,'' predicts Dr. Stephen Sweriduk,
medical director of Shields Healthcare Group of Brockton, Mass.,
whose 10 machines make it the biggest player in the Bay State's MRI
business. Tests already confirm that imaging can identify heart
troubles at a stage before they cause an attack or other damage,
and those techniques are being finetuned to provide critical data
on the walls, valves, vessels and other parts of the coronary
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many different ways to look at the heart right now,
from ultrasound and nuclear medicine to coronary angiography,''
says Sweriduk. ``But the newest MRI scanners are so fast they
actually freeze cardiac motion, doing what all the other tests do
combined. . . . I think this will displace the other tests; you'll
have everything done in one stop and you'll be finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that information we'll be able to decide who gets medical
therapy and who gets surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   MRIs always have been harmless to patients, which is especially
reassuring to anyone who worries about the radiation required with
x-rays and CT scans. Now the per-procedure cost for insurance
companies, which a decade ago ranged from $1,200 to $1,500, are
about a third of that, which relieves some of the concerns that
insurers have had about the proliferation of such tests. If a
doctor orders an MRI insurers typically pay the entire cost.
</P>
<P>
   Add up the lower costs and expanded uses and you have a
diagnostic device that is booming, displacing many uses of x-rays
and going head-to-head with the also-hot technology of CT scans,
which is faster and better at providing images of some body parts
but not as precise with others. What that means for hospitals is
getting the most out of the MRI machines they have and asking the
state for permission to purchase new ones, and for patients it
means a greater likelihood of using the procedure _ and having to
wait in line.
</P>
<P>
   At Massachusetts General Hospital, for instance, one MRI device
is being used 24 hours a day, seven days a week, while the others
run from 7 a.m. to 10 p.m. Usage is equally intense at Beth
Israel-Deaconess, which has four scanners. And at New England
Medical Center the volume of magnetic imaging tests is up 12
percent in just the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running at maximum capacity,'' says Dr. Daniel O'Leary,
the chairman of radiology at New England Medical. ``Waiting lines
are growing well beyond two weeks now, and we've put in an
application for a second machine,''
</P>
<P>
   As the technology takes off, prices of imaging machines are
coming down much the way they are for computers, although new
machines being developed for specialized uses like the ones in the
operating room can cost more than $2 million. The newer machines
also tend to be more patient-friendly, letting the person have his
head out of the machine if the area being photographed is from the
mid-chest down. Other design changes are being tried to quiet the
magnets, which sound like a pile-driver and echo in a patient's
ears.
</P>
<P>
   McArdle, the retired electrician from Scituate, says he's had so
many MRIs that he's come up with his own system for handling the
noise and claustrophobia: ``I kind of separate myself mentally from
the machine. I put myself on the golf course and play my game, and
I actually make out better in the machine than on a real golf
course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
