<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CAUSES HEARTBURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What causes heartburn?
</P>
<P>
   SA, Mattapan, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First things first. Your heart is not involved in heartburn.
That uncomfortable feeling is near your heart, but it's actually in
your lower esophagus, the tube that carries food from your mouth
down into your stomach. But ``Esophagus Burn'' doesn't really have
the same ring to it, does it?
</P>
<P>
   The term doctors use is ``acid reflux.'' The hydrochloric acid
produced in your stomach leaks up into the esophagus through what's
called the lower esophageal sphincter. Dr. Timothy Wang,
gastroenterologist at Massachusetts General Hospital, explains that
the lower esophageal sphincter works like tightening a rubber band
around a straw.
</P>
<P>
   Muscles tighten in a ring around the esophagus just where it
meets the stomach, relaxing to let food down into the stomach but
tightening up before the stomach acid can get up into the
esophagus.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrochloric acid is no big deal in the stomach, since the
lining is protected by a thick layer of mucous. But the esophagus
doesn't enjoy such protection. There, stomach acid irritates the
tissue in what feels like a nice fresh jalapeno pepper dissolving
in your chest. (Stomach acid, produced by parietal cells in your
stomach's lining, has a pH of 2. Straight vinegar is pH3. On the
logarithmic pH scale, that makes stomach acid ten times more acidic
than vinegar.)
</P>
<P>
   Why does the acid get up into the esophagus, where it doesn't
belong?
</P>
<P>
   Wang says that under certain conditions, that ring of lower
esophageal sphincter muscles doesn't close tightly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Acid reflux is most often caused by nothing more than eating too
much. All the extra food in the stomach pushes back up against the
sphincter and some acid leaks out. A big meal also kicks the
parietal cells into overdrive, producing more acid.
</P>
<P>
   Lying down with a full stomach contributes to acid reflux
because gravity is no longer helping pull the food down. Spicy
foods acutally don't cause acid reflux. They may be spicy hot, but
that's not the heat of heartburn. Foods that DO induce heartburn
include fats, caffeine, alcohol, and chocolate. They increase the
production of stomach acid, and thus likelihood of reflux. (Alcohol
also relaxes the sphincter muscles.)
</P>
<P>
   It is also myth that stomach acid helps us digest our food. We
apparently don't need it.
</P>
<P>
   Chewing, and enzymes, and the stomach's muscular grinding help
break the food into the slurry called ``chyme'' (pronounced kime)
that passes into the small intestine, where enzymes finish the job
of digestion. ``We think stomach acid is leftover from a time when
our predecessors ate their meals whole, and sometimes still
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Now our meals are usually dead by the time we eat them, and
forks and knives help break them into digestible-sized bits before
we even swallow them.
</P>
<P>
   While an occasional mild case of acid reflux is common, seven
million Americans suffer much worse. They have Gastro-Esophageal
Reflux Disease. GERD. You're a GERD sufferer if you are afflicted
by acid reflux once or twice a week. Wang says that while GERD
patients sometimes have unique underlying medical conditions that
contribute to their heartburn, most suffer reflux for the same
reasons many of us do. It just hits GERD sufferers harder and more
often.
</P>
<P>
   Serious GERD is more than an uncomfortable inconvenience. A
recent study in Scandinavia published in the March 18 New England
Journal of Medicine reports a seven-fold increase in esophageal
cancer among people with moderate to severe heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   Too much acid getting too far up in your esophagus can actually
get into your trachea, your breathing tube, and cause asthma-like
symptoms, coughing and voice problems. Wang says that President
Clinton is known to take a GERD medication, and that acid reflux
may contribute to his occasional hoarseness.
</P>
<P>
   What can you do? Well, the over-the-counter medications like
Tums, Rolaids, Mylanta and Maalox neutralize acid. They're for mild
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Medications that stop the secretion of acid sometimes help the
more stubborn cases. So can drugs that tighten the sphincter.
There's even heartburn surgery which tightens up the lower
esophageal sphincter.
</P>
<P>
   But the best advice of all, Wang says, is to eat more frequent,
smaller meals, not just a few big ones, and cut down on fats,
caffeine and alcohol. Just don't create the conditions that set up
acid reflux in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
