<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR'S ABUSE OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ If the case against Susan McDougal was absurd _
and it was _ then the case against Julie Hiatt Steele is sick,
bordering on sinister.
</P>
<P>
   All the cases of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr are sideshows
on their best days, but the one that starts this week in Virginia
sets a new low in the pointless pursuit of the weak and vulnerable
out of what looks more like spite than justice.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal at least was once in a position years ago that in
theory might have produced knowledge of serious crimes by big shots
in the Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Julie Hiatt Steele, by that stretched standard, is a nobody.
Or, more precisely, she is everybody, living proof that the
government's power can reach into any life with shattering results
and no purpose beyond, in Starr's case, pique.
</P>
<P>
   Steele's alleged crime is a stubborn refusal to confirm a key
detail or two in the infamous White House ``groping'' story of
Kathleen Willey. For this, she faces obstruction of justice and
perjury charges.
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, Steele is the only person to have been
charged with a crime in Starr's two-year, sex-drenched inquisition
into President Clinton's private life that yielded Monica Lewinsky
and a parody of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that Steele's indictment was timed for the
first day of Clinton's farce of a Senate trial in January. It was a
typical Starr stunt that deserved every bit of the widespread
condemnation it received.
</P>
<P>
   The Steele case is absurd. In Willey's oft-contradicted and
contradictory tales, Steele is supposed to be what the prosecution
calls a ``contemporary corroborating witness'' _ a person to whom
Willey confided the alleged groping incident in November of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Willey also says she asked her friend to confirm their talk to a
Newsweek reporter.
</P>
<P>
   After doing so in confidence, however, Steele then recanted. She
has claimed that the chat with Willey didn't happen that way, and
that Willey asked her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   A while back, I ran into another witness _ former Willey friend
Harolyn Cardozo _ who confirmed Steele's account in two grand jury
appearances and added details about Willey's fantasy life pursuing
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be still another, unnamed Willey friend, who
will also confirm the story. But much more importantly for the
purpose of evaluating a major criminal case, it also turns out
there are at least four more people who back Steel; moreover, five
of the six people who maintain that Willey was ``thrilled'' by
whatever it was that happend in fact or in her mind have been known
to Ken Starr all along.
</P>
<P>
   That last nugget comes courtesy of an excellent investigation of
the case from official sources that was just published by The
Nation magazine and builds on an equally stunning report in March
by Nina Totenberg of National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   One of the people turns out to be the ubiquitous Linda Tripp.
This has been known for a long time. What is new in a media sense,
thanks to The Nation, is the details of Tripp's story. It turns out
they have always been available in the fine print of Starr's
impeachment referral to Congress, but may have been ignored because
the type in the transcripts of her grand jury testimony was
microscopic.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Tripp testified that she not only saw an
anything-but-angry Willey right after the alleged incident but
spoke with her frequently on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp tells a tale of ridiculously relentless, fantasy pursuit
of Clinton. She also said she warned the Newsweek reporter that the
Willey story was baloney, an important factoid because Tripp says
it was then that she told him there was a much better sex story,
which turned out to be Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Nation's investigation is also especially valuable for its
fresh facts about attempts by Willey to market her story for money
before it was in the press, contradicting her initial image as
reluctant truth-teller.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out this involved bigtime New York literary agents and
not only trash-for-cash tabloids, one of whom (Lynn Nesbit) says
Willey was fishing for a book deal two months before the first
Newsweek article was printed, an assertion documented by records.
</P>
<P>
   That information fits neatly with the already known efforts in
the wake of her appearance on CBS' ``60 Minutes'' to both sell a
book and sell a tale to the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   As the Steele case begins, there are two points that make it far
more than a final flutter in the last moments of Starr's official
life.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious one is about what has been done in the government's
name to an ordinary person caught up in this mess. If there is such
a thing as abuse of a prosecutor's discretion _ especially in the
face of a mountain of evidence that fairly scremes ``bogus'' _ this
is it.
</P>
<P>
   The other involves the press. At the time of ``60 Minutes''
interview a year ago, Willey was the rage. But other than putting
her on TV and jabbering about whether she ``seems credible'' nobody
really checked facts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all these months later, the consequences of political
scandal-mongering are clear. That's why the Willey story is is on
the back pages today, even as Julie Hiatt Steele remains in the
dock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
