<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATING TO LIVE LONGER CAN TAKE A LIFETIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a list of the 118 most nutritious foods. ``How many are
in your diet?'' asks Natural Health magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. Butternut squash. Cantaloupe. Carrots. Dandelion?
</P>
<P>
   Dandelion. An important source of vitamin A. How to get more
dandelion into my diet? Maybe a little lunchtime grazing in the
park.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I figure out how to get my minimum daily requirement
of dandelion, I'm sure some researcher will have proven that it's
useless, or even dangerous. That's the way things seem to go on the
health front. Just when you think you're doing the right thing, a
study surfaces and what was good is now bad, and vice versa. These
180-degree turns are hard on those of us who plan to live forever.
Who can keep up with all this stuff?
</P>
<P>
   For years we were led to believe that eating eggs meant certain
death. Last week, a Harvard School of Public Health study revealed
that healthy people can eat up to seven eggs a week without
increasing their risk of heart attack or stroke. That's the latest
scientific finding, at least. Tomorrow, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Eggs are among Natural Health magazine's 118 most nutritious
foods, a good source of vitamin D, vitamin B-12, riboflavin, and
pantothenic acid. Personally, I plan to eat as many eggs as
possible before the Harvard School of Public Health changes its
institutional mind and decides eggs should be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   To counteract cholesterol overload, I'll wash down the eggs with
plenty of red wine. Another study released last week shows that
drinking wine made from Bordeaux grapes is why the French, who are
famous for eating nothing but goose liver and brie, have fewer
heart attacks than Americans. Eat eggs. Drink wine. Be happy.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, red Bordeaux doesn't appear on this list of the 118 most
nutritious foods. Maybe wine isn't considered a food, strictly
speaking. Or maybe Natural Health hasn't caught up with the latest
research. It changes so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Where was I? Apricots. Avocados. Nectarines. Sturgeon?
</P>
<P>
   Does sturgeon caviar count? It might even be doubly nutritious,
since it's eggs. It's an expensive way to get your MDR of vitamin
A, but nobody ever said trying to live forever would be cheap. It's
not easy, that's for sure. Planning how to acquire and eat even
half of these 118 most nutritious foods could bring a person to her
knees.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil nuts. Brown rice. Catfish. Chia seeds?
</P>
<P>
   According to yet another study released last week, people who
attend religious services once a week live longer than those who
don't. Other recent studies have shown that those who meditate or
do yoga live longer. Laughing can lengthen life span, too,
according to another well-publicized study. And it seems that every
time you turn around, another piece of research emerges showing
that an active sex life promotes longevity. Assuming you're in the
mood. No wonder everybody wants to live forever.
</P>
<P>
   What else? Tea. Drinking tea, black or green, is an absolutely
essential part of the longevity plan. Garlic is a must, too. And
soy, of course. And whey, as in curds and whey. Why whey? Why not.
Whey is hot. This month, at least. I read about whey in Life
Extension magazine, a publication devoted to just what its title
implies. Its pages are filled with ads for a staggering array of
ads for dietary supplements aimed at extending life span.
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody doing research on people who try to do everything
necessary to extend their life spans? I wouldn't be surprised to
pick up the paper one morning and find that they die earlier than
average. Meanwhile, I'm hedging my bets.
</P>
<P>
   Guava. Parsnips. Quinoa . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
