<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-CHICAGO-BOS &LR;      05-03 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-CHICAGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTING CAST GIVES `CHICAGO' LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CHICAGO 
Musical in two acts, with music by John Kander and lyrics by Fred
Ebb. Book by Bob Fosse and Fred Ebb based on play by Maurine Dallas
Watkins 
Directed by Walter Bobbie. Choreography, Ann Reinking. Set, John
Lee Beatty. Costumes, William Ivey Long. Music director, Vincent
Fanuele. Originally directed and choreographed by Fosse 
Starring: Ann Reinking, Ruthie Henshall and Adrian Zmed. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Elvis didn't know when to do it. Sinatra didn't know
when to do it. Why should Ann Reinking know when to do it?
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Ann Reinking exploded onto Broadway when she replaced
Gwen Verdon in ``Chicago.'' Her jaw-dropping athletic swirls and
kicks injected the show with sexy vitality. Her legs reached for
the sky in a magnificent celebration of themselves. Nearly a
quarter-century ago, her dancing dazzled us.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I had the privilege of observing the
choreographer Reinking fine-tune the second touring company of
``Chicago.'' She saw everything. If a dancer was a fraction of an
inch short, Reinking caught it. If another was trying to round off
a sharp step, she sympathetically pointed it out. And, let me put
this as kindly as I can: Ann Reinking, the choreographer of the
current ``Chicago'' at the Shubert Theatre, would never hire Ann
Reinking, the dancer. Never.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not privy to the conflicts that must have accompanied the
decision to coax Reinking out of retirement to replace the injured
Sandy Duncan. There's no doubt the Reinking name sells tickets. The
run has been extended two weeks. But her performance does an
injustice to her legend and her colleagues. Watching her dance in
``Chicago'' is like listening to Sinatra, during his final tour,
stumble through the lyrics to ``My Kind of Town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago'' is my kind of musical.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't owe as much to the town as it does to the image
Chicago conjures up in the popular imagination. Sex and
speak-easies. Wise guys and even wiser gals. Director-choreographer
Bob Fosse, who had a tortured love-hate relationship with both his
art and the audience, laid everything on the table in this tabloid
tale of ``murder, greed, corruption, violence, exploitation,
adultery, and treachery.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted the cast to seduce the audience _ to render us
speechless in his world, a world defined by body language where
spectators are stunned by sexy acrobatics. From the egomania of the
slimy Billy Flynn, played competently by Adrian Zmed, to Ruthie
Henshall's erotic Velma Kelly and Carol Wood's prison matron, the
show retains the trappings of Fosse's vision but not the heart and
soul.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the show hit town _ featuring Jasmine Guy,
Charlotte d'Amboise, and Obba Babatunde _ it was understandably
celebrated. The jazzy, pulsating score was at one with the dancers,
who looked as if they could out-hustle the Chicago Bulls in their
prime. The spare set, with the orchestra in a center box flanked
simply by two ladders and a few chairs, focused attention where it
should be _ on the talent.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the magnificent score, the one consistent element in
this generally languid production is the supporting cast. The stars
should take their cues from their anonymous underlings who
revitalize the proceedings with a well-defined, energetic rendition
of the ``Cell Block Tango.'' In fact, instead of using star power
to draw ticket sales, the producers might consider promoting from
within and trusting the audience to embrace the talented newcomers.
They have the legs that gives ``Chicago'' legs.
</P>
<P>
   And that, after all, is what Fosse was after. Angry legs. Exotic
legs. Legs that stretch to the ceiling. Legs that belong to the
pounding, athletic style of Gene Kelly rather than Fred Astaire's
subtlety and grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago'' sweats. But this one doesn't. And though Reinking
gets great marks as a trouper, she seems to be the only one left
breathless at the end of a long evening.
</P>
<P>
   Velma greets the crowd at the opening of the second act with
``Hello, suckers. Welcome back.'' This time, she's not kidding.
Unlike the Broadway production and the previous touring company,
this production ultimately fails. And no matter how many knowing
winks and comic asides Reinking delivers, they can't disguise the
fundamental problem that she's just not in the kind of physical
condition required for this demanding show. This time ``Chicago''
slipped us the old razzle-dazzle, playing us for suckers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
