<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-HARRIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING JULIE HARRIS PLAYS `THE GIN GAME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the morning after the Littleton, Colo., shootings, and the
subject is inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Julie Harris, 73, the recipient of 10 Tony nominations
and an unprecedented five Tony Awards for acting, is on the phone
from her room in the Watergate Hotel in Washington, D.C. She's
costarring in Washington with Charles Durning in a national tour of
``The Gin Game,'' D. L. Coburn's Pulitzer Prize-winning
two-character play. The massacre in Littleton reminds her of
Shakespeare's line in ``Hamlet'' about ``the heartache and the
thousand natural shocks that flesh is heir to.'' She deplores the
hate that seems to animate so many, from Colorado to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's character in ``The Gin Game'' is animated not by
hatred, but by _ well, here's how Harris describes her: ``At the
end, finally, Fonsia realizes what she's done. All she had to do
was let Weller win a couple of games. But she's abandoned and
ruined him. `Oh, no,' she thinks. She realizes it's exactly what
she did to her son and to her husband. She's been doing it all her
life. It's a powerful lesson. It makes you want to say, `Come on,
we've got to love one another.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The action of the play pits Fonsia against Weller in a series of
gin games, during which the two elderly characters get to know each
other _ and we get to know them _ in conversations that grow
increasingly sharp as Fonsia wins hand after hand.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says she's not absorbed by gin, cards, games or even the
spirit of competition. ``My mother and (older) brother Bill were
game players. I don't care whether I win or lose, but my brother
and mother cared. My uncle plays bridge and if he loses it carries
over into the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked onstage with Ethel Waters and Rex Harrison. I knew
they had egos. But ego should be tempered with humility. Judi Dench
says that acting isn't the whole of life _ family and friends are
the whole of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Coburn, speaking on the phone from Dallas later, says
Harris successfully merges the ``very nice person'' she is in real
life with Fonsia's ``fully vindictive, sharp-edged'' character. But
he clearly means that making herself less than nice is a feat of
acting.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's big break occurred in 1950, when she played Frankie
Addams, the motherless 12-year-old tomboy who's convinced that
she'll be going along on her brother's honeymoon in Carson
McCullers's poignant ``The Member of the Wedding.'' Reprising the
role in the movie earned her an Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie was only Harris's first indelible character. In 1952,
she appeared in John Van Druten's ``I Am a Camera,'' the play that
foretold the durable musical ``Cabaret.'' Harris played the
indefatigable party girl Sally Bowles, earning her first Tony
Award. (She also took the role in the 1955 movie.) Her second Tony,
in 1956, was for her St. Joan in Lillian Hellman's adaptation of
Jean Anouilh's ``The Lark.'' There was a third Tony in 1969 for
``Forty Carats,'' and a fourth in 1973 for her Mary Todd Lincoln in
James Prideaux's ``The Last of Mrs. Lincoln.'' In 1977, she won her
historic fifth Tony for her definitive Emily Dickinson in William
Luce's ``The Belle of Amherst,'' directed by her good friend
Charles Nelson Reilly. (He's also directing this ``Gin Game,'' the
11th production in which they've worked together.)
</P>
<P>
   Coburn says that actors who've played Weller Martin, Fonsia's
opponent in gin, ``see themselves in Weller'' while actresses ``get
to Fonsia by a process,'' a process that requires making her
sympathetic while seeming hard. The irony, says Coburn, is that the
actresses win the awards. ``Jessica Tandy, a previous Fonsia, won a
Tony; Julie won a Tony nomination,'' he says. He says the marriage
of Tandy and Hume Cronyn ``showed through'' their acclaimed
performances in the roles. Harris, who saw Cronyn and Tandy perform
the piece on stage when she was ``20 years younger,'' thinks she
and Durning _ friends who've played opposite each other several
times _ are ``funnier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Durning is funny. When I first played opposite him, he was a
Shakespearean clown. And Reilly is a very funny man,'' says Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn says when he conceived the play, it was around ``a man
and woman in conflict, a conflict in souls. . . . The man was of a
particular temperament; the woman was fragile and vulnerable but,
it turned out, an iron maiden.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Weller, the conflict involves God. Weller's fate comes out
through a simple card game. It becomes the most important thing in
his life. It symbolizes his loss of control _ as if any of us ever
has control over our lives; if we do, it's earlier, not at this
stage of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, an avid gin player himself, says Fonsia's streak of luck
is ``not beyond the pale'' of reality. He was once losing heavily
to a someone on a lucky streak in Mexico when suddenly earthquake
tremors began shaking the chandelier above them. ``It's an
earthquake,'' his opponent exclaimed. ``Shut up and deal,'' Coburn
replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
