<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WORLD-BOS &LR;      05-03 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT BARKER, ON THE HOME FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANOTHER WORLD 
By Pat Barker 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 278 pp. $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   However blurred the gender lines of contemporary fiction, war is
a literary province that has belonged largely to men, for a couple
of obvious reasons: They are the ones who have fought it, and
they're the ones who came of age in a toy-soldier world, thereby
grasping (often seduced by) its imaginative allure. This
double-edged privilege has given us stories that romanticize war as
well as those that wholly condemn it, most of them witness to a no
man's land where mostly men have been.
</P>
<P>
   Then came British writer Pat Barker, whose First World War
``Regeneration'' trilogy (published here through the early '90s)
captured the sickening emptiness of the Somme and the ravages of a
soldier's mind, all of it delivered in the elegiac tradition of
Hemingway. Already acclaimed in England for the gritty realism of
such early works as ``Union Street,'' Barker brought to her war
novels a fiercely authentic sense of the losses incurred from the
outset: the class distinctions of the British army, the yellowing
skin of a munitions factory worker, the failures of even medicine
and language to offer salve or understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another World,'' Barker's first novel since the trilogy ended
with ``The Ghost Road'' (1996), has an old soldier at its center,
and its laconic, blistering family drama combines elements both of
her domestic novels and of her war stories. Set in contemporary
Newcastle, in northern England, the story's close-focus plot lacks
the poetic reach of her earlier work; still, Barker can do more
with less than most of her peers. With its dying centenarian and
its murderous children, ``Another World'' conveys the modern family
in all its thwarted glory _ riddled with unhappiness but bound
together by something less precise, waiting on the future and yet
shackled to the present by the past.
</P>
<P>
   The details of these characters' lives outside their nuclear
realm are sparse; what matters is the web of intimacy they've
created and hang suspended in. Nick Halford, the somewhat reluctant
head of the family, is an academic; his second wife, Fran, is
pregnant with the couple's second child together. Jasper, their
toddler, is at the mercy of his horridly alienated half-brother,
Gareth, Fran's 11-year-old son. And now the happy clan has been
joined by 13-year-old Miranda, Nick's daughter by his first
marriage; her visit is precipitated by her mum's recent reentry
into a psychiatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   So we know from the outset of ``Another World'' that this is
hardly going to be the Swiss Family Robinson, with everyone working
together toward mutual survival; what's conveyed instead is a
milieu of exhaustion and silent anger that seems poised to blow.
Barker suggests this volatility with frightening efficiency:
Gareth, for instance, who spends most of his waking hours playing
video games, finishes his toilette each night by wiping his
stepfather's toothbrush around the inside rim of the toilet. The
boy never knew his father; Fran, for her money, remembers him as
``a stain on the sheets.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Barker's gifts is her mix of compassion and bleak
realism, and if Nick and his haphazard tribe are bound together by
duty and misery, they also seem oddly normal. Love lurks in the
room, somewhere, even if no one has the energy anymore to summon
the word. When Nick collects Miranda at the train station, they've
just moved into an old Victorian on Lob's Hill and are trying to
make the place livable. Peeling off the wallpaper in the living
room one evening, they discover an intact portrait of the family
who lived there a century ago: the Fanshawes (``like `Wuthering
Heights,' '' Miranda says brightly), who had a war industrialist as
their patriarch, and who guarded a family secret that would raise
the hair even on Gareth's young neck. Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bronte, sort of, but also like Hawthorne, who wrote an
early Gothic novel by the same name. Barker has superimposed this
story _ the perilous fate of the Fanshawes, perhaps sealed by the
old man's profiteering _ upon Nick and his gang, one assumes in
order to suggest the hazy emotional parallels of history, or at
least the commonalities of memory. It doesn't quite work. The novel
takes on a ghostly sheen, at least episodically, where young girls
hover about in long dresses and where bad things happen to good
people. But this post-Gothic poke in the ribs is no match for the
story of the real paterfamilias of Nick's family: his grandfather
Geordie, ``fragile and indestructible as thistledown,'' who
survived the First World War only to battle a lifetime of memories
_ now dying of cancer, hardly peacefully, at the age of 101.
</P>
<P>
   Nick's respite from his family, if you can call it that, is the
deathwatch he keeps over his beloved Geordie, who has been more a
father to him than a grandfather. At the center of their long,
muted goodbye is the memory of Geordie's brother, Harry, who died
alongside him at the Somme and about whom Geordie speaks only in
troubled dreams and half-sentences. This is Barker's territory, and
she invokes it beautifully _ even the last agonies of Geordie's
illness are fearlessly rendered with a master's timing. But in
constructing two competing stories that are supposed to elucidate
one another, she's created a problem similar to the one that
plagued ``The Ghost Road'': Borrowing from Peter to pay Paul, she
winds up shortchanging them both.
</P>
<P>
   The title of ``Another World'' refers, fluidly and repeatedly,
to the various realities offered and imposed by our perceptions:
the passage of time, the unreliability of memory, the malleability
of history. These are grand themes, and sometimes the novel lives
up to them; Barker's confidence as a stripped-down, elegant stylist
is evenly matched by her moral depth. Sometimes, though, you can
feel her family drama straining for the higher scaffolding beyond
its reach. What feels right-sized in both conceit and execution is
the old soldier himself: noble and cantankerous and facing death
with grim necessity, which is a far less fancy phrase than courage
and one that Geordie would probably prefer. For if Barker knows
brilliantly that memory is what makes us human, she also
understands its price: the cost tallied daily not just by what
we've lost, but by what we can't undo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1347EDT &QL; 
