<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-2TAKES-     05-03 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHER STARS, OTHER SCREENS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only is there life after ``The Phantom Menace'' this summer,
there's life before it, too. Once George Lucas's behemoth ``Star
Wars'' prequel dropped into the May 19 slot, the other films began
filling up summer's open parking spaces fast. On the calendar,
summer begins June 21. In Hollywood, summer begins this Friday.
That's because summer is the season when studios make the largest
chunk of their money _ 40 percent _ and there are only so many
summer weekends. Between now and Labor Day, look for more than 100
releases. They'll be looking for you.
</P>
<P>
   The parade starts Friday with a face-off between remakes:
Shakesepeare's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' and the old Boris
Karloff horror classic ``The Mummy.'' It won't stop until Julia
Roberts, Liam Neeson, Brendan Fraser, and Hugh Grant weigh in twice
each, in different films, while Michelle Pfeiffer, Will Smith, John
Travolta, Adam Sandler, Tom Cruise, Nicole Kidman, Mike Myers,
Sharon Stone, Richard Gere, Pierce Brosnan, Spike Lee, and
animations ranging from ``Tarzan'' to a ``South Park'' spinoff
jockey for screens. Here's a list of the entries, in order of
opening date:
</P>
<P>
   ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' (Friday) _ Shakespeare's back in
Hollywood for yet another all-star go at his summer of love in the
dreamy woods, orchestrated by Stanley Tucci's Puck, who observes
what fools Michelle Pfeiffer, Kevin Kline, Calista Flockhart,
Rupert Everett, Stanley Tucci, and Christian Bale be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' (Friday) _ Brendan Fraser, having played George of
the Jungle, this time plays the guy in the Egyptian tomb. Not the
old Karloff character in the dusty tape, but the one fighting him,
alongside love interest Rachel Weisz. The joker here is that
plutocrat Lucas's Industrial Light &AMP; Magic supplied the mummies and
other monsters added in by special effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea with Mussolini'' (May 14) _ If you've been wondering what
Oscar-winner Judi Dench would do for an encore after Queen
Elizabeth I, here's the answer. She stars alongside compatriots
Maggie Smith and Joan Plowright in a period piece drawn from the
childhood of Franco Zeffirelli. Lest you suspect a Brits-only plot,
be advised that the fourth star is Cher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' (May 19) _ OK, OK, you
already know that this first of three prequels to the ``Star Wars''
trilogy focuses on Darth Vader as a cute, gifted, pre-Dark Side
tyke (Jake Lloyd) alongside Liam Neeson's Jedi Master and Natalie
Portman as Luke Skywalker's and Princess Leia's mom. How can you
not? The only question is whether it's of a piece with the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' (May 21) _ Give it credit for having the
guts to go up against ``The Phantom Menace,'' though it's hardly
aimed at the same demographic. This one, filmed in Rockport last
summer, finds Kate Capshaw's bookstore owner taking a romantic
flyer with Tom Everett Scott's younger man, cheered on by Ellen
DeGeneres, Tom Selleck, and Gloria Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' (May 28) _ Let's hear it for Julia I. In her
first of two romantic comedies this summer, Roberts plays a movie
star who's also a diva (she insists it's fiction). While in London,
she meets and beds Hugh Grant's shy bookstore owner. He really does
some acting, pretending to be a stranger to media craziness, as she
teaches him the joys of dodging paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thirteenth Floor'' (May 28) _ This Roland Emmerich sci-fi
project, greenlit long before ``The Matrix,'' would love to ride
that film's flashy coattails as it straddles a story line that
shuttles beteeen 1937 and the present, set in motion by a tycoon's
mysterious death and tied to razzle-dazzle special effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct'' (June 4) _ Here's some casting against type, in an
unusual story about a world-class primatologist accused of killing
two park rangers in a gorilla preserve in Kenya. Anthony Hopkins is
the accused, maintaining a stony silence and a primitive nobility.
Cuba Gooding Jr. _ presumably taking a cue from Robin Williams _
plays the shrink who tries to rehab him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' (June 11) _ Here comes
Mike Myers again, as his joky little film turns into a franchise.
Back he comes in several guises, in fact, including Powers and his
nemesis, Dr. Evil. The level of humor in this goof on the '70s is
indicated by the names of Heather Graham's character (Felicity
Shagwell) and Kristen Johnson's (Ivana Humpalot).
</P>
<P>
   ``The General's Daughter'' (June 11) _ It's John Travolta time
again, this time in a thriller rising from an uncivil action. He
plays an army officer investigating the vicious murder of the
general's daughter. To do it, he must negotiate a minefield of
cover-ups inhabited by Madeleine Stowe, James Woods, Timothy
Hutton, and James Cromwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' (June 18) _ If it's summer, it must be another Disney
animation. This one, voiced by Tony Goldwyn as Edgar Rice
Burroughs's swinging single and Minnie Driver as Jane, will bring
new meaning, the studio hopes, to the concept of Hollywood and
Vine. If it should click, look for Disney to replicate it in the
Broadway musical jungle, to say nothing of the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' (June 18) _ Pierce Brosnan isn't
James Bond here, but he wouldn't mind if some of 007's suave style
rubbed off on this millionaire art thief. Rene Russo and Denis
Leary costar in this remake of one of the great Boston movies. The
1968 version starred the late Steve McQueen and Faye Dunaway.
She'll be seen here in a cameo role as Brosnan's therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' (June 18) _ Here's a
movie about offending people, starting with the MPAA, which has
rated it R. Only fitting, since the movie is an anti-censorship
outing about kids subverting a stern ratings committee formed after
they sneak into an R-rated movie and learn a few words we can't
print here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Daddy'' (June 25) _ Given Adam Sandler's box-office action
in ``The Water Boy'' and ``The Wedding Singer,'' the title probably
refers to the movie, and the studio's wishful thinking about its
take. It's less likely to refer to his loser character in it, a law
school grad named Koufax who strikes out a lot until he grows up by
taking care of a 5-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' (June 25) _ After years of being regarded
as a one-play author (``The Importance of Being Earnest''), recent
revivals of this work and of ``Lady Windermere's Fan'' have
reminded the world of Oscar Wilde's generosity and dazzling wit.
Cate Blanchett, Jeremy Northam, Minnie Driver, Rupert Everett, and
Julianne Moore restore it to its high gloss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
