<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     05-03 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... high gloss.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West'' (July 2) _ Will Smith, the box-office king of
July 4 on the basis of ``Independence Day'' and ``Men in Black,''
returns as a 19th-century government op taking on an evil Kenneth
Branagh and a giant mechanical tarantula. Kevin Kline and Salma
Hayek provide moral _ and, when necessary, immoral _ support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arlington Road'' (July 9) _ Jeff Bridges, a professor who has
made a study of domestic terrorism after his FBI-agent wife was
killed in a shoot-out, doesn't like what he sees when new neighbors
Tim Robbins and Joan Cusack move in next door. The result is a film
of disturbing pertinence, done in a way that sets it apart from
other extremist-bomber movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut'' (July 16) _ This is the late Stanley
Kubrick's swan song, but it'll be remembered as the film in which
Nicole Kidman and Tom Cruise appear nude as married therapists
pushing the envelope of sexual obsession. The high degree of
secrecy and security surrounding the film and its reclusive maker
has added to its mystique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haunting'' (July 23) _ Jan De Bont revs up the special
effects to turn this remake of Shirley Jackson's ``The Haunting of
Hill House'' into a high-tech creepfest. Liam Neeson, demoted from
Jedi Master to ordinary prof, plays mind games with Lili Taylor,
Catherine Zeta-Jones, and Owen Wilson, only to find the house
playing games with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight Club'' (July 23) _ Director David Fincher, who led Brad
Pitt through the stygian ``Seven,'' this time leads him into the
bloody underground world of private fight clubs. Accompanying
Pitt's sadomasochistic character through the ultraviolence is a
dysfunctional couple played by Edward Norton and Helena Bonham
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runaway Bride'' (July 30) _ Just because she's co-starring
opposite Richard Gere again, and being directed by ``Pretty Woman''
director Garry Marshall again, don't push the parallels, Roberts
advises. Here she plays a woman who never can quite make it all the
way down the aisle, which piques the interest of headline-hungry
reporter Gere, who investigates and is hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer of Sam'' (July 30) _ Spike Lee's hot-button take on New
York City's Son of Sam killings of the 1970s and the vigilantism
they generated in a Bronx Italian neighborhood. John Leguizamo,
Mira Sorvino, Jennifer Esposito, Adrien Brody, Anthony LaPaglia,
Patti LuPone, Ben Gazzara, and Bebe Neuwirth play the locals who
seethe more than Michael Badalucco's killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Blue Sea'' (July 30) _ We're going to see a lot of
thrillers about genetic engineering gone wrong. This one not only
is among the first, but plugs its cautionary tale into an
experiment designed to produce big-brained sharks. This should give
it a certain jaws-dropping appeal, as Samuel L. Jackson, Thomas
Jane, and LL Cool J slip into their wet suits to cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery Men'' (August 6) _ Comic-book antiheroes goof on the
superhero movie as Ben Stiller's sputtering nerd leads fellow
shleps William H. Macy, Hank Azaria, Janeane Garofalo, Wes Studi,
and Paul Reubens against Geoffrey Rush, playing an archfiend named
Frankenstein in a place named Champion City. A possible sleeper,
given the cast, which also includes Tom Waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' (August 13) _ Hugh Grant again, this time
as an art dealer whose girlfriend (Jeanne Tripplehorn) wants to
plug him into a Mafia connection (James Caan) determined to use his
gallery as a money-laundering device. Grant doubled as director
when this romantic comedy needed reshoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dudley Do-Right'' (August 13) _ Another blast from the past
for Brendan Fraser, who this time returns to dorkdom as the
dimwitted Canadian Mountie from Jay Ward's 1960s animated TV
series. British actor Alfred Molina, who sneers with the best of
them, plays the heavy, Snidely Whiplash. Sarah Jessica Parker is
the virginal Nell Fenwick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Muse'' (August 20) _ Speaking of shleps, Albert Brooks
plays a low-level Hollywood writer praying for inspiration, then
having his prayers answered by Sharon Stone's contempo LA muse. It
goes so well that he begins to fear she'll desert him for top-dog
screenwriter Jeff Bridges. Stone finds ways, we are assured, to
make her comedy debut sexy as well as funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killing Mrs. Tingle'' (August 20) _ ``Scream'' scribe Kevin
Williamson makes his directing debut in this dark movie he says is
more comedy than screamfest, though hardly bloodless. ``Dawson
Creek'' diva Katie Holmes stars as a high-schooler who figures
there's nothing wrong with her grades that bondage and a crossbow
can't cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astronaut's Wife'' (August 27) _ Sci-fi thriller starring
Johnny Depp as a NASA guy who comes back from a space shot unable
to remember what happened when he briefly blacked out, and Charlize
Theron as his wife who becomes pregnant, then begins to harbor dark
suspicions that the life in there is from out there.
</P>
</TEXT>
