<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-HATCHER-BOS &LR;      05-03 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-HATCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERI HATCHER MAKES HER STAGE DEBUT IN A FAMOUS ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Scrunched up in the theater balcony, in clothes so
baggy they leave everything to the imagination, new mom Teri
Hatcher is discussing her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher finds it vaguely disturbing when strangers on the street
do this _ and they still do _ but she also knows she's got a pair
of pop-culture icons under that sweatshirt. After all, they starred
in not one but two episodes of ``Seinfeld,'' including the must-see
sendoff. Suddenly the whole world seemed to know that ``They're
real, and they're spectacular,'' as her parting shot at an
uncertain Jerry went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that funny, how much attention that line got?'' says
Hatcher, who by then was already accustomed to the attention that
comes from having one of the most downloaded images on the
Internet. ``It comes up all the time. It's sort of stuck with me,
but, hey, that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot is OK with Hatcher these days. She's got a new baby, a new
home in New York, and a new way to risk her reputation six days a
week. With no theater experience, little voice training, and even
less guarantee that she wouldn't be hooted off the stage, Hatcher
stepped into the role of Sally Bowles, the pathetic party girl at
the center of ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   No question Hatcher has guts. Whether she has the goods is open
to interpretation. Some reviews love her, others hate her, and the
audience, she says, can go either way on any given night. With
small tables set around the stage to resemble a Berlin cabaret, the
feedback is immediate. All she has to do is glance at the lip of
the Wilshire Theatre stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the tradeoff; you get both sides,'' Hatcher says. ``There
have been nights where every single person in those front tables
has sat there with their arms not just crossed, but clenched,
looking at you like there's not a chance in hell you will ever win
them over. Then there are nights where everyone sitting there has a
smile on their face. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there are nights when those same scowlers are crying
at the end and are so moved they can barely clap, but you know why
they're not clapping,'' she adds. ``This play is such a big trip
and I feel like if people want to come and I have to win them over,
then that's my job. I don't get mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Now winding up in Los Angeles, where ``Cabaret'' has played to
good-size crowds, Hatcher next has to woo audiences in Boston. The
production opens May 7 at the Colonial Theatre, with 35
performances scheduled over the four-week run. That's about 56,000
tickets, 56,000 chances to convince people she belongs in the role
immortalized by Liza Minnelli and then reworked to stunning effect
by Tony Award winner Natasha Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   On stage in her babydoll dresses _ looking so tiny and, yes,
flat-chested _ Hatcher doesn't try to compete with either actress.
She knows she doesn't have Minnelli's lungs or Richardson's acting
pedigree. In fact, offstage her voice drops an octave in reverence
when she recalls seeing Richardson on Broadway and how the entire
production inspired her to want to sing, dance, act like that.
</P>
<P>
   On her own, Hatcher hired a dialect coach to help her with
Bowles's British accent and a singing teacher to stretch her ``I
love to sing in the car'' soprano. She practiced scenes and got the
producers to agree to see her. They did not, however, agree to pay
her way. Hatcher, still living in Los Angeles at the time, bought
her own ticket to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `You'll have to audition like everyone else,'
and I was like, `Great,' '' Hatcher says, drawing out the word to
emphasize that she means it. ``It was one of the first times that I
was so inspired. I really just was inspired to audition. You know,
I never thought I'd get the part.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing against other name actressess, actresses with Broadway
experience, not to mention any theater experience at all, Hatcher
won over her first, crucial audience. She says she thinks they
wanted someone with a raw, untrained voice, not a professional
Broadway belter _ a vixen who could project vulnerability. Hatcher
is the first to admit she's learning as she goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did joke, about three weeks into rehearsal, that if I get
creamed in Los Angeles they might as well tie an anchor around my
career and throw it into the East River,'' Hatcher says, smiling
with relief that she's sitting in the balcony to tell the story.
``Yeah, I'm putting myself out there. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a great thing that starts to come over you,'' she
adds. ``You start trusting yourself and the work you've done,
trusting the director. I mean, why would they cast someone they
thought was just totally incapable? The way this cast feels about
me and I feel about them, that's where you have to get your
strength, not from what the critics say.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher credits her parents with her willingness to take this
risk and to risk rejection in Hollywood year after year. Born and
raised in northern California, she describes her folks as
``brilliantly smart'' but too fearful of returning to the poverty
of their own childhoods to chance much themselves. Instead, she
says, they instilled in their daughter a sense that they would be
there to catch her if she failed _ and, by extension, the ability
to dream and dare.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I feel I've never made choices out of a fear of it not
succeeding,'' says Hatcher. ``What I have experienced is the
deepest, deepest pain of when they don't succeed. That's what can
be brutal about this business. I mean, not everyone is going to
like you, and that's something I think has been hard for me to
accept.''
</P>
<P>
   The people whose approval means most to her these days are the
cast members who surround her, veteran stage actors who sing,
dance, play instruments while the action unfolds. In turn, she's
effusive in her praise of them, including the accordion player
temporarily staying with her. A note tacked to the hallway bulletin
board apologizes for not mentioning ``how fabulous you all are by
name'' on ``The Tonight Show,'' then reminds them ``that's what's
in my heart. I love you all!''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the other night the banjo player warned her that
people were going to start mistaking her for a singer. What do you
mean? she demanded to know. Which song? The song was ``Maybe This
Time,'' one of her showcase numbers, and he meant she sounded
strong and sure. The compliment still makes her light up, the only
color on her otherwise unadorned face.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher says she doesn't have time for makeup these days, not
with the show and not with 16-month-old Emerson Rose, even if it is
actor/husband Jon Tenney's turn on the night shift. After starring
in movies such as ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' and appearing in any
number of sitcoms, Hatcher stopped seeking roles from the time
Emerson was born until ``Cabaret'' came along. Even now, she frets
about missing the bath/bedtime ritual.
</P>
<P>
   But Tenney and Emerson do drop by every Saturday between the
matinee and the evening show and treat Hatcher to dinner.
Afterward, Emerson sits in the dressing room with Mommy, both
facing the mirror, both playing dress-up. Days, Hatcher walks
around with Sally Bowle's chipped green nail polish and brassily
streaked hair and laughs to think what people must think.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher insists she doesn't buy into the whole body-conscious,
looks-obsessed Hollywood routine. She says she tries to eat well
and work out regularly and fails miserably at both. A good day, she
says, is one when she runs a brush through her hair. As Hatcher,
who is warily pushing 35, puts it, ``The way people think of me and
the way I am are definitely not the same. That's just the image.''
</P>
<P>
   She convinced the producers of ``Cabaret'' that was true. Now
she's taking her new image on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
