<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL'S NOT AN URBAN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The melodrama of New England's wandering warriors has already
reached one crucial turn in the plot. The Patriots will not be
playing in Boston, not in its 22 wards, not alienating urban
neighbors, not taking up valuable land needed for a growing city.
</P>
<P>
   Pro football is a suburban enterprise. When the East Rutherford
Jets take on the Tempe Cardinals or the Irving Cowboys face the
Instant-Beltway-Village Redskins, many fans indulge in tailgating,
an activity forced upon them by the lack of anything else to do.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is an urban game, enhancing a city's attractions and
strengthening its economy because it is based on 81 home games a
year, not eight. Cities that build new downtown ballparks discover
that acres of parking lots are not necessary. In Denver, Coors
Field transformed Lower Downtown's blighted lots into thriving
commercial and retail life. LoDo repeals Melanie's folksong lament:
The city has replaced parking lots with an urban paradise.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the Giants open a new ballpark next season,
but the city is building no new parking lots. Instead, it installed
a new trolley line along the Embarcadero. Added trains will arrive
at a commuter depot a block away, ferry service will be available,
and many spectators will walk from Union Square, a 10-minute stroll
away. How many pro football fans walk to the game?
</P>
<P>
   Pro football still plays mutt-in-the-manger in many cities,
distracting civic leaders and forecasting doom in a life without
field goals. The ploy has succeeded in St. Louis, Oakland, and San
Diego. The NFL's vice presidents for propaganda tour the provinces,
cooking up deals. Los Angeles, the home of the deal, resists and
somehow prospers without the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In the odyssey of the Patriots, Boston played a crucial role in
the chalk-talk sessions run by Paul Kirk, the lawyer and former
Democratic national chairman. Kirk noticed that the city had
changed since he hauled in passes for John Yovicsin's Harvard teams
in the 1960s. A lot of Boston College rings rested on the
conference table.
</P>
<P>
   One hero emerged from the sandlots of Hyde Park. Mayor Thomas
Menino made a pro forma offer of the former incinerator land near
Massachusetts Avenue to the Patriots. The site was a logical backup
when the Patriots tried to invade South Boston, with no more
success than the British Army's attempt in March of 1776. Menino's
punt-blocking effort affirmed Boston's good intentions, but was not
taken seriously amid the hailstorm of Hartford's proffered
greenbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston site was to be a fabled ``Megaplex,'' a hideously
named public relations stunt among the many Hail Mary passes heaved
by the team's owners. The late Billy Sullivan, the first owner, was
considered feisty and insistent when he searched for a new stadium.
He now seems like Pop Warner and Santa Claus compared to his
successors, all self-designated saviors.
</P>
<P>
   When Victor Kiam, the boss of Remington, took over, the Globe's
Will McDonough predicted that he would be the first man in history
to try to cut his own throat with an electric razor. Then the
Budweiser heir, James Busch Orthwein, arrived, providing full
employment to local consultants. Former idealists from the Dukakis
era toiled like Clydesdales to sell the Megaplex before reality
derailed it.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bob Kraft, the cardboard king, is driving the bus for the
Boston-Brighton-Chestnut Hill-South Station-Neponset-Route
1-Offramp-Providence-Pawtucket-Hartford Patriots. If success is a
journey, not a destination, this franchise is a perennial Super
Bowl champ.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford, whose former hockey team now plays somewhere in the
Lesser Antilles, will win if it loses and lose if it wins. That
once-great capital, whose charms attracted Samuel Colt and Samuel
Clemens, will find its salvation not in the centrifugal forces of
shoulder pads and suburbanization, but in its own history and urban
character.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
