u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HOKKAIDO-BOS &LR;      05-03 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HOKKAIDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SCENT OF CHERRY BLOSSOMS AND JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HOKKAIDO HIGHWAY BLUES 
Hitchhiking Japan 
By Will Ferguson 
Soho Press, 433 pp., $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hokkaido Highway Blues'' begins with an end, and an abrupt one
at that. We are ready to embark on an unlikely journey, and instead
of a beginning, the opening line is the opposite: ``Cape Sata is
the end of Japan.'' This is unsettling, and the uneasiness persists
until almost the end of the brief opening chapter _ when, after
desultory encounters with a squid vendor and a Japanese tourist,
the first sakura _ cherry blossoms _ are sighted.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first of many gentle jokes played by Will Ferguson, an
irreverent itinerant exchange teacher from Canada, on this
delightful trip through the most oblique of major nations. Like
many traditional Japanese, he gets to his subject in a roundabout
way and, once he does arrive, acts a little surprised that he has
found it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Sakura are a primary symbol of Japanese culture, their startling
beauty, ephemeral life, and sudden death exemplifying some basics
of the Japanese take on human existence. Every spring, the
cherry-blossom front advances from south to north, as symbolic of
the season as the march of fall foliage from north to south in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Peak season is the occasion for song, dance, and an abundance of
rice wine. It was in just this setting one year that, Ferguson
says, he announced his intention to follow the cherry-blossom front
from beginning to end, hitchhiking the whole way from Cape Sata,
southernmost point on Japan's main islands, to Cape Soya in the
north.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming it on the sake is probably another illustration of a
Japanese social device turned to the author's purpose. Ferguson,
author of ``The Hitchhiker's Guide to Japan,'' clearly was itching
to write his own contribution to the shelves of Japan books
authored by long-term foreign residents.
</P>
<P>
   Much as a Japanese employee, if drunk enough, is forgiven for
telling off his boss, Ferguson, with his alleged drunken vow, sets
his project in motion in a way that frees it from the ponderous
pretensions and overgeneralizations that have ruined many a book on
Japan before this. Instead, well-researched history and
well-considered sociological observations are finely blended and
balanced with tales of the road, with no attempt to sum up.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchhiking along, meeting people at random but not always in
brief, Ferguson delivers observations that are sometimes touching,
sometimes amusing, and always true. Additionally, they are almost
always good-humored _ even when the subject is the generally
despised Gaijin card, which he is ordered to produce when he spaces
out while trying to hitchhike on a national highway (which is
illegal) and flags down a police car.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaijin card, he writes, in one of many dead-on
characterizations, ``is a fascist tradition that makes most
long-term residents seethe. In Japan, foreign residents must submit
to being fingerprinted and registered, and must carry their ID
cards with them at all times. . . . It is nothing short of ethnic
bullying, bureaucratically entrenched racism, institutionalized
xenophobia, etcetera, etcetera.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he continues, ``I kind of like my Gaijin card. It makes
me feel like an emigre in a spy movie . . . mulled over by security
men who eye you suspiciously and say things like `Your papers are
not in order' in deep Slavic accents. Not that this has ever
happened. This was the first time any Japanese policeman had ever
asked to see my card. I was delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   The cops released him with a good-humored warning and gave him a
lift. The episode has, in the best sense, some of the flavor of
folk singer Arlo Guthrie's encounter with police in the song
``Alice's Restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   The author's abiding interest in the subject, his sturdy good
humor, and the fact that he neither fawns over Japan nor bashes it
all contribute to his success. But it is his ability as a writer
that really makes the book work.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his reaction after failing repeatedly to get through a
confusing maze of streets to a temple he wants to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he says, ``I did what any intrepid traveler would do _
I gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only then, as though a fog had lifted, did I notice the
neighborhood I had been trying to escape. It was one of those
villages-within-a-town-within-a-city that contains Japan like gift
boxes within gift boxes. . . . I walked deeper and deeper into the
side streets and avenues. . . . The scent of spring and wood smoke
folded itself around me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed an alley so narrow I could run my hands along the
houses on either side of me. I looked in on people's lives. . . . A
woman raking the driveway gravel. A man tending a garden of bonsai.
Futons hung out to catch the sun from upstairs windows like seasick
passengers slumped over the edge of an ocean liner. Clothes drying
on bamboo poles, the pants legs strung up as if in mid-karate
kick.''
</P>
<P>
   As a wordsmith and a traveler, Ferguson knows where he is going.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1356EDT &QL; 
