<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPING UP SAVINGS TO MEET GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Based on the following information, can you tell me if my
husband and I are saving enough for retirement, how we should
allocate our savings, and how much we can expect to accumulate in
15 and 25 years? I am 40 and my husband is 39. I have a $20,000 IRA
invested in the Fidelity Emerging Growth fund, an account to which
I don't currently contribute. My husband has a $150,000 401(k) plan
to which he contributes $571 a month and to which his employer
contributes half that amount in the form of company stock. Because
of a change in the 401(k) plan, we need to reallocate the money,
with these fund options: Invesco Total Return, Fidelity Growth and
Income, Fidelity Spartan US Equity Index, Fidelity Magellan,
Fidelity US Bond Index, Fidelity Growth Company, Fidelity Emerging
Markets, Fidelity Diversified International, and a money market
fund.
</P>
<P>
   D.M., Stoneham, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you continue with contributions at the current level,
including those of your husband's employer, and if both the IRA and
401(k) realize average annual gains of 10 percent, you will have
$1,051,614 in 15 years and $2,899,391 in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But before you get too comfortable, consider the likely effects
of inflation: If inflation runs at an average 3.5 percent, the
buying power of that $1,051,614 after 15 years will be equivalent
to $627,968 in today's money. Under the same assumption, the
25-year accumulation would have the buying power of $1,226,868 in
1999 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Since you mentioned elsewhere in your letter that you have a
current annual income of $120,000, even with the 25-year
projection, you would face a pretty substantial drop in income upon
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if your husband maintains his 401(k) contributions as
a percentage of salary rather than as a dollar amount, the
contributions would increase every time he gets a raise,
effectively boosting the projected accumulations, and probably by a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while I don't like to speculate on what Social
Security will look like in 15 or 25 years, it will likely survive
in some form and improve the overall situation.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd be more comfortable if you could boost the savings
level, which currently represent only 5.7 percent of your annual
income.
</P>
<P>
   As for allocation of your savings, let's begin with your IRA. My
suggestions here are to fill in a couple of areas that aren't
available on your husband's 401(k) menu.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure quite what you hold _ Fidelity has an Emerging
Markets fund, but none I can find called Emerging Growth. If you
hold Emerging Markets, the time to sell was long, long ago. But
better late than never. I'd put half the money in Fidelity Select
Health Care fund and the remainder in Fidelity OTC.
</P>
<P>
   As for your husband's 401(k) portfolio, you don't mention how
much of the assets are in his company's stock, or whether he would
move all or some of that money to other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, you'd want to limit your holding of a single stock to a
maximum of 25 percent, and I'd be more comfortable with 20 percent
of the entire portfolio (meaning $34,000 when you include your IRA
in the calculation).
</P>
<P>
   As for the remainder, I would divide half of the money between
Fidelity Growth and Income and Fidelity Spartan US Equity Index,
both of which operate with large-cap domestic stock portfolios that
represent a blend of growth and value issues.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that one, Growth and Income, is a managed
portfolio, while the other simply tracks the stocks of the major
domestic companies. I'd then divide whatever is left between
Fidelity Diversified International and Invesco Total Return funds.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that your husband maintain his contributions to the
401(k) along the same lines set out above, and periodically reduce
the amount of his company's stock to whatever percentage of the
total portfolio you have decided upon, putting the proceeds in the
same allocations I've suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the generous contributions of his employer, this is
something you should adjust regularly _ say on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally I have nothing at all against that company stock _
I'm suggesting the sales only to increase diversification and
reduce risk.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you decide you can and should save more, resume
contributions to your own IRA. If you made the maximum annual
contribution allowed, which would mean putting in $166.66 a month,
you would increase your overall savings rate to 7.4 percent of
income.
</P>
<P>
   These additional investments would not only add $66,446 to the
pool after 15 years and $205,709 after 25, but it would also allow
the two elements of the portfolio it represents _ mid-cap stocks
and health care stocks _ to keep pace with the segments in your
husband's account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are almost 80. We get $24,500 in Social Security, and we
have $7,700 in tax-free bonds, $5,000 worth of Treasury notes and
bills, and $5,900 in telephone stock. As the Treasuries mature, the
new ones pay less, but we feel safe. Which way to go?
</P>
<P>
   W. E., Chelsea, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sometimes the security of government securities is worth the
few basis points of additional yield that you might get if you went
into less rock-solid investments.
</P>
<P>
   The only suggestion I have is to look closely at your tax
situation and question whether you are profiting from their
tax-free status.
</P>
<P>
   Would you be better off selling these and replacing them with
more Treasury notes and bills?
</P>
<P>
   You would face a federal tax liability on the interest you earn,
but the chances are that the additional yield would more than
offset the tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, the interest on these government securities is
free of Massachusetts state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
