<HEADLINE>
WHO'S IN THAT NEW BEETLE?
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies NEW BEETLE-INVASION) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The average U.S. buyer's annual family income: $86,000, a
higher income than for buyers of any other Volkswagen, even the
pricier models, for which buyers' incomes average $63,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The person behind the wheel may well have received the New
Beetle as a gift. The birthday Beetle. The anniversary Beetle. The
third-car-in-the-family Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   _ True to every cliche, the car is the boomers' Beetle. The
average U.S. buyer is 44, emerging from right smack in the middle
of the baby boom generation (78 million potential Beetle drivers
born between 1946 and 1964).
</P>
<P>
   _ More than half of buyers are married; only one-third have
children at home. Slightly more than half are male.
</P>
<P>
   _ What did they pay? The average transaction price: $18,050.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Volkswagen of America.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
