<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FREEDOM-BOS &LR;      05-03 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FREEDOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROSTRATE NATION BECOMES A WORLD POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FREEDOM FROM FEAR 
The American People in Depression and War, 1929-1945 
By David M. Kennedy 
Oxford. 936 pp. Illustrated. $45 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There never was a time like the period between 1929 and 1945.
Stuffed with great change and great challenge, it left a nation
transformed, altering its character, its position in the world, its
view of its responsibilities, and its conception of its promise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, America was wealthy and withdrawn. By 1945 it had
tasted the depths of the Great Depression and the burdens of world
power. In 1929, it was tentative and, apart from a brief brush with
big-power tensions in World War I, untested in the world. By 1945
it was confident and muscular, the preeminent world power
economically, militarily, and culturally.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, its worldview and its leaders were rooted in the 19th
century. By 1945, its worldview and leaders were to define the
remainder of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   This is modern America's story _ modern America's most
thrilling, most irresistible, and most significant story _ and in
this massive volume, David M. Kennedy, a Stanford University
historian, makes it his story in a way that no one has before.
``Freedom from Fear,'' the fourth installment of the new Oxford
History of the United States to appear, is as much a triumph as its
predecessors, providing every indication that the series, once
completed, will stand as the most comprehensive and most compelling
narrative history of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kennedy's epic story is more than a fitting companion to
Robert Middlekauff's ``The Glorious Cause: The American Revolution,
1763-1789,'' James McPherson's ``Battle Cry of Freedom: The Civil
War Era,'' and James T. Patterson's ``Grand Expectations: The
United States, 1945-1974.'' In many ways, the period covered by
Kennedy's work is the most astonishing era of all, a combination of
the despair of depression (the greatest the nation ever endured)
and the heroics of war (the greatest crusade of the century, maybe
of all time), with the volume ending with America, as Winston
Churchill put it, ``at this moment at the summit of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy portrays a nation so powerful that it commanded half the
earth's manufacturing capacity, so advanced that it generated half
the world's electricity, controlled two-thirds of the world's gold
_ and so dominant that it owned 100 percent of the world's atomic
weapons. ``The war had shaken the American people loose and shaken
them up, freed them from a decade of economic and social paralysis
and flung them around their country into new regions and new ways
of life,'' he writes. ``It was a war that so richly delivered on
all the promises of the wartime advertisers and politicians that it
nearly banished the memory of the Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this story _ besides, of course, the energy and
genius of the American people themselves _ is the commanding figure
of Franklin Delano Roosevelt, truly first in war, first in peace,
and first in the hearts of his countrymen. He is the linchpin of so
much _ the connection between a nation governed by the aristocracy
and a nation moved by the impulses of mass taste; the connection
between a people who had barely any ties to its national government
and a people whose jobs, outlook, and safety depended almost
entirely on government; the connection between an America planted
in the 19th century and an America determined to shape the 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave the nation a presidential civics lesson that defined
nothing less than the ideology of modern liberalism,'' Kennedy
writes. ``He breathed new meaning into ideas like liberty and
freedom. He bestowed new legitimacy on the idea of government. He
introduced new political ideas, like social security. He
transformed the country's very sense of itself, and of what was
politically possible, in enduring ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of this could have, maybe even might have, happened without
Roosevelt. But it didn't happen without him. He was there. He
presided over it all, and more, dominating the politics and culture
of the country in a way that no other leader ever has. Kennedy's
title for this volume, ``Freedom from Fear,'' is clearly an echo of
FDR's famous four freedoms, but it stands for something more _ the
Roosevelt conviction and achievement: that security, personal and
national, was the business of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security was the touchstone, the single word that summed up
more of what Roosevelt aimed at than any other,'' Kennedy writes.
Here is Roosevelt himself: ``I place the security of the men, women
and children of the Nation first.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Roosevelt always deserved credit for protecting the
nation's security. Kennedy is critical of FDR's preparation for the
postwar world, saying he ``banked on goodwill and personal charm to
compose the conflicting interests of nations.'' That's probably
true. But Roosevelt's bank of goodwill and personal charm still
served him, and the nation, well. It permitted him to force the
uncompromising to compromise, the irreconcilable to reconcile, the
unwilling to become willing. The result is a legacy that, for all
its faults, excesses, and inconsistencies, still is the
underpinning of American society. (The Republicans made huge gains
in the 1942 congressional elections but Social Security and some of
the other Roosevelt programs were untouched. Many of them remained
untouched through the Reagan years.)
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt came to office in another America; indeed, Kennedy
speaks of the 1930s as having ``opened a fissure across the
landscape of American history no less gaping than that opened by
the volley on Lexington Common in April 1775 or by the bombardment
of Sumter on another April four score and six years later.'' He
came to power in a country whose population was 44 percent rural,
where 45 million had no indoor plumbing and almost none had
electricity. It was a world of wood stoves and oil lamps and well
water. That was the good news. The Great Depression made things
even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Kennedy's take: ``History's wealthiest nation, the
haughty citadel of capitalist efficiency, only four years earlier a
model of apparently everlasting prosperity, land of the pilgrims'
pride, of immigrant dreams and beckoning frontiers, America lay
tense and still, a wasteland of economic devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt gave Americans hope for the future, some tools to
build a future, and a vision to sustain the future. The hope, the
tools, and the vision helped win the future, but the future was
built by the war. Roosevelt and the New Deal got the country back
on its feet; the war set it running.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a thunder squall ionizes the sultry summer air, World War
II left the American people energized, freshened, and invigorated.
Depression America had been a place of resignation, fear, and
torpor. America at war was quickened by confidence, hope, and above
all by movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy tells this story with sweep and with telling detail.
Like: Army dentists pulled 15 million teeth during World War II.
The average GI was 5 feet 8 inches tall and weighed 144 pounds. The
daily toilet paper allotment for an American soldier was 22.5
sheets (compared with the 3 sheets allotted to British soldiers).
It required more than 600 tons of supplies a day to sustain a US
combat division.
</P>
<P>
   The war cleared Europe of the Nazis, cleared Asia of its native
imperialistic threat, changed gender roles in the United States,
set in motion both the civil rights and the women's movements, and
seeded the suburbs. It changed the world, and it changed Americans'
view of the world. ``It was a war,'' Kennedy writes, ``that had
brought them as far as imagination could reach, and beyond, from
the ordeal of the Great Depression and had opened apparently
infinite vistas for the future.'' When we look back on the past, it
is clear that the future began there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
