 Monday, May 3, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Mark
Helm at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)    WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY (Washington) _ The search for a diplomatic
solution to the Kosovo war escalates with the arrivals here of
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is trying to mediate an end
to the conflict, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who won the release of
three American GIs held captive in Serbia. Jackson is bringing a
letter to President Clinton from Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SENATE (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to reject a
resolution by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that would authorize
President Clinton to use ``all necessary force and other means,''
including land troops, in the military campaign against Yugoslavia.
By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Forget all that optimistic talk
about bipartisan cooperation between the White House and Congress.
The Yugoslavia bombing has exposed the continuing Republican
bitterness toward President Clinton, expressed in the constant
references to ``Clinton's war'' and the House refusal to either
oppose his policy or support it. This is Impeachment II, a second
go at trying to bring him down and this time take Al Gore with him.
By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
