<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``The Apple'' An astonishing film from Iran, based on
a true story and featuring its principals, two 12-year-old sisters
locked since birth inside their small house in a poor Tehran
neighborhood by their fearful and befuddled old father finally
sprung by a social worker. What happens to them when they break out
into the world around them is affecting in its own right and a
potent political allegory besides. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``The Book of Life'' Hal Hartley's seriously trippy take on
the last day of the millennium has Martin Donovan as a reticent,
deadpan Jesus trying to decide whether it's time to kick off the
Apocalypse. The provocative premise almost overcomes the script's
lapses _ but in any case you just have to give it up for a film
that casts singer P. J. Harvey as Mary Magdalene. (Unrated) (Renee
Graham) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR)  &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``Entrapment'' Star allure carries this silly and
overextended millennium heist plot, served up with gloss and
slickness. Reliable old Sean Connery, warm and rugged as a wary
superthief who isn't afraid to show his age, and Catherine
Zeta-Jones, as his smart and shapely new partner in crime, are the
reasons to give this one a try. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ! &LR;  ``Idle Hands'' Devon Sawa begins well as a pothead slacker
so out of it he doesn't realize his parents have been murdered,
much less that his own right hand, demonically possessed, did it.
But this stab at gory over-the-topness, culminating in the usual
mayhem at the big school dance, runs out of script long before it
runs out of fake blood. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Open Your Eyes'' A stylishly twisty reality-shift outing
from Spain: A handsome Casanova who treats women badly has his face
shattered by one of them, then finds himself being interviewed by a
therapist inside a prison. You'll be confused but never bored as
the film's jagged style keeps us guessing which of its several
scenarios is the one that's really happening. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``Radiohead: Meeting People Is Easy'' Mostly languorous,
95-minute authorized documentary of Radiohead's 1997 tour. The band
was breaking through to something like stardom, which seems to
entail bigger demands but no more fun. Meant for the obsessive fan,
really: It hasn't been a hard day's night for a long, long time.
(Unrated) (Jim Sullivan)
</P>
</TEXT>
