<HEADER>
A2282 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      05-03 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK DOINGS IN THE ICE AND THE MOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I love maps. I have collected them since well before my teens.
Maps are promises of escape and opportunity; they let me know what
is over the mountain range; they are reminders of where I have been
and of adventures good and bad. So I was delighted to be given
``Tony Hillerman's Indian Country Map and Guide'' (Time Traveler
Maps, PO Box 30, Mancos, CO 81328, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   The map shows locations and provides descriptions from 13
Hillerman mysteries, setting out the locales from the many riveting
scenes Hillerman has given us over the years, and wedging those
locales into the Four Corners country, between the sacred mountains
of the cardinal directions as denoted by the Navajo. Having grown
up under the shadow of one of those sacred mountains (Sierra Blanca
Peak in Colorado), and having visited the other three, I have the
advantage of being able to judge the cartographer's art from
experience on the ground, and I can attest that this is a nifty map
that any map collector, and any Hillerman fan, will want.
</P>
<P>
   Just as perfect a gift would be a series of compact Oxford
paperbacks known as Oxford Twelves, each containing 12 relatively
unknown short stories. Apparently there are eight of these out,
with two more planned, though I have only three: ``Tales of
Murder'' and ``Mystery Stories,'' both edited by Jack Adrian, and
``American Crime Stories,'' edited by Rosemary Herbert. These are
editors of wide reading and good judgment, and the result is nearly
perfect. The ``Tales of Murder'' range from Richard Marsh's ``An
Illustration of Modern Science'' (1896) to Vincent Cornier's ``The
Monster'' (1951). All are good and some more than that, and though
I like to think I know a thing or two about this genre, nine of the
stories are new to me. Herbert's selections are equally fresh.
</P>
<P>
   A fine new biography, ``Teller of Tales: The Life of Arthur
Conan Doyle'' by Daniel Stashower (Holt, $32.50), also helps us
remember that there really still is a canon to this body of
literature. Stashower writes mysteries himself; as a winner of the
Raymond Chandler Fulbright Fellowship, he was able to spend a year
in England and Scotland on research, and as a result he has some
fresh things to say. I like the way he respects Conan Doyle's
yearning for a spiritualist utopia, how he sees that the people who
populate the grand master's stories are not typical Victorians (as
they so often are taken to be), and how the Edwardian period was
truly different. This is a fine biography; one needn't give a fig
for Sherlock Holmes to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Equally engrossing is Stan Jones's ``White Sky, Black Ice''
(Soho, $22), ``a Nathan Active investigation'' set in Chukchi,
Alaska. Active is a state trooper who is eager to get out of the
isolated village where he deals with repetitive problems of
alcoholism, drugs, snowmobile and dog sled accidents, poaching,
vandalism, and brawls. Inevitably the jacket tells us Jones is
``Tony Hillerman in snowshoes,'' and Jones is, like Hillerman, good
at demythologizing Native Americans (the book deeply involves
Inupiat culture) and at detecting fear in an apparently serene
landscape. This is a debut novel, and I look forward to more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogsbody, Inc.,'' by L. L. Thrasher (Write Way Publishing,
10555 East Dartmouth St., Suite 210, Aurora, CO 80014, $22.95) is
not a debut, but the author is new to me. Despite the title, which
tells us that private detective Zachariah Smith will take on just
about anything in his small eastern Oregon town, the story is
sophisticated, cleverly told, with a nonstop plot and great
characterization. A doctor is killed by a sniper during a rally
outside a women's health clinic; as she was about to speak to Smith
at the time, he may have been the target. A rebellious teenager
goes missing, presumably a runaway from his feckless father and
drunken mother. Points of view on abortion are nicely but not
didactically aired. Smith is an interesting person in his right,
not just a cause of action.
</P>
<P>
   John Caine is back, and he's an old acquaintance. Earlier I
compared him to Travis McGee, but in ``Emerald Flash'' by Charles
Knief (St. Martin's, $23.95), Caine is less intellectually
resourceful _ falling into situations he might have avoided if he
had just read more books like this one _ and a good bit more
physically daring. Set in Hawaii, with some harrowing chase
sequences on Kauai, this book reinforces the ensemble actors Knief
is assembling and deploys them nicely across an action story in
which one does not want to pause too often to ask ``Why?'' Knief is
well on the way to challenging John D. MacDonald, though there is
some distance to go yet: After all, MacDonald wrote scores of
books, and we have known Honolulu's premier private eye for only
three. More, please.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robin W. Winks reviews mystery fiction once a month. The chair of
the department of history at Yale University, he relaxes in Alaska
and Hawaii _ as far away from New England as he can get.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
