<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``East of the Mountains'' by David Guterson (Harcourt Brace,
$25). The struggles of a man at the end of his days. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Adultery: And Other Diversions'' by Tim Parks (Arcade,
$23.95). Essays by the novelist, on the tension between freedom,
necessity, and mortality. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect'' by Sara Lawrence-Lightfoot (Perseus, $23). Six
vignettes illustrating the complex power of a simple idea. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Making Peace'' by George J. Mitchell (Knopf, $24). The man who
brokered Northern Ireland's peace agreement writes a fair and
quietly balanced account of the process. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Prayer for the Dying'' by Stewart O'Nan (Holt, $22).
Highbrow terror: a spare, ominous fictional portrait of a Wisconsin
town struck by diphtheria in the years after the Civil War. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan: American Financier'' by Jean Strouse (Random House,
$34.95). A thoroughly documented, consciously nonpartisan biography
of that colossus of capitalism J. P. Morgan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman: An Intimate Geography'' by Natalie Angier (Peter
Davison/Houghton Mifflin, $25). Learned and witty, exhilarating and
subversive, this ``working map'' dismantles our received wisdom
about how the female body works and what it means. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
