u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-NIGHT-HNS &LR;      05-03 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC SCORES WITH `SPORTS NIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We're out. Two minutes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Every week you hear that as the first commercial break comes up
on the fictional ``Sports Night'' highlights show on the
Continental Sports Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, ``Sports Night'' is a behind-the-scenes look at
the characters who run what is essentially ESPN's ``SportsCenter.''
You are there, on the floor, as they fade out. You listen _
intently _ as the dialogue races between anchors, producers,
editors, makeup people and network suits. Everybody who walks onto
that set is interesting in some way.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, the show is back on the air, and this
show-within-a-show format has you captured.
</P>
<P>
   It's this special you-are-there relationship that fuels ``Sports
Night.'' Well, that's not exactly true. It's brilliance that fuels
the show. It's amazing to think that ABC, which airs ``Sports
Night,'' isn't completely thrilled with the performance. While the
show may not be a Nielsens god, it's certainly not a bottom
dweller.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the season finale, you'll hear those familiar words
again: ``We're out. Two minutes back.'' You'll be wishing the
real-life TV show would never go away and that it had another 22
episodes to carry you over into next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' is one of television's very best shows, a rare
30-minute mix of comedy and drama that
</P>
<P>
   The show was slow to catch on with viewers but is now a runaway
train of populist love, who-would-have-guessed-it, re-evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer and writer Aaron Sorkin has created a daring
show that has consistently rewarded patient viewers. Can the show
be cloying? Absolutely. Is it heavily stylized? Yes. But so what?
At least it has style and dares to be different and damned if
you're not, after this last episode, left with the feeling that
something special is going away.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's the emotional stew of a very good TV show. And
wouldn't it be great, as May brings the TV season to an end, if we
felt that way about a lot more shows?
</P>
<P>
   The details of this finale are not as important as merely
celebrating their existence. But you'll find anchor Casey (Peter
Krause) and producer Dana (Felicity Huffman) finding out maybe they
really are soul mates; the return of Isaac (Robert Guillaume) from
his stroke (written into the plot because of Guillaume's real-life
illness); and the usual emotional roller coaster of sentimentality
and sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Sports Night'' bows out for the season, you realize just
how well cast this show is. If Huffman doesn't win an Emmy _ hands
down _ something's terribly wrong in Hollywood. Krause and Josh
Charles, who plays his co-host on the show, have a natural
chemistry while being vastly different characters. Two of the
show's supporting cast _ Sabrina Lloyd as Natalie and Joshua Malina
as Jeremy _ are standouts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the experimental and ingenious elements of ``Sports
Night'' is that it's all done in 22 minutes. It would certainly
merit an hour _ and we'd all be better off for it. But juggling the
disparate emotions of the show is part of the trick that brings us
back each week.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the finale, which manages to mix Dana's anal retentive
control habits (funny) with her emotional collapse (sad), and
Casey's paternal breakthrough with his son (touching) with his
inability to express his true emotions to Dana (frustrating), is
virtuoso stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But Sorkin and company have been doing this all season. That
some people want to quibble with one of the few TV shows that
actually stretches out and exposes itself while taking chances is
the worst kind of quibbling.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't seen ``Sports Night,'' or catch it only
occasionally, watch the finale. It will make you long for reruns so
you can play catch-up, and it will place you in the same emotional
state as the diehards: anxious, circling September on the calendar,
waiting to go back on air.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes out is nothing. Four months will be unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
