the released American prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton and Keizo Obuchi,
the Japanese prime minister, discuss deregulating Japanese
industry, spurring the economy and issues involving North Korea. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-MOSCOSO (Panama City, Panama) _ A Woman-in-the-News
profile of Panama's president-elect, Mireya Moscoso. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ The newly elected Turkish
Parliament erupted in fury Sunday and prevented one of its female
members from taking her oath of office while wearing a head scarf.
The deputy had said that her scarf simply reflected a private
commitment to Islam, but many Turks consider it an inflammatory
provocation. Turkey is strongly secular, and its political and
military leaders fiercely resist any religious influence in public
affairs. By Steven Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A unanimous Supreme Court upheld the
government's standard for evaluating a crime committed in an
immigrant's home country, rejecting the claim that political
motives should make a difference. Plus a roundup of other court
action. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ After 13 days of
vigils, funerals and media scrutiny, many Columbine High School
students were eager to return to the daily routine of academic
life. The students are to attend classes, beginning today, at
nearby Chatfield High School. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-KILLERS (Undated) _ In the wake of the shootings at
Columbine High School, psychiatrists say it is the fragile children
_ not sturdy ones _ who are most likely to ``break'' in dramatic
ways, according to a growing number of ``psychological autopsy''
studies of youthful suicides, and from less formal studies of
adolescents who have committed murders. At the same time, other
studies have shown that the turbulence, pathology and confusion
considered ``normal'' in adolescence are in fact far from typical.
By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE (Jackson, Miss.) _ Developments at a national
conference on school violence. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-NH (Somewhere in N.J.) _ Elizabeth Dole campaigns around
New Hampshire. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PATAKI-DRUGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ N.Y. Gov. George Pataki unveils
his plan to water down the strict drug laws enacted under Gov.
Nelson Rockefeller. He recommends slightly lower penalties for drug
selling in return for the abolition of parole. By Raymond
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FILM-STUDIO (New York) _ Robert De Niro, the actor, and
Harvey Weinstein of Miramax Films announce plans to convert the old
Navy Yard in Brooklyn into film studios. By Charles V. Bagli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE (Undated) _ MediaOne, the No. 3 U.S. cable
television company, accepted a takeover offer from AT&AMP;T,
terminating its agreement to merge with smaller rival Comcast.
Comcast must now decide whether it will launch a counteroffer by a
Thursday deadline.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft and the Justice
Department release their witness lists. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (new York) _ At 1:50 p.m., the Dow industrials were ahead
149 points, the NASDAQ composite down 16. Stocks are somewhat
higher in Europe, little changed in Hong Kong, and closed for
holidays in both London and Tokyo. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Ford and DaimlerChrysler report U.S. auto
sales for April. Ford's report will be the first one to include
Volvo. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-IPO (New York) _ Goldman Sachs will price its initial
public offering after the market closes. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-PUERTO-RICO (Undated) _ SBC Communications Inc. and
Telefonos de Mexico to buy Cellular Communications of Puerto Rico
for $464 million. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-APPOINT (Geneva) _ The World Trade Organization, after a
weekend of acrimonious negotiation, failed to choose between two
rivals for the director-general post. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
