<HEADER>
A2296 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWBEETLE-INVASION-TE     05-03 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBEETLE-INVASION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BUG STILL HAS BUYERS WAITING MONTHS FOR DELIVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by NEW BEETLE-BUYER) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kirsten Green wanted Volkswagen's New Beetle so badly that she
dreamt of the car regularly. A shiny yellow Bug drove around her
nighttime subconscious so often that she mentioned the dreams to
her husband, who secretly ordered her the car.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered his plans. The Arlington, Texas, couple built a
carport in anticipation of their new arrival. They waited for
months. She had more Bug dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Michael Green brought Kirsten to Fort Worth's Autobahn
Motor Group. There sat her yellow dream car with a big bow on it
and a sign ``Reserved for Kirsten Green.''
</P>
<P>
   She burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen of America calls its New Beetle ``probably the most
emotional car in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   More so than a Jaguar? A Porsche?
</P>
<P>
   At $16,000 to $20,000, it's a more affordable emotion, one that
maneuvers easily through our memories of fun times in a fun car.
</P>
<P>
   Even for those born after 1979, the last model year for the
original Beetle, the New Beetle fuels an emotional response to its
happy, shiny colors, rounded silhouette and flower-bud vase on the
dash (the flower sometimes twirls when the air conditioner is on
full blast).
</P>
<P>
   Even now, about one year after the model was introduced in March
1998, dealers say New Beetle buyers still are waiting from one
month to more than a year for delivery, depending on the options
requested.
</P>
<P>
   Want a standard transmission, maybe a black or a white car? The
wait is not long.
</P>
<P>
   Want the most popular colors, yellow or silver? With automatic
transmission, a sunroof and leather interior? You have time to
build the carport.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting lists aren't expected to go away. In Arlington, 60
people are on the Hiley Volkswagen waiting list for the New Beetle;
at Autobahn in Fort Worth, 75 are cooling their heels. Even test
drives are difficult to come by _ Autobahn Motorcar used to keep a
New Beetle on the lot for that purpose, but it proved too popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Six Flags here,'' Chris Pipes, New Beetle salesman
at Autobahn Motorcar Group, said of the amusement-ride atmosphere
that accompanied the test car.
</P>
<P>
   The '90s Bug was never meant to be a massive seller, and the
company has no plans to step up production. It was meant to draw
attention to the entire line of VWs, accelerating interest in the
company that also wants to sell a lot of Golfs and Jettas.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be working.
</P>
<P>
   Autobahn is planning a mid-June opening of a 31,769-square-foot,
$1 million expansion of showroom space and service bays for VWs as
well as Porsches. And new models of the New Beetle are likely to
keep interest charged _ the New Beetle BLX model with a
turbo-powered diesel engine and a speed-deployed ``spoiler'' went
on sale in late April. The convertible model is expected by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   All this hoopla does not create an emotional response in
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another new car,'' said Kelly Huffman, 29, owner of
Arlington's The Bug Stop, a repair and parts shop for the original
Beetle, those built between 1949 and 1979. ``The old ones really
look like the people's car.''
</P>
<P>
   Huffman keeps a mailing list of 15,000 registered owners of
original Beetles in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The New Beetle is a Bug body on the same chassis as the VW Golf
or Jetta. Unlike the original, the engine is water-cooled and in
the front. Six stereo speakers are standard. The glove box is
``silicone-dampered'' to prevent noisy clattering. The bud vase is
there at the request of the chairman of VW's North American region,
who recalled the ceramic vases installed in the luxury models of
European Volkswagens in the 1950s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fun stuff, the New Beetle also is earning high marks
for safety and handling, leading Motor Trend magazine to name it
its import car of the year for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just cute. When you buy a car and make the first
couple of payments, cute won't cut it,'' Pipes said.
</P>
<P>
   But cute doesn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other drivers smile and wave. They give me the peace sign,''
said Kirsten Green. She's age 32, so she never drove the original
Beetle, but when she first saw the new one, she knew it would drive
her out of what she calls her staid, white, four-door sedan world.
``It turns heads.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
