<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     05-03 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, May 4:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-KILLERS (Undated) _ In the wake of the shootings at
Columbine High School, psychiatrists say it is the fragile children
_ not sturdy ones _ who are most likely to ``break'' in dramatic
ways, according to a growing number of ``psychological autopsy''
studies of youthful suicides, and from less formal studies of
adolescents who have committed murders. At the same time, other
studies have shown that the turbulence, pathology and confusion
considered ``normal'' in adolescence are in fact far from typical.
By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, this story also lised under COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING on
the AM budget.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-FAILURE (Undated) _ The severe condition known as
congestive heart failure today is the only form of heart disease
that is on the rise in the United States. In a way, the epidemic of
congestive heart failure is good news, evidence of the progress
that has been made in saving the lives of heart attack victims and
people with other heart problems alive. About 4.9 million Americans
have heart failure, and an estimated million of them are under the
age of 60. Every year, 400,000 new cases are diagnosed, and the
condition leads to more than 800,000 hospital stays, including many
repeat visits. Congestive heart failure is the leading cause of
hospitalization in the elderly, and hospital bills accounted for
much of the $18.8 billion spent on the disease in 1998. Health
experts say the problem is getting worse. By Denise Grady. (2675
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AGING-SHUTTLES (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ America's aging
space shuttles, often criticized as monuments to 1970s technology,
are slowly being replaced by much more modern spacecraft _
themselves. Since the first one flew in 1981, the shuttles have
been steadily modified during their lifetimes, NASA engineers and
managers say, and are much more modern beneath their familiar skin
than most people realize. By Warren E. Leary. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TURTLES-ASIA (Undated) _ One of the world's great centers of
turtle and tortoise diversity, Southeast Asia has long teemed with
species found nowhere else in the world. But in recent years,
researchers say, this biological treasure trove has been converted
into a gold mine for profiteers who have been gathering every
turtle in sight for sale as food and medicinals in the turtle
markets of neighboring China. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAKING-BOMBS (Undated) _ The carnage at Littleton reportedly
caused in part by the explosion of homemade bombs highlighted the
ease of making such devices from common, easily obtainable
materials. Many lethal recipes from ``The Anarchist's Cookbook''
originally published in the 1960s, and from other public sources,
have been broadcast electronically for years, available to anyone
with a computer and access to the Internet. An essay by Malcolm W.
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RIVER-RESCUE (Undated) _ The San Pedro River is in danger of
drying up because groundwater pumping for urban development and
farms is drawing water from the river on both sides of the
U.S.-Mexico border. Saving this ``extraordinary biological treasure
chest,'' as an international panel of experts recently called the
river habitat, has become a test case for a cooperative effort
under the NAFTA to save an ecosystem shared by the two countries.
By Jon Christenson. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: on genetic
engineering of plants, long neck dinosaurs known as sauropods and a
huge undersea volcano near the Samoa Islands. By Henry Fountain.
(700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEERE-LYME (Boston) _ A Scientist-at-Work profile: Dr.
Allen Steere has been studying Lyme disease for 24 years, longer
than anyone else. He was the first to identify the ailment among a
baffling cluster of kids with swollen knees in Lyme, Conn. Over the
protests of civic leaders he gave the disease the town's name. He
led research efforts on the vaccine, then came under fire for his
theory that some people with Lyme disease suffer a post-disease
syndrome, which has prompted some insurance companies to cease
coverage. By David France. (1580 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: By the
time most compulsive gamblers seek help, they are hugely in debt,
owing anywhere from $38,000 to $120,000 and sometimes more, and
their families are a shambles. About 80 percent of problem gamblers
seriously consider suicide and 13 percent to 20 percent attempt
suicide or succeed. More than 5 million Americans are pathological
or problem gamblers, and another 15 million are at risk of falling
into the same morass, according to a study reported last month by
the National Gambling Impact Study Commission. By Jane E. Brody.
(1240 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MACULAR-DEGENERATION (Undated) _ Work in Progress: A drug
activated by shining light into the eye could offer hope for people
suffering from age-related macular degeneration, the leading cause
of severe vision loss in the elderly. By Andrew Pollack. (800
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTORS-BUSINESS (Undated) _ More and more physicians find
they are unable to deal with the complexities of today's medical
business and are returning to school to complete MBA's or enrolling
in dual business programs during medical school. By Adam Nagourney.
(1025 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-CYCLO-CROSS (Undated) _ Cyclo-cross, a combination
of mountain biking and steeplechasing, is catching on among fitness
advocates. Participants ride laps over a narrow loop that is filled
with technical challenges like logs, sand pits, mud puddles, and
man-made obstacles. The courses travel over soggy meadows, stream
beds, and dirt trails; no more than half the distance may traverse
paved road. Riders often hop off their bikes, sling them over their
shoulders, and sprint over unbikable terrain on foot. By Liz
Neporent. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Short items on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pro and con: Is sunlight exposure the best means of achieving
optimal body levels of vitamin D? (200 word each side).
</P>
<P>
   _ At altitudes above 8,000 feet, people need to consume double
the water they would at sea level, yet a survey of 126 hikers on a
popular 14.5-mile trail elevated over 10,000 feet found that only 1
percent carried a sufficient water load, a half liter per hour of
walking, according to a recent study. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Most parents of toddlers and preschoolers try to be careful
about what they serve their children to avoid choking. But a report
presented last week at a meeting of the American Society of
Pediatric Otolaryngology warned that meals served to young children
outside the home may present an even greater choking risk.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLOOD-PRESSURE (Undated) _ People with high blood pressure
often fail to respond to medication, leading their doctors to
prescribe more and more pills for them. Instead, doctors should
help them remember to take the pills they already have, an
international expert in blood pressure control said last week. By
Abigail Zuger, M.D. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Why do so many
teen-agers have trouble waking up in the morning? Is there any way
to train yourself to make getting up at 7 a.m. easier? Morning
sleepiness may have a cause as simple as lack of sleep. The
solution may be to cut down on some sleep-robbing activities and
gradually change bedtime and waking time in 15-minute increments
until the person wakes refreshed at a desirable time. (300 words)
</P>
