<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMANTEC-CEO-HNS &LR;      05-03 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMANTEC-CEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CEO TOUTS FUTURE OF SOFTWARE MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. _ John W. Thompson, the new chief executive of
Symantec Corp. was hitting his conference table with the flat of
his hand, his voice rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be a poster boy. I will not. I will NOT. I WILL
NOT!''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson drove home the point that he refuses to become, in his
words, ``the poster boy for African-Americans in Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering these sentiments, the announcement of Thompson's
appointment to run the Silicon Valley's seventh largest software
maker couldn't have come at a worse time.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Symantec announced Thompson's appointment last
month, the Rev. Jesse Jackson had barnstormed through Silicon
Valley, announcing that his civil rights organization was going to
concentrate and publicizing the Silicon Valley's ``digital divide''
_ what Jackson sees as the exclusion of minorities from the revved
up high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who had spent the last 28 years climbing through IBM's
executive ranks, soon found himself being asked for comment on
Jackson's initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse Jackson's presence in the Valley had not a thing to do
with my appointment,'' said Thompson, a graduate of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``It had nothing to do with
the color of my skin.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment echoed by Carl Carman, a Symantec director
based in Boulder, Colo. ``We hired him because of his strong
background in software sales and marketing, and for his incredible
leadership abilities. Not because of his ethnic background.''
</P>
<P>
   And considering Thompson's take on the alleged ``divide,''
Jackson may want to reconsider enlisting his help.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that's fueled on the intellectual capital
of the people it can hire,'' said Thompson, 50. ``Considering that,
I can't imagine this industry being exclusionary in any way.
That's, well, that's just idiotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who 28 years ago stood out in the early blue-suited
sales army at IBM (``I had a large mustache and even larger afro'')
believes that the lack of minorities in Silicon Valley industries
stems from the small number of minorities graduating with math and
science degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the fundamental reason that needs to be investigated,''
Thompson said. ``I don't think it has something to do with industry
leadership supposedly biased against African-Americans or
Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he would focus on pushing Symantec into the
future. He hinted during an interview that his strategy includes a
consolidation of Symantec's software publishing efforts, currently
spread out over a number of best-selling software titles, including
Norton Utilities and anti-virus software. But some brands, such as
its pcCommute, have been weak performers, and anti-virus software
publisher Network Associates has been spending heavily to promote
itself as an alternative to Symantec's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we sit where we are, we'll be a tombstone,'' Thompson said.
``The expectations of me, with a supportive board, is to now take
the company somewhere different.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he might concentrate some of those future efforts
on embedded computer chips and handheld personal computers, a
growing market segment ignored by the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll find out over the next few weeks and months what our
plans are,'' Thompson said. ``We're going to pick some things to
concentrate on, areas that I want us to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chief executive inherits a fairly healthy company, in
financial terms. Last Thursday, Symantec reported earnings of 44
cents per share for its fourth quarter ending April 2. The report
exceeded expectations. The company earned $25 million (before
one-time charges) on $175.6 million in sales for the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In its third quarter, Symantec earned $24 million on $156.1
million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's announced strategies are already drawing praise from
industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symantec has a great brand name and some key products,'' said
Alex Cutler, a New York analyst who's followed Symantec for a
number of years. ``Now one of the challenges they face is to tie it
all together in a comprehensive message.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Thompson's heritage was at IBM, and Symantec is
very lucky to have him on board at this point in time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
