<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-FOOD-LIST-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOUTHERN-STYLE RESTAURANTS IN AND AROUND THE NATIONAL CAPITAL
 &HT;    With SOUTHERN-FOOD-LIST. Moving in (t) travel and (d) food
categories for release Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expensive (most dinner entrees $15 and up):
</P>
<P>
   B. Smith's. Gumbos and such. Owned by former supermodel Barbara
Smith. Union Station, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Brown's. Frogmore stew and other low-country dishes.
Southern Swank. 950 15th Street NW, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Vidalia. Shrimp 'n Grits and other creations of Chef Jeff Buben.
1990 M Street NW, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate (most dinner entrees $8 to $15):
</P>
<P>
   Music City Roadhouse. Family-style dining and Redneck Chic. 1050
30th Street NW, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Old Glory Barbecue. Smoke-flavored ribs, brisket, shrimp and
chicken. 3130 M Street NW, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Red, Hot and Blue. Memphis-style ribs and pulled pork
sandwiches. Various locations in Washington and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   RT's. Crawfish and other Cajun cooking. 3804 Mount Vernon Ave.,
Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Southside 815. Sweet potato biscuits and Virginia ham. 815 S.
Washington St., Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive (most dinner entrees $5 to $8):
</P>
<P>
   Black-Eyed Pea. Traditional ``meat and three'' vegetables.
Various locations in suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Avenue Grill. Super soul food. 1100 Florida Ave. NW,
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
