<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2374 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-LIST-HNS &LR;      05-03 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S MISSING FROM THE `GREAT BOOKS' LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Like the lists that came before it, the Modern
Library's list of the 100 best English-language works of non
fiction this century begs for argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cold Blood'' at No. 96? No Cornelius Ryan? No ``Let Us Now
Praise Famous Men''? ``The Education of Henry Adams'' _ read by
only a handful outside the walls of academe _ rated No. 1? A raft
of obscure works nudging better-known and better-loved books off
the list? It doesn't make much sense.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than hem and haw over the list, how about just
throwing together another list, one that splits time between
nonfiction classics and odd, backwater books that have never lost
their ability to bring a smile or a raised eyebrow?
</P>
<P>
   How about a quick list of 50, easily found in most libraries or
yard sales or in the sale bin at used book stores, and well worth a
read?
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library panel, in trying to rectify the mistakes of
its fiction list, insisted no nonfiction writer be given more than
one title and added two women, a black author and two younger
writers to its judges.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, though, came up with a list that feels pressed-in and
ponderous, heavy on academic reading and light on the more
enjoyable nonfiction books of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best writing of the century came in English travel
books between the wars, but the Modern Library list offers no
titles. This list does. Only one sports book _ ``The Sweet
Science'' by A.J. Liebling _ is included by the Modern Library.
This list corrects that.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library spurns movies, music, the best-written books
from World War II and Vietnam, and biographies in general.
</P>
<P>
   This list doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   It had no chance of making the Modern Library list, but surely
there is a place in the best English-language nonfiction books of
the century for Daniel Taylor's ``Spiritua America.'' The former
railroad man and war veteran, writing through University Publishers
in Los Angeles in 1974, uses the English language in a way that
continues to surprise and delight.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of books like that on this list, using the
English language in a way that brings a chuckle and wheeze and
sometimes a catch in the throat _ lacking, perhaps, in the pure
information offered by the Modern Library, but making up for it in
song and wallow.
</P>
<P>
   Additions to the list of the 100 best works of English-language
nonfiction in the 20th century, in no particular order:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men, James Agee and Walker Evans.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Army of the Potomac,'' Bruce Catton.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``A Bridge Too Far,'' Cornelius Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Hot Countries,'' Alec Waugh.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``The Summer Game,'' Roger Angell.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Dispatches,'' Michael Herr.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Brave Men,'' Ernie Pyle.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``By-Line: Ernest Hemingway.''
</P>
<P>
   9. ``The Shadow of Blooming Grove,'' Francis Russell.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Fear and Loathing on the Campaign Trail '72,'' Hunter S.
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   11. ``We Played the Game,'' edited by Danny Peary.
</P>
<P>
   12. ``Mystery Train,'' Greil Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   13. ``The First Day on the Somme,'' Martin Middlebrook.
</P>
<P>
   14. ``Here Lies Eric Ambler,'' by Eric Ambler.
</P>
<P>
   15. ``Muhammad Ali,'' Wilfred Sheed.
</P>
<P>
   16. ``Barbarossa,'' Alan Clark.
</P>
<P>
   17. ``Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance,'' Robert M.
Pirsig.
</P>
<P>
   18. ``The Executioner's Song,'' Norman Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   19. ``The Name Above the Title,'' Frank Capra.
</P>
<P>
   20. ``Revolt in the Desert,'' T.E. Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   21. ``From the Dreadnought to Scapa Flow,'' A.J. Marder.
</P>
<P>
   22. ``Kent State,'' James A. Michener.
</P>
<P>
   23. ``Baseball When the Grass Was Real,'' Donald Honig.
</P>
<P>
   24. ``Son of the Morning Star,'' Evan S. Connell.
</P>
<P>
   25. ``The Sea and the Jungle,'' H.M. Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   26. ``All the President's Men,'' Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   27. ``The Glory and the Dream,'' William Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   28. ``Glass Houses: Ten Years of Free-Lancing,'' Carleton Beals.
</P>
<P>
   29. ``Huey Long,'' T. Harry Williams.
</P>
<P>
   30. ``The Epic of America,'' James Truslow Adams.
</P>
<P>
   31. ``This Kind of War,'' T.R. Fehrenbach.
</P>
<P>
   32. ``Spiritua America,'' Daniel Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   33. ``Some Desperate Glory,'' Edwin Campion Vaughan.
</P>
<P>
   34. ``Reporting Vietnam,'' The Library of America.
</P>
<P>
   35. ``The Gentleman in the Parlour: A Record of a Journey From
Rangoon to Haiphong,'' W. Somerset Maugham.
</P>
<P>
   36. ``The Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test,'' Tom Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   37. ``When the Movies Were Young,'' Linda Arvidson (Mrs. D.W.
Griffith).
</P>
<P>
   38. ``A Distant Mirror,'' Barbara Tuchman.
</P>
<P>
   39. ``European Journey,'' Philip Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   40. ``Berlin Diary,'' William L. Shirer.
</P>
<P>
   41. ``The Diary of Anne Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   42. ``The Second World War (Volumes 1-6),'' Winston Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   43. ``The Best and the Brightest,'' David Halberstam.
</P>
<P>
   44. ``The Boys of Summer,'' Roger Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   45. ``The Rising Sun (Volumes 1 and 2),'' John Toland.
</P>
<P>
   46. ``The Rise and the Fall of the Third Reich,'' William L.
Shirer.
</P>
<P>
   47. ``900 Days: The Siege of Leningrad,'' Harrison E. Salisbury.
</P>
<P>
   48. ``Rumor of War,'' Philip Caputo.
</P>
<P>
   49. ``Citizen Hearst,'' W.A. Swanberg.
</P>
<P>
   50. ``Soul of a New Machine,'' Tracy Kidder.
</P>
</TEXT>
