<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
 CITY STAR BUDGET-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City Star budget offers for Tuesday, May 4
</P>
<P>
   ISO _ American isolationism has deep currents that are surfacing
in the debate over how to prosecute the Yugoslavian war. Scott
Canon and Rick Montgomery. 35.
</P>
<P>
   CIG: Opening statements expected today in the federal court
trial that pits the family of Charles Steele against Brown &AMP;
Williamson. The trial evidence will include some secret company
memos that the Vandalia, Mo., family contends will show the
cigarette maker knew about the dangers of its product. The $25
million suit is the first to go to trial in Kansas City. Steele, a
longtime smoker of Kools, died of cancer in 1995. Mark Morris. 20.
</P>
<P>
   NUGROC: An inner-city Kansas City church takes on a local grocer
that parishioners claim is expensive and dirty, but they have to
patronize because it's the only source of food in the neighborhood.
The church is St. Therese Little Flower, 58th and Euclid; the store
is Metro Super Thriftway, 63rd and the Paseo. Jeff Spivak. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: Possible story on Missouri Senate approving ``partial
birth'' abortion bill. If it is more wrangling with no resolution
will probably keep it short. Other possibility is short story on
negotiators reaching agreement on how to allocate family planning
dollars. That is part of the budget, which has to be done by Friday
at 6 p. m. That too could trigger a new round of abortion
arguments, especially since the well has been poisoned over the
same issue in the Senate. Will Sentell. 15 inches.
</P>
<P>
   LOGAN: It's not fair that one of Kansas City's most memorable
doctors might be best remembered for taking an ax to construction
equipment and then going to jail with a flower in his lapel. But a
1939 jailhouse photo is part of a new exhibit on Logan Clendening
at the University of Kansas Medical Center. He was a renaissance
man: Writer, doctor, friend of Hemingway and Mencken, collector of
rare medical books that make up the Clendening Library at KU
Medical Center. But he wasn't altogether well-adjusted. Brian
Burnes.
</P>
<P>
   ATF (would move late): The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms will conduct a seminar for Kansas City area school
administrators on how to handle bomb threats and how to develop a
bomb incident plan. The Monday night program is in response to
requests following the Colorado shootings. The seminar will be from
7 to 10 p.m. Photo. Richard Espinoza.
</P>
<P>
   GRAVES _ In the end, Kansas Gov. Bill Graves carried the day,
pushing through a transportation plan and delivering another
stinging defeat to conservative Republicans who had fought any talk
of a tax increase. John L. Petterson and John A. Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   NICHE _ Some Kansas City area farmers find their niche in
specialty crops -- yuppie food, organics, etc. By Eric Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB (Tentative) _ What does it cost the public when someone
calls in a bomb scare? Julius Karash and others.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM _ About 1,000 government telcommunications managers are
in Kansas City this week for a conference to learn more about what
Sprint and MCI have to offer in terms of new services. The
conference today also features Vinton Cerf, the so-called Father of
the Internet. By Ted Sickinger, with PHOTO
</P>
</TEXT>
