<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, May 4.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (Denver) _ Doings at the Star Wars Celebration in
Denver. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS (New York) _ The Tony Award nominations are announced. By
Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   PAINTERS-EYE (London) _ Can artistic talent be measured
scientifically? A laughable notion, perhaps. And yet, according to
``The Painter's Eye,'' an intriguing small show at the National
Portrait Gallery in London that runs through June 13, some of the
secrets of the creative process are now being cracked by the latest
biomedical technology. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   SWAN-BALLET-REVIEW (New York) _ The NYC Ballet's ``Swan Lake''
at the New York State Theater. Reviewed by Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Another World'' by Pat Barker
(Farrar, Straus, Giroux). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Media Matters''; and, on HBO,
the TV film, ``Thug Life in D.C.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
