<HEADER>
A2436 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-UNIONS-840(2     05-03 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-UNIONS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR-MANAGEMENT CLASHES MAY GROUND AIRLINES AS PROFITS CONTINUE TO
SOAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Things are tough all over _ at least for
airline executives who are responsible for maintaining working
relationships with their unions.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is still hovering near the peak of its best profits
ever. Not surprisingly, workers industrywide are clamoring for a
larger _ and, they believe, fairer _ share of the profits. And many
workers are doing much more than just clamoring.
</P>
<P>
   At all but a few carriers, labor has quickly moved to _ and
sometimes beyond _ the saber-rattling stage. American Airlines, for
example, piled up millions of dollars in losses after a pilots
sickout in February.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some industry experts and long-term observers believe
the U.S. airline industry, which has never been known for peaceful
labor relations, has perhaps entered the most contentious
environment ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 20 years of doing this, this is the most difficult
period of labor management negotiations and relations I've ever
seen,'' said Jerrold Glass, Washington-based labor relations
consultant to airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, George Hopkins, a Western Illinois University history
professor and author of two books on pilots unions, agrees that
``there is something new in this current and soon-upcoming spate of
labor negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been raw feelings between management and labor in
the airline industry many, many times,'' Hopkins said. ``I can't
really tell you all the reasons why, but it does seem there's more
of that now than at any time in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick review of recent disputes at major airlines tends to
bear that out.
</P>
<P>
   _In September, the Air Line Pilots Association conducted a
15-day strike against Northwest Airlines. Northwest lost more than
$400 million because of the strike and is still struggling to win
back alienated passengers.
</P>
<P>
   _In February, members of the Allied Pilots Association conducted
a sickout against American Airlines that forced the company to
cancel 6,700 flights and cost it about $225 million. Ostensibly,
the dispute was over American's plans for integrating the pilots of
the recently acquired Reno Air into American's corps. However, it
was the latest hostility to erupt between the pilots and
management, after a brief strike in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _A few weeks after the pilots sickout, a flight attendants
strike at America West was averted at the last moment when
management capitulated to union demands rather than lose even more
money because of a job action.
</P>
<P>
   _Last month, Delta Air Lines' management canceled delivery of
four Boeing 777s after Air Line Pilots Association leaders opened
talks on pay rates for pilots flying the aircraft by demanding a
pay rate 47 percent higher than what American pays its 777 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   _And just last week, Alaska Airlines, whose operations were
sporadically disrupted during the last two years in mini-strikes by
its flight attendants, had to cancel about 10 percent of its
flights because of what management described as a slowdown by
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only carriers not caught up in or headed for a
significant labor dispute are United, Southwest and Continental.
United's parent, UAL Corp., is 52 percent owned by United
employees. And Southwest and Continental have their unions locked
into long-term contracts, with the exception of Continental's
flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, at least 15 major union contracts are already up for
re-negotiation, or will come up for re-negotiation during the next
15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry experts say it's not hard to figure the
reasons behind the gathering labor storm in the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 1999 being the sixth consecutive year of strong earnings,
it is not surprising at all that airline labor is demanding its
piece of the profit pie,'' said Julius Maldutis at CIBC
Oppenheimer, the dean of Wall Street's airline analysts. ``The
central theme in the industry over the next two years or so is
going to be trying to find a way to achieve labor peace. And that's
just going to be difficult to do.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, how airline managements handle labor's demands will
be a key variable in how markets value airline securities,'' said
Maldutis, who two weeks ago downgraded his rating on Delta shares
to a ``hold'' because of ``the uncertainty surrounding labor
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the big profits, the current state of airline labor
relations is also a natural outcome of the transformation that
began 21 years ago with the Airline Deregulation Act, said Hopkins,
who generally sides with labor.
</P>
<P>
   The Railway Labor Act of 1926, which governs airline labor
relations, was passed during a ``very conservative era, dominated
by people like Calvin Coolidge and Warren Harding,'' Hopkins said.
``They were worried about the impact on the economy of strikes by
the transportation unions. So the Railway Labor Act makes it very,
very difficult for transportation unions to strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, on balance it has worked out very well for the unions
because their contracts never expire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means companies can't replace workers very easily. So
when a contract opens up for re-negotiation, the workers can keep
their jobs and use all sorts of methods to bring economic pressure
on the companies. Eventually, it becomes more cost-effective for
managements to cut a deal giving the unions most of what they want
than it is to continue suffering the losses caused by union members
withdrawing their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the transportation union members are the
highest-paid union members in America relative to what they could
earn with their same set of skills in other industries,'' Hopkins
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress deregulated the airline industry, fostering
aggressive competition and a new imperative to control spending, it
didn't alter the Railway Labor Act, he added.
</P>
<P>
   And because labor is one of the few areas of costs that
management can exercise some control over, a period of intense
labor-management conflict became inevitable. All that was needed,
Hopkins said, was for the industry to remain significantly
profitable long enough for all the union's contracts to come up for
renegotiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a labor regulatory environment designed to work in
a regulated environment now being applied in a very profitable,
deregulated environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding matters, Hopkins added, is the high level of
distrust that has built up between management and labor as airlines
scrambled to rein in their high costs in the post-deregulation era
and unions fretted about both job security issues and retaining
their relatively high pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, who openly sides with airline managements, agreed that
dynamics of the competitive and labor regulatory regimes are
pushing both sides toward confrontation more than ever before. And
the industry's own growth and success, he said, are exacerbating
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very large number of employees in this industry have never
been through a down cycle or a furlough period like the airlines
typically see,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last downturn in the early 1990s was the worst ever in
terms of financial losses. But it wasn't the worst downturn in
terms of its impact on jobs lost. Plus, a lot of people now in the
industry, especially those on the ground operations side of the
business, have been hired since 1992 and simply don't understand
how bad things can get in a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managements have to negotiate contracts with one eye on the
next downturn,'' he said. ``But many workers' expectations are so
unrealistic. They did their givebacks or gave concessions in the
early 1990s and everybody wants their big paybacks now. There's no
patience. The idea seems to be to get it all now while the getting
is good because nobody knows when the next downturn is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
