<HEADLINE>
CHEAPER DRUG COCKTAIL CAN TREAT AFRICAN HIV  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MAY 3, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By MICHAEL DAY  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A century-old drug has emerged as a rare source of optimism in
the face of Africa's rampaging AIDS epidemic. Trials in southern
Africa have shown that hydroxyurea, in combination with an existing
HIV drug, could be a cheap alternative to the expensive drug
cocktails pitted against the virus in the developed world.
</P>
<P>
   In rich countries, many HIV-positive people have ''triple
therapy'' _ drug combinations that inhibit two key viral enzymes,
HIV protease and reverse transcriptase. Thanks to these drugs, many
seriously ill patients have been able to resume normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   But at around $12,000 a year, triple therapy is beyond African
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the continent most affected by HIV, this is pie in the
sky,'' says Steve Miller, who runs a private HIV clinic in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting organized by the Research Institute for Genetic and
Human Therapy in Washington, D.C., Miller and another southern
African research group last week showed that there is a more
affordable alternative _ the combination of a low dose of ddI,
which inhibits reverse transcriptase, and hydroxyurea, which is
sometimes used to treat leukemia and sickle-cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Hydroxyurea has been investigated as a possible AIDS treatment
for several years. Unlike existing drugs, it does not inhibit
specific viral enzymes. Instead, it slows down the synthesis of
nucleic acids and also blocks the activation of the CD4 white blood
cells in which the virus replicates.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has tested the drug combination on 127 AIDS patients,
both men and women. In 68 percent of them, levels of HIV in their
blood became undetectable within 24 weeks, and stayed that way.
Levels of CD4 cells rose significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was with some scepticism I started this experiment,''
Miller says. ''But I think this regimen gave very satisfactory
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Dickinson, who runs an AIDS clinic in Gaborone, Botswana,
has tested the double drug combination on 150 patients. ''The
results were remarkable,'' she says. ''Most of my patients were
extremely ill and unable to work. But after treatment most of them
were working again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson's patients had to pay for their own blood tests, and
not all of them could afford to do so. But of the 98 who were
tested, nearly 70 percent had levels of HIV below the threshold
detectable by basic assay equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Per head, the annual health care budget in Botswana is about
$1600. A year's supply of the new treatment costs $1200, of which
$1100 is the cost of the ddI.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is a tenth of the cost of triple therapy, it is
still a daunting sum for Botswana. Dickinson now wants Bristol
Myers Squibb, which makes ddI, to cut its prices in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The company could not provide a spokesperson to comment, but has
until now been reluctant to make the drug available more cheaply.
''They haven't lowered their prices because they say it will start
a black market,'' says Dickinson. ''This is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug combination does have side effects. Dickinson saw
reduced production of blood cells in some patients, but this was
serious in only 8 percent of cases. Some of Miller's patients had
darkened skin and nails. ''But overall the side effect profile is
rather good and no worse than one would see with anything else in
treating HIV infection,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, interest in hydroxyurea is also growing in the
developed world. Some AIDS specialists are using it as a
''salvage'' treatment when other drugs have failed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
