<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2446 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTER-LCD-DISPLAYS-(     05-03 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTER-LCD-DISPLAYS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MAY 3, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEW LCDs RETAIN IMAGE WITHOUT POWER   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By PAUL MARKS  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A liquid crystal display that keeps on showing its last image
even when someone has pulled the plug will eat up less power and
extend the battery life of cell phones, palmtops and laptop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Where safety is paramount, such as intensive care or aircraft
instruments, a screen that can retain the last display before power
loss would be invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, researchers put the new LCD though its paces at the
Defense Evaluation and Research Agency (DERA) in Malvern,
Worcestershire. The LCD saves power by switching itself off after
it has displayed the same image for a preset time. Conventional LCD
screens need a constant power supply, but the new device only draws
power when the screen is updated with new data.
</P>
<P>
   When an electric field is applied to a standard LCD, it changes
the orientation of rod-like molecules in a liquid crystal substance
_ and this in turn changes the polarization of light passing
through them. So each cell, or pixel, can switch from light to dark
_ but only as long as you maintain the appropriate voltage: lose
the power and the image disappears. Such devices are called
monostable LCDs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier attempts to develop a bistable LCD that hangs onto its
last image have only had limited success, according to Guy
Bryan-Brown, lead researcher in the displays group at DERA. A class
of materials known as ferroelectric LCDs initially looked promising
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue with ferroelectrics is their severe sensitivity to
shock,'' Bryan-Brown says. Unlike standard liquid crystals which
can align their molecules in three dimensions, ferroelectrics are
fluid in two dimensions and crystalline in only one. This means
that when subjected to knocks, ferroelectrics lose their
orientation and consequently any image they are displaying.
</P>
<P>
   DERA's answer is to use a tiny corrugated electrode _ like a
diffraction grating _ to encourage the rod-like molecules to stay
put. The grating aligns the molecules nearest to it in a preferred
direction that depends on both the grating geometry and the applied
voltage. By experimenting with the parameters of the undulating
grating surface, DERA's researchers have made the bistable LCD
shockproof.
</P>
<P>
   ''The liquid crystal wets the grating surface and is in intimate
contact with it, so the molecules never actually leave the grooves
of the corrugations, even when subjected to shock,'' Bryan-Brown
says.
</P>
<P>
   DERA says bistable displays in pagers could eat up to 1000 times
less energy, while cell phone displays could draw up to 100 times
less power. Bryan-Brown says the new LCDs could be made cheaply
using the same foil stamping techniques that already produce
millions of holograms for credit cards. Built into a cash card, the
unpowered LCD could continually display your bank balance, and
could simply be updated by cash machines.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
