<HEADER>
A2455 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-SEX-TEX     05-03 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-SEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATION OF CHURCH AND SEXUALITY NOT HEALTHY, MINISTER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too many pulpits are silent about sex _ especially if it
involves discussions of condoms or abortion, says the Rev. James L.
Demus III. And he is trying to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to break the silence about human sexuality and
reproductive health in your church,'' Demus told a group of about
30 Fort Worth religious leaders recently. ``If you have 100 members
in your church, you will have 10 or 15 who have sexuality issues
related to abortion, condoms or other matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Demus, pastor of the Park Manor Christian Church in Chicago,
openly discusses even the most controversial of topics in his
500-member congregation. During a sermon on ``Sex and Society,'' he
tossed out condoms from his pulpit to emphasize that such
protection is needed to help prevent sexually transmitted diseases,
such as AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people thought it was the greatest thing in the
world, but some of the older people were asking, `What's going
on?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Demus addressed a meeting sponsored by Planned Parenthood of
North Texas to launch an effort to enlist local religious
authorities in presenting broad-based information about birth
control, abortion and other subjects related to human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are establishing a group called Clergy for Responsible
Choices,'' said Michael Comini, executive director of Planned
Parenthood's Tarrant County office. Its goal will be to establish a
forum for faith leaders to discuss birth control and other subjects
related to human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservative faith groups have begun to offer sex education
materials, but many do not include discussions about condoms or
birth control pills on grounds that it might promote premarital
sex. Also, many of those groups teach that abortion is unbiblical
and immoral.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a popular Southern Baptist program for teen-agers,
called True Love Waits, has young people sign a pledge that they
will refrain from sexual intercourse before marriage. Program
leaders do not discuss contraception, though.
</P>
<P>
   Demus agrees with the biblical ideal of abstinence. But he said
faith groups need to be more realistic and realize that many
unmarried people do not abstain from sex and that decisions on
abortion are very complicated and involve different situations with
each individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became pro-choice about 10 years ago when a 13-year-old
girl, who was pregnant, came to me asking for advice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pastors, priests and rabbis who present artificial contraception
and abortion as choices for individuals will face much opposition
from anti-abortion conservative Christian leaders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dangerous work,'' he said, referring to the violence
that has sometimes erupted at abortion clinics. ``But it's worth
it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Fort Worth session, Rabbi Ralph Mecklenburger, leader
of Congregation Beth-El, a Reform Jewish congregation, said the
idea of artificial contraception and abortion is not as
controversial as some might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of America's population is pro-choice; so are a
majority of Catholics,'' Mecklenburger said. ``The Religious Right,
self-destructively, has hurt its own candidates on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Comini said he hopes religious leaders will work with Planned
Parenthood to sponsor workshops and other programs concerning all
issues surrounding human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Goddard, founding director of a sex education program that
has been presented to religious groups since the early 1980s,
agrees that the church is too silent on issues of human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of churches offering sex education is increasing,
though,'' said Goddard, founding director of Christian Life
Enrichment Sources, based in Kingswood, near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Goddard is best known for weeklong sex education summer camps in
Texas and New Mexico attended by young people who are entering the
ninth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a biblically based program that presents abstinence as
God's ideal,'' she said. ``But we have sessions on birth control,
anatomy, levels of sexual arousal, oral sex, abortion and other
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen Texas congregations, mostly aligned with Christian
Churches (Disciples of Christ,) send teens to the summer camps, she
said. Presbyterians, United Methodists and other mainline Christian
groups also participate.
</P>
<P>
   Goddard, a Presbyterian, believes sexual intimacy is a gift of
God, and that churches, synagogues and mosques are the appropriate
places for information about that gift to be taught.
</P>
<P>
   Demus echoed that thought, and said if faith groups don't teach
about sex, young people will get most of their knowledge about it
from movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
