<TEXT>
<P>
   BRECKENRIDGE AND ODESSA, TEXAS _ In the 1920s, it was hard to
keep people out of Breckenridge. These days, it is harder to get
them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   A town that once boasted the world's most prolific oil
production and was a Mecca for ``wildcatters'' looking for an
instant fortune is now home to only a handful of oil producers
determined to eke out a living on what is left under the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Arnot, a third-generation oil engineer who is one of the
handful, speculates that there is very little future for a town
that depends so heavily on the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a good look around,'' he says. ``Pretty soon this place
is going to look like `The Last Picture Show.'''
</P>
<P>
   In common with hundreds of towns throughout the Texas and
Oklahoma Oil Patch, Breckenridge has been hit hard by a two-year
plunge in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   As cheap foreign oil floods the American market, driving the
price to an all-time low, domestic producers have had to sell their
oil at a price far below what it costs them to operate their wells.
</P>
<P>
   Although prices in recent weeks have rebounded from their low of
$10 a barrel last December, over the past year 50,000 oil-industry
jobs in the United States have been lost and 140,000 unprofitable
wells have had to be plugged.
</P>
<P>
   Worst-affected have been the smaller producers in the Oil Patch
who operate so-called ``stripper'' wells. These high-cost wells,
which produce fewer than ten barrels a day, account for 20 percent
of domestic oil production.
</P>
<P>
   All over Texas, small family companies that have kept three
generations going have been forced into bankruptcy by the long
depression in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, representatives of independent producers lobbied
Congress for emergency relief. Yet few are optimistic that federal
aid will save their way of life.
</P>
<P>
   When small producers suffer, so do the towns they live in. As
businesses in west and central Texas go bust and families leave the
area in search of jobs elsewhere, the shrinking tax base has
devastated local schools, hospitals and government offices.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephens County, where Breckenridge sits, 1999 tax revenues
from the oil industry are projected to be only $112 million, down
from $146 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The school district has lost 10 percent of its pupils, along
with the state dollars that go with them.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Oil Patch are used to cyclical recessions, and
the 1986 crash in oil prices was more dramatic than the recent
slump _ not least because oil was the only way to make a living
then.
</P>
<P>
   Yet oil producers now fear that the diversification of the Texas
economy (along with a greater reliance on foreign oil) has made
lawmakers less concerned with the plight of the domestic oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In little over a decade, the microchip has replaced the oil
derrick as the driving force behind the state's economy, making
Texas far less dependent on stable commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   In March, unemployment in the state was at 4.5 percent, the
lowest for that month in 19 years. In Odessa, however, a city in
the oil-reliant Permian Basin, it was 10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Oil Patch now feels left behind and discontented; and it has
found a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On April 14 Pat Buchanan, that steel-ribbed nationalist and
perennial candidate for the Republican presidential nomination,
went to Odessa and vowed to make the United States free of ``cheap
foreign oil.''
</P>
<P>
   On the home turf of Governor George W. Bush, the Republican
front-runner, Buchanan's message drew rousing applause.
</P>
<P>
   Even with oil prices recovering from their 1998 lows, many in
the industry believe that the damage done to independent companies
may be irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of producers have gone bankrupt during the crisis, and
the wells that have been plugged can be reopened only at great
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, as foreign oil each year represents a larger slice
of American consumption, the market share of domestic producers
continues to slip.
</P>
<P>
   According to one industry analyst, independent producers may
``survive the surgery, but die of pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most worrying consequence of the past two years is
that declining revenues have forced oil companies to cut their
exploration budgets.
</P>
<P>
   If oil firms stop searching for new sites, it is likely that
domestic production will shrink over the next few years as the
present wells dry up. This could prolong the misery for smaller oil
companies, and hasten the decline of even more small Texas towns.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it could bring the end of an era that began in 1923,
when the first gusher gushed in west Texas. Its owners named the
well ``Santa Rita,'' after the patron saint of desperate causes. &QL; 
