<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO'S-ADULT-TOYS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE NATO'S `SMART' WEAPONS SIMPLY TOO CLEVER?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent, provocative 850-word ``separate buy'' article is
from the current (week beginning 1 May 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight years ago, the American bombing of Iraq introduced a
fascinated public to the notion of weapons so ``smart'' that they
could weave their way through the labyrinths of central Baghdad
before unleashing their load with deadly accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The arsenal deployed in that war was kids' stuff, defense buffs
now say. Less than a tenth of the bombs dropped were
precision-guided, whereas nearly all the weapons now being aimed at
Yugoslavia are equipped that way.
</P>
<P>
   Why, in that case, has the air campaign not been more
successful? After five weeks of war, NATO says it has wrecked
Serbia's oil-refining capacity and taken bites out of several other
industries, from tank-repair factories to producers of vacuum
cleaners and cars.
</P>
<P>
   It has destroyed six out of the seven bridges over the Danube
that link Serbia with points north.
</P>
<P>
   General Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, said this week his
bombers had inflicted ``moderate to severe'' damage on the Yugoslav
forces' communications and, by attacking roads and railways, had
made it much harder for them to send fresh troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains possible, he admits, for troops to ``walk through
the rivers and gullies and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could NATO stop the dispatch to Kosovo, over the past few
days, of a few thousand newly mobilized reservists _ to replace
combat casualties, says the general.
</P>
<P>
   However patchy these achievements may sound, professional airmen
say that the bombers of Serbia have performed competently. When
targets have been pinpointed, they have invariably been well
struck.
</P>
<P>
   But there is the rub: finding things to bomb is hard when NATO
is under strong pressure to avoid either losing aircraft or killing
civilians _ and all the obvious targets have been hit already. At a
``safe'' altitude of 5,000 meters (16,250 feet), identifying
targets is often impossible.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, say pundits, it has been a ``good war'' for weapons
guided from space _ or to be precise, by America's Global
Positioning System (GPS), a network of satellites created by the
Pentagon and used by civilian navigators from all countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the other sort of smart weapon _ laser-guided munitions _
has been a disappointment because it cannot be used accurately in
cloudy or smoky conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The limits of laser guidance were highlighted tragically this
week by the accidental bombing of Surdulica, a town near Serbia's
border with Bulgaria, where at least 16 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is preparing to deploy a warhead known as
``Enhanced Paveway,'' which is guided by both satellites and
lasers. The GPS would be used to bring it through the clouds, and
only in the final stage would the laser actually be turned on.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem has been that GPS-guided weapons are in short
supply, though the Pentagon is scrambling to speed up deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, commanders are crying out for more devices known
as JDAMs _ joint direct attack munitions _ which can be strapped on
to ``dumb bombs'' and then steered by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   At only $20,000 each, JDAMs are better value than cruise
missiles _ also guided by satellite _ which can cost up to $1
million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   An ideal aircraft for delivering these smartened-up munitions is
the giant B-2 bomber, which can direct 16 of them at different
targets simultaneously, even in quite bad weather. But the B-2
itself is so expensive (at more than $2 billion) and so
embarrassing to lose that it can be sent into action only very
cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Given the drawbacks of using air power alone, and the continuing
reluctance to make ground troops fight their way in, is there a
halfway house?
</P>
<P>
   American forces in Albania seem to be preparing to mount a sort
of land intervention without ever quite touching the ground.
</P>
<P>
   They have at last deployed, after several weeks' delay, a fleet
of 24 Apache helicopters (one of which crashed soon after arriving
at Tirana, Albania's capital) and a deadly form of artillery known
as Multiple Launch Rocket Systems (MLRS).
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a lingering fear that the Apaches _ each of
which carries 16 Hellfire antitank missiles with a range of eight
kilometers (five miles) _ could be vulnerable to hand-held
surface-to-air missiles, with which guerrillas brought down so many
Soviet helicopters in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   As for the MLRS artillery systems, which would be used in close
cooperation with the Apaches, their showers of ``steel rain'' could
kill huge numbers of Serbian troops.
</P>
<P>
   But since bombs which go astray or fail to explode immediately
are not primed to destroy themselves (as, for example, smart mines
are), they could also kill western soldiers if left in the path of
a NATO advance.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Apache and the MLRS will be ruthlessly effective if
NATO (maybe with the help of special forces or ethnic-Albanian
guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army) can clearly see Yugoslav
troop concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite the smartness of their eyes-in-the-sky (for
example, the J-STARS air-to-ground surveillance which America wants
Europe to buy), NATO's commanders still seem unsure where exactly
in Kosovo the Serbs' 40,000 troops and 400 or so armored vehicles
actually are. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
