<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2465 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNSHIFTING-1000(2Ta     05-03 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSHIFTING-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING BIG SALARIES, OBSESSIVE SPENDING FOR A MORE MEANINGFUL
LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeanie Crane bakes chicken in a solar box cooker. It keeps her
electric bill down. Besides, she doesn't have a stove.
</P>
<P>
   Crane turns on the heat only when a few sweaters can't warm her
bones, and she unplugged her full-size refrigerator last year. She
even does without a real bed. Why cramp her one-room Fort Worth
apartment when the sofa is plenty comfortable?
</P>
<P>
   Crane is 58, the mother of a grown son and the former owner of a
profitable fabrics store. She still belongs to the Network for
Executive Women and has $100 season tickets to the classical music
series at Bass Performance Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But she lives in a 400-square-foot garage apartment, drives a
1984 Chrysler with rust spots, and shops for her clothes at thrift
stores. All on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe,'' Crane insists, ``frugality can set you
free.''
</P>
<P>
   The technical term for Crane's lifestyle is downshifting:
getting off the treadmill of earn more-spend more to live a less
stressful, more meaningful, more earth-friendly existence.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has gained enough momentum over the past decade
that the federal government is now subtly acknowledging its
existence. Downshifting authority Betsy Taylor will speak about the
trend Tuesday at the National Town Meeting for a Sustainable
America. The President's Council on Sustainable Development is
sponsoring the four-day conference, which runs through Wednesday in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The promoters of downshifting _ authors such as Juliet Schor and
organizations like the New Road Map Foundation _ emphasize the
connection between the world's dwindling natural resources and
Americans' seemingly endless need to acquire things. Our insatiable
appetite for more, they suggest, has not only left us deep in debt
but also with less time to do the things that really make us happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `more is better' definition of the American Dream has a
lot of hidden costs,'' said Taylor, executive director of the
Center for a New American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to downshifters, is simply to buy less
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Crane gave up a $60,000-plus annual income to pursue her ideal
job: recording storytelling audio tapes for senior citizens. She
manages a thrift store part time and works 15 hours a week at a
retail shop to support herself. Her stress level has plunged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a varied life, and it's very satisfying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the life most Americans aspire to.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 50 years, the average U.S. home size has doubled,
and the average person's spending may have jumped as much as 70
percent, according to Schor's book ``The Overspent American,''
recently released in paperback. Yet, survey after survey reveals
that, on the whole, we're less satisfied with our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing awareness that the earth does have limits,
and we as individuals also have limits,'' said Taylor, former
director of the Merck Family Fund, an environmental foundation. If
the whole world consumed like Americans do, she said, it would take
``four more planets right now'' to keep up with the demand for
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Taylor co-founded the Center for the New American Dream
with the goal of helping people ``reduce and change the way they
consume, and improve their quality of life.'' The group's Web site
received a half-million hits in the first quarter of 1999, twice as
many as during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working parents feel a squeeze _ trying to parent, trying to
work, trying to have a community life _ and they are hungry for
more time,'' Taylor said. At least one expert speaking about kids
and violence in the aftermath of the Columbine High School
shootings noted that parents today feel immense pressure to work
long hours to earn more money and, presumably, buy more stuff. This
leaves less time to build healthy relationships with their kids.
</P>
<P>
   That stress, coupled with a willingness to live with less stuff,
is fueling a growing interest in downshifting, Taylor believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downshifting is a huge movement, and there's not one way to do
it,'' Taylor said. ``There are millions of Americans opting to
reduce their work and their pay in order to get more time. For
some, that's job sharing, for some it's going to a four-day week,
for some it's just not taking a promotion that would mean a heavier
workload.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1995, Kathy Huddle-Hall was miserable at her management
job with a local hospital. She and her husband worked long hours
and rewarded themselves with a big house in Mansfield southeast of
Fort Worth. But they had little time to spend with their two boys.
They bought things to make themselves feel better about their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were into `running on the treadmill': earning big money and
spending big money,'' Huddle-Hall said. ``We truly believed the
more money you made, the happier you should be.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
