<HEADLINE>
PILL TAKING, NOT PILL, IS OFTEN THE PROBLEM IN HYPERTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People with high blood pressure often fail to respond to
medication, leading their doctors to prescribe more and more pills
for them. Instead, doctors should help them remember to take the
pills they already have, according to an international expert in
blood pressure control.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Boston on Friday at a conference on pill-taking
behavior sponsored by the American Heart Association, Dr. Hans R.
Brunner, a professor of medicine at the University of Lausanne in
Switzerland, said that more than half the time, cases of high blood
pressure that seemed beyond the control of standard blood pressure
drugs could actually be easily controlled when patients began to
take the drugs correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Brunner collaborated with Dr. Michel Burnier on a study at the
university of 40 men and women with high blood pressure that
remained elevated despite a combination of three different blood
pressure drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The participants in the study put their pills in containers with
electronic memory devices in the caps that registered every time
the bottle was opened.
</P>
<P>
   The data in the caps were then downloaded into a computer and
transformed into graphs on paper so that the participants could see
how often they forgot to take their medications over a period of
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In more than half of the patients, blood pressure fell to normal
levels when they realized how many doses they were skipping and
worked out ways to remember to take the pills correctly. Only a
third required major adjustments in their medications for their
blood pressure to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the No. 1 problem in the management of hypertension
today,'' Brunner said. ``We have wonderful drugs for treating high
blood pressure, but using some kind of monitoring of pill taking
has to become an integrated part of the tools we use, together with
the drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   High blood pressure affects nearly 50 million Americans, but it
is adequately controlled in less than 30 percent of them, according
to data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey
sponsored by the National Center for Health Statistics. In some
people the blood pressure remains high because they stop taking
medications or never begin them, but in many others blood pressure
medication just seems not to work.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that only 55 percent of people who take blood
pressure medication have normal blood pressure levels.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that lowering blood pressure to normal levels
greatly reduces the risk of dying from strokes and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Some people fail to take their medications because of side
effects, Brunner said, but many others simply forget, and are
unaware of how many doses they skip. ``Doctors must learn that this
is normal behavior,'' he said, and learn to help patients
compensate for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors often ask about pill taking in a very half-hearted
way,'' said Dr. Thomas H. Lee, a cardiologist at Harvard University
who is the medical director of Partners Community Health Care, a
managed care organization in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   If paying more attention to the issue means doctors can avoid
prescribing escalating combinations of stronger, more expensive
blood pressure drugs, Lee said, there will be a double benefit:
preserving the patient's health and doing it more cheaply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
