<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2486 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     05-03 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPULSIVE GAMBLING: OVERLOOKED ADDICTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Mass., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic box is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stories of compulsive gamblers could make the hardest heart
weep.
</P>
<P>
   A 75-year-old man from New Jersey lost nearly his entire
retirement fund when he turned to gambling to fight the loneliness
and depression that gripped him after his wife died.
</P>
<P>
   A Philadelphia boy, 17, stole from his parents, forcing them to
lock up everything he could pawn. Then he landed in prison twice
for credit card fraud and bad checks. He tried to commit suicide
before finally entering a recovery program.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-year-old woman from upstate New York used the maximum
amounts of six credit cards and spent her daughter's trust fund on
the craps table and poker machine, then tried to kill herself
before turning to Gambler's Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman gambled away her son's college tuition and a third
woman's husband left her because she could not control her
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   By the time most compulsive gamblers seek help, they are hugely
in debt, owing as much as $120,000 or more, and their families are
a shambles. About 80 percent seriously consider suicide; 13 percent
to 20 percent attempt suicide or succeed in killing themselves, a
rate higher than that for major depression.
</P>
<P>
   More than five million Americans are pathological or problem
gamblers, and another 15 million are at risk of falling into the
same morass, according to a study reported last month by the
National Gambling Impact Study Commission.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5 percent of people develop a gambling problem at some
time, five times the rate of schizophrenia and twice that of
cocaine addiction, said Dr. Nancy Petry, a psychologist studying
treatment for compulsive gamblers at the University of Connecticut
Health Center in Farmington.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, 95 percent of compulsive gamblers were men, but
now nearly a third are women and a growing number are teen-agers.
Americans are spending more than $500 billion a year on gambling,
an amount that has doubled in a decade. And opportunities to gamble
are increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the traditional venues of race tracks and casinos in
Las Vegas, Reno and Atlantic City are state lotteries, quick-draw
games and casinos with all kinds of enticements on Indian
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   All but two states have legalized gambling in the form of
lotteries, dog races and horse races, and since the late 1980s
casinos have opened in 27 states and Puerto Rico. Now there is also
gambling on the Internet, so that people can place bets without
leaving home and without anyone in the family knowing what they are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the incidence of problem gambling is
highest in states with the most sources of legal gambling. And for
many, the problem starts early in life.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide studies by Dr. Howard Shaffer, a psychology professor
at Harvard University, revealed a rate of problem gambling among
adolescents of 9.4 percent compared with 3.8 percent for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that 10 percent to 15 percent of youths who start
gambling soon lose some control over their gambling behavior and
that men with severe gambling problems typically started gambling
before they were 14. But most women who are problem gamblers never
gambled in their youth.
</P>
<P>
   Although in 1980 the American Psychiatric Association defined
compulsive gambling as an addiction problem comparable to alcohol
and drug abuse, pathological gambling has received relatively
little attention. Only 150 gambling counselors are certified
nationwide, compared with hundreds of thousands of drug and alcohol
abuse counselors, Dr. Petry said.
</P>
<P>
   As with other addictions, compulsive gamblers develop tolerance
and withdrawal symptoms. The psychiatric association's diagnostic
manual lists addiction characteristics that include a need to
increase the amount and frequency of the behavior to achieve the
desired excitement (tolerance); discomfort upon being abstinent
(withdrawal); inability to control the behavior, despite repeated
efforts to cut down or quit; continuing the behavior despite the
realization that it is causing serious problems; engaging in the
behavior more often and for longer than intended and experiencing
interference with other functions of life.
</P>
<P>
   Problem gamblers are driven by the need to be ``in action'' _ to
feel the arousal and euphoria from betting that other addicts get
from drugs or alcohol, said Dr. Sheila B. Blume, medical director
of the alcoholism, chemical dependency and compulsive gambling
programs at South Oaks Hospital in Amityville, N.Y. Winning brings
a high comparable to that of addictive drugs; losses result in
acute distress driving a gambler to try to recoup the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Many compulsive gamblers have other addictions as well. About
half who enter treatment programs have histories of substance
abuse. Dr. Blume estimates that there are about 40 treatment
programs for gamblers in about two dozen states based on approaches
used for other addictive disorders.
</P>
<P>
   But she and Dr. Petry said that few professionals looked for
gambling problems in their clients and few programs were prepared
to treat them.
</P>
<P>
   Gamblers Anonymous, patterned on the 12 steps and group support
of Alcoholics Anonymous, is the most established program with
documented effectiveness. Dr. Petry has begun a study of a
different approaches that has shown early encouraging results and
will soon receive the first grant ever awarded by the National
Institute of Mental Health for the gambling addiction treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 120 pathological gamblers will take part in a study
of cognitive behavioral therapy in which participants will learn
how to identify the factors that set off their gambling behavior,
identify gambling patterns related to life occurrences and develop
obstacles and alternatives to gambling.
</P>
<P>
   A third of participants will go through an eight-week program
guided by a professional therapist, another third will use a
self-help manual on their own and a third will serve as the control
group. All participants will also be referred to Gamblers
Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Participants will also be shown how to manage financial
problems. The group insists that gamblers pay off their debts,
however slowly. Those interested in participating in Dr. Petry's
free, confidential treatment study should call (860) 679-2177.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
