<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2491 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MACULAR-DEGENERAT     05-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MACULAR-DEGENERATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG OFFERS HOPE FOR ELDERLY WITH EYE DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., N.Y., Calif.)   (af)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A drug activated by shining light into the eye could offer hope
for people suffering from age-related macular degeneration, the
leading cause of severe vision loss in the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The condition, a deterioration of the retina, affects an
estimated 25 percent of Americans over the age of 65. It is now
virtually untreatable.
</P>
<P>
   But in a clinical trial involving about 600 patients, 61.4
percent of those who took the drug, known as Visudyne, had vision
that was either stable or improved after one year, compared with
45.9 percent of patients in a comparison group.
</P>
<P>
   While such results show only modest effectiveness, ``when you
have a modest difference for a huge disease it's pretty
important,'' said Dr. Neil M. Bressler, a professor of
ophthalmology at the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine
and the principal investigator in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, announcement of the results touched off a huge gain in
the stock of the drug's developer, QLT Phototherapeutics of
Vancouver, Canada. QLT intends to apply to the Food and Drug
Administration for approval to sell the Visudyne in partnership
with Ciba Vision, a division of Swiss drug giant Novartis AG.
</P>
<P>
   Macular degeneration gradually destroys the macula, the central
part of the retina that picks up the finest details of what people
see. People with the condition experience a partial or complete
loss of central vision.
</P>
<P>
   They usually can still see out of the side of the eye, but such
peripheral vision is often not sharp enough to allow them to read,
watch television, recognize faces or drive.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 percent to 90 percent of cases are of the so-called dry
form, in which yellow deposits accumulate on the retina. The more
serious wet form is marked by the growth of abnormal, leaky blood
vessels behind the retina.
</P>
<P>
   Visudyne is only for the wet form, which, while less common,
accounts for most of the cases of blindness caused by the
condition. The company estimates there are 200,000 new cases of the
wet form diagnosed in North America each year.
</P>
<P>
   The only treatment now available is to destroy the blood vessels
with a laser. But this treatment is suitable for only a small
percentage of patients. Also, the laser can injure healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   But photodynamic therapy, as the use of light-activated drugs is
called, ``is more like a smart missile,'' said Dr. Richard B. Rosen
of the New York Eye and Ear Infirmary.
</P>
<P>
   Visudyne accumulates preferentially in the fast-growing blood
vessels behind the retina. The drug is given intravenously, and
about 15 minutes later a red laser is shined into the eye for about
a minute and a half. The drug is activated and destroys the
abnormal cells while doing little damage to surrounding tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Photodynamic therapy has been used with limited success against
cancer, but it appears to be finding its niche in macular
degeneration. Miravant Medical Technologies of Santa Barbara,
Calif., is testing another light-activated drug for macular
degeneration, in partnership with Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Julia G. Levy, president of QLT, said her inspiration came
in part from the fact that her own mother, who has since died, got
the disease at 85 and three years later could not watch television
or read.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to try to convince herself she could see better than
she could,'' Dr. Levy recalled. ``She didn't want people to know
she couldn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Many desperate patients are expected to flock to Visudyne if it
is approved. But some experts say the trial results were not that
impressive. Even when vision was stabilized, meaning a loss of
fewer than three lines on a standard eye chart, it rarely improved.
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 percent of treated patients registered an improvement of
at least one line on the eye chart, compared with 7 percent in the
control group. Moreover, the stabilization does not appear to be
permanent and the drug cannot repair already-damaged retinal
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible treatments being tested include radiation
therapy, surgery and anti-angiogenesis drugs, which block the
formation of blood vessels and have attracted attention as a new
approach to cancer therapy.
</P>
<P>
   While a cure remains elusive, Bressler said, ``We'll chip away
slowly and surely and make the quality of life for these people
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1609EDT &QL; 
