<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2503 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-COUNTRY-HNS &LR;      05-03 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-COUNTRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR WANTS TO REDEFINE COUNTRY MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENNGROVE, Calif. _ Gerald Haslam slipped a cassette of Maddox
Brothers and Rose into the tape player and listened to ``Sally, Let
Your Bangs Hang Down,'' grinning when the group got to the verse,
``Sally calls me her man, but she's a-gettin' all she can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very popular line among grade-school boys in
Oildale when I was growing up,'' said Haslam, 61, who lives in
Penngrove, a town of 900 south of Santa Rosa. ``The teacher sure
didn't want to hear you singing this song.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other songs teachers didn't want to hear youngsters
singing, said Haslam _ most of them country songs, put down as
``Okie'' music in the '40s and early '50s, when Haslam was going to
school with Merle Haggard in Oildale.
</P>
<P>
   Haslam, a retired Sonoma State University professor, has made a
crusade of fighting the white-trash image of ``Okie'' music. In his
new book, ``Workin' Man Blues,'' published by the University of
California Press, Haslam argues that California had a strong
country music tradition even before the Okie migration of the 1930s
and the influx of Hollywood cowboys in the '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much of the definition and direction of country music
has been dictated by Nashville, Haslam feels a need to offer
another viewpoint, to spread the gospel of California country.
</P>
<P>
   During the month of May, he'll move through Stockton,
Bakersfield, Fresno, Menlo Park, Santa Rosa, Sonoma and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Haslam wants to do away with the elitism that labels country
music as ``redneck California is country too music, peckerwood
music, Okie music ... to me, American culture is of a piece. I
don't think there's high art and low art. They're intertwined with
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Haslam is squarely in the camp of country singers like Haggard
and Buck Owens. To Haslam, their music flies in the face of the
bland, orchestrated country of stars such as Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Country's being held in check by what I call the gatekeepers
in Nashville,'' he said. ``You go to a Garth Brooks concert, all
the smoke, the lights flashing ... he's going to have a pointed bra
out there next.''
</P>
<P>
   While Haslam champions Haggard and Owens, ``The Comprehensive
Country Music Encyclopedia'' counts them among ``new
traditionalists,'' those who've followed the lead of Hank Williams,
Bob Wills and Patsy Cline _ from Haggard and Owens to Emmylou
Harris, George Strait, Ricky Skaggs, Iris DeMent and Dwight Yoakam.
</P>
<P>
   The encyclopedia smugly notes ``the success of Garth Brooks ...
and the infusion of more rock and pop music attitudes into country
in the early '90s, effectively ended the New Traditionalist era.''
</P>
<P>
   But Haslam rejects that notion, saying, ``People have asked me
to define country music. I just tell them to listen to Buck Owens
and the Buckeroos doing `Second Fiddle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Haslam also rejects the notion that traditionalism has breathed
its last. Real country music grabs you with its rhythms, he said,
with its heartbreaking words and its call to dance. And that isn't
about to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This music has always been blacker than its audience, which is
why it's been rejected in other places,'' he said. ``But in
California, it was never really rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the songs that most say ``country'' to him, Haslam
starts with a black singer, Stoney Edwards, and his classic,
``She's My Rock.'' The other country songs Haslam cites are Owens'
``Act Naturally,'' Lefty Frizzell's ``I Can't Get Over You to Save
My Life,'' ``Sally Let Your Bangs Hang Down'' from the Maddox
Brothers and Rose, Bob Willis' ``Roly Poly'' and Tex Williams'
``Smoke! Smoke! Smoke! (That Cigarette).''
</P>
<P>
   None of those tunes are likely to make the Nashville Top 10, but
Nashville's hold on country hasn't been good for the music, Haslam
said. ``I'm not anti-Nashville, I'm just against the dominance of
Nashville.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the home of the Grand Ol' Opry and the headquarters of
country taste, Nashville tends to hold grudges against bands that
buck the trend, said Haslam, against people who have gone their own
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, Rose Maddox has never been inducted into the Country
Hall of Fame,'' he said. ``Do you believe that ...'
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Nashville, Haslam said, that embraced the
``country'' music of Olivia Newton-John and Barbara Mandrell. He
pointed with pride at ``California's fierce retention of
hard-country styles in the face of soft country's national
domination.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has also backed rockabilly, which Elvis Presley called
``nothing but hopped-up country.''
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays Haslam has to search the radio dial to find
stations that play traditional country. ``What they're calling
country on radio now is very much this stuff, this marmalade,'' he
said. ``Homogenized, Big Mac music.''
</P>
<P>
   To Haslam, real country is drawn from a sense of loneliness,
``almost a sense of abandonment'' that came to the workers who gave
up their homes and emigrated to places like Detroit and Chicago and
California, to the shipyards around the San Francisco Bay, once the
hotbed of country honky-tonk.
</P>
<P>
   As a Tommy Collins tape played in the background, Haslam counted
off the names of country stars who came to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Price, Tex Williams, George Jones, Johnny Cash ... they
were almost an afterthought in California's musical history. It's
amazing to me that these people passed through this state without
really being acknowledged.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, for someone who grew up with Haggard, Haslam's
book offers no interview with Haggard, and precious few personal
insights. Although he worked on the book for more than five years,
Haslam said Haggard was always ``too busy'' to sit down for an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Haslam's touch is also missing in the chapter on Owens, who at
one point could claim 16 straight No. 1 tunes on the Billboard
charts and is still a force in country music.
</P>
<P>
   But Haslam's impassioned defense of country music and the wealth
of pictures from the early days of California honky-tonk make
``Workin' Man Blues'' a certifiable classic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
