<HEADER>
A2513 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNSHIFTING-2ndTake-     05-03 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSHIFTING-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: you should be.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a lunch break one day, Huddle-Hall wandered into a bookstore
and stumbled onto Joe Dominguez and Vicki Robin's book ``Your Money
or Your Life.'' She read it in three days. She read parts to her
husband. She began taking steps the authors suggested to change her
relationship with money.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most incredible sense of power came over me,'' said
Huddle-Hall, 45. She stopped eating lunch out every day and buying
coffee every morning. She stopped going to the garden center on the
weekends and picking up knickknacks she really didn't need. She
started socking away big chunks of her paycheck, which turned out
to be very lucky.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, Huddle-Hall lost her job.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of panicking, she took the opportunity to downshift.
With her husband still working, Huddle-Hall decided her new career
would be to stay at home and save money.
</P>
<P>
   She began reading ``The Tightwad Gazette,'' a newsletter out of
Maine. She cut her grocery bill from $140 a week to $80 by
comparative shopping. She started cooking meals from scratch and
built a solar oven.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Huddle-Hall became aware of the effect her buying
habits had on the environment. Instead of buying clothes that need
to be dry-cleaned, she now sticks to natural fabrics. Instead of
buying a new pair of shoes for each outfit, she has two sensible
pairs that go with everything.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, Huddle-Hall's entire outlook on consumption, the
environment, money and life changed. She's happy. She went back to
work part time, on her own terms. She and her husband plan on
retiring early and spending their time volunteering.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (''Your Money or Your Life'') taught me is you deserve to
have power over your money, because earning your money is how you
spend your life energy,'' Huddle-Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning to live inexpensively frees you to do some of the
things you really, really want to do in life without waiting until
you're a millionaire or (retired),'' added Crane, who formerly
taught a seminar titled ``Living on Less Successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowering consumption has the added benefit of relieving a
seriously overtaxed environment, Taylor stressed. Americans
especially, she said, must face the fact that ``the planet is
broken and the planet has limits, and our lifestyles have a direct
effect on that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
