<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-CYCLO-CROSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MUD, ON DIRT, OVER LOGS, IT'S CYCLO-CROSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cyclocross, a sport that combines aspects of mountain biking,
steeplechasing and NASCAR auto racing, is beginning to develop a
following in the United States after decades of popularity in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For the very committed, it is part of the extreme sports trend,
but other enthusiasts hail it as an activity for anyone who can
ride a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclocross participants ride laps over a narrow loop that is
filled with obstacles like logs, sand pits, mud puddles and
obstructions that include fences and piles of plywood. Cyclocross
events are often put together by enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Courses travel over soggy meadows, stream beds and dirt trails.
Generally, no more than half the distance traverses paved road.
Riders must hop off their bikes several times over the three-mile
course, sling them over their shoulders and sprint over unbikable
terrain on foot.
</P>
<P>
   A pit stop is required every few laps to allow the rider's crew
to make a few quick adjustments or change a tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pit area is a very exciting place to be,'' said Tim
Johnson, a professional cyclist who lives in Middleton, Mass.
``There are mechanics and handlers working frantically to get their
cyclist back out on the course _ just like in auto racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson believes that cyclocross is a good activity for the
average cyclist because, though fast and challenging, it does not
require superior athletic ability. ``Most riders are out there to
have fun and spend an hour or so covering themselves and their
bikes in mud,'' he said. Most people can adequately prepare
themselves for a cyclocross ride by working out an hour a day three
or four days a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edmund Burke, an exercise physiologist and author of
``Serious Cycling'' (Human Kinetics, 1995) agrees. ``A cyclocross
race takes no longer than an hour or so to complete, so daily
two-hour training sessions on the bike aren't necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he recommends several short, high-intensity cycling
workouts a week, some uphill running, plus two or three weight
training sessions weekly that concentrate on the lower back,
abdominal and leg muscles. ``Training and racing cyclocross get you
into great shape because it's an ultimate cross-training
experience,'' he said. ``It involves running, cycling, jumping,
climbing, and lifting.''
</P>
<P>
   Popularity of cyclocross seems greatest in the Northwest, West
and Northeast. Events are often held in urban areas with good park
systems like Seattle and New York City. Burke speculates that part
of the reason for cyclocross' growing popularity is that it
requires an investment of no more than a few hundred dollars.
Though top racers ride fancy European-made cyclocross cycles that
cost upwards of $2,000, most riders make do with old road bikes
retrofitted with wide brakes and skinny, nubby tires designed for
control and traction.
</P>
<P>
   Pit crews typically consist of family members and friends who do
not mind getting splattered with mud as cyclists fly by.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 21, thinks it has potential as a spectator sport as
well. Indeed, when he claimed the bronze medal at the Cyclocross
World Championships in Slovakia in February, 10,000 spectators were
on hand, and the race was broadcast live throughout Europe. ``It's
a multilap event, so people can line the course,'' Johnson said.
``Plus it's easy to tell who's winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The cyclocross racing season begins in late summer. For
information about cyclocross events and clubs, contact USA Cycling
(719) 578-4581 or visit its Web site (www.usacycling.org).
</P>
<P>
   The Mud Zone (www.themudzone.com) is also a good source for
beginners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
