<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE POLLUTERS ESCAPE BUSH'S BIG STICK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's oft-repeated call for
people to accept personal responsibility for their actions
certainly has a responsible ring to it. But it also has a hollow
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is well known for exhorting wayward youths and struggling
welfare recipients, in particular, to straighten out their lives if
they want to avoid undesirable consequences. All told, it's pretty
sound advice.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has delivered a similar message _ up to a point _
to the corporate citizens of Texas, most notably those industries
responsible for large amounts of the pollutants that befoul our air
and threaten the health of responsible and irresponsible people
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Bush preaches corporate responsibility when he asks companies
operating the oldest industrial plants in the state to voluntarily
upgrade their equipment and reduce their emissions.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a double standard in his messages. Sanctions await
delinquent youths and welfare moms _ but not the ``grandfathered''
industrial polluters _ who don't heed the governor's plea.
</P>
<P>
   During his first legislative session in 1995, Bush proposed _
and the Legislature adopted _ welfare changes that, among other
things, require recipients of public assistance to go to work or
lose their benefits. And lawmakers, with Bush's backing, toughened
penalties for juvenile criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bush not only wants to penalize the welfare mothers who
refuse to work, but also wants to penalize their children by
cutting off the entire family from cash assistance. The self-styled
compassionate conservative says that, in the long-term war to break
the welfare cycle, that is the ``compassionate'' thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   In a further crackdown on juvenile offenders, the governor is
backing legislation to require automatic detention for youths
arrested for using firearms to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush proposed that students who fail after three tries to
pass the standardized skills test for their grade level not be
promoted. Although the bill is being revised by lawmakers, it could
be considered the governor's ``tough love'' approach to ending
social promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The governor obviously recognizes that sanctions are often
necessary to promote responsibility. But he offers no big stick if
some of the state's worst corporate polluters don't clean up their
acts.
</P>
<P>
   These facilities aren't exempted from all environmental
regulations. But they are exempted _ or ``grandfathered'' _ from
state permits and the stricter pollution controls that those
permits generally require because the plants already existed or
were under construction in 1971, when new emissions standards were
imposed under the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists the voluntary approach is working because about 50
companies have agreed to reduce their air emissions at more than
100 plant sites. But that is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Grandfathered plants, according to state government's own
estimate, account for about one-third of the industrial air
emissions in Texas. That is particularly significant at a time when
metropolitan areas like Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth violate the
national health standard for ozone smog.
</P>
<P>
   It also is particularly unacceptable when you consider the fact
that corporate leaders, when they lobbied for their exemptions in
1971, argued that old plants would soon be closed or forced to
obtain permits for major modifications.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight years later, that's a pretty worn-out argument.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is considering a bill _ the Senate has already
approved it _ that would formalize the voluntary program and
encourage companies to upgrade their emissions controls. But the
measure wouldn't require companies to sign up and wouldn't penalize
those that didn't.
</P>
<P>
   There is the threat that lawmakers, maybe next session, maybe
not, would clamp down on companies that don't cooperate. But the
public's health deserves a tougher stance from the public's elected
representatives now.
</P>
<P>
   There's another major _ and relevant _ difference between
government's relationship to corporate polluters and its
relationship to juveniles and welfare moms. People associated with
corporate polluters make big political contributions to state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report prepared by environmentalists, who are
waging a tough war against the voluntary program, Bush, Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry and current members of the Legislature have received
more than $4.6 million in industry-related donations during the
past six years.
</P>
<P>
   Although those contributions may not have purchased the hearts
and minds of elected officials, in many cases they bought the next
best things _ their ears. And although legal, the political
donations make a smelly policy even more malodorous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
