<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-03 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU GET TO PICK NEW POSTAGE STAMP DESIGNS FOR THE '90S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Can we hit the hyperdrive and get into the next
millennium faster?
</P>
<P>
   The '90s have been a pathetic decade. Or so we gather from the
U.S. Postal Service whose greatest advance in the '90s was to give
us candidates for stamps to represent each decade of the century.
</P>
<P>
   For the '60s, the public voted for things like the Beatles,
Woodstock and the Barbie doll, even though it was invented in 1959.
The Postal Service didn't give us a chance to vote on any
assassinations or riots.
</P>
<P>
   For the '70s, the stamp that got the most votes was the yellow
smiley face _ enough said. For the '80s, the personal computer and
the fall of the Berlin Wall won big.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're back way below the level of the yellow smiley face,
which stayed around in the '90s to fill a vacuum of vacuity.
</P>
<P>
   That's how bland the '90s seem to be, at least to whoever at the
Postal Service picks the candidates for stamps of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   I believe this is what Cliff Clavin has been doing since
``Cheers'' shut down. Or maybe the '90s really have been incredibly
boring, even by post office standards.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope, please. The one with the stamps on it:
</P>
<P>
   To represent '90s people and events, you can choose between the
Gulf War, ``improving education,'' ``cultural diversity,''
``sustained economic growth,'' ``recovering species'' and ``active
older Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   They all sound like courses I don't want to take.
</P>
<P>
   You know when you have to put things in quotation marks they'll
be hard to illustrate. If you can't paint a picture of something
that fits on a stamp, like a peace symbol or a Roosevelt, you don't
really have a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   I guess for ``sustained economic growth'' you have a jagged
upward line on a graph that runs into a higher stamp price.
</P>
<P>
   How do you paint a picture of ``improving education,'' something
that hasn't happened in America anyway? More representative of the
'90s would be a picture of a metal detector.
</P>
<P>
   You can illustrate the Gulf War, but the laser-bomb cross hairs
might confuse people with the Balkans War, which may go on into the
2000s.
</P>
<P>
   For arts and entertainment, you can vote for ``Seinfeld,''
computer art or the movie ``Titanic.'' Never mind that we've
already forgotten ``Titanic'' and would confuse the stamp for one
representing the 1910s, a much more notable decade than this one.
</P>
<P>
   The sports category gives us junior golf. Michael Jordan or the
Bulls didn't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The science category includes virtual reality (how do you put
that on a stamp?) and ``return to space,'' which I guess would be
represented by a more wrinkly picture of John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest advances in the '90s came in the burgeoning field of
lifestyle, and the Postal Service offers us stamps representing
cell phones, home offices, museum attendance, community service,
sports utility vehicles and ``the popularity of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder coffee has been so popular. We needed something to
keep us awake in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee? Jerry Seinfeld? Museum attendance? Junior golf?
</P>
<P>
   These stamps representing contemporary American life give an
impression of passivity and boredom that is so overwhelming you
can't even use the word ``overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   You just feel, well, whelmed. It's a real word meaning
``submerged.''
</P>
<P>
   We're still submerged in the '90s and it's hard to know what
stamps will represent the decade. There are still eight months to
go and anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   Please, something happen.
</P>
<P>
   What's happened so far? On-paper wealth, the caffe latte
industry, cell phones and SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones and SUVs are at least illustratable, but who wants
to see any more of them?
</P>
<P>
   ``The popularity of coffee'' could be represented by a Starbucks
logo, but friends won't let friends lick a Starbucks stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we're too close to the '90s to find our symbols. I don't
think so. The following are my write-in candidates for stamps to
represent the '90s:
</P>
<P>
   There should be a ``.com'' stamp, even if it may spell .doom for
the Postal Service. You don't want to have specific .com stamps,
like Amazon.com, because such companies may have vanished by the
time the snail mail gets to its destination.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the .com stamp will be wildly overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   You want a symbol of the '90s? How about a stained blue dress
stamp _ self-adhesive, natch.
</P>
<P>
   If we must have an SUV stamp, why not kill two birds with one
stamp by making it a white Bronco?
</P>
<P>
   We definitely need a cruise missile stamp. It's the weapons
system and foreign policy of choice of the '90s. Unfortunately,
when your mail goes astray, it'll be way off target.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise missile is like the Postal Service that way. And boy,
did the Postal Service miss the '90s. I'm not sure I will.
</P>
<P>
   Send me your suggestions for stamps of the '90s, preferably by
e-mail at morseexaminer.com, where the Postal Service can't lose
them.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, how about a stamp saying, ``You've got mail''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
