<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONSANTO-SEEDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEED POLICE ARE WATCHING FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEN ALEXANDER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The wagon train plods slowly, resolutely across
the untamed West.
</P>
<P>
   The camera focuses on faces of the sturdy, clear-eyed pioneers,
Ma and Pa Suggs, as they look ahead toward a future on this rich,
unbroken soil. It will yield bounteous crops thanks to diligent,
unstinting labor _ and a carefully preserved supply of seed grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma, I know our food's runnin' low and we may have to live on
jackrabbit stew but don't go touchin' none of our seed corn. That
there corn'll make a future for Billy and Sarah and their youngun's
on down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a Monsanto Corporation back then, chances are
that a rider would have galloped up and called out, ``Hold on
there, Sugqs. You plant that there seed corn that you collected
from your last crop back in Illinois, my company will slap you with
the gol-durndest lawsuit you ever heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   See, Farmer Suggs may have planted genetically engineered seed
developed by Monsanto or some other giant biotech company, seed
which, thanks to a 1980s U.S. Supreme Court decision, is considered
``intellectual property'' and, as such, may be patented.
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, you may buy seed for ONE planting. And if you save any of
that crop as seed for next year's crop, you're stealing Monsanto's
intellectual property and are subject to a royalty claim, plus
havinq your farm inspected for the next five years to make sure
you're not reprising this dastardly crime.
</P>
<P>
   Genetically engineered seeds are not like hybrid seeds, the
latter being incapable of self-reproduction. I know this because I
grow a small patch of corn in my California back yard in Lafayette.
Each year I buy about $3 worth of hybrid, super-sweet corn seeds
which produce around 300 ears of incredibly sweet, tender corn,
enough to pass out to favored friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   I shred and plow in the stalks, as all good greenies do, and
invariably an unpicked ear will be in the ground and pop up the
following year. I've left one or two of these to develop and the
resulting plant is a goofy mutant, all tassel and leaves and no
ears.
</P>
<P>
   Genetically engineered seeds can happily reproduce themselves,
hence Monsanto's litigious posture: We can't have farmers not
buying our seed every year and affecting our bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Not content with waving subpoenas around, the biotech biggies
have developed a new genetically engineered strain of seeds that
kill themselves after one sprouting. This is known as Terminator
Technology, a wrinkle that many geneticists worry can spread to
other, untreated seeds and render them suicidal too.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto pooh-poohs such fears, but there is a growinq movement,
especially in Third World countries, to bar the sale of such
self-eliminating stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Monsanto also makes Roundup, the popular weed
killer? In yet another bottom line booster, they've managed to
introduce a Roundup-immune gene into their seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the scenario: Use their immune seeds, the plants grow and
the grower can spray the whole field willy-nilly, killing weeds
without killing the crop. It's a double-barreled profit maker: Sell
non-reproducing seeds and sell lots more Roundup (if you use the
stuff, you know how expensive it is).
</P>
<P>
   Unless some spoilsport ecologists manage to get some new laws
passed or undo some old ones, the future looks immutably rosy for
those who would control the world's agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   No more self-sufficient Farmer Suggses who can better their lot
by enough hard work; any increase in production is eaten up by
having to buy patented seeds every year.
</P>
<P>
   If some poor boob happens to replant from his own crop, it's off
to the courtroom or into the slammer. Then if the boob, having
learned his lesson, decides the only way to get ahead is to plant
his suicidal seeds intensively, he'll need gobs of Roundup to keep
those little sprouts from being crowded out by the weeds. It's a
win-win situation, or a lose-lose situation, depending on whose
side you're on.
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Ken Alexander, now retired, for many years
was editorial cartoonist with this newspaper.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
