<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYCAPITAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY TOP RODEO COMPETITORS MAKING THEIR HOME ON THE RANGE IN
STEPHENVILLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ On a cool, misty but sunny morning, Ty
Murray began his day at 7:30, punching cattle on his 1,851-acre
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Within two hours, Murray, a seven-time winner of rodeo's world
all-around title, has doctored a sick mother cow and has moved a
bawling herd of cattle from one pasture to another.
</P>
<P>
   He relishes the rural life near Stephenville, where he and
two-time world bull riding champion Jim Sharp moved nine years ago.
What Murray and Sharp started has become a stampede of rodeo
competitors heading to this town of 14,400.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, 10 world-class competitors _ bull riders
Troy Dunn, Tuff Hedeman, Gilbert Carrillo and Adam Carrillo, barrel
racers Cheyenne Wimberly and Charmayne James, calf roper Cody Ohl,
team ropers Martin Lucero and Steve Northcott and saddle-bronc
rider Tom Reeves _ have moved in. The rodeo competitors cite many
factors, including relatively cheap land, a central location on the
North American rodeo circuit, the abundance of Texas rodeos nearby
and the proximity to Dallas/Fort Worth Airport and their traveling
companions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the rural, agricultural atmosphere,'' Murray said.
``With all of the traveling that we do, it would be handier to live
five minutes from D/FW Airport instead of 1 1/2 hours away. But it
wouldn't be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray owns a secluded ranch that offers a picturesque backdrop
of brownish-white rocky soil, and lush, wooded rolling hills dotted
with stock ponds and winding creeks. His state-of-the-art gray
stone-brick home overlooks a vast range.
</P>
<P>
   Like Murray, Dunn owns a lush cattle ranch. But it's thousands
of miles away, near the Great Barrier Reef on his native
Australia's East Coast. But he makes his fortune on the North
American bull riding circuit _ he won $221,791 last year _ and
savors a simple home life near Stephenville.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said he acquired a three-bedroom country home and two acres
for $76,000 and might have paid twice as much for a home close to
Fort Worth. And he's just down the road from Ohl, the two-time
world calf roping champion, and within 20 minutes of Hedeman,
Murray and Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got tired of living in apartments, and we looked for land
near Fort Worth, but it was too bloody expensive,'' Dunn said. ``So
we looked around Decatur and Bowie, but not many of our closest
friends lived there. But in Stephenville, I've got a lot of mates
like Ty, Tuff and Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   With an abundance of cowboys parading their big belt buckles
around town, the coffee-shop chatter in Stephenville often consists
of two thoroughly Texas topics: football and rodeo. First, there's
the latest news on the town's high school football program, which
has won three state titles in the past six years. Then the
conversation shifts to the latest feats of Stephenville's extensive
roster of rodeo athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville's square is crowned with a stone courthouse
surrounded by signs touting the town's success in football and
rodeo. On the square's northwest corner, the bios of 14 rodeo and
horse show stars, including Murray and Hedeman, are embedded in the
concrete area dubbed the Cowboy Capital Walk of Fame, which was
dedicated in November.
</P>
<P>
   Erath County's claim as rodeo's Grand Central Station stems from
the 1940s, when stock contractor Everett Colburn took a group of
cowboys by train from Dublin (also in Erath County) to New York for
the sport's then-premier rodeo, at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn and his partner, the late actor Gene Autry, built a
bowl-shaped arena in Dublin and produced rodeos. That in turn
influenced many stars, including bucking stock rider Harry
Tompkins, who moved to the area in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Tarleton State University established a successful
rodeo team. Tarleton's men (1967) and women (1969, '70 and '71) won
national college rodeo championships soon after and remain
competitive. Both teams qualified this weekend to advance to next
month's College National Finals Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look around town today, it seems like almost everyone
has a horse,'' said rodeo livestock owner Terry Walls, who competed
on the 1967 men's team and raises rodeo livestock on his 350-acre
ranch seven miles north of town. ``A lot of people who rodeoed at
Tarleton have stayed here and gone into business.''
</P>
<P>
   And more and more rodeo competitors are joining them in
Stephenville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's laid back here, and people don't hound you for
autographs,'' Gilbert Carrillo said. ``They're used to bumping into
name cowboys because Stephenville is the cowboy capital of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
