<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-RIVER-RESCUE-ART-     05-03 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RIVER-RESCUE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS' GREEN OASIS IN DESERT IS IN PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JON CHRISTENSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. _ From a bird's-eye view, it is easy to see
why the upper San Pedro River in southeastern Arizona is such an
enticing rest stop. Surrounded by barren brown desert for as far as
the eye can see, the river sticks out along the Mexican border like
a big green sign on a long, lonely stretch of western highway
saying: Gas, Food, Lodging.
</P>
<P>
   The San Pedro River, which flows from Mexico into Arizona 75
miles southeast of Tucson, is a rare breed in the American
Southwest: a free-flowing river with a healthy forest of willow,
cottonwood, and other trees, shrubs and grasses, which harbor a
banquet of insects for hungry birds.
</P>
<P>
   Each spring, up to four million migrating warblers, vireos, and
other songbirds stop to rest and refuel here on their way from
winter roosts in Mexico and Central America to summer nesting
grounds in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Around 400 species of birds, nearly two-thirds of the kinds of
birds seen in North America, have been observed here, and 220
species breed along the river. The river is also at the
northernmost tip of the range of green kingfishers, gray hawks, and
other birds rarely seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes the upper San Pedro River one of the top
spots in the country for bird-watching.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Pedro River is in danger of drying up because
groundwater pumping for urban development and farms is draining the
river. And saving this ``extraordinary biological treasure chest,''
as an international panel of experts called the river habitat in a
report last November, has become a test case for an effort under
the North American Free Trade Agreement to save an ecosystem shared
by the United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Next month the governing board of the Commission for
Environmental Cooperation, which was created as part of the
environmental side agreement to NAFTA, will consider the advisory
panel's recommendations for ways to save the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take the San Pedro out, you are jeopardizing a
hemisphere's bird populations,'' said Paul Hardy, program manager
for the Nature Conservancy on the upper San Pedro River, and a
member of the advisory panel. ``It would be like trying to drive
cross country if you took out all the gas stations and
restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Many migratory birds funnel through the upper San Pedro River
because riparian forests on other rivers in the Southwest, like the
Rio Grande and the Colorado River, largely disappeared when the
rivers were dammed and natural water flows were disrupted, Hardy
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The San Pedro River sustains the largest surviving expanse of
broadleaf riparian forest in the Southwest. Even in the driest
spells, there is water in most of a 50-mile-long stretch of river
that straddles the border.
</P>
<P>
   This upper section of the San Pedro River is kept alive by a
vast underground aquifer that is estimated to contain more water
than the combined capacity of the Lake Mead and Lake Powell
reservoirs on the Colorado River. But this abundance is both a
blessing and a curse.
</P>
<P>
   The river depends on water that seeps into the river bed from
the aquifer. But the high water table also means pumping is cheap
and easy. And in Arizona, it is unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Sierra Vista and the neighboring Fort Huachuca
Army base, as well as farms and small towns on both sides of the
border, have been pumping more water than is replenished by
rainfall. The pumping has created what hydrologists call a ``cone
of depression'' in the aquifer, which is much like the vortex in a
drain.
</P>
<P>
   It draws water from the surrounding area into the main well
fields that supply the city and Army base. The outer edge of that
cone of depression is now beginning to suck water from the San
Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues at the current rate, with an overdraft of
7,000 acre-feet (2.3 billion gallons) of water a year, the
stretches of the river that have previously run all year will go
dry in spring and early summer, when migratory birds visit.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some cottonwood and willow trees are already showing signs of
stress with roots stranded in dry ground in the summer, according
to research by Dr. Julie Stromberg, a University of Arizona
hydrologist and a member of the study team. If the groundwater
drops another three feet, which is expected to happen in some
stretches over the next decade, Dr. Stromberg predicted, half of
the riparian forest will die.
</P>
<P>
   In order to keep the San Pedro flowing, the advisory panel
recommended conservation and groundwater recharge projects that
included buying land and conservation easements to restrict
groundwater pumping and housing subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, roughly 40 miles on the United States side of the
San Pedro was made into the first riparian national conservation
area managed by the Department of Interior's Bureau of Land of
Management. The government bought 56,000 acres of farmland and
stopped pumping irrigation water.
</P>
<P>
   A moratorium on cattle grazing led to rapid recovery of the
understory riparian forest. Songbird populations doubled and
tripled, bureau biologists said. The endangered southwestern willow
flycatcher returned to the area although it has yet to nest.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, two beavers were released on the river in the hope
that they would build dams that create the marshy willow thickets
that the flycatchers prefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have really seen a beautiful change in the river,'' said
Bill Childress, manager of the San Pedro Riparian National
Conservation Area. ``A lot of things are headed in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau recently spent $250,000 to finish fencing the
conservation area to keep cattle away. Local governments plan to
spend $407,000 over the next year on conservation and groundwater
recharge projects. But even if all of the projects are successful,
the numbers still do not add up. The groundwater deficit will
continue to worsen, the panel says.
</P>
<P>
   With loss of habitat all but inevitable on the United States
side, the experts concluded that the best hope for maintaining
viable habitat was to extend the conservation area upriver and into
Mexico. That kind of explicit trade-off was not well-received in
Mexico, said Dr. Hector Arias-Rojo, a hydrologist with the
Institute for the Environment and Sustainable Development of the
State of Sonora, and the only Mexican member of the expert team.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory panel ultimately agreed that Mexico should not be
called on to solve a problem created in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the idea of extending the protected area south is
slowly taking hold. Arias-Rojo is part of a team of scientists,
coordinated by the federal Environmental Protection Agency, which
is using the upper San Pedro River basin as a case study of
desertification. And this summer, Arias-Rojo will be setting up
bird monitoring programs in Mexico, with help from Bureau of Land
Management biologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no mechanism right now'' for a border-spanning
conservation project, Arias-Rojo said. ``However, we are building
the bridge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
