<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORD-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      05-03 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD FACES HUGE STAKES IN CALIFORNIA LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ In the largest class-action lawsuit to go to
trial against an automaker in American history, the Ford Motor Co.
is accused of fraudulently covering up a potentially dangerous
stalling problem in 22 million cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit, set for trial May 11 in Alameda County
Superior Court, contends that Ford withheld information about a
defective ignition module from federal regulators and the public.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks more than $3 billion in damages, about 1.5
percent of Ford's worldwide revenues for 1998. Ford faces
additional potential damages in five companion lawsuits filed on
behalf of another 27 million past or present Ford owners in other
states. Those cases are on hold while the case in Oakland is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   The case pits the nation's second largest automaker against an
unusual team: the San Francisco law firm of Hancock, Rothert &AMP;
Bunshoft, which is best known for insurance coverage work; and
Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety, a
Washington, D.C., nonprofit organization started in the 1970s by
Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has denied the allegations and says that while some earlier
cars had flawed modules, it offered to fix them in the worst cases
and improved them in later cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no safety defect in any of those modules,'' said Don
Lough, one of Ford's lawyers. ``These vehicles were not having
accidents or stalling at any higher rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Key evidence includes internal Ford documents describing
problems with the Thick Film Ignition (TFI) module. One 1983 report
on intermittent TFI failures warned: ``Safety is affected.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought on behalf of more than 3 million
Californians who own or owned 1983 to 1995 model Ford cars and
trucks with TFI modules mounted on the distributor.
</P>
<P>
   The module switches electric current to the coil, sending a
spark to the distributor, which directs it to the spark plugs,
igniting the air-fuel mixture in the engine cylinders. The
rectangular device consists of a power transistor and integrated
circuit inside a plastic cover on a metal base meant to disperse
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Ford mounted the module on the distributor, one of the hottest
places under the hood, in all 1983 to 1987 cars and light trucks,
and in some other vehicles up to 1995. Ford says it was put there
to ease assembly and boost reliability.
</P>
<P>
   But the complaint says that Ford knew no later than 1985 that
placing the module on the distributor exposed it to unsafe
temperatures that could make the module fail, resulting in possible
stalls, loss of control and ``risk of serious personal injury and
death.'' It says that failures can be intermittent and hard to
detect.
</P>
<P>
   Ford could have mounted the TFI module away from the engine
block for just $7.75 a vehicle, the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company sold millions of Ford, Lincoln and Mercury
vehicles with defective distributor-mounted modules, even as it
advertised that ``Quality is Job One,'' the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Ford Motor Co. said there was no hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that there never was a massive stalling
problem,'' said a brief filed by Richard C. Warmer of the San
Francisco office of O'Melveny and Myers. He called the coverup
charge preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a barrage of pretrial motions and appeals to the state
Supreme Court, Ford has failed to get the suit dismissed. The
company was hit with almost $100,000 in sanctions for improperly
trying to consolidate the six cases in federal court in Michigan,
where Ford is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, each distributor-mounted TFI module is a potential
time bomb,'' Ditlow said. ``Ford has needlessly endangered the
lives of millions of consumers and has cost them millions of
dollars in expenditures by concealing a design defect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lough countered that about 16 million cars covered by the
lawsuit are still on the road. ``If there was a safety defect in
those cars, there is no way Ford could have hid it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suit has drawn special notice because of the legal theories
behind it, which the plaintiffs' lawyers say could help hold
corporations more accountable and which defense lawyers say could
start a flood of new class-action suits.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of claiming that each car in the class actually stalled
or caused an injury, the suit contends Ford violated California
consumer protection laws by misleading the public, the press and
regulators about the module's unusual propensity to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seek personal injury damages, the suit demands that
Ford give up profits it gained by allegedly covering up the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks statutory and punitive damages, and either
an order that Ford replace the modules or pay compensatory damages
of $250 to each class member.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has ridiculed the suit as a ``no injury'' class action.
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to be the first ruling of its kind, Alameda
Superior Court Judge Michael E. Ballachey has interpreted the
California Legal Remedies Act as allowing a $1,000 fine against
Ford for each of the 3.1 million people the jury finds the company
defrauded _ potentially $3.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ballachey also has ruled that _ if the jury finds Ford liable _
he is willing to become the nation's first judge to use court
powers to order a vehicle recall.
</P>
<P>
   The California Manufacturers Association, the California Chamber
of Commerce and the Product Liability Advisory Council _ which
together represent more than 800 corporations _ sought to file
appeal briefs supporting Ford's effort to dissolve the class
action. However, the state appeals court declined to review the
briefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The novel and extraordinary class action theory ... in this
case is a recipe for disaster,'' said one brief, saying that
class-action lawsuits based on ``latent defects'' will have an
``extremely harmful effect ... on commerce in California and
throughout the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
