<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      05-03 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvesting Proteins
</P>
<P>
   Through genetic engineering, plants can become living drug
factories, producing antibodies and other proteins for use in
pharmaceuticals. But the difficulties and costs involved in
extracting and purifying these proteins from plant tissue has
prevented the process from being adopted on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Rutgers University have developed a different
way of getting recombinant proteins from a plant: out through the
roots. By growing plants in a hydroponic, or water-based, medium
rather than soil, it may be possible to harvest the proteins simply
and continuously as they are secreted.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who described their work in the current issue
of the journal Nature Biotechnology, introduced DNA for producing
three kinds of foreign proteins into tobacco plants. Fused to the
DNA were ``endoplasmic reticulum targeting signals,'' molecular
chains designed to trick the plant into routing the proteins into
its secretory system. The resulting plants secreted large amounts
of the proteins through their roots. In plants that lacked the
targeting signals, the compounds remained in the root cells.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers noted that the process, which they call
rhizosecretion, can be optimized to produce even larger amounts of
proteins than shown in their studies. The process should also cut
down on the purification process, which contributes substantially
to the cost of producing such proteins. Plants secrete relatively
few proteins from their roots, so separating the desired protein
from the others in the hydroponic solution should be less of a
chore.
</P>
<P>
   Not-So-Graceful Sauropods
</P>
<P>
   Sauropod dinosaurs have been depicted as the giraffes of the
prehistoric world, holding their long necks in a swanlike curve to
browse the treetops for food. Experts have often wondered how the
circulatory systems of such dinosaurs could pump blood up to the
elevated head, with some suggesting that they must have had
multiple hearts to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   But now researchers have determined that sauropods probably
didn't have such a haughty posture after all. In fact, the
researchers report in the current issue of Science, the dinosaurs'
necks _ which reached lengths of up to 40 feet _ were practically
straight, sloping gently downward. Rather than dining in the trees,
the sauropods probably grazed along or near the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Fossilized bones being too heavy and fragile to manipulate, the
researchers, from Northern Illinois University and the University
of Oregon, used the next best thing: a computer model.
Specifically, they developed software to simulate the neck
structure and motion of two species of sauropods, diplodocus and
apatosaurus (which used to be known as brontosaurus).
</P>
<P>
   These ``virtual necks,'' when manipulated by computer, showed
that sauropods were a lot less limber than previously thought.
Diplodocus, in particular, could barely raise its head higher than
its back.
</P>
<P>
   Volcano in the Sea
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution have
discovered a major underwater volcano near the Samoa Islands that
rises more than 14,000 feet from the ocean floor. It is as if Mount
Whitney, the highest peak in the 48 states, had been plopped down
in the middle of the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The location of the volcano had been predicted from a series of
earthquakes in the region in 1995. But maps of the sea floor near
the island chain, created using altimetry data from satellites,
showed only a small hill-like feature. The scientists made a more
detailed bottom survey from a research ship that revealed the
volcano's true size: about 22 miles across at the base, and rising
to within 2,000 feet of the surface. The top is marked by a
circular caldera that is about a mile across and 1,300 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery lends credence to the idea that the Samoa Islands
are, like the Hawaiian Islands, a ``hot spot'' chain, formed as
part of the earth's crust slowly migrates across a fixed hot spot,
or plume of magma rising through the mantle. The newly discovered
volcano, which the scientists named Fa'afafine, is at the far
eastern end of the Samoa Island chain, and probably represents the
current location of the hot spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
