<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEART-FAILURE-ART     05-03 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-FAILURE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGESTIVE HEART FAILURE ON RISE IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his blue jeans and T-shirt, walking laps around
the corridors at Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan, Joe Senatore
could almost be mistaken for a visitor rather than a patient. What
gives him away is the pole he wheels alongside him, hung with
pouches of medication trailing intravenous lines that tether him to
the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Senatore, who is 48, once drove a truck for a living. He is
cheerful and strongly built, with just a bit of gray in his hair,
and it is hard to believe that without the medication, he would not
be able to stroll the hallways, and would probably have trouble
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, when he was only 36, Senatore suffered a
severe heart attack at his home in Bayshore, N.Y. One of his
coronary arteries, the vessels that carry blood to nourish the
heart, became completely blocked by cholesterol deposits. His heart
stopped beating, but doctors shocked him back to life and later did
a procedure to reopen the blocked artery. But the attack had
damaged muscle in the main pumping chamber of his heart, the left
ventricle.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years he was tiring easily and had trouble catching
his breath. He had developed congestive heart failure, a severe
condition that is an increasing cause of death and disability in
the United States _ and the only form of heart disease that is on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the epidemic of congestive heart failure is a sign of
progress, evidence of advances in saving the lives of heart attack
victims and people with other heart problems. But these survivors
are often left with weakened hearts that cannot keep up with the
body's needs. As a result, fluid collects in the abdomen and lungs,
and sometimes in the feet and legs, causing fatigue, swelling and
shortness of breath. Low blood flow may also damage other organs,
especially the kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   The symptoms can be treated with drugs: diuretics to help the
kidneys excrete extra water, and digitalis and other medications to
strengthen the heartbeat and normalize rhythm. But for Senatore, as
for many patients, the drugs gradually lose power. This year he
could barely walk from his car to the soccer field to watch his
children play. Periodically, fluid would fill his lungs, sending
him to the emergency room gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drowning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, he would stay in the hospital for a few days of
treatment with strong intravenous drugs. But with each episode it
became more difficult to replace them with pills so he could go
home. By the last week of April, Senatore had been at Mount Sinai
for a month, on the waiting list for a heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Senatore, who has a teen-age son and daughter, hopes to recover
enough to go home for a while. ``The doctor would rather I stay,
but this is the season for graduations and recitals and soccer
games,'' he said. On the other hand, he said, ``I don't want to
come back in here on a stretcher, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone else on the transplant list can tell a similar
tale of progressive disability from congestive heart failure, of
trying to buy time as drugs stop working.
</P>
<P>
   About 4.9 million Americans have heart failure, and a million of
them, like Senatore, are under the age of 60. Every year, 400,000
new cases are diagnosed, and the condition leads to more than
800,000 hospital stays, including many repeat visits. Congestive
heart failure is the leading cause of hospitalization in the
elderly, and hospital bills accounted for much of the $18.8 billion
spent on the disease in 1998. Health experts say the problem is
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Because doctors can now save many heart attack victims who
probably would have died in the past, and because Americans are
living longer, more and more are surviving long enough for heart
failure to catch up with them. In that sense, the epidemic is
really a shift in causes of death or, as Dr. Valentin Fuster,
president of the American Heart Association calls it, ``the price
of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Other conditions, in addition to heart attack, can lead to heart
failure. Three-quarters of patients have high blood pressure, and
some have diseased heart valves. Both conditions make the heart
work harder, which can eventually weaken it. Clogged arteries in
the heart and elsewhere are also risk factors, and so are diabetes,
alcoholism and chronic lung diseases like emphysema. Less common
causes include genetic disorders, chemotherapy for cancer and viral
and other infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could prevent coronary disease, we might prevent heart
failure,'' said Dr. Michael Domanski, head of the clinical trials
group at the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute. But that
would mean persuading people to control their cholesterol, blood
pressure and diabetes, and to exercise more and smoke less _ advice
that many Americans ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Once the heart is injured, it tries to compensate. Healthy cells
try to do the work of damaged ones, changing their metabolism and
growing larger. Often, the entire heart gradually enlarges and
changes shape, a process known as remodeling. But the oversized,
misshapen heart cannot pump blood efficiently, and the struggle may
turn into a vicious cycle of deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   If a healthy heart and one that had reached the final stage of
heart failure were placed side by side, anyone could tell the
difference, according to Dr. Alan Gass, director of transplant
cardiology at Mount Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   ``The normal one will look small, the size of a fist, and kind
of pink and rosy,'' he said. ``The other will be big and grayish,
maybe twice the size of the normal one. It's ugly.'' A diseased
heart may weigh a pound and half, twice as much as a normal heart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 43,837 Americans died of heart failure, and it is
listed as a contributing factor in about 250,000 deaths a year.
``It takes years off people's lives,'' Domanski said. Healthy
Americans aged 67 to 74 can expect to live another 10 to 18 years,
but if they develop heart failure severe enough to require a
hospital stay, their life expectancy is reduced to two to four
years. It also causes great suffering, leaving its victims in what
Domanski calls a ``breathless existence.''
</P>
<P>
   In its worst form, stage four heart failure, the disease leaves
a person housebound, short of breath even at rest. Lying down makes
it harder still to breathe, as fluid pools in the lungs, and many
people find that the only way they can sleep is propped up on
pillows or sitting in a chair. As fluid builds up in the lungs,
some liken the sensation to drowning, and they may be rushed to the
emergency room, gasping for breath and coughing up blood and mucus
_``bubbling at the gills,'' as one doctor put it.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
say that survival after a diagnosis of heart failure is ``bleak and
may be worse than the prognosis for most types of cancer.'' Five
years after diagnosis, half of all patients are dead; 20 percent
die within in a year. Compared to the general population, those who
survive are six to nine times more likely to die suddenly from
disturbances in heart rhythm brought on by heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the increase in congestive heart failure has
inspired researchers to look for new ways to treat it _ developing
drugs, surgical procedures and mechanical pumps to assist heart
function _ or, better, to prevent or at least delay its
progression. Many medical centers have created clinics that
specialize in heart failure. The hope is that with better
treatment, patients who already have the disease will survive
longer and with a better quality of life, even if the condition
kills them in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are detecting the disease much earlier,'' said Fuster, who
also directs the cardiovascular institute at Mount Sinai Hospital.
``With echocardiograms we can now detect a person who has a mild
decrease in heart function, and we can begin to treat this person,
and I think we are preventing this person from appearing in later
years with significant trouble. Fifteen years ago we did not have
the technology to detect it earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain drugs, Fuster said, most notably beta blockers and ACE
inhibitors, have helped many patients control symptoms, and may
increase survival by slowing the progression of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lynn Smaha, a cardiologist at the Guthrie Clinic in Sayre,
Pa., said, ``ACE inhibitors have been a godsend to many patients.''
The drugs lighten the load on the heart by relaxing blood vessels
and reducing the body's tendency to retain salt and water. ACE
inhibitors also seem to prevent heart enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Beta blockers were not recommended for people with heart failure
in the past, but recent studies have suggested that they also may
help, by stabilizing heart rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors should be making better use of both types of drugs,
Fuster said. Also, many cardiologists say these drugs should be
used more often against conditions that can lead to heart failure,
like high blood pressure. In general, many experts believe
hypertension is undertreated in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an epidemic evolving,'' Fuster said, ``but at the
same time the outlook is beginning to look better.''
</P>
<P>
   When drugs no longer work, doctors sometimes turn to surgery in
hope of restoring heart function. Replacing damaged valves can
help, and so can repairing aneurysms, thin and bulging spots, like
bubbles on a tire, that sometimes form on the walls of the heart as
a result of scarring from a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   But one procedure has largely been abandoned, because it helped
too few patients: an operation in which a muscle from the patient's
back was wrapped around the heart and then stimulated to contract
by a pacemaker-like implant.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, another operation, developed in Brazil by Dr.
Randas Batista, attracted attention in the United States, and some
surgeons here began trying it after Batista reported excellent
results in several hundred patients. The procedure involves slicing
out part of the left ventricle, including some healthy muscle, to
return a failing heart to a more normal shape and size.
</P>
<P>
   But American surgeons have lost some of their initial enthusiasm
for the operation. Dr. Patrick McCarthy, surgical director of the
Kaufman Center for heart failure at the Cleveland Clinic, went to
Brazil to learn the procedure from Batista. Now, he said: ``We've
done 62, on patients who were very sick and whose only alternative
was transplant. At six months, 38 percent had to be put back on the
transplant list. At two years, 40 percent were OK, but 60 percent
had returned to heart failure and were back on the transplant
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some patients were clearly helped by the operation,
McCarthy said, doctors could not predict who they would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have two patients with everything the same, and one
would do fine and the other would have to go right to transplant,''
McCarthy said. He now rarely performs the Batista operation, but it
has inspired him to look for better alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   One is a less extreme operation that nonetheless rebuilds the
heart. In one procedure in January, for instance, McCarthy repaired
a leaky valve, did bypasses of the coronary arteries and reshaped
the heart by removing scar tissue left by a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The patient, Mary Constance Sekerak, who is 72, had developed
congestive heart failure shortly after suffering a severe heart
attack in 1997. She deteriorated rapidly and in 1998 was accepted
as a transplant candidate. By that time, she needed oxygen and had
begun using a wheelchair. Rather than continuing to go downhill
while waiting for a transplant, she chose the remodeling procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can walk for 20 or 30 minutes now,'' she said last week. She
works out for an hour three times a week at a cardiac
rehabilitation center. ``Seventy-two might sound pretty old,'' she
said, ``but when you have grandchildren, these are people you want
to keep up with.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For people who are fading too fast to wait for a transplant,
doctors sometimes implant electrically powered pumps in the chest
that act as a bridge to transplant until a donor organ comes along.
Two such pumps, called left-ventricular assist devices, were
approved by the Food and Drug Administration last fall. The devices
cost about $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The pumps are placed in the abdomen below the heart, and blood
is piped into them from a tube bored into the ventricle, and pumped
back out through another tube that feeds into the aorta. The
devices are powered either by a console plugged into an outlet or a
battery pack, so a cable has to pass through the patient's skin.
</P>
<P>
   Infections, which can be fatal, are a risk. Pump failures also
occur, said Dr. Eric Rose, chairman of the department of surgery at
Columbia University. Nonetheless, he and his colleagues consider
the pumps a good choice for some patients, and Rose said his team
had implanted about 150 so far. Many patients can go home with them
while awaiting a donor heart, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and researchers at other medical centers are conducting a
study to find out whether the pumps can be used long term, as
``destination therapy,'' instead of just as bridges. So far, 38
patients have signed up, but 100 more are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Without the device, Rose said, ``these patients have a two-year
survival of 25 percent or less.'' He added: ``We're hypothesizing
that this will approximately double their survival time, that half
will live two years. That would be a dramatic improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Fauzi Kanhan, a 55-year-old man who is awaiting a transplant at
Columbia, had an assist pump implanted on April 2 after his
breathlessness became unbearable. Kanhan has extensive damage to
all the chambers of his heart and is not well enough to leave the
hospital for his home in Palisades Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fantastic device,'' Kanhan said, gesturing to
the tube that emerged from his side. The device hissed and clicked
softly, and the console by his side showed his pulse rate, which
ranged from 60 to 80 as he talked and shifted about. If someone
else with severe heart failure asked whether he would recommend the
pump, he said, ``I would say go for it. Nobody likes a foreign
body, but it's saving my life.''
</P>
<P>
   When would he like to have his transplant, and get rid of the
machine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Kanhan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start to be a bit blue-sky and look down the pike, we
would like to do xenotransplants,'' Domanski said, referring to
heart transplants from animals, which are most likely to be pigs
that have been genetically engineered for that purpose. ``But
that's probably not right around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other researchers also said that as scientists learn more
about the cellular and molecular changes that occur as heart
failure progresses, they may be able to devise better drug
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond drug treatments, Fuster and other experts look to
research involving ways to use a patient's own tissue to regenerate
healthy heart muscle. Fuster said an exciting development occurred
in March, when Japanese researchers reported that they had taken
bone marrow cells from mice and stimulated them to develop into
muscle cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely innovative,'' he said, ``a breakthrough.''
If the same could be accomplished with human cells, he said, ``if
we saw a patient with a scarred heart, and could transform marrow
cells into myocardial cells as they were in fetal life, we could
make a scarred heart normal. This is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Implantable pumps that do not need wires passing through the
skin are also expected, Domanski said, and would greatly reduce the
risk of infection and make it more feasible to consider them a
long-term remedy. In addition to developing pumps that assist only
the left ventricle, researchers are also working on devices that
would replace the entire heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way,'' Domanski said, ``and there's still a
long way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
