<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCTORS-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS ACQUIRING NEW LETTERS: MBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one had ever said that starting her own allergy practice
would be easy, but Dr. Cheryl Lynn Walker was not prepared for the
anxieties that beset her after she opened her doors to patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would get up in the morning, and I would just feel
overwhelmed,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the practice of medicine, she found, was not
the medicine but the practice. Like many physicians, Dr. Walker,
who opened her practice in Chicago in 1990, felt under siege in the
changing landscape of health care, where managed care and corporate
medicine now rule, and doctors often need to be as conversant in
the language of business as they are in healing.
</P>
<P>
   So Dr. Walker did what a growing number of doctors are doing:
she went back to school _ for a master's in business degree.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say more and more doctors are doing just that, as
universities add or adapt programs to meet doctors' needs. The
University of Tennessee, for one, started a program last year; the
Boston University School of Management is starting another one in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, medical schools have created programs for students
who want to study for a business degree simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of doctor who seeks an MBA, moreover, appears to be
changing. While the degree is still a pedigree for doctors who
aspire to run a hospital or a health maintenance organization,
where they may never lay hands on a patient, it is now increasingly
attracting doctors who intend to keep practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Some solo practitioners, part of a dwindling breed, also hope a
business degree will give them the financial acumen to allow them
to survive by teaching them how to run their practices more
efficiently. But the investment is considerable, with tuition alone
in the tens of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John A. Fromson, vice president of professional development
for the Massachusetts Medical Society, said last week that when his
organization polled its 17,000 members about whether to begin a
business degree program, 10 percent expressed strong interest. The
medical society, after fielding inquiries from dozens of business
schools, decided to enter into a partnership with Boston
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message was clear that physicians did, indeed, want some
sort of business management training,'' Fromson said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors cite numerous reasons for the change. Where once those
in small or medium-size practices spent most of their time with
patients while clerical staff members handled billing and filed
insurance claims, doctors now find themselves having to make
business decisions on which the survival of their practices could
hinge.
</P>
<P>
   They must decide, for example, which contracts to accept from
managed-care companies. To determine whether the fees offered in a
contract will cover their costs, doctors often must do the kind of
analyses of their own practices that have more traditionally been
used in business settings.
</P>
<P>
   Business schools teach doctors not only the basic principles
that allow them to make these calculations, but also about the
overall economics of health care and how to work in teams.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew McLean Thomas, an internist from Columbus, Ohio, who
graduated from medical school in 1995, decided two years later to
get an MBA. He is now enrolled at the Fisher College of Business at
Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said patients could be better served if administrators
making broad policy decisions in large health care organizations
had not just business degrees but medical ones.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who hopes to treat patients and to work as an
administrator, said it was essential in the current changing
medical climate for doctors in management positions to have
training in business to make decisions that resulted in the best
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to making business decisions, the days of `I am
doctor, therefore I am right, and cost be damned' are out the
window,'' Thomas said. ``Everyone has to understand we're living in
an era of constrained resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not every doctor is enamored of the trend toward combined
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Laster, chancellor emeritus of the University of
Massachusetts Medical Center, expressed concern about the growing
number of doctors who go back to school for business training,
questioning whether practicing doctors should adopt the philosophy
of business executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation that a single individual can espouse and live
by the two incompatible creeds appears unrealistic,'' Laster wrote
in a 1998 issue of American Medical News, published by the American
Medical Association, ``and I will not allow my family members to be
guinea pigs for testing whether these professional polarities can
be successfully used. I say let businessmen be businessmen and
pursue profits, and let doctors be doctors and care for patients.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
