</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCTORS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: for patients.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Dr. Walker, 40, going to business school did present a kind
of culture shock. She was the only doctor in the executive MBA
program at the University of Chicago, and she quickly had to learn
a new way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   But within a year of graduating from the part-time program, she
said, she had recouped the cost of the degree, about $25,000,
largely through improved billing and administrative practices.
</P>
<P>
   Walker says the business training has not affected how she
handles her patients.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said, by teaching her to be more efficient, the
training allows her to use her time the way she wants: spending
more time with patients and working two days a week in research.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while she is glad she went back to school, Dr. Walker
sounds anything but sanguine about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my small practice,'' she said. ``And so I've decided
that I'm just going to give it the best that I can, until I can't
do it any longer. And then at that point I will need to join up
with a larger group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
