<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HEALTH AND FITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Del., Colo.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRO &AMP; CON
</P>
<P>
   Benefits and Risks Of Sun Exposure
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Is exposure to sunlight the best way to get the
amount of Vitamin D that our bodies need?(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Alisha Berger
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no question that chronic, excessive exposure to
sunlight is harmful to the skin, we should not ignore the important
beneficial effect of sunlight exposure _ the production of vitamin
D.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies have reported that between 41 percent and 54
percent of adults over age 50 are deficient in vitamin D. This
silent epidemic causes the painful bone disease osteomalacia, as
well as exacerbating bone loss, osteoporosis and the risk of
fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the hypothesis that the higher incidence of colon, breast,
prostate and ovarian cancer in people living at higher latitudes
could be due to lack of vitamin D production in the skin has
recently gained new scientific backing.
</P>
<P>
   Increased production of vitamin D in the skin, by the action of
sunlight, may play an important role in the regulation of cell
growth and help prevent the development of some cancers.
</P>
<P>
   It has been estimated that 90 percent of our vitamin D
requirement comes from casual exposure to sunlight. It is difficult
to get the recommended amount of vitamin D from the diet alone. It
is naturally rare in food and is found only in cod liver oil and
fatty fish such as salmon, and some foods are fortified with it.
</P>
<P>
   _ DR. MICHAEL F. HOLICK
</P>
<P>
   Professor of medicine, dermatology and physiology, Boston
University Medical Center
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin D is an essential nutrient with a critical role in
maintaining healthy bones and absorbing calcium from the diet.
There has been speculation that vitamin D supplementation beyond
regular requirements may be able to reduce the risk of certain
types of cancers such as colon or breast, but the data to support
this in humans has been circumstantial.
</P>
<P>
   And high doses of vitamin D derivatives as chemotherapy in
preexisting tumors have so far been disappointing. This does not
rule out a potential role for the vitamin in reducing the risk of
tumors that are not yet present.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome of definitive studies, attempting to
boost vitamin D levels above normal by intentional sun exposure is
not the best approach. If you were asked to enroll in a trial of a
new injectable drug that was thought to help reduce cancer risk,
you might say yes. What would you say though, if you were told that
the vehicle in which the drug is given is a known carcinogen that
also suppresses the immune system and accelerates aging?
</P>
<P>
   If vitamin D is proven effective for reducing the risk of
internal cancers, nutritional supplements will likely be the
preferred method to deliver the dose. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _DR. MARK NAYLOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Assistant professor of dermatology, University of Oklahoma
Health Sciences Center
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION For Hikers, the Perils of High and Dry
</P>
<P>
   Most mountain hikers are ending up high and dry, according to a
University of Colorado study conducted in Rocky Mountain National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   At altitudes above 8,000 feet, people need to consume double the
water they would at sea level, yet the survey of 126 hikers on a
popular 14.5-mile trail elevated over 10,000 feet found that only 1
percent carried a sufficient water load, a half liter per hour of
walking, said Dr. Jack Westfall, the lead author of the study. A
third of the 126 hikers surveyed carried only one liter for the
entire 16-hour trip, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``At high altitudes your body works harder to survive. You
breathe twice as fast,'' said Westfall, who teaches family medicine
at the University of Colorado Health Sciences Center in Denver.
Most water loss is due to respiration, rather than perspiration. If
dehydration results, you experience ``fatigue and profound
thirst,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that only 30 percent of hikers used
sunblock. ``Solar radiation is much greater at high altitudes,''
Westfall said. ``You can get severe burns above the tree line
because there is nothing absorbing light and the sun reflects off
the snow.'' He recommends lotion with an SPF factor of at least 20.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers can minimize the deleterious effects of high altitudes by
spending two days acclimatizing themselves at spots around 8,000
feet. During these periods, Westfall said, ``Don't do anything
strenuous. Just hang out, maybe take a one-hour hike.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, the number of Americans hiking and
backpacking has doubled, and now includes 40.1 million
participants, said Mike May of the Sporting Goods Manufacturers
Association, a trade group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Nancy Stedman
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY Staying Vigilant for Choking Hazards
</P>
<P>
   Meals served to young children outside the home may present a
greater choking risk than those served at home, according to a
report presented last week at a meeting of the American Society of
Pediatric Otolaryngology. Dr. James S. Reilly, chairman of the
department of surgery at Dupont Hospital for Children in
Wilmington, Del., noted that care givers may not always be aware of
the most appropriate foods for a given age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain foods put children at risk, and it begs us to avoid
providing food that younger children can't handle,'' said Reilly,
the lead author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, researchers reviewed 5,588 cases over a seven-year
period in which children under 20 were hospitalized for choking on
small objects or food. Seventy-eight percent of injuries involved
children under 4. Children with developmental delay or who had
cerebral palsy were five times as likely to suffer injury from
foods that were given to them.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the foods most likely to result in injury were
nuts (544), chunks of meat (125), chicken parts (121), seeds (116),
carrots (83), hot dogs and sausage (70), fish bone (52), apples
(47) and hard candy (34). None of the cases were fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most children under 3 don't have all of their teeth, and so
there may be an element of risk when they ingest hard, small,
smoothly textured foods like hot dogs,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   He recommended that children be supervised while they eat and
that nuts, hot dogs, carrots, and apples be consumed with care.
</P>
<P>
   _Alisha Berger
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
