<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONFICTION-BOOKLIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN MAILER'S NOT THE ONLY ONE WHO'LL DISPUTE TOP 100 NONFICTION
LIST
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by NONFICTION-BOOKLIST-LIST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If civilized disagreement is the hallmark of sophisticated
individuals, the Modern Library's just-released list of its panel's
choices for the 100 best nonfiction books will give lots of
self-styled literati the chance to prove just how sophisticated
they are.
</P>
<P>
   The list _ limited to books written in English and published in
the 20th century _ is absolutely unofficial. The Modern Library, a
division of giant publisher Random House, decided last year to draw
attention to its line of ``classic'' reprinted titles by putting
together a panel of writers who selected an arbitrary Best 100
works of 20th-century fiction. The results _ headed by James
Joyce's ``Ulysses'' and F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby''
_ proved only that a group of older white males preferred books
written by older (or long dead) white males.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Modern Library's brain trust is back with the nonfiction
100. It has added two women and an African-American to the panel,
offering token appeasement to those whom it aggravated the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The result still invites furious criticism. ``The Education of
Henry Adams'' is a reasonable No. 1, but it's doubtful too many
people other than panel members have even heard of, let alone read,
``The Varieties of Religious Experience'' by William James, at No.
2. (It's enlightening to note that the James book is a Modern
Library title.) Booker T. Washington's ``Up From Slavery'' is a
worthy third, though skeptics might assume it was placed that high
not in tribute but as token. (On the fiction list, Ralph Ellison's
seminal ``Invisible Man'' was only 19th.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X'' limps in at 51. Room is found
at 93 for Richard Hofstadter's ``The American Political
Tradition,'' but nowhere to be seen are Theodore White's ``The
Making of the President 1960,'' which served as a blueprint for the
modern political primary system; ``The Best and the Brightest,''
David Halberstam's epic dismantling of the U.S. government's
ill-advised foray into Vietnam; or ``All the President's Men,'' the
Bob Woodward-Carl Bernstein recounting of the fall of Richard Nixon
and The Washington Post reporters' role in it.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Mailer will undoubtedly fume. ``In Cold Blood,'' Truman
Capote's masterful fiction/fact recounting of brutal murder, is
acknowledged at No. 96, but Mailer's two similar masterworks, ``The
Armies of the Night'' and ``The Executioner's Song,'' are both
ignored. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Cleverly, Modern Library has made it possible for readers to
electronically ``vote'' for their own Best 100 lists on the Random
House Web site at www.randomhouse.com. Outside voters have had
months to respond to the fiction hundred, and that response is just
as quirky as the original voting by the Modern Library panel. Ayn
Rand's ``Atlas Shrugged'' and ``The Fountainhead'' are first and
second, followed by L. Ron Hubbard's ``Battlefield Earth'' and
J.R.R. Tolkien's ``The Lord of the Ring'' trilogy. None of these
titles made the panel's list.
</P>
<P>
   In the few days since the 100 nonfiction honorees were
announced, Web site voting has produced an almost laughable
response: As of Friday morning, New Age guru Peter McWilliams was
No. 1 with ``Ain't Nobody's Business If You Do,'' and Ayn Rand's
``The Virtue of Selfishness,'' co-authored with Nathaniel Branden,
was No. 2. It must be assumed that lots of Ayn Rand fans use the
Internet. ``The Education of Henry Adams'' does not appear on the
reader nonfiction 100, though ``Ulysses'' is at No. 11 in its
fiction poll.
</P>
<P>
   So what's to be made of all this? Well, somebody at the Modern
Library is due another raise. The nonfiction list, with all its
warts, obvious favoritism to Modern Library titles and glaring
omissions, is being talked about _ just like the fiction list.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that starts people talking about books is good for
everyone. Hundreds, maybe thousands, of people who haven't read
``The Education of Henry Adams'' since it was forced on them as a
college assignment may reread this wonderful tale of society
force-fed into modern times. Those who forgot the thrill of Robert
Massie's ``Nicholas and Alexandra'' will furiously return to it,
just to confirm their certainty it should have made the Modern
Library's list. Book critics everywhere will analyze it all,
tossing in their opinions as though the Modern Library list might
have had some legitimacy had they been added to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   And the Modern Library brain trust will wallow in the publicity.
Just like last time with the fiction list, it's the big winner
here.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
