<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMM-BANKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATOR GRAMM PRESSES FOR BANKING OVERHAUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Phil Gramm has wasted no time taking the reins
of the Senate Banking Committee and establishing who's boss.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican, who became chairman in January, has
brought the tricks he learned on the presidential campaign trail _
from organizing pep rallies to making sound bites _ to the task of
moving landmark legislation that would restructure the nation's
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he faces his first major test as chairman when the
Senate takes up the controversial and far-reaching bill. On Monday,
the Senate began consideration of legislation that would break down
the walls that separate banking, securities and insurance
companies, spurring creation of financial supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often you get to handle the most important banking
bill in 60 years,'' Gramm said in an interview. ``I want to pass a
good bill.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Gramm, a ``good'' bill is one to his liking and one
that, for the moment, he has not been able to reach a compromise on
with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's committee approved the bill on March 4 by a vote of 11-9
along party lines. The administration is so opposed to the
legislation that President Clinton personally wrote Gramm in early
March threatening a veto _ an unusually personal and early warning
in the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   In a long-awaited meeting on Thursday with Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of
South Dakota and Sen. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, the ranking
Democrat on the banking panel, Gramm again failed to reach a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good discussion. We did not reach an agreement on the
issues in dispute,'' Gramm said. ``My job as chairman is to try to
pass this bill. It's a bill that's important to all three
industries that are directly affected and even more important to
their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarbanes and other Democrats unhappy with some of Gramm's
provisions have indicated that they may filibuster the bill. Gramm
acknowledged the possibility by saying, ``I hope we don't encounter
gridlock on this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists say the bill has two provisions that could kill it:
</P>
<P>
   _Limits on the Community Reinvestment Act (CRA). For more than
20 years, the law has required banks to make loans in their
communities. Gramm wants to put curbs on a law he says has become
burdensome.
</P>
<P>
   _Responsibility for regulatory oversight. The Treasury
Department and the Federal Reserve Board are in a turf fight over
which agency would control the newly structured financial entities.
Gramm favors the Federal Reserve Board and Clinton favors the
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Although both issues are considered ``veto bait,'' the CRA is by
far the more controversial provision. Busloads of minority
protesters, in fact, demonstrated outside Gramm's Washington home
on a recent Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who was not home at the time, called the protest ``an
effort to intimidate'' and said, ``This is part of this job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Community Reinvestment Act was designed to spur lending for
home purchases and small business investment in minority
communities. But Gramm and other critics contend that the CRA has
grown into an onerous burden on many banks. Supporters insist that
it has been crucial to urban revitalization and call the CRA a
civil rights issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the White House and Senate Democrats, CRA is the Holy
Grail,'' said John Heasley, general counsel of the Texas Bankers
Association. ``It is the closest thing to social and economic
justice in a banking regulatory world.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the senator's perspective,'' Heasley said, ``it is
government getting involved in the private sector to determine how
loans are made.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's provision to exempt rural banks from CRA provisions
would affect as many as 200 of Texas' 840 state and national banks,
Heasley said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has enraged community groups by describing as
``extortion'' bank payments to groups that question a financial
institution's commitment to local lending.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates counter that banks have worked with many of the groups
as partners in developing good lending prospects and making the
process easier in minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extortion is simply not a part of the partnerships,'' said
John Taylor, president of the National Community Reinvestment
Coalition. ``CRA has been instrumental in curbing the practice of
red-lining and dramatically increasing access to capital and credit
for traditionally underserved neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader has also weighed in, telling
community activists last month, ``These blunderbuss attacks on CRA
are amazing even for a Phil Gramm, who has made a career out of
carrying dirty water for banks and big corporations. The CRA is one
of the great success stories of our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Community Reinvestment Act are marshaling
their forces for this week's fight. Civil rights groups plan a
rally on Tuesday and the U.S. Conference of Mayors has sent a
letter to all senators, signed by more than 150 mayors who support
the CRA and oppose Gramm's proposed changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As mayors, we recognize that CRA has been an essential tool in
revitalizing cities around this nation,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mayors who signed the letter are Kenneth Barr of Fort
Worth, Jack Miller of Denton, Mary Lib Saleh of Euless, Charles
Scoma of North Richland Hills and ]Ron Kirk of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry, which for more than 10 years has been
trying to change the Depression-era rules that govern it, is taking
a low profile on the Community Reinvestment Act. After Gramm
organized three ``pep rallies'' of industry lobbyists to support
the bill, bankers made some muted complaints about the CRA, but
insiders say they have learned to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge, huge paperwork problem,'' said Ed Yingling,
executive director of government relations for the American Bankers
Association. ``No matter what your grade is, you're still subject
to challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Yingling gives Gramm high marks for aggressiveness and energy in
assuming the chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is hands-on,'' said the banking industry lobbyist,
referring to the pep rallies Gramm organized. ``We're not used to
having a senator, let alone the chairman, directly involved in
strategy and telling us the things that need to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
