<HEADER>
A2665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-KENTUCKY-DERBY-FO     05-03 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKY-DERBY-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprise win has Lukas tracking Derby record
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ On the day before the Kentucky Derby, Wayne
Lukas was looking over his shoulder at Bob Baffert, who was yapping
at his heels. Lukas had trained three Derby winners, Baffert two.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the Kentucky Derby, Lukas had turned the page
on Baffert in the history books, ahead 4-2. Now Lukas was looking
at Ben Jones, the only trainer with more Derby winners. At age 63,
Lukas is two victories behind Jones with, on the Lukas timetable,
plenty of time to catch up with the trainer who dominated the Derby
in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   With a grand wave, Lukas pointed to the green signboard with
white lettering posted by Churchill Downs near the stable door at
his barn Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   On the sign were the names Winning Colors, Thunder Gulch and
Grindstone, with the name of Charismatic, winner of the 125
Kentucky Derby, soon to be added. ``You will notice,'' Lukas said,
``there is plenty of room at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason I can't go on winning this race. I'm
enjoying what I do. I'm healthy. There is plenty of time to train
any number of horses as long as you don't play golf or go to the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the main thing is that I've got the client base to keep
coming up with winners. I'm going to get Derby horses every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Lukas' primary backers, Bill Young of Overbrook Farm,
owner of Cat Thief, third Saturday, and Bob and Beverly Lewis,
owners of Charismatic, were at the trainer's side during the race.
His other top owner, Satish Sanan, stood in the barn door behind
Lukas on Sunday, sharing the winner's glow.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody wishes Lukas well. He has won so much.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Maker, the top Lukas assistant in Kentucky , was leading
Charismatic back to the stable after the race when a voice cried
out, ``He'll never win again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike had the right answer,'' Lukas said. ``He doesn't have to
win again.''
</P>
<P>
   With 14 races before the Derby, Charismatic had more losses (11)
than any horse in the field. Already, there are suggestions that
Menifee or the Baffert entries may be favored over the Kentucky
Derby champion May 15 at the Preakness. Lukas shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was going to be criticism when I ran this horse
on 13 days rest in April,'' he said. ``He needed the work. Maybe
some horses need 15 outs (races) to run their best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go to the store and get a book that tells you how to
win the Derby. You can't find a computer chip that tells you how to
win. That's why this race is so great. There is no formula.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe Lukas did not know the answer, but he
asked about the exact amount of the winner's purse. The answer:
$886,200. ``A nice thing is that 10 percent of that goes to ol'
Wayne,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Whittingham, who died last month, is the only other
trainer with $100 million in earnings. With his Derby payday, Lukas
will surpass $200 million soon, perhaps before May is over.
</P>
<P>
   Like the trainer, the winning jockey, Chris Antley, took 10
percent of the Charismatic winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Antley was not the first choice for the Derby ride.
</P>
<P>
   Lafitt Pincay had the last California assignment on the Derby
winner April 3. Pincay did not want the Kentucky job.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey won with Charismatic at Keeneland on April 18. But
Bailey was committed to ride Worldly Manner Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas talked about what a good match Antley and Charismatic
were. In truth, when the decision was made two weeks ago to go to
the Derby with the Lexington Stakes winner, not many top jockeys
were left uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas saw Antley hold up an index figure Saturday just before
Charismatic came to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antley is lucky that he won,'' Lukas said. ``If he had gotten
beat, I'd have that finger in my office in a jar, making a pickle
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Crittenden writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
