<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are planning a long car trip this summer and I will need
to occupy myself by reading. But I am one of those people who gets
sick from reading or looking at pictures in a car. I have heard of
some device you put on your wrist and it prevents you from becoming
sick or nauseous. Do you know where I could get one of these?
</P>
<P>
   _A. Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   A: You are looking for Sea-Bands, sold in area pharmacies. You
might try this nondrug approach to curing motion sickness. No
guarantee it will work. Sea-Bands won't hurt you and they sell for
less than $10. Motion sickness is the conflict between your body
sensing the motion of the moving car and your eye working to
concentrate on the words on the page. A common cure for motion
sickness is to keep your eyes fixed on the horizon _ where the car
is going. Let me know if Sea-Bands work for you!
</P>
<P>
   Q: I received a Christmas gift of M&AMP;M cookies in a jar for all
my volunteer hours at my child's school. I have tried several
recipes and have not found the same texture cookie. My family wants
the recipe for M&AMP;M cookies in a jar. Can you help? _E. Emmons
</P>
<P>
   A: Glad your school efforts were recognized. Bravo! This is a
Jackie Gannaway recipe. Call Gannaway at 477-7070. ($3.95 plus tax,
add shipping if ordering from Gannaway.) Enjoy 23 cookie mixes and
three brownie mixes in this booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The term ``tank'' for a pond seems uniquely Texan. How did
the usage get started? _D.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: A tank is an artificial reservoir, pool or cistern. Texas has
only one major natural freshwater lake, Caddo Lake, according to
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission, so building
tanks and damming rivers is essential for an adequate water supply.
Texana expert Mike Cox says water-poor West Texas has many tanks,
and both tanks and ponds are commonly referred to as tanks. In East
Texas, where ponds probably outnumber tanks, ``pond'' is the term
used for both.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do birds really sing more in the spring, or do they just seem
to? _Susan M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yep, they sure do. Travis Audubon Society's John Kelly says
most of the singing is by males looking for mates (hear a few bars
of ``I'm in the Mood For Love''?) and warning other birds to stay
clear of their territory (all together now, ``This land is my land
...''). Spring is, after all, nesting season. The most versatile
avian chanter? The East Coast's brown thrasher. This relative of
the mockingbird sings more than 2,000 different phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I enjoyed reading how round toothpicks are made. Now please
tell me how string cheese is made. _S.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: String cheese is mozzarella cheese in an interesting shape.
According to Greg Desautels, quality assurance manager for Saputo
Cheese USA, mozzarella has an inherent stringing property.
Technically, the cheese's milk proteins line up in straight lines
after the cheese is kneaded and heated. To make it string cheese,
taffy-like mozzarella cheese is pumped into an extrusion head
(think of a giant sieve). The cheese (about a half-inch thick)
comes out in long ropes. After being chopped into 4 1/2-inch
lengths, the string cheese is dropped in brine, cooled and
packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I purchased a NewCom modem at Circuit City in April 1998. I
mailed in the $30 rebate offer but have yet to receive it. The Los
Angeles Better Business Bureau said they've stopped taking
complaints about NewCom because of poor response. How I can get my
rebate check? _Kyle Stubbings
</P>
<P>
   A: I think you can kiss the rebate goodbye. After several chats
with NewCom (not an easy place to contact), I received a letter
from NewCom's attorney (J.C. Fedalen, Sabo &AMP; Green, 23801 Calabasas
Road, Suite 1015, Calabasas, Calif. 91302) stating, ``NewCom is ...
resolving the rebate issue by way of a stipulation and settlement
in a lawsuit ... rebates will be paid under the auspices of the
Court.'' The Los Angeles BBB is accepting complaints about NewCom
(the tally: 36 complaints, 16 satisfied, 1 unresolved, 19 ignored
or pending). Send your complaint to the LABBB, P.O. Box 970,
Colton, Calif. 92324. Q: I have a moderately sized collection of
brass and would like to clean it and store it. I had thought I
could wrap it in paper towels and then seal it in storage bags. Do
you have any suggestions as to how to store it and not have it
tarnish? _Gloria Eckstrom
</P>
<P>
   A: Darren Wicker of Austin Brass recommends wrapping the brass
items in cloth (old sheets?) before placing them in plastic.
Tarnish is retarded by limited exposure to air. The plastic will
help do that. However, Wicker warns not to let the plastic touch
the brass, especially if the brass is lacquered. Lacquered brass
should never be stored in hot areas such as attics or garages.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A short time ago there was an obituary that included a very
moving snippet from a poem: ``... and when he shall die, take him
and cut him out in little stars, and he will make the face of
heaven so fine that all the world will be in love with night ...''
A few years ago I lost my own beautiful adult son. After that
dreadful event I began writing poetry of my own. Can you find out
the poet and title and where I can find the poem? _O.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``And pay no worship to the garish sun.'' Act III, Scene 2
from William Shakespeare's ``Romeo and Juliet.'' This popular
passage is spoken by Juliet opining in the Capulet orchard.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
