<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It was a rainy spring evening and I looked out my window on
Washington Square at the shiny, deserted streets. Then I realized
that the streets were not entirely deserted: there was a couple in
front of the New York University dormitory, dancing a slow, elegant
jitterbug.
</P>
<P>
   As I watched, I was suddenly on the Champs Elysees, 40 years
ago. I was studying at the Sorbonne under the G.I. Bill, and
friends had assembled a makeshift band. They were playing as my
future wife and I jitterbugged in front of an entranced crowd of
Parisians who tossed coins in a hat. We left the coins for our
friends but I have lived on the nostalgia ever since.
</P>
<P>
   -HOWARD MILKIN
</P>
<P>
   Down and out in the early '70s, I turned to panhandling on
Second Avenue, a few blocks north of St. Mark's Place. I had heard
the legend that one of my colleagues, with a master's degree in
psychology, was pulling down thousands a month on the street by
sizing up his patrons and using what he thought would be the ideal
pitch for each one. However, I was barely able to get a meal or two
each day. Once, when I approached a man waiting for a bus and
politely asked for spare change, he turned, peered into my eyes,
and pinched my cheek. ``Too much fat,'' he said as he turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, I found work and now, two master's degrees
later, I remember with gratitude the people who helped me then, for
example, a woman who looked like a secretary and dug through her
wallet to give me $1.50 when I was very hungry. Now that I'm living
better, when panhandlers approach, look clean and have no signs of
flagrant addictions, I get a charge out of sometimes handing them a
$20 bill, knowing well what they feel like at that moment.
Sometimes they actually dance, other times they get a faraway look
and tears fill their eyes. I've done it myself and I know how long
they wait for such moments.
</P>
<P>
   _ROBERT E.COGSWELL
</P>
<P>
   Elie Feuerwerker was on a 96th Street bus crossing Central Park
when the bus driver took up his microphone to announce: ``Would the
person with the Walkman make it less loud? I can't drive and
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ira Wells probably won't be challenged when he describes his
103-year-old mother as the oldest living graduate (class of 1916)
of Hunter College. Lillian Welkowitz, who lives on Staten Island,
recently asked her son to comparison-shop for an air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   He reported that New Jersey prices were a bit lower than those
locally, but Mrs. Welkowitz, a former mathematics teacher, decided
to patronize a local shop. ``The slight difference won't make much
difference pro-rated over 10 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Berg was strolling on Fifth Avenue when a pair of
teen-age girls, wearing blue jeans, T-shirts and baggy jackets,
shopping bags in hand, passed him. He overheard this conversation:
</P>
<P>
   First girl: ``You know, 15 was awful for me _ like I felt
inadequate _ you know, like, I had absolutely no self-esteem _
like, it was awful!''
</P>
<P>
   Second girl: ``Well, you seem O.K. now.''
</P>
<P>
   First girl: ``Yeah. But it's, like, I'm 17 now. Now I know
exactly where I'm going. Like, you know, I feel really great.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Berg's summation: ``Boy, it must be great to be 17 _ like,
you know, I can hardly remember _ like, when I was 17.''
</P>
<P>
   Informative and fascinating messages sometimes appear at subway
token booths. A couple of examples, late last year at the 77th
Street uptown booth, Maxine Levinson noted such daily maxims as
``Lots of people confuse bad management with destiny,'' and ``If
you always do what you've always done, you'll always be what you've
always been.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, at 86th Street and Broadway, the message read,
``Fear is a little dark room where negatives are developed.'' Who
knew a subway station could be the source of enlightenment, asked
Leland J. Brandt, just one of the straphangers who left the station
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   There were 17 people divided up for a softball game. Nine
children, ages 4 to 14, formed one team and eight adults, ages 35
to 70, formed the other team. During the warm-up session, the
adults knew their goose was cooked when one of them overheard our
grandson, Ted, saying: ``Let's practice grounders. The grown-ups
can't bend.'' P.S. The children won.
</P>
<P>
   _BARBARA SCHREIBER
</P>
<P>
   Amy and Kent Hikida were at a performance of the Broadway show
``Art.'' The lights dimmed, the actors entered and most eyes were
focused on the minimal white on white painting on which the play
centers. Focal point or not, the art didn't impress one
theatergoer. A woman shouted from the balcony, ``My son has one
just like that, only it's in red.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pump restaurant, a small establishment on 31st Street near
Lexington Avenue, will be dark on what is one of the busiest
dining-out days of the year. A sign in the window advises: ``Closed
Mother's Day. We will be celebrating our first Mother's Day with
our 4-month-old daughter. Owners Steve and Elena Kapelonis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-NYT &LR;      05-03 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SEE WHAT THEY WANT TO SEE IN COLORADO SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., S.C., Ala.)  (mk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If there is a lesson to be learned from the deadly
shootings at a Colorado high school, Democrats and Republicans are
studying two different textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the general consensus is that there is no one cause or
explanation for the April 20 rampage at Columbine High School that
left 15 dead, the two political parties disagree about what they're
willing to consider.
</P>
<P>
   While denouncing violence in movies and video games, Democrats
also view the tragedy through the prism of gun control, saying the
shooting underscores the easy availability of guns and points to
the need for stricter regulation of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure the NRA will criticize those of us who connect this
violence with the easy access of guns in America,'' said Sen.
Dianne Feinsten, D-Calif. ``But sadly, times of tragedy like this
are often the only times people pay attention to the problems
plaguing our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., last week called on the Senate to
consider a colleague's bill on handgun control, decrying the
``inordinate number of pistols and firearms in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans say the shooting is all about a cultural
meltdown in a nation awash in media violence, and in which little
premium placed on either morality or personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not been acculturated with the kind of
gentlemanliness and gentlewomanliness, not inculcated with
religious faith and discipline, maybe a lack of values or
whatever,'' said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., in describing the
mentality of some young people today.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats agree that violence on the Internet, on
television and in the movies has gotten out of hand. President
Clinton, in fact, plans to host a national summit on violence in
the media at the White House on May 10. At the same time, Clinton
wants Congress to pass a comprehensive series of new gun-control
laws, including the enactment of a waiting period for the purchase
of handguns, the expanding of background checks for the purchase of
explosives, and the banning of minors from possessing semiautomatic
assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party, however, appears unwilling to cede any
ground on the issue of gun control. Some GOP lawmakers have devoted
entire speeches to the nation's deadliest school shooting without
once mentioning the word ``gun.'' And many Democrats who come from
rural districts in the South and West are reluctant to embrace any
new gun control measures, saying that no new law could have stopped
the violence in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In short, lawmakers see in the school shootings what they want
to see. The tragedy at Columbine has become Exhibit A on Capitol
Hill, providing the perfect example for whatever it is a lawmaker
or interest group wants to argue.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., tied the shooting to a lack of prayer
and faith in schools. ``Have we created a spiritual void in our
schools, which is now being filled with drugs and sex and
violence?'' DeMint asked. ``It is clear there were very deep
spiritual problems in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader had a different but predictable
take, placing the blame on corporate America, ``the powerful monied
interests that produce this culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said that the quest for bigger profits has led to a
proliferation of movies, video games and artists that celebrate
violence and nihilism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Focus on the deeper problems,'' Nader urged. ``Behind every
Marilyn Manson are corporations and corporate executives who
cynically draw their compensation packages from the fruits of such
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader's comments touch on another aspect of the debate over the
Colorado tragedy _ the role of money in politics. While Clinton and
many lawmakers have called on Hollywood to take the lead in
limiting the random violence in movies and television, they also
have their hand out for campaign donations. In 1997-98, political
action committees associated with the entertainment industry
contributed $2.8 million to candidates. Republicans, who control
Congress, collected roughly 55 percent of that total, compared to
45 percent for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, one of the most powerful lobbies
on Capitol Hill, is also generous with its donations. According to
a study by Common Cause, the NRA spent close to $2 million on
political contributions to candidates and national parties in
1997-98. Roughly 85 percent of that total went to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin reports from the Washington bureau of the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
