 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, May 4, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The pressure is now on President
Clinton as he prepares to meet with Russian special envoy Victor
Chernomyrdin and receives a letter from Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic via the Rev. Jesse jackson. This, as the latest in the
continually escalating U.S.-led NATO bombing of Serb military
targets in Yugoslavia. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWS _ RAMSTEIN, Germany _ Three U.S. soldiers held
captive in Yugoslavia for a month pass preliminary medical
examinations and begin meeting their families, but U.S. officer
says they may have been initially maltreated. Developing. (Holmes,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Monday debates a
resolution by Sen. John McCain authorizing President Clinton to use
``all necessary force'' to prevail in the Balkans. Ater a debate
stretching into the evening, the Senate is expected to table the
motion, adding yet another element of certainty to congressional
support of the war effort. (Malone, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CAMP _ KUKES, Albania _ Their refugees have hot meals and
electricity in every tent. Their field hospital soon will boast a
full-scale operating theater. Now the managers of the so-called
``Arab camp'' are finishing an airstrip that could receive the
first C-130 loaded with their supplies as early as Tuesday, and
will be improved enough within weeks to serve as a forward base for
NATO war planes. They are relative newcomers to the world of
big-time international humanitarian aid, but the United Arab
Emirates are building a show-stopper. (Kunstel, Cox News Service).
20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HALL _ Tony Hall is back from Macedonia; he and Dick
Armey have a 1 p.m. pressfab to talk about it. (Montgomery, Dayton
Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BAXTER _ A look at the political implications of the Rev.
Jesse Jackson's success in gaining the freedom of three U.S.
soldiers. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTONMICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ List of rebuttal witnesses
expeced in Microsoft antitrust case. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN 2000
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DONORS _ ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore raised nearly as
much money in Georgia as the entire field of Republican
presidential candidates, according to a computer-assisted analysis
of Georgia donations in the first quarter of 1999. Texas Gov.
George W. Bush led the GOP field, followed by Elizabeth Dole and
Gary Bauer. While the race is still early, the donations show that
Bush has the best fund-raising organization in the Peach state with
the potential to raise even larger sums in the months ahead.
Bauer's strong third-place showing indicates that the conservative
think tank founder is winning the battle to attract conservative
voters over former vice president Dan Quayle and publisher Steve
Forbes, both of whom are vying for conservative votes in Georgia.
Two Atlanta law firms, Alston &AMP;Bird and Troutman,Sanders, have been
unusually active donors. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/GORE-BELLSOUTH _ ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore wanted to
make a strong statement in his first presidential filing. Georgia's
BellSouth wanted to make one of their own. Over four days,
BellSouth executives chipped in more than $45,000 in personal
donations to Gore, one of the biggest corporate contributions to
Gore anywhere in the country. The telecom company, which has a long
history of supporting Republicans, says the Tennessee Democrat and
technology junkie understands their issues better than anyone else.
Foskett 25''
</P>
<P>
   DOLE _ ATLANTA _ Georgia donors to Elizabeth Dole illustrate her
ability to draw from a wide spectrum, everyone from moderate
Democrats to Truett Cathay, the conservative founder Chick-Fil-A.
(Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-HEIRS _ More on the Jefferson heirs. A Trotwood man
undergoes a DNA test in hopes of proving he's an heir to Jefferson.
The man who did the study establishing the Salley Hemming link is
at the house, as well as a PBS filiming the whole thing. (Keilman,
Dayton Daily News). 15. (Kimbrough, Dayton Daily News). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-CHARGE-DEBATE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Pressure and frustrations
are growing for those involved in telephone access charge fight.
One lawmaker told the House State Affairs Committee last week that
some had characterized her as ``a 'ho'' for Southwestern Bell
because her bill is seen as favoring that company. The chairman of
the committee, Rep. Steve Wolens, left the hearing infuriated
because he could not get questions answered and Bell appeared to be
claiming support for the bill that it didn't have. And those TV ads
are generating constituent pressure to do something. The committee
is expected to complete its hearing on Monday, but no action will
be taken yet. (Hight, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
