<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BLAME GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: CORRECTS 7th graf to reflect that the Senate did not table
the ``all necessary force'' resolution Monday but is expected to do
so Tuesday.)
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Immediately after the Senate refused to convict
President Clinton on the House impeachment charges, congressional
leaders of both parties solemnly vowed to put the partisan
bitterness behind them and work together in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Feb. 12 the Democrats were chastened by the president's
close call, and the Republicans were alarmed about public
disapproval of their sex-and-lies vendetta. Both needed a respite.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it. That was two and a half months ago and this is now.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombing of Yugoslavia has exposed the permanent reality
of Washington politics in the convulsive Clinton era. The
congressional Republican majority hates the president and is still
trying to do him in, even if it makes the GOP look foolish again in
the process. Call it Impeachment II.
</P>
<P>
   The House performed the ludicrous stunt last week of refusing to
support the air war or the use of ground troops while also refusing
to advocate withdrawal. Don't stay, don't go. Hide in the rabbit
hole.
</P>
<P>
   The House then topped that preposterous muddle by voting to
appropriate twice as much money as the president had requested to
bolster the military's ability to wage the very war for which it
had ducked any responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority had some Democratic help in this crazy,
cowardly exercise, but it was essentially a GOP strategy to
embarrass and undermine Clinton by isolating him. And the
philosophically divided Senate is going down the same circuitous
path. On Tuesday it is expected to table, or set aside, a
resolution that seemed destined to lose which would give the
president a free hand as commander-in-chief to use ``all necessary
force'' in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   These contortions are as much about domestic politics as about
foreign policy, appeasement, humanitarian instincts, NATO prestige
and individual conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The president who remained popular during the whole Monica
Lewinsky mess is finally falling in the opinion polls over public
discontent with the uncertain war. One poll now puts his approval
rating on Kosovo at 46 percent _ still respectable but no longer
impressive. And that makes him newly vulnerable to his foes.
</P>
<P>
   This time he could take down Vice President Al Gore with him.
Gore could not be tarred with skirt-chasing, but he is stuck with
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are not concealing their base motivation. They
don't trust Clinton and therefore won't endorse his conduct of the
military exercise, no matter what it is. Oddly, Secretary of
Defense William Cohen, a respected former GOP senator, doesn't
count for anything in this political equation. Once admired as a
military expert, he suffers from guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives call it ``Clinton's war,'' as though Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic is just an innocent bystander in the
Kosovo crisis rather than the cause of it all. In arguing with
Democrats, they refer to Clinton as ``your president,'' meaning not
theirs and rejecting the outcome of the last election. Respect for
the institution of the presidency is yet another casualty of
partisan bickering.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Clinton is blameless in all this. He has given Capitol
Hill plenty to distrust him about. He has not appeared sure-footed
in his defense of the hapless Kosovars, and most of us can't figure
out just what is going on over there. Is the NATO bombing making
headway or merely making things worse?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says he is not asking for ``total victory,'' just
``minimal conditions'' to allow the Kosovars to go home, meaning
some sort of armed international security force to protect them
after a withdrawal of Milosevic's thugs. He also talks about ``a
measure of autonomy,'' which Kosovo had before Milosevic's assault.
</P>
<P>
   This is not exactly a ringing call to arms and is not quite what
he originally described as his ultimate goal. But Kosovo, like
Clinton himself, is a work in progress. To accept that this
exercise in firepower will work out okay, you have to trust the
president to know what he is doing. The Republicans are mean and
stupid but they have a point.
</P>
<P>
   The other day President Lyndon Johnson's oil portrait was
finally hung in Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle's office
beside those of other Democratic presidents of the modern era. In
unveiling the picture, Daschle noted Johnson's remarkable
legislative achievements, which alone would have defined a great
presidency. LBJ broke traditional barriers blocking federal aid to
education, initiated Medicare and Medicaid, mandated civil rights
in public facilities and equal rights in the voting booth, and
launched an ambitious war on poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's domestic legacy was overwhelmed by the disastrous
Vietnam War. By mismanaging it he squandered his place in history.
A generation despised it as ``Johnson's war'' _ although it was
also John Kennedy's and Richard Nixon's.
</P>
<P>
   This is what could happen to Clinton, already weakened by the
impeachment charade. In some ways Clinton is more like LBJ than
JFK, his own favorite for comparison purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment stemmed from his personal behavior, but warfare
is a different matter. Now Clinton is trapped in ugly circumstances
not of his making, as Johnson was, and has no good options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
