<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clouds swirling around a sluggish low pressure zone south of
Long Island on Tuesday will cover most areas from the northern
Appalachians to the Middle Atlantic Coast. Patchy rain and drizzle
will dampen much of the region, especially near the coast. Active
onshore breezes blowing across the chilly waters of the Atlantic
will keep temperatures far below the seasonal average along the
coast from southern New England to Virginia. Farther west,
steadfast high pressure will promote another mild day with ample
sunshine across the eastern part of the Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful jet stream disturbance will cause potent
thunderstorms with high wind gusts to sweep from northeastern Texas
and eastern parts of Kansas and Oklahoma early Tuesday into
Missouri, Arkansas and Iowa in the afternoon and evening. Strong,
shifting winds between the ground and 20,000 feet will impart
rotation to some of the storms raising the risk of tornadoes.
Farther north, variable clouds and some showers and thunderstorms
will precede a front in the eastern Dakotas and Minnesota. In the
wake of the front, clouds, scattered showers and cool breezes from
the north will prevail in much of the western Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Cool and unsettled weather will persist over the Northwestern
States. Clouds and a mixture of rain and snow showers will be
common along west-facing mountain slopes from the Cascades to the
northern Rockies. A mix of sun and clouds will occur in the lower
elevations. Meanwhile, the Southwest will be mainly sunny with
gusty breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Topsy-Turvy Weather
</P>
<P>
   The mercury managed only 68 degrees at Orlando, Fla., on
Saturday, setting a record for the lowest high temperature ever
observed there on May 1. Meanwhile, temperatures soared to a record
79 degrees at Marquette, Mich., on Saturday. The reversal of the
normal north-to-south distribution of temperatures was accompanied
by a topsy-turvy distribution in barometric pressure, with a warm
high over the Great Lakes and a cold low over the Southeast. In
turn, prevailing winds from the west were replaced by moist winds
from the east, which fueled rain in the Carolinas over the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
