A2716 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-03 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE DESIGNS ON YOUR OWN WEB PAGE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - What say we learn how to design a Web page? &QL; 
Aah, come on! It's easy! At least it's easier than filling out your
annual income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Why should you bother creating your own Web page? I can think of
several reasons. Here are two:
</P>
<P>
   1) The Web is an invaluable tool for communicating with people
in your neighborhood and around the world. Be a part of it!
</P>
<P>
   2) You might already have free ``Web space'' at your disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet service providers offer their customers free
personal Web space, or room on a computer for storing Web pages.
America Online, for example, provides 2 megabytes for each screen
name on an account. Other ISPs offer 5, 10 or more megabytes per
user.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you don't go over the limit, there should be no
additional charge for using this personal Web space. So why not use
it?
</P>
<P>
   Check with your ISP to see if your monthly access fee includes
Web space. And learn your ISP's Web-page rules. Can you design from
scratch? Or must you use a template? Is the free Web space strictly
for personal use? Or can you use it to sell your homemade salad
dressing? Are there space and content restrictions?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of content: Don't think your Web page needs to include
something earth-shattering, such as a cure for cancer. Put up
pictures of the grandkids or the dog. List links to your favorite
Web sites. Share family news. Display your artwork. Make a page for
your child's class. Write your life story. Post your resume. Tell
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The point in creating a personal Web page is to have fun, not
worry about how many visitors you will get. Certainly, it's good to
get lots of visitors, and that can be a goal. But don't think that
it's a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Have I convinced you yet? Yes? Good. Starting with this column,
we'll spend a few weeks looking at how to create simple Web pages.
We will cover the basics _ enough to get you started.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more than is presented here, there are many
avenues for you to follow.
</P>
<P>
   There are Web sites that cover beginning and advanced design. A
couple sites for beginners include junior.apk.net/jbarta/tutor/ or
home.earthlink.net/thomasareed/pixelpen/. (Note that neither
address has ``www'' at the beginning. Also, both contain tildes.)
</P>
<P>
   There also are many books available. My favorites include ``HTML
4 for the World Wide Web'' by Elizabeth Castro, published by
Peachpit Press, and ``HTML 4 for Dummies'' by Ed Tittel and Stephen
N. James, published by IDG Books.
</P>
<P>
   What do you need to design Web pages? Not much. Any text-editing
program will do. Notepad, supplied with Windows, works just fine.
The only other thing you will need is a browser. Whether it's
Netscape's Navigator or Microsoft's Internet Explorer makes no
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Many people use HTML editing software, such as CoffeeCup HTML
Design Editor. These programs make it easier to write HTML, the
language of Web pages. But they are not required.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many people use Web-page design software, such as
FrontPage 98. You can use these fancy _ and sometimes expensive _
programs to design pages without having to know HTML. But they can
be tricky to learn. And, again, they are not required for what we
will attempt here.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another tip before we get started: You can view the HTML
behind nearly any page you find on the Web! Windows users need only
right-click on an open portion of a Web page and choose ``View
Source.'' Macintosh users can do the same via a drop-down menu.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the HTML, or ``source code,'' of a page can make you
dizzy, especially if it's a complex page. But you can also get some
good ideas from what other people have done. Like the way a page
looks? View the source code to see how they did it.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what is HTML? It stands for ``HyperText Markup
Language.'' It's a $500 term that describes a 50-cent concept: The
text markers _ or tags _ that make things appear certain ways on
Web pages are written in a certain style, otherwise known as HTML.
</P>
<P>
   So how's it work? Think bookends. You want to keep a handful of
books upright on a shelf? You need two bookends _ one on the left,
one on the right. HTML works the same way. There is an opening
version and a closing version of most HTML tags. The stuff you put
between the opening and closing tags _ the content _ is affected by
the tags on either side.
</P>
<P>
   All opening tags are letters and/or numbers sandwiched between a
less-than symbol and a greater-than symbol. Closing tags are built
the same way, except they include a forward slash (/) after the
less-than symbol.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the opening tag that makes text appear in bold face
is b. The closing tag is /b. Want to make the word ``test'' appear
in bold? Do it like this: btest/b. Get it? Generally, this is how
all HTML tags work.
</P>
<P>
   A handy list of the most common HTML tags and what they do can
be found at www.willcam.com/cmat/html/crossref.html.
</P>
<P>
   Some HTML tags carry attributes and values. To set a specific
font for your page, you use the font tag with an attribute and a
value that lists the name of the font you want used. In this
example _ font face``arial'' _ ``font'' is the tag, ``face'' is the
attribute and ``arial'' is the value.
</P>
<P>
   As you get further into creating Web pages, you will learn that
you can use HTML tags together. This is called nesting tags. For
example, you can make the word ``test'' appear in both bold and
itallic like this: bitest/i/b.
</P>
<P>
   Notice the order in which the opening and closing tags appear in
the above example. This is important. You should always close the
most recently opened tag first.
</P>
<P>
   Say you want to create a Web page with blue text (font
color``blue'', /font), and you want a headline (h1, /h1) at the top
of your page with the words in itallic (i, /i).
</P>
<P>
   It would look like this: font color``blue''h1iThis is the
headline/i/h1/font.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make a quick page!
</P>
<P>
   Open a blank page in your text editor. Type an opening HTML tag
like this html. Then type an opening title tag like this title.
Type a title that will appear at the top of the browser window when
your page is viewed. Then, type /title.
</P>
<P>
   Next, type an opening body tag like this body.
</P>
<P>
   Then, skip down a ways and type a closing body tag like this
/body and a closing HTML tag like this /html. This is the structure
of a very basic Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Now, your page is ready for content, which goes between the
opening and closing body tags. Add anything. Type a sentence. Since
this is just a test page, have fun and experiment. Check the Web
page listed above for HTML tags to try.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a tip: An opening paragraph tag looks like this p. Use it
to add space between paragraphs. You can add a closing tag like
this /p, but it's usually not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to close the most recently opened tags first. And leave
the /body and /html tags at the bottom. Don't put any content below
them.
</P>
<P>
   When you save your page, give it a short first name followed by
``.html'' as in ``test.html.'' If you don't specify the ``html''
part, Notepad will call it ``txt'' and your browser will not open
the page properly.
</P>
<P>
   To view your page, open your browser (you don't have to go
online). In Navigator, click FILE and OPEN PAGE. Then click CHOOSE
FILE. Find test.html (or whatever you called your page) and
double-click on it. Then, click OPEN. Your page should open.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Explorer works the same way, except you click on BROWSE
instead of CHOOSE FILE, and OK instead of OPEN.
</P>
<P>
   View your page as you go. It's fun to experiment with a new tag,
save the file and then see what the results look like in your
browser. Remember to hit RELOAD or REFRESH to make your browser
redisplay your page after you've made changes.
</P>
<P>
   That's it for this week. Next week, we'll look at more basics,
including how to create links and how to make your pages more
colorful.
</P>
<P>
   Are you dizzy yet? I hope not! &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
