<SLUG> BC-STAGE-TONYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARADE' TOPS TONY NOMINATION FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Parade,'' a critical and commercial failure, led Monday's Tony
field with nine nominations; a play by the late Tennessee Williams
was nominated as the best new play of the year; ``Wit,'' the
Pulitzer-Prize winning drama, was ruled ineligible; and all three
of David Hare's plays were shut out in the best-play category, as
was the highly regarded ``The Weir.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's Tony time, with all the attendant Byzantine rules and
controversial omissions and commissions. The musical nominations
were real head-scratchers. That the incidental score for ``Twelfth
Night'' was nominated for best musical is one indication of how
weak the field is this year for both revivals and new work. On the
other hand, it was a particularly rich year for drama.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's ``Not About Nightingales'' was considered a new play
by the Tony committee because it had not been produced before.
Vanessa Redgrave discovered it among Williams's papers and brought
it to the National Theatre in England, who coproduced it with
Houston's Alley Theatre. Her brother, Corin, who starred in it, is
one of the play's six nominees, along with Trevor Nunn, the
director who's also head of the National.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Williams won't be competing with fellow American
masters Eugene O'Neill and Arthur Miller. O'Neill's ``The Iceman
Cometh'' and Miller's ``Death of a Salesman'' are the favorites in
the revival category and its highly regarded stars, Kevin Spacey
and Brian Dennehy, will duke it out for best actor over Redgrave
and Brian O'Byrne of ``The Lonesome West.'' ``Salesman'' also had
six nominations, ``Iceman'' five. Miller, incidentally, will
receive a lifetime achievement award as will Uta Hagen and
executive Isabelle Stevenson, who coordinates the Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   Two classics, ``Electra'' and ``Twelfth Night,'' round out the
revival category. Zoe Wanamaker was nominated for the former, but
Helen Hunt was not nominated for the latter. Warren Leight's ``Side
Man,'' Patrick Marber's ``Closer,'' and, surprisingly, Martin
McDonagh's ``Lonesome West'' were the other new-play nominees.
``Side Man'' might have the legs to win here since it's a new
American play, although ``Closer'' is the class of this category.
``Wit'' was not eligible because it has not been playing in a
theater large enough to be considered a Broadway stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Tony nominations clearly show that Broadway does not have
the economic or emotional wherewithal to produce serious plays any
longer. Except for ``Twelfth Night,'' all the nominees originated
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Regional theaters _ the Goodman in Chicago and the Alley in
Houston _ produced or coproduced ``Salesman'' and ``Nightingales,''
respectively. ``Side Man'' transferred from off-Broadway. The rest
proved themselves in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In the musical categories, Livent, the producing company that
went bankrupt, got some good news Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Parade,'' the musical it coproduced about the
Leo Frank lynching, ``Fosse'' the musical homage had eight
nominations. Frank Wildhorn's ``The Civil War'' was also nominated,
but look for ``Fosse'' or the acclaimed underdog, ``It Ain't
Nothin' but the Blues'' to win this one. In fact, Don Sebesky's
orchestrations might be the only award ``Parade'' takes home.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its lackluster reviews, ``Annie Get Your Gun'' with
Bernadette Peters could take the revival award. There's a
been-there, done that feel to the well-produced ``Peter Pan'' with
Cathy Rigby; ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' wasn't any better
received than ``Annie . . .''; and ``Little Me'' could be the
dictionary definition of mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Oscar winner Judi Dench will look to add a Tony to
the shelf for ``Amy's View,'' but Nicole Kidman was not nominated
for ``The Blue Room.'' The awards are June 6 and the search is
still on for a host to replace Rosie O'Donnell. If you're looking
to bet the mortgage, put your money on Bernadette Peters in
``Annie'' and Elizabeth Franz as Willy Loman's wife in
``Salesman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
