<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANOTHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANOTHER WORLD': GHOSTS, AND NOT THE FRIENDLY KIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her critically acclaimed trilogy (``Regeneration,'' ``The Eye
in the Door'' and ``The Ghost Road''), the English writer Pat
Barker worked an artful improvisation on the lives of the poets
Siegfried Sassoon, Wilfred Owen and Robert Graves and their World
War I compatriots to produce a powerful antiwar fiction that probed
the lasting emotional consequences of combat.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest novel, ``Another World,'' examines a related theme _
the hold of time past over time present _ through the prism of
three generations of a family living in Newcastle. Though Ms.
Barker has larded their story with portentous symbolism and some
specious talk of ghosts, her keen attention to psychological detail
enables her to reveal how these people's daily lives proceed in the
``shadow of monstrosities,'' in the shadow of death and loss and
casual cruelty, in the shadow of betrayal and self-deception.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 101, the family patriarch, Geordie, is reliving
the horrors of World War I as he lies in his sickbed; he is
convinced that he is dying from a bayonet wound received during the
war, not from the stomach cancer that is eating away at his body.
Almost every night he suffers terrible flashbacks that take him
back to the trenches of France, where his brother Harry died in
1916. Geordie blames himself for Harry's death; he remembers his
mother saying at Harry's memorial service, ``It should have been
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Geordie's grandson Nick is also grappling with fallout from the
past. Although Nick and his wife, Fran, have just settled into a
new house with their 2-year-old, Jasper, and have another baby on
the way, their fragile family harmony has been disrupted by their
stepchildren. Fran's hostile son, Gareth, spends all his free time
playing violent video games and trying to undermine his stepfather
(his favorite ploy is to run Nick's toothbrush under the toilet
bowl rim before replacing it in its holder), while Nick's teen-age
daughter, Miranda, nurses secret resentments and fears. She finds
it hard to forgive Nick for leaving her mother, who has been
hospitalized for depression.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nick's comfortably middle-class family enjoys a
considerably cushier life than the working-class characters in Ms.
Barker's gritty early novels (``The Century's Daughter,'' ``Blow
Your House Down'' and ``Union Street''), its members are subject to
the same sense that life is short, nasty and brutish. As Ms.
Barker's plot unfurls, we are made to see that the customary family
bonds of loyalty and devotion are often illusory, that love,
particularly fraternal love, can be highly conditional.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Barker's characters learn that mortality
lurks behind every endeavor, be it service in the Great War or a
simple family outing to the beach. For Nick, in particular, time
increasingly seems to move on fast forward. ``He seems to be living
in one of those speeded-up sequences beloved of wildlife
photographers,'' Ms. Barker writes. ``Fran's stomach swelling, the
children growing, the house rose blooming and decaying, Geordie
dwindling into death before his eyes. Time must move at a constant
pace, he supposes, but that's not how we experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   To symbolize the power the past continues to exert over the
present, Ms. Barker has contrived a macabre set piece that proves
as gratuitous as it is initially gripping: While removing the old
wallpaper in their living room, Nick and his family uncover an old
mural on the wall. It is a haunting and obscene painting of the
Fanshawe family, who previously owned the house _ a family, like
Nick's, with one young child and two older step-siblings _ a
family, Nick will later learn, at the center of a grisly murder.
When Miranda sees the mural, she darkly announces, ``It's us.''
</P>
<P>
   This heavy-handed attempt to draw parallels between the Fanshawe
family and Nick's not only proves to be a large red herring, but is
also a sensationalistic distraction from the moving story of Nick's
efforts to come to terms with Geordie and Geordie's efforts to come
to terms with his earlier life. It is also a distraction from the
very real virtues of this novel: Ms. Barker's nuanced depiction of
her characters' interior lives, her unsentimental rendering of
their daily travails and her finely calibrated delineation of the
workings of memory. In the end the visceral power of her writing
steamrollers the novel's very evident flaws, a novel, one hopes,
that will win this talented writer a wider audience in the United
States and send readers back to her earlier work.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANOTHER WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   By Pat Barker
</P>
<P>
   278 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
