<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CAMP-0504-COX     05-03 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAMP-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARAB ENTRY IN HUMANITARIAN AID ARENA IS A WINNER
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0504.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ They still wade through mud when it rains. And
there's no disguising that they live in tents on the stony ground.
But Kosovar refugees lucky enough to stay at the cutting edge
``Arab camp'' are treated to a bounty of luxuries inconceivable
till now in the desolate domain of refugee life.
</P>
<P>
   They have hot chicken stew for lunch and electricity in every
tent. Some sleep on metal-spring beds. Their field hospital soon
will boast a full-scale operating theater.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday afternoon five trucks loaded with gravel waited on
the edge of the narrow, potholed road bordering the camp to deal
with that mud problem that will reappear when the hot dry weather
gives way to summer storms.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of the so-called ``Arab camp'' are relative
newcomers to the world of big-time international humanitarian aid,
but the United Arab Emirates are building a show-stopper on what
was idle farmland just three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Obaid Al-Ketbi, commander of the military half of the
operation carried out in tandem with the UAE Red Crescent Society,
summed up the attitude in an interview Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an open budget for this mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of refugee cars park daily outside the fence ringing the
camp on the southern outskirts of Kukes, and scores of newly
arrived Kosovar Albanian exiles routinely sit on the grass awaiting
word that there is room for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are told these are the best conditions, here in this camp.
We heard it is run by Muslim people,'' said Nasar Veliu, 25, who on
Sunday was moving his extended family of 15 people into one of the
massive UAE tents that measure at least 30 by 18 feet and can sleep
40.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that this latest of the Balkan tragedies has engulfed a
predominantly Muslim population may have helped attract the UAE
largesse, although Al-Ketbi said only that his country saw a need
and responded.
</P>
<P>
   The tent set aside for use as a mosque is not the only element
differentiating this Arab camp from the Greek or Italian or other
camps blossoming on swaths of undeveloped land around this city.
The camps here commonly are known by the country or organization
that finances and manages the set-up of tents, latrines, food
service and other logistics of emergency living.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   This camp will be the biggest. It now has about 400 tents
holding an estimated 5,000 refugees, and those numbers are expected
to double, Al-Ketbi said.
</P>
<P>
   All services are provided or contracted by the UAE, while other
camps normally congregate services from agencies such as the World
Food Programme and Medecins du Monde (Doctors of the World).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to manage 100 percent by our own people,'' said
Al-Ketbi. ``We try to provide everything from the UAE government
and from our volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Saeed Al-bloushi, chief physician at the field hospital, has
up to 200 in-patient beds in tents. With justifiable pride he
described his facility as ``becoming a tertiary referral center for
the region,'' treating patients from other camps as well as local
Albanians sent from the Kukes hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The operating theater, radiology lab and first set of Kosovar
Albanian twins are expected to arrive any time, he said. The doctor
is comforted by the four camp generators that keep his lights and
new, state-of-the-art equipment on line.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most lavish and ultimately most impactive
expenditure is the airstrip that is expected to receive the first
C-130 loaded with UAE supplies this week. It will also be used by
NATO for humanitarian aid now, but will be improved enough to serve
eventually as a forward base for NATO war planes.
</P>
<P>
   Till now the UAE has flown supplies from its capital, Abu Dhabi
and from Europe to the Albanian capital Tirana, then sent them up
here via four UAE military helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Increased NATO use of the Tirana airport required the UAE to cut
back from four daily C-130 flights to only one or two, Al-Ketbi
said. So they decided to build up the old Albanian military air
strip about a mile down the road from the UAE camp. The C-130s will
fly here directly.
</P>
<P>
   The packed and graded airstrip is 950 meters long, or about half
a mile, said Lt. Col. Paolo Fregosi, the Italian lieutenant colonel
in charge of the NATO troops here as part of AFOR, the NATO
humanitarian aid mission. NATO troops already are based at the air
field and will run it.
</P>
<P>
   Radar and an imported control tower are yet to be installed, but
then the strip will be able to handle more traffic than a couple of
C-130s and NATO helicopters every day, Fregosi said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops plan to build a staging area to house refugees who
will be flown out, he said, as part of the effort to clear this
increasingly tense border area of the 100,000 refugees who could be
very vulnerable targets.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he suggested, the field could be used by NATO for
other purposes he would not specify.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for humanitarian purposes for the moment,'' said Fregosi.
``The future is in the hands of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
