<HEADER>
A2739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS04-COX     05-03 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks ready to do business
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Now, with the Hawks' regular season down to two games,
it's a question of needs and of what team responds best to
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks might have to win one more game _ tonight at Miami or
Wednesday against Washington in the Georgia Dome _ to hold onto
fourth place in the Eastern Conference. There also is the faint
hope of a Central Division title and No. 2 seed in the East, but
that scenario requires Cleveland to win at Indiana, plus two Hawks
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to respond better (against Miami) than we did
against Cleveland,'' Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens promised after his
team struggled to put away the depleted Cavaliers 76-65 Sunday
night. He blamed the absence of energy and focus on Friday's
disappointment against the Pacers, a 92-90 overtime loss at home.
</P>
<P>
   Dikembe Mutombo agreed with his coach. ``We will be ready for
Miami,'' Mutombo said. ``You will see a different team. We know
what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the Hawks rarely are ready for the heat Miami brings
to its games. They've lost seven of their last nine to Pat Riley's
team, with Mutombo consistently out-muscled by his former
Georgetown teammate, Alonzo Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens says Mutombo will fare better this time. Against
Cleveland, Mutombo had only eight rebounds and five points.
``Except for that, Deek's been focused every night. ,'' Wilkens
said. ``You have to have that when you play Miami. You have to be
ready for their double teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Tacitly conceding that he has been a relatively easy mark for
fellow Hoya alums Mourning and Patrick Ewing, Mutombo has taken a
harder line with them that precludes socializing.
</P>
<P>
   He refused Ewing's invitation to dinner last Tuesday when the
Knicks came to town and said he would not visit with Mourning
before tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all summer to get together and talk,'' Mutombo said.
``But this is business. Patrick and 'Zo are my friends, but they
are also my opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   With only a game in New York remaining on its schedule after
tonight, Miami needs one victory to clinch home-court advantage
through all three rounds of the Eastern Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In a small sidelight to the game, the Hawks have replaced Miami
as the stingiest team in the NBA. The Hawks allow 83 points a game,
and the Heat's average climbed to 83.8 after stunning losses to
Boston and Chicago and Sunday's 100-93 victory over Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence that the Heat's average went up when
Mourning missed both losses. After suffering a slight fracture of
his right eye orbit, he came back Sunday with 19 points, 12
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have been hit hard by a rash of minor eye injuries. Ty
Corbin will not play tonight after suffering a fracture of his left
eye socket Friday. Alan Henderson had his left eye raked Sunday
night. Squinting after the game, he complained of blurred vision.
It took two days for Steve Smith's right eye to return to normal
after Larry Johnson poked him last week.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson wondered Sunday if he should return to Atlanta for
medical attention, but Mutombo would not hear of it. ``You're
coming with us,'' he told the younger player. ``We need you with
us. They have doctors in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson did go home. He and Corbin were examined Monday
morning, and Henderson was declared out until Wednesday. Corbin,
wearing goggles, also should be available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
