<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-STADIUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soccer supporters want stadium built
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After waiting too late to try save an old stadium, a
group of Atlanta soccer leaders figured they needed a better way to
fight for their sport in a city that didn't seem to care. The
fledging Save Our Stadium organization routinely blasted political
and business leaders who did nothing to change the fate of
Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium; the soccer group envisioned the
stadium as a soccer venue after the Braves baseball club moved out.
</P>
<P>
   But when the wrecking ball finally came down in the summer of
1997, it galvanized Save Our Stadium members to keep plugging away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned a lesson the hard way,'' said Robert Tracey, a
former board member of the group. ``It just made us more
tenacious.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking on the power structure, the soccer diehards
joined a growing cadre of Atlanta business figures, and unveiled
plans Monday for a $100 million ``Atlanta Soccer Village,'' billed
as the first of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   With the aim of helping make Atlanta the ``sports capital of the
world,'' the proposed complex would serve as a magnet to lure a
Major League Soccer franchise, as well as host of international
soccer matches, youth and adult amateur tournaments and other
sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Making the announcement at the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce
were former Atlanta Chiefs coach and North American Soccer League
commissioner Phil Woosnam and veteran public-relations executive
Amanda Brown-Olmstead, the project's manager. The complex would be
built under the auspices of the Georgia State Soccer Association,
but it also would have significant business backing for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you bring professionalism to our
passion for soccer,'' said Rex Hardaway, chairman of the soccer
association's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   But the two most critical details of the proposal _ a 200-acre
site and financing _ are yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Soccer Village Management Corporation is considering
five sites, and soon will make public presentations in those
communities. Project officials have declined to identify specific
property locations, but they said they hope to make a site decision
by the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the proposal, a 25,000-seat stadium,
expandable to 40,000, would be only the second soccer-specific
stadium in the United States. On May 15, Atlanta Soccer Village
officials will be in Columbus, Ohio, where the MLS Crew franchise
will christen a 22,500-seat facility built by team investor Lamar
Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   MLS sent a representative to Atlanta for Monday's announcement,
and U.S. Soccer Federation secretary general Hank Steinbrecher flew
in for the occasion. ``When the GSSA says it's a great project, we
know it's going to be a great project,'' Steinbrecher said.
Brown-Olmstead said project funding would come from a variety of
sources, almost all of them private. A stadium would be the first
of three steps required to earn MLS consideration for its 2003
expansion phase. The city must line up potential franchise
investors and demonstrate support for the resuscitated A-League
Atlanta Silverbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for real, folks,'' Hardaway said, ``and we're going to
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
