<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     05-03 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING LIVES IN THE AIR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A talented young colleague of mine died suddenly in her kitchen
a few years ago despite everything her husband and an emergency
squad could do. I found the funeral particularly difficult because
a medical expert had told me she need not have died; that a heart
in cardiac arrest in an otherwise healthy person could be restarted
with almost no damage provided it is done quickly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defibrillators, which can do the job in time, are a familiar
prop on hospital television dramas, where they are wheeled
on-screen _ ponderous and complex machines. But defibrillators are
also now available as automated battery-driven devices that cost
about $3,000 and are the size and weight of a desk dictionary.
Amusement parks have them. Casino hotels in Las Vegas have them.
Airports have them. EMS has them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And now more airlines are getting them and training their
employees to use them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without a defibrillator, an airborne plane is among the worst
places to suffer cardiac arrest because effective help is at least
half an hour away, on the ground. But with a defibrillator, the
compact fuselage, where everyone can be kept seated in an
emergency, may be one of the most best places to put a
defibrillator to work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The key to saving a life in cardiac arrest is speed. When cells
are deprived of blood, they begin to die, and that includes brain
cells. Medical studies show, and the Red Cross and other agencies
teach, that chances of survival decrease 10 percent with every
minute that passes without circulation of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Quick application of cardiopulmonary resuscitation can force
blood out of an inactive heart into the body as a holding action.
But a defibrillator can shock the heart into working again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To reassure myself that I could handle an emergency, I recently
took the Red Cross four-and-a-half-hour class on how to help others
with cardiopulmonary resuscitation, rescue breathing and a
defibrillator.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deaths occur on airplanes with some regularity. In the six
months between July 1 and Dec. 31 last year, the major United
States airlines reported that 103 passengers had become acutely
sick on board, and that planes were diverted to the nearest airport
to get help 34 times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the 103 people stricken, at least 56 died in flight or later
in a hospital. (The outcome of some hospitalization cases was not
known.) Not all the causes were cardiac arrest, of course; there
were cases of asthma and terminal cancer and hemorrhages.
</P>
<P>
   But one case in particular struck me: A 43-year-old man
traveling from Palm Beach, Fla., to Newark, N.J., last summer was
helped by three fellow passengers _ all with some
medical-assistance training _ while the plane was diverted to
Jacksonville, Fla. The passenger was dead by the time the plane
landed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the heading ``defibrillator'' on the reports are four
choices: ``not needed,'' ``shock delivered,'' ``monitor only'' and
``not available.'' This last choice was what was checked off in the
report by the airline, whose identity is not given on the form. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is the now-famous Michael Tighe, a
Boston public health officer saved at 62 by an American Airlines
flight attendant, an emergency medical technician, a physician, a
nurse and a ``shock delivered'' aboard a plane going from Boston to
Los Angeles and diverted to Denver.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tighe's is not the only life saved on this airline since it
began installing defibrillators in July 1997, according to
American's medical director, Dr. David McKenas. He said that on
eight occasions the devices took readings and were activated to
administer shocks. Of these eight patients, five were revived,
although one died later in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   This was a survival rate of 62 percent, McKenas pointed out, or
50 percent if the hospital death is included in the nonsurvival
column. The survival rate for field rescue work by EMS squads and
the like is 10 percent, because of the delay in getting
defibrillators to patients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Qantas, the Australian airline, began installing defibrillators
in 1991, and reports it has eight long-term survivors out of at
least 23 people with heart attacks. The most recent success at
Qantas, according to Agnes Huff, a spokeswoman, was at a departure
gate at Chek Lap Kok Airport in Hong Kong on Feb. 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After July 1 the office of the federal air surgeon, Dr. Jon L.
Jordan, will have a year's worth of statistics for domestic
airlines. The figures are being collected under a provision of the
Aviation Medical Assistance Act of 1998. Congress wanted the data
for an evaluation of the medical kits now required on United States
planes. The act also provides immunity from lawsuits to good
Samaritans who help in emergencies on airplanes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the study, Jordan said, the FAA, of which he is
the chief medical officer, can decide to propose a rule changing
the medical kit requirements it has established, it can stand pat
or it can turn the matter back to Congress for action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, airlines are buying portable defibrillators. In
addition to Qantas, Virgin Atlantic and Air Zimbabwe were early
among foreign airlines. Varig of Brazil and Swissair _ and
doubtless other foreign lines _ have them. British Airways has
begun installation and training of its flight attendants and
expects to have all 250 planes equipped within a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the domestic lines, things have been moving faster lately,
possibly because of the wide publicity given to American's success
in November. Delta says its planes will all have defibrillators by
June. US Airways has the devices on a third of its fleet and
expects to complete the job by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   United will start installation later in the year, its spokesman
says, and will finish by March 2000. Continental is ``still
evaluating them,'' as is Trans World Airways, whose spokesman, Jim
Brown, said that a decision would be made after the FAA study was
complete. Northwest said it was planning defibrillators for its
fleet although a date has not been fixed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises, based in Los Angeles and Seattle, announced in
March that its fleet of 10 vessels was getting 65 portable
defibrillators to augment the hospital models in its infirmaries.
Disney also has five ``strategically located'' portable
defibrillators aboard its Magic, along with two in the clinic.
Kiersten Murane, a spokeswoman, says the Wonder will be identically
equipped when she goes into service Aug. 15. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The big advantage of the portable defibrillator, which experts
are now calling an AED, for automatic external defibrillator, is
that it leaves virtually no space for mishandling by a nonmedical
person. I took my training on the Heartstream by Hewlett-Packard of
Seattle, but the Lifepak 500, made by Medtronic Physio-Control in
Redmond, Wash., has the same safeguards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Red Cross class, which was organized for seven of the
agency's own employees on Amsterdam Avenue in New York, mock-ups of
the Heartstream were used. They are identical to the real thing,
right down to the recorded voice that tells the operator what is
going on, but they do not administer a shock. The dummies used for
CPR training are also used for defibrillator training: they are
part of the same sequence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our instructor, Deanna Ambroso, covered procedures in detail,
including how to take off rubber gloves _ needed for rescue
breathing _ without contaminating your hands. She warned about not
using the device on a wet or metallic surface. The class went
through a sequence of possibilities, from someone's choking through
someone's being unconscious, not breathing and having no pulse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The classroom defibrillators could be programmed for various
scripts, including misapplication of the plastic pads to the
patient. When the cords, plugs and plastic pads are unfolded for
use, there is a diagram on each pad showing where it is to be
applied to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   The sticky side goes onto the skin without any jelly or stickum.
The real kit, which I examined in The New York Times' medical
department, has razors to shave chest hair, which may keep the pads
from adhering. The plug on the cord is stuck into the the machine
and it is turned on. The voice says it is monitoring the heart and
no one should touch the patient. It may then say that a shock
should be administered and everyone is to stand back. Administering
the shock involves pressing a button. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All this is a good deal less difficult than administering CPR,
which is probably going to be necessary in an emergency while
someone gets the defibrillator, or calls for help. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is starting pilot programs in 17 cities for
companies that want to own defibrillators and train their
employees: Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Denver, Detroit,
Durham, N.C., Farmington, Conn., Honolulu, Houston, Kansas City,
Mo., Los Angeles, Miami, New York, Philadelphia, Seattle and St.
Louis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local Red Cross chapters can provide information about classes.
For corporations in New York, the Greater New York Red Cross number
is (212) 875-2034. The American Heart Association is also providing
rescue courses that include defibrillator training. Information:
(800) 242-8721.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
