<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIAONE-COX     05-03 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T offer accepted by board; Comcast can counter
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AT&AMP;T Corp. edged closer to victory Monday in its bid
to buy MediaOne Group Inc. _ all without firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The huge company's offer for MediaOne, originally valued at $62
billion, was accepted over the weekend by the cable provider's
board, which gave rival bidder Comcast until Thursday to top the
AT&AMP;T proposal. And while Comcast has yet to publicly respond to the
deadline, it apparently lost a potential partner who could have
helped pool enough stock and cash to out-bid AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   America Online was reported by CNBC to have dropped out of talks
with Comcast and Microsoft aimed at hammering out a plan to combine
resources in a bidding war against AT&AMP;T. America Online declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In March, MediaOne accepted a $52 billion offer from Comcast.
That agreement included a $1.5 billion payment to Comcast if some
other bidder succeeding in purchasing the company.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Comcast was still considering whether to mount
another bid. Should AOL withdraw, Comcast would be left hoping
Microsoft or another company will help pony up the needed money.
And since AT&AMP;T's offer out-did the original Comcast offer for
MediaOne by about $8 billion, any counter-bid now must be high
enough to at least give AT&AMP;T pause, or else AT&AMP;T will simply up the
ante again.
</P>
<P>
   Many metro Atlanta consumers may be forgiven puzzlement at the
furor over MediaOne. The largest area cable provider with more than
500,000 customers, MediaOne's reputation has been uneven at best.
MediaOne has long maintained that it has worked hard to improve
inadequate customer service, but its image has continued to take a
battering. Earlier this year, the service of a number of MediaOne
cable customers was accidentally cut off during the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere, MediaOne's systems are viewed with approval and
even envy. The company has large operations in Boston, Detroit, Los
Angeles, Miami and Minneapolis, but virtually all those MediaOne
systems were bought from Continental Cablevision, which was known
as a top-flight cable company. By contrast, Atlanta operations were
purchased from two companies, GCTV and Wometco. Wometco, which
represented the larger share of customers, had a splotchy service
record.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what makes MediaOne so attractive elsewhere is also being
done in Atlanta. The company has spent hundreds of millions of
dollars upgrading the systemto bring every customer interactive
services including video and television, as well as high-speed
Internet access and telephone service, too.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne has more than 100,000 high-speed customers, who receive
a version of the Internet access service called Road Runner that
was developed with Time Warner, Microsoft, Compaq and Newhouse.
AT&AMP;T has a different cable provided high-speed service, called At
Home.
</P>
<P>
   But what AT&AMP;T really wants is MediaOne's fat pipeline to the
Internet. And it is that broadband pipe that Microsoft wants access
to, as well. AT&AMP;T is willing to buy most of that broadband access _
at least for starters.
</P>
<P>
   A richer deal
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has offered $30.85 a share in cash, plus 95 percent of a
share for each MediaOne share. The various offers on the table have
been valued differently, partly because the stock prices have
fluctuated and partly because some reports do not include the debt
that the buyer would absorb.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being $8 billion higher, the AT&AMP;T offer includes
a cash component and voting stock _ which Comcast had not proposed.
</P>
<P>
   America Online has no cash, but could contribute its stock to
any deal-making. Those shares are currently worth $124 billion, but
have been subject to the roller-coaster of Net stocks. Microsoft,
which has also asked for the information needed to make a bid, can
more easily afford to join the fray. But does it truly have the
will?
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock is worth $403 billion _ more than twice that
of AT&AMP;T's _ and it also has a hefty pile of cash _ $20 billion _
that could sweeten any deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet strategy may be more crucial to Microsoft than simple
short-term finances. Microsoft wants badly to sell software to
cable companies for high-speed and interactive services that will
be delivered via set-top boxes. Microsoft already has an investment
in Comcast. Teaming up with Comcast in a winning bid would give
Microsoft access to tens of millions of customers.
</P>
<P>
   But if Microsoft wins the battle for MediaOne's set-top boxes it
may risk losing the war by aggravating AT&AMP;T, which became the
nation's second-largest cable company when it purchased
Tele-Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, what if Microsoft sides with Comcast and then loses?
</P>
<P>
   What Microsoft might settle for, is a little bit of both.
Already a part owner of Comcast, Microsoft may be threatening a bid
for MediaOne in order to play for a better deal with AT&AMP;T. AOL too
might prefer to have a lucrative deal with every cable company
rather than even an exclusive pact with one.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other potential partners for Comcast. Former
Microsoft founder Paul Allen, who in Charter Communications has
been putting together his own cable company, is also reportedly
interested.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
