A2746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOV0-WARNER-COX     05-03 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOV0-WARNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force base plays key role in Kosovo conflict
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARNER ROBINS, Ga. _ Far from the war-torn Balkans, 11,000
Middle Georgians in a mostly civilian force are working overtime to
support the allied war effort in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The huge Warner Robins Air Logistic Center at Robins Air Force
Base is responsible for repairing or replacing about 80 percent of
the electronic equipment and weapons systems on U.S. fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees are working 12-hour days, 7 days a week, said Air
Force Major General Richard N. Goddard. Some units are totaling up
to 75 percent more hours than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gearing to the need. I try to tell our people that we're
in a war. They aren't calling it a war,'' Goddard said.
</P>
<P>
   A steady stream of crates and boxes, some 218,000 pounds in all,
leave the base every day by commercial carrier. Many are marked
with the code numbers ``999'' meaning they are bound for the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 15 warehouses with over 250,000 items here. Everything
from nuts and bolts to F-15 wings,'' said Col. Joe Carter, who
heads the defense distribution depot.
</P>
<P>
   It's Carter's job to make sure that everything necessary leaves
the center on time.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, are a legion of electronics technicians, airplane
mechanics, metal workers and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   This is Georgia's largest industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   One of five such centers that support military operations
throughout the world, this center handles all regularly
scheduledmaintenance on the F-15 fighters used in Kosovo. It also
maintains most of the Air Force's air cargo planes, including the
giant C-5A.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining the military's aging fleet is a tricky business,
said Debbie Walker, chief of industrial production.
</P>
<P>
   Many manufacturers and suppliers of equipment when aircraft
first came into production are no longer in business. To keep the
aircraft flying, workers at Warner Robins have to manufacture many
of the parts.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest challenge, said Goddard, is keeping 30-40 year-old
airplanes flying. The center has ``world class'' industrial and
engineering capabilities, said Goddard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A C-5 might need only one particular part that isn't made any
more. We manufacture it here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Whitt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
