<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPSQ&AMP;A-0504     05-03 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPSQ&AMP;A-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A: ``I'M NOT SCARED ANY MORE'': A GULF WAR VETERAN GIRDS FOR
HIS SECOND WAR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0504.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ Fear is part of preparing for war.
</P>
<P>
   It's something most of the of the 5,000 American combat troops
here won't talk about -- least of all with us ``pukes'' from the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Kevin Boldin of the 1st Armored Division(CQ) is an
exception. At 29, Boldin has been there and done it. So he doesn't
mind opening up about what war anxiety is like when you are young.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers what it feels like in the pit of your stomach when
you have to sneak over a hostile border at night and clear
anti-tank mines while you're wearing a chemical weapons suit.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he did when he was a 20-year-old recent graduate of
Carver High School in Columbus, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   During the Gulf War, Boldin was then one of the farthest forward
troops. He was a combat engineer of the 1st Infantry Division.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's 29 and has a wife and two kids back at his base in
Baumholder, Germany. He's getting ready for his second war, maybe
the world's last war of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Boldin spoke to Cox Newspapers correspondent Joseph Albright as
the tall, imposing soldier stood next to the big armored car with
gun turrets that he commands. It's called a Bradley Fighting
Vehicle. It's the battlefield taxi that carries seven infantrymen
as they dash forward just behind the first wave of tanks.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Boldin's Bradley is assigned to guard this runway that
sits 64 miles from the border of Yugoslavia's embattled Kosovo
province. If a ground war starts, he could well be ordered forward
as part of a NATO effort to breach Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's front lines. He and his fellow soldiers haven't been
told what's going to happen, but they wouldn't be surprised if it's
ground combat.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about what it's like in your gut before a battle.
</P>
<P>
   Boldin was next to a vast field of rutted and slowing drying mud
a foot deep. The generals call this place ``Hawkbase.'' That's the
new name of the encampment by the runway for the Apache helicopter
gunships and their 5,000 U.S. Army support troops.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Boldin had to say:
</P>
<P>
   Q: So where did you end up in the Gulf War
</P>
<P>
   A: We went into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So now you are here for another one.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, here for another one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So how does it feel like?
</P>
<P>
   A: Back then, I was, you know, a little scared. I am not scared
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Not even a little bit?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not even a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because it's my job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You know how to do it . . .
</P>
<P>
   A: I know how to do it now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So back then in the Gulf, your job was clearing roads and
stuff like
</P>
<P>
   that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, and mine fields.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This was on the first night of the ground war?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, we had to clear 'em. It was called the Big Breach.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After that, nothing scares you?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, nothing scares me. I don't think I'm supposed to be here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did it come close then?
</P>
<P>
   A: Didn't come close. I guess I'm blessed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what is different about this deployment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Now, I got the mud. I liked the sand better. You don't have
to worry about your books getting all muddy, and you got to scrape
them off at night and stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It must have been tough at the beginning here with all the
mud?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, you get used to it. It's getting better now,
everything is all right now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the mood of the troops? What are people thinking?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hmm, well. You know, you got younger soldiers, they're kind
of, you know, they're kind of scared. You know it's normal, it's
natural.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So now they're the ones looking up to you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, they're the ones looking up to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: They're asking what was it like in the Gulf War?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you tell em?
</P>
<P>
   A: I say, once I was in your shoes. And you know, I know where
you're coming from. They're going to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the Gulf War, there were still some people around from
Vietnam?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh yeah. A lot of 'em. But there is nobody from Vietnam now.
They've all retired.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
