<HEADLINE>
TURKEY SCANDALIZED BY WOMAN'S WEARING OF SCARF IN PARLIAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Last week, almost no one in Turkey had heard
of Merve Kavakci. Now, she stands accused of nothing less than
trying to destroy the nation, and Turks are talking of little else.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit has begun assembling a new
government, but few seem to care. Even the figure of Abdullah
Ocalan, the captured Kurdish revolutionary, who is intensely hated,
has suddenly faded from the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Front pages of Monday's newspapers were dominated by large
photos of Ms. Kavakci on the floor of Parliament, where her
appearance with a head scarf on Sunday sparked pandemonium.
Television stations endlessly rebroadcast tape showing members of
Parliament angrily waving their arms and shouting insults at her.
</P>
<P>
   The country's chief prosecutor, Vural Savas, announced that he
had opened a criminal investigation. He may charge her with
violating a law that punishes anyone who ``openly incites people to
enmity and hatred by pointing to differences of class, race,
religion or creed.''
</P>
<P>
   In some Muslim countries, laws or social pressures force women
to cover their heads. Here the reverse is true. Wearing the scarf
in public universities, courtrooms and especially in Parliament is
strictly taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Secularism is one of the pillars of the Turkish Republic.
Powerful military and civilian leaders believe that the head scarf
is being used as a symbol by fundamentalists whose ultimate goal is
to pull Turkey away from the modern world and back toward religious
obscurantism.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, no woman who wore a head scarf had ever been
elected to the Turkish Parliament. Two were elected in April. One
appeared at the inaugural session on Sunday without her scarf, to
the vigorous applause of her colleagues. The other, Ms. Kavakci,
who is a member of the religious-oriented Virtue Party, refused to
remove hers.
</P>
<P>
   As tension rose in the parliamentary chamber, a 45-minute recess
was declared, and when members returned, Ms. Kavakci was absent. As
a result, she did not take her oath of office. She may soon be
stripped of her seat under a rule that allows the expulsion of
members who miss five consecutive sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is an agent provocateur,'' President Suleyman Demirel
asserted in a television interview. ``What she has done is
separatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavakci, 31, appeared before journalists Monday to read a
statement. ``Know this,'' she declared. ``I will defend to the end
this office that the people have given me, in a manner suited to a
woman from the Virtue Party, with this appearance and within the
law. I cover my head in accordance with my religious beliefs. It is
a personal choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavakci may have set the stage for a new round of
confrontation between secularists and those who favor a greater
role for religion in Turkish life. The Virtue Party is the
successor to the Welfare Party, which was banned last year on the
grounds that it was anti-secular. A case in which the government
seeks to ban Virtue is now pending.
</P>
<P>
   Virtue leaders have been trying to portray their party as
different from Welfare, asserting that it is ready to work within
the secular system. That argument now becomes more difficult to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders point out, however, that there is no explicit ban
on the head scarf in Parliament. ``We don't want to confront the
state, which is our state,'' said a senior Virtue leader, Abdullah
Gul. ``But if the state doesn't accept you, you have to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's confrontation might someday be the subject of a tale
called ``Necmettin Erbakan's Revenge.'' Erbakan is the guiding
figure in the Islamic political movement. He became prime minister
in 1996, but a year later was forced to resign, under intense
pressure from secularist military officers. Later his party was
outlawed, and he was banned from politics for five years.
</P>
<P>
   He has reportedly been running Virtue from behind the scenes,
though, and placing Ms. Kavakci on its list of candidates was
reportedly his idea. Thus he planted a time bomb in the heart of
the political establishment. It exploded on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
