<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-9     05-03 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN IMMIGRANTS WOOED BY FRONT-RUNNERS IN ISRAELI ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHDOD, Israel _ The middle-aged man spoke the halting, simple
Hebrew of a new immigrant, and with a habitual wariness learned
back in Moscow, he would identify himself only by his first name.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander, a factory worker who came to Israel from Russia
two years ago, could not have been clearer about his choice for
prime minister in the Israeli election on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Netanyahu,'' he said as he strolled with his mother
through an immigrant neighborhood in this southern coastal city.
``I'm against giving up territory to the Arabs, because we'll end
up with no country. The Arabs want it all. You can't make peace
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Alexander asserted, Ehud Barak, the Labor Party
candidate, who is the main opponent of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, is a socialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Russia, and I know what socialism is,'' he said. ``We
don't want socialism here.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter that Labor has moved away from the socialist vision of
its early leaders, or that Barak wants to keep chunks of West Bank
territory in a final peace deal with the Palestinians. Many of the
780,000 immigrants who have come to Israel in the last decade from
the former Soviet Union favor Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of the Russian immigrant votes were for him in
the last national election in 1996, post-election surveys
indicated, and current polls show similar levels of support.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in an authoritarian state with vast territories, many of
the Russian-speaking immigrants instinctively prefer Netanyahu's
image of a strong leader who stands tough on ceding land to the
Arabs. A collective memory of Soviet anti-Jewish repression and
resurgent anti-Semitism in Russia have contributed to a surge of
Israeli nationalism among the newcomers that tilts many of them to
the right.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because they lack the entrenched political identities of
veteran Israelis, the same immigrants are seen by the candidates as
the most susceptible to persuasion, forming a critical voting bloc
that might be swayed more easily than other groups.
</P>
<P>
   With about 580,000 eligible voters, about one-seventh of the
Israeli electorate, the Russian-speaking immigrants are being
vigorously courted by both front-runners in the race for prime
minister. Both have appealed to Russian voters in television ads,
using Russian subtitles to get their messages across.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest community whose attitude is still
changeable,'' said Ephraim Sneh, a Labor lawmaker who is in charge
of Barak's campaign among the Russian immigrants. He cited recent
opinion polls indicating that a quarter of the Russians were
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye to their votes, Netanyahu and his most powerful
political ally, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, have visited Moscow
in recent weeks, meeting Russian leaders and granting interviews to
Russian television stations that are heavily watched by immigrants
on cable broadcasts back in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The visits were billed as strictly diplomatic, focused on
curbing reported leaks of Russian nuclear and missile technology to
Iran and arms sales to Syria. But they seem to have had an impact
on the immigrants, many of whom still feel linked to their native
land.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll published by Israel's most widely circulated
newspaper, Yediot Ahronot, 26 percent of the immigrants surveyed
said they would be more inclined to vote for Netanyahu if he worked
to improve Israel's ties with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting an uphill battle in largely hostile territory, Barak
has struck back with overtures of his own, using a Russian-language
campaign jingle and a personal message to immigrant voters in his
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   He has addressed the uneasiness of the largely secular
immigrants with Israel's Orthodox rabbinic establishment, which has
questioned the Judaism of many new arrivals and set tough standards
for the conversion of those it deems not Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has served notice that in his Cabinet the interior
minister, whose department registers immigrants as Jews and grants
them citizenship, will not come from Shas, the Sephardic
ultra-Orthodox party.
</P>
<P>
   Shas has controlled the powerful Interior Ministry for more than
a decade as a crucial partner in a series of governing coalitions.
But the ministry's treatment of immigrants not recognized as Jews,
some of whom it has deported, has angered the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said the ministry should be run by an immigrant, the
main campaign demand of Yisrael B'Aliya, the Russian immigrant
party headed by Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with Russian voters, Sneh argues that Barak's peace
policies will improve the Israeli economy while Netanyahu's hard
line will lead to deepening diplomatic stalemate and economic
recession that will cost immigrants their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is depicted as slavishly bowing to the whims of his
ultra-Orthodox allies, while Barak is described as a cultured
candidate whose world view is closer to that of the immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the immigrants' lack of familiarity with Barak works against
him, along with their perception that he lacks Netanyahu's ability
to drive a hard bargain while resisting diplomatic pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Barak is strong enough to stand up to the
Americans, or strong enough to negotiate with the Palestinians and
the Syrians,'' said Mark Livshitz, an engineer living in Ashdod who
emigrated eight years ago from Ukraine. ``Netanyahu is stronger.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The imprint of anti-Jewish repression in the Soviet Union and
grass-roots anti-Semitism in present-day Russia has led many
immigrants to conclude that only a tough stand will insure Israel's
survival. So they admire Netanyahu's defiance of American
diplomatic pressure to give ground in negotiations with the
Palestinians and consider territorial concessions a dangerous
gamble with national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a strong leader,'' said Lev Melamed, deputy editor
in chief of Vesty, the most widely circulated Russian-language
newspaper in Israel. ``Having lived in a country that was a
superpower, they take the imperialistic view that you don't cede
land. Peace should be made from a position of strength, and if you
give up land you're showing weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman Bronfman, a Parliament member from Yisrael B'Aliya, said
the newcomers were products of their Soviet upbringing. ``They
carry the conceptual baggage of a totalitarian regime,'' he said,
``and Netanyahu represents a more totalitarian approach, with his
message of `a strong leader for a strong nation.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dermer, a political strategist for Yisrael B'Aliya, said
opinion polls he had conducted indicated that seven out of 10
Russian immigrant voters would choose Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your model of leadership depends on what country you're
from,'' Dermer said. ``The immigrants haven't lived with the
Arab-Israeli struggle long enough to get tired of it. There's no
fatigue factor, so they're going to take a harder line. When they
see terrorism they want a harsh response.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
