u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-ATTEMPTEDMURDER-     05-03 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-ATTEMPTEDMURDER-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman goes on trial for attempted murder of newborn
 &HT;    By Ken McCall
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN CO., Ohio _ Deborah Mackey buried her face in her hands
Monday morning and cried quietly as she listened to her
tape-recorded attempts at explaining why she gave birth in a
Franklin factory bathroom last December and then left her newborn
baby in a trash can.
</P>
<P>
   The recorded police interrogation provided the most dramatic
moments in the first day of Mackey's trial on charges of attempted
murder and child endangering. The 38-year-old Carlisle native has
pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity and waived her right to a
jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what came over me,'' Mackey told Franklin Police
Det. Rick Thacker from her hospital bed, just four hours after she
gave birth. ``I was scared and something just happened that I did
such a horrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey broke down crying on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I did it,'' she said, sobbing. ``I can't
believe it. I There's no excuse for what I did. I know it was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting behind Mackey, more than a dozen of her family members
fought back tears as they listened to the tape in Warren County
Common Pleas Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be punished. I know that,'' Mackey said during
the interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel sorry for me. I don't. As I said, what I did was
cold and heartless.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey told the detective that she never told anyone she was
pregnant, including the father, her live-in boyfriend. She said she
intended to give the baby up for adoption, although she admitted
she had made no plans or contacted any agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to have a better life than the one I could give
it,'' she told Thacker. ``But from what I did it's not very
obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   When the detective accused her of leaving her baby in a trash
can ``to die'' and said that was no way to preserve a better life,
Mackey said on the tape, ``I don't know. Something was happening in
my head. Something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey's attorney, Don Oda, said in his opening arguments to
Judge P. Daniel Fedders that he would show his client was legally
insane at the time she gave birth. He cited the prosecution's own
psychologist, Bobbie Hopes, who he said would testify Mackey has
``schizotypal personality disorder'' and underwent a transient
psychotic episode when she gave birth. As a result of her
condition, he said, Mackey sometimes cannot relate to people and
``loses touch with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Police, he predicted, would describe Mackey as ``detached,
unusually calm, quiet'' during the hours after the birth and
abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Thacker agreed during cross-examination that Mackey
appeared mostly emotionless and expressionless when he interviewed
her in her hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Wendy Ford, who investigates child abuse for Butler
County, said Mackey was emotionally ``very flat'' during several
interviews in days following the birth.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant County Prosecutor Andy Sievers promised in his
opening remarks that evidence would show Mackey knew full well what
she was doing when she repeatedly refused offers of assistance in
the bathroom of Ample Industries, claiming that blood on the floor
was the result of unexpected menstruation.
</P>
<P>
   Her attempts to clean up and hide evidence of the birth and her
clear recollection of events, Sievers asserted, would show that
Mackey was legally sane.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, her abandonment of Holly Ann in the cold
bathroom harmed her and would have killed her if she had not been
discovered by a cleaning lady.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to hospital reports from the day of her birth that
found Holly Ann had severe hypothermia, frostbite on her left hand
and feet, and respiratory distress syndrome _ all caused by her
abandonment in the trash can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of abandonment and selfishness,'' he said.
``She clearly attempted to kill that baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense was scheduled to begin this morning at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ken McCall writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
