<HEADER>
A2766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HALL04-COX     05-03 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HALL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS MEMBERS SAW 'MISERY' IN REFUGEE CAMPS
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After slogging through a mucky tent compound in
Macedonia last weekend, a group of House members returned to say
they were awestruck by the scale of the human suffering triggered
by the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they expressed fear at the prospect of ethnic Albanian
refugees still living in tents when winter comes, the lawmakers
said they were pleased by the optimism America's strained military
holds for fulfilling its mission of driving Serb forces from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, led by Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas,
returned Sunday night after visiting the refugee camp, two air
bases and NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, a veteran of refugee camp visits around
the world, said conditions at the crowded camp in Skpoje,
Macedonia, were bad but orderly. He said the United States must
plan to spend more on humanitarian relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went because a million people are in misery,'' Hall said.
``A lot of people were talking about the winter, but they better
worry about the summer. It could be a major health problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said doctors at the site have begun seeing cases of
measles, and with seasonal temperatures rising, the camps could be
ideal places for waves of infectious disease such as cholera and
dysentery.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he'll offer an amendment to the $12.9 billion
emergency spending bill now working its way through the House so
more is spent on immediate relief efforts. In the bill, $195
million is budgeted directly for refugee assistance, though
additional money will go to border countries such as Macedonia to
help offset what they've spent so far.
</P>
<P>
   Hall believes some of the economic assistance, such as the
rebuilding of infrastructure, can wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important,'' Hall said, ``but compared to a million
refugees it's not important right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, who last week voted against a resolution supporting the
air campaign, seemed moved by the sights and sounds and stories of
the 28,000 people living in the refugee camp. He didn't
specifically endorse Hall's blunt assessment that the spending bill
is inadequate for the humanitarian needs, but said he understood
the perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my understanding that we were fairly generous in the
(emergency spending bill) as it goes now for relief,'' Armey said.
``(But) I don't think anybody, any of us, could come away from
that, seeing that hardship, without feeling a sense that whatever
we're doing we probably need to be doing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey also spoke forcefully on the need ``to develop a sense of
urgency'' about the plight of these refugees if they're still
living in tents when winter rolls back around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why in the middle of a beautiful springtime it
hit me so hard, an awareness of what that winter would be like for
people,'' Armey said. ``I say it's imperative, I just don't think
they'll survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hall and Armey, joined by others from both parties, were
uniformly impressed with the morale of the U.S. military personnel
they met. Armey said delegation members sensed some frustration
over the political limits imposed on the targets the military can
attack, but no one complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonetheless, there was a broad sense of conviction, belief,
commitment to completing the objectives of this air war,'' Armey
said. ``And I sensed nobody that felt an incapability of doing
that, and the subsequent need for ground troops for the completion
of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
