<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SENATE-HNS &LR;      05-03 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE POISED TO KILL PLAN AUTHORIZING GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Monday was poised to join the House
in going on record against an expansion of the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was scheduled to vote Tuesday on a resolution
authored by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
that would allow President Clinton to use ``all necessary force and
other means necessary'' to end Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's killing of ethic Albanians in Kosovo, the southern
province of Serbia, the dominant republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Republican and Democratic leaders of the Senate oppose
the resolution and McCain, its major sponsor, conceded that he it
would be ``badly'' defeated.
</P>
<P>
   In debate leading up to the vote, senators from both parties
criticized the conduct of the air war thus far, claiming that
Clinton has not done a good job of managing the U.S.-led North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's (NATO) bombing campaign in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is unclear,'' said Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis.,
``I don't believe the administration has articulated the goal of
the air strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., said the administration has ``made
a policy mistake'' by getting involved in the Balkans where, he
said, ``I do not believe we have a viable national security
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The House voted last week to require Clinton to consult Congress
before sending combat land forces into Kosovo. The House also
failed to support a resolution in favor of continuing the air
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the McCain-Biden resolution, Sen. Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb., said Clinton's stated policy of having no plans to use
ground troops was ``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question the conduct of the war from the beginning
has been questionable but it still leaves us where we are,'' Hagel
said. ``We must face the reality of what do we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued that it was the Senate's ``duty'' to send a clear
message about the conflict in the Balkans and he criticized the
House for its contradictory votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is America's war, not Bill Clinton's war,'' McCain said,
referring to the practice of some House Republicans of referring to
the conflict as ``Clinton's war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us in Congress are so distrustful of the president
that we feel obligated to damage the office in order to restrain
the current occupant,'' McCain claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the resolution, including Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., said it was ``too broad and too open ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Another opponent, Senate Foreign Relations Chairman Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., criticized the resolution on the grounds that ``the United
States Senate cannot and must not force the president to take
measures that he is unwilling or unprepared to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers suggested the Clinton administration step up
efforts to find a diplomatic solution to the conflict in Yugoslavia
and allow ethic Albanians to return to Kosovo, a province of
Serbia, the dominant republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that we have not stopped the slaughter _ ethnic
cleansing goes on and on and on,'' said Sen. Paul Wellstone,
D-Minn., who suggested a 48-hour pause in the air war to see if a
diplomatic solution can be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no consensus in the Congress or in the country with
regard to what we've already done in Kosovo'' said Feingold in
explaining why he thought it was unwise to give Clinton permission
to send in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Both Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., had sought to indefinitely
delay a vote on McCain's resolution because they were concerned
that a divisive debate on the Senate floor would send the wrong
signal to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle argued that the Senate didn't need to debate a
resolution authorizing additional force until Clinton asks for it.
The Senate voted in favor of authorizing the air campaign on March
23, the day before that military action began.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate parliamentarian ruled that McCain's resolution
had to come to the Senate floor under the terms of the 1973 War
Powers Act. Congress approved the war powers measure in the waning
days of the Vietnam War to compel presidents to consult Congress in
advance of military action involving U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that the Tuesday vote was designed to avoid a
straight up-or-down ballot on the measure. Instead, the vote will
be on a motion to table the McCain-Biden resolution, thus deferring
it indefinitely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
