<HEADER>
A2769 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT     05-03 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUDE RANCHES  
 HONOLULU LOCKERS  
 SILK ROAD TOURS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I would like to take our 12-year-old
granddaughter to a dude ranch next spring. We prefer to stay in New
England or the mid-Atlantic states. Any suggestions? _ Anne Olesky,
Summit, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Among the dude ranches in the Northeast are these: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK STATE: Cold River Ranch, Route 3, Tupper Lake, NY
12986; (518) 359-7559.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Acres Farm and Ranch Resort, County Route 14, Gilboa, NY
12076; (800) 252-7787.
</P>
<P>
   Pinegrove Resort Ranch, Kerhonkson, NY 12446; (914) 626-7345.
</P>
<P>
   Ridin-Hy Ranch Resort, Post Office Box 369, Sherman Lake,
Warrensburg, NY 12885; (518) 494-2742.
</P>
<P>
   Roaring Brook Ranch and Tennis Resort, Post Office Box 671,
Route 9N, Lake George, NY 12845; (518) 668-5767.
</P>
<P>
   Rocking Horse Ranch, 600 Routes 44-55, Highland, NY 12528; (800)
647-2624.
</P>
<P>
   Roseland Ranch Resort, Hunns Lake Road, Stanfordville, NY 12581;
(914) 868-1350.
</P>
<P>
   Thousand Acres Ranch Resort, 465 Warrensburg Rd., Stony Creek,
NY 12878; (800) 458-7311.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA: Flying W Ranch, Star Route 2, Tionesta, PA 16353;
(814) 463-7663.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT: Firefly Ranch, Post Office Box 152, Bristol, VT 05443;
(802) 453-2223.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA: River Ridge Ranch, Route 1, Box 119-1, Millboro, VA
24460; (540) 996-4148.
</P>
<P>
   Typical ranch rates are about $75 to $120 a day for each adult
(less if you don't ride), and about $50 to $75 for a child your
granddaughter's age. This will usually include two to three meals a
day and at least an hour to 90 minutes a day on horseback, although
a few charge extra for riding. Some places stress riding rather
than the typical ranch activities, like hayrides, rodeos and
nightly shows.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about some of these dude ranches, you can
contact Guest Ranches of North America at www.guestranches.com.
Also, the Dude Ranchers' Association, LaPorte, Colo., (970)
223-8440, www.duderanch.org, represents ranches in the Western
states, but could provide help in choosing a ranch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I will be traveling to China in the fall, with
stopovers in Hawaii in both directions. Is there any place at
Honolulu International Airport where items that won't be needed in
China (beach gear, snorkeling equipment, etc.) can be stored? _
Robert F. Koester, Grantham, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is such a facility, on the first level of the main
public parking garage, close to baggage-claim areas E and F. It is
open 24 hours a day, with an attendant on duty.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to store equipment and baggage here. The
first is short-term storage (48 hours or less) in coin-operated
lockers. The lockers measure 35 inches high, 19 inches wide and 31
inches deep. The price is $6 a day; you pay $1.50 when you place
the items in the locker and the rest when you pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   For items that will be stored longer than 48 hours, there is a
storage room overseen by the attendant. The charge is $3 a piece
each day, $6 if the piece is longer than 35 inches. The storage fee
can be paid in cash or traveler's checks; no credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at the storage facility suggests that you leave your
baggage as early in the day as possible. Passengers returning to
the mainland on an afternoon or evening flight will often drop off
their bags in the morning and spend their remaining hours on the
island unencumbered. Information: (808) 836-6683. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you know of any travel agency that has a tour of the Silk
Road? _ B. Franklin Reinauer II, Green Pond, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Silk Road, the ancient trade route from China, was about
4,000 miles long. By various routes, it went from the Chinese city
of Changan (now Xian), across the North China Plain, through the
Pamir Mountains and the Karakoram Range to Samarkand, Damascus and
the Mediterranean ports of Alexandria and Antioch (now Antakya).
</P>
<P>
   Today, segments can be explored on tours offered by a number of
companies. The comfort level of accommodations varies, as does the
level of physical fitness required of participants. All prices are
per person, based on double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Tiller International Tours, P.O. Box 475637, San Francisco, CA
94147, (415) 921-8989, has an Ancient Silk Route tour Sept. 6-29.
It starts in Beijing and goes to Samarkand, with stops in Lanzhou,
Dunhuang, Turpan in the Gobi Desert, Kashi (where the north and
south Silk Roads merged), Tashkent, Khiva and Bukhoro. Price:
$4,595, with meals and accommodations; trans-Pacific and regional
flights extra.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Asia, 180 Varick St., New York, NY 10014, (800)
736-8187, offers a 20-day Silk Road tour with departures May 23,
Sept. 26, Oct. 24 and April 9, 2000. It starts in Beijing, and
includes Xian, Lanzhou, the Han Chinese desert outpost of
Jiayuguan, Dunhuang, Turpan and Kashi. Price: $3,195, with
accommodations, daily breakfast, land transport and flights in
China, guides and entrance fees.
</P>
<P>
   Exodus, 9 Weir Rd., London SW12 OLT, (44-181) 675 5550, fax
(44-181) 673 0779, has a 21-day Silk Road Explorer tour from
Islamabad to Beijing with departures July 26, Aug. 23, Sept. 13 and
Oct. 4. It starts with a drive along the Karakoram Highway into the
Himalayas, going through the Khunjerab Pass (elevation 15,420
feet). Stops in Xian and Beijing, too. Most hotels are modest, with
private bath, and most meals are included. Price: $2,930 (at $1.62
to a pound).
</P>
<P>
   Regent Holidays, 15 John St., Bristol BS1 2HR, (44-117) 921
1711, fax (44-117) 925 4866, has various itineraries based on level
of accommodations, from simple with shared baths to trekking and
camping. For example, a 16-day tour of the Chinese Silk Road is
$1,866, including accommodations in standard hotels, daily
breakfast, a few other meals, sightseeing and ground
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Geographic Expeditions, 2627 Lombard St., San Francisco, CA
94123, (800) 777-8183, fax (415) 346-5535, has three separate tours
over the Silk Route, all of which it describes as rigorous. A trip
through the Turugart Pass (12,370 feet) Sept. 19 to Oct. 12 costs
from $5,290 to $6,690, depending on group size. From Sept. 5 to 27,
there is a trip through the Khunjerab Pass for $4,390 to $5,190.
And the southern Silk Route is covered on a trip Sept. 6 to Oct. 1,
for $5,490 to $6,490. Rates include accommodations, guides, most
meals and all transportation along the tour route; international
air fare extra.
</P>
