<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-INS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES GIVE U.S. DISCRETION IN DECIDING WHICH IMMIGRANTS MERIT
POLITICAL ASYLUM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A unanimous Supreme Court on Monday rejected a
Guatemalan immigrant's bid for political asylum and in the process
gave the federal government broad discretion in deciding which
self-proclaimed freedom fighters merit U.S. protection.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in their 9-0 ruling, said courts should defer to
the attorney general's decisions on whether an immigrant is
justifiably trying to escape political persecution at home or
merely seeking to avoid legitimate prosecution for having committed
serious nonpolitical crimes. The high court, agreeing with Attorney
General Janet Reno, ruled that the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in San Francisco wrongfully rejected the decision of the
Justice Department's Board of Immigration Affairs, which denied
Juan Anibal Aguirre-Aguirre asylum because his attacks on
Guatemalan civilians, burning of buses and vandalism of stores were
acts not of politics but of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre-Aguirre had claimed that his behavior was a legitimate
form of political protest in response to the Guatemalan
government's doubling of public transportation fares. But the board
rejected that argument, saying the immigrant's violent response was
grossly disproportional to the government's action.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit, however, said the board failed to give adequate
consideration to Aguirre-Aguirre's request for asylum.
Specifically, the appeals court said the board should have weighed
three factors: the political necessity and success of Aguirre's
methods, if his acts were atrocious or grossly out of proportion to
their objective, and whether he would be persecuted if returned to
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court, reinstating the board's decision, said
federal judges, including those on the 9th Circuit, should not
interfere with the largely political decision of the attorney
general, an executive branch official, as to whether an immigrant
should be granted asylum. Such decisions are often based not only
on law but on diplomacy, the high court said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (on the Supreme Court) have recognized that judicial
deference to the executive branch is especially appropriate in the
immigration context where officials exercise especially sensitive
political functions that implicate questions of foreign
relations,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the court in
Immigration and Naturalization Service vs. Aguirre-Aguirre.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision by the attorney general to deem certain violent
offenses committed in another country political in nature, and to
allow the perpetrators to remain in the United States, may affect
our relations with that country or its neighbors,'' Kennedy said.
``The judiciary is not well positioned to shoulder primary
responsibility for assessing the likelihood and importance of such
diplomatic repercussions.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices also said the bureau was within its statutory
authority to reject Aguirre-Aguirre's request for asylum, a form of
protection U.S. law permits the attorney general to grant to people
who would face persecution in their home countries on account of
their race, religion, nationality, membership in a particular
social group or political opinion. The board came to the legitimate
conclusion that Aguirre-Aguirre's acts amounted to serious
nonpolitical crimes and that Guatemala had a sovereign right to
prosecute him for such offenses, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
