u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-HNS &LR;      05-03 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO CONTINUE AIR WAR, DESPITE DIPLOMATIC EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite escalating diplomatic activity aimed at
ending the war over Kosovo, President Clinton said Monday that
NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia would continue until President
Slobodan Milosevic withdraws his troops from the province and
allows an international military force to police a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our air campaign cannot stop until Mr. Milosevic shows he is
ready to end the nightmare for the people of Kosovo,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who helped secure the
release of three American GI's held captive in Yugoslavia. But the
president added that there would be no pause in the air war, as
Jackson had sought as a gesture of good will, until Kosovo's ethnic
Albanians are allowed to return to their villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Americans are home. Their families, their friends and
the American people, whom they have served faithfully, must be
grateful. But nearly 1.5 million Kosovars are not home,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conditions for ending the bombing are not complicated. The
Kosovars must be able to go home, with security and
self-government. Serbian security forces must leave Kosovo. An
international security force must deploy, with the power not just
to monitor but to protect all the people of Kosovo, Albanians and
Serbs alike,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signalled a possible softening of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization's position by saying that the alliance might
suspend bombing if Yugoslavia initiates ``at least the beginning of
withdrawal of Serb forces'' and meets the other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The demands came on a day of stepped-up diplomacy, as Clinton
met separately with Jackson and Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's
Balkans envoy who is trying to mediate an end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke at a news conference with Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, Jackson arrived at Andrews Air Force Base
outside Washington from his weekend meeting with Milosevic in
Belgrade. The U.S. government did not sanction that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. soldiers were taken prisoner March 31 along the border
of Macedonia and Yugoslavia and freed Sunday after Jackson appealed
to Milosevic for their release.
</P>
<P>
   After escorting the soldiers to a military base in Germany,
Jackson returned to the United States bearing a letter for Clinton
from Milosevic that proposes a face-to-face meeting as a step to
ending the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson wouldn't discuss the contents of the letter,
officials believe that it reiterates Milosevic's insistence that
NATO stop the bombing and withdraw its forces from the region. In
exchange, the Yugoslav leader may allow ethnic Albanians to return
to Kosovo under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who toured bombed buildings in Belgrade and held hands
with Milosevic at a prayer meeting, told reporters upon his arrival
in Washington Monday that ``we have a negotiating deal on the table
which should be pursued.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides rejected Milosevic's overtures, asserting that
Clinton would not meet with the Yugoslav president. ``I would
suggest that he (Milosevic) shouldn't keep too much time available
on his schedule,'' said Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who has shuttled between Moscow, Belgrade and
western capitals, met with Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials downplayed expectations for a
diplomatic breakthrough, while at the same time they encouraged
Moscow to continue its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This meeting today is not an event; it's part of a process in
which we believe the Russians can play a constructive role,'' said
State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Russia can play an important role in resolving this
conflict and implementing a political settlement,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin dispatched Chernomyrdin, a
former prime minister, to Washington for the meetings after
speaking with Clinton by phone Sunday about the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Milosevic met with Chernomyrdin and proposed a
peace plan that was immediately rejected by NATO officials because
it would not permit an armed force in Kosovo to enforce a peace
treaty _ something about which NATO is unwavering. Kosovo is a
province of Serbia, the dominant state in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, John Steinbrunner, a foreign policy specialist at the
Brookings Institution, said a diplomatic solution might be in a
nascent stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be wildly optimistic, you can see signs of a
peace agreement in what Jackson and Chernomyrdin are saying. These
are the early signs,'' he said. Brookings is an independent
Washington-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic activity came after a night of intensified NATO
bombing in Yugoslavia in which aircraft began targeting the
nation's electrical grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the lights went out across 70 percent of the
country, I think, shows that NATO has its finger on the light
switch in Yugoslavia now, and we can turn the power off whenever we
need to and whenever we want to,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said
in Brussels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
