<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2776 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-YOUNG-KILLERS-ART     05-03 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-YOUNG-KILLERS-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CHILDREN KILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(rm) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They seemed, people said at the time, like normal children from
normal families, rattling along the bumpy emotional road that most
people believe represents the normal course of the teen-age years.
</P>
<P>
   But when psychiatrists investigated the suicides of 27 youths in
the Pittsburgh area, interviewing the victims' friends, teachers
and family members, their inquiry revealed not normal teen-agers,
pushed to extreme action by the pressures of modern society, but
severely disturbed adolescents whose psychological problems were
longstanding and whose unhappiness had leeched out in a hundred
clues that were ignored or undetected by those around them.
</P>
<P>
   This contrast between surface assessment and underlying reality,
mental health experts said, is typical of most cases in which
teen-agers have committed acts of extreme violence, killing
themselves or others.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks following the Littleton, Colo., shootings, public
discussion has focused on cultural factors, including media
violence, the availability of guns, video games, the tyranny of
high school cliques and the pressures on students to achieve. And
no one disputes that these pressures on teen-agers are real. But
the deeper truth of what happened at Columbine High, many experts
said, may lie less in the troubles of the world at large, but in
the problems and personal histories of the two teen-age killers,
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Much remains unknown about the two young men and their families.
Yet the experts said they will not be surprised if time reveals a
similar disjunction between surface and reality, uncovering a more
complicated story beneath the initial reports of well-adjusted
students in ``utterly normal'' families.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it looks inexplicable, if they don't seem to have the
history of troubled relationships and temperamental difficulties''
said Dr. James Garbarino, professor of human development at Cornell
University and author of ``Lost Boys: Why Our Sons Turn Violent and
How We Can Save Them'' (Free Press, 1999). ``But as the days
proceed and these boys' lives are put under the microscope, we may
begin to see a pattern of early difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   The realization that it is fragile children _ not sturdy ones _
who are most likely to ``break'' has emerged from a growing number
of ``psychological autopsy'' studies of youthful suicides, and from
less formal studies of adolescents who have committed murders. And
though aggression against the self and aggression toward others
were once viewed as distinct entities, research is suggesting that
the two sometimes go together: People who attempt suicide, for
example, show more aggressiveness and impulsiveness throughout
their lifetime than people who are not suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other studies have shown that the turbulence,
pathology and confusion considered ``normal'' in adolescence are in
fact far from typical.
</P>
<P>
   In studies of adolescents in the United States and in other
countries, Dr. Daniel Offer and his colleagues at the University of
Chicago found that the rates of mental illness in teen-agers were
identical to those in adults. Though every teen-ager has ups and
downs, ``the typical adolescent is a pretty healthy, happy,
purposeful person,'' said Dr. Kenneth Howard, professor of
psychology at the university who collaborated with Offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your kid is behaving like a `typical adolescent' _ sullen,
depressed, getting poor grades, having trouble with friends _ that
kid needs help, and it's not a phase,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to this upbeat portrait of normal teen-age
development, Dr. David Shaffer and his colleagues at Columbia
University found, in an in-depth study of 120 adolescents in the
New York area who committed suicide between June 1, 1984, and May
31, 1986, that 90 percent suffered from a diagnosable psychiatric
disorder, such as major depression or another ``mood disorder,''
alcohol or drug abuse, previous suicide attempts or disruptive
behavior. And in more than a third of the New York suicides, the
symptoms had begun more than five years before the victim's death.
</P>
<P>
   Among the risk factors identified by Shaffer and other
investigators, including Dr. David Brent, the child psychiatrist
who conducted the study of the 27 Pittsburgh suicides, were
difficulties in school, neither being in school nor working, a
family history of suicide, a significant lack of ``satisfying
communication'' with parents, exposure to parental discord or
abuse, and stressful life events, particularly disciplinary or
legal problems, and interpersonal losses.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. John Mann, Dr. Victoria Arango at Columbia University and
other investigators have added to this complicated package the
finding that suicide victims have lowered levels of serotonin, a
messenger chemical, in areas of the brain's frontal lobe involved
with planning and impulse control, indicating that biological
factors may also leave some people less able to resist acting on
suicidal urges.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, studies of youthful murderers frequently find in such
children a history of abuse, humiliation, terror or neglect, as
well as evidence of psychiatric disorders and neurological
abnormalities. Often, teen-age murderers show a pattern of
disturbed relationships with others and destructive behavior that
only comes to light after they commit a crime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, Luke Woodham, who in 1997 killed his mother and two
students and wounded seven other students at his Pearl, Miss., high
school, had been seen beating his dog with a club, wrapping it in a
plastic bag, setting it on fire and tossing it into a pond,
Garbarino writes in ``Lost Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Also common in many children who erupt in violence, said many
experts, is a deadening of human feeling _ a striking inability to
feel remorse, love, or empathy toward another human being. Dr.
Bruce Perry, chief of psychiatry at Texas Children's Hospital in
Houston, said such children may know that they have done something
wrong, but are unable to connect to their action in an emotional
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sat in my office with a 14-year-old child who two days
previously had killed somebody,'' Perry recalled, ``and he sat in
my office and colored and talked about it almost as if he were
describing a sporting event he had observed, instead of an event
that he had caused.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar dissociation from reality was expressed by Woodham in
his tape recorded confession: ``It was like I was there and I
wasn't there,'' he said. And Columbine High students described the
chilling detachment of Harris and Klebold as they made their bloody
circuit through the school, killing 12 students and a teacher
before committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Littleton shootings, the hunger for answers
has focused attention on guns, media violence, video games and the
pressures on school children to achieve. But the message from
studies of adolescents who kill others or themselves is that no
single factor can explain their actions. Instead, researchers say,
children who kill must be seen as extremely vulnerable children who
accumulate risk throughout their lives and finally succumb:
Garbarino likens it to ``a tower of blocks. You put one more block
on the tower, and it topples over.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, rates of both teen-age suicides and homicides committed
by teen-agers have risen sharply over the last three decades,
leveling off recently at their all-time highs. And the onset of
mental disorders like depression, manic depression and alcoholism
is earlier than it once was. More than 1.5 million Americans under
age 15 are seriously depressed, according to the National Institute
of Mental Health. Other estimates put the figure even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Vulnerable children, because they are the first to falter, offer
a warning, marking the fault lines in a culture in which more and
more children are taking their own or others' lives. Teen-agers,
said Michael Meade, founder of Mosaic, a Washington state-based
organization devoted to working with adolescents at risk, are
desperately hungry ``for genuine involvement and genuine
attention.'' In a world of violent images, ready availability of
guns and pressure to succeed, adults, he says, cannot start
listening too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Mann of Columbia put it more bluntly:. ``When vulnerable kids
crack, the weapons that are at hand make the consequences of that
vulnerability more serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
