<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-QUARTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TO MOVE INTO BANKBOSTON QUARTERS IN MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He coveted his competitor's business for years; soon
he will occupy his rival's manor.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Murray, chief executive of Fleet Financial Group Inc.,
will find himself ensconced in a new executive suite at BankBoston
Corp. when the two banks, which are merging, set up their new
corporate headquarters at BankBoston later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Announced Monday, the two companies' decision to use
BankBoston's imposing tower at 100 Federal St. as home base puts
the combined bank in one of downtown Boston's most dramatic
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   By moving some of its staff and operations from its headquarters
at One Federal St. across the road to BankBoston, Fleet will free
up a large chunk of highly coveted commercial space in a booming
property market with little vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know, nor does the bank, how much, if any, space
could be freed up,'' said Mark M. Weld, a senior director at
Clarion Partners, a Boston-based real estate firm that owns and
manages One Federal.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to use BankBoston's structure as headquarters is
grounded in symbolic and practical significance. Though the two
banks describe their merger into the nation's eighth-largest bank
as a combination of equals, Fleet, the larger of the two, is
technically acquiring BankBoston _ a fact underscored by Fleet's
impending move into its rival's building.
</P>
<P>
   A 37-story structure of mahogany granite, BankBoston's building
boasts modern facilities and a striking profile. Built for the bank
in 1971, the tower includes retail shops, a state-of-the-art
trading floor, a pedestrian plaza, and, on the top floor, the
Boston College Club.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Fleet's 40-story skyscraper, also built in the
1970s, is a gray, stone aggregate. Fleet has 11 floors, with
executive suites at the top, just below the Harvard Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reviewing our corporate facilities and taking into
account our projected needs, the selection of 100 Federal to be our
headquarters makes sound business sense,'' Murray said in a
statement Monday. But when the combination was announced in March,
Murray joked that while BankBoston was prettier than Fleet on the
exterior, Fleet was nicer inside.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and his counterpart at BankBoston, Charles K. Gifford,
decided to use BankBoston after reviewing facilities plans. The
decision, taken earlier than expected, may have been speeded up to
give the two companies a jump start in melding their operations and
cultures. Fleet won't begin moving into BankBoston until the merger
is finalized later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Once with headquarters in Providence, Fleet relocated to Boston
in 1995 when it acquired Shawmut National Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between scrappy Fleet and patrician BankBoston
extended in recent years even to architectural matters. Fleet
renovated its imposing lobby six years ago, prompting BankBoston to
seek to do the same, only better, Weld said.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston leases all but three of 100 Federal's 37 floors from
the Atlanta-based real estate arm of French insurer Equitable Axa.
Around 4,100 of the bank's 25,000 employees are at the building,
which is known as ``the pregnant building'' for its distinctive
bulge. About 1,000 of Fleet's 35,000 employees are at Fleet
headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
