<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POWS-0504-COX     05-03 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POWS-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICAN POWS REUNITED WITH FAMILIES, UNDERGO FURTHER MEDICAL
TESTS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0504.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSTUHL, Germany _ In a private day behind the walls of an
American military hospital, the three U.S. soldiers who spent 32
days as POWs in Yugoslavia were reunited with their families and
underwent further medical tests that showed their capture by Serb
forces was more brutal than it first appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The servicemen spent their first full day of freedom in
tearfully happy meetings with their parents, siblings and other
relatives, who flew overnight from the United States to arrive in
Germany on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers and their families appeared briefly for the
cameras on the balcony of the hospital wing. All smiles, they gave
the thumbs-up and OK signs. ``It's great!'' some shouted to
reporters below.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials at the Landstuhl Regional Medical Center
released further details of the injuries the three suffered,
indicating that the soldiers were beaten severely during and
perhaps after their capture by Serb forces on March 31 on the
border of Yugoslavia and Macedonia, where the U.S. peacekeepers
were based.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three suffered broken bones, revealed in x-rays and
other examinations since their arrival in Germany on Sunday
following their release negotiated by the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., has a broken nose
that is healing and Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles had two
broken ribs which have begun to heal and will require no further
treatment, said Col. Mack Blanton, chief of clinical services at
the hospital. Ramirez also lost 11 pounds during his incarceration.
The third former POW is Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lingering injuries, Blanton said the three were in
``generally good health.'' Blanton said they were upbeat about
visiting their families.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to remain in the hospital, near the Ramstein
Air Base in southwestern Germany, for another two or three days.
President Clinton will arrive in Germany on Wednesday. White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton would like to meet with the
three servicemen and their families, but that the president did not
want to delay their return home.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the servicemen were captured, Yugoslav authorities
released videotape showing the soldiers badly bruised. The
servicemen said after they had left Yugoslavia on Sunday that their
treatment was generally good after the initial confrontation with
the forces that nabbed them.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. David Grange, commander of the U.S. Army's 1st
Infantry Division, said he suspected the soldiers were treated more
harshly than their initial public comments suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that all the treatment was well,'' Grange said.
``I think it might have been they were poorly treated at the
beginning, but that'll be determined.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the soldiers were exhibiting the so-called
Stockholm syndrome, where those imprisoned begin to identify
psychologically with their captors, Grange said, ``The
investigation will determine that, and I think you'll see mixed
results.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of interview with the soldiers so far, Grange said
he was convinced that ``they were definitely in Macedonia,'' not in
Yugoslav territory as Serb authorities have maintained when they
were captured while on patrol in a Humvee military vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials said the complete account of the soldiers' ordeal
and the circumstances of their capture would be aired when their
investigation is completed later this week.
</P>
<P>
   After taking 30 days of leave, the soldiers were likely to
return to their units, which are based in Germany, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
