<SLUG> BC-DELL-FAST-SEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL, NORWEGIANS TEAM TO CREATE TOP WEB SEARCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Norwegian company is teaming up with Dell Computer Corp. to
create a new Internet search engine they claim will be the most
comprehensive ever.
</P>
<P>
   Fast Search &AMP; Transfer Inc. says its new site, which begins
operation Tuesday at www.alltheweb.com, already has 80 million
indexed Web pages. That compares with about 150 million pages
indexed by the popular AltaVista search site and 125 million pages
in the Northern Light index of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But Fast president David Burns says his service will be up to
200 million pages by summer. Burns also said the new search system
developed by his firm will enable the company to eventually create
the first index of the entire World Wide Web. ``When you search the
whole Web,'' said Burns, ``you can find sites that are those
absolute gems.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the magazine Science estimated the Web contained 320
million pages, and it has continued to grow rapidly since then.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns said Fast will be able to keep up. It is based on a
new search architecture developed by computer scientists at Fast's
parent company in Oslo. The new system should make it relatively
simple to increase the size of the index merely by connecting more
and more computers.
</P>
<P>
   Dell will provide the hardware _ rack-mounted PC servers with
Intel Pentium II processors. These computers are located at the
Waltham, Mass. facility of Exodus Communications Inc., one of the
nation's leading Web-hosting companies, which houses and provides
security and maintenance for other companies' Internet computers.
</P>
<P>
   The same building houses the computers that drive the Lycos
search service, and Lycos' headquarters is less than a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is a former Lycos executive, and Fast has built
specialized search engines for Lycos. The controversial MP3 search
service that lets Lycos users find free digital music recordings on
the Internet is operated by Fast.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' own Web search engine contains about 50 million pages,
far fewer than the number claimed by Fast. But Burns isn't looking
to compete with Lycos or any of the other major search sites.
Instead, he wants these companies to license the Fast search engine
and host it on their own sites. Fast's chief competitor is Inktomi
Corp. of San Mateo, Calif., whose search engine powers the Lycos
Hotbot site.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers like Curt Monash, president of Elucidate
Technologies LLC of Lexington, Mass., scoff at Fast's
bigger-is-better approach to Web searching. Monash argued that
today's search engines already provide too much information,
overwhelming users with too much information. Enlarging the index
will only make matters worse, Monash said. ``Having a bigger piece
of mediocrity is not that big an accomplishment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns figures that Web portals will combine the Fast search
service with other kinds of Web indexes to give a more precise
method for finding exactly what the user is searching for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1909EDT &QL; 
