<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-AIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES PLEDGES $25 MILLION TO HELP DEVELOP AIDS VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Software mogul William H. Gates Monday pledged $25 million over
five years to help develop a vaccine against AIDS, an effort for
which President Clinton has set a 2007 deadline but which has shown
frustratingly slow progress to date.
</P>
<P>
   Through his $5.2 billion charitable foundation, the Microsoft
founder and chairman will more than double the yearly budget of the
International Aids Vaccine Initiative, a New York-based nonprofit
partnership funded by several foundations and United Nations
groups. Last December, Gates pledged $100 million for improving
access to vaccines among Third World children.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative's president, Dr. Seth Berkley, said Gates's
``historic act of generosity will allow us to significantly
accelerate the scientific effort'' but that his group estimates it
needs another $300 million to $500 million to succeed. The Alfred
P. Sloan Foundation Monday pledged another $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only one possible AIDS vaccine is undergoing
so-called phase 3 trials with human volunteers, the final stage
before the Food and Drug Administration considers approval.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 5,000 US volunteers are expected to sign up for tests of
the Vaxgen Inc. product called AIDSvax, which seeks to keep the
human immunodeficiency virus from entering body cells rather than
stimulating antibodies to kill already infected cells. Boston's
Fenway Community Health Center is participating in the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago officials in Uganda, where nearly one in 10
residents is infected with the AIDS virus, launched smaller-scale
tests of a French product that uses a canary pox virus to carry HIV
genes and trigger development of antibodies against versions of HIV
found in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 possible vaccines to prevent AIDS have been
identified in recent years. But because so many different viral
strains cause AIDS, and they manipulate cells to hide from the
body's immune system, developing a vaccine has proved
extraordinarily complicated.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton pledged in May 1997 to ``do all I can'' to develop
an AIDS vaccine by 2007, US researchers have been especially
concerned about rushing into tests that could infect volunteers
with a lethal disease. Some activists question whether
pharmaceutical companies are dragging their feet on vaccines
because they gross $1 billion yearly from AIDS treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that we need to move many other vaccines forward,
and there is a range of different approaches that we think ought to
be pursued'' simultaneously, said Victor Zonana of the vaccine
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, more than 30 million people have been
diagnosed with AIDS or are infected with the virus that causes it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
