<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-0504-COX     05-03 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REBUTTAL WITNESSES NAMED FOR FINAL PHASE OF MICROSOFT TRIAL
 &HT;    Moved in both (w) Washington) and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Barring a last-minute settlement, the Microsoft
antitrust trial will enter the payoff phase, probably in late May,
with the warring parties seeking to overcome weak spots in their
initial arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and Microsoft each named three rebuttal
witnesses Monday. They will use those witnesses to try to gain the
upper hand during the crucial period of the case, which promises to
shape antitrust law in the high-tech field for the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will call David Colburn, senior vice president for
business affairs of America Online; Gordon Eubanks, president and
chief executive officer of Oblix Inc.; and Richard Schmalensee,
acting dean of the Sloan School of Management at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The government witnesses will be Garry Norris, an International
Business Machines executive; Franklin Fisher of MIT, who in earlier
testimony argued that Windows has given Microsoft monopoly powers
that it has used to engage in anti-competitive business practices;
and Edward Felten, a computer science professor at Princeton
University and earlier witness.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states, which sued the software
giant nearly a year ago, must seek to show how Microsoft's hardball
business tactics have harmed consumers by driving up prices or by
curtailing innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Before a Feb. 26 recess, government prosecutors offered
compelling evidence that Microsoft repeatedly used its
Windows-based market dominance to pressure personal computer makers
and software companies to dance to its tune, especially in their
choices of Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the rebuttal case for the defense is aimed at
persuading U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is
presiding over the trial without a jury, that Microsoft's power
over the personal computer market is limited and, perhaps in the
long run, transitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rebuttal witnesses will show that the $10 billion merger
of AOL and Netscape completely undercuts the government's case,''
said William Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel. ``Our rebuttal
witnesses will also show that competition and innovation are
stronger than ever in the software industry, and that consumers are
seeing extraordinary benefits from Microsoft and the industry as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Colburn, who had testified for the government in October, will
be questioned as a hostile witness. Microsoft said in papers filed
with the court Monday that it will seek to show how the recent
merger of America Online and Netscape Communications undermines the
government's contention that Microsoft was seeking to lock in a
dominant position in Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the merger and evidence Microsoft has gathered
through court-authorized discovery, the company will also question
Colburn about ``the completeness and candor of prior testimony''
given by Colburn in this case, the court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks is a former top figure at Symantec, a leading software
utilities maker. At Oblix, Eubanks heads a privately held business
directory software firm that is based in Silicon Valley. It counts
Netscape, Novell, and Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, a leading
venture capital firm, among its investors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials said Eubanks will testify on the dynamic
competition that exists throughout the software industry, and the
benefits of that competition for innovation and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Schmalensee stumbled on the stand last January when he appeared
for Microsoft. David Boies, the government's lead lawyer, had
confronted him with an essay Schmalensee wrote 16 years ago that
seemingly contradicted his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate reaction is, what could I have been thinking,''
Schmalensee said then, adding that the earlier essay ``does not
provide a good indication of my present views.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents unsealed Monday, IBM, the world's largest
computer maker, presented evidence to support the government's
charge that Microsoft has used its Windows software licenses to
maintain a choke hold on computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, the government witness, is a former director of software
strategy for IBM and currently program director in the networking
hardware division, a mid-level post. He is expected to contend that
Microsoft imposes restrictions that exclude competing technologies
while punishing manufacturers by charging them more for Windows if
they fail to act as a Microsoft strategic partner.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is not expected to resume before May 24.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
