<HEADLINE>
TALK IS CHEAP BUT DISTRACTED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   British Telecom is offering customers in certain areas trial
tests of Freetime, a service wherein calls are free but talkers are
interrupted by 10-second advertisements every two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Telegraph of London, such systems are in use in
Sweden, Denmark and Italy, ``where they have proved to be popular
with teenagers and cash-strapped households but an irritant to
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   A 10-second ad plays at the beginning of the call, before the
connection is made, and at regular intervals thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The vote to authorize a congressional medal for civil rights
hero  &UR; Rosa Parks &LR;  was 424 to 1, reports the Hill, the lone nay cast
by Rep.  &UR; Ron Paul &LR; , R-Texas. The congressman, a Libertarian,
``votes against anything that he thinks the Founding Fathers did
not explicitly contemplate,'' says the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   He said in a speech that he has ``great respect for the courage
and high ideals of Rosa Parks ... who is widely recognized and
admired for standing up against an overbearing government
infringing on individual rights.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Wysor &LR; , a physician who this month patented an
ointment that he claims could help women have orgasms, exulted to
the New York Times, ``It increases blood flow tremendously and
basically eliminates the need for foreplay.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Muhammad Ali &LR;  will appear  &LR; May 9  &LR; on ``Touched by an Angel''
to get across the message that violence is not a solution to life's
problems. ``Fighting is not the answer to frustration and hate,''
he told TV Guide. ``It is a sport, not a philosophy of life. I do
not promote anybody becoming a professional boxer. I would prefer
children use it as a springboard, not a career choice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Miramax mogul  &UR; Harvey Weinstein  &LR; insisted on smoking a cigar
aboard the Concorde a few weeks ago, and when his &LR;  the plane landed
at Heathrow, the Times of London says, he received a summons. When
the case came up in court, shortly afterward, Weinstein was a
no-show. An aide told the British newspaper, ``We know nothing
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for British Airways said that apparently Weinstein
``does this all the time,'' but his ``behavior is very unusual for
Concorde. There is a small customer base of regular Concorde
travelers, including Hollywood celebrities and captains of
industry, who have a quiet air of confidence about their
influence.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mirror of London says  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR;  plays a woman
accidentally sawed in half by magician  &UR; Woody Allen &LR;  in Allen's
next film, ``Picking Up the Pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Italian newspapers are reporting that  &UR; Monica Lewinsky  &LR; is
talking with the Italian film company Filmauro about appearing in a
Christmas movie. Filmauro is best known for sex comedies.
</P>
<P>
   _ In preparation for a possible cable TV show based on his
magazine, George,  &UR; John F. Kennedy Jr. &LR;  has been taking TV lessons.
MSNBC says he had to learn not to look skyward when he was
thinking, which used to be a habit. ``It made his eyes all white
and sort of spooky,'' said an eyewitness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOCAL PRIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco makes the grade: The pesticide manufacturer
d-Con is out with its annual top 10 list of cities with rodents,
and we're No. 9. The leader, the city with ``the worst mouse
problem'' in the country, is Los Angeles, followed by New York, San
Antonio, Salt Lake City tied with Boise, Dallas, Philadelphia,
Houston, Chicago, San Francisco and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Describing a perfect day in the life of a San Franciscan, in
the latest issue of GQ,  &UR; Owen Edwards &LR;  drops the following place
names: Lake Merced's UCSF boathouse, Peet's on Fillmore; &LR; , the
Golden Gate Bridge; &LR; , Skywalker Ranch, Nicasio Reservoir, the
Station House Cafe in Point Reyes Station, Billy Blue haberdasher,
the Fraenkel Gallery, Bix and Bruno's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Design doesn't interest me _ only humble products and women's
problems. Females are the future. Men are tired.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Designer  &UR; Philippe Starck &LR; , telling ID magazine of his plans
to design pantyhose for Wolford and tampons for 7-Eleven.  &UR; J.D. &LR; 
 &UR; Beltran  &LR; was awestruck by Starck's declaration that he ``wants to
go inside the human body.''
</P>
</TEXT>
