<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CHAISSON-BOS &LR;      05-03 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CHAISSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINA DEFENSEMAN'S DEATH SHOCKS NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than six hours after they eliminated Carolina, the Bruins'
playoff victory became a footnote to tragedy early Monday morning
when veteran Hurricanes defenseman Steve Chiasson, 32, was killed
in a one-car accident while driving to his home in suburban
Raleigh, N.C., following the team's charter flight from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   According to the North Carolina State Highway Patrol, Chiasson
was thrown from his pickup truck when it overturned in north
Raleigh at about 4:15 a.m., a little more than three hours after
the Hurricanes' charter touched down at Raleigh-Durham
International Airport following their 2-0 loss at the FleetCenter
in Game 6 of their best-of-seven Eastern Conference quarterfinal.
Sergeant M.R. Johnson, a police spokesman, indicated that alcohol
was a factor, according to evidence at the scene and interviews
with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation is continuing,'' said Johnson in a phone
interview. ``We're still looking into a lot regarding the wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner's office said no autopsy would be
performed, and Johnson estimated that Chiasson's blood-alcohol
level would be determined when a toxicology report is completed in
two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable in saying that alcohol was involved,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Team spokesman Chris Brown said by telephone that, along with
several nonalcoholic beverages, the Hurricanes carried two cases of
beer on a charter that numbered 52 passengers, and when the plane
landed, there was no indication that Chiasson was impaired or even
had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Trooper K.L. Horn and Sergeant J.D. Henderson were
at the scene of the accident and went to the family home ``sometime
before 6 a.m.'' to inform Chiasson's wife, Susan, of her husband's
death. The couple have three children _ Michael, 7; Ryan, 4; and
Stephanie, 2.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference late in the morning, Hurricanes
president/general manager Jim Rutherford told reporters that, after
the plane landed, ``It was my understanding that we were all
heading home. I got a call at approximately 5:30 this morning from
a player to say that (Chiasson) had the accident. I don't know
exactly who was with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford added that he and ``a lot of players'' gathered at a
teammate's house soon after learning of the fatality and called
``players, coaches, and trainers and all the people close to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Chiasson _ a onetime All-Star whose 12-year NHL
career included tours of duty in Detroit, Calgary, Hartford, and
Carolina _ sent shock waves throughout the league. ``When a young
life ends prematurely, when a young family loses a husband and
father,'' said commissioner Gary Bettman in a statement, ``words
cannot begin to express our sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The news hit particularly hard in Raleigh and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes coach Paul Maurice, who last remembered seeing
Chiasson in the vistors' locker room at the FleetCenter when
Maurice addressed the team after Sunday's loss, said in a phone
interview, ``I think we're all still quite a bit in shock, probably
a little disoriented by the whole thing. When you spend that much
time with someone, get to know their family . . . you know how it
is in this situation. You come to rely on each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice was awakened with the news at about 6 a.m. by
Rutherford's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so shocking,'' he said, ``that even as I'm sitting here
talking to you, I still can't believe it. The understatement is
that it puts things in perspective _ and that's really an
understatement. Everybody gets home and gives their wife and kids a
hug.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricane players will assemble at the rink Tuesday, when he
will address them about the situation, said Maurice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough day,'' he said, ``and we have a few more
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Rutherford described Chiasson _
considered a team leader, though he wasn't a captain _ as ``the
kind of guy everybody wants to be around. Certainly a big member
with his teammates and just a real ordinary guy that loved the game
of hockey and that loved the people around him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston the news cast an eerie pall over the Bruins' first
playoff series triumph in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody around here is just silent; it put a damper on the
whole series,'' said Bruins president/GM Harry Sinden, who was
informed of the tragedy by his office on his car phone while
driving to work at about 9:30. ``I had a sunken feeling. You don't
have much time to enjoy a series victory, and you just can't when
something like that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden acknowledged that Chiasson had been one of Carolina's top
performers in the series, playing steady defense, manning a point
on the power play, and killing penalties. But that had become
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that a guy left a wife and three kids at 32
is the real tragedy,'' he said. ``I didn't know him, but no matter
how you look at it, it's like one of our own. They get the feeling
of being invulnerable, players do.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Sinden suggested that teams might consider
providing transportation home for the players after season-ending
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happened before,'' he said. ``After you lose like that,
there probably is a tendency to . . . commiserate a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning drink, although the Hurricanes contend that was not the
situation on their flight and Sinden said that during the season,
``There is so little alcohol consumed by the Bruins on charters.
Maybe just one beer. Some flights there's none at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the apparent alcohol factor, Bruins Anson Carter and
teammate Landon Wilson considered Chiasson's death a cautionary
tale for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we drive home after a charter,'' said Wilson, ``it's
amazing we haven't gotten in an accident. We're in such a rush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a speed demon going home,'' said Carter. ``That's going to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most stunned was Bruins assistant general manager Mike
O'Connell, Chiasson's Detroit teammate and defensive mentor in the
late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was a rookie, he was a fine guy _ he is a fine guy,''
said O'Connell, who was called at home by his office with the news.
``He leaned on a few of us older guys to get him started _ how to
buy a house, what to do, how to handle situations. He was a warrior
on the ice, a true throwback hockey player, someone you'd love to
have on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   To defuse the tragedy, O'Connell savored a memory of his
erstwhile protege. At the end of Chiasson's rookie season, after he
had played on the world junior team, he and O'Connell were among
several Red Wings drinking in a downtown Detroit bar. Wayne Gretzky
also was there with his Edmonton entourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne came up to me, we said hi, and we talked for a little
bit,'' said O'Connell. ``Then Gretzky left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Great One had ignored Chiasson, who didn't expect any
recognition _ then was stunned when Gretzky returned, walked up to
him, and extended his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Steve, I'm Wayne Gretzky' _ as if Steve didn't know
that,'' said O'Connell. ``Then Wayne told him, `I just wanted to
tell you I thought you did a great job in the world juniors.' And
he walked out again. Steve said to me, `Imagine _ him knowing me.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Now a much wider audience knows Steve Chiasson. Tragically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
