<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FORCE WILL NOT BE WITH ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's not like I didn't go to movies in 1977. If
someone that year had asked me which pictures I'd seen, I'd
probably have said, ``All of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, I missed ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   I was just out of college, still deciding what I wanted to be
when I grew up, still trying to make sense of the world, still
hoping to ``find'' myself.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I was exactly the same, only with longer hair.
</P>
<P>
   This was before HBO, VCRs and Blockbuster. The only place to see
a film without commercials was in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   So, I went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Fever'' came out in 1977. And ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind.'' And ``Pumping
Iron.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't miss any of them.
</P>
<P>
   I even saw ``The Goodbye Girl,'' although, thinking back, that
might have had something to do with the beautiful, brown-eyed
reporter I'd met at a small paper in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   She was just out of college, too, already a grown-up, already
making sense of the world, and with no need to ``find'' herself, as
she'd never been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the reality of a woman left me with no need to escape into
science fiction. It's difficult to say after all this time.
</P>
<P>
   But the year came and went, and for me no ``Star Wars''.
</P>
<P>
   I remember hearing about the movie, and reading about it, and
seeing reports on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Darth Vader was a bigger bad guy in 1977 than Gary Gilmore, the
convicted murderer whose heart was stopped by firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   The names of Luke Skywalker and Princess Leia were in the news
as much as Elvis Presley, whose heart was stopped that year by
fried peanut butter sandwiches and prescripton drugs.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't tell you anything about Han Solo in 1977, but I knew
everything about the three solo home runs Reggie Jackson hit in
successive at-bats in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``The Empire Strike Back'' was released in 1980, I'd
begin telling people that I had, in fact, seen ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   `'Loved that R2D2,'' I'd say.
</P>
<P>
   It was easier than trying to explain how I possibly could have
missed the movie. But, with no ``Star Wars'' experience, I was in
no hurry to see ``Empire.'' And never got around to it.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Return of the Jedi'' was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   By 1983, the publicity was overwhelming. What began as an
innocent lapse in my movie-going plans, developed into a solemn
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   I became determined NEVER see any movie in the series, to plant
myself on the shore of American popular culture and not be swept
away by George Lucas's tidal wave.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy, over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before ``Return of the Jedi'' was released, the
brown-eyed woman gave birth to our first child. Since then, there's
been another.
</P>
<P>
   Video versions of all three films have found their way into my
living room at one time or another. Most likely rented for the
kids, or carted over by friends.
</P>
<P>
   There was a close call just last summer, when my little boy had
``Star Wars'' in the VCR for nearly 10 minutes, ejecting it only
after I dangled ``Tarzan's New York Adventure'' before his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The monkey beat the robots - for now.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how much longer I can hold out. The insane hoopla
for ``The Phantom Menace'' has sliced through the American psyche
like a light saber.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the movie, but the toys, the advertising, the
magazine covers, the TV interviews, the previews, the music videos,
the video games, the comic books, the web sites, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to beat back that kind of assault, even when armed
with classics like ``Captain Blood,'' ``She Wore A Yellow Ribbon,''
``Duck Soup'' and ``The Incredible Mr. Limpet''.
</P>
<P>
   But, I believe someone's got to try. Someone's got to make a
stand. Someone got to look the monster in the eye and say:
</P>
<P>
   The Chewbacca stops here. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
