<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEA-OTTERS-HNS &LR;      05-03 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-OTTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA OTTERS MAY BE PLACED ON ENDANGERED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The population of sea otters along the
California coast is dropping so quickly that scientists fear it
could be approaching extinction.
</P>
<P>
   After a calamitous centuries-long decline, then a revival, the
numbers started falling again in 1995 by about 90 per year. The
most recent count, late last year, estimates that only 1,937
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``More otters are dying each year than being born,'' said
biologist Carl Benz, who heads a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
team responsible for the recovery of sea otters. ``If this trend
continues, it's entirely possible that this species may go
extinct.''
</P>
<P>
   The otter, the smallest marine mammal species on Earth, is
believed partly to be the victim of infectious disease, water
contaminants, fish nets and fishing pots.
</P>
<P>
   Just four years ago, scientists were hopeful the population
might grow to at least 8,000 within four decades, perhaps up to
30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, the year that sea otters went on the Endangered
Species Act's list of threatened species, the numbers had edged up
every year to an all-time high of 2,377 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1995 the spring count has dropped by 11 percent, and
Benz says that if the trend continues, the Fish and Wildlife
Service may move to declare the otter endangered, a step that would
increase protections and the likelihood of research funding. The
agency has estimated that 1,850 is the smallest population required
to maintain a sustainable population off the coast, although the
number may be revised downward.
</P>
<P>
   Even as their numbers drop, otters are slowly expanding north
and south along the coast. The range now extends 240 miles from
Half Moon Bay in San Mateo County to Cojo Anchorage south of Point
Conception in Santa Barbara County.
</P>
<P>
   In Monterey Bay, otters are a popular attraction as they float
on their backs while loudly cracking open clams on their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think that they'll be there forever and ever,'' said
biologist Steve Alcorn, deputy leader of the otter recovery team
leader at Fish and Wildlife. ``And that may not be the case. This
population is no longer recovering, and mortality appears to be
spread along all ages. It's a difficult thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are finding dead and stranded otters on beaches at
higher numbers than ever _ about 200 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is only a portion of the ones that are dying,'' Alcorn
said. ``It doesn't account for the animals that never wash up on
the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists, who hope to gain about $1.7 million per year for
five years to explore the causes, cite numerous theories for the
troubles:
</P>
<P>
   _ Infectious disease. The National Wildlife Health Lab in
Madison, Wis., run by Fish and Wildlife, has found that since 1992
more than 40 percent of dead otters carry infectious diseases,
including parasitic worms and encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fishing equipment. Sea otters can become entangled and drown
in large-mesh gillnets, and gillnet fishing is increasing in
southern Monterey Bay. Regulations require nets to be set in waters
deeper than 180 feet to spare otters, but otters go into deeper
waters, too. The commercial fishing industries are beginning to use
pots that have a funnel shaped interior, which can trap otters as
they venture inside.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starvation. Otters eat 25 percent to 30 percent of their body
weight a day. Some scientists believe there's a scarcity of sea
urchin, abalone and crab, as well as otters' less preferred foods:
mussels, squid and starfish in the middle of the range.
</P>
<P>
   _ Natural predators. As otters expand their range north of Santa
Cruz, some of the dead ones show signs of white shark attack.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speedboats. There are a few reports of boats' striking sea
otters in Elkhorn Slough at Moss Landing and in other spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any clear answers,'' said Jim Estes, a
marine biologist at the U.S. Geological Survey's Biological
Resources Division at the University of California at Santa Cruz.
``But we know some things. Infectious disease is a major cause of
mortality based on all the fresh carcasses since the early 1990s.
There's no question that this has been an important factor in the
failure of the California sea otter population to recover
rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Marine Mammal Center in Sausalito, parasitologist Murray
Dailey is trying to isolate the types and life cycles of
acanthocephalan worms that infest otters. The pathology department
at the University of California at Davis also is studying ways in
which otters may pick up the deadly organisms, perhaps in sewage or
by eating carrier animals.
</P>
<P>
   Estes wants more study on whether otters are drowning in droves,
which occurred in the 1980s, before new regulations controlled
gillnets. More fish pots, which catch live animals for market, are
being used on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sea otters once extended into the northern Japanese archipelago
to the east coast of Kamchatka eastward through the Commander
Islands, Aleutian archipelago and Pribiloff Islands to the Alaska
Peninsula and along the Pacific Coast of North America to about
central Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   Before fur traders nearly wiped out the southern population
between 1742 and 1911 _ leaving only 50 animals on the Central
Coast _ an estimated 20,000 lived from middle Oregon to central
Baja California. Worldwide, the number dropped to 2,000 from
300,000. An International Fur Seal Treaty in 1911 protected otters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are 100,000 around the world, with about 98,000 in
the northern population of Alaskan and British Columbian waters and
the balance along the California coast.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, because of the small number of animals, the limited
distribution and the increasing threat from oil spills, otters were
listed as threatened, preventing oil, fishing and other industries
from conducting activities that killed or harassed them.
</P>
<P>
   Sea otters thrive in a narrow ecological zone of rocky
shorelines and kelp beds. Adult males weigh an average 64 pounds
and are 4 1/2 feet long, compared with 43 pounds and 4 feet for
females. They use their padded and clawed forepaws for voracious
feeding and grooming and their flipper-like hind legs for graceful
aquatic locomotion.
</P>
<P>
   Their reddish-brown fur is glossy and so dense that some animals
have 650,000 hairs per square inch. The fur traps air and insulates
them from cold sea water, unlike seals and whales, which have
blubber for insulation. Otters have little subcutaneous fat for
energy storage and must constantly feed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
