<SLUG> BC-STRONGARM-CHIP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL TOUTS FAST STRONGARM PROCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. - Intel engineers in Chandler are working on the
chip equivalent of a fuel-efficient vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers want handheld computers and other electronics that can
download graphic-rich Web pages, but their energy-guzzling
microprocessors tend to devour battery power.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Intel said Monday that its next generation
StrongARM processor, due out in the second half of next year, will
offer three times the processing speed of its predecessor while
using slightly less power.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the chip can run at lower processing speeds and use as
little as one-tenth the power, explained Jay Heeb, design and
architecture engineer for Intel's next generation of StrongARM.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks to be pretty impressive,'' said Trevor Yancey, vice
president of technology at the Scottsdale, Ariz., market research
firm IC Insights.
</P>
<P>
   The chip builds on StrongARM technology Intel acquired from
Digital Equipment Corp. in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said the forthcoming StrongARM chip will run at 600
megahertz per second and use a reasonable amount of energy or run
as slow as 150 MHz and use very little energy.
</P>
<P>
   And it can offer a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the chip is being used in a handheld computer
and the user is downloading a color graphic from the Internet, the
chip will operate at processing speeds of up to 600 megahertz.
After the picture is downloaded and is being viewed, the
microprocessor will operate at a lower speed, saving the battery
power, Heeb said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dominating the industry, Intel's next StrongARM
processor will compete with chips made by Hitachi, Toshiba and
others. ``They need to make up some market share here,'' said Ken
Dulaney, vice president of the San Jose market research firm Mobile
Computing.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the next StrongARM appears to have compelling
attributes, namely: ``performance, price and power.''
</P>
<P>
   The processor is designed for devices such as set-top boxes,
handheld computers, Web phones and some Internet products. It's
part of Intel's ongoing efforts to expand beyond its core market of
producing 80 percent of the microprocessors used in the world's
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a smart move on Intel's part, say several analysts who
expect the popularity of handheld devices to boom.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide growth of handheld devices is expected to grow at a
compounded annual rate of 43 percent until 2002, according to
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   IDC forecasts that by 2002 worldwide shipments of the gadgets
will surpass 25 million units in a market worth more than $13
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Intel's trying to make the most of the market
opportunities,'' said Jill House, a research analyst at IDC. ``They
are better off supporting everything rather than just picking one
pony and betting on it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing can be reached at rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  SUBURBAN-CLOUT-ART-2TAKE     05-03 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS TAILORING THEIR PITCHES TO SUIT SUBURBAN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SUBURBAN-CLOUT-ART-2TAKES-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anyone perplexed by the time Vice President Al Gore
has devoted recently to traffic jams, car phones and suburban
sprawl should consider this: Fifty years ago fewer than a quarter
of Americans lived in the suburbs. Now half or more do. Every 10
years, another 10 members of Congress represent predominantly
suburban districts.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle for the presidency and control of Congress gets
under way, that growth pattern is having a profound effect on the
language and policy proposals of the parties: from the focus on
education and child-rearing to the interest in controlling sprawl
to a search for ways to appeal to the high-technology workers who
populate the office complexes along suburban beltways.
</P>
<P>
   So Al Gore looks at suburban land use policies. Elizabeth Dole
courts suburban women by braving jeers in New Hampshire to defend
the ban on assault weapons. And Rep. Thomas Davis, the new chairman
of the House Republican re-election effort, looks for candidates
tailored for just such fast-growing areas as his own affluent
Virginia district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly where the rubber is hitting the road today is the
suburbs,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer demographics are behind much of the political interest in
the suburbs. To show what the shifting living patterns could mean
to Democrats whose core voters are in the cities, Al From, the head
of the centrist Democratic Leadership Council, points to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   When John F. Kennedy narrowly won the state in 1960, he noted in
an article in The New Democrat, Chicago cast 35 percent of the
Illinois vote. Twenty-six percent came from the suburbs. In 1996
when Bill Clinton was re-elected, the suburbs cast 40 percent of
the state's vote, Chicago only 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electorate of the 21st century,'' From told Democrats in
Idaho recently, ``will be more educated, more affluent, more
suburban, more independent, less unionized _ unless we can turn
that around _ and less urban than the electorate in the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the case that the political alignment of suburban
voters seems to be shifting. Two decades ago, suburbanites were
considered bedrock Republicans, drawn to the party's message of
lower taxes and fewer handouts for the poor. Now, as suburbs age
and events like the shootings in Littleton, Colo., show that they
are not immune from violence, suburbanites have become more willing
to vote for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton led George Bush in the suburbs in 1992 and made even
stronger inroads in 1996, winning key suburban counties all across
the industrial Midwest and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Suburbs, of course, range vastly in character from older
communities near the cities to the new strip malls and subdivisions
rising from more distant farm fields. When politicians speak of the
suburbs, they use the phrase as shorthand for key groups of swing
voters: the ``soccer moms'' who were so sought after in the 1996
election; married couples with children; affluent independents; and
the high-technology workers of the information age who populate
office complexes miles from cities.
</P>
<P>
   Linda DiVall, who is the pollster for Mrs. Dole, says the
crucial demographic group is parents who have children under 18
living at home. ``They are a little more Republican than Democrat,
and the candidate that wins this group tends to win the election,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   All this means that politicians are listening closely to voters
like those in Montgomery County, a Republican area outside
Philadelphia that stretches from densely packed brick homes to the
swanky Main Line. The county backed Clinton twice and ousted a
Republican congressman last November in favor of Joe Hoeffel, a
Democratic county commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel was sounding out constituents one recent Saturday in
supermarkets when Joyce Wilson accosted him by a vegetable counter
to talk of the shootings at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this country is just kind of crazy the way it is
handling guns,'' said Ms. Wilson, a pastor's assistant. She also
deplored the growth in the area's Delaware Valley. ``A lot of our
town commissioners are reluctant to stand up against the
builders,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At another supermarket, Lynne Hall, 52, a manager for a medical
office, showed how precarious the Democrats' hold on voters like
her might be. ``I voted for you,'' she shouted to Hoeffel, ``but I
still don't like that president.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Issues like education, transportation and health care have long
been on the national agenda, and they have an appeal stretching
beyond the suburbs. But the focus on the suburbs _ and thus broadly
on middle class families _ has subtly changed how the issues are
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to separate class from geography,'' said Geoffrey
Garin, a Democratic political consultant. ``Think of where the
health care debate has gone. It's not about insuring the uninsured.
It's about HMOs. The debate is about how to treat people who
already have insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true with education. Once Democrats emphasized
educational programs for poor children and Republicans spoke about
eliminating the Education Department. Now both parties are gearing
the debate toward the interests of middle class families, the
Democrats stressing class size and the Republicans offering tax
credits for parochial and private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   New this year to the national agenda are issues that appeal
almost entirely to suburbanites. Gore and some Democrats like
Hoeffel are talking of suburban sprawl, traffic congestion and
preservation of open space _ issues that are already playing
prominently in state and local political races.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, there were more than 200 ballot referendums around
the country on maintaining open space. This week, the White House
is sponsoring a National Town Hall meeting on the subject in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, with Gore at the forefront, has
proposed a $10 billion ``Livability agenda'' that includes tax
credits to support bonding authority for protecting farmland and
cleaning up abandoned industrial space as well as mass transit
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The livability issue is huge here,'' said Hoeffel in his
district office where he used a map of the county to point out
traffic trouble spots and new development. ``The suburban sprawl
that we're experiencing is happening all over the country, and
suburban people are up in arms.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one Republican strategist, Christine Matthews, thinks
her party is underestimating the resonance of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be empathetic to the fact that people are going a
little crazy,'' she said. ``You're going out and all you see are
these giant Wal-Marts, and they are every few blocks and its not
the kind of environment people want to live in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
