<P>
   SUBURBAN-CLOUT (Washington) _ Fifty years ago fewer than a
quarter of Americans lived in the suburbs. By early next century
more than half of Americans will live there. Every 10 years,
another 10 congressional districts become suburban. As the battles
for the presidency and control of Congress get under way, these
growth patterns are already having a profound effect on the
language and policy proposals of the two parties. By Alison
Mitchell. 1,571 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ After 13 days of
vigils, funerals and media scrutiny, many Columbine High School
students were eager to return to the daily routine of academic
life. The students are to attend classes at nearby Chatfield High
School. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ The Dow Jones industrial average
blew past the 11,000 mark Monday, just 24 trading days after it
topped 10,000 for the first time. The Dow average closed the day at
11,014.69, up 225.65 points. The 10 percent move from March 29 to
May 3 was not the fastest such rise in market history, but it was
the quickest jump of 10 percent to come during a period of
prolonged market strength. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
