<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Tuesday, May 4, and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN _ Let the hire beware. Daily News columnist Ken
Lloyd, Ph.D., a specialist in organizational behavior, answers
readers' questions on workplace ethics and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-DOW (Los Angeles) _ The Dow Jones Industrial Average
topped 11,000 for the first time amid signs the economy continues
to expand, though not fast enough to prompt a Federal Reserve
interest-rate increase. The latest milestone came barely a month
after the Dow average passed the 10,000 mark on March 29. It
reached 10,000 during trading on March 16. By Deborah Adamson.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   XIRCOM-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ Shares in modem maker Xircom Inc.
rose 12.78 percent Monday after the Thousand Oaks-based company
announced its entering the PDA market; personal data assistants,
that is. Also, CIBC Oppenheimer initiated coverage on the issue
with a ``strong buy'' recommendation and set a 12-month price
target of $40. Shares closed Monday at $25.375. By Ben Sullivan.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
