<HEADLINE>
GLOBE NAMES HANAFIN EDITORIAL DIRECTOR OF ON-LINE ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Teresa Hanafin, assistant managing editor for
technology at The Boston Globe, has been named editorial director
of the newspaper's Web site, Boston.com, Globe officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hanafin, 43, will continue to manage computer-assisted reporting
projects for the newspaper. The new slot will give her the
additional responsibility of directing content strategy for
Boston.com, one of the nation's leading newspaper Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teresa's distinguished news career coupled with her
technological skills and interests make her an excellent and
obvious choice for this job,'' said Globe editor Matthew V. Storin.
</P>
<P>
   In her 14-year career at the Globe, Hanafin has covered state
politics, development, and Cape Cod. She worked for two years as
assistant business editor and went on to be deputy city editor and
city editor. In March, she ended a two-and-a-half-year tenure as
the paper's metro editor. Under her leadership, the metro staff won
several national journalism prizes, including the George Polk
Award, the Investigative Reporters and Editors Award, and the
Headliners Award.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Millstein, Boston.com's chief executive, said Hanafin's
selection is ``consistent with our desire to integrate more of what
we do on Boston.com with the interests of the Globe newspaper.''
The Web site, launched in October 1995, recorded 29.2 million page
views in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
