<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TEACHER, FRIEND GO ON TRIAL FOR DRUG SMUGGLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A former high school teacher and her boyfriend
went on trial in federal court here Monday, accused of recruiting
teen-agers to drive carloads of marijuana from Mexico into Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme let Juan Galan and Rebecca Besa reap the financial
rewards of smuggling drugs while minimizing their risk of arrest,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Ried said in opening arguments.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers cast their clients as undeserving casualties
of America's overzealous war on drugs. They called on the jury to
be wary of convicted smugglers who would appear as ``patriot
witnesses'' for the government under grants of immunity or with
deals to reduce their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are criminals, except all of a sudden when they
join the other side, they're patriot witnesses,'' said Alan Brown,
who represents Besa.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old former English teacher at Eagle Pass High School
wiped her eyes and shook her head from side to side as the
allegations were laid out before U.S. District Judge Fred Biery.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Pass is about 140 miles west of here and is across the Rio
Grande from Piedras Negras, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Ried said evidence against the couple would include receipts
showing Besa rented cars used by the smugglers and hotel rooms
where they stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew very well everything that her boyfriend did,'' Ried
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said Besa's only interest in Galan was romantic, and
that she thought he was working as a government informer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence will show that she was used by Mr. Juan Galan,
because she was in love with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Galan, a 26 year-old Mexican national portrayed by prosecutors
as a drug-dealing playboy, listened to the translation of court
proceedings Monday with no obvious signs of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Alex Scharff conceded that Galan is no angel, but
he said his client isn't a drug kingpin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an ordinary guy who did some things that were wrong,''
Scharff said.
</P>
<P>
   Both defendants are charged with conspiring to possess marijuana
with the intent to distribute, and employing people under 18 in a
drug transaction. Galan also is charged with operating a continuing
criminal enterprise and illegal possession of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   To convict him on the criminal enterprise charge, known as ``the
kingpin statute,'' the government must prove Galan supervised five
or more people in the criminal enterprise, that it involved three
or more criminal acts, and that it generated a substantial amount
of money.
</P>
<P>
   Ried said that between 1993 and 1998, Galan directed smugglers
carrying from 50 to 800 pounds of pot at a time, from Piedras
Negras to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved from Eagle Pass to San Antonio in 1998 and, at
the time of their arrest in November, $47,000 in cash was found in
their apartment, Ried said.
</P>
<P>
   A search of Galan's mother's home in Eagle Pass uncovered three
guns, which Galan was prohibited from owning because he is an
illegal immigrant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
