<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-DALEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCE CHIEF BRINGS NAFTA MESSAGE TO TEXTILE PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying his goal is to promote free trade, US Secretary of
Commerce William Daley visited a Fall River textile plant Monday
and met with business leaders while angry union members stood
outside questioning the free trade policy that has cost them their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, part of the first leg of Daley's national trade
initiative ``The National Trade Education Tour,'' began at the
World Trade Center in Boston, where the trade secretary met with
several business and political leaders. They included US Senator
Edward M. Kennedy; David Weinstein, chief of environment and
government affairs at Fidelity Investments; and Ann Finucane, chair
of the New England Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's prosperity in the years to come will depend on how
well our companies and our workers are able to compete in the world
economy,'' Daley told the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want every man, woman, and child in America to understand
that trade matters,'' he said. ``We want to hear their views and
come up with a new approach on trade that ensures that the maximum
number of Americans benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Daley urged business leaders to do all they could to
support free trade, union leaders argued that the North American
Free Trade Agreement has helped destroy the nation's ailing
manufacturing sector and has stripped many US workers of viable
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud you for saying we need to have a dialogue,'' AFL-CIO
president Robert Haynes said. ``I agree that the American public
needs to be educated about trade, but I also believe that you and
the president need to be educated about the insecurity of the
American worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Daley and his entourage toured Quaker Fabrics, a
Fall River manufacturer of upholstery fabric whose work force has
increased to 2,400 from just over 1,000 five years ago. The company
was selected for the tour by the US Department of Commerce because
it has succeeded in a region where many textile manufacturers have
shutdown or moved operations overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kelly, a credit manager at Quaker Fabrics, said the
company expects between $250 million and $280 million in sales this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose Quaker Fabrics because we felt people in Fall River
need to see the positive (aspects of free trade),'' Daley said in
an interview after the plant tour. ``There is no question that
there have been job dislocations over the last decade, not just
because of trade but also because of technological change. No trade
agreement is all good or all bad. The key is to keep things
balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the office of the Union of Needletrade Industrial and
Technical Employees (UNITE), many workers said it would take more
jobs rather than a national tour to convince them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want free trade. We want fair trade,'' said Claire
Francoeur, a 35-year-old curtain maker who was born and raised in
Fall River. ``We can't compete with foreign wages that are $1 an
hour or less.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
