<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-MEDIONE-BOS &LR;      05-03 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MEDIONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL DEFECTION CASTS DOUBT ON BID FOR MEDIONE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The chances are diminishing that a partnership between
Comcast Corp. and two leading technology companies will outbid AT&AMP;T
Corp. to acquire MediaOne Group, the nation's fourth largest cable
television provider.
</P>
<P>
   America Online Inc. Monday reportedly dropped out of a hastily
formed financial arrangement with Comcast and Microsoft Corp. to
acquire MediaOne, whose largest market for cable TV and high speed
Internet service is Massachussetts.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne has touched off one of the highest profile bidding wars
on Wall Street in years. The Colorado-based company's extensive
cable network is coveted by major corporations seeking to offer
high-speed Internet access, local phone service and enhanced
entertainment services.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Philadelphia-based Comcast, the nation's third
largest cable company, unveiled a $48 billion agreement to acquire
MediaOne only to have AT&AMP;T make a $54 billion unsolicited
counteroffer in late April.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, MediaOne's board of directors agreed to accept
the AT&AMP;T offer of stock and cash. They abandoned Comcast's offer of
stock only, and gave it until Thursday to come up with a higher
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Both AOL, based in Dulles, Va. and Microsoft of Redmond, Wash.
have expressed interest in helping Comcast make a new bid. Last
week, AOL and Microsoft signed ``confidentiality'' agreements with
MediaOne, the first step in merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL has dropped out, a decision first reported by CNBC
Monday afternoon. ``If AOL backs out, I think the probablility that
Comcast can come back with a higher offer is lower than it was last
Friday,'' said Thomas Egan, senior cable and satellite analyst at
PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne shares Monday fell 1 3/4 to 79 7/8 while AT&AMP;T stock
rose 5/8 to 51 1/8. Comcast stock climbed 3 1/16 to 65 15/16 while
Microsoft shares fell 1 9/16 to 79 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   An AOL spokeswoman declined to comment on the CNBC report that
cited unidentified people close to the Internet service company.
CNBC reported that AOL was deterred by the financial demands of
partnering with Comcast.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Microsoft or AT&AMP;T, AOL does not have substantial cash to
back a high-priced acquistion of MediaOne, according to several
Wall Street analysts. However, AOL wants to crack the high speed
Internet access market over cable wires, since it is losing
customers to MediaOne and other cable providers. About 50 percent
of AOL's customers use relatively slow dial-up modems to access the
World Wide Web and cable provides an attractive, faster
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL has the strategic reasons for getting closer to the cable
industry, but it lacks the cash, while Microsoft has the money, but
not the same critical need to get close to the major cable
players,'' said Gary Farber, an analyst at SG Cowen &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft declined to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even without AOL, Comcast may still find the cash it needs.
Microsoft cofounder and billionaire Paul Allen, who controls
Charter Communications Corp., the nation's sixth largest cable
television operator, is reportedly talking with Comcast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
