known as informal, or third-party, diplomacy, a type of peacemaking
also practiced by former president Jimmy Carter, UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan, and dozens of current and former politicians
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jackson who in 1984 persuaded Syrian president Hafez
Assad to free a captured US Navy pilot, Lieutenant Robert O.
Goodman Jr. Later that year he talked Fidel Castro into releasing
48 American and Cuban political prisoners. And in 1990, he won
freedom for more than 700 women and children being held as human
shields by Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse works best this way,'' said Roger Wilkins, a close
friend of Jackson's and a historian at George Mason University.
``He uses his celebrity to great advantage. This is one time where
his celebrity enhances the chance for success, and where the chance
for success is the ripest. And you have to figure that if Milosevic
even let him come to Belgrade it must be because he wanted to send
several messages to President Clinton that he otherwise could not
send.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins said he is not sure whether the Milosevic message will
be that it is time to negotiate or that the Yugoslav president is
not about to blink.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilkins and others who know Jackson say that the close
relationship between Clinton and Jackson _ a relationship once
strained by Clinton's 1992 criticism of Jackson and other black
leaders but now so intimate that Jackson frequently prayed with
Clinton during the dark days of the Monica Lewinsky scandal _
guarantees that Milosevic's words and any other signs from him will
be delivered in full to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Jackson's strength is that he is an American who,
because he is black, represents an underdog in the eyes of people
in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Milosevic and Assad feel they are being beaten on
by America,'' said Brian Mandell, a lecturer in public policy at
Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government. ``They see Jesse as
someone who also has had to deal with that in his own society.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Lance, another long-time Jackson friend, said he is often
disappointed that critics claim Jackson is being ``manipulated'' by
the likes of Saddam Hussein or Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that is 180-degrees wrong. You can't manipulate him.''
Nor is Jackson a simple intermediary, said Lance. He is a persuader
and will work to persuade everyone _ Milosevic, Clinton, the
general public _ that the fighting must end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally heartfelt as far as I'm concerned,'' said Lance,
who advised Jackson during his 1988 run for the Democratic
presidential nomination. ``He really believes in `keeping hope
alive,' and he sees a situation here where he believes hope is
needed. He is sincere. And, look, this'' mission to Belgrade ``was
not without personal risk. There were bombs going off. It was a
dangerous place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into dangerous places without official diplomatic blessing
is often the only way to get the ball rolling when two sides have
staked out hard-line positions, said Babbitt. But government
officials often bite their nails during such missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials don't know what these non-official actors are going
to say,'' she said. ``They have no control over them. That's what
makes them nervous. They might say or do something that undermines
the government's position.''
</P>
<P>
   That appears not to have happened in Jackson's case, she said.
His comments on landing Monday were no more radical than a call for
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must seize this moment to take the step to dramatic
diplomacy from bloody, protracted war,'' Jackson said. ``We have
the power to bomb. We should have the strength to negotiate. A
bridge has been blown up, the bridge of diplomacy and trust, and
that bridge must be restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Jackson succeeds in restoring dialog, an exceedingly
difficult task lies ahead: Hammering out an agreement that meets
the substance of NATO's demands _ allowing Kosovo's Albanians to
return under armed international protection. That will be the
central mission of Chernomyrdin and other diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Fisher, a professor at Harvard Law School and director of
the Harvard Negotiation Project, was involved in peacemaking
projects from Camp David to Nicaragua to Afghanistan. He sees the
Balkan conflict as extremely complicated in part because of the
sequencing that is needed. One of many examples he gives: How can
Serb forces be pulled out without leaving Serb civilians in Kosovo
vulnerable to revenge raids by members of the Kosovo Liberation
Army?
</P>
<P>
   ``The public ought to realize that moving to peace is terribly
difficult and complicated,'' said Fisher. ``The process is more
important than the ultimate solution, and it will require
third-party help.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin may be that party. If he is, the process will be
shuttle diplomacy _ a constant round of diplomatic missions aimed
at narrowing differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse Jackson can open doors,'' said Mandell, the Kennedy
school lecturer. ``He can change the discourse of escalation. He
can put an important pause in the situation. But he can't transform
the situation. It is up to others to work out the details on
international peacekeeping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
