<HEADLINE>
SLEDGE HAMMER USED TO KILL TEXAS MINISTER, WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PATTY REINERT  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Weimar minister and his wife, found beaten to death
in the church parsonage Sunday, were killed with a sledge hammer,
police said Monday as they investigated the first murders the town
of 2,000 could recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were lying in their bed,'' said Police Chief Bill
Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's in shock. Nobody here, even the old-timers I've
talked to, ever remembers a murder in Weimar.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said the bodies of Weimar United Church of Christ
minister Norman J. ``Skip'' Sirnic and his wife, Karen, were
discovered Sunday morning after church members in the town 90 miles
west of Houston grew concerned that the couple had failed to show
up for services.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy reports were not available Monday, but Livingston said
it appeared that the Sirnics were killed late Friday or early
Saturday. Their killer apparently broke into the house through a
rear door off the carport, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said he called in investigators from the Fort Bend
County Sheriff's Department to help with the gathering of evidence
from the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were searching for the couple's 1998 red Mazda
pickup, but Livingston stopped short of saying theft was believed
to be the motive for the killings. He noted that besides the
pickup, items taken from the Sirnics' home, including a Sega
Genesis video game and a VCR, were ``minor stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends said they spoke with the Sirnics by telephone about 10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, and neighbors noticed that the pickup was missing from
the couple's driveway about 6 o'clock the next morning, the police
chief said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, church members began morning services without the
minister when he was presumed to be running late, said Donna
Trefny, who has attended the church for more than four decades and
occasionally helped out in the church office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not at all like him to be late,'' she said, so a couple
of church leaders went to check on the minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came back and just announced, `Something's happened,'''
Trefny said. ``And when we left the church, the police were there.
It's a terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Sirnic, who would have turned 47 Sunday, had been pastor at
the 130-member church for the past 10 years. Karen Sirnic, 47,
served as the church's secretary. The minister had a college-age
son from a previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Sirnic was remembered Monday as a caring pastor who made a point
of visiting the sick and elderly in hospitals and area nursing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man of considerable energy and considerable
compassion,'' said the Mark Miller, conference minister of the
South Central Conference of the United Church of Christ. ``He was
very enthusiastic and very active, but he was also quiet. He wasn't
out to go and save everybody, but when you needed him, he would be
there for you. There is a great deal of love here for him and
Karen.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said a steady stream of congregants and ministers from
other Weimar churches visited the church as word of the murders
circulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been coming in all day,'' he said. ``There is such
shock, and people want to ask, `Did this really happen?''' Miller
said counselors were on hand to talk with church members and people
from the community. Funeral arrangements were pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
