<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE REGGIE LEWIS DRUG USE AT ISSUE AS TRIAL OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As the malpractice trial stemming from the death of
Celtics star Reggie Lewis began Monday, attorneys for Lewis' widow
claimed that allegations of cocaine use by the Lewis are irrelevant
to the case, while a lawyer for one of the three cardiologists
being sued countered that it's the very core.
</P>
<P>
   Concealing such information would be the same as showing up in a
doctor's office with a stomach ache and failing to tell him you'd
just eaten ``a two-week-old meatloaf,'' said attorney William F.
Dailey Jr.,, who represents Dr. Gilbert Mudge, the cardiologist
whom Donna Harris-Lewis has accused of failing to diagnose her
husband's deadly heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Robert G. Harley, who represents Harris-Lewis, said
allegations of drug use are immaterial, as well as false. Lewis's
doctors, he said, were responsible for providing top-qualty care
regardless of the cause of his heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   The first witness to testify Monday, Dr. Gerald Miley, a New
England Baptist internist who examined Lewis after he blacked out
during an April 1993 playoff game, said he asked Lewis three times
if he had used cocaine, and each time Lewis answered that he had
not.
</P>
<P>
   Miley said he ``took at face value'' Lewis's assurance that he
had not used cocaine because, ``I had no reason not to believe
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dailey, in his opening statement to jurors in Suffolk
Superior Court, said Lewis had ``great motivation'' to hide any
ilegal drug use since disclosure would have nullified the balance
of his $9 million contract with the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Miley, the initial witness called by Harris-Lewis's lawyers,
said that based on his review of tests conducted on Lewis, he
believed the 27-year-old suffered from a possibly life-threatening
heart abnormality, one that Harley claimed was treatable, if
properly diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Reggie gotten a defibrillator, we wouldn't be here
today,'' Harley said in his opening statement. ``As a result of not
having that defibrillator, we all lost one of the finest young men
of his generation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mudge, Harris-Lewis has sued two other
physicians, Peter L. Friedman and Mark A. Creager, accusing them of
misdiagnosing her husband's heart condition. Harris-Lewis -- who
sat quietly in the front row of the spectator gallery, flanked by
acquaintances -- agreed to settle last week with a fourth doctor,
Dr. John Rutherford, now in practice in Texas. Details of the
settlement have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge says he could not accurately diagnose Lewis's condition
because Lewis withheld information on his cocaine use until two
weeks before he collapsed and died while shooting baskets at
Brandeis University on July 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had sought a second opinion from Mudge after a team of
doctors at New England Baptist Hospital chosen by the Celtics
diagnosed Lewis with arrhythmia, a potentially life-threatening
defect that could end his career.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis then consulted with Mudge, one of Boston's most respected
cardiologists, at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge concluded that Lewis suffered from a neurological disorder
that caused fainting spells. With proper treatment, he said, Lewis
could return to basketball. Three months later, Lewis died while
shooting baskets in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The state medical examiner listed the cause of death as
adenovirus 2, a virus that could have caused inflammation of the
heart, tissue scarring and, ultimately, death.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey suggested to jurors that Lewis had ignored doctors'
orders to restrict his physical activity to stretching,
weightlifting and tai chi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Lewis was told before he went out the door at Brigham and
Women's Hospital that he was not to exercise without having a
(heart) monitor in place,'' said Dailey, adding that a witness will
testify she saw Lewis ``glistening with sweat'' while shooting
baskets after his discharge.
</P>
<P>
   While the trial, which is expected to last four weeks, will
focus on whether Mudge and his two co-defendants at Brigham and
Women's Hospital made misjudgments that resulted in Lewis's death,
Monday's proceedings made clear that alleged cocaine use by Lewis
will be a key issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Harris-Lewis tried unsuccessfully to bar any mention
of alleged drug use from the trial, arguing that the issue had been
raised ``for the sole purpose of trashing'' Lewis's reputation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
