<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE READY TO AVOID KOSOVO POLICY VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate plans to dodge a major vote Tuesday on
the Kosovo conflict by setting aside a measure that would authorize
President Clinton ``to use all necessary force and other means'' to
prevail in NATO's attack on Yugolsavia.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing congressional anxiety over Clinton's Kosovo policy,
the White House and leaders of both parties Monday warned senators
against sending the world conflicting signals by effectively
sanctioning an all-out war in the Balkans a week after the House
officially refused to support US involvement in the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was prepared to heed the warnings by sidetracking the
resolution through a procedural vote, angering several war veterans
in the chamber who are pushing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat amazing to me that Congress is not ready to make
clear its resolve,'' said Senator John F. Kerry, a Vietnam veteran
and cosponsor of the resolution. ``There is an awful lot of
hand-wringing and politics going on that seems to belie the reality
of what's at stake in this conflict,'' Kerry said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Senator John McCain, an Arizona
Republican and former prisoner of war in Vietnam, is aimed in part
at preventing the United States from engaging in limited military
action that could end in defeat, as occurred in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, anticipating the Senate sidestepping the resolution,
blasted his colleagues for allowing ``American pilots and possibly
American soldiers to risk their lives for a cause that we will not
risk our careers for.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is seeking the Republican presidential nomination,
attracted eight other cosponsors for the bipartisan measure,
including Connecticut Democrats Christopher J. Dodd and Joseph I.
Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   But an array of unlikely allies emerged to oppose the measure.
In a lengthy debate on the Senate floor, Clinton's foes said the
president's current policy is misguided and Congress should not be
seen as expanding his authority in the conflict. They argued the
measure would strip Congress of the power to stop the
administration from escalating the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration needs to learn the rule of holes. When you
find yourself in one, stop digging,'' said Senator Tim Hutchinson,
an Arkansas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, including Kerry, called on Clinton to better
articulate his goals in the Kosovo conflict. The president's
supporters also criticized the administration for insisting from
the start that the United States would not use ground troops, to
the possible benefit of Yugoslavia's military planners.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of Democrats _ and some Republicans _ said Congress
should allow more time for the NATO airstrikes to work before the
Senate grants Clinton additional authority that he has yet to seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is not the right time to debate a wider war,'' said
Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who is expected to join a large majority
of his colleagues in voting to table the measure. ``President
Clinton has made it clear that if ground troops are necessary, he
will ask for the support of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen, a former Republican senator
from Maine, spoke with the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, and
several former colleagues Monday in anticipation of a vote Monday
night to table the measure. But Lott postponed the vote until
Tuesday to permit senators to continue debating the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the measure asserted their goal was not to give
Clinton ``carte blanche'' in the Balkans but to push him to prepare
for the possibility of sending in ground troops if the airstrikes
fail and the US military remains involved in the NATO mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are forcing the president to lead,'' said Senator Chuck
Hagel, a Nebraska Republican and Vietnam veteran. ``That's what
this resolution is about. We're not abdicating.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel all but taunted his colleagues to permit a direct vote on
the measure. ``Isn't this terrible,'' he said sarcastically on the
Senate floor. ``We're actually asking senators to take a stand.
What is this country coming to, asking senators to stand up and
take a stand. It's offensive, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   One senator took a forceful stand: George V. Voinovich, an Ohio
Republican who is the only senator of Serbian ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to stop the bombing,'' said Voinovich, who blamed
Clinton, NATO and the State Department for ``allowing their egos to
get in the way of their common sense and good judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich, the former governor of Ohio, added: ``The time has
come for NATO to get off its high horse, restrain its ego and,
instead of trying to save face over a major foreign policy blunder,
start thinking about saving lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
