<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   El Al Marks Jubilee With Free Stop in Rome
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate demand linked to celebrations in Rome and
Jerusalem, beginning this summer El Al will offer a stopover in
Rome at no extra charge to passengers traveling between New York
and Tel Aviv. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Vatican committee in charge of pilgrimages to
Israel for the Great Jubilee Year 2000 named El Al its official
carrier to the Holy Land. Beginning June 21, the airline will
provide flights from Kennedy International Airport to Rome leaving
at 6:45 p.m. on Monday and Thursday and arriving at 8:50 a.m. the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   These dates accommodate travelers who want to hear Pope John
Paul II's addresses on Wednesday and Saturday. Daily flights from
Rome to Tel Aviv, except for Friday, leave at 10:50 a.m., arriving
in Israel at 3 p.m. Pilgrims who wish to take their stopover in
Rome on the return trip may also do that at no extra charge. Round
trip tickets valid from July 11 to Sept. 16 cost $829, not counting
taxes, if purchased by Tuesday; thereafter the price is $1,486.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee celebrations in Rome, Jerusalem and in local churches
elsewhere began this Easter and continue to Christmas 2000.
Information: (800) 223-6700 or (212) 768-9200.
</P>
<P>
   From Slag Heap To Serial Gardens
</P>
<P>
   Two former Yorkshire coal mines are the unlikely site of a new
British attraction that celebrates environmental awareness. The
Earth Center, a $160 million science center, opened last month in
Doncaster, 172 miles north of London. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indoor and outdoor exhibitions, including gardens, play areas,
adventure trails and high-tech galleries, aim to convey serious
messages about ways to protect the earth's resources. The cleaning
up of the slag and polluted soil of these former coal mines is
itself an example of regeneration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the themed areas is the Planet Earth Galleries, a vast
space with a subterranean feel. Echoing acoustics and kaleidoscopic
images projected onto rotating glass panels and gigantic glass
spheres create a range of effects, from the blur of a busy highway
to the green calm of a rain forest: a solar spectrum installation
using lights, projection prisms and mirrors creates a rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   In the Action for the Future Gallery, magic windows with
three-dimensional clouds reveal visions of a ``fantastic future''
in cities and in the countryside, with examples of such projects as
purifying water in Tanzania and preserving Antarctica from
industrialization. In Nature Works, children can collect aquatic
bugs and view magnified insects on a giant screen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 35-acre grounds include a forest garden and 21st century
terrace garden and orchards. Water from the nearby River Don is
treated and used in five colorful bog gardens, and even the
lavatories are an exhibit, with waste water being cleaned by algae
and sunlight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant, three cafes, a barbecue and bar serve organic food
whenever possible. The Earth Center, Denaby Main, Doncaster DN12
4EA, telephone (44-1709) 512000. Open daily 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.,
March to October. Admission $14.50, children $11.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain Prices For Haute Cuisine
</P>
<P>
   A half-price sale at the Paris Ritz? It's true. The two-star
restaurant at one of Paris' fanciest hotels will soon be serving
langoustines in dill jelly, breaded asparagus with morel mushrooms,
a grenadin de veau, and cherries jubilee _ along with assorted
wines and coffee _ for $85 a person. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The catch? It's a one-day deal. On May 27, the Ritz, (33-1)
43.16.30.80, will join more than 3,000 other restaurants throughout
France to celebrate the fourth annual Fete de la Cuisine by
slashing the price of a gastronomic fixed-price meal by 50
percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The festival aims to initiate a new clientele to the joy of fine
dining, and participating restaurateurs are encouraged to spotlight
regional products. The cozy Auberge des Arts in Nice, (33-4)
93.85.63.53, plans a five-course meal around pigeon farci a la
nicoise and Provencal wine for $45. The one-star Restaurant Pierre
Orsi in Lyons, (33-4) 78.89.57.68, will serve Macon and Cote du
Rhone wines with six courses that include smoked salmon, truffled
ravioli stuffed with foie gras, turbot in champagne sauce and duck
a l'orange with mushroom risotto for $65. The Parisian one-star
chef Bernard Fournier of Le Petit Colombier, (33-1) 43.80.28.54,
organizes the event. ``I love to connect with people who couldn't
dream of eating at such fancy places at normal prices,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ireland, Sweden, Germany, Italy, Spain and Luxembourg
will join the initiative for the first time. A distinctive Fete
poster will be displayed outside all participating restaurants. An
updated list with addresses and telephone numbers can be found at
www.lhotellerie.fr.
</P>
<P>
   _ CORINNE LABALME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Variations on a Theme: Flexible Flashlights
</P>
<P>
   Two new flashlights may interest travelers. One is ideal for
backpackers; the other is powered by a hand crank and would be
valuable when batteries fail, or as an automobile emergency light. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The smaller light, the Ranger, by Lumatec, has an
inch-and-a-half fluorescent bulb at one end and a bulb with a
focused beam at the other. It is 5 inches long and 3 inches wide at
the wider end, and can be stood on end or hung by a lanyard with
either end facing down. It operates on four AA batteries, and comes
with one replacement bulb but no batteries, for $19.95.
Information: (800) 776-7945. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Freeplay ``self powered'' lantern can be plugged into an
outlet and charged so it will operate for two hours, or you can
charge it by winding it up. If its retractable handle is wound 60
turns, the power is retained indefinitely until it is used. It can
provide a steady or a flashing beam. It is 10 inches long, 5 inches
wide and weighs 4 pounds 2 ounces. It can be used to provide power
to other devices that use batteries. Including an extra bulb, it
costs $69 at Sharper Image, Discovery Channel and other specialty
stores. Information: (800) 946-3234. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ BETSY WADE
</P>
<P>
   A Sculpture Garden at the National Gallery
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Art will open a sculpture garden on a
six-acre site near its West Building on May 23, providing an
outdoor setting for the works of such artists as Louise Bourgeois,
Mark di Suvero, Roy Lichtenstein, Sol LeWitt, Ellsworth Kelly,
Lucas Samaras, Claes Oldenburg and Coosje van Bruggen, and Tony
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The new sculpture garden, which is not far from the Hirshhorn
Museum's sculpture garden just across the Washington Mall, was
built with a gift from the Morris and Gwendolyn Cafritz
Foundation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was designed by Laurie D. Olin, a landscape architect, around
an existing circular pool that is converted to an ice-skating rink
in the winter. The garden will be enclosed by a decorative metal
fence with marble piers and plinths designed to complement the
classical style of the West Building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the opening, on May 22, a free afternoon jazz
concert on the Mall will celebrate both the sculpture garden and
the 100th anniversary of Duke Ellington's birth. The performers
will be the Duke Ellington Orchestra and the Dukes of Dixieland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the sculpture garden, as well as to the National
Gallery itself, is free. Hours for both: Monday to Saturday 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m., Sunday 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Information: (202) 737-4215. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ IRVIN MOLOTSKY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
