<SLUG> BC-TONYS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TONY LIST, PLAYWRIGHTS WITH STAYING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a season that brought works by Tennessee Williams,
Arthur Miller and Eugene O'Neill to Broadway, those playwrights
showed their staying power Monday when their dramas led the Tony
Award nominations for straight play.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' ``Not About Nightingales,'' a prison drama that
received its first production this year _ more than 60 years after
it was written and 16 years after the author's death _ took six
nominations, including one for best new play.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's ``Death of a Salesman'' was also nominated in six
categories, including best revival, best director (Robert Falls)
and best leading actor (Brian Dennehy). Miller was also awarded a
special Tony for lifetime achievement that is to be presented at
the ceremony on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's ``Iceman Cometh'' took five, including the nomination
for best revival of a play, tying with ``Twelfth Night'' and the
ballet ``Swan Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   And offering proof that there can be life after death in the
theater, the musical ``Parade,'' which was produced by Lincoln
Center and Livent and closed in February, won nine nominations, the
most of any production. Nominations for the production, which
recounted the 1915 lynching of Leo Frank, a Jewish factory
supervisor in Georgia, included best musical, best direction of a
musical (Harold Prince), best original score (Jason Robert Brown)
and best performance by a leading actor and actress in a musical
(Brent Carver and Carolee Carmello).
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, David Hare, the British
playwright who brought an impressive three productions to Broadway
this season, was effectively shut out of the competition. Not one
of his plays _ ``The Blue Room,'' ``Amy's View'' or the acclaimed
``Via Dolorosa,'' the one-man production in which he stars _ was
nominated for best play. Two members of the cast of ``Amy's View''
did receive nominations: Judi Dench for best performance by a
leading actress in a play, and Samantha Bond for best performance
by a featured actress in a play.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Not About Nightingales,'' nominations for best
new play went to ``Closer,'' by Patrick Marber; ``The Lonesome
West,'' by Martin McDonagh, and ``Side Man,'' by Warren Leight.
</P>
<P>
   This year's nominees, announced Monday morning by Dennehy and
Swoosie Kurtz at Sardi's restaurant, were selected by a group of 28
theater professionals appointed by a Tony Awards administration
committee. The Tony Awards, now in their 53rd year, are presented
by the League of American Theaters and Producers and the American
Theater Wing, which founded the awards in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Awards will be voted in 21 categories by 812 theater
professionals and journalists who are scheduled to mail their
ballots at the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more glaring omissions from this year's nominees were
``The Weir,'' Conor McPherson's new play, and ``On the Town,''
which _ though Mary Testa was nominated for best featured actress
in a musical _ was excluded from the best musical revival category
in favor of ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' ``Little Me,'' ``Peter Pan''
and ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   The actresses Natasha Richardson and Anna Friel of ``Closer''
were also passed over.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Kevin Spacey's insistence that ``The Iceman Cometh''
is an ensemble production (he refused top billing), and strong
reviews for several performers in the 19-member cast, only Spacey
received a nomination _ for best leading actor in a play.
</P>
<P>
   There were also some unorthodox nominees this year. Although
Matthew Bourne's production of ``Swan Lake'' was deemed ineligible
for best musical, it won five nominations Monday, including best
performance by a leading actor in a musical (Adam Cooper), best
direction and best choreography (Bourne for both).
</P>
<P>
   While the choreography for ``Fosse'' was ruled ineligible on the
grounds that it was adapted from Bob Fosse's original steps, the
production was nominated for best new musical.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Parade,'' nominations went to several other
productions that have already closed. ``Twelfth Night,'' which
closed in August, received five nominations, including best revival
of a play and best original score for Jeanine Tesori's music to
Shakespeare's words. ``Little Me,'' which closed in February,
received four nominations, including best performance by a leading
actor in a musical (Martin Short). And ``Marlene,'' which closed on
Sunday, was nominated for two awards: best book of a musical (Pam
Gems) and best performance by a leading actress in a musical (Sian
Phillips).
</P>
<P>
   A Tony Award could mean a much-needed financial boost for
several productions with flagging ticket sales, namely ``Not About
Nightingales'' and ``Side Man.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the pre-nomination jockeying by several producers
apparently paid off; ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' which
opened off-Broadway, was nominated for best musical after moving to
the Vivian Beaumont, a Tony-eligible theater, just before the
deadline. And Elizabeth Franz was nominated in the featured actress
category after the producers of ``Death of a Salesman''
successfully lobbied to move her from the leading actress category,
which was considered more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, such strategic moves were unsuccessful. Despite
winning Tony consideration for Peter Stone's revised version of
``Annie Get Your Gun,'' the musical was not nominated for best book
(though the show did receive three other nominations, including one
for best revival).
</P>
<P>
   The first hour of the Tony Awards ceremony, which moves from
Radio City Music Hall to the Gershwin Theater this year, will be
broadcast live on PBS beginning at 8 p.m. The remaining two hours
will be seen on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Special awards for lifetime achievement will also be given to
the actress Uta Hagen and to Isabelle Stevenson, chairwoman of the
American Theater Wing. Another special Tony will be presented to
the production of ``Fool Moon,'' and the annual regional theater
award, which includes a $25,000 grant, will go to the Crossroads
Theater Company of New Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
