<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT &LR;      05-03 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JAPANESE PREMIER ANNOUNCE DEREGULATION INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
of Japan professed Monday to be in fundamental agreement on
strategies to pull Japan out of a seven-year-long slump and
deregulate its economy. But their daylong meeting underscored how
many of Clinton's once-ambitious economic initiatives with Tokyo
have been sunk by the Japanese recession.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, the sixth prime minister Clinton has dealt with in six
years, spent all morning at the White House, talking about the
containment of North Korea, Japanese aid to Kosovar refugees and
deregulation. He and the president then announced agreement on
deregulating a range of Japanese industries, from
telecommunications to medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, foreign firms will now be able to own 100 percent
of cable television operations in Japan and foreign
telecommunications companies will be guaranteed more fairly priced
rates to connect into Japan's domestic telephone network.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Clinton went out of his way to praise
Obuchi while pressing him to ``use all available tools to restore
solid growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said they feared that any of the benefits of
Japan's government spending program to spur the world's
second-largest economy has been undercut by the unwillingness of
many Japanese companies and consumers to spend. And they
acknowledged that Monday's deregulatory accord would mean little if
Japan's economy keeps contracting.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Japanese recession has changed the nature of
meetings between Japan's leaders and Clinton. The president came
into office promising to exert great pressure on Japan, open its
markets, and invoke sanctions if Japan's bureaucracy stood in the
way. But that energy was spent after the United States and Japan
battled over an accord on automotive trade in the summer of 1994,
and it has never really recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The auto agreement was the first big effort by the Clinton
administration to clear away regulatory hurdles that American
manufacturers had complained about for years. But while the
agreement led to some changes in Japanese regulations, the economic
benefits Clinton had envisioned never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For example, under that agreement the administration once
boasted that the Big Three auto companies would be displaying their
cars in more than 1,000 Japanese showrooms by this year. They are
now in 193 showrooms, the U.S. Trade Representative's office says,
scarcely more than when the accord was signed.
</P>
<P>
   And sales of cars manufactured by Ford, GM and DaimlerChrysler
are down by 34 percent in the first quarter of this year, compared
to the same quarter in 1998. That is a far steeper decline than the
than the falloff in overall Japanese car sales _ yet the president,
who was briefed on the decline, never mentioned it in Monday's
meeting, according to participants.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of Japan fatigue around here, and it was evident
in the meetings,'' one senior administration official said Monday.
``There comes a moment when you recognize that while you've made
some progress, it's hard to provide much proof that American
workers or companies are going to benefit anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the most notable shift in recent times is the absence
of pressure from the business community to press Japan for more
openings.
</P>
<P>
   American auto executives are virtually silent about Japan these
days, and DaimlerChrysler walked away recently from a chance to
take a big stake in the ailing Nissan Motor Corp., the second
largest Japanese manufacturer. Estimates from private economists
that Japan will be lucky to grow at 1 or 2 percent annually over
the next decade have scared away many American companies, even
though the cost of buying land for factories in Japan have not been
this low in decades.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an astounding turnaround: American companies are
turning their backs on 120 million of the world's richest
consumers, at the very moment that the Japanese government says,
for the first time since before World War II, that it is actively
seeking American investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Obuchi said to the president today, `We would
like to see American companies invest more heavily in Japan,' ''
Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. Trade Representative, said Monday.
``In six years here, that's the first time I've heard a Japanese
prime minister utter those words.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi argues that deregulation is critical to reviving Japanese
industry, and many Japanese executives agree. His Economic Strategy
Council _ made up of business executives, former bureaucrats and
other influential Japanese _ recently circulated in Japanese and
English an extensive report detailing laws and regulations that
should be swept away. They ranged from proposals to establish
high-technology businesses to the development of bankruptcy laws
that would allow the sell-off of assets of unsustainable
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Japan experts note that similar reports have been prepared in
Japan since the early 1980s _ and resisted by bureaucrats who did
not want to lose control over every aspect of the economy, and by
businesses that feared the onset of competition. But there are
signs now that Japan's prolonged pain has result in a rethinking,
in which the deregulation of American industries has become a
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Japanese firms who now realize that
bringing down their costs _ their energy costs, their
telecommunications costs _ are critical to their survival,'' said
Richard Fischer, Ms. Barshefsky's deputy, who lived in Japan for a
year while working in private industry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the clear effort by the White House and Obuchi's
handlers to portray this as a harmonious summit, there were two
areas of clear disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned Obuchi, first in private, then more mildly in
public, that he would begin a trade action against Japan if its
shipments of steel to the United States did not soon return to the
levels that existed before the onset of the Asian economic crisis.
A flood of low-cost foreign steel has already resulted in some job
losses in the steel industry, leading to a Commerce Department
action to penalize Japan and other countries for ``dumping'' steel
at prices below the cost of production. While Japan's shipments to
the United States have fallen in recent months, Clinton vowed
stiffer action unless the levels decline even more.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders did a more delicate dance around the question of
whether Japan will continue its huge deficit spending _ amounting
to 8 percent of its gross national product _ to spur the economy.
Obuchi has been reluctant to promise further spending, even though
it is becoming increasingly clear that Japan's economy will shrink
without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have adequate policy measures in place,'' he said at
Monday's press conference. ``We will continue to look at
developments as they transpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said only that Japan should keep its spending measures
in place until the economy recovers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
