<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GRAPHITE-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-SECRET BOMB BELIEVED USED TO BLACK OUT YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Deletes inappropriate close quote in penultimate graf.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The top-secret weapon that zapped a large part of Yugoslavia's
electrical power supply was a ``soft bomb'' first used in the Gulf
War. The high-tech weapon was developed by the Navy after a
training mission accidentally blacked out a portion of Southern
California, defense analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials refused to comment Monday on the bomb that
sprayed graphite over the power station and shorted its circuits,
though they were clearly pleased at its apparent ability to turn
out the lights in Belgrade virtually at will.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon was targeted at the large, open-air switching yards
that connect electrical power plants to the grid of power
distribution lines that serve large areas through substations and
individual electric lines, said John Pike, an analyst for the
Federation of American Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb can be delivered either by cruise missiles or aircraft,
but NATO wouldn't even say how the devices got to their targets
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the bomb is detonated in the air over the electrical
facility, the explosion hurls a number of smaller ``bomblets'' that
in turn spew many spools of graphite thread into the air. Graphite
is a good conductor of electricity, and when the threads fall onto
the electrical wires of the switching stations, they short-circuit
the power lines and send huge surges of electricity through the
entire power grid, said Pike.
</P>
<P>
   Pike compared the effect to that of sticking a fork into a
toaster. ``It not only blows out the toaster, but trips the circuit
breaker in the house,'' he said. The bomb ``is going to damage or
destroy some of the hardware in the switchyard itself, and put a
surge through the grid and trip out a lot of the substations,'' he
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the strikes knocked out power to about 70 percent
of Serbia for about seven hours overnight. Department of Defense
spokesman Kenneth Bacon, refused to speak about the bomb, which he
said is ``highly classified,'' but mentioned that one goal of using
it was that it ``disorients and confuses their computers by
shutting them off quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   This strategy first appeared in the Gulf War, when similar
bombs, known as KIT-18s, were used to attack power stations around
Baghdad, said Pike. They contained flexible metal strips instead of
graphite fibers.
</P>
<P>
   In their 1995 book, ``The General's War: The Inside Story of the
Conflict in the Gulf,'' Michael Gordon and Bernard Trainor say the
idea for the bomb grew out of a training accident in Southern
California. Aircraft were dropping ``chaff,'' hundreds of metallic
strips long used to confuse enemy radar, when a bunch of it fell
onto a power switching station and blacked out a large area of
Orange County, the book says.
</P>
<P>
   In a flash of inspiration, someone in the Navy saw the makings
of a new weapon, which is now enabling NATO to put ``its finger on
the light switch in Yugoslavia,'' as NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-COX     05-03 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole's money trickling in from spectrum of support in Georgia
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truett Cathy and Michael Leven have spent more than 90 years
between them serving people, Cathy at his Chick-Fil-A restaurants
and Leven at a succession of hotel chains.
</P>
<P>
   But Cathy tends to prefer Republican candidates, while Leven
often is comfortable with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, both men are supporting former Red Cross
president Elizabeth Dole's bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And their financial help, along with donations from such other
prominent Georgians as Deen Day Smith and Ginny Millner, is an
example of the range of support Dole needs if she is to be
successful.
</P>
<P>
   The $55,250 Dole raised in Georgia in the first three months of
1999 is a pittance in a presidential campaign in which $20 million
is likely to be the price of admission.
</P>
<P>
   But her list of Georgia contributors illustrates a certain
diversity that meshes with Dole's aim of reaching beyond
traditional GOP voters, especially since she is taking nuanced
stands on such sensitive issues as abortion rights and gun control
that may alienate the most conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Leven, president of U.S. Franchise Systems and a 14-year Atlanta
resident, and Cathy are interesting bookends. Leven backed
Democrats Max Cleland and Michael Coles in the two most recent U.S.
Senate campaigns. Cathy sided with Republicans Guy Millner and Paul
Coverdell, although he made a small donation to Cleland in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Leven backs abortion rights and is active in local Jewish
affairs. Cathy closes his restaurant chain on Sundays and is known
for his commitment to Christianity as well as to his chicken
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have some disagreements, but so what?'' Leven said of
Dole, a born-again Christian and opponent of abortion rights. ``The
most important part is that she offers leadership, she's a
wonderful role model and her heart is in the right place. She is
not running to fulfill any ego requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Leven met Dole in the early 1990s when he was president of
Holiday Inn Worldwide and organized a promotion with the Red Cross.
Dole eventually invited Leven to join the Red Cross's board of
governors.
</P>
<P>
   She also asked Leven for his help on her campaign. He and
Atlanta attorney Oscar Persons are the only Georgians on her
125-member national finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   Leven said he has sent 400 to 500 letters seeking contributions
to people on his ``holiday card list.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have called to say they to help or volunteer,'' Leven
said. ``They feel she's an underdog, but that she's viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy was not available for an interview for this article. But
Chick-Fil-A spokesman Don Perry said Cathy met Dole for the first
time last fall when they were on the same program of motivational
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do both Cathy and Dole share religious beliefs, they
also may be distant relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's mother is a member of the Cathey family, and while the
name is spelled differently, ``We believe it is from the same
family tree,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Georgia contributors, Millner is an evangelical
Christian who is married to Guy Millner. Smith, whose first husband
built the Days Inn motel chain, also is known for her support for
Christian causes. But she is a conservative Democrat, even if her
son, Clint Day, is a former Republican state lawmaker and candidate
for senator and lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's other Georgia donors include: James McMahan, a builder
whose apartment complexes reshaped Atlanta's Lenox Road; David
Shafer, the Republican nominee for secretary of state in 1996;
Randolph Thrower, an Atlanta lawyer and former chairman of the
city's Ethics Board; and Marilea Towery, the wife of former state
Republican Rep. Matt Towery.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
