<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-BELLSOUTH-COX     05-03 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies like BellSouth lead the way in donations
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore earned nothing but scorn for
his exaggerated claim of inventing the Internet. But the
self-described technology junkie is laughing all the way to the
bank as he solicits contributions from the nation's multibillion
dollar technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at Georgia's BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   In just four days in February and March, 37 BellSouth executives
and spouses chipped in $46,500 to Gore's 2000 presidential
campaign, one of the biggest showings of individual support from
any company in the country.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth CEO F. Duane Ackerman and his wife, Kappy, led the
way, each contributing the maximum - $1000 to the primary election
and another $1000 to the general election campaign. Senior
BellSouth executives from Atlanta to New Orleans followed suit,
writing checks for $1,000 that were hand-delivered to Gore's
campaign in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman declined to be interviewed for this article. But
Margaret Greene, who heads the company's lobbying and regulation
unit and first met Gore in 1985, said Gore was a natural for
BellSouth, the world's ninth largest telephone company, because of
his family ties to Tennessee and his technological savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known him for a long time and have been working with him
a long time,'' said Greene, adding that BellSouth employees were
also long-time supporters of Gore's father, the late senator Albert
Gore Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Since being elected vice president in 1992, Gore has taken an
active role in shaping policy at the Federal Communications
Commission (FCC) and positioned himself as the administration's
principal voice on technology issues. He fashioned the
administration's position on the massive telecommunications
deregulation bill of 1996 and he has been the White House's leading
advocate of linking all school classrooms to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's involvement in technology issues is paying handsome
dividends as he gears up for his 2000 presidential bid. Gore raised
more than $75,000 from the computer industry in the first quarter
of 1999, most of it from the cash-rich Internet and chip companies
located in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of BellSouth, Greene said the company is most
interested in how Gore and the federal government will step into
the raging band width debate - a battle between cable providers,
wireless companies, long distance telephone companies and the
regional Bells over how Internet and telephone access will be piped
into homes across America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of our technology, telecommunications networking
technology, as a reform vehicle is something the vice president has
been in the lead talking about for as long as I can remember,'' she
said. ``He is one of the more active voices in how the Internet
rolls out and how our technology is advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Regional telephone companies are also increasingly optimistic
that the current FCC panel, composed of three Democrats and two
Republicans and all appointed by Clinton, will finally allow a
regional Bell to offer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   For BellSouth, this is a $10 billion market in its nine-state
service area. Ackerman recently predicted that 20 to 30 percent of
that market could be BellSouth's if it were allowed to compete with
AT&AMP;T, Sprint and other long-distance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Ornstein, a scholar with the American Enterprise Institute
who was picked by Gore to be on commission studying digital
television, said technology and telecommunications companies like
Gore because the Clinton administration has taken a hands-off
approach to regulating the emerging technologies of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That obviously appeals to these folks,'' Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Moir, a Washington lobbyist who represents business
telephone users, said BellSouth is supporting Gore because of what
he isn't talking about. Moir said that Gore has been silent on the
issue of lowering the access charges the regional Bells charge to
long distance companies, fees which in turn are passed on to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far he hasn't said word boo about rate reductions, and this
is a guy who never missed a mike during the '96 telecom fight,''
said Moir. ``You know you can't talk about billions of dollars of
rate reductions and then go to a fund-raiser with BellSouth.''
</P>
<P>
   With 88,450 employees and $23.1 billion in revenues, BellSouth
is one of Georgia's biggest corporations and one of its biggest
political players. Its two PACs are the state's second largest
behind UPS. And adding in personal donations from company
executives and unregulated soft-money donations to the two major
political parties, the company consistently ranks as one of the
biggest political givers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 elections, BellSouth made nearly $1.4 million in
donations to candidates and parties, 55.5 percent to Republicans
and 45.5 percent to Democrats. So far this year, the company has
contributed $54,400 in soft money to the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee (DCCC).
</P>
<P>
   The company also made $5,000 PAC donations to GOP hopefuls Lamar
Alexander and Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) this winter. The Alexander
donation came at the request of BellSouth employees from Tennessee,
and the contribution to McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, was in recognition of McCain's long-standing ties to the
company, Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been helpful to us on the Commerce Committee, he
understands our issues very well and a lot of people are committed
to him,'' Greene said of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But Greene said she will continue to do whatever she can to help
the vice president. ``I hope I'm not done yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
