<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2879 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-PRESSURE-2TAKES-N     05-03 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-PRESSURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME U.S. COMPANIES START TO ADDRESS EMPLOYEE BURNOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., Colo.)  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Linda Davis, the Great Lakes-area sales manager
for Hewlett-Packard, realized she had a crisis on her hands. Her
sales team had been chalking up impressive revenues, but the strain
of long work hours was showing. There were too many broken
marriages, the attrition rate had risen to 20 percent, and when
asked on the annual company survey if they were ``experiencing
excessive pressure'' on the job, more than 50 percent of her staff
members had said yes.
</P>
<P>
   So when headquarters sought volunteers for an experimental
program to reduce and redesign workloads, Ms. Davis jumped.
Employees are now asked to set annual goals not only for
productivity but for leisure as well. They are expected to meet
both, and if they fall short, their supervisors have to answer for
it.
</P>
<P>
   At monthly meetings, team members are asked to list three
business goals and three personal ones. And when a staffer achieves
a milestone, like leaving at 2 p.m. to take a daughter ice skating,
co-workers are encouraged to applaud with the same gusto as they
would for someone landing a large order for laser printers.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a decade of piling on the responsibilities, a
smattering of American companies like Hewlett-Packard are beginning
to worry about the consequences. Concerns ranging from a lack of
creativity to ``burnout'' _ the point at which an employee becomes
too tired to work effectively or, sometimes, even at all _ have
emerged as among the most urgent topics at human resources forums.
The movement to do something about the problem is just beginning,
but some companies are experimenting with ways to alleviate
outsized workloads. Reforms include everything from limiting work
to 40 hours a week to discouraging employees from checking their
e-mail and phone messages over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At Hewlett-Packard, Ms. Davis admits that the emphasis on
leisure has had a noticeable effect on the work side of the
equation. Some tasks have been reorganized so they can be shared by
9-to-5 administrative assistants, and on the whole, ``expectations
have been lowered.'' Still, she says, productivity has barely
suffered where it counts. The Great Lakes area remains one of
Hewlett-Packard's top sales regions, and out of a staff of 74, she
lost only two people last year _ both of whom were promoted within
the company. Moreover, several staff members who received outside
offers have stayed put, and one top performer who had been lured
away by a start-up actually returned.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the last wave of corporate initiatives aimed at helping
employees balance work with their personal lives _ initiatives that
included flexible hours, telecommuting and concierge services _ new
programs like Hewlett-Packard's aim for more than convenience. At
their most ambitious they address the fundamental problem of how
much time a job demands and how to build a life beyond work.
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of burnout has not been measured in any meaningful
way, but since the corporate downsizing of the '80s, American
workers report feeling more pressed at work. Professionals and
managers said they clocked an average of 48 hours a week, according
to a 1997 work force study conducted by the Families and Work
Institute, a nonprofit research group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But to judge by anecdotal evidence, a significant subgroup toils
upward of 55 hours a week, while part-timers often find themselves
putting in more than 35 hours a week. In the automobile and
communications industries, hourly wage-earners have also seen their
week grow as mandatory overtime has become more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   The main impetus for the current effort to re-evaluate growing
workloads is the drum-tight labor market, in which unemployment is
at a 30-year low. ``These days,'' says Peter Cappelli, author of
``The New Deal of Work: Managing the Market-Driven Workforce''
(Harvard Business School Press, 1999), ``employees are able to push
back a lot more and are much less willing to work themselves to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting to the new environment has been especially difficult
for the most demanding employers. The Big Five accounting firms,
which are notorious for their grueling hours and travel schedules,
have suddenly found that their young, intensively trained staff
members are being snatched away. Deborah Holms, director of the
office for retention at Ernst &AMP; Young, hopes the firm's new
emphasis on ``empathy and humanity'' will build loyalty. Pilot
programs being tested at the company include ``permission'' for
employees not to answer their voice mail and e-mail over weekends
and while on vacation, and ``utilization committees'' that monitor
employee overtime and redistribute work when the total workload
consistently registers more than 50 to 55 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the straightforward problem of retention, corporations
are motivated by a growing body of research that shows that working
long hours over long periods is not necessarily cost-effective.
Mindy Fried of the Center for Work and Family at Boston College has
been trying to quantify how much money companies lose because of
the errors and additional medical claims that result from overly
long hours. ``The research is pretty clear that as people work over
a certain number of hours, productivity goes down, stress goes up,
and work isn't as good,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   SAS Institute Inc. in North Carolina is a privately held
software company that has experienced double-digit sales growth for
two decades. It is also something of a workers' paradise, where
full-time employees, starting with the chief executive officer, Jim
Goodknight, clock in for just 35 hours a week. The company
switchboard shuts down at 5 p.m., and the main gate is shut an hour
later. Jeffrey Pfeffer, a professor at Stanford Business School,
recently studied SAS, which is based in Cary, outside Raleigh. He
concluded that not only does the company save tens of millions of
dollars each year because its turnover rate is a fraction of the
industry average, but it also gains by having more alert, less
error-prone programmers.
</P>
<P>
   David Russo, SAS' vice president for human resources, says that
five years ago competitors considered the company's 40-hour work
week freakish and impractical, but ``in the last two years, we've
had 20 companies _ some really big companies _ come down and study
what we're doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, intense pressure to stay on the technological
cutting edge and to maintain high growth rates has made 16-hour
days a norm. But after years of trying to entice programmers with
idiosyncratic benefits like gourmet kitchens and pet-friendly
office spaces, some companies are beginning to create a work pace
that is more sustainable over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   John Gage, the chief engineer at Sun Microsystems, a
manufacturer of workstations and compatible software, describes his
programmers as ``lone poets'' who get so involved in their work
that they often will not leave their screens until the company
pries them away. To sway these workaholics, Sun, which is based in
Palo Alto, Calif., has developed an informal buddy system under
which programmers monitor each other. ``That way, if someone
disappears into his office for a few days, someone will go rescue
him,'' Gage explains. The company has also hired a slew of what he
euphemistically calls ``get-a-life'' counselors, whose job it is to
coach code writers on the joys of the real world _ sunlight, bike
riding, children.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the hours backlash limited to professional and managerial
employees. Unions say that reducing mandatory overtime has become
increasingly important to their members. The United Auto Workers
has made it one of the pillars of its official negotiating
platform, proclaiming that ``heavy and steady overtime work can
lead to depression, fatigue and confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Communication Workers of America went on strike
against US West until the telephone company agreed to a pay raise
and to cut mandatory overtime in half, to a maximum of eight hours
a week, by January 2001. Mike ``Ice'' Withrow, vice president of
CWA Local 7777 in Englewood, Colo., said the time-and-a-half
compensation did not make up for the fact that members felt ``they
didn't have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Victories at US West and experiments at progressive employers
like Hewlett-Packard aside, many workplace experts say they are
seeing a lot more talk than action. Jeremy Rifkin, author of ``The
End of Work,'' laments, ``We still have too many employers who have
bought the idea that the only way you get ahead is by chaining your
workers to their chairs until they drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Meisinger, senior vice president of the Society of Human
Resource Managers, says that the same tight labor market that makes
companies consider reducing hours also makes them pile on the work.
After all, the job has to get done somehow. ``Companies see the
problem, but they don't know how to fix it,'' she says. ``There is
plenty of wringing of hands, but if an employee goes on vacation
and there is an emergency, you will call him.'' The only difference
now? The company will ``feel guilty'' about the intrusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-DONORS-COX     05-03 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DONORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore leads search for Georgia money
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the first three months of the year, Vice
President Gore raised nearly as much money in Georgia for his 2000
presidential bid as the entire field of Republican hopefuls, a
computer-assisted analysis of Federal Election Commission reports
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gore led the money chase in Georgia with $209,025, drawing
heavily on lawyers and business leaders who supported President
Clinton in 1992 and 1996. He was followed by Texas Gov. George W.
Bush with $88,564 and Elizabeth Dole with $55,250.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many large states have shifted their presidential
primaries to early part of next year, candidates are under enormous
pressure to raise a lot of money early. Georgia's March primary now
falls relatively late in the process, but the state's concentration
of businesses and wealthy donors put it high on the candidates'
list for generating contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent of all the donations raised in Georgia came from
just 10 ZIP codes in and around the northern suburbs of metro
Atlanta. The top giving zip code was 30327 in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush, the GOP front-runner, raised less than Gore in
Georgia, the figures are somewhat misleading. While Gore began
raising money in January, Bush started in March. Bush raised nearly
all of his money in a two-week blitz beginning March 17, drawing on
a network of contributors who were longtime supporters of his
father, former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The speed at which Bush was able to generate so many
contributions suggests that the Texas Republican is well organized
in Georgia and has the potential to raise significant sums in the
Peach state.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter financial reports also reflected a strong
showing of support for conservative activist Gary Bauer. Bauer
raised $33,100, third most behind Bush and Dole among Republicans,
and well ahead of the other GOP hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Those results may indicate that Bauer, who founded the Family
Research Council in Washington and is a former Ronald Reagan
staffer, has the early lead in the battle to win conservative votes
in Georgia. Former Vice President Dan Quayle, publisher Steve
Forbes and commentator Pat Buchanan also are vying for the
conservative vote in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those candidates drummed up much financial support.
Quayle raised only $5,725 and Forbes $2,000; Buchanan did not file
a first-quarter report. A fund-raiser for Quayle in Atlanta last
week reportedly raised $25,000 for the former vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), who is targeting many of the same
moderate Republican voters as Bush and Dole, raised $9,500 in
Georgia, $5,000 of which came from BellSouth's political action
committee.
</P>
<P>
   While it is still early in the fund-raising contest, the first
reports tell much about the candidates' support. The first
contributors are usually part of a candidates' inner circle of
supporters _ or those who want to make a statement of loyalty
early.
</P>
<P>
   Some are personal friends of the candidates. Some give even
though they know that their candidate may not win.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta City Councilman Richard Guthman met Dole more
than 20 years ago on a State Department Exchange trip. ``I was most
impressed by her intelligence, her personality, her strength and
determination,'' said Guthman, who gave Dole $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Guthman said he knows Bush is the GOP favorite but noted that
``strange things happen in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Blue, president of Ronald Blue and Co., met Bauer at a
conference in Montana 15 years ago and the two became friends.
Bauer tapped Blue to be his national finance chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Gary will prevail or not, but I think he will
run a very credible campaign,'' Blue said. ``I wouldn't say to
people that he is going to win, but I would say let's give him a
chance to get his message out.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), who is a member of
Bush's exploratory committee, Bush reached into the network of
contributors who helped elect his father to the White House in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Some donors said they contributed to Bush even though they don't
know much about what he stands for.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Guy, a retired Atlanta businessman and a World War II
comrade of the former president, said he received a phone call from
the Bush campaign and quickly wrote checks for a $1,000 from both
he and his wife. ``I don't know him all that well, but I know he's
a good man,'' said Guy said of the younger Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gray, president of Gray Ventures in Atlanta, said he got
the pitch from his brother, C. Boyden Gray, President Bush's former
White House lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure,'' said Gray. ``I don't know who
organized it, but it was a national effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also received help from about a dozen lawyers at Troutman
Sanders who contributed $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who comes to Atlanta for his first big Georgia fund-raiser
May 24, raised more than $45,000 from senior executives at
BellSouth, the telecommunications giant.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also picked up contributions from former Democratic Party
Chairman Ed Sims and AFLAC president Daniel Amos. Former Gov. Zell
Miller also gave Gore $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Seydel, an executive with the Seydel Companies, said he
jumped into help Gore because of the vice president's commitment to
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as an expansion of what the Clinton
administration has done for the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Georgians opted to give to more than one candidate. Former
Coca-Cola president Donald Keough gave to both former Sen. Bill
Bradley and to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Failed GOP gubernatorial nominee Guy Millner contributed $1,000
to former Gov. Lamar Alexander, who raised money for Millner in
each of his three statewide campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Millner's wife, Ginny, gave $1,000 to Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
