<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-MOSCOSO-NYT &LR;      05-03 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-MOSCOSO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIREYA MOSCOSO: PANAMANIAN PRESIDENT PLEDGES FIGHT AGAINST POVERTY
AND UNEMPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY _ For more than 20 years, Mireya Elisa Moscoso lived
in the shadow of a man 45 years her senior who, she says, even told
her how to wear her hair.
</P>
<P>
   But by the side of that man, her late husband and Panama's
three-time president, Arnulfo Arias, she also gained a political
schooling that on Sunday helped transform her into ``Senora
Presidenta,'' the first woman to become president of this country
of 2.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The triumph of Senora Mireya is a triumph for the Panamanian
woman,'' said Kaiser Bazan, one of two vice presidental candidates
on the Arnulfista Party's winning ticket, at an impromptu victory
rally Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, 52, became one of Latin America's first female
presidents in what many Panamanians regarded as the most important
election in the country's short history. Her administration will
oversee the transfer of the Panama Canal from United States to
Panamanian control this year under treaties signed in 1977. She
will also preside over the withdrawal of American troops for the
first time since Panama was carved out of Colombia in 1903 in a
move engineered by the Americans in order to build the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso said in an interview last week that her goal for the
canal is to insure that ``users feel that it is as well taken care
of as when it was with the United States.'' But throughout the
election campaign, in which she defeated two other candidates,
including the son of Gen. Omar Torrijos, the strongman who ruled
Panama after the military coup that deposed her husband in 1968,
Moscoso said her first priority would be to tackle poverty, which
affects more than a third of the population, and the country's 12
percent jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
   She also wants to slow the pace of such economic reforms as the
privatization of state-owned utilities and has promised an end to
corruption and nepotism in the government, which she takes over
from the Revolutionary Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't forget my roots or my commitment to fight
unemployment, poverty and its consequences,'' she said Sunday night
after winning with 44 percent of the vote. ``I want for his country
what I want for my son, Ricardo _ that he have the right to grow up
in a democratic country, with guaranteed freedoms, with judicial
stability and with social justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso was born to a rural family of six children that sank
into poverty with the death of her father, a schoolteacher, when
she was 10. She was 17 and working as a secretary after graduating
from high school when she first met Arnulfo Arias, at a friend's
birthday party in the early 1960s. Arias was a 62-year-old widower
and physician who had already been president twice, only to be
ousted both times by political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a man with a lot of character who I felt loved me, and I
fell madly in love,'' Moscoso said in an interview last week at her
party headquarters, in a office with walls full of black-and-white
photographs of Arias. ``He adapted me to him completely: he told me
how I was going to wear my hair, how I was going to talk. He had a
very strong personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso worked in his presidential campaigns and in the coffee
business she has managed, along with 300 employees, since Arias'
death in 1988. In 1968, after Arias was removed from the presidency
for a third time, in a military coup, she joined him in exile in
the United States, where she married him the next year and remained
until he died in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   A later marriage ended in divorce after five years. She has a
7-year-old adopted son.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso said she initially rebuffed requests by her husband's
supporters to carry on his work. But in 1990 she coordinated the
creation of the Arnulfista Party to replace her husband's old
party. And in 1991 she took over as party president, in order, she
said, to keep it out of the hands of people wanting to use it ``for
their own personal convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, when she first ran for president and came in second,
the small, fragile-looking woman had emerged as Panama's main
opposition leader and the self-described ``voice of the people.''
She took on the Revolutionary Democratic Party, which had ruled
Panama with a succession of military governments through the 1970s
and 1980s and yielded power to the Arnulfistas only from 1990 to
1994, accusing it of neglecting the poor while enriching those in
power and warning of the threat of ``another PRI,'' a reference to
the political party that has dominated Mexico through most of this
century.
</P>
<P>
   Many Panamanians, however, cited her lack of a college degree
(she studied interior design at Miami-Dade Community College) and
the possibility that she might be easily manipulated as major
drawbacks. And not everyone remembered Arias with fondness.
Although the late president had created a social security system,
strengthened labor laws and gave women the vote, his views included
a curious mix of fascism (and connections to Italy in the 1940s for
which the United States encouraged one of the military coups
against him), racism, mysticism and nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   During her campaign, Moscoso downplayed her educational
shortcomings, saying, ``My biggest university was that of Dr.
Arias.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I often think of Ronald Reagan, who surrounded himself with
the best advisers and was an excellent president,'' she said in the
interview. ``I can do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   She called sexism an even bigger obstacle to her political
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they say Mireya doesn't have the capacity,'' she
screamed to tens of thousands of supporters at her closing campaign
rally, ``although they say that because she is a woman she can't be
president, I tell you here, I can wear pants just like the men in
this country. And I know when to put on skirts and when to put on
pants too.''
</P>
<P>
   (This prompted Martin Torrijos, her main opponent in the race,
to quipp: ``Now we know what she meant when she talks about change
_ a change of clothes.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now many Panamanians look to her to fully exploit the economic
potential of the Panama Canal property, worth an estimated $4
billion, for the average Panamanian, and distribute the riches
fairly. For that she will have to contend with a 72-seat unicameral
legislature dominated by opposition parties, which won a majority
of seats in Sunday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes from way below,'' said Ronald Luque, a 25-year-old
waiter attending one of her rallies, referring to her humble
beginnings. ``The hope is that someone who came from below will
help more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
