<HEADLINE>
LITTLETON MAN FACES GUN-SALE CHARGE IN MASS SHOOTING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ A 22-year-old local man who once attended
Columbine High School was arrested Monday for allegedly supplying
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold with a semi-automatic handgun, one of
the four guns used in the school rampage, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark E. Manes will be charged with providing a handgun to a
minor, a felony under Colorado law punishable by two to six years
in prison and a fine up to $500,000, said Steve Davis, spokesman
for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   Manes was the first person arrested in direct connection with
the April 20 massacre that killed 15 people, including the gunmen.
A girlfriend of Klebold's who gave the gunmen two shotguns and one
rifle remains under investigation, authorities said, but is not
considered a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Manes allegedly gave, traded or sold a TEC DC-9 semi-automatic
handgun to either one or both gunmen while they were under 18 years
old. Klebold died at 17; Harris turned 18 on April 9, 11 days
before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said police had not yet determined whether Manes knew what
Harris and Klebold were planning. Such knowledge could turn the
charge into an ``aggravated'' offense, punishable under Colorado
law by up to 12 years in prison, local prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Manes were unsuccessful, but his lawyer said
Manes had no idea what Harris and Klebold had in store.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was horrified when he heard what happened,'' attorney
Robert Ransome said in an interview. ``He did not know it was going
to happen, and the evidence will show that to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ransome said Manes was introduced to Harris and Klebold through
a mutual friend who worked with the two gunmen at the Blackjack
Pizza parlor in Littleton. The lawyer said Manes was not a friend
of either gunman and had no other dealings with them.
</P>
<P>
   Ransome said Manes was not a licensed gun dealer but declined to
say where he is employed. He said Manes's only previous offense was
possession of drug paraphernalia as a juvenile. ``He's been clean a
long time. He's a decent young man,'' Ransome said. He said Manes
attended Columbine but did not know if he graduated from the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Manes was released on $15,000 bond pending a May 10 court
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said authorities were still working to determine if any of
the murder victims was killed with the TEC DC-9, a weapon whose
manufacture was banned under the 1994 Brady Bill. Sales of existing
weapons are permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mauser, father of slain student Daniel Mauser, said at an
antigun rally Saturday that his son was killed with the TEC DC-9.
Davis said he did not know what led Mauser to that conclusion.
Attempts to reach Mauser Monday were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The TEC DC-9 used in the Columbine killings traveled
cross-country in the five years since it was manufactured in Miami
by the gunmaker Intratec. First, it was purchased by Zander
Sporting Goods, an Illinois firearms wholesaler. From there, it
went to a Denver-area store called Just Guns. When that store went
out of business, the owner gave it to a friend, Larry Russell, to
sell on consignment at a Colorado gun show.
</P>
<P>
   Russell has said he did not know the name of the person to whom
he sold the gun, but said he would not have sold it to anyone under
age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Because Russell was not a licensed dealer at the time, no
background check or other gun control measures had to be followed.
That exemption from the law, described by gun control advocates as
a dangerous loophole, has become a focus of legislative discussion
on state and federal levels in the wake of the Columbine shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he did not know whether Manes purchased the gun from
Russell or from someone else. He also said he did not know exactly
when Russell allegedly provided it to the gunmen, or whether it was
given to Harris, Klebold or both.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the only other arrest related to the rampage involved a
hardware store clerk who allegedly lied about having sold Harris
and Klebold propane tanks, nails and other materials they used to
build more than 50 bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not ruled out the possibility of more arrests,
though Davis said no suspects are being sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've always, from day one, had a feeling that there had to
be some people who had some knowledge or helped them plan or build
some of these bombs,'' Davis said. ``I think they're still leaning
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Klebold's girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, might not face charges
because it is not illegal under Colorado or federal law for a
person without a criminal record to give minors long guns such as
rifles or shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the county coroner's office confirmed that Harris's
body contained the prescription drug Luvox, which is used to help
control obsessive-compulsive disorder. Pharmaceutical specialists
have said they do not believe the drug played a role in the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the carpenter who erected 15 wooden crosses atop a
hill near the high school removed the 13 remaining crosses. Two of
the crosses _ memorials to the gunmen _ already were torn down by
the father of one of the shooting victims. The carpenter said he
had grown tired of the criticism he received for building 15
crosses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
