<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTRADER-SHUTDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE CRACKS DOWN ON N.J.-BASED DAY TRADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In its campaign to clamp down on rogue day-trading
firms, Massachusetts securities regulators say New Jersey-based
All-Tech Investment Group has agreed to not reopen its
Massachusetts branch for two years and pay a $50,000 fine to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement ``sends a clear message'' to day-trading firms,
said Matt Nester, director of securities for the Massachusetts
securities division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously a highly speculative, highly risky form of
trading,'' he said Monday. ``Firms have to disclose risk or there
are going to be consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Day-trading is an exploding form of stock-market trading that
has little to do with investment. Rather, traders buy and sell
stocks, sometimes hundreds of times a day, betting on miniscule
movements in price. Dozens of firms, including All-Tech, have
sprung up across the country to cater to them. Viewing day-trading
as little more than gambling, Massachusetts regulators led a
nationwide crackdown against firms that appeared to exploit
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech closed its branch in Watertown in November, shortly
before state regulators brought charges alleging a wide range of
abuses. They included forgery, deceptive marketing, trading
customer accounts without authorization, creating phony accounts,
and misleading regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's settlement, All-Tech neither admitted nor denied the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just happy it's over,'' said Neal Sullivan, an
All-Tech attorney. ``There was a bad office manager in that branch
who has been terminated for his activities. They just want to get
out of the line of fire and run a repectable business.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech, one of the largest day-trading chains in the country,
has 22 offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
