<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BEGINS DEBATE ON KOSOVO CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly six weeks after the air war in Yugoslavia
began, the Senate took up debate on Monday over authorizing
President Clinton to use all means necessary to win NATO's fight
for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan resolution was championed by Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and presidential aspirant, who said the Senate had to
encourage the president ``to wage this war more effectively than he
has done thus far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does not, the shame is on him,'' McCain said. ``If we
lose this war, the entire country and the world will suffer the
consequences. Yes, the president would leave office with yet
another mark against him. But he will not suffer that indignity
alone. We will all be less secure. We will all be dishonored.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution appeared to be doomed by opposition from the
Senate's leadership and was likely to be shelved on Tuesday
morning, its supporters said. The majority leader, Trent Lott of
Mississippi, postponed a scheduled vote on Monday night after
McCain criticized a four-hour limit on debate.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``a debate that many did not want and few will mind
seeing disposed of quickly,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly frustrated, McCain, a former Navy aviator who was shot
down over Vietnam and held prisoner for seven years, said senators
had ``allowed American pilots and possibly American soldiers to
risk their lives for a cause that we will not risk our careers
for.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on senators who believed ``that this war is not worth
the cost in blood and treasure necessary to win it'' to stand up
and vote to cut off the funds to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's leadership had little desire for a vote on McCain's
resolution, with its clear call for the use of ground troops if
necessary to achieve victory in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Their enthusiasm was extinguished last week when a contentious
House, in a tie vote, rejected a measure offering political support
for the air war and simultaneously voted against withdrawing
American forces from the battle. Many in the Senate, and some in
the House, thought that vote sent at best a mixed message and at
worst a sign of aid and comfort to President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate vented some of its own deeply divided
opinions about the fight for over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the resolution came from across the Senate's
political spectrum. ``What Senator McCain's resolution does is give
our president carte blanche,'' said Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio.
``We should not give the president blanket authority to get us into
another Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said the resolution's language
would authorize the United States to use ``every weapon known to
mankind'' against Serbian forces, including ``chemical, biological
and nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for the resolution also crossed party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now weeks into an air campaign that may last months,
and Americans need to prepare themselves now, psychologically at
least, for war,'' said Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., a co-sponsor of
the resolution. ``We can't wait to see how it turns out before we
risk taking a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   In pointed contrast to House Republicans, many of whom are
calling the fighting ``Clinton's war,'' McCain said it was
``America's war.'' In the same vein, Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind.,
attacked the idea that ``this is President Clinton's war, and when
he falls flat on his face, that's his problem.'' He said, ``If the
president needs shoring up, that may be our job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
