<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD NAMES PUSH TECHNOLOGY ISSUES ASIDE TO LEAD RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DOW-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average's charge above
11,000 on Monday was led by formerly stodgy stocks sensitive to the
business cycle while money moved out of technology shares,
continuing a trend that has been in place for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial giants like Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing and
General Motors received a lift from a report from the nation's
purchasing managers indicating that the economy was growing with
little pressure for higher interest rates and that export markets
were reviving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole new team of horses that are leading this
thing,'' said Ralph Acampora, head of technical analysis at
Prudential Securities. ``Five weeks ago, when the market first
closed above 10,000, the leadership was different. Money rushing
into a whole new set of stocks has lifted off a whole new bull
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which first closed above 10,000 on March 29, gained
225.65 points on Monday, to 11,014.69. So far this year, it is up
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which hit a record last
week but trails the Dow's performance this year, gained 19.45
points, or 1.5 percent, to 1,354.63. More than 400 stocks in the
index rose, while 82 fell.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for many investors, among the S&AMP;P 500's losers
were stocks like Microsoft, America Online and EMC, three issues
that have been standard-bearers for the entire market. Microsoft
fell 1 7/16, to 79 7/8; America Online slumped 9 3/4, to 133 1/8,
and EMC dropped 1 15/16, to 107.
</P>
<P>
   Selling in technology was not confined to those issues. The
Nasdaq composite index fell 7.27 points, or three-tenths of a
percent, to 2,535.58. And the Internet stock index compiled by
Thestreet.com slumped 23.29 points, or 3.6 percent, to 632.97.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet decline was led by Amazon.com, which tumbled 21
1/8, to 150 15/16, and Yahoo, which fell 12 1/8, to 162 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclical stocks had another excellent day, and the Dow Jones
transportation average hit a record. The Morgan Stanley index of 30
cyclical stocks jumped 15.88 points, to 612.62, a new high. And the
transportation average climbed 49.3 points, or 1.35 percent, to
3,696.59.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 stocks in the Dow industrials, roughly half are
cyclicals, companies with fortunes closely tied to changes in the
domestic and global economic cycle. Among them, Minnesota Mining
and General Motors led the index higher. 3M gained 4 7/8, to 93
7/8, and GM rose 4 11/16, to 93 3/4. Goodyear Tire and Rubber, one
of the Dow's worst performers last year, gained 3 9/16, to 60 3/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
