A2903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-COX     05-03 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cyclicals drive the Dow past 11,000
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed above 11,000 on Monday,
just over a month after topping a historic 10,000, as favorable
economic news attracted intense investor interest in cyclical
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new bull market,'' said Prudential Securities chief
technical analyst Ralph Acampora, who said he expects to raise his
current Dow target of 11,500 in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole new team of horses leading the market,''
Acampora said in a conference call with financial reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the recent shift of buyer interest to
so-called cyclical, or economically sensitive, stocks that
typically outperform the market during periods of strong economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the case Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Dow cyclicals included General Motors, which rose $4.63
3/4 to $93.75; Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, $4.87 1/2 to
$93.87 1/2; Goodyear Tire, $3.56 1/4 to $60.75; International
Paper, $2.06 1/4 to $55.37 1/2; and Union Carbide, $3.50 to $48.37
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Dow reversed Friday's loss with a steady,
daylong climb to a new high of 11,014.69.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow made history March 28 when it closed for the first time
over 10,000 _ a feat that took almost a year from its 9,000 close
on April 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The strong performance of cyclical stocks this far into an
economic expansion _ eight years _ is unusual, because they tend to
perform best in the early stages of a business cycle.
</P>
<P>
   But these stocks are being propelled by continued favorable
economic news, such as last week's report that the economy grew at
a bigger-than-expected 4.5 percent annual rate in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing stocks surged Monday after the National
Association of Purchasing Management reported its index of
manufacturing activity remained above a reading of 50 percent,
signifying expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The index actually fell 1.5 percentage points, which was also
favorably received as an anti-inflationary move.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the money going into the typically undervalued
stocks of the Dow and other Big Board issues is coming out of the
market's previous group of leaders, especially technology stocks
and, within that sector, the Internets.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the only loser among major stock indexes on Monday
was the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index, which fell 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The recent sell-off in once-highflying Internet stocks continued
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said major players such as America Online, Amazon.com
and eBay are giving back some of their recent gains after posting
better-than-expected first-quarter results last week.
</P>
<P>
   Acampora said he expects to revise his Dow forecast shortly but
declined to speculate on what it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would get to 11,500 later in the year,'' he said.
``So I have to go back to drawing board. As we get closer to
11,500, I will raise the target.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
