<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ETrade moving jobs to suburban Atlanta
 &HT;    By Cheryl Crabb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ETrade Group Inc. plans to add about 2,000 jobs in
Alpharetta, becoming the latest high-tech company to expand in the
booming suburb north of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials confirmed Monday that ETrade will add from
1,900 to 2,200 employees and 450,000 square feet of office space to
its year-old Alpharetta campus where it currently employs 300
people. Its expansion in the Windward Business Park will take place
over the next two-and-a-half years, said Jerry Dark, a vice
president with Palo Alto, Calif.-based ETrade.
</P>
<P>
   The rapidly growing Internet stock brokerage could become one of
Alpharetta's largest employers. Nortel Networks is the city's
biggest employer with a staff of 1,700, and it too has plans to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade's first 700 additional employees are expected to move in
between January and June 2000. Atlanta-based Holder Properties
Inc., the developer for the project, has started construction on a
150,000-square-foot to 200,000-square-foot building, Dark said. The
Staubach Co. represented ETrade in its real estate negotiations.
The company now has one building in Alpharetta but envisions a
corporate campus with four or five buildings for employees with
responsibilities in customer service, marketing and financial
services. In addition to online trading, ETrade offers a variety of
personal financial services over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A publicly traded company with 1998 revenues of $245 million,
ETrade has more than doubled its number of accounts since launching
its Destination ETrade Web site seven months ago. Last week, it
signed up its one millionth customer, a software publishing
consultant from Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   Although ETrade will relocate some staff, the ``vast majority of
hiring'' will be done in metro Atlanta. The metro area's labor
force was critical in the company's decision to expand here.
Alpharetta was selected because of the availability of land,
high-tech infrastructure and quality of life, Dark said.
``Alpharetta is a great place for people to live,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade is one of several major technology companies locating or
expanding in the north Atlanta suburb, said Diana Wheeler,
Alpharetta's community development director. Smaller high-tech
firms that provide services to corporate giants feed off this
growth. High-tech industry accounts for more than 20 percent of the
city's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited to have them,'' Wheeler said of the
high-tech businesses that have flocked to the city in recent years.
``It's a clean industry and it has put us on the cutting edge. It's
no longer just a California phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Crabb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
