<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daredevils become more cautious with age
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Molly was little she liked to stand at the top of
the stairs and leap into my arms. Austin ``Full Contact Soccer''
Emerson was, from the start, even more extreme: The Tower of Terror
at Disney World didn't fall fast or far enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Two more thrill junkies to accompany me down zip lines
and off rope swings and up mountains where their mother doesn't
care to tread.
</P>
<P>
   But the world has ways of offering thrills when you don't need
them. This past Sunday, the preacher asked how many of the children
in the congregation had received bomb threats at their schools in
the previous week. Dozens of little arms went up.
</P>
<P>
   Do these kids need any more thrills?
</P>
<P>
   Now we have two new babies, and I marvel at the way my view of
risk has changed. I still play street hockey with our older
children, but when I fall down it takes longer to get back up.
Similarly, the pitfalls facing the twins seem deeper and scarier
than the ones I remember from Molly's grade school days.
</P>
<P>
   There are two explanations. Either the world is becoming a more
dangerous place, which I doubt, or I'm getting older, which is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Children are born to leap, then look. You can't string a safety
net under every tree they climb. But one thing should come as a
relief to Maureen. If children learn to be daredevils by studying
their fathers, the twins will have a more sober role model than
their siblings did.
</P>
<P>
   Write to married staffers Maureen Downey and Bo Emerson at The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail them at bemerson(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
