<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for reasons behind school shooting
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fallout from the Columbine High School massacre
continues this week as Newsweek ($3.50) and Time ($3.50) search for
clues to teen violence. A Time/CNN poll of teenagers points to
availability of guns, the Internet, uninvolved parents, video games
and violence in movies, television and music as factors that were
``somewhat responsible'' in the Colorado shootings.
</P>
<P>
   So what can parents do about kids who are absorbed in a world of
computers and video games? Time suggests that they check the
ratings of computer games, block offensive content and monitor the
Internet sites their children visit.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek, in a cover story on the secret lives of teenagers,
puts the blame on parents who don't spend enough time with them.
According to the magazine's poll, nearly half of those surveyed
believe that baby boomers are worse parents because the experiences
they had in the 1960s make them less able to provide a strong moral
base. Other results show that many of the 31 million people between
the ages of 12 and 19 say they feel alone and alienated despite
being richer, better educated and healthier than any other group in
history.
</P>
<P>
   BUGGED: Bacteria that are building resistance to antibiotics is
an old story, but one that continues to plague us. U.S. News &AMP;
World Report ($2.95) examines the race to come up with new drugs
and new plans of attack before it's too late. Even worse, the
magazine says, the use of antibacterial products in our homes may
be compounding antibiotic resistance.
</P>
<P>
   FEEDING FRENZY: Hide the Chianti and watch your liver.
Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) reports on the fight in Hollywood over
the sequel to Thomas Harris' ``The Silence of the Lambs.'' Dino De
Laurentiis, who turned Harris' ``Red Dragon'' into ``Manhunter''
for the big screen, has first negotiation rights to the movie
version of ``Hannibal.'' But MGM insists it has rights, too, since
De Laurentiis passed on making ``The Silence of the Lambs.''
Bidding for ``Hannibal'' is expected to break the $8 million mark
set by Michael Crichton's ``Airframe.'' Meanwhile, booksellers are
licking their lips over the June release of Harris' certain best
seller.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE A ROLLING STONE: Music critics have been trying to explain
(and, in most cases, understand) Bob Dylan ever since the nasal,
mumbling folk singer became a legend in the 1960s. In this week's
New Yorker ($3), writer Alex Ross suggests they were looking in all
the wrong places. It's the music, not the man, that matters, says
Ross, who followed a recent Dylan tour and attended six concerts in
six nights.
</P>
<P>
   PEACHTREE ACQUISI-
</P>
<P>
   TION: Emmis Communications Inc., owner of Atlanta magazine, has
agreed to buy Peach-
</P>
<P>
   tree/Symbol magazine. The final issue of Peachtree/Symbol is
scheduled for June; after that, subscribers will receive Atlanta
magazine. Peachtree's publisher, Greg Caccavale, will join the
staff of Atlanta as sales development director.
</P>
<P>
   KUDOS: The Oxford American, the bimonthly magazine published by
John Grisham and edited by Marc Smirnoff, beat The New Yorker and
other prestigious competitors to win a National Magazine Award for
best single-category issue. The topic was Southern music. Newsweek
picked up an award for reporting on the Monica Lewinsky affair, and
Vanity Fair won the general excellence award for magazines over 1
million circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
