<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsi ads push link to new `Star Wars'
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pepsi hopes the Force is with it.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 beverage company launched its ``Star Wars'' promotion
Monday when it announced it will begin distributing limited-edition
collector cans tied to the upcoming release of the ``prequel'' to
the original film series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a very powerful promotion for Pepsi
this summer,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage
Digest. ``Star Wars has become part of the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico, which has been locked in an intense battle for U.S.
market share against Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co., is planning to
spend hundreds of million of dollars in promotions and advertising
to connect its beverages and snack foods with the new George Lucas
film, ``Star Wars, Episode 1 _ the Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   The set of 24 can designs on Pepsico soft drink brands will
initially picture one of the film's five central characters, along
with a brief biographical comment. Pepsi, for example, features
Anakin Skywalker, while Darth Maul is on Mountain Dew. Queen
Amidala will be featured on Diet Pepsi Chancellor Valdrum on Pepsi
One and Qui-Gon Jinn on Storm (in selected markets).
</P>
<P>
   The cans will start appearing on store shelves this week in
advance of the May 19 debut of the film. Then, every two to three
weeks, new characters will be introduced on the five participating
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Purchase, N.Y.-based company will distribute a
total of 250,000 special Gold Yoda cans for all five brands.
Consumers can choose between keeping this collector's item or
redeeming it for a $20 ``Star Wars'' check that can be cashed for
personal use.
</P>
<P>
   In all, more than 8 billion ``Star Wars'' cans will be
distributed in the United States this summer, said Pepsi spokesman
Jon Harris.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be large in-store ``Stars Wars'' promotions,
including life-sized, three-dimensional latex characters and
cardboard cutouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about enhancing the fan experience,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also about trying to grab market share, analysts said. In
1998, Coca-Cola Co. controlled 44.5 percent of the U.S. soft-drink
market, compared with 31.4 percent for Pepsico, according to
Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Coca-Cola launched its biggest promotion for the
summer. About 45 million Coke Cards will be distributed in hopes of
boosting sales of the Classic brand. The cards, which target
teenagers, provide discounts and special offers at restaurants,
theme parks and other entertainment venues.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
