<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Best intentions can't guarantee kid safety
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Our 4-month-old twins have yet to stub a toe or scrape
a knee. I know the bruises, bloody noses and blisters will come.
And I won't be able to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   We can't safeguard children from all harm, no matter how
deliberate and conscientious we are. In the aftermath of Littleton,
many parents are wondering aloud whether private school or home
schooling is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   But wearing school uniforms or learning geometry at the kitchen
table can't guarantee safety. I wish it were that simple.
</P>
<P>
   I went to a small private school, but there was no magic shield
protecting my circle. Two classmates at St. Catherine's died before
graduation. One drowned on a family outing. The other fell off the
back of his dad's pickup truck in the driveway. On most days, in
most cases, the tumble would have produced a bump on the head. But
Tommy's fall was that one-in-a-million accident, and he died
instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of similar catastrophes, I hover over my brood. While Bo
encourages our older two children to climb higher on the magnolia
tree, I plead with them to come down. He tells them to ``have
fun.'' I remind them, ``Be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   I know that I should curb my anxiety. The higher they climb, the
wider the view. But I worry.
</P>
<P>
   Write to married staffers Maureen Downey and Bo Emerson at The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or
e-mail them at bemerson(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
