<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTSNIGHT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Sports Night' engages smarts and heart
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There isn't a better, odder new sitcom this season than ABC's
``Sports Night.'' An hour drama built into a half-hour comedy, it's
a weekly trip to you-know-not-where, by turns funny and maddening,
obsessive and profound.
</P>
<P>
   Though set exclusively in the high-rise New York offices of a
nightly sports news show, it's not about sports; it's about
relationships and work, with sports as the easy-does-it,
talk-it-out metaphor for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A writer once wrote, `As if it matters how a man falls down,
when the fall is all that's left, it matters very much,' '' Jeremy
(Joshua Malina), the fanatically nerdy associate producer,
announces in the control room seconds before airtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he mean by that? Do not abandon blowouts. Watching
proud and accomplished athletes battle in the face of odds that are
virtually hopeless is one of the more stirring sights in all of
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phillies have been down 14-1 since the third inning,'' he
concludes, ``and I think it's the best game we've got. That is
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's season-ender stays true to the quirky, no-compromises
course ``Sports Night'' established from the start. No other
network show this good is more consistent at doing what it wants to
do.
</P>
<P>
   It opens the way it almost always opens: people talking, a
deadline looming, but the people not talking about the deadline.
The two likeably pretty-boy anchors, Dan (Josh Charles) and Casey
(Peter Krause), sit at their anchor desks and, as the seconds are
counted out until they're on the air, talk about their lives' most
pressing issues. Casey, divorced, is puzzled by the strange new
formality of his 9-year-old son; single Dan is puzzled by a woman
he's dated returning to the husband from whom she was separated.
</P>
<P>
   Dan's last words before the camera blinks on, ``It's a world
gone mad.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who've followed ``Sports Night'' all season _ ratings
have been lukewarm, though ABC has re-upped it for next year _ the
real action centers on Dana (Felicity Huffman), the show's
razor-sharp, tightly wound ringmaster. Though she's had a crush on
Casey, she recently became engaged to someone outside the office.
That plays out tonight with neurotic brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who haven't watched regularly can catch enough
from the fringes to make it worth while. As long as you understand
that it's a world gone mad, you're in the loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night''
</P>
<P>
   9:30 tonight on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
