<SLUG> BC-BUS-WRECK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUBBOCK CHURCH REELING FROM `TRAGIC' DEATHS OF SIX GIRLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Members of the Green Lawn Church of Christ were
reeling at the deaths of six, teen-aged girls, killed when a travel
trailer sideswiped a church bus returning from a retreat Sunday in
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The six, ranging in age from 13 to 16, had been attending a
retreat sponsored by Green Lawn at a camp operated by Lubbock
Christian University near Artesia, N.M. They were bound for Lubbock
on U.S. 82 about 1:30 p.m. when the accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a westbound pickup, driven by Lawrence Matthews, 75,
of Dewey, Ariz., swerved and Matthews' trailer tore along the side
of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The six were identified as Heather Bauman, 13, daughter of
Arthur and Suzanne Bauman of Tahoka; Megan Flynn, daughter of John
and Elaine Flynn of Wolford; and Talitha Beeman, 16, daughter of
Tom and Brenda Beeman; Sara English, 15, daughter of Jady and Susan
English; Sarah Johnson, 14, daughter of Keith and Lori Johnson, and
Astyn Qubty, daughter of Johnny and Diane Qubty, all of Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Four other girls were injured in the wreck. Three of those were
in stable condition at an Alamogordo hospital. The fourth was in
critical condition with head injuries at Albuquerque University
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   William Libby, 60, of Albuquerque, a passenger in a pickup
traveling behind the bus, also was killed in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The six girls, members of various churches in the Lubbock area,
had all been part of a group of 80 who participated in the two-day
retreat. They were among 28 persons riding in the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just tragic. They were all happy, vibrant young people,''
said Shelley Parnell, a church sponsor who had attended the
gathering with the teen-agers. ``We don't know why God chose
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnell said she and her sons had been in study groups with
several of the girls during the weekend, but had left Artesia
earlier in the day Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had known Sara (English) before the retreat,'' said Parnell.
``She was a great encourager, a strong presence in the youth group,
always bright, loving, giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had left a little note for me, saying how glad she was
that she had come on the retreat and what a good time she had
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnell said she had met Aston Qubty during the weekend function
and marveled at the 14-year-old's exuberance. Qubty, who attended
Lubbock Christian Junior High, played volleyball and basketball at
the school, as well as being an active member of the Green Lawn
Church of Christ youth group.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seemed to have so many friends,'' said Parnell. ``She was
always happy, never down. I wondered, 'Is she always this 'up'?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Megan Flynn, a freshman who played the flute in the Tahoka High
School Band, also was described as active in her church.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was involved in practically every church activity,'' said
Alva Conklin, minister of the Wolford Church of Christ. ``She was
just so likeable as a person and shined as a Christian so much that
she influenced a lot of other kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just an outstanding young person.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Johnson, an eighth grader at Smylie Wilson Jr. High in
Lubbock, was a National Honor Society member who participated in
volleyball, basketball and track. She had been selected ``teen of
the month'' at Smylie Wilson for May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this could have been worse and we are thankful that
the Lord saw fit to spare some of those on the bus,'' Dale Mannon,
minister at Green Lawn, told the Associated Press. ``We are
comforted by the fact that these girls were on a trip in which they
were celebrating and strengthening their faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were spending time with the Lord and now they are with
the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
