<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OHIO-DRAGONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daytonites debate Dragon monicker
 &HT;    By Marc Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Thirteen-year-old Richard Burque of Huber Heights
likes dragons so much, he decided to submit the name for Dayton's
Class A baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just popped into my head,'' said Burque, a seventh grader
at Studebaker Middle School and one of 12 fans who offered the name
Dragons.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same name that local baseball authorities had already
chosen for the new team.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday at Court House Square, under a brilliant blue sky, the
Dayton Dragons became official. During a noontime ceremony that
featured a nearly two-story high inflatable dragon, Burque and most
of the hundreds of other fans on hand roared approving as the name
was announced and uniforms and logos unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans said they liked the uniqueness of the name, although
some thought it lacked any connection to the city and the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset. It (needed) to be something that had to do
with the Wright Brothers,'' said Larry Mathis, 62, a retired
General Motors employee who lives in Centerville. ``Anything with
flight _ that's what this city is. Even Fairmont (High School) got
rid of the Dragons.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it.,'' said Donald Estelle of Dayton. ``The dragon _
that's got a lot of spunk. I hope the team's got a lot of spunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of time constraints, team officials decided to choose
its name and logos prior to orchestrating a contest to ``guess''
the team's name.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Robert Murphy said about a half dozen employees
of Mandalay Sports Entertainment _ the team's ownership group _
brainstormed about possible names, including some that played on
Dayton aviation heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tossed names around,'' Murphy said. ``Some people said we
shouldn't do anything with an aviation theme. They wanted something
fresh. We listened around our office to see which names people were
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Dragons was the one Murphy heard most often. Once the name was
chosen, graphic artist Terry Smith of California _ designer of the
NHL San Jose Sharks logo _ was picked to design the logo.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton logo features a large green dragon head with orange,
black, silver and white trim. Home uniforms display the stylized
name Dragons across the chest with Dayton spread across the chest
of road uniforms. The caps have a green D with a dragon's tail
flourish on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great logo,'' said Burque, who was chosen in a random
selection as the contest's grand winner and received two season
tickets to Dragons games as well as a merchandise pack. The 11
runners up received merchandise packs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dragons are already contemplating changes, some finetuning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking of altering it (the dragon head),'' Murphy
said, ``maybe with smoke coming out of the nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Katz writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
