<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUE TO BUDGET CUTTING, MEDICARE SPENDING UNEXPECTEDLY FELL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New government data show that Medicare spending
actually declined in the first half of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and President Clinton clamped down on Medicare spending
in the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, curbing payments for many
services. They expected to slow the growth of Medicare. But for the
six months ending March 31, Medicare spending was in fact $2.6
billion less than the $106.5 billion spent in the similar period
the previous year, according to data from the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   With cuts proving deeper than Congress intended, health care
providers of all types are furiously lobbying Congress to restore
money cut from their payments. They are competing with Medicare
beneficiaries who want to use the same pot of money for new
benefits, especially coverage of prescription drugs, now a major
out-of-pocket expense for the elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare spending has risen continually since the program began
in 1965, and federal officials had predicted that the growth would
pick up again this year after it slowed to 1.5 percent last year.
But so far the predictions are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Hanns Kuttner, an expert on health policy who worked in the Bush
administration, said, ``This defies the first principle of Medicare
policy analysis: that Medicare costs will always rise faster than
the rate of inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John B. Breaux, D-La., who headed a bipartisan commission
on the future of Medicare, said, ``We're now starting to feel the
pinch from the Medicare cuts required in the balanced budget
agreement, and I fear the worst is yet to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, hospitals, physical therapists, home health agencies,
nursing homes and health maintenance organizations have deployed a
small army of lobbyists, seeking to persuade Congress to rewrite or
repeal parts of the 1997 law. Home health care and nursing homes
have been hit particularly hard. As a result of the cuts, they
contend, patients have less access to some types of care, like home
health services in some parts of the country, and the quality of
care has begun to erode.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare is clearly spending less than Congress anticipated. In
the spring of 1997, before passage of the Balanced Budget Act, the
Congressional Budget Office predicted that Medicare would spend
$1,348 billion on health care for the elderly and disabled from
1998 to 2002. About 39 million people are now enrolled in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   After the law was signed, in a spirit of bipartisan celebration
in August 1997, the budget office revised its estimate, predicting
that Medicare spending would total $1,249 billion in that five-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   Now the budget office is predicting that Medicare will spend
$1,146 billion in that period, a huge amount of money but much less
than anticipated just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jordan J. Cohen, president of the Association of American
Medical Colleges, said, ``There was a gross underestimate of the
savings from the Balanced Budget Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth E. Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, said, ``Congress really overshot the runway when it
passed the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other factors have helped stop the growth of Medicare. A
federal crackdown on fraud and abuse has made doctors, hospitals
and home health agencies more cautious in the claims they submit to
Medicare, so they are less likely to overcharge the government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Medicare and its contractors are taking more time
to review and pay claims. The contractors are moving more slowly
because they have adopted new safeguards to detect fraud, and
because they are preoccupied with getting Medicare computers ready
for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when Congress cut Medicare payments for one type of
service, health care providers often responded by providing more of
another service, for which the money continued to flow freely. But
this has become difficult because Congress in 1997 cut back
Medicare payments for almost all types of health care services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law had more synergy than we expected,'' said Gail R.
Wilensky, chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory Commission,
an independent body that advises Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare spending for home health care fell nearly 15 percent
last year, to $14.9 billion, and the Congressional Budget Office
now says home health agencies will get a total of $79 billion from
1998 to 2002, or $48 billion less than the office predicted in
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare payments to skilled nursing homes rose 8.9 percent last
year, to $13.2 billion, but the budget office foresees a decline of
3.8 percent this year. The budget office now says nursing homes
will get $66.7 billion from 1998 to 2002, or $16.6 billion less
than the office predicted in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have drafted a letter to state officials
saying that some nursing homes face ``drastic declines in
revenues'' and ``may suddenly close their doors, potentially
placing residents at risk.'' Spokesmen for nursing home chains
agree and are pleading with Congress for more money. But an
increase for any group will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a political sense, there's only a certain amount of money
available for Medicare,'' said John C. Rother, chief lobbyist for
AARP, formerly known as the American Association of Retired
Persons. ``To the extent it goes to providers, then it's not
available for additional benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the 1997 law was squeezing Medicare payments more
than expected, Wilensky said, ``In the short run, the answer is
definitely yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office predicts that, despite ``the
sudden flattening of Medicare expenditures'' in the last year,
annual outlays will more than double in the next decade and will
exceed $400 billion by 2008. By then there will be more than 44
million beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anticipated growth,'' it said, ``reflects advances in
medical technology that are expected to raise health care costs and
a continued increase in the use of services by beneficiaries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
