<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS TO GO PUBLIC, ENDING 130 YEARS AS PRIVATE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of mulling it over and at least one false
start, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. said Monday that it would formally
end its 130-year status as a private partnership by selling 69
million shares, or roughly 15 percent of the firm, to the public at
$53 each, raising $3.66 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The offering, the second-largest initial stock offering by a
U.S. company, comes roughly seven months after Goldman canceled
plans to go public because of last summer's turmoil in global
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   One month after Goldman put its plans on hold, Conoco Inc., a
division of DuPont, raised $3.96 billion in the largest stock
offering by a U.S. company.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer's squall, the stock market has rebounded and
climbed to a series of new peaks. Goldman, meanwhile, aptly
demonstrated its ability to bounce back from a market downturn with
strong first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   So vibrant, in fact, was the demand for shares of Goldman's
offering among institutional investors that the underwriters of the
offering, led by Goldman itself, brushed aside the usual formality
of holding an over-allotment of shares in reserve to meet
exceptionally high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 9 million-share over-allotment will be sold along
with the 60 million originally planned shares, Goldman said Monday.
The $53 offering price is at the high end of the range of $45 to
$55 range Goldman had said it anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in the shares, which will begin Tuesday on the New York
Stock Exchange under the symbol GS, will be closely watched on Wall
Street, where few recent initial offerings not involving Internet
companies have been well received.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that could drive demand once trading starts is that
no retail investors outside of Goldman's exclusive network of
high-net-worth customers received shares in the offering, according
to Wall Street executives. Even the best retail customers of the
dozen major Wall Street firms that joined Goldman in the
underwriting syndicate will have their first opportunity to buy
shares Tuesday. That is unusual; in most big stock offerings,
retail customers of the biggest underwriters receive at least some
allocation of shares.
</P>
<P>
   Of the shares being sold, 51 million are being offered by
Goldman Sachs, and the remaining shares are being offered by two
institutional shareholders, Sumitomo Bank Capital Markets Inc. of
Japan and Kamehameha Activities Association, the giant Hawaiian
landowner and education fund.
</P>
<P>
   The offering values Goldman Sachs at nearly $25 billion, roughly
equivalent to the market value of J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co. has a market value of $31.8 billion, while Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co.'s market value is nearly $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Of Goldman's anticipated market value, about half will belong to
the company's 221 current partners, and another 20 percent will be
shared by the company's 13,000 employees. The rest of the nonpublic
shares are roughly split among Goldman's 125 retired partners and
the two outside institutional shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
