A2917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BAXTER-COX     05-03 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BAXTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anti-war debate stirs old echoes
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was, by the Rev. Jesse Jackson's account of it, a very
curious lesson in ethnic sensitivity: the civil rights leader,
pressing for the release of the three American soldiers held in
Yugoslavia, patiently explaining to the alleged war criminal,
Slobodan Milosevic, how it wouldn't do just to release a white
soldier and retain two Hispanic-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As he has been in the past, Jackson was persuasive, convincing
Milosevic to release all three soldiers without conditions. His
emergence with the freed captives in tow Sunday was another of
those time warp moments in a story already overloaded with
confusing precedents.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, this administration's attitude has been chillier
toward the independent diplomacy of Jackson _ the president's
family counselor during the Monica mess _ than Ronald Reagan's in
1984 or George Bush's in 1990, when Jackson won similar concessions
from Hafez Assad, Fidel Castro and Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's latest diplomatic feat does, in fact, come at a more
delicate juncture.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an understandable tendency to try to grasp this
conflict in terms of either Vietnam, with the grim prospect of an
intractable, increasingly unpopular morass, or the Gulf War, with
the happier promise of a prompt, high-tech solution. This has
resulted in such paradoxical moments as Sunday when Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott followed Jackson in evoking John Lennon's Vietnam
era appeal and called on the administration to ``give peace a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand how the political response to the war is taking
shape in this country, however, it might be more useful to look
farther back to the way the debate was framed in the years before
the nation's entrance into World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In such vocal critics of the Balkans war as former Vice
President Dan Quayle, Rep. John Kasich and commentator Pat
Buchanan, it's much easier to trace an hereditary link with the old
isolationist wing of the Republican Party in the 1930s than the
liberal McCarthyites and student radicals of the 1960s anti-war
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of that day seemed to evaporate with the 1940
nomination of the Republican internationalist Wendell Willkie and
the shock of Pearl Harbor, which made the political argument moot
for a time.
</P>
<P>
   But the Main Street, middle-American sentiments formerly
expressed by followers of the late Sen. Robert Taft have proven to
be resilient enough to matter in the century's closing year. Old
lines run deep: The two Democrats who joined with 15 Republicans
last week to force a legal showdown over the War Powers Act were
from Taft's home state of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   One could hear an echo of those days in last week's House
debate, when Democratic Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland compared
Kasich to British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain for suggesting
negotiations with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of Taftism is not the administration's only concern,
however. Unless the letter Jackson brought with him from Milosevic
holds the key to an unexpected resolution of the current Balkan
conflict, Jackson's foray to Belgrade and the administration's
decision to brush aside his appeal for a bombing halt could signal
the beginning of a more vocal critique of the war from the left,
which so far has been much conflicted about how to react to this
conflict. And that would leave the Clinton administration defending
itself on both political flanks.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
