<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTSNIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPORTS NIGHT' FANS WILL CHEER JAFFEE'S RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, I figured that working for Isaac Jaffee at
Continental Sports Channel would be better than a lifetime supply
of cashews. Shoot, I'd have worked for peanuts, but Jaffee went and
had a stroke and left me wondering if I should even bother applying
for a job there.
</P>
<P>
   Before he took ill, Jaffee was a big bottle of Elmer's on the
workbench of life. When the joinery of a late-night sports show was
buckling under the pressure of breaking news, technical hiccups and
personal conflicts, Jaffee kept it all together with a well-placed
dab of good counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But during Jaffee's absence these past few months, CSC and its
signature show, ``Sports Night,'' have come unglued. The anchors
have behaved erratically, occasionally doing the show without
pants. Worse, their producer is her own lifetime supply of nuts,
and nobody seems able to get through to her on conventional
channels. Even the smart-as-a-whip assistants, who usually keep
things running when the big dogs are foaming at the mouth, have
shown signs of distemper.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, CSC doesn't really exist and ``Sports Night'' is
only a fictional TV show about a fictional TV show. But when
Jaffee's alter ego, Robert Guillaume, actually went down with a
stroke in January, the best new show of the 1998-99 television
season got sick, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Guillaume returns briefly for a season finale
that's far more predictable than ``Sports Night'' tends to be. But
it's great to have him back for a few seconds, and even more
comforting to know he intends to return in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   As I mentioned months ago, when this season was barely into its
first ratings sweep, Jaffee is the kind of boss we'd all like to
have or like to be: tough but fair, demanding but supportive,
unafraid to make a decision. His only failing seems to be that he
didn't groom a successor in the event of his prolonged absence.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it happens. You never plan to be sick. And, in a way, the
reaction of the ``Sports Night'' crew to the Guillaume/Jaffee
stroke was fairly typical: mild panic, and then an uneasy
arrangement as everyone hunkered down and hoped for the best. But
as the cast carried on gamely without Guillaume's brilliantly
subtle portrayal of Jaffee, it was obvious that the ``Sports
Night'' dynamic was changing. Scripts that were crackling became
brittle. Characters that were unusual became annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the inevitable case of creative vapor lock paying
a visit to Aaron Sorkin's brainchild. Different as ``Sports Night''
is, it is not immune to the pernicious conventions of network TV.
Well-known for his independent streak, playwright Sorkin still gave
in on some fronts (or at least succumbed to a man's stereotypical
images). For example, the leading women of ``Sports Night'' still
wear the skin-tight uniform of the sexy sitcom babe. And when it
comes to neurotic behavior, Felicity Huffman's Dana Whitaker is the
character most likely to win a weekend in a padded hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that ``Sports Night'' isn't a sitcom. Its half-hour
format hews to the sitcom model, and so ABC dresses it as a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night's season-ending episode makes it clear that
Guillaume is the key if ``Sports Night'' is going to have the
success it deserves as an example of The New Wave of TV. Sure, Dana
is smart and feisty, Dan Rydell (Josh Charles) is smart and witty,
and Casey McCall (Peter Krause) is smart and obsessively
compulsive. ``Sports Night'' also gives us the smart and combless
Natalie Hurley (Sabrina Lloyd) and the smart and relentless Jeremy
Goodwin (Joshua Malina).
</P>
<P>
   Together, these off-kilter characters create a bizarre sort of
Greek chorus while simultaneously playing the principal characters
in a weekly minidrama. Their clever, rapid-fire byplay often
becomes the main dialogue, making it quite apparent that in each
person's life the big story isn't necessarily the one at the top of
the newscast.
</P>
<P>
   During Guillaume's absence, though, the chorus escaped from the
corral. Character development took a back seat to cleverness, and
``Sports Night'' ceased being a must-watch item. It was as if
Sorkin and his writers were playing Scrabble, trying to come up
with impressive words while waiting for Guillaume to recover and
bring the show back to its center.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Guillaume's time on the screen is barely worth a
mention in the credits, but his presence does give an otherwise
silly episode its essential compass. Let's hope he never leaves
``Sports Night'' again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
