<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED WITH PROVIDING A GUN USED IN ATTACK AT SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As Columbine High School students returned to
class Monday for the first time since the massacre there almost two
weeks ago, a 22-year-old graduate of the school was charged with
providing a powerful, semi-automatic handgun to one of the killers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office said he
did not know whether the man, Mark Edward Manes, sold, gave or lent
the gun or which gunman, Eric Harris or Dylan Klebold, was the
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who worked with Harris and Klebold at a local pizza
parlor put Manes in touch with them, said Steve Davis, the
sheriff's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents tracked the pistol, a Tec-DC9, from its
manufacturer, Navegar Inc., in Miami to a wholesaler in Illinois
and then to a gun shop in a suburb 5 miles north of Denver. After
the shop closed last June, Larry Russell, a business partner of the
owner, sold the gun at a Denver area gun show.
</P>
<P>
   Manes was booked on a charge of providing a gun to a minor, a
felony, and was released on $15,000 bond. A conviction could carry
penalties as severe as six years in jail and a $500,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold's girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, has admitted buying two
shotguns and a rifle for him. But she was not charged because it is
legal in Colorado for a minor to own shotguns and rifles.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting bond this afternoon, Manes did not immediately
return to the modest pea-green ranch-style house in the Columbine
Hills subdivision where he grew up, half a mile east of the Harris
residence.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson County Coroner's Office reported Monday that
Harris had the antidepressant Luvox in his system when he and
Klebold went on a shooting and bombing rampage at the school,
killing 12 students and a teacher before killing themselves. The
Department of Defense has said that the Marines rejected Harris'
application for enlistment when it learned he was taking the drug,
which is commonly prescribed for obsessive compulsive disorder, but
can also be used to treat depression.
</P>
<P>
   When the Columbine students returned to class Monday, at their
former rival, Chatfield High School, ``eight to 10 friends or
associates'' of the gunmen, who could ``all be classified as
witnesses,'' were asked not come, Davis said. He said that school
officials had asked for a list of the students and called their
parents, asking them to home school them for the remainder of the
school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of reasons, but primarily for their
well-being, as well as because it's a very uncomfortable, difficult
time for everyone involved,'' said Rick Kaufman, a spokesman for
Jefferson County Public Schools. ``Our goal is to get back to some
normal schedule, there's still about four weeks of school left so
there is still plenty of learning yet to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Chatfield High School welcomed the Columbine students with
banners and signs with messages including ``We Are One.'' The sign
showed the Columbine school colors, blue and white, and the
Chatfield colors, maroon and white, intertwined into a heart shape.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the school year, Chatfield students will attend
school in the morning and Columbine students will have classes in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students arriving during the lunch hour Monday
looked as if they had a new uniform _ blue jeans and white T-shirts
that read ``We Are...'' on the front and ``Columbine'' on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little nervous,'' said Sara Filipiak,'' a 15-year-old
freshman who was also wearing a little blue and white ribbon on her
shirt. ``But I want to be with my classmate and teachers.'' The
cheerleader from Columbine said she was in the cafeteria when the
shooting began on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Mental health counselors were in every classroom, encouraging
students to describe what they saw. For students overcome with
emotion, the school had set aside ``safe rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students said they did not want to talk to counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more comfortable talking to my friends and stuff,''
said Sara, who said she also talked to her family about her
experience.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to preserve privacy, sheriff's deputies kept
reporters away from Chatfield, largely standing on the far side of
a busy avenue. With television networks competing intensely over
the story, Jon DeStefano, president of the Jefferson County Public
Schools, announced Friday that at least one news organization had
supplied video cameras to students, offering to pay them to
surreptitiously film inside the school.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, repercussions were still heard here over the
sheriff's office admission that a neighbor's complaint that Harris
was setting off pipe bombs and posting death threats on the
Internet never made it to the desk of a juvenile magistrate. On
March 25, 1998, one week after the complaint was filed, the
magistrate granted a form of juvenile probation to Harris, who was
charged along with Klebold with breaking into a van. On Friday, the
magistrate, John DeVita, said he would not have granted probation
to Harris in the van break-in if he had been told of the threats.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the sheriff's spokesman, said that record keeping at the
sheriff's office is not computerized and that records are not
automatically sent to juvenile magistrates or diversion officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
