<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: KOSOVO AND COLUMBINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The failure of the House of Representatives to muster
even a one-seat majority in favor of the administration's air war
in Yugoslavia has given birth to a new dictum: Foreign policy stops
at the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that politics stopped at the water's edge, and
that was where foreign policy started. But when the vast majority
of House Republicans are unwilling to give even symbolic backing
for the administration's air campaign against Slobodan Milosevic,
while U.S. pilots are in the middle of that war with 18 NATO
allies, then you know we're in a new world.
</P>
<P>
   It's now official: Bill Clinton has made the Republican Party
crazy. And he has done that by taking all the Republicans' good
stuff and leaving them with abortion. How crazy are the House
Republicans today? Crazy enough to vote against the air war in
Yugoslavia, but in favor of massively increasing the defense
budget; crazy enough to vote in favor of expanding NATO, while
dissing NATO's biggest post-cold-war operation. Say what?
</P>
<P>
   But as dysfunctional as the House Republicans are these days,
that is not the whole explanation for last week's 213-to-213 tie
vote. In fairness, the House vote was about more than just hating
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   I've just spent a few weeks on the road in America, from the
East Coast to the Midwest to California, talking with people
interested in current events, and the ambivalence that was
reflected in the House vote is a true mirror of the ambivalence in
the country about Kosovo. The early enthusiasm has waned _ not
because of Kosovo or Clinton, but because of Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever enthusiasm existed for a ground war in Kosovo, or even
the sort of intense air campaign that I have favored, has been
diluted by the murders at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
And people in Washington are missing something important if they
don't understand that.
</P>
<P>
   The events in Littleton knocked the stuffing out of this
country. It's not that people are using it as an excuse for
ignoring the hard choices in Kosovo. It is more profound. They are
sincerely troubled by Columbine, and what it might say about their
own schools, their own communities and their own kids, and it has
broken the intense focus on Kosovo. People see the horrific
pictures of refugees streaming out of Kosovo, they read about the
atrocities, but, for many, their hearts and minds are engaged
elsewhere. Littleton has gone to a very deep place.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to understand why. The shootings in Littleton were
not by deprived youths, and they were not carried out by an
obviously depraved single gunman, who could be written off as a
psycho. Rather, they happened in a ``Leave It to Beaver''
neighborhood _ and the gunmen were Wally and Eddie Haskell. Until
we hear from the parents in this story, until we unearth the
psychological smoking gun that explains how a young man of
privilege could go to the prom on the weekend and then shoot up his
schoolmates the next week, it is going to gnaw at the country.
</P>
<P>
   It has left people who live half a country away from Littleton
feeling less safe. A man came up to me in Baltimore the other day
and said that when he was growing up, no one in his neighborhood
locked the doors, and kids, even those looking for trouble, had to
go a long way to find it. The murders in Littleton, though, and
particularly the fact that one of the presumed gunmen had his own
blood-chilling Web site, had got him thinking afresh about his own
kids, he said. He suddenly realized that, with the Internet, it
didn't matter anymore what neighborhood he lived in, or whether he
locked the doors or not _ because trouble was now a fingertip away.
With ``one mouse click,'' his kids could be in a porn shop, a
pedophile's living room, a casino, a gun shop, a neo-Nazi hall, and
Lord only knows where else.
</P>
<P>
   And there is something else out there, an unstated question,
also gnawing at people: If our own kids can shoot other kids at
school, how can we ever hope to cure Kosovo? We are chasing evil in
the Balkans, hoping to catch it, and then we find it's right around
the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine cannot be, and should not be, an argument for walking
away from Kosovo. In fact, I found that if I scratched people, most
still favored some sort of American activism in Kosovo. But you do
have to scratch people more now, because they are, emotionally,
otherwise engaged. Their hearts and minds are focused on a
different front _ the one in their own backyards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
