<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-MARKETPLACE-2NDTA     05-03 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MARKETPLACE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: declining markets. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But on Monday twice as many stocks advanced as fell on the New
York Stock Exchange, indicating strength throughout the market.
That the shift away from the Nifty Fifty and into value stocks has
been accomplished as the broader indexes are rising is just another
case of history being made by this prolonged bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Acuff argued that value stocks were so depressed, prior to the
April move, that their rebound looked like a turnaround typically
seen after stocks have fallen. ``The trigger was people felt the
U.S. economy continued to be strong, the rest of the world was
improving and it was almost the equivalent of coming out of a
recession or the bottom of a bear market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's euphoria coincided with the pricing of Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co.'s initial public stock offering of 69 million shares. The
offering, priced at $53 a share, raised $3.66 billion for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Investment managers said that money pouring into stocks that had
previously been depressed had an explosive effect on their prices.
Because many of these companies had been rejected by investors for
years, their market values were low and their trading had become
desultory. With investors charging into these stocks, their shares
reacted like beach balls held underwater and suddenly released.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors who had been pursuing the stocks and strategies
that had produced the biggest gains in recent years may be
unconvinced that value companies can stay on top. Old habits _ such
as buying large growth companies in the belief that their earnings
and share prices only go up _ die hard. And they are especially
tough to abandon after they have provided such astounding profits
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   No question, if the S&AMP;P 500 continues to underperform the Dow by
a large margin, there will be legions of unhappy investors. That's
because in recent weeks, most of the money going into stock mutual
funds has flooded the gates of index funds that mirror the
performance of the S&AMP;P, which is a laggard. And most of the
top-performing mutual funds in the first quarter of this year were
those that held the former leadership stocks. Investors who placed
money with these managers as a result of their recent gains are
likely be disappointed now.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts warn that while the broadening of the market is
positive, until the hoped-for earnings gains among the cyclical
stocks appear, it remains expensive historically. Richard Brody,
head of U.S. equity management at PPM America in Chicago, said:
``If you have a continued rotation out of the bigger names, you
could have the S&AMP;P suffering some significant declines. Maybe the
value stocks continue to outperform because they don't correct as
much as some of the larger-cap stocks. Going up 10 percent a month
is not a sustainable rate. It would be nice, but it's not
sustainable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
