<SLUG> BC-DOLE-N.H.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE STICKS TO STANCE ON GUNS IN CHALLENGE TO THE NRA
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By   RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Taking on the National Rifle Association,
long a sacred cow among many Republicans, Elizabeth Dole asserted
Monday, ``I don't think that any special interest group should
dictate what our position is going to be on particular issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's remarks, responding to questions from reporters,
amplified her speech at a Republican Party gathering here on
Sunday, when she called for measures like retaining the prohibition
on assault weapons, backing a ban on armor-piercing bullets and
favoring child safety locks on guns. The speech drew a tepid
response from the Republican audience.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Mrs. Dole said her comments on guns in the wake of
the killings of 15 people at a high school in Littleton, Colo.,
were part of her strategy to win the presidential nomination by
trying to ``push the Republican Party in a more inclusive
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, he added, would continue to reach out to moderate
voters and ``speak with a different tone of voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, who made herself available to a small cluster of
reporters following her on the campaign trail Monday afternoon,
insisted that she was not worried that her position on guns would
damage her prospects among conservatives in the Republican
primaries. In most polls in New Hampshire, which traditionally
holds the first primary, and nationwide, Mrs. Dole places second to
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to share my views, then we'll see who agrees and who
disagrees,'' she said. ``Obviously you want to take into account
everyone's interests. But, certainly, I don't think the party
should be dominated by special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the NRA was too influential, Mrs. Dole replied: ``Well,
let's leave it where it is. I certainly believe in the Second
Amendment and a person's right to bear arms. But, like I said last
night, you don't need an AK-47 to defend your family. If that's
something that an organization disagrees with, then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Manown, a spokesman for the rifle association, said that the
group just concluded its annual conference and that no official was
available to respond to Mrs. Dole's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole also spoke out for the first time about Bush. Asked
about his impressive early showing, she said; ``He's certainly got
a famous name _ that's one thing. But he'll have to make the
appearances and speak to the issues. Then we'll see if it holds
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican contenders have groused about Bush's decision
not to appear at a dinner here on Sunday, or at any other events,
until after the Texas Legislature adjourns on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Monday about the governor's decision, Mrs. Dole said:
``He had to make a judgment whether he's going to come and be with
the rest of us last night or not. And his judgment was he wanted to
stay in Texas. And that's his privilege and his right.''
</P>
<P>
   Will his absence hurt Bush?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what happens,'' Mrs. Dole said as she slipped into
her waiting car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
