<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-650&AMP;A     05-03 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SHIFTS TACTICS ON BOMBING ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-NATO) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO warplanes have begun flying more low-altitude
bombing raids against Yugoslav forces in Kosovo, a practice that
until now had been ruled out as too dangerous, Pentagon officials
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the lower-altitude raids, NATO is seizing upon
improved weather and its growing aerial armada to launch 500 to 600
missions a day against a broader array of targets. The increased
tempo and the stepped up low-level bombing is paying dividends,
NATO and Pentagon officials insist.
</P>
<P>
   But this is also being accompanied by a stepped-up Yugoslav
defense. The net result of these factors has been a greatly
increased risk to allied pilots. Three NATO fighter-bombers were
hit by ground fire over the weekend, and one of them crashed.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the six weeks of air and missile strikes, fear of
casualties has limited the exposure of pilots to Yugoslavia's
anti-aircraft batteries and surface-to-air missiles. As a result,
most of NATO's 3,300 strike missions have been conducted from high
altitudes, typically more than 15,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Pentagon and NATO refuse to discuss the
altitudes at which pilots are now operating, but the Pentagon
recently showed a video image of an F-16 fighter bomber strafing
oil storage tanks near Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina, from
what appeared to be far less than 15,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   And A-10 Warthogs, which are the Air Force's premier aircraft
for destroying tanks but which have been limited to spotting
missions at higher altitudes, have for the first time launched
significant numbers of attacks at low altitudes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In another shift from previous tactics, NATO warplanes have been
hitting targets they encounter while flying over Yugoslavia as well
as preselected ones. In some cases, officials said, low-level
attack jets loiter in the skies outside of Yugoslavia and, when
directed by reconnaissance aircraft, dart in over Kosovo to blast
tanks, artillery batteries and command posts, which brings the
planes much closer to enemy guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're flying more sorties,'' a senior defense official said.
``We're flying more hours in the day. We're flying against more
targets. And we're focusing on more targets that are moving in
Kosovo and that require flying at different altitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO has escalated its air campaign, Yugoslavia has
intensified its counterattacks. The same clear skies that have
aided NATO pilots have allowed Yugoslav gunners on the ground to
fire more effectively and intensely on the ever-increasing number
of aircraft overhead. A full moon in recent days has made it even
easier to spot allied warplanes at night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said on Monday that an F-117 stealth fighter was hit
early Saturday by shrapnel from a Soviet-era SA-3 surface-to-air
missile, but was able to return to base in Germany. The officials
said another American aircraft, an A-10, made an emergency landing
in Macedonia after one of its two engines was knocked out by heavy
ground fire. Neither pilot was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the officials said that an American F-16 that crashed
with engine failure over Serbia on Saturday had in all likelihood
been hit by Yugoslav ground fire or exploding fragments from a
ground-to-air missile. The pilot was rescued and whisked to an
allied air base within three hours of plummeting to the earth near
the Bosnian border. Officials had said on Sunday that they did not
believe the plane had been hit.
</P>
<P>
   In the 41 days of attacks so far, NATO has lost only two planes
to combat fire, the F-16 and an F-117 stealth fighter shot down on
the fourth day of the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a Harrier jump jet flown by the Marine Corps crashed
into the Adriatic while on a training mission, and a Apache
helicopter crashed in Albania last week. But so far the United
States and NATO have suffered no significant casualties and no
deaths.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A senior Defense official said there appeared to be no
connection between the hits on the three aircraft, which evidently
were flying at different altitudes when struck, none especially
low. ``It's still a very capable air defense system,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, senior Pentagon officials said on Monday that the forces
of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, had increased both
anti-aircraft fire and surface-to-air missile attacks, especially
in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Possibly Milosevic feels like he has to be a little more
defensive,'' Maj. Gen. Charles F. Wald, a senior officer on the
Pentagon's Joint Staff, said on Monday. ``The intensity of the air
campaign has increased significantly over the last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   As the allied bombing has weakened the ability of Yugoslavia's
air defenses to operate effectively as a network, Wald said,
gunners on the ground seem to have been given more latitude to
shoot at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have less of a central control over their weapons,
possibly, and therefore, there may be a little more autonomy for
people to fire'' the surface-to-air missiles, Wald said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, Yugoslavia's missile operators are now
occasionally turning on their targeting radars to home in on NATO
warplanes, despite the risk that carries of drawing fire from
allied anti-radar missiles.
</P>
<P>
   But in another sign the Pentagon is worrying about the risk to
pilots, Secretary of Defense William Cohen has activated 120 Air
Force reservists called up from the 939th Rescue Wing in Portland,
Ore., whose job is primarily to swoop in behind enemy lines to free
downed allied aviators.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pentagon seeing results, American military intelligence
now estimates that Yugoslavia's troops in Kosovo will run out of
fuel in six weeks without new methods of supply.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, NATO carried out some of its most successful
bombing of the air campaign. Wald said that about 50 percent of the
77 targets hit were Yugoslav army or special police forces. Allied
warplanes also hit communication lines, command bunkers, radio
relay stations and surface-to-air missile sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
