<HEADER>
A2932 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LA     05-03 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAMS FOSTERS RESPECT AS UCLA COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Adams has been a Bruin for life. He graduated from UCLA in
1962 _ that's two years before the basketball team won its first
NCAA championship _ and he's in his 25th season as its baseball
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Although Adams won his 1,000th game earlier this season, he's at
an age (59) when coaches are nudged out if the program isn't
competing for a national championship year after year.
</P>
<P>
   With seven games to play, the Bruins are breaking even this year
(26-26) and have only been consistently dominant in the 1990s.
Still, Adams is one of the nation's most respected coaches,
well-liked by his peers and admired by his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gary Adams is one of the great guys and class acts in
college baseball,'' said USC coach Mike Gillespie, who first
competed against Adams as a Trojans player in the early 1960s. ``He
has got a thousand friends, a friend for every win. He is a real
credit to college baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no significant call for him to step down _ which might
be the case at another school with another coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hear the whispers,'' Adams said. ``If the
administration says, `You must win,' I can find ways to win. That
hasn't been expressed to me in any kind of a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who said he isn't disappointed by this season because of
his team's youth, isn't retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good condition,'' he said. ``(I'll stay) as long as
UCLA wants me, as long as the players want me and as long as I'm
happy doing what I'm doing, which I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams hasn't lost touch with players and his reputation for
developing players is respected by major-league scouts. A few
scouts who watched the Bruins upset nationally ranked USC 8-5 on
Sunday said Adams' players are polished and ready for professional
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 32 players Adams has sent to the major leagues are
Eric Karros, Troy Glaus, Tim Leary, Todd Zeile, Jeff Conine and Don
Slaught.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason UCLA has 17 players on the roster who were
drafted out of high school but who chose to attend UCLA. Freshman
pitcher Josh Karp turned down a reported $2 million signing bonus
from the Braves last year to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a good feeling from (Adams),'' said sophomore
outfielder Bill Scott, who was drafted in the 24th round by the
Braves in '97 out of Alemany High. ``You're able to talk to him. He
tries to make it the best situation for you to get drafted. From
high school to now, I've learned a lot and I'm a better
ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams says he is available to the players, but he's not seeking
to become their friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm their `dad' away from home, but I'm not one of them,'' he
said. ``I tell them, `Don't invite me to your parties.' (But) I try
to keep an open door. I try to stay communicative. I know the
juniors and seniors on this team have no problems approaching me.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is 50-59 since advancing to the College World Series in
'97. With a roster full of standout freshmen and sophomores, the
Bruins could be ranked among the nation's top 10 teams next season.
</P>
<P>
   Adams will be ready to make a run at the national title that has
eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do anything but coach college baseball,'' Adams said.
``This is all I've ever done. I'm not qualified to do anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   !tag!f &QC; Helvetica f+b f-i s &QC; 12 w &QC; 12 l &QC; 16!tag!Playoff picture &QL; 
If UCLA can sweep Oregon State this weekend, and win at least two
of three against Stanford at home on May 14-16, it will merit
serious consideration for an at-large bid to the NCAA playoffs,
which begin on May 28 with a field of 64 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at how the NCAA selection committee will look at
the Bruins and the rest of the Los Angeles-area Division I teams:
</P>
<P>
   __ Locked in: USC, Pepperdine, Cal State Fullerton. The Trojans
can either get in automatically by winning the Pac-10 (USC is two
games behind first-place Stanford) or receiving an at-large bid,
despite losing two of three against UCLA this past weekend. Expect
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   USC (30-22, 15-7) slugged its way to the national title last
year, but don't forget the Trojans had a first-round pick in staff
ace Seth Etherton. Junior left-hander Barry Zito has accepted the
No. 1 starter's role and flourished with a 10-2 record and
nine-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   If Zito beats Washington on May 14, he can become the third
Pac-10 pitcher since 1989 to win all his conference starts.
Etherton was 10-0 in '97 and Scott Erickson was 10-0 for Arizona in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (37-10, 16-8), which is leading the West Coast
Conference's Coast Division, can host the WCC championship series
if Loyola Marymount continues its slump.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, who have cooled a bit since winning 31 of their first
35 games, are battling USC for the chance to host one of the
playoffs' 16 sub-regionals.Cal State Fullerton (40-9, 21-3 in the
Big West) has been ranked as high as No. 2 in some polls and is
making a run at its fourth national championship.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fighting for consideration: UCLA, Loyola Marymount, Long
Beach State. With nonconference wins over Georgia Tech (two), Rice
and Arkansas (two), UCLA proved it could be competitive in a
regional situation.
</P>
<P>
   What hurts the Bruins' cause is an 0-4 record against Cal State
Northridge, UC Santa Barbara and McNeese State, and a 12-19 record
away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Also, UCLA's scheduled nonconference game with nationally ranked
Cal State Fullerton on Wednesday was canceled when the Titans found
out the NCAA counted their exhibition game against the Angels on
Easter as one of the 56 games a team is allowed to play during a
season.
</P>
<P>
   LMU (26-23, 14-10) rose to No. 29 in Collegiate Baseball's poll,
sweeping Pepperdine three weeks ago. But the Lions have lost seven
of nine since then and are now in a tie with Portland for the West
Division lead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its recent slump, this was a Lions program that hadn't
had a winning season since 1991 before taking the WCC title last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State (27-19, 15-8) was under .500 midway through the
season but, as has been the 49ers' pattern under head coach Dave
Snow, finished strong. An at-large bid isn't a slam dunk, but the
49ers' past success in the postseason will probably carry them
through.
</P>
<P>
   __ Maybe next year: CSUN.The Matadors won't have an argument
against being shut out of a bid this season; they are 25-28 after
losing two of three at New Mexico over the weekend. With a solid
recruiting class and good young talent, head coach Mike Batesole's
Matadors could win 40 games next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
