<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE-NYT &LR;      05-03 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI SAID TO WEIGH JOINING COMCAST IN BID FOR MEDIAONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL and GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Setting the stage for a showdown between two of the nation's
biggest communications companies, MCI Worldcom Inc. is seriously
considering joining Comcast Corp. in its multibillion-dollar fight
against AT&AMP;T Corp. to acquire MediaOne Group, the big cable
television company, executives close to the negotiations said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, MediaOne accepted AT&AMP;T's unsolicited $58
billion offer to acquire the company, repudiating its previous $53
billion agreement to be acquired by Comcast, another big cable
carrier. Under terms of its deal with MediaOne, Comcast now has
until the end of Thursday to make a new bid.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has sought partners ever since AT&AMP;T made its offer two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, MCI Worldcom was close to signing a
confidentiality agreement with MediaOne that would allow MCI
Worldcom to examine MediaOne's secret internal financial
information, according to executives close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Those executives also said that Paul Allen, a co-founder of
Microsoft and a billionaire entrepreneur, had decided against
helping Comcast fight AT&AMP;T, which far outstrips Comcast in
financial firepower.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that America Online Inc., the No. 1 Internet
service provider, had also decided against helping Comcast on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives added that America Online could well join the
Comcast camp if a third company were enlisted to help carry the
financial load.
</P>
<P>
   That third company could end up being MCI Worldcom, the No. 2
long-distance communications company and longtime foe of AT&AMP;T, the
No. 1 long-distance company. Executives close to the discussions
said that MCI Worldcom did not want to help Comcast on its own, but
would potentially be amenable to a three-way partnership,
particularly with America Online. MCI Worldcom and America Online
already have a close relationship as a result of their cooperation
in the purchase of Compuserve.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. has also been weighing a partnership with
Comcast, but the executives close to the talks said MCI Worldcom
was not as interested in teaming with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   For MCI Worldcom, joining a bid for MediaOne would represent a
major change in strategic direction. Bernard Ebbers, the company's
chief executive, has long focused on business customers rather than
residential users. By helping Comcast acquire MediaOne, he would
end up with a significant presence in mass-market cable television.
</P>
<P>
   At some level, the main strategic reason for MCI Worldcom to
jump into the battle may simply be to keep MediaOne out of AT&AMP;T's
hands. Since agreeing to acquire Tele-Communications Inc., the No.
2 cable company, last summer, AT&AMP;T has decided that it will try to
use cable systems across the nation to offer consumers integrated
packages of television, telephone and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Though MCI Worldcom owns the world's biggest Internet carrier,
Uunet &UR; / &LR; , the company has not set out a detailed strategy for
offering high-speed Internet service to consumers. Winning access
to MediaOne's roughly 5.5 million customers could help plug that
strategic gap _ while also blocking AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Were MCI Worldcom to win MediaOne, it could be a painful defeat
for AT&AMP;T and its fast-moving chairman, C. Michael Armstrong. Both
he and Ebbers have reputations for being decisive and unafraid of
remaking their companies. A battle over MediaOne would be the first
time the two men go head-to-head in a takeover fight.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's board met Monday. The nature of its discussions was
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom has maintained a relationship with America Online
for years. In 1997, America Online sold its communications network
to what was then Worldcom Inc. in a complex three-way deal that had
Worldcom also acquire the network of Compuserve, a rival online
service. Last year, after Worldcom acquired what was then MCI
Communications Corp., Stephen Case, America Online's chairman,
joined the board of the new MCI Worldcom. Today, America Online is
one of MCI Worldcom's biggest data customers.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday whether Microsoft _ which already has a
$1 billion investment in Comcast _ would come to Comcast's aid
independently. Microsoft has the necessary finances to underwrite
an offer, and there has even been some talk that it could make a
separate offer for MediaOne. But a person close to Microsoft said
it would be hard to imagine the company doing that.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has made a number of investments in cable companies,
including NTL Inc., a cable and telephony provider in Britain, but
has always taken a relatively small minority stake. Its $1 billion
investment in Comcast, for example, left it with just 11.5 percent
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   An executive close to the negotiations said that America Online
had ``decided to take a pass'' on joining Comcast independently
because Comcast was asking America Online to commit too many
resources to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Though this person was not specific, other executives close to
the negotiations said that America Online would have been expected
to contribute both stock and cash to the Comcast bid.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Allen did not return phone calls Monday, and a
spokesman for America Online declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   America Online was a more obvious bidder than Microsoft and was
generally thought to have more to lose if AT&AMP;T acquired MediaOne.
America Online is concerned that AT&AMP;T intends to shut independent
Internet providers like America Online out of the cable systems
that it controls. Joining with Comcast could help America Online
keep MediaOne's cable systems out of AT&AMP;T's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   But America Online is also trying to win access to cable systems
in other ways, including normal business negotiations and lobbying
efforts in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward to the day when many American households have
high-speed access to the Internet, America Online has also struck
deals with some of the nation's biggest local telephone companies,
including Bell Atlantic Corp., to jointly offer Internet service
using an advanced telephone technology known as digital subscriber
lines, or DSL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     05-03 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIST OF FINAL WITNESSES RELEASED IN MICROSOFT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. and the government both released
the names Monday of the final witnesses each intends to call when
the antitrust trial resumes later this month. The list indicates
that the government hopes to shore up its case, while Microsoft's
goal, at least in part, is to change the subject of discussion to
one that might make the government's case seem irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising announcement came from Microsoft. The
company is summoning David Colburn _ a senior executive for America
Online and an important government witness earlier in the trial _
to testify as a hostile witness in the final, rebuttal stage of
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn will be questioned about ``the completeness and candor
of prior testimony,'' Microsoft said, and as part of the company's
effort to argue that America Online's purchase of the Netscape
Communications Corp. undermines the government's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rebuttal witnesses will show that the $10 billion merger
of AOL and Netscape completely undercuts the government's case'' by
showing that ``competition and innovation are stronger than ever in
the software industry,'' said William Neukom, Microsoft's senior
vice president for law and corporate affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will also call Gordon Eubanks, the former chairman of
Symantec Corp., maker of the Norton Utilities programs for Windows,
and Richard Schmalensee, an economist and dean of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology Sloan School of Management. Schmalensee was
Microsoft's economic witness earlier in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is also recalling its chief economic
witness, Franklin M. Fisher, another MIT economist. It will also
recall Edward Felten, the Princeton University computer scientist
who served as a government witness earlier in the trial, and Gary
Norris, an International Business Machines Corp. executive who was
for several years director of IBM's software strategy division.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said they were confident of their case and
hoped their rebuttal witnesses would shore up areas of weakness
exposed during the earlier part of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Felten, is being called in part to rebut any
technical statements Microsoft might make that government lawyers
find questionable. He and his staff found several of the technical
flaws in Microsoft's demonstration tapes played in court earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The overarching goal, government officials said, is to keep the
strong legal advantage they believe they have already gained.
</P>
<P>
   A senior IBM executive, John Soyring, has already testified for
the government, and there is some overlap between the areas he
discussed and the ones Justice Department lawyers intend to raise
with Norris. But they also intend to question him about Microsoft's
efforts to stop IBM from offering software on its computers made by
Microsoft's competitors, according to a filing with the court.
</P>
<P>
   With its witnesses, Microsoft wants to open up new areas of
evidence. A filing with the court shows that the company wants to
use Colburn to help make the case that Netscape, America Online and
the government plotted, in effect, to hide for two months the
developing deal between Netscape and America Online because they
were afraid news of it would hurt the government's case.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official called that ``a desperate attempt
to distract attention from Microsoft's illegal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about the transaction has any relevance to the case,''
the official added, ``and nothing about it will break Microsft's
stranglehold on the operating system market.''
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks, now the head of Oblix, a business-directory software
manufacturer, led Symantec during the years when the company sold
utilities that Microsoft later incorporated into the Windows
operating system. But Microsoft wants to show that Symantec then
came up with new ideas, like antivirus software, to replace the
lost business and continued to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft describes Eubanks as a friend and competitor. In a
filing with the court Monday, Microsoft said Eubanks would testify
about ``the rapid pace of change in the software business, and the
inability of anyone to predict the directions in which computer and
communication technology would evolve over the last 10 years,'' and
``the expansion of the concept of an operating system through the
addition of new features and functions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Eubanks said, ``Microsoft has done some
bad things,'' but added that the company and its chairman, William
H. Gates III, had been victims of the American tendency to tear
down those who are too successful.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fisher and Schmalensee will have to repair damage they did
to government and Microsoft cases during earlier cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he did not think Microsoft's behavior had harmed
consumers, a statement he later tried to modify. And Schmalensee
was shown to have offered opinions in previous years that were
opposite the ones he was espousing in court, leading Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson to question his credibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
