<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notes: April award a good sign for Smoltz
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz was voted the National League pitcher of
the month for April. The last time that happened, it was his first
step toward a rendezvous with the Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said if I had to pick a month, it'd be October,''
said Smoltz, who was 4-0 with a 1.51 ERA last month. ``But I'm
elated with the honor. And to win it in April. . . I usually don't
start out very well.''
</P>
<P>
   With one notable exception. The monthly award was his first
since winning both April and May honors in 1996. He lost his first
start of the season that year, went on a 14-game win streak and
steam-rolled right into a lopsided NL Cy Young vote. The league hit
.200 against him that season. Last month, that average was .177.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever seen Smoltz better, manager Bobby Cox said,
``No, he can't pitch better. How could you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree,'' Smoltz said, laughing. ``I've worked very hard to
get to this point. It's such a long year. A realistic part of you
knows you're going to have some bad days. You try to avoid as many
as possible, make the good ones so good that the bad doesn't (seem
as bad).
</P>
<P>
   While Smoltz did post the lowest ERA among NL starters,
Houston's Shane Reynolds (4-1), St. Louis' Kent Bottenfield (4-0),
New York's Dennis Cook and San Diego's Andy Ashby (4-1) all matched
his win total. Bottenfield's ERA was 1.53.
</P>
<P>
   Tab, please
</P>
<P>
   The luxury tax statements were released by Major League
Baseball, indicating that based on their pending 1999 payroll, the
Braves owe $772,000. The Braves say: hogwash.
</P>
<P>
   MLB's estimate was derived from the club's opening day payroll
of $73.59 million, but does not reflect the subtraction of Mark
Wohlers' $5.2 million salary. Though the Braves continue to pay
Wohlers as part of the April 16 trade with Cincinnati, his contract
is designated to the Reds, possibly moving the Braves out of the
luxury tax bracket. Tax assessments are not final until the final
day of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threshhold for the luxury tax is a moving target. It
changes throughout the year,'' said team president Stan Kasten.
``Do the math. Plus, the money we saved (with the trade) is the
$700,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The clubs that would be assessed this year: Los Angeles ($5.15
million), New York Yankees ($4.25 million), Baltimore ($4.07
million), Atlanta and the New York Mets ($525,000). The luxury tax
system, as provided in the game's last basic work agreement,
expires after this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Candidate, Part II
</P>
<P>
   With a new wave of speculation washing over manager Ray Miller's
future in Baltimore, Braves batting coach Don Baylor's name has
again come up as a possible replacement. Though any more regarding
Miller is not expected until Wednesday, Atlanta general manager
John Schuerholz not only denied the Orioles have ever called for
permission to talk with Baylor but downplayed the chance Baylor
would be leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's a guy who's got managerial experience and
success and probably is a natural lightning rod of attention,''
Schuerholz said. ``Don and I discussed all of this up front when he
joined us. We've got an understanding that if the opportunity
comes. . . But I don't want to make a lot of that because he's
comfortable here.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
