<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FILM-STUDIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SNAGS, DE NIRO AND MIRAMAX PLAN BROOKLYN STUDIO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, actor Robert De Niro
and Harvey Weinstein of Miramax Films announced a tentative
agreement Monday to build a movie studio at the Brooklyn Navy Yard,
major elements of the deal to transform the cavernous shipbuilding
complex into a glamorous film factory are not in place.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed $150 million project would turn a 15-acre site on
Wallabout Bay into 12 huge sound stages for film and television
production and revive the home of Brooklyn's oldest industry, the
long-closed 129-year-old Navy Yard. But the economics of such a
project and the vagaries of the film industry are daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a news conference got under way Monday near the dry
docks at the Navy Yard, De Niro's company, TriBeCa Productions, and
the developer for the project, Vornado Realty Trust, had not signed
a letter of intent with city officials, despite repeated attempts
during a series of meetings last weekend and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nor had Steven Roth, chairman of Vornado, been able to sign a
separate agreement with the moviemakers, De Niro and Harvey
Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax Films, that detailed the extent
of their involvement in the project.
</P>
<P>
   The financing is not quite in place and two men who started the
project, Louis Madigan and Cary Hart, are objecting to the city's
proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   That did not stop Giuliani, De Niro, Weinstein or Roth from
declaring their allegiance to Brooklyn and their intentions to
build a Hollywood-style studio where tens of thousands of workers
once labored. The mayor, like nearly every other executive or city
official who went to the microphone, made note of his birth in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This facility will allow producers to shoot an entire movie,
from start to finish, right here in New York City,'' Giuliani said.
``It will not only encourage new film production in the city; it
will also help revitalize an area that has long been under-used.''
</P>
<P>
   De Niro, whose company produces about five films a year, was
equally ebullient. ``Everything we would do, we would do here,'' he
said. ``That's the whole point. Being part of this is very exciting
for me and great for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a little like the mobster-turned-therapy patient he
played in his latest film, ``Analyze This,'' De Niro added: ``I
could be wrong a little bit here and there. But you cannot fail in
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the still unsigned deal, the venture led by
Vornado would invest $35 million. The Fisher real estate family,
which owns Plaza Construction, would build the project, and become
a partner in the deal. The city, in turn, would provide a $25
million low-interest loan, while Brooklyn Navy Yard Development
Corp. would put in another $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Union Labor Life Insurance Co. is considering investing
providing about $82 million in financing, although it has not yet
made a commitment. Keyspan Energy, which will build the electrical
system, may also invest.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the proposed letter of intent obtained by The New York
Times specifies the role of the city and Vornado, but it does not
say a word about the obligations of TriBeCa Productions. Miramax,
which shoots 10 to 15 films a year, is not even a signatory.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Levine, the deputy mayor for economic development,
acknowledged that there was still lots of work to be done,
including environmental studies and other reviews. ``Hopefully,''
he said, ``we'll be back in a year to break ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry executives contend that many of the major film
companies are in the midst of cutbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
