<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES POSSIBLITY OF BOMBING PAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Giving his strongest hint yet of flexibility,
President Clinton Monday said he was open to a pause in NATO's
bombing campaign if there was ``clear and unambigious'' evidence
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would begin withdrawing
troops from Kosovo, allow the refugees to return home and agree to
an international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   As Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy to Kosovo,
arrived at the White House for talks with Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, Clinton said, ``We could have a bombing pause if
it's clear that it will be an aid of that larger purpose.'' White
House aides later downplayed any change in the US position on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After their meeting, Chernomyrdin said the two men were ``closer
to a diplomatic solution'' to end the Kosovo conflict and that he
would resume the conversation with Gore. The former prime minister
said he had brought Clinton a letter from Russian President Boris
Yeltsin that contained concrete proposals to end the air war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very complicated issue,'' Chernomyrdin said. ``We will
keep on working. ``We remain hopeful. The stakes are very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later met with the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who
hand-delivered a letter from Milosevic requesting a meeting with
the president. Jackson afterward suggested the president should
call Milosevic to thank him for releasing the three American POWS
on Sunday. Such a conversation, he said, could lead to further
talks between the two men. Jackson said Clinton told him he would
think about it.
</P>
<P>
   But before the meeting, White House spokesman Joseph Lockhart
said Milosevic knew what he had to do to end the bombing and asked,
``What is there to talk about?''
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson was flying to Washington to meet with Clinton, the
released soliders, who had been imprisoned for 32 days in Belgrade,
were reunited with their families Monday in Germany and passed
preliminary medical examinations. The three servicemen are Steven
Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas; Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; and Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said X-rays shows that Stone had suffered a broken
nose and that Ramirez had broken ribs. Both injuries were now
healing. Ramirez also had a swollen right leg and doesn't remember
how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   But more good weather allowed NATO to keep its promise not to
``reward'' Milosevic for releasing the soldiers and continued with
its punishing assaults on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav media reported NATO warplanes mistakenly hit a bus,
killing at least 17 people and injuring 21 others. NATO officials
said they had no information on the bus traveling from the western
Kosovo city of Pec to Rozaje in neighboring Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav reports said the bus was full of women and children and
that rescue teams were unable to reach the scene right away because
the bombing continued. Three civilian and two police vehicles also
were hit during the airstrikes, which were thought to be aimed at a
nearby police and army checkpoint, according to those reports.
</P>
<P>
   If the report is true, this would be the second bus hit by
alliance bombs in three days. NATO officials have admitted a stray
missile hit a bus north of Pristina on Saturday. Serb sources said
39 people were killed in that incident. In all, the alliance has
admitted that mistaken airstrikes since April 12 have left about
159 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, work crews struggled Monday to restore power to the
Yugoslav capital and large parts of Serbia after an attack on the
Belgrade power grid caused a massive blackout Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has promised to target military sites and installations and
tried to minimize disruptions to civilians, but the latest bombing
of electrical sites temporarily affected 70 percent of Serbia,
alliance officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a new style of airstrikes, NATO warplanes dropped ``soft
bombs'' that explode above electric power plants, spraying graphite
strips that short-circuit power stations. The bombs, which also
were used in the Persian Gulf War, struck Kostolac's power grid 50
miles east of the capital that supplies much of eastern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombers also hit electricity transformer yards as well the
towns of Nis, Novi Sad, Drmno, Obrenovac and Banina Basta.
</P>
<P>
   This shows that ``NATO has its finger on the light switch in
Yugoslavia now, and we can turn the power off whenever we need to
and whenever we want to,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Monday:
</P>
<P>
   --The Pentagon ordered to active duty an Air Force Reserve
search-and- rescue group, raising to 2,236 the number of reservists
mobilized for the Kosovo conflict. The call-up of 120 members of
the 939th Rescue Wing based in Portland, Ore., comes after one US
warplane crashed in Serbia over the weekend and another was hit by
ground fire but landed safely.
</P>
<P>
   --The Senate for the first time since the airstrikes began,
debated a measure that would allow Clinton to use ``all necessary
force'' to resolve the Kosovo conflict. But lawmakers are expected
to avoid voting directly on the resolution through a procedural
maneuver. Senator Paul Wellstone, a Minnesota Democrat, called on
Clinton to consider a pause in the bombing ``to improve the
environment for diplomatic discussions now underway.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A surprise night train from Kosovo poured more refugees into
Macedonia, where some 11,000 ethnic Albanians, many of them women
and children, were backed up at the main border crossing. The UN's
refugee agency said 2,000 people had arrived during the night,
adding to the 5,000 who were already camped out in a temporary
holding center at the Blace checkpoint between Macedonia and
Kosovo. NATO said it planned to build camps in Albania for another
160,000 refugees, including up to 60,000 now in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   --In Macedonia, British Prime Minister Tony Blair visited the
teeming Stankovic camp and said Britain would double its cash aid
to $64.5 million and also take in an unspecified additional number
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   --Germany's Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping said his country
will commit 600 more troops to international efforts to aid Kosovo
refugees in Macedonia and Albania. Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
cabinet is expected to discuss the extra deployment Tuesday, with a
parliamentary vote this week.
</P>
<P>
   --Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi told Clinton during a
summit meeting between the two leaders that Japan would contribute
$200 million to aid the refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   During a joint news conference with Obuchi, Clinton said, he was
not trying to achieve ``total victory'' over Milosevic. ``What I am
asking for are the minimal conditions necessary for the Kosovars to
be able to go home and live in security with self-government; that
is, they won't go home unless the Serb security forces are
withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger
later said the president's comments was not a softening of his
position. ``We need verifiable evidence that he is withdrawing,''
Berger said of Milosevic. ``We're not even close to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
