<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSION FIGHT ROILS WORLD TRADE ORGANIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A leadership crisis disrupted operations of the World
Trade Organization on Monday after weekend negotiations collapsed,
with no breakthrough in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the New Zealand and Thai finalists for the post of
director- general at the 134-nation group both insisted their
candidate should win.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats fear that the brawl at the four-year-old organization,
which makes rules and arbitrates disagreements in international
commerce, could stall resolution of many trade disputes and
jeopardize preparations for new trade talks set for Seattle in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether this is resolved quickly or without blood on the
floor, it could impact on the climate for preparations,'' said
Pakistan's trade envoy, Munir Akram, whose country backs the Thai
candidate. Carlos Perez del Castillo, Uruguay's top trade delegate,
who backs the candidate from New Zealand, said, ``The WTO is
absolutely paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the organization's rules, the term of the outgoing
director-general, Renato Ruggiero of Italy, which was to expire
Friday, was extended through Monday because a successor had not
been chosen. He appointed a caretaker administrator to handle
routine chores, but only a new director-general can make important
decisions, such as selecting arbitrators for disputes and admitting
new members.
</P>
<P>
   Animosity over who would replace Ruggiero first broke into the
open Friday when the organization's selection committee said one
candidate, Mike Moore, a former New Zealand prime minister, had the
highest and broadest geographical support among member nations.
Supporters of Moore's rival, Supachai Panitchpakdi, Thailand's
deputy prime minister and commerce minister, furiously rejected the
choice, contending that the 62-59 vote among member countries was
dubious and too close to declare Moore victorious.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of countries supporting each candidate caucused Monday,
each accusing the other of hardball tactics. On Sunday, countries
backing Moore urged delegates not to resort to a precedent-setting
and potentially divisive vote that Supachai's supporters are
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization has sought to avoid a formal vote for
fear that it could set big trading powers like the United States
and the European Union against the smaller, but more numerous,
developing countries, creating polarizing frictions that would
undermine its legitimacy. Traditionally, the organization tries to
make important decisions by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Both finalists insisted they would fight to the end, suggesting
there was no room for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not pulling out,'' Supachai said. Moore, in a telephone
interview from New Zealand's mission in Geneva, said: ``We're
stronger than before. The issue now is whether you support the
rules or not.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of countries backing Moore, which included Uruguay,
Venezuela, France, Turkey and Sweden, issued a statement urging
Supachai to withdraw. ``If Moore is vetoed, there is no way
Supachai will be the next director-general,'' said Perez del
Castillo of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Supachai's backers, led by developing countries, have become
increasingly angry over what they view as a bias against him by the
large trading powers, particularly the United States. Zimbabwe's
envoy, T.J.B. Jokonya, complained Saturday that a ``most deadly
arsenic diatribe was unleashed on those who dared to oppose the
wish of the anointed.'' He was referring to efforts by supporters
of Moore to defeat Supachai.
</P>
<P>
   Many nations supporting Supachai were stunned at the choice of
the selection committee because the 52-year-old Thai economist had
reportedly been ahead since the process of country-by-country
consultation got under way last fall. Many believed the selection
was purposely delayed in order to garner more support for Moore,
50.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big boys thought it would all be decided behind closed
doors, like last time,'' Akram of Pakistan said. ``But the WTO has
evolved and it's time for a developing country choice.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bangkok, politicians argued that it was time to review ties
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, an influential supporter of Supachai, was sticking by its
candidate. Yoichi Suzuki, a trade diplomat from Japan, said, ``We
have more problems with the process than the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki said the vote tally announced Friday ``shows that it's
finely balanced,'' adding, ``You can't tell who is winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
