<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL BIG AUTOMAKERS POSTED ROBUST APRIL SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In a further sign of consumers' willingness to keep
spending in a robust economy, auto sales maintained their sizzling
pace in April.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co., DaimlerChrysler AG, Toyota, Honda and Nissan,
along with a number of smaller automakers, reported strong sales
Monday, and the industry as a whole is on track to match or beat
its vigorous sales pace of last April.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said its sales rose 6.6 percent last month to 345,672
compared with the corresponding period a year ago. Those figures
included Volvo sales, since Ford's acquisition of the Swedish
automaker was completed March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding Volvo's results, Ford's sales rose 4.1 percent, with
car sales falling 1 percent and sales of sport utility vehicles,
minivans and pickup trucks rising 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said sales at its American unit, Chrysler, rose
2.0 percent to 225,195. Mercedes-Benz sales dropped 0.8 percent in
the United States last month. Excluding the Mercedes' results,
DaimlerChrysler's car sales rose 5.9 percent and its truck sales
edged up 0.4 percent to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Honda sales have set records each month this year. In April,
sales rose 4.0 percent to 90,352. Honda's car sales fell 3.1
percent but were offset by a 52.9 percent rise in truck sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence in the economy remains strong and continues to
drive consumer demand for big-ticket items,'' said Dick Colliver,
executive vice president for American Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota sales rose 9.6 percent to 118,833. Nissan sales rose 21.5
percent to 47,243. ``There's a lot to celebrate,'' said David
Bradley, an auto analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Auto stocks generally rose Monday. Ford was up $2.75, to
$66.6875, and DaimlerChrysler increased $1.9375 to $100.125.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. is scheduled to report its April sales
results Tuesday. GM put on hefty discounts last April, which
jump-started its sluggish sales, and will have a tough time
improving on its results year-over-year. Indeed, Wall Street
analysts expect GM's sales to drop as much as 3 percent. Bradley
said that ``even if the numbers are down a bit, they would still be
very strong numbers.'' Shares rose $4.6875, to $93.75.
</P>
<P>
   Month after month, this year's auto sales results have surprised
even the experts: auto industry economists have repeatedly raised
their industry sales forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing it pretty much every month this year as the
results kept coming in stronger and stronger,'' said W. Van
Bussmann, corporate economist at DaimlerChrysler. In December, he
predicted the industry would sell 14.8 million cars, trucks,
minivans and sport utility vehicles this year. He has raised his
forecast four times since then, to 15.6 million cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Economists at Ford and GM have also increased their estimates.
Ford began the year predicting the industry would sell between 14.6
million and 15.1 million cars and light trucks this year. In
mid-March, it added a half-million vehicles, and just a few weeks
after that said sales would likely fall at the top end of the
range, or 15.6 million, in line with Chrysler's predictions.
</P>
<P>
   GM's forecast mirrored Ford's at the beginning of the year, and
economists there now expect the industry to sell between 15.3
million and 15.9 million cars and light trucks this year.
</P>
<P>
   During the first quarter, sales reached an annual pace of 16.6
million, well above last year's first-quarter sales of 14.9
million. Even if the pace slows somewhat later this year, the
industry could break its all-time sales record of 16 million cars
and light trucks, set in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is a possibility that we'll exceed that 1986
record,'' said Ellen Hughes-Cromwick, a senior economist at Ford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
