<SLUG> BC-SBC-PUERTO-RICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC-TELMEX DEAL SEEKS PHONE CARRIER IN PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Betting on both wireless phones and the Caribbean economy, SBC
Communications Inc. said Monday that it had joined with Telefonos
de Mexico SA in an agreement to acquire Cellular Communications of
Puerto Rico Inc., the biggest wireless phone carrier on that island
and in the United States Virgin Islands, for $464 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, including $350 million in assumed debt, was the first
move into the Caribbean for SBC, the No. 2 local phone company in
the United States after Bell Atlantic Corp. SBC is the dominant
local phone company in Texas and California and owns 10 percent of
Telefonos de Mexico, or Telmex, Mexico's dominant phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular Communications, which is based in New York and does
business under the Cellular One brand name, lost about $30.9
million last year on revenue of $155.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   For SBC, the deal would not seem to have a short-term impact
comparable to the company's deal in January to acquire Comcast
Corp.'s East Coast wireless business for $400 million. But a
significant presence in Puerto Rico could eventually help SBC
expand into other areas of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as significantly, SBC's senior management may believe
that it can run the Puerto Rican wireless business better than can
the company's current management.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, however, Edward E. Whitacre Jr., SBC's chairman,
praised Cellular Communications' current leadership and said the
company was poised to expand into the standard telephone business.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Cellular Communications'
shareholders would receive $29.50 in cash for each of their shares.
The stock rose 17.9 percent, or $4.25, to $28 in heavy trading
Monday. Telmex's American depositary receipts were up 4.6 percent,
or $4.25, to $80 on the New York Stock Exchange, where SBC was down
1.6 percent, or $1, to $54.75.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and Telmex did not specify how they intended to split their
ownership, saying only that Telmex would own at least 25 percent of
the Caribbean venture.
</P>
<P>
   SBC declined to comment on reports that it might be negotiating
to join the European partnership of Deutsche Telekom and Telecom
Italia, but executives close to the company said SBC was not
discussing a partnership with the European communications giants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
