<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLETE WNBA DRAFT CAN BE EXPERIENCED ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the Women's NBA plans a live cybercast of its
draft on the league's official site (www.wnba.com).
</P>
<P>
   The league is billing the event as the first major-sport draft
exclusively on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   OK, before anyone starts a debate on the WNBA's place as a major
league, consider that the league faced a possible shutdown during
negotiations with players on a collective bargaining agreement.
That's right. The league had labor issues with its players and the
dispute jeopardized the season, which is scheduled to begin May 26.
From this vantage, that qualifies the WNBA as a major sports
league.
</P>
<P>
   Having made that point, the league's cybercast, which starts at
10 a.m. Tuesday, should be worth a visit if only to see how it
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see clips on the news _ in parts,'' said Stefanie
Scheer, director of Internet Services for NBA Entertainment. ``This
is unique because it's the only way to watch the draft from
beginning to end.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA site plans user-directed video, live audio coverage, a
draft toteboard, live chats with draft selections and lots of
digital photos.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA.com's resources for such an effort are in place. The site
is a sister production of NBA.com in cooperation with NBA
Entertainment and ESPN Internet Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   During the event, broadcasters Mike Breen and Meghan Pattyson
are scheduled to give selection-by-selection announcements and
analysis with occasional updates from news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Users tired of talking heads can try the site's WNBA.cam, a
robotic camera that can be remotely controlled with a computer
mouse. The camera provides multiple still images that users can
access.
</P>
<P>
   The site also has a decent warmup act: scouting reports and
photos from the WNBA's predraft camp last month, biographies and
video highlights of eligible prospects, polls and message boards.
</P>
<P>
   Scheer said it's difficult to predict how many will view the
draft. The technique might be applied to draft coverage on NFL.com
or NBA.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be looking at it carefully,'' Scheer said.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER WNBA RESOURCES: Keep in mind that WNBA.com isn't the only
place for women's basketball fans to follow the league. While the
league doesn't match its male counterpart in fan-authored sites, a
few unofficial efforts stand out.
</P>
<P>
   BEST FANZINE: The 3 Pointer (www.the3pointer.com) is an
excellent resource for hardcore WNBA fans. Compiled by Sylvia Cagle
of Sacremento, Calif., her fanzine has sections on each WNBA team,
fan-written articles _ with headlines such as ``WNBA Poetry'' and
``This is not your father's NBA'' _ and links to players and team
pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the players are so reachable, we've been fortunate to
have a lot of contributions from players themselves,'' Cagle said.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PLAYER SITE: Surprisingly, the best fan page isn't of
Sheryl Swoopes or Rebecca Lobo. The Sue Wicks Fan Page
(www.monmouth.com/~dkochan), created and well-designed by Diana
Kochan in adoration of the New York Liberty forward, has the best
collection of links and background data of any active player.
</P>
<P>
   BEST TEAM SITE: The Phoenix Mercury Fan Page
(www.allsports.com/wnba/mercury/wnba.html) is one Mercury fan's
update on her favorite team, the WNBA and women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   MOST INTERESTING TEAM SITE: The Sisters of No Mercy
(www.sistersofnomercy.com) is an odd, yet interesting creation that
follows the Mercury. The site is maintained by season ticketholders
Jan Newman and Beth Ells of Phoenix who dress as nuns at the games.
Known as Mother Mary Hoops and Sister Three Point, they show up at
home games waving rulers or signs and giving referees the business.
</P>
<P>
   BULLISH FOR BELFOUR: If you think Internet stocks are going
through the roof, shares of Stars goalie Ed Belfour are going for
$165.20 a pop on Wall Street Sports (www.wallstreetsports.com).
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street Sports is a free online game in which members
(450,000) participate in a sports stock market where pro athletes
are traded as securities for fun and prizes. Values are determined
by an athlete's performance and/or the demand for his stock.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's shares have the third-highest value among NHL players.
Buffalo Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek's shares go for $203.21
apiece and Colorado Avalanche goaltender Patrick Roy shares are
worth $195.12 each.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's price-to-earnings ratio ... uh, goals-against-average
must be driving the price.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
