<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW CROSSES 11,000 MARK JUST 24 DAYS AFTER 10,000
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average blew past the 11,000 mark, just
24 trading days after it topped 10,000 for the first time. The 10
percent move from March 29 was not the fastest such rise in market
history, but it was the quickest jump of 10 percent to come during
a period of prolonged market strength. The Dow rose 225.65 points,
or 2 percent, to 11,014.69, led by cyclical stocks. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index gained 19.45 points, to 1,354.63, but the
Nasdaq composite index fell 7.27 points, to 2,535.58 as money moved
out of technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   SOME COMPANIES EASING WORKLOAD
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a decade of piling responsibilities on workers, a
smattering of American companies are beginning to worry about the
consequences, ranging from a lack of creativity to burnout. And
several companies are experimenting with ways to alleviate outsized
workloads, including everything from explicitly limiting work to 40
hours a week to discouraging employees from checking their e-mail
and phone messages over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   GUMBEL RETURNING TO MORNING TV
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Gumbel's long-anticipated return to morning television
will become official today when CBS announces that he has agreed to
become the anchor of a revamped ``CBS This Morning'' program, which
will be in a new studio on Fifth Avenue in New York City at the
entrance to Central Park. The new program, with Gumbel and a
still-to-be-named woman co-anchor, is scheduled to start sometime
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON AND OBUCHI TALK STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan
professed to be in agreement on strategies to pull Japan out of a
seven-year slump and deregulate its economy. But their meeting
underscored how many of Clinton's initiatives with Tokyo have been
sunk by the Japanese recession.
</P>
<P>
   FORD GAIN LEADS SIZZLING AUTO SALES
</P>
<P>
   Auto sales maintained their sizzling pace in April. Ford
reported a 6.6 percent rise, and gains were also reported by
DaimlerChrysler, Toyota, Honda, Nissan and several smaller auto
makers, putting the industry on track to match or beat its vigorous
sales pace of last April. GM is to report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING AND INCOME RISE
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing grew in April for the third consecutive month, and
personal income and spending and construction spending all rose in
March, a private industry survey and government reports showed.
Personal incomes rose four-tenths of a percent in March after
rising five-tenths of a percent in February, the Commerce
Department said.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT AND U.S. NAME WITNESSES
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and the government released the names of the final
witnesses each intends to call when the antitrust trial resumes
later this month. The list indicates that the government hopes to
shore up its case, while Microsoft's goal, at least in part, is to
argue that America Online's purchase of Netscape Communications
undercuts the government's case.
</P>
<P>
   VENCOR PLANS TO MISS DEBT PAYMENT
</P>
<P>
   Vencor, one of the largest operators of nursing homes, said it
would not pay $14.8 million due in interest on $300 million of
notes that mature in 2005, providing new fodder for investor
concerns about its ability to survive.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL SEEKS IMPROVED FIBER OPTICS
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Networks plans to announce today that it has developed a
product that could increase the capacity of fiber optic
communications networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
