<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MAY 3
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-TENN-HEALTHCARE-NYT (moved on Friday, Apr. 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Apr. 30,
about Tenncare, the Tennessee health care program for the
uninsured, misstated the number of people enrolled. As noted
elsewhere in the article, it is 1.3 million, not 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misspelled the surname of the governor who
established the program. He is Ned McWherter, not McWerter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-STEEL-COMPETE-NYT (moved on Thursday, Apr. 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Apr. 29,
about the effect of minimills on the United States steel industry
misstated the surname of the founder of Weirton Steel. He was
Ernest T. Weir, not Weirton.
</P>
<P>
   BC-EQUITIES-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 2,
misspelled the name of a company with an initial offering of three
million shares. It is Media Metrix, not Media Matrix.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TV-ARK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Friday, Apr. 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Apr. 30,
about the television movie ``Noah's Ark,'' shown in two parts
Sunday night and last night on NBC, misidentified the director of
the 1972 film ``The Ruling Class,'' another film in which the voice
of God has a role. It was directed by Peter Med-ak; Peter Barnes
wrote both films.
</P>
</TEXT>
