</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDER HINTS THAT 3 GI'S WERE BEATEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Mich.)  (Eds.: Note dateline and byline have changed from early budgets)
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three American soldiers freed from a Yugoslav
prison over the weekend met with their families in Germany on
Monday, and their commander suggested they had been mistreated
while in custody.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, who were released by President Slobodan Milosevic
on Sunday after a personal appeal from the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
appeared before reporters with family members at a U.S. Army
medical center in Landstuhl.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. David Grange, commander of the soldiers' unit, said
there were indications that their captors had mistreated the
soldiers even though the men have said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them were poorly treated at the beginning, but that
will be determined,'' Grange said at a news conference in
Landstuhl.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers are Specialist Steven M. Gonzales, 22, of
Huntsville, Texas; Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich. Army officials are interviewing them, a process that could
take a few days.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon the spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, said,
``Everything we have learned so far suggests that these soldiers
were illegally detained in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were captured 32 days ago while on patrol near the
border of Macedonia and Serbia. Bacon said military officials are
still determining the circumstances of their capture.
</P>
<P>
   Once the soldiers finish their interviews, Bacon said, each will
get 30 days' leave, presumably in the United States. He expects the
soldiers to rejoin their units after that.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also said two Yugoslav soldiers who were captured last
month by Kosovo rebels and turned over to NATO by the Albanian
government are being held in Germany. He did not say when they
might be freed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
