<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/03/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BALTIMORE -- May 3, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES-4, 5-03 --
A small but passionate group of Cuban-Americans protesting outside
Camden Yards against Cuba's national baseball team playing in
Baltimore. With the wrangling over visas and flight delays behind
them, the Cubans finally faced the Baltimore Orioles on Monday
night. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MILL VALLEY, Calif. -- May 3, 1999 -- SCHOOL-VIOLENCE,
5-03 -- Deanna Miller and her husband Max greet their son Max, 9,
on the playground of his school last week. In the wake of the
schootings in Littleton, Colo., the Millers have refused to allow
Max to play video games which depict violence. The roots of the
Littleton shootings lay in the American culture's fascination with
violence and the obsession of many children with fantasy
role-playing games said Dave Thomas, the district attorney of
Jefferson County, Colo., where the Columbine High School shootings
took place. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BALTIMORE -- May 3, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES-3, 5-03 --
The Cuban flag joins the American during a pre-game ceremony at
Camden Yards on Monday. With the wrangling over visas and flight
delays behind them, Cuba's national baseball faced the Baltimore
Orioles Monday night. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- May 3, 1999 -- KOSOVO-DIPLO, 5-03 --
President Clinton and his national security team meet with Viktor
Chernomyrdin, left, at the White House on Monday to discuss the
situation in Kosovo. From left, Chernomyrding, Clinton, Vice
President Al Gore, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, National
Security Advisor Sandy Berger and Assistant Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KUKES, Albania -- May 3, 1999 -- KOSOVO-DOCTOR, 5-03 --
Dr. James Desmoore listens as ethnic Albanian woman describes her
ailment to an interpreter at a local clinic treating ethnic
Albanian refugees from Kosovo. Lack of medicine, scarcity of
equipment, resistance from local doctors and an unending stream of
needy refugees combine to make this refugee frontier a test of
humanitarian resolve and medical ingenuity. (Edward Keating/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
