morals and cutthroat ethics. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EDWARDS, Calif. -- May 3, 1999 -- SCI-AGING-SHUTTLES-2,
5-03 -- The Space Shuttle Columbia towed to the Shuttle Processing
Area at NASA's Dryden Flight Research Center following its fifth
flight in space in November 1982. America's aging space shuttles,
often criticized as monuments to 1970's technology, have been
steadily modified during their lifetimes, NASA engineers and
managers say. There is much more modern technology beneath their
familiar skin than most people realize. (NASA /New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 3, 1999 -- SCI-AGING-SHUTTLES-1, 5-03 --An
older flight deck, on the Space Shuttle Columbia, top, with cathode
ray television screens, and the revamped Atlantis. The modern
cockpit has digital display screens, a new navigation system and
other electronics that rival the latest airliners. America's aging
space shuttles, often criticized as monuments to 1970's technology,
have been steadily modified during their lifetimes. (NASA /New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3)SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. -- May 3, 1999 -- SCI-RIVER-RESCUE-2,
5-03 -- Trees and green along the San Pedro River stand in stark
contrast to the desert around it. The river is in danger of drying
up because ground water pumped for urban development and farms is
drawing water from the river on both sides of the U.S.-Mexico
border. (Jon Christensen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2)SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. -- May 3, 1999 -- SCI-RIVER-RESCUE-1,
5-03 -- Paul Hardy, a conservationist, examining a bird's nest
along the San Pedro River. The river is in danger of drying up
because ground water pumped for urban development and farms is
drawing water from the river on both sides of the U.S.-Mexico
border. Hardy warns, ``If you take the San Pedro out, you are
jeopardizing a hemisphere's bird populations.'' (Jon
Christensen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- May 3, 1999 -- SCI-STEERE-LYME, 5-03 --
Celebrity and controversy have followed Dr. Allen Steere, in his
laboratory at the Tufts School of Medicine, from the time he gave
Lyme disease its name to his recent work on a Lyme vaccine. After
leading the research efforts on the vaccine, Steere then came under
fire for his theory that some people with Lyme disease in fact have
a post-disease syndrome. His theory has prompted some insurance
companies to cease coverage. (Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
