<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEST-DRESSED-FASHION-     05-03 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-DRESSED-FASHION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDATED, TRIVIAL, ADORED: THE BEST-DRESSED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although nobody was wearing white gloves or
reminiscing about the good old days, last week's committee meeting
of the Best-Dressed List definitely had a deja vu feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was in a time warp,'' said one participant,
among a dozen or so society figures and journalists who convened in
secret at the Fifth Avenue apartment of Eleanor Lambert to decide
who belongs and who doesn't on the world's oldest clotheshorse
list.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Lambert, for people not up on such matters, is the
nonagenarian fashion press agent whose real achievement was to help
turn American designers into personalities. That was in the 1940s,
before anyone knew about Norman Norell, Bill Blass or the charisma
of the jet set, when designers were kept hidden in back rooms, and
if fashion editors went to Seventh Avenue at all, they were greeted
by stiff-armed manufacturers in fireproof suits.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Lambert, the daughter of a circus promoter from
Crawfordsville, Ind., changed that. She started the twice-a-year
fashion shows and the Coty Awards gala, which took place at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and was the forerunner of the Costume
Institute's annual silk-purse party.
</P>
<P>
   She was in the right place at the right time, namely, at the
dazzling intersection of fashion and society in the early 1960s.
And she was able to exploit her position chiefly because she
controlled one of the most flagrantly superficial promotional
devices ever conceived: the International Best-Dressed List. ``It's
a trivial thing,'' said Miss Lambert lightly of her list.
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, Jackie, Gloria, Babe _ was there ever a list that so
gloriously affirmed the status quo while creating excitement for a
new style of life? There were people who would have killed to be
considered BDL, and, Miss Lambert said, some tried to use their
influence, even money to get on the list. It was that big a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terribly proud of myself,'' recalled Nan Kempner, the
Park Avenue socialite, who got on the list several times in the
mid-1960s, along with Gloria Vanderbilt, Mica Ertegun, Chessy
Rayner, Amanda Burden, and Marisa Berenson. ``In that time, it
mattered a great deal. It was a kudos.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Lambert is a little vague about the origins of the list,
stating in one account that it was founded by French designers in
1924 and in another that it was the brainchild of a New York Times
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Her confusion has nothing to do with her age. She has always
been vague about the details, a trait common to shrewd, old-time
press agents. As Marylin Bender said of Miss Lambert in ``The
Beautiful People'' (1967): ``Her accomplishments are all the more
impressive because they arise out of seemingly total confusion. She
is chronically tardy and affects a vague, helplessly feminine
manner at times, but always manages to pull her chestnuts out of
the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Best-Dressed List is a remarkable social record,
specifically of New York. In most years, the list reflects a frank
preference for women of classic style and pedigree, to say nothing
of means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is something innately conservative about the
whole setup,'' said Amy Fine Collins, a Vanity Fair writer, who
made the list for two years before being bumped up to the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out to pasture,'' admitted Ms. Vanderbilt, a Hall of
Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Mrs. Kempner described this permanent status, ``The Hall
of the Forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   In another sense, however, the Best-Dressed List seems absurdly
quaint when all the rules (hem lines, proportions, the right shoes)
have been thrown out. ``I think it's great that Miss Lambert has
kept the traditions up,'' said Andre Leon Talley, a Vogue editor
and frequent committee member. ``But the list doesn't reflect the
social or cultural Zeitgeist as much as it should.'' The group has
tried in recent years to be more populist, citing the influence of
stars like Madonna and Nicole Kidman.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But apparently, open-mindedness has its limits. When William
Norwich, the columnist and House &AMP; Garden writer, proposed both the
Prince of Wales and Prince the performer several years back, Jerome
Zipkin, the late social arbiter, rose up, pointed a finger, and, as
Norwich recalled, roared, ``Don't you ever say those two names in
the same breath here again!''
</P>
<P>
   (``Zippy was Zippy,'' a longtime committee member conceded. ``It
was always a good thing if he liked you.'')
</P>
<P>
   But then, the committee has never professed to be broadly
informed except where aristocrats and jet setters are concerned.
``Last year, I nominated Maxwell, the singer,'' Talley said, ``and
a few people in the group said, `Oh, is that the heir to the
Maxwell coffee fortune?'''
</P>
<P>
   Like other designers with new ideas, John Bartlett treats his
recent inclusion on the list (men have had their own category since
1966) with bemused surprise, but said, ``The people who'd be on my
list would be thrown out.'' He mentioned the actor Alan Cummings,
the designer Jil Sander, and a London corset maker named Pearl.
``He's so bizarre looking,'' Bartlett said approvingly. ``He's like
watching a train wreck. You just can't take your eyes off him.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, that wouldn't have gone over with Miss Lambert's
committee members last week. Not that they wouldn't have had an
opinion about a man in a corset. It's just that they seemed to have
an agenda, and as the name of each nominee was bandied about the
room, they quickly reached a consensus, and then another was thrown
into the ring, carved up (but gently) until they had a list.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the choices seemed to spring full blown from newspapers
that very month: Kenneth I. Chenault, the new chief executive of
American Express, and Tony Duquette, the flamboyant set designer
and decorator who's been having a big comeback. Others simply came
from the Upper East Side. It was 1965 all over again, except with
loose hair.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's list: Aerin Lauder, Brooke Douglass de Ocampo,
Eliza Reed, Patricia Herrera, and Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece,
all part of the so-called junior social crowd; Victoire de
Castellane, a Paris fashion muse; Serena Linley, a daughter-in-law
of Princess Margaret; Marian McEvoy, editor of Elle Decor; Jade
Jagger, a daughter of Mick Jagger, and the actresses Uma Thurman,
Cameron Diaz and Gwyneth Paltrow, who almost didn't get on.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the committee thought that anyone who'd wear a
dress to the Oscars that fitted as poorly as Ms. Paltrow's didn't
belong on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The other male winners were Prince Pierre d'Arenberg, Count
Ruffredo Gaetani, an Italian businessman; Phillips Hathaway of
Sotheby's; Lord Hindlip of Christie's; Thomas Kempner, the banker;
Prince Michael of Kent, John F. Kennedy Jr., the rock singer Lenny
Kravitz, and the actors Rupert Everett and Dylan McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Lambert's list makers were under the impression that their
identities and comments would remain anonymous, so they spoke
freely in her apartment. But on Friday, Women's Wear Daily
published the names of the committee, which included Reinaldo
Herrera, a Vanity Fair editor who is married to the designer
Carolina Herrera; the jewelry designer Kenneth Jay Lane, Norwich,
and several Conde Nast contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the trade paper called them ``a motley group,'' and
said that Herrera and Lane got into a spat.
</P>
<P>
   One detected the hand of Miss Lambert in the brouhaha, although
she denied that she had released the names, as the paper reported.
As for the drama between Lane and Herrera, Lane had joked that
Herrera had used his influence to put his daughter Carolina Jr. on
the Best-Dressed List.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera objected. Lane offered him an apology and a cigarette.
``It wasn't a big deal at all,'' Herrera said.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that the list is an anachronism, but said that
doesn't mean it is irrelevant. He explained:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk down the streets of New York today, it seems as
if the whistle has blown for the factory, and the factory workers
are let out. Everybody looks the same. No originality, no
individuality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
