<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0504-C     05-03 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0504-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writethru; updates with comments from senior official;
Chernomyrdin, Jackson meetings; latest on NATO strikes . . .
 &HT;    CLINTON SIGNALS WILLINGNESS TO DEAL, BRING 'PAUSE' TO NATO AIR
STRIKES
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-POWS-0504; KOSOVO-CAMP-0504; KOSOVO-TROOPSQ&AMP;A-0504.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signaled Monday a broad
willingness to deal with Belgrade over the terms under which NATO
air strikes against Yugoslavia might end, saying he would support
``a bombing pause,'' under ``the right circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   In a retreat, Clinton softened his position on the composition
of an international peacekeeping force for the embattled Yugoslav
province of Kosovo. He dropped his earlier insistence on NATO
leadership of such a body and instead said the alliance must be ``a
big part of'' any peacekeeping contingent.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official later tried to downplay the
remarks, telling reporters there was no meaningful shift in U.S.
demands for a peacekeeping force commanded and controlled by NATO.
Clinton made clear, though, that he was not wedded to any specific
formulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's discussion, room for discussion, within
limits, about who's in this force and all of that,'' said Clinton,
who is scheduled to leave Tuesday to visit NATO headquarters in
Brussels and to speak to U.S. troops in Germany that are
participating in Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   With extraordinary specificity and candor, Clinton detailed his
inner anxieties over continuing an escalating bombing campaign that
has presented growing risks even as it takes a mounting toll on
Serb military targets and fielded forces.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three days, two NATO aircraft have crashed, a third
took heavy anti-aircraft fire and a fourth dropped a bomb that
destroyed a civilian bus, killing, according to state-run media in
Yugoslavia, 47 people. Yugoslav media reported that NATO strikes
destroyed a second bus Monday, killing at least 20. NATO officials
had no confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not relish every night sending young Americans and our
NATO allies up in planes flying very fast under very hazardous
circumstances in which their safety is at risk,'' Clinton said
during a White House press conference. ``I do not relish the
thought that inevitably some of those bombs will go astray and some
Serbian civilians, or some Kosovar civilians, could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   And, said Clinton, ``I do not relish the continuing burdens on
the people of Albania and Macedonia,'' a reference to the estimated
700,000 ethnic Albanian refugees that have poured across those tiny
countries' borders from neighboring Kosovo. ``I am eager to get the
Kosovars out of the camps and on their way back home and
rebuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks, made during a joint news conference with
visiting Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, kicked off what's
expected to be a week of intensive diplomacy. Clinton left the
press conference to meet with Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Victor
Chernomyrdin, to discuss possible ways to end the conflict with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin emerged from the 90-minute meeting to tell
reporters that U.S.-Russian differences were narrowing, but no
breakthrough was in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got closer to a diplomatic solution,'' Chernomyrdin said.
``It's a very complicated issue. We'll keep on working.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official who later briefed reporters on
background, however, was less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   He shot down any prospect of a near-term solution, saying ``I
expect this discussion with the Russians, with our allies, will
continue over some days,'' and, perhaps, ``some weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, his Russian interlocutors
and the United States remain far apart on the issue of how to
constitute a post-settlement security force in Kosovo. Milosevic
wants civilian monitors under United Nations command.
</P>
<P>
   The United States insists that Kosovar refugees will not return
to their homes without the protection of heavily-armed military
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin -- who sent Clinton a letter via
Chernomyrdin outlining Moscow's position -- has agreed on the need
for some sort of military peacekeeping force, but has not yet
accepted a NATO presence in such a force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian government continues to share our basic
objectives,'' said State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin. ``Now we
have to find an implementation mechanism to achieve those
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the Chernomyrdin meeting, Clinton met with the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, who secured the weekend release of three American
soldiers from Milosevic and, in exchange, called for a halt in
NATO's air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's attacks continued unabated, however, with U.S. and allied
pilots hitting 45 targets across Yugoslavia between Sunday morning
and early Monday, in one of the most furious 24-hour periods since
the campaign began March 24. The strikes were expected to escalate
further overnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read NATO's response as the idolatry of might,'' Jackson
told ABC News. ``I read it, in some sense, as the arrogance of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said Jackson's focus on the U.S. prisoners' release didn't
reflect the purpose of the NATO strikes: to combat Serb atrocities
that U.S. and NATO officials estimate have left at least 4,000
ethnic Albanians dead and have driven 1.5 million more to flee
their homes in Kosovo over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think more attention should be focused on the brutal war
crimes,'' continuing to unfold inside Kosovo, said Rubin. ``Jesse
Jackson was not able to go to Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic gave Jackson a letter to Clinton, which the White
House received on Sunday. The letter, though, ''has nothing new in
it,'' said the senior White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that NATO's essential demands have not changed.
The alliance will continue its bombing campaign, Clinton said,
until Milosevic ends the military campaign targeting the majority
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and agrees to allow refugees to return
to their homes and enjoy political autonomy under the protection of
an international security force.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO began bombing Yugoslavia nearly six weeks ago, the
White House specified a NATO peacekeeping force as one prerequisite
for ending the attacks. The administration later said such a force
must be ``NATO-led.'' Two weeks ago, the administration stepped
back slightly from that position, saying the force must simply have
``NATO at its core,'' a formulation that Rubin stuck to Monday
during his daily press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   During repeated references to the force, however, Clinton
himself pointedly dropped even the more ambiguous ``core,''
reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, what I said is subject to negotiation is, who is going to
be in the security force, how is it going to work and all of
that,'' Clinton said, responding to a reporter's question. ``Except
I do believe that the NATO group has to be a big part of it
because, otherwise, the Albanians, the Kosovar Albanians, won't
want to go back. And neither will the armed groups among the
Albanians readily lay down their arms.''
</P>
<P>
   A compromise over the make-up of such a peacekeeping force could
set the stage, Clinton suggested, for a broader diplomatic solution
to the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said that under the right circumstances, we would be
willing to have a bombing pause,'' Clinton said. ``But we would
need acceptance of the basic principles and at least the beginning
of withdrawal of Serb forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Until such a solution is reached, Clinton said, the bombing
campaign would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not trying to drag this out,'' said Clinton. ``But I am
determined to pursue our policy until we know that we have a chance
to do what has to be done in order for this to work as a practical
matter, and in order finally, to, clearly and unambiguously,
reverse the policy of ethnic and religious cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
