<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAINTERS-EYE-NYT &LR;      05-03 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINTERS-EYE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOTHESIS: THE ARTIST DOES SEE THINGS DIFFERENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., U.K.)  (lh) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Can artistic talent be measured scientifically? A
laughable notion, perhaps. And yet, according to ``The Painter's
Eye,'' an intriguing small show at the National Portrait Gallery in
London that runs through June 13, some of the secrets of the
creative process are now being cracked by the latest biomedical
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is built around a recent study of the interaction
between an artist's eyes, hand and brain while he draws a face. By
measuring his controlled or unconscious responses on three
different machines and by comparing the results with the reactions
of nonartists, researchers believe they have already proved that
the artist's mind is indeed different.
</P>
<P>
   The study was carried out by John Tchalenko, a British scientist
and a documentary filmmaker, along with teams of cognitive and
neuropsychologists and neurophysiologists from Britain and the
United States. The chosen artist was an English figurative painter,
Humphrey Ocean, four of whose works are in the National Portrait
Gallery's collection.
</P>
<P>
   The project was born somewhat accidentally of an earlier purely
artistic experiment in which Tchalenko and Ocean, an old friend,
decided to record each other at work. For 100 hours Tchalenko and
his camerawoman, Belinda Parsons, filmed Ocean while he painted
them. The painting, ``Double Portrait,'' and the film were then
shown side by side in several leading British galleries in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years after that, I was looking again at the tapes,
which were time-coded, and I began to pick up Humphrey's eye
pattern movements,'' recalled Tchalenko, 61, whose own scientific
background is in seismology, the study of earthquakes. ``This was
interesting in that it showed how a painting is produced, not
merely seen,'' he added. ``When I contacted the specialists, I was
surprised to discover how little was known about how artists
actually work.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a $30,000 grant from the Wellcome Trust, a large
medical research charity, Tchalenko then turned for help to
scientists from Oxford University's physiology department. They
used a special ``eye tracker'' camera to follow Ocean's eye
movements and a sensor that recorded his hand movements. For
comparison purposes, nonartists were tested in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the section ``The Eye Captures,'' the exhibition
shows how the camera follows Ocean's eyes as he selects a portrait
model from among four young men. Photographs of each man carry red
markings that indicate how the artist explores the special features
of each face, starting with the eyes and working through a rapid
series of short fixations, with as many as 140 fixations per
minute.
</P>
<P>
   When he begins sketching, however, Ocean's rhythm changes. As he
looks at the model, he focuses on a very specific place, which may
represent a single pencil line. He also glances from the paper to
the model about 12 times per minute, each fixation lasting about
one second. Thus, of the five hours that he spent completing the
drawing, one hour was spent looking at the model. In contrast,
nonartists look at the model in a far less methodical way.
</P>
<P>
   For the section ``The Hand Implements,'' where a movement sensor
measured the artist's hand in conjunction with the eye, Ocean was
given just 12 minutes to sketch a face, ``Luke 2.'' The exhibition
displays the finished drawing as well as another computer drawing
that shows every movement of his hand, on and off the paper. This
serves to confirm how Ocean frequently and repeatedly practices
each line just off the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my work, I'm after precision and I think detail is
precision,'' Ocean explained. ``Detail means where the line lands,
and if it lands a millimeter to the right or a millimeter to the
left, it changes the weight, in some way, or the shape that it is
describing. So when that line lands, you want it to land in the
right position, whatever that is.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Oxford University experiments were able to
quantify eye-hand coordination, it is the brain that links the eye
and the hand. And for the section ``The Brain Processes,''
Tchalenko and Ocean traveled to Stanford University in California,
where the artist's brain was scanned through a functional magnetic
resonance imaging technique. Specifically, while lying in the
scanner, he was given small sketchbooks and was asked to copy six
photographs of faces and six abstract shapes.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that the study came up with its most revelatory
results. The ``seeing'' process for everyone takes place in the
visual cortex at the back of the brain, which receives nerve
signals representing light captured in the retina. At the same
time, increased blood flows are evidence of increased brain
activity. In this exhibition, thanks to photographs of scanned
``slices'' of different brains, it is possible to see that, when
drawing a face, nonartists in the experiment used only the back of
the brain, while Ocean used mainly the frontal part of his brain.
And this, apparently, is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Humphrey, the real transformation was taking place in the
front, where you find emotion, previous faces, painting experience,
intentions and so on,'' Tchalenko explained. ``In essence, the
control subjects were simply trying to copy what they saw. But
Humphrey was creating an abstracted representation of each
photograph. He was thinking the portraits.''
</P>
<P>
   Tchalenko emphasized that this study was very limited in its
scope since it involved only one artist drawing black-and-white
portraits. Next he would like to study a painter as he mixes and
chooses colors as well as an abstract artist who is painting from
his imagination and not from a model. But he said it was difficult
to raise money for such projects. ``Science bodies think this is
art, and art bodies think this is science,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he thinks the results obtained so far already have
practical uses for other professions where eye-hand coordination is
critical, like surgery and air traffic control. ``Keyhole surgery
involves the same input-output as painting,'' he said. ``I'm sure
we can get to the stage where we can identity a particular
surgeon's eye pattern. It would then be possible to measure if,
say, he is tired. I think what we have demonstrated is that the
science and technology is already in place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
