<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      05-03 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPTOMETRIST AT BARNEY'S  
 SILVER-AND-GOLD DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A downtown optometrist, Selima Salaun, has taken up
residence at Barneys New York. So the store's hip customers can now
wear her prescription glasses with their Pradas, Yohjis, Manolos
and Kazukos.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salaun, who has optical stores in SoHo and the East Village
(plus a lingerie store called La Cosette and a trendy boutique
called Bond 07, both downtown), has installed Elena Rosen, one of
the optometrists on her staff, in a fourth-floor room at Barneys to
examine eyes by appointment and dispense prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Selima collection of eyeglass frames, plus others by Martine
Sitbon, Francis Klein, Kyoto and Moda, is ensconced in a corner of
the hosiery department on the main floor. There are frames
appropriate for men and women and even some for children. So you
can get matching mother-daughter or father-son frames.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been selling sunglasses,'' Judy Collinson, an executive
vice president of Barneys, said, ``and people were buying them to
put their own lenses in. So we thought we should add the extra
service. And we knew Selima was one of those fashion secrets that
Barneys customers would relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   Frames range from $150 to $450, and lenses from $90 to $400 (for
invisible grading). The lenses are ground in the SoHo store, so
delivery usually takes 48 hours, but longer for the graded ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers strolling on Madison Avenue in the last few months
may have noticed a shop called Lagos and assumed it was another
Greek jeweler selling imported wares. The jewelry even has that
opulent Old World look. But the owner and designer, Steven Lagos,
41, is an American from Philadelphia who has a workshop and store
in his hometown and always dreamed of a store in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The dream came true last November on the corner of 67th Street,
at No. 794, where the selling space is tiny but the windows large
enough to showcase the jewelry inside. Most of the pieces are
silver trimmed with gold and adorned with pearls or semiprecious
stones; the average price is $1,000. The styles are more classic
than modern, with beading, fluting and grillwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lion's share of my business is in silver-and-gold
combinations,'' Lagos said on a recent visit. ``We sold 90,000
units in silver and gold last year.'' In addition to his own stores
(there's a third one in the Bellagio hotel in Las Vegas), the Lagos
jewelry is sold at Neiman Marcus, Saks Fifth Avenue and some
independent jewelers.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos said he started making jewelry in the early 1970s, while
he was still in high school. ``The craft movement was happening,''
he remembered, ``and I started making spoon jewelry. I had a van
and went around selling it at flea markets. I became fascinated by
the idea of making things. A lot of hand work goes into the jewelry
today. There are 75 craftsmen working in my studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagos progressed from spoons to repairing jewelry and then to
designing. The silver-and-gold collection evolved in the mid-1980s
for Neiman's, which wanted to develop a bridge jewelry collection,
something that was between costume and fine jewelry. His first
store in Philadelphia opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our customers are real-jewelry customers,'' he said.
``They buy Lagos for fun, for travel, because it isn't as costly as
the good stuff they buy from Cartier or Van Cleef &AMP; Arpels.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did recently add some 22-karat gold-and-platinum jewelry
with diamonds that goes for as much as $40,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
