<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HALL-COX     05-03 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer could be 'major health problem' in Macedonian camps, Hall
warns
 &HT;    By By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After wandering through a mucky tent compound that
houses ethnic Albanians in Macedonia and Albania last weekend, a
group of House members returned to say they were awe-struck by the
scale of human suffering triggered by the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   And even as they expressed fear at the prospect of refugees
still living in tents when winter comes, they said they were
pleased by the optimism America's strained military still holds
about fulfilling its mission to drives Serb forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tony Hall (D-Dayton, Ohio) was the ranking Democrat on
the trip led by Majority Leader Richard Armey of Texas, which
returned Sunday night after visiting one refugee camp, two air
bases and NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a veteran of refugee camp visits around the world, said
conditions at the crowded camp in Skopje, Macedonia, were bad but
orderly. He said the U.S. must plan to spend more for humanitarian
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went because a million people are in misery,'' Hall said.
``A lot of people were talking about the winter, but they better
worry about the summer. It could be a major health problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said doctors at the site have begun seeing cases of
measles, and with seasonal temperatures rising, the camps could be
ideal places for waves of infectious disease such as cholera and
dysentery.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he'll offer an amendment to the $12.9 billion
emergency spending bill now working its way through Congress to
redirect some money so more is spent on immediate relief efforts.
In the bill, $195 million is budgeted directly for refugee
assistance, though additional money will go to border countries
such as Macedonia to help offset what they've spent so far.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall believes some economic assistance, such as the
rebuilding of infrastructure, can wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important,'' Hall said, ``but compared to a million
refugees it's not important right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, who last week voted against a resolution supporting the
air campaign, seemed moved by the sights and sounds and stories of
the 28,000 people in the refugee camp. He didn't specifically
endorse Hall's blunt assessment that the spending bill is
inadequate for humanitarian needs, but he understood the
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my understanding that we were fairly generous in the
(emergency spending bill) as it goes now for relief,'' Armey said.
``(But) I don't think anybody, any of us, could come away from
that, seeing that hardship, without feeling a sense that whatever
we're doing, we probably need to be doing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey also spoke most forcefully on the need ``to develop a
sense of urgency'' about the plight of these refugees if they're
still living in tents when winter returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why in the middle of a beautiful springtime it
hit me so hard, an awareness of what that winter would be like for
people,'' Armey said. ``I say it's imperative, I just don't think
they'll survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hall and Armey, joined by others from both parties, were
uniformly impressed with the morale of the U.S. military people
they met during their base visits. Armey said everyone he met
sensed some frustration over the political limits imposed on which
targets they can attack, but no one complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonetheless there was a broad sense of conviction, belief,
commitment to completing the objectives of this air war,'' Armey
said. ``And I sensed nobody that felt an incapability of doing
that, and the subsequent need for ground troops for the completion
of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
