<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3001 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXXON-APPEAL-SPI &LR;      05-03 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-APPEAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXXON TRIES TO GET $5 BILLION VALDEZ SPILL PENALTY SET ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Exxon Corp. mounted a multipronged legal offensive
here Monday, urging the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to set
aside the record $5 billion award to fishermen and others damaged
by the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   While saying Exxon ``deeply regrets'' the spill that fouled a
400-mile-long stretch of Alaska beaches, the company's attorney,
John Daum, argued that there are limits to the deep pockets of the
world's largest oil company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $3.5 billion in expenses Exxon incurred is clearly enough
to deter anybody from anything,'' argued Daum, a partner in the Los
Angeles law of O'Melveny and Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon has fought for five years the punitive damage award handed
down by an Alaskan jury. It has yet to pay anything to the
fishermen, business operators and Alaska natives who sued the oil
company. An estimated 40,000 people, some of them Seattle-based
fishermen, would potentially benefit from the award.
</P>
<P>
   But a three-member panel of federal appellate judges appeared
receptive to some of the company's appeals during Monday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The company claimed that it already has paid out $2.2 billion in
cleanup costs, more than $1 billion in civil settlements and
criminal fines, and dispersed $300 million to fishermen and fish
processors.
</P>
<P>
   Brian O'Neill, a Minneapolis lawyer who argued the plaintiffs'
case to the Anchorage jury, defended the jury's verdict before the
appeals court panel.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said the decision of jurors, who heard more than three
months' testimony on America's worst environmental disaster,
``should be treated with great deference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting a drinking alcoholic in charge of a supertanker is
inherently reckless conduct,'' O'Neill argued.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Capt. Joseph Hazelwood, who was drinking in
the hours before the Exxon Valdez departed the oilport of Valdez
and went off course to avoid floating ice. Hazelwood was in his
cabin and an inexperienced third officer was on the bridge when the
tanker hit Bligh Reef and discharged 11 million gallons of crude
oil into Alaska's pristine Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Punitive damages are designed to punish reckless behavior and,
by their severity, to deter future calamities that can cause
widespread harm.
</P>
<P>
   In the polite but cut-and-thrust environment of the federal
courtroom, a major issue argued was whether Exxon behaved
``recklessly'' _ as the jury found in awarding punitive damages _
or was guilty of the lesser offense of negligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon stipulated (in the trial) that Captain Hazelwood was
negligent in leaving the bridge,'' Daum said. ``We did not
stipulate anything to do with recklessness.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys were closely questioned by the two Republican
appointees on the appellate panel.
</P>
<P>
   The most skepticism of the plaintiffs' case was voiced by Judge
Charles Wiggins. A former California congressman, Wiggins gained
brief national attention 25 years ago as President Richard Nixon's
chief defender in House Judiciary Committee impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins peppered O'Neill with questions about whether
Hazelwood's drinking was a direct cause of the accident. If
recklessness can't be established, Exxon doesn't owe ``a damned
cent'' in punitive damages, he remarked.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Wiggins jokingly asked whether the Exxon Valdez
was better off, given the captain's drinking, in not having
Hazelwood on the bridge. An uncomfortable O'Neill was left to argue
that a drunken Hazelwood would have performed better on the bridge
than his inexperienced third mate, Gregory Cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the judges' questions, Exxon effectively raised issues
before the appellate panel.
</P>
<P>
   Daum seemed to strike a chord with Wiggins in arguing that the
$5 billion judgment was excessive, in his words, ``200 times the
highest award ever upheld by an appellate court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is dominated by the overwhelming settlement,''
Wiggins later told O'Neill. ``That assumes liability. I am not sure
you have identified liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Andrew Kleinfeld of Fairbanks, an appointee of President
Bush, asked meticulous questions of both sides. But he appeared to
respond to Exxon's argument that a $5 billion settlement is not
necessary to deter future accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they break a tanker on rocks, they lose $25 million worth
of oil, plus the break in the tanker, plus they have $2 billion in
cleanup expenses: Why is that not enough to make them more
careful?'' asked Kleinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill replied that all the risks and potential spill costs did
not stop Exxon from running tankers captained by alcoholics, with
tired and overworked crews.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime judge appointed to the 9th Circuit by President
Kennedy in 1961, Judge James Browning kept his counsel over the
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel also heard arguments over the so-called
``Seattle Seven,'' a consortium of seven Seattle seafood processors
who made a backdoor deal with Exxon at the onset of the damage
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Seven were paid $70 million in damages. They
remained plaintiffs, however, and secretly agreed to hand over to
Exxon their share of the final damage award in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Russell Holland, who presided at the
trial in Alaska, later decried the agreement, which was not
disclosed to the court or jury, as ``pernicious'' and ``an
astonishing ruse.'' He refused to let the seafood processors
participate in any punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   But Daum argued Monday that the deal should be reinstated. It
was good not only for the seafood processors and Exxon, but ``good
for society'' and ``good for the courts,'' he said. ``Public policy
favors settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Exxon lawyer added that such pre-trial agreements are
usually not disclosed. Kleinfeld disagreed. ``In my experience,
they're usually disclosed in discovery,'' he said, referring to the
evidence gathering that goes on before a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon also called for a new trial based on the arguement that
one of the Anchorage jurors was harassed into agreeing to the
amount of punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was the conduct of a bailiff who, during deliberations,
pulled his pistol out of its holster, held out a bullet, and
suggested to a juror that the jury member holding out against
punitive damages ``be put out of her misery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In any criminal case, in any ordinary civil case, a new trial
would have been granted without question,'' Daum argued. He said
the incident threatens ``the integrity of the jury process in
general.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kleinfeld noted that the bailiff's ``stupid comment'' was
taken as a joke by the juror to which it was made. The holdout
juror never learned of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anyone actually believe he was going to kill the juror?''
asked Kleinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted that the bailiff was caught, fired and later
died of a heart attack. ``That ought to be a deterrent,'' he told
Daum.
</P>
<P>
   The Exxon damages trial lasted through the summer of 1984, and
was followed by 23 days of deliberation in which the jury decided
on damages. ``When trials get really long, crazy things happen,''
said Kleinfeld.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
