<HEADER>
A3002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-ERXLEBEN-TRIAL-CO     05-03 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ERXLEBEN-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $3 million settlement expected in fraud suit
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Football star turned foreign currency trader
Russell Erxleben agreed Monday to settle a civil lawsuit filed by
10 investors who claim Erxleben defrauded them of $1 million
through his now-defunct foreign currency trading company.
</P>
<P>
   If the settlement is approved today by District Court Judge Paul
Davis, a judgment of $3 million could be entered against the former
star kicker for the University of Texas Longhorns, attorneys said
Monday. The $3 million figure would include actual and punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the plaintiffs can collect on the judgment remains to be
seen. Erxleben's lawyers say he doesn't have any of the money taken
in by his trading company, Austin Forex International.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Forex closed its doors Sept. 11 after taking in $50
million from about 800 investors.
</P>
<P>
   The suit by the investors is one of several filed against
Erxleben and Austin Forex in the wake of the company's collapse. It
was the first case to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal regulators also have been investigating the
company and Erxleben for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Erxleben has denied any wrongdoing, attributing the lost
millions to trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's settlement offer was made by Erxleben's lawyer, John
Stratton. Robert Goldsmith, attorney for the plaintiffs, told the
judge that the lawyers would either present a written settlement
agreement to the court this morning or resume the trial, in which
Erxleben is accused of fraud, breach of fiduciary trust and
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $50 million invested in Erxleben's company, less than
$400,000 in cash remains, testified Janet Mortenson, the
court-appointed receiver to Austin Forex.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Forex was in business for about one year, and it
attracted large and small investors. The company pooled investors'
money and proposed to make foreign currency investments with them.
</P>
<P>
   But Mortenson estimated that $17 million coming from later
investors was used to repay early investors. Austin Forex,
Mortenson said, was a fraudulent ``Ponzi scheme'' in which early
investors were repaid with money from later investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared to me that Austin Forex had no sources of money
other than investors' money,'' Mortenson said, ``so any funds paid
to investors came from other investors.''
</P>
<P>
   The receiver said Erxleben was uncooperative in helping her sort
out what happened to all the money.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Orr, one of Erxleben's lawyers, said his client doesn't
have any of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Erxleben lost the money in trading,'' Orr said in an
interview. ``He did not put money in his pocket. He does not have a
hidden fund of cash. He just made a lot of bad trades and lost the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Erxleben appeared in court at the start of the trial but left
soon after. He would have been required to take the stand and
testify later in the case, Davis ruled Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will reach an agreement,'' said John Gilmore,
one of the investors. ``Otherwise, we will resume the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The other plaintiffs in the case are Wayne McMichael, James
Foster, Louis Hill, Karen Dougherty, Gennelle Rutland, Katherine
Holcomb, Billy Holcomb, William Beck and Francis Reissig.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Ladendorf writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
