<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXCUTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush is reported willing to call tax cuts session
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who's delayed a final
decision about running for president until the legislative session
ends, is willing to call a special session to get approval for $2
billion in tax cuts, several lawmakers told the Austin
American-Statesman Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Holding two fingers less than an inch apart, one lawmaker said,
``We're this close to a special session.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lawmaker said the governor has said, ``My front porch
strategy is working well enough that I may as well stay here for
the summer.'' The lawmaker couldn't say whether Bush was making a
threat or a simple comment.
</P>
<P>
   None of the sources wanted to be identified because of ongoing
discussions, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Though not officially a candidate, Bush is an early front-runner
for president.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has declared that he won't leave Texas to campaign
during the legislative session, which ends May 31. A special
session presumably could delay Bush's campaigning even longer.
</P>
<P>
   The early polls, however, aren't all good news for the governor.
In one, few Texans could name any Bush accomplishments as governor.
In a New Hampshire poll, Bush's popularity fell when the names of
potential candidates were replaced with biographical descriptions.
Those findings could mean Bush needs to score a major victory this
session.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the governor has indicated a willingness to call a
special session, Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said, ``Not that I
am aware of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes we have ample time to enact significant
tax cuts and education reform between now and May 31,'' McClellan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas governors can call special sessions for up to 30 days and
can set the agenda. An agenda regarding education spending or tax
cuts, however, would be broad topics under which lawmakers could
consider a host of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already approved a bill that supporters say cuts
property taxes by $1 billion. The bill also would raise the minimum
teacher salary schedule by $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, has questioned the
level of tax cuts in the Senate bill. Sadler, chairman of the House
Public Education Committee, has offered an alternative with $500
million in property tax cuts and more than $3 billion for teachers'
pay and increased school spending. The issue is expected to be
debated in the education committee this week.
</P>
<P>
   Other tax cuts, including some for businesses and some for
consumers, have passed the Senate and are likely to start being
considered by the full House next week.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other issues, Bush put tax cuts and teachers'
compensation at the top of his agenda this year. He originally
called for $2 billion in property tax cuts, $307 million in
business tax cuts and $330 million in sales tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's proposed state budget has room for about $1.5
billion in overall tax cuts and the House's version of the state
budget has room for $3 billion in new education spending and tax
cuts and another $700 million available for other things, like
sales and business tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   According to one of the sources, Bush now wants $2 billion in
total tax cuts. Told that he could get $1.5 billion, the governor
said he was willing to wait for $2 billion, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the sources took Bush's comments as threats or a line in
the sand. Instead, they said Bush appeared to be making clear that
his potential presidential bid could wait beyond May 31. One source
said Bush's comments were made in a joking manner. But another
disagreed, saying Bush appeared serious, but not threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers said if Bush talked about a special session,
it was likely just an opening to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has a press conference and says here's what we get or
else there's a special session, then there's a line in the dirt,''
said lobbyist Chuck McDonald, who was an aide to former Gov. Ann
Richards. She went through three special sessions, including the
last one in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said he doubts the governor is seriously considering a
special session because he can claim victory now. And Democrats,
McDonald said, should be wary of trying to push Bush into a special
session where he could be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not accurate to say Democrats don't have anything to
lose,'' he said. ``They could lose all the concessions they've
gotten up to now.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the Senate forced changes resulting in more money
for teachers and less for property tax cuts before the bill was
sent to the House. They also broadened business tax cut proposals
to help inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   Another source, who asked not to be named, said a special
session has potential benefits and drawbacks for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plus side is that he's a man of principle fighting for
what he believes in,'' the source said. ``If he gets (the tax cuts
he wants) or close, it shows strong leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is that it indicates he's having a tussle _ a
fight _ with the Legislature. It could delay or slow down his
(presidential) campaign effort. And, if he gets a third or a half
of what he wants, why wasn't that good enough in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
