</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KANSAS-STATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions face K-State offense after heavy turnover
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A year ago, with mercurial quarterback Michael
Bishop running and passing, the Kansas State Wildcats led the
nation in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the Wildcats, short eight starters from a unit that
averaged 48.0 points a game, are producing something else with
near-equal proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   While the defense is plugging in three new starters and expects
to be at least as strong as last year's unit, which ranked in the
NCAA Division I-A's top 10 in all four major statistical
categories, the offense enters the fall with question marks at
several key positions.
</P>
<P>
   _Quarterback. Bishop had a hand in 37 of the Wildcats' 65
offensive touchdowns, and his big-play potential either by running
or passing (12 TD passes of at least 25 yards). Jonathan Beasley, a
junior who redshirted last year after lettering in 1996 and '97, is
probably a slightly better passer than Bishop but not as explosive
of a runner. He was unable to seize the job in the spring because
of a hand injury, but neither Adam Helm or sophomore Jeremy Milne
was able to make a run at the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to get better,'' said Coach Bill Snyder. ``I think
they haven't expressed a consistency that you would like to have.
There are certain things about their games that just need time and
effort and focus on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   _Offensive line. Only two starters _ center Randall Cummins and
left tackle Milford Stephenson _ are back, and a third player who
had six starts at right tackle, Thomas Barnett, left the team in
the spring and may not return. Cummins missed nearly all of the
spring with a leg injury and Stephenson replaced him, but
Stephenson will likely be a utility linemen in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches like what they've seen from left tackle Chris
Bailes, a redshirt freshman, but starting defensive tackle Damien
McIntosh, a second-team all-conference pick last fall, worked on
offense in the spring and may switch positions.
</P>
<P>
   _Running back. Starting halfback Eric Hickson is gone and will
be replaced by a pair of explosive backups. Frank Murphy, who
missed four games last year because he violated NCAA rules by
receiving a car from a booster, is back and promises big things. In
the spring game he carried 21 times for 89 yards but also fumbled,
something he did all too frequently a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who has great speed, also saw time at receiver in the
spring, but he concentrated on running back after projected
starting halfback David Allen, who returned four punts for scores
last season, was injured.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting addition is junior-college transfer Joe Hall, who
is 6-2, 265 pounds. He has said he wants a shot at halfback,
despite having the size that would seem to make him a better fit at
fullback.
</P>
<P>
   _Receiver. Aaron Lockett returns after making honorable-mention
All-Big 12 as a freshman and will be the go-to guy. Sophomore
Brandon Clark (6-3, 220) and junior-college transfer Quincy Morgan
(6-2, 205), who redshirted last season after playing a year with
Bishop at Blinn College, are both big targets who can run.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
