<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-1STLD-WR     05-03 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS WITH RUSSIAN ENVOY, SAYS BOMBING WILL CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 7th graph to add full name and correct time element)  (See also KOSOVO-NATO) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton held an extended discussion
Monday with the Russian special envoy for the Balkans, but the
White House remained pessimistic about the prospect of a deal
anytime soon to end the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials expressed gratitude for Russian efforts to
broker a peace, but said the bombardment of Yugoslavia would
continue unabated until President Slobodan Milosevic bends to
allied demands.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy, for 90
minutes at the White House late Monday afternoon, and then briefly
with the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who secured the freedom last weekend
of three American servicemen held in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said after his meeting with the president that he
had brought a plan from Moscow and Belgrade for ending the Balkan
conflict, but did not provide details. He said that he and Clinton
had discussed the terms under which NATO would halt its air attacks
on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got closer to a diplomatic solution,'' Chernomyrdin said.
However, he added, ``This process requires a very detailed
negotiation, discussion. There can be no uncertainty because the
stakes are very high.''
</P>
<P>
   But American officials said that Milosevic appeared no closer to
accepting allied terms for ending the fighting despite six hours of
talks with Chernomyrdin last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect these discussions will continue for days and weeks,''
Samuel R. Berger, the White House national security adviser, said
at a briefing Monday evening. ``It won't result in some magical
breakthrough in the next nanosecond.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the Russians were useful as an intermediary between
NATO and Belgrade, a historical ally of Moscow. He said he believed
that ``the Russian position is closer to ours than Milosevic's
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin continued the talks into the late evening with Vice
President Al Gore and a small group of administration officials at
the vice president's residence. The two have worked together on
U.S.-Russian relations since 1993 and have spoken frequently on the
crisis in the Balkans since the allied air campaign began on March
24.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference on Monday afternoon before his meetings
with Chernomyrdin and Jackson, the president brushed aside calls
for a pause in the bombing in response to the release of the
soldiers and other apparent overtures in recent days by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there would be no allied halt in hostilities until
the Serbian ethnic and religious cleansing of Kosovo ceases and the
1.5 million ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo are allowed to
return in safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the president also seemed to provide at least a small
opening for progress on the diplomatic front, saying that he would
consider a bombing pause ``if it's clear that it will be in aid of
that larger purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty to talk about,'' Clinton said of the Russian
initiative to bring an end to the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the composition of a post-war peacekeeping force
was open to negotiation. Last week, Milosevic said in an interview
that he would accept a lightly armed foreign presence in Kosovo,
staffed by non-NATO countries like Russia. While NATO has set out
conditions that would include an armed force with NATO at its core,
Clinton said Monday that such a force could include non-NATO
members including Russia, Ukraine, even Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Administration aides said that political arrangements for Kosovo
could be discussed with Belgrade once the shooting stops.
</P>
<P>
   The president also offered a somewhat softer formulation of
other conditions NATO is demanding as the price for ending the
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the bombing of Yugoslavia could end if there
were ``clear and unambiguous evidence that a withdrawal is
underway,'' a more moderate variation on previous demands for
withdrawal of all Serbian army and police forces from the province
of Kosovo on a ``precise and rapid timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, the national security adviser, said that Clinton did not
intend to signal any change in NATO conditions for ending the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a new position,'' Berger said. ``That answer has
been given 50 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was attempting to navigate a narrow passage between
resolve on allied war aims and flexibility on terms for ending the
conflict, as calls for a negotiated ceasefire grow and divisions on
the war deepen in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting with the president, Jackson said, ``We must seize
this moment to take the step to dramatic diplomacy from bloody,
protracted war.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kofi Annan, the secretary-general of the United Nations, said in
New York Monday night after returning from Europe that there was no
immediate prospect of peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he welcomed the release of the American prisoners,
but warned, ``We still have a lot of work to do on the political
and the diplomatic front before I can say that we are on the verge
of a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan met late last week with German and Russian leaders,
including Chernomyrdin, but returned to New York with no concrete
proposals for ending the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything,'' he said, ``the trip to Moscow and Berlin has
reconfirmed my belief that we should do whatever we can to find a
political solution because the implications of the alternative are
too frightening to contemplate.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The success of Jackson's free-lance mission to Belgrade to win
freedom for the prisoners, along with a 213-213 vote in the House
on a resolution in support of the allied air campaign last week,
have noticeably changed the climate in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Monday deferred action on a bipartisan resolution
calling on the president to use ground forces, if necessary, to win
the war in the Balkans. The resolution appeared doomed by
opposition from Senate leaders, who appeared more eager for a
negotiated settlement than victory on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's conduct of the campaign has been questioned from the
beginning. But now that six weeks of bombing have failed to reverse
the wretched exodus from Kosovo, the calls for a quick diplomatic
deal to end the bloodshed are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton welcomed the release of the American prisoners, who were
undergoing medical testing at an American military hospital in
Germany on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the president said that their release alone was not
sufficient to end the allied air attacks. The two things are
``completely separate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are very thankful for their release, let me be clear
why the military operations must continue,'' Clinton said. ``Three
Americans are home. Their families, their friends and the American
people, whom they have served faithfully, must be grateful. But
nearly one and a half million Kosovars are not home. When will
these people see their homes again, with the safety and rights Mr.
Milosevic has often pledged, but never delivered?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted he was not seeking ``total victory'' over
Serbia and said he was conducting the war reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not relish every night sending young Americans and our
NATO allies up in planes flying very fast under very hazardous
circumstances in which their safety is at risk,'' the president
said. ``I do not relish the continuing burdens on the people of
Albania and Macedonia. I am eager to get the Kosovars out of the
camps and on their way back home and rebuilding. I do not relish
the thought that inevitably some of those bombs will go astray and
some Serbian civilians, or some Kosovar civilians, could be
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``I am not trying to drag this out. But I am
determined to pursue our policy until we know that we have a chance
to do what has to be done in order for this to work as a practical
matter, and in order finally, to, clearly and unambiguously,
reverse the policy of ethnic and religious cleansing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
