<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIATION-WARNING-NYT     05-03 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIATION-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP WARNS OF LIKELY RADIATION DANGER AT OLD BOMB FACTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Tenn., Md.) (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department, which has been raising money
for its costly environmental cleanup of old bomb factories by
leasing them to commercial tenants, may be exposing ordinary
factory workers to excessive radiation, an environmental group
says.
</P>
<P>
   At the site in Oak Ridge, Tenn., where the department once
processed uranium for nuclear weapons, manufacturers of machine
tools, cardboard boxes and other products pay reduced rent or
barter for space by cleaning up the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The department argues that the program saves tax dollars and
accelerates the cleanup of a 50-year legacy of bomb making. Robert
De Grasse, director of the office of worker and community
transition, said the department was trying to achieve the safety
levels set by the Environmental Protection Agency for re-use of
Superfund sites, a category that includes Oak Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in trying to protect workers that come on to our
sites,'' De Grasse said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Institute for Energy and Environmental Research, a
longtime critic of the Energy Department's environmental
stewardship, contends, however, that the department is inadequately
monitoring the workers' exposure to radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to go down the road of creating a new generation
of exposed workers, without knowing whether they are members of the
general public, or radiation workers?'' said Arjun Makhijani,
president of the institute, which is based in Takoma Park, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Environmental Protection Agency say they are
also concerned about worker safety at the site, now called the East
Tennessee Technology Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that we do not know if workers are at risk or
not,'' said John B. Blevins, an Oak Ridge Project Manager for the
environmental agency. ``There is not enough information that DOE
has provided to EPA to make a determination either way. In that
situation, we think it's not prudent to continue to lease until we
can insure that they're protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup work could be creating airborne contamination, Blevins
said, and some radiological and chemical hazards left from nuclear
operations may not have been cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's report said that in one building, cleanup
workers in protective clothing were scraping concrete while
employees of tenants worked nearby in ordinary work clothes. The
building is mostly one giant room, with a 35-foot-high ceiling,
divided into sections by chain-link fences. Energy Department
officials say they monitor air conditions when cleaner workers chip
at concrete.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over worker safety dates from 1996, when leasing
started; about 23 companies now employ about 200 workers at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department has set an exposure limit for the workers
equal to exposure for workers in the bomb factory, or 5 rem per
year of radiation. That is about 13 times the amount of radiation
that the average American receives from all sources, natural and
man-made. The department says actual exposures are a tiny fraction
of that amount, but its limit is 200 times the level that the
Environmental Protection Agency has established for nuclear
industries' exposure of members of the general public, 25 millirem
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants at the Oak Ridge site say they are happy. Mike Walker,
president of Dienamic Tooling Systems, which employs 15 people in a
27,000-square-foot space, said of the Energy Department, ``any time
they have removed concrete, or done anything that has potential for
things to be moved in air, they always have air monitoring
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The department gave his employees instruction in radiation and
held a long question-and-answer session, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Logixx Automation, Inc., another machine tool company, moved to
Oak Ridge to take advantage of surplus equipment, including gantry
cranes that can handle 31 tons, and space at $1 a square foot. B.J.
Lipari, the company's president, said radiation exposure was lower
at Oak Ridge than in the company's old location, in Golden, Colo.,
where natural background levels are higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
