<HEADLINE>
TAB FOR GRADUATION GIFTS RUNS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALISSON CLARK   
 Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Forget the personalized pen-and-pencil set _
this year's college graduates are hoping for trips, cars, computers
and, most of all, cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is the hot ticket right now,'' said Gil Sanchez, a
University of Florida political science student who graduated
Saturday. ``We're in a transitional period, between finding a job
and going to grad school, and we need emergency money to pay the
bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez plans to use most of his graduation money to take care
of his debts and buy a suit, then enjoy what's left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent to pay off bills, the other percent for fun
stuff _ that's kind of the graduate rationale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marlen Kroll, an English major, will put his graduation money
toward a summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking a road trip to Toronto for two weeks, so I'm hoping
to get some money to finance that,'' he said. ``Some people want
the titles to their cars that their parents own, or for them to
take care of their credit card bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Etzkin has his sights set on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it through five years of college without a computer,
which is pretty funny since I'm getting a degree in electrical and
computer engineering,'' he said. ``I just used my roommates or went
to the lab. But it would be really nice to have something that
would last me a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Etzkin said his friends are asking for equally practical gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are having their diploma framed, or getting a briefcase.
But I have one friend who I'm kind of jealous of who's getting a
trip to Europe _ that's pretty awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuan Tran, a zoology major, said he doesn't really need anything
for graduation, but his friends have bigger ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my friends are saying they want to get a car, but I
think they're just dreaming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Dave Daniels, an accounting major who hinted to his
parents that life as a pedestrian was getting kind of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got me an '88 Volvo,'' he said. ``It's a lot better than
my bike.''
</P>
<P>
   Food science and human nutrition major Leigh Ann Gordon and her
brother, a senior at the University of South Florida, are sharing
the same graduation gift _ a trip to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both major nature buffs,'' she said. ``I was going to go
to Europe, but then my parents said they'd take us with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anneliese Doyle, an English and women's studies major, is hoping
to get some money for a professional wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need some clothes I might look presentable in,'' she said.
Her boyfriend had a different idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting power tools from his father. I guess he figured
he's getting older now and he ought to have his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoology and women's studies major Marisa Roberts is also
stocking up on grown-up items, with an eye toward filling an empty
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting furniture from my dad. That's all I know about,''
she said. ``I guess the ideal would be a car _ everyone wants a new
car. Or a new home, or paying for a master's program.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from the modest three-initial chrome pen, but
the Cross pen and pencil sets _ which sell for $80 for a boxed set
to $200 for a desk set in a marble stand _ are still popular with
graduation traditionalists, said Karen Robbins of Central Florida
Office Plus, an office supply store in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just this week I've sold three or four sets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
