u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAA-BLACK-BOXES-550&AMP;A     05-03 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-BLACK-BOXES-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA CALLS FOR EXPANDING BLACK BOX CAPACITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ The Federal Aviation Administration is calling
for new ``black boxes'' on thousands of airplanes over the next
five and a half years, including replacing the standard 30-minute
cockpit voice recorders with models that capture two hours of
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes, prompted by shortcomings made obvious by
the crash last September of Swissair 111, an MD-111 brought down by
a fire near Halifax, Nova Scotia, were announced Monday by Jane
Garvey, the agency administrator, near the start of a three-day
international symposium here on crash recorders. Experts here said
that every form of travel could be safer if advanced black boxes
were carried by planes and trains, which have some form of data
recording now, and trucks and even cars.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium was run by the National Transportation Safety
Board, which has been urgently seeking the changes. Ms. Garvey said
her agency would also accept another safety board recommendation,
that older Boeing 737s, which have what board officials repeatedly
referred to as ``primitive'' flight data recorders, be upgraded by
August 2000. The FAA had given the airlines until August 2001; now
it says that upgrades that record the function of the rudder must
be completed a year sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The board has been seeking better flight data recorders on the
737 since the crash of USAir 427, in September 1994, which took
more than four years to solve. But FAA officials had previously
said that an August 2000 deadline would require that planes be
grounded for the upgrade, because not enough time remained to fit
the work into existing maintenance schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garvey said Monday that the schedule was ``very
aggressive,'' but that it could be adhered to. She also promised
special consideration for the one airline that took extensive
action before any requirement was formulated: Southwest Airlines,
which flies only 737s, voluntarily upgraded its flight data
recorders.
</P>
<P>
   All commercial planes made after 2002 would have new recorders
entirely, under the recommendations endorsed by Ms. Garvey. Those
planes would have two, each a combination flight data recorder and
cockpit voice recorder, to improve the chance that at least one
would survive.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation would require an independent 10-minute power
supply to enable recording to continue even if a plane's electrical
system stopped working. That would mean the end of recorders that
use a tape loop, board officials say, in favor of those that record
sound digitally. These recorders use only about 10 watts of power,
compared with 30 or 40 watts for a tape recorder. Another advantage
is that the memory chips are more likely than tape to survive a
crash.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash of TWA 800, which exploded off Long Island in
1996, investigators said that another tenth of a second of time on
the voice recorder might have given them far more data about what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recorders have proved their worth over the decades as probably
the single most effective investigative tool we have,'' said James
E. Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, who
credited black boxes with helping reduce the accident rate in
aviation to .0002 per million miles flown last year, which was
one-sixtieth the fatal accident rate in 1960.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Trains carry ``event recorders'' and some ships carry ``voyage
recorders,'' but, Hall pointed out, ``The one mode where recorders
have not yet had an impact is highway accident investigations,
where more than 90 percent of all the accident fatalities occur.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors has equipped 30 million cars with such recorders,
and other manufacturers have also equipped some vehicles, but
investigators have not been given the tools to extract the data
after a crash. Car manufacturers use the recorders when
investigating crashes in which the air bag deployed.
</P>
<P>
   In aviation, the newest planes have recorders that can give
stunning results, safety experts said. Hall said that in 1996, the
crashes of two Boeing 757s in deep water, one near Peru and the
other near the Dominican Republic, were solved quickly, without the
need to recover much of the wreckage, because of their advanced
flight data recorders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
