<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-RUSHDIE-2TAKES-     05-03 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RUSHDIE-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSHDIE ROCKS ON: HIS LATEST NOVEL HELPS PUT THE PAST BEHIND HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KIPEN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ `The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' begins on the day
Salman Rushdie's old life ended, with a fictional earthquake on
Valentine's Day 1989 _ the same day the author learned that the
dying Iranian leader Ayatollah Khomeini had put out a contract on
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably, of everything in the book, the thing I was
most uncertain about, whether to use that date or not,'' Rushdie
says, discussing his latest novel with The Chronicle while in town
for the American Booksellers Association convention. ``And really,
right up to the book going to the printer, the publishers kept
saying, `Well, make up your mind.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end I left it in, partly because I thought, well, if
I'm starting a book about a cataclysm in someone's life, everyone
is going to make the association anyway. The other reason, the
reason I really left it in, was because I felt it would give the
date another meaning for me. Instead of just having this terrible,
dark anniversary, now it's also the date my novel begins. That's a
good enough reason for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, the bounty on Rushdie's head _ like the hair on
it _ appears to be all but gone.
</P>
<P>
   For a man regularly demonized in certain quarters over the
years, Rushdie looks strangely like an imp: forked beard,
mischievous smile, dark blazer over what looks like a gray Gap
T-shirt, and a pair of baggy pants _ well befitting one of
contemporary English literature's premier vaudevillians. Also a
pair of sunglasses, worn indoors and prompting the now-familiar
question about his safety in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that stuff is much easier now, and the only reason
there is any degree of security here'' _ he indicates the pleasant,
beefy gentleman just outside, and the limousine whose doors require
all one's weight just to push them closed _ ``is that I didn't want
the LAPD to start making a big number out of it. The main reason is
to pacify the local security forces so they don't overreact. But
it's all coming back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those other assassins, the critics, reviews of the new
book, currently No. 2 on The Chronicle Best-Sellers list, have been
wildly mixed. What's unusual is that many writers have praised or
pilloried it for the same reason: its massive erudition, the
tremendously wide _ some say scattershot _ range of its references
to culture high and low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' is a love story about two
fictional musicians whose partnership spans almost the whole
history of rock 'n' roll, overdubbed with impassioned, funny
meditations on music, mythology, history, exile and a medley of
other themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an odd thing these days,'' Rushdie says, ``that writers
can be criticized for knowing things. I mean, to criticize someone
for ignorance is one thing, but to criticize someone for knowing
something is odd. I use whatever materials come to hand to create
as rich a world as I can create, just as, as a reader, those are
the books I like to inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   ``... The way I've always thought of it, at least for myself, is
if you build a big car, then put a big engine in it. The big engine
is always narrative. If you can begin to tell people a story that
involves them, interests them, moves them, you can do almost
anything else and they will let you.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as splicing rock lyrics into the rarefied confines of a
literary novel. One song in ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' will
appear on U2's next album, a prospect all the more pleasing to
Rushdie because, as he admits with a wink, ``I'm happy to say that
the lyricist owns half the song.''
</P>
<P>
   Invited to mix an imaginary party tape for his readers, Rushdie
quickly warms to the topic:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no escaping Elvis,'' he begins. ``I love the lyric of
`All Shook Up.' It's very funny. `Itchy as a man on a fuzzy tree.'
It's a fantastic line. `My friends say I'm acting queer as a pup' _
these are very strange lines. I know it's there to rhyme with `up,'
but nevertheless. ... And I might choose `Tutti Frutti,' `He's So
Fine,' `Leader of the Pack.' Then there's the meat of when I was
really a teenager and in my early 20s: ``Good Vibrations.''
``Surfin' USA,'' ``Surfin' Safari,'' ``Little Old Lady From
Pasadena.'' I was just in Pasadena this morning, and I was
thinking, `Go granny, go granny, go granny go.'''
</P>
<P>
   The case could be made that Rushdie's ``Satanic Verses'' was a
novel about theater, his ``The Moor's Last Sigh'' a novel about
painting, and now, with ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet,'' he's
written about rock 'n' roll. The obvious question, for a writer so
besotted with film that ``The Satanic Verses'' ends with a
shameless steal from ``The Manchurian Candidate,'' is when we will
finally get Rushdie's Hollywood novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only a matter of time,'' Rushdie allows, ``given
someone who is as keen on movies as me. As for the next book, I'm
suffering from an embarrassment of riches. I have an idea which is
a kind of futuristic thriller. I have an idea for a historical
story set in Renaissance Florence. History was my subject, and so
many people were there at the same time _ Botticelli, Machiavelli,
Savonarola. It's an amazing period. Then there's another voice in
my head which says that after a book as long and elaborate and
baroque as this, what would please me most would be to do something
very stripped down, very spare, very lean, and I have an idea for
that as well, which is what I suspect is what I'm actually going to
do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd also like to be faster. I have sort of a feeling that I'm
52, and how much longer is there? If I spend four or five years
writing a book, how many more years have I got? Not enough. So
maybe that will speed me up _ urgency. The ticking of a clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bombs anymore, just clocks. Yes, Rushdie knows his days are
numbered _ but maybe, finally, God willing, no more than anyone's.
Does he ever think about what direction his life might have taken
if Khomeini had gone into the dry-cleaning business?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things you are taught when studying history
is never ask the question `What if?' Because what happens is
already hard enough. I guess less people would know who I was, but
those people who knew would know my name for the right reasons. It
was a strange fate to become famous for the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I really have no idea what we'd be sitting here talking
about, if we'd be sitting here talking about anything, had it not
been for what happened. It's just one of the things that happened
in my life, and writers' lives aren't usually as interesting as
this. I hope my life gets less interesting from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
