<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-DIAMONDBACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cameron helps Reds regain winning feeling
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Mike Cameron, oh-for-Atlanta over the weekend and
oh-for-2 Monday night, picked a perfect time to end the
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron drove a bases-loaded single off the right field wall
with one out in the ninth inning, ending the game dramatically and
providing the Cincinnati Reds with a 4-3 victory over the Arizona
Diamondbacks in front of a comfortable gathering of 13,943 in
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Boone started it with a perfect first-pitch bunt for a hit
up the third base line and Pokey Reese bunted him to second.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks walked pinch-hitter Mark Sweeney intentionally,
then relief pitcher Darren Holmes walked pinch-hitter Hal Morris on
four pitches to load the bases for Cameron, who delivered on a
1-and-0 count.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Steve Parris, summoned from Triple-A Indianapolis
as a stand-in starter for demoted and punished Brett Tomko, gave
the Reds exactly what they asked _ 5 1/3 innings, three runs, five
hits, three walks and a strikeout, turning over a 3-3 tie to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Dennys Reyes, Scott Sullivan and Scott Williamson strung zeros
across the board to keep the score in place until something could
be done to alleviate the situation, which Cameron obliged.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon, searching frantically for a lineup with
some hits in it, shuffled the deck _ dropping Mike Cameron from the
leadoff spot to No. 2 and elevating Michael Tucker to leadoff, plus
dropping slump-shrouded Barry Larkin to No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else am I going to do?'' McKeon said. ``I'm just changing
it up, mixing it up. I'm putting two speed guys on top with Sean
Casey (third) behind them for a left-right-left look. We'll do this
a day or so, see if it gets us going. . .see if we can put three or
four hits together.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't put three or four hits together in the first inning
against Andy Benes, but Benes helped with a pair of walks and
Larkin produced from the No. 6 spot for three runs.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Mike Cameron walked, Casey singled and Vaughn
walked, filling the bases. Cameron scored while Eddie Taubensee
grounded to first and Larkin drove a two-run single up the middle
for two more.
</P>
<P>
   Parris walked pitcher Benes to start the third and it cost him a
run. Benes took third on Tony Womack's single and scored on Jay
Bell's sacrifice fly, a well-smote ball that center fielder Cameron
flagged with a lunging stretch after a long spring.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Stinnett was Arizona's catcher when the lineups were
circulated, but he was scratched with flu-like symptoms and
replaced by Damian Miller, who just happened to be 2 for 3 career
against Parris.
</P>
<P>
   Make it 4 for 5. Miller singled in the second, then tied the
game in the fourth with a two-run homer behind Steve Finley's
triple.
</P>
<P>
   When Parris issued a one-out walk in the sixth, his night was
done and McKeon used Reyes and Sullivan to finish the inning and
leave it 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds put up a mild threat against relief pitcher and former
Red Greg Swindell in the seventh when Pokey Reese singled and
pinch-hitter Mark Lewis bunted him to second. Pinch-hitter Jeffrey
Hammonds took a called third strike, Cameron popped foul to the
catcher, end of mild uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Mild Uprising II surfaced in the eighth when Casey led with a
single, but it, too, died ingloriously. Vaughn flied to right,
stranding his third runner of the night, Taubensee lobbed to left
and Larkin popped to center as the Reds traveled eight innings
without putting together back-to-back hits.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
