<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-ASSETS-FREED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FREES ASSETS OF SUSPECT IN EMBASSY TERROR BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Treasury Department on Monday unblocked more
than $24 million in bank accounts held by Salih Idris, the Saudi
owner of a pharmaceutical plant in Sudan that American cruise
missiles destroyed last August after the terror bombings at
American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago the government blocked Idris' assets, after
intelligence reports linked Idris to Osama bin Laden, the Islamic
militant leader who authorities believed inspired the Africa
bombings, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Idris' lawyers, who had sued the government to unblock the
accounts, said that Monday's action was a tacit acknowledgment that
the investigation into the Africa bombings had failed to
substantiate that Idris was connected to the bin Laden terrorist
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's order, lifting all restrictions on the Bank of America
accounts, also effectively removes any suggestion that Idris has,
at any time, maintained a relationship with Osama bin Laden or any
terrorist group or organization,'' said a statement by Idris'
lawyers, Mark MacDougall and Steven Ross.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the Treasury action strengthened their assertion
in an expected lawsuit against the government that the United
States mistakenly targeted the pharmaceutical factory. The United
States attacked the Al Shifa plant in Khartoum and a suspected
terrorist training camp near Khost, Afghanistan, on Aug. 20 in an
effort to curb the activities of bin Laden, a Saudi exile, after
the bombings of the two American embassies in East Africa. Bin
Laden has denied any role in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Idris, who was born in the Sudan, said he was pleased with the
decision. ``I am grateful,'' he said in a statement, ``that the
United States has taken the honorable course and has corrected, in
part, the serious harm that has been done to my family and our good
name.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no formal apology from the Treasury Department,
which provided no explanation of why it unblocked Idris' assets and
has not officially announced any change in the American view of
Idris' ties to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The government's justification for attacking the Sudanese plant
remains a matter of dispute, although American officials have stood
by their assertions that soil samples obtained clandestinely from
the site tested positive for traces of Empta, a chemical used in
the production of VX nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have acknowledged that they did not know that
Idris owned the plant at the time, but other American officials
said that afterward they collected strong evidence linking him to
bin Laden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
