<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0518 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-FIRE-COX     05-03 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Over sixty apartment residents homeless after fire
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Georgia, Texas editors.)
 &HT;    By Robin McDonald and Doug Payne
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some of the 75 families at home when fire roared
through luxury apartments Monday have told fire investigators that
sprinklers never worked and fire alarms were silent during the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The four-alarm fire began about 6 p.m. in Building 200 of the
Summer Lakeside Apartments in north Fulton County. Some of the
residents were just sitting down to TV or coming home from work.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment building, completed in June, was equipped with
smoke detectors inside individual apartments and outside, in
addition to a sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported late Monday night, but residents were
shaken by alarms that remained silent and sprinklers that stayed
dry throughout the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the building's estimated 100-125 residents were alerted
by quick-thinking neighbors who pounded on doors and shouted to
clear the building.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 64 of the 75 apartments in Building 200 were
destroyed by flames, smoke and water, according to fire officials.
</P>
<P>
   A.D. Bell Sr., assistant fire chief for Fulton County, said fire
investigators questioned the complex's maintence man, who said the
sprinkler system had been installed but didn't know if it was
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (the maintenance man) was not sure whether the sprinkler
system had pressure on it or not,'' Bell said. ``Fire codes require
the system have pressure at all times and if he was working on it,
he should've told us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire investigators reported the fire appeared to have started
outside the building, probably on a balcony on the second or third
floor, and spread up the building's outer walls and into the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said it's possible that if the flames spread in that manner
_ above alarms and sprinklers _ it might offer an explanation for
the systems not working. Bell said the investigation into the fire
must be finished before he can confirm such a scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment managers were on hand at the fire, but refused to
speak to reporters. Mark Borders, leasing manager for Summer
Lakeside Apartments, said the complex is owned by Walton Concierge
Service of Houston, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Residents also told firefighters that smoke detectors in
individual apartments didn't sound, but Bell said that may be
because the smoke hadn't reached them at the time. Residents said
they believe their individual smoke detectors are working because
they have gone off numerous times when cooking. Despite early
reports that firefighters were hampered by a nearby water main
break earlier in the day, Bell denied that there was any difficulty
on that account. ``What we do know is the water main break had no
impact on the operation of the fire hydrants in this complex.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire, which began at about 6 p.m., took more than an hour to
contain and required 60 firefighters drawn from Fulton, DeKalb and
Cobb counties.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story building had garages on the bottom floor.
Apartment rents ranged from $770 for a one-bedroom unit to $1,200
for a two-bedroom unit, according to residents.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pace was at home in her second-floor apartment when a man
ran down the hall banging on the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Pace ran out of her apartment barefoot to find the hall filled
with smoke, but she heard no fire alarms in the hall. She said the
stairwell also was filled with smoke. She passed by the apartment
where she believes the fire started and said no sprinklers were
activated.
</P>
<P>
   She called her fiance, Mike Hammer, from her cell phone in her
car. Hammer said when he arrived, firefighters appeared to be
having trouble getting the water pressure they needed to fill their
hoses.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said they had looked at a number of complexes making sure
the apartment they rented would have adequate fire alarms and
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ''But no alarms went off. No sprinklers went off. ... There are
sprinklers in the building. I wouldn't have rented here if there
hadn't been,'' Hammer said. ``When you've bought into that and it
doesn't work, it's very disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammer and Pace are planning to get married May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ''All our clothing, our rings are in there,'' Pace said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials were unable to confirm rumors that the fire began
with an outdoor grill.
</P>
<P>
   Residents recalled that about two weeks ago the complex sent a
notice around warning against grills, saying they were a violation
of the fire code.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Roberts, who has lived in the complex since October, said
he heard a maintenance man shouting about the fire. He said the
sprinkler system never came on as he joined in, running through the
building pounding on doors and occasionally kicking them in,
because ``you never know who can't hear or who's sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts also tried to save residents' pets. One dog ran past him
and down the stairs. ``I just let it go.'' Eric Brown, 31, said he
was coming home from work when he saw the flames and smoke. He ran
into the building to rescue his cats at about 6 p.m. and said he
questioned why there were no alarms or sprinklers operating, but
added, ``It was a little too late to worry about it at that time.''
He rescued one cat and found the other outside after the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Tami Hartman, 27, a teacher, was watching the news on TV and
paying her bills when someone ran past her apartment and banged on
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a guy. He said, 'You might want to get out.' I
thought, 'What am I supposed to take with me?' `` Hartman
recounted. She escaped barefoot, wearing a 1991 T-shirt from a frat
party, carrying her bills and her insurance file. As she ran out,
she said she smelled smoke, but heard no alarms.
</P>
<P>
   After the blaze was almost extinguished,Tina White, 27, a
resident of apartment 213 since July, was worrying over the loss of
her boyfriend's 1990 championship ring from Georgia Tech. ``I've
got renter's insurance, but that won't take care of the memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin McDonald and Doug Payne write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. Doug Nurse , Will Anderson and
Mike Weiss contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
