<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONE-CHARGE-DEBATE-C     05-03 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-CHARGE-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate on Bell pricing bill uncovers concerns
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Even as Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. scored a
major regulatory victory last week before the Public Utility
Commission, it suffered a late-night embarrassment before the House
State Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was considering a bill that would provide
Southwestern Bell with much of the price deregulation that it
wants. But the two lawmakers sponsoring the bill, Reps. Leticia Van
De Putte, D-San Antonio, and Toby Goodman, R-Arlington, found
themselves on the defensive, denying they were messengers for the
company and struggling to explain the bill's fine points.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake for so many different parties if
Southwestern Bell prevails, emotions were running high at the
hearing, which finally was cut off at 1 a.m. Friday and resumed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Rep. Steve Wolens, D-Dallas,
complained at one point that he was having so much trouble pulling
out complete answers to his questions that he was ``feeling like a
dentist,'' and he was still angry the next day, calling the hearing
``terrible . . . it was dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, it remained unclear what damage, if any, there
was to Southwestern Bell's hopes of getting more freedom to raise
and lower prices without state approval. The legislative session
ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the most visible part of this debate has been a
barrage of opposing television commercials by Southwestern Bell and
a coalition led by AT&AMP;T. The gist of each company's ad is that
their competitor would raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has passed a bill that would give Southwestern Bell
more pricing freedom under various conditions, but in the House,
Van De Putte and Goodman have substituted for it a version far more
favorable to the company, whose parent, SBC Communications Inc., is
based in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two lawmakers said they are not carrying the bill
for Southwestern Bell, both showed the effects Thursday night of a
barrage of criticism about the legislation from AT&AMP;T, other
telephone companies and consumer groups such as Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, I have not enjoyed at all just the slightest
inference that I'm carrying water for Bell,'' Van De Putte said at
the hearing. ``And in some cases, people have said that I'm their
`ho.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman withered under Wolens' detailed questioning, finally
saying at one point that he was ``going nuts with this damn
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolens, a highly successful courtroom litigator and generally
regarded as a consumer advocate, seemed particularly provoked by a
feeling that Southwestern Bell and the Texas Association of
Broadcasters had not been totally candid about language in the bill
that would appear to make it easier for Southwestern Bell to offer
video services.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Ann Arnold, you should have been more forthcoming
tonight . . . it would have been nicer if you had been more
forthcoming rather than my pulling all this stuff out of you,''
Wolens said to Arnold, executive director of the broadcasters'
association.
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, a Southwestern Bell lobbyist, defended the provision
on the grounds that the company would provide additional
competition in the cable market.
</P>
<P>
   That Southwestern Bell is interested in video services indicates
just how complicated this fight is. The main issues are:
</P>
<P>
   _Southwestern Bell wants a lot more freedom from state
regulations to raise and lower the prices that it charges for its
numerous services so that it can meet what it sees as a coming
assault by AT&AMP;T. AT&AMP;T has been buying up or getting access to cable
systems as a way of ``wiring around'' Southwestern Bell to new
customers, not just for long-distance service but also for local
phone and computer services. Last week Southwestern Bell won a
major victory when the PUC effectively agreed to recommend to
federal regulators that it be allowed to sell long-distance service
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom want a sharp reduction in the ``access
fee'' of 12 cents a minute that they and other long-distance
companies must pay Southwestern Bell to complete their in-state
long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   _AT&AMP;T says Southwestern Bell has no real competition yet, so it
should remain regulated.
</P>
<P>
   _A separate group of relatively small phone companies, trying to
get a toehold in the telecommunications market, is less concerned
about Southwestern Bell's entrance into the long-distance market
than about the company's ability to underprice them in competition
for business customers. Giving Southwestern Bell more price
flexibility on local services now while letting it into the
long-distance market is ``tantamount to giving Bell nuclear
weapons,'' warned Royce Holland, chairman of Allegiance Telecom of
Texas Inc.
</P>
<P>
   _Consumers Union fears that Southwestern Bell will lower prices
for business customers, making up for it by raising prices on
residential customers. While Southwestern Bell has agreed to freeze
basic local residential rates until 2005, under the bill it would
be free to raise prices on a number of other services, such as
caller identification. Most of these services now have rate caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they have to take the cap off services like caller
return and caller ID unless they intend to raise the price?'' asked
Janee Briesemeister, a policy analyst for Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
