<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0523 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENCOR-DEBT-NYT &LR;      05-03 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENCOR-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENCOR MISSES DEBT PAYMENT, RAISING QUESTION OF SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vencor Inc., one of several troubled nursing-home chains, missed
a payment on its debt Monday, providing new fodder for investor
concerns about its ability to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which said last month that its survival was an
issue, said Monday that it would not pay $14.8 million due in
interest on $300 million of notes that mature in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Battered by Medicare cutbacks and heavy financial losses,
Vencor, which is based in Louisville, Ky., is trying to negotiate
new terms from banks and Ventas Inc., a real estate investment
trust that retained almost all the properties when Vencor split in
two early last year.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's announcement, Vencor said it had opened a 35-day
period before the banks could demand repayment and force it to seek
protection under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law, an
action that could also push Ventas to seek bankruptcy protection.
The banks had already set a deadline of May 28 for Vencor to comply
with the terms of its loans.
</P>
<P>
   Vencor said last month in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission that it had a deficit of $683 million in
working capital. It reported a loss of more than $600 million in
the fourth quarter of 1998. Medicare officials have demanded the
return of $90 million that the government said were overcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Vencor, which have lost most of their value this year,
fell 6.25 cents Monday to 87.5 cents, on the New York Stock
Exchange. Shares of Ventas fell 12.5 cents, to $4.375. Bonds of
Vencor have plunged 82 percent since January. They were bid Monday
at about 15.5 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the crux of the problems at Vencor, one of the
nation's largest operators of nursing homes and hospitals for
long-term patients, was the refusal of a co-founder, W. Bruce
Lunsford, to reduce the rents the company pays. Lunsford, who
resigned as Vencor's chief executive in January, still holds that
post at Ventas, the real estate investment trust that holds the
leases on most of the facilities Vencor operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not looking good for Vencor,'' said Lori Price, a health
care analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer. She said the banks would probably
act to protect their stake unless Lunsford agreed to rent
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   But another analyst who specializes in troubled companies said
that Lunsford had strong reasons to keep Vencor afloat. He added
that other nursing home operators would also insist on low rental
terms because most of the industry is struggling with cuts in
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said that
if Vencor foundered, Ventas would be stuck with more than $200
million it had guaranteed for leases that Vencor has with other
landlords.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Vencor refused to comment Monday. Officials at
Ventas did not reply to messages requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Abramowitz, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein, said
the ``most logical thing'' would be for Vencor and Ventas to merge
back into one company, which would ``give them the resources to pay
all their debt and lease obligations without invoking Chapter 11.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``least logical,'' he said, would be to end up in bankruptcy
court.
</P>
<P>
   Vencor operates 60 hospitals, 309 nursing homes with 40,000
licensed beds, and related service businesses in 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in Medicare payments virtually crippled the formerly
lucrative business of providing contract therapists and other
specialized workers to many of the country's small nursing homes.
Under the new system, which took effect last summer, Medicare
typically pays a flat amount for each nursing home patient instead
of paying an added fee for each service the patient receives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990503.0524 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NY     05-03 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOPSY REPORT ON POLICE SHOTS THAT HIT DIALLO IS RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The official autopsy of Amadou Diallo has found that
of the 19 police bullets that hit him, one traveled up his right
leg, while a second pierced the sole of his right sneaker,
according to a report by the city's Medical Examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Diallo family have argued that based on an
independent autopsy they had arranged, these shots are evidence
that Diallo was fired upon by the police as he lay on the ground
after being felled by an initial barrage of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But the Medical Examiner's report does not describe the position
of Diallo's body as individual bullets struck him and draws no
conclusions about the order in which the shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   The report, a copy of which was obtained Monday by The New York
Times, says Diallo, who was fired upon 41 times by four police
officers, died of ``multiple gunshot wounds to trunk with
perforations of aorta, spinal cord, lungs, liver, spleen, kidney
and intestines.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the four officers, who have been indicted on charges
of second-degree murder, said they believed that the report
rebutted the contention of the Diallo family's lawyers, Peter
Neufeld, Barry Scheck and Johnnie Cochran. They argue that the
officers callously fired at Diallo as he lay on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen C. Worth, who represents Officer Edward McMellon, one of
the four officers, said the report showed that the trajectories of
many of the shots were consistent with Diallo's standing upright
when he was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld said he had no comment on the official autopsy but added
that the family's position remained unchanged. ``There are two or
more bullets which compel the inference that the police continued
to shoot him after he fell to the ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the indication that two of the bullets hit Diallo
after he had fallen, Worth said: ``Out of 41, is it possible that
one of them hits him as he is going down? Sure. But that is a far
cry from saying that they were shooting for sport at a prone
body.''
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Examiner's report is important evidence because
there are no witnesses to the entire sequence of events that led to
the Feb. 4 shooting of Diallo, 22, an unarmed immigrant, in the
vestibule of his Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, whose case is scheduled to be tried in January,
returned to desk jobs Monday. Meanwhile, Neufeld said Diallo's
parents filed a notice of claim with the city last week, the first
step toward filing a civil lawsuit to seek damages in the death of
their son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
