<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves strike for 3 in 8th, trump Cards
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox New sService
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time Brian Hunter saw a Cardinal uniform in
Atlanta, he was wearing it, but not for long. The date was July 31,
1998, and the Cardinals marked the day by releasing him.
</P>
<P>
   The wandering first baseman returned the favor Monday night. His
pinch-hit double brought in the winning run in a comeback three-run
eighth inning as the Braves opened a three-game series with St.
Louis with a 4-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves nicked St. Louis rookie Jose Jimenez for just five
hits through the first seven innings but never reached him for two
in one inning until the eighth, when Chipper Jones walked, Brian
Jordan singled up the middle and Javy Lopez tied the score with
sharp single to left.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Scott Radinsky, who entered the game with a 7.36 ERA,
then watched pinch-hitter Brian Hunter yank a double on an 0-2
count into the left field corner, scoring ex-Cardinal Jordan with
the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   After an intentional walk to Andruw Jones to load the bases,
Walt Weiss lifted a fly into shallow right field, and even with the
heavy-legged Lopez running, he scored easily for a 4-2 lead as Eric
Davis made a weak throw.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals took a 2-1 lead in the eighth. Ray Lankford could
do nothing with the first two strikes Mike Remlinger threw him but
he managed to do plenty with the third, driving his second homer of
the season into the Braves bullpen for a one-run advantage. The run
was the second allowed by Remlinger in seven relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter Tom Glavine worked into the seventh of a 1-1
game, when he allowed one-out singles to Jose Jimenez (1-for-17
career) and Darren Bragg, which after 121 pitches was enough for
manager Bobby Cox. Rookie Kevin McGlinchy took over and struck out
Edgar Renteria and then McGwire on a called third-strike fastball
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing no decision, Glavine was charged with one run and seven
hits, walking two and striking out six. He lowered his ERA by more
than half a run to 4.61.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone collected his sixth RBI of the homestand in the
bottom of the third, tying the score 1-1 with his third double of
the season. Walt Weiss opened the inning with a walk, took second
on a Glavine groundout and scored easily when Boone dropped an
opposite-field blooper down the right field line.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
