<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-CIRCULATION-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER INDUSTRY FAILS TO STEM CIRCULATION DROP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Months of effort by the nation's newspaper publishers to rein in
price increases and to promote their publications aggressively
failed to stem the industry's long-term circulation decline. The
latest figures from the Audit Bureau of Circulations showed average
daily circulation down five-tenths of 1 percent, while Sunday
circulation dropped by 1 percent, for the six months ending March
30.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers that showed the greatest ability to buck the
trend were those in competitive markets, like the Denver and
Minneapolis areas, or those that command a national audience, like
USA Today and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest circulation declines among large papers came in
Boston and Philadelphia, according to the report, which did not
include the latest figures from The Buffalo News, which is owned by
Warren Buffett and had shown a 9.6 percent decline in the last
reporting period. The Boston Herald, owned by Patrick J. Purcell,
lost 9.4 percent of its circulation, which declined to 262,317. The
Philadelphia Inquirer, a Knight-Ridder publication, lost 7.3
percent of its circulation, which fell to 401,968.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gruneich, an analyst with Bear Stearns, said: ``It really
seemed like in early 1997 the industry came to a consensus that it
wasn't going to let circulation drop any further. Soon thereafter
we saw a firming in numbers.'' He added that the latest results
were a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic increases were registered in Denver, the most
competitive newspaper market in the country, where price cuts have
been so deep that some subscribers have been able to purchase
newspapers for little more than a penny a day. The Denver Post,
owned by Media News Group, now has a circulation of 370,423, up 4.7
percent. Its rival, The Denver Rocky Mountain News, owned by E.W.
Scripps Co., gained 10.4 percent, up to 359,068 over the same
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ABC, the average weekday sales of USA Today
reached 1,818,000, bolstered by a Friday-only circulation of more
than 2.1 million. The heavy Friday sales makes the Gannett Co.'s
flagship the best-selling newspaper in the country on average,
although Dow Jones &AMP; Co.'s national financial daily, The Wall
Street Journal, still outsells USA Today Monday through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times registered a 2.2 percent daily circulation
increase for a total circulation of 1,134,974. Daily circulation of
The New York Daily News increased by three-tenths of 1 percent, to
729,449, while The New York Post, which is owned by News Corp.,
increased to 433,744, a gain of two-tenths of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But across the nation, such gains were the exception, not the
rule. ``The newspaper industry has had, since the invention of
television, a weakening circulation picture,'' said John Morton, an
industry analyst who runs his own company, Morton Research Inc.
``Up until the 1990s, it just meant that circulation didn't grow as
fast as households. Now it's losing ground.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The industry, he said, still has a ``very strong'' franchise.
``It's still a huge business and a huge penetration.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the newspapers showing circulation declines for their
Sunday newspapers were The Chicago Sun Times, owned by Hollinger,
whose circulation declined 2.9 percent, to 411,334; The St. Louis
Post-Dispatch, the flagship newspaper of Pulitzer Co., which lost
2.7 percent of its Sunday circulation, which declined to 524,695,
and The Boston Globe, which is owned by the New York Times Co., and
lost 2.4 percent of its Sunday circulation, which declined to
730,420.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday circulation of The Daily News of New York declined by
1.9 percent, to 835,429. The circulation of The New York Post's
Sunday edition, which was introduced in 1996 and sold nearly
300,000 copies within a year, registered its first year-to-year
decline in the latest figures, dropping by 4.7 percent, to 351,970.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday circulation of The New York Times defied this trend,
increasing to 1,687,959, or 2.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
