<SLUG> BC-GUMBEL-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS WILL MAKE IT OFFICIAL: GUMBEL IS ON MORNING TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bryant Gumbel's long-anticipated return to morning
television will become official Tuesday when CBS announces that he
has agreed to become the anchor of a revamped ``CBS This Morning''
program, which will be in a newly created studio on Fifth Avenue at
the entrance to Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   CBS will introduce Gumbel, as well as the program's new
executive producer, Steve Friedman, in a news conference scheduled
for Tuesday afternoon. The news conference will take place at the
General Motors Building, the ground floor of which CBS has leased
for use as the studio for the new morning program.
</P>
<P>
   Among others, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Donald Trump, who
manages the building, are expected to attend the news conference.
Network executives declined to comment about Gumbel's appointment.
But Friedman said the deal was in place, and the new program, with
Gumbel and a still-to-be-named female co-anchor, would be ready to
go on the air sometime in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun,'' Friedman said. ``We going to try to
build a franchise. You don't do it overnight. But it's great to be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel was the anchor for NBC's ``Today'' program for 15 years,
the longest tenure on record. Friedman was his executive producer
for six of those years. Gumbel left ``Today'' in 1997 to join CBS
as the anchor of a news magazine show called ``Public Eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The network canceled that program after just one year on the air
when it failed to attract strong ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, CBS has looked for a new role for Gumbel. After ABC
revamped ``Good Morning America'' in January, replacing its hosts
with two well-known news anchors, Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson,
Gumbel's name appeared in speculation that CBS would look for a
similar injection of star power for its morning program. ABC's
original plan to use Ms. Sawyer and Gibson as temporary
replacements has lately evolved into a much longer-term
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Today'' show has dominated the morning ratings for several
years, not missing a beat since Matt Lauer replaced Gumbel as the
co-anchor with Katie Couric.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by NBC, which is owned by General Electric, to
return ``Today'' to its 1950s roots by moving its studio to a
street location in Rockefeller Center greatly helped that show's
ratings. Tourists have flocked to stand outside the studio's
windows every morning. Now the idea of a studio that overlooks a
recognizable Manhattan location is apparently de rigueur. ``It's
become the price of admission,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, a unit of Walt Disney, is also building a studio with a
Manhattan view for its morning show. The ABC studio, also expected
to be ready in the fall, is on the second floor of 1500 Broadway
overlooking Times Square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
