<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CYCLICALS, AGAIN, CARRY THE DOW INDUSTRIALS INTO RECORD TERRITORY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MARK VEVERKA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
The party ain't over.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the gluttonous media feast surrounding the Dow Jones
industrials' shattering of 10,000, yesterday's romp past the 11,000
mark was more like quiet after-dinner cordials.
</P>
<P>
   While 10,000 was no more than an arbitrary benchmark, the same
holds true for 11,000 _ except that it only took 24 trading days
for the dowdy Dow to rack up another 1,000 points to smash its
latest barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it appears that the smokestack cyclicals carried the
day. Cyclicals, as regular Street Smarts readers may know, are
stocks of companies that are directly linked to economic factors,
such as interest rates and unemployment. As you may recall, these
rather unglamorous holdings, such as Du Pont, Chevron and Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing, helped the Dow get over the 10,000 hump
after financial stocks and drug companies did most of the heavy
lifting.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to 11,000. Cash rotated
out of many cyclicals and back into technology growth stocks for a
spell. Many of the industrials rose so high, so quickly that
concerns about their staying power began to surface. Investors
began wondering whether the strong showing by cyclicals was merely
a ``head fake,'' which is Wall Street parlance for a false start or
a short-lived surge.
</P>
<P>
   However, judging by yesterday's showing, the blue chips of the
Dow are demonstrating that their run could be real. General Motors
rose $4.69 to close at $93.75, while 3M soared $4.88 to $93.88.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Goodyear Tire and Rubber, which had been one of the
Dow's biggest laggards, jumped $3.56 to close at $60.75. The Dow
climbed about 10 percent in April compared to about 5 percent for
the broader S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll see these (cyclical) stocks roll over
(and decline),'' says portfolio manager Carson Levit of Dresdner
RCM Global Investors in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to be the start of something (more
substantial),'' Levit says.
</P>
<P>
   The industrials, and its many cyclical components, have seen a
resurgence largely because central banks around the world slashed
their interest rates. This makes it easier for foreign
manufacturers to borrow money and begin growing their businesses
again. And to do that, they will start buying oil from Chevron,
tractors from Caterpillar and trucks from General Motors, Levit
explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is extrapolating some of that global economic
strength, which is returning to a number of (American)
industries,'' Levit says. ``Their stocks are rising in anticipation
of higher earnings growth.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the catch. While many of the world's economic markets
appear to be on the mend, they are far from fully recovered. Japan,
for example, may be near the bottom of its recession, but it is by
no means experiencing robust economic health.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it is possible that investors' expectations of the
revitalized cyclicals may get ahead of reality. In many cases, some
cyclicals _ such as Caterpillar _ have erased a year's worth of
market decline in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Now that expectations have been raised, it's quite possible that
some of these companies won't see their businesses grow as fast as
shareholders would like, Levit warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could still happen is that there could be more
(international) economic weakness out there, (but) I really don't
expect that to happen,'' Levit says.
</P>
<P>
   PLUGGING IN: It is with mixed emotions that I announce I am
leaving my financial columnist post at The Chronicle at the end of
next week. I have accepted a job at Barron's as West Coast Editor
and writer of the magazine's soon-to-be weekly Plugged In
technology column. In addition to the column, I hope to do cover
stories, features and some television work for CNBC, which is a
partnership between NBC and Barron's parent _ Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has only been a year since I left the Wall Street
Journal to join The Chronicle, it has been a privilege to write
this column, and I still have a handful more to file before saying
so long. I will be based in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
