<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3167 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSAMERICA-FUNDS-SF     05-03 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSAMERICA-FUNDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SHOOTING THE MOON _ TRANSAMERICA FUNDS SOAR ON GUTSY BETS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
O ne of the nation's most successful mutual-fund managers toils in
obscurity in a small, cluttered office in San Francisco's
Transamerica Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Treick, 35, runs the Transamerica Premier Aggressive
Growth Fund, which soared a phenomenal 84.1 percent last year, and
the Transamerica Premier Small Company Fund, which was up 80.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index _ the principal
benchmark for institutional investors _ rose 28.6 percent,
dividends included.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggressive Growth and Small Company funds were the top
performers in their categories last year among funds tracked by
Morningstar Inc., and they ranked seventh and ninth, &LR; 
 &LR; respectively, among 3,197 domestic equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   Treick, a fast-talking, hyperkinetic native of Wyoming, joined
Transamerica as a securities analyst in 1988. He later worked on
the Transamerica trading desk and as manager of some of the
company's own assets. In July 1997, he got the opportunity to run
his first mutual fund when he was appointed manager of the newly
created aggressive growth and small company funds.
</P>
<P>
   Treick has been wise enough to follow an investment strategy
that is exactly in tune with today's wildly speculative stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   He has made big, gutsy bets on a limited number of hot
performers such as Amazon.com, Dell Computer and Cisco Systems, and
has held them tenaciously no matter how perilously high they have
soared.
</P>
<P>
   Both his funds have continued to turn in strong performances
this year. The aggressive growth fund was ahead by 23.4 percent
from the end of 1998 through last week, while the small company
fund boasted a 12.2 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the S&AMP;P 500 was up 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their brilliant records, neither of Treick's funds has
attracted vast amounts of investor money yet. They each have total
assets of around $200 million _ not much in an industry where $1
billion in assets is considered ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Treick figures that big money isn't likely to flow into his
funds until he has established more of a track record. Financial
advisers and many individual investors prefer to wait until a fund
has been around for at least three years before they will commit
substantial amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   Treick also is handicapped by the fact that his funds are
no-loads, which means that they aren't touted by brokers. Brokers
prefer to confine their selling efforts to funds that will earn
them a commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Transamerica name might be another handicap.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is being acquired by Aegon NV, an insurer
based in the Netherlands, is widely regarded as solid but stodgy.
Its name doesn't normally conjure up images of stock-market
fireworks in the public mind.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, Transamerica actually has a notable mutual-fund
record. It can boast not only Treick's overachieving funds, but
also two above-par performers managed by his colleague Jeffrey Van
Harte, 40.
</P>
<P>
   Van Harte's Transamerica Premier Equity Fund gained 33.7 percent
in 1998, and his Transamerica Premier Balanced Fund, which invests
in bonds and money-market instruments as well as stocks, surged 29
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This year, through last week, the equity fund gained 12.3
percent, while the balanced fund rose 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Treick holds only about two dozen stocks in each of his funds,
and several of them appear in both funds, among them Amazon.com,
Alternative Living Services, Probusiness Services and Hollywood
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating on a limited number of companies is ``great in a
market upturn,'' he says _ that is, if you pick the right
companies. With few companies in your portfolio, your hottest
performers don't get offset by a lot of so-so performers and
laggards.
</P>
<P>
   Treick contends that with his stock-picking methods you'll
probably be better off in a downturn, too.
</P>
<P>
   He focuses on companies with savvy managements, commanding
positions in their markets, strong returns on invested capital,
strong cost controls, rapid inventory turnover and heavy cash flow
that allows them to seize attractive investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that fit those parameters have usually performed
relatively well in down markets, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Treick pays little attention to earnings growth and
price-earnings ratios _ the financial gauges most commonly followed
by investors.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, his largest holding, hasn't earned a profit yet, and
Dell, one of the five largest holdings in his aggressive growth
fund, recently was selling at a hefty 80 times earnings for the
latest 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Treick notes that earnings figures can be misleading, because
companies with poor fundamentals can sometimes increase their
earnings temporarily by flooding the market with their products, or
through other forms of financial legerdemain.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, such methods ``will come back and bite them,''
he observes.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how high any of his stocks soar, he says, he will hold
them as long as their managements stick to a sound strategy. If
they do, ``the risk of a permanent decline in the stock is not very
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar analyst Emily Hall points out that Treick's
willingness to stay fully committed to his highest-flying stocks is
unusual in the fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot will sell, or trim back heavily, on their picks that get
very pricey,'' she observes. ``If this growth-crazy market ends,
this is the kind of fund that could _ I'm not saying will _ get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial planner and mutual-fund devotee Kurt Brouwer, with
Brouwer &AMP; Janachowski in Tiburon, acknowledges that Treick
``probably is a very good money manager.''
</P>
<P>
   But he warns: ``When you are playing in a high-stakes game, the
cards can't always run with you. Some days they will run against
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Treick concedes that the market will move against him from time
to time. He got a taste of that in the past six trading sessions,
when Amazon.com's stock fell $59.19 to $150.94 _ a 28 percent
haircut.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he is so confident in his investment strategy that
he considers his funds appropriate investments for any and all
investors willing to hold their shares for at least 18 months. If
you wait that long, he explains, you should be able to ride out any
serious downturns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
