<HEADLINE>
JURY PICKED IN LOUIMA CASE; OFFICERS' TRIAL TO OPEN TUESDAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After five weeks of effort, a jury was selected
Monday for the long-awaited trial of four police officers accused
of brutalizing a Haitian immigrant. Opening statements and the
first witnesses are expected Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly controversial case with bitter racial overtones, the
federal jury that will decide whether the immigrant, Abner Louima,
was tortured in a Brooklyn police station after his arrest in a
street brawl in 1997 comprises eight white people, one black person
and three people who identified themselves as Hispanic, lawyers in
the case said.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the jurors will not be disclosed to the public or
to the defense and prosecution lawyers, under a ruling by Judge
Eugene H. Nickerson. He decided during the pretrial proceedings in
the Brooklyn courtroom to withhold the names in hopes of insuring
that outside pressures do not affect the jurors' judgments.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it could not be learned where the jurors live. The
federal district from which they were chosen comprises three of the
city's five boroughs _ Brooklyn, Queens and Staten Island _ and
Long Island. The jurors' occupations or vocations were also not
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson interviewed more than 200 jury candidates over 10
days. The 12 jurors chosen will weigh testimony and arguments in
what prosecutors have described as one of the most explosive and
graphic cases of police brutality in New York City in years.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers _ Justin A. Volpe, Charles Schwarz, Thomas
Wiese and Thomas Bruder _ are charged with violating Louima's civil
rights. Prosecutors say they beat him without justification in a
police car after his arrest in a melee outside a Brooklyn nightclub
in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say that later, at the 70th Precinct station
house, Volpe rammed a stick into Louima's rectum and then his
mouth, causing severe injuries to his rectum and bladder, while
Schwarz held him down. A sergeant, Michael Bellomo, is also on
trial, charged with trying to cover up the beating in the police
car.
</P>
<P>
   All five defendants call the charges untrue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the process Monday of choosing the 12 jurors and six
alternates from the preliminary panel, prosecutors from the U.S.
Attorney's office and the defense lawyers exchanged accusations
that each side was using its challenges in an illegal effort to
exclude people from the jury for racial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors contended that the defense lawyers were trying
to exclude four members of minority groups, but Nickerson rejected
the accusation in three instances, finding that the defense had
given acceptable reasons, unrelated to race, for rejecting those
prospective jurors. In the fourth instance, he upheld the
prosecution's accusation and that juror was seated.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the defense lawyers accused the prosecution of trying
to exclude three white people because of their race. Nickerson
rejected the defense accusation in all three instances and those
prospective jurors were not seated.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
