<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND SCHOOLS CHIEF MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two weeks of bitter sparring, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew finally met face to face
Monday, but studiously avoided any mention of the issues that have
divided them _ school vouchers and mayoral control of the public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The two men emerged separately from the City Hall meeting, which
lasted more than an hour. Crew looked strained and smiled wanly as
he walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said the meeting had focused on more immediate issues _ the
board's plan to end social promotion and its $11 billion plan to
repair crumbling schools and relieve overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just walked in and said, `Hi, how you doing?' shook hands
and sat down,'' Crew said, adding that the ensuing discussion was
``typical'' of their standing Monday meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Crew had left, Giuliani strode down the steps of
City Hall, grinning broadly, and walked straight to his car, which
was waiting to take him to an appointment at the Brooklyn Navy
Yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a businesslike meeting,'' the mayor said after arriving
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The low-key tone belied the magnitude of the gulf that has
opened in recent weeks, as the two have engaged in an escalating
campaign of recriminations over the state of the public schools and
how to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's ability to set the education agenda in New York City
is at stake, as well as whether Crew will be able to continue as
the leader of the nation's largest school system.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on more routine educational matters Monday reflected a
new strategy of waiting each other out, rather than direct
confrontation, aides to both men said. But Giuliani hinted that he
had not backed down on vouchers or dismantling the Board of
Education and that the overt war of the last two weeks might simply
have converted into a cold war. ``As to the rest of it, you know,
we'll continue to evaluate and I'll make my judgment in the
future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A close adviser to the mayor said he would not be surprised to
see the dispute resurface, though it was hard to predict when. ``I
see them getting further apart rather than closer,'' the adviser
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
