r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBADS-SPENDING-SFCHR     05-03 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBADS-SPENDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB AD SPENDING PASSES OUTDOOR MEDIUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CAROL EMERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Just a few years into the World Wide Web's existence, advertising
expenditures on the Internet have surpassed spending on outdoor
ads, an old-as-the-hills medium that includes billboards and taxi
tops.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on Web banner ads, site sponsorships and e-mail
marketing more than doubled in 1998 to $1.92 billion from $906.5
million in 1997, according to a study released yesterday by the
Internet Advertising Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on outdoor ads, meanwhile, totaled $1.5 billion, the
IAB said, citing data from New York ad agency McCann Erickson
Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are remarkable given that the Web is an infant
medium while outdoor ads have been around since Coca-Cola was a
snazzy new drink and Prince Albert tobacco ads graced the sides of
New England barns.
</P>
<P>
   The relative expenditures are also somewhat surprising given
that click-through rates of Web ads _ the frequency with which
people click on the ads _ are falling. As the novelty of banner ads
wanes, click-through rates have fallen to less than .5 percent,
compared with about 1 percent just a year ago, according to
NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   What the numbers don't reveal is how much of Web ad spending
stems from a calculated strategy and how much is driven by the hype
and optimism that are propelling Net stocks through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   People who make their living from digital marketing acknowledge
that they are working in the equivalent of the Stone Age of the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Internet's strength as an advertising medium may lie
in the future, when, for example, advertisers will be able to
target ads to surfers based on their buying patterns or demographic
characteristics. This is now done to a limited extent by
advertisers on just a few sites.
</P>
<P>
   Even the information generated by tracking ``clickstreams'' is
not being fully utilized. A survey by Jupiter Communications
released yesterday found that only 22 percent of Web advertisers
``make optimal use of clickstream data _ data that is critical to
making intelligent, cost-effective marketing decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's common now for everyone to measure click-through,'' said
Ken Sacharin, media director of Young &AMP; Rubicam San Francisco.
``The new challenge is to measure other things, like what is the
cost per qualified lead,'' in other words, how much it costs to
send an ad to a surfer who meets a profile the advertiser is
targetting.
</P>
<P>
   ``At an even higher level, we want to measure who makes further
inquiries into a product or service, who bought something and who
returned to buy something again,'' said Sacharin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the rudimentary tracking being done today,
``We're already measuring our online campaigns with greater rigor
than we do our offline campaigns in general,'' said Sacharin.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Tim Meadows, vice president of marketing with NetRatings,
``It's hard to click on a billboard and buy something. The Web is
not just a medium that provides content and context but a
marketplace that actually lets people conduct business on it.''
</P>
<P>
   By one measure, Web ads are a bargain. Last year, Net
advertising accounted for about 1 percent of the total $200 billion
in U.S. annual ad spending, yet Web-viewing time accounts for
between 4 and 5 percent of time exposed to all media by the average
American, said Sacharin.
</P>
<P>
   If those revenues were distributed evenly, ``the Web would be
getting $8 (billion) to $10 billion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pete Petrusky, director of new media for
PricewaterhouseCoopers, ``I think we're in the first inning of
what's going to be an extra-inning game.''
</P>
<P>
   Other findings from the study, which was conducted for the IAB
by &UR;  &LR; Petrusky's team at PricewaterhouseCoopers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumer product advertising accounted for 29 percent of Web
ad spending, computers made up 20 percent, financial services 19
percent, telecommunications 8 percent and new media 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barter deals comprised only 6 percent of Web ad revenues, with
93 percent of such deals paid for in cash. The remaining 1 percent
were parts of broader packages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty-six percent of expenditures were for banner ads, site
sponsorships made up 30 percent, full-screen animated
``interstitials'' 5 percent and e-mail ads 1 percent. A
miscellaneous category accounted for 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ A growing number of Web sites price ads according to
performance benchmarks _ such as whether viewers clicked on the ad
_ instead of simply measuring how many times the ad was flashed on
computer screens. Forty percent of ad spending was priced simply
according to the CPM, or cost per thousand times the banner flashed
on a computer screen. Six percent of ad spending was based purely
on performance measures. The majority, 54 percent of ads, were
``hybrid'' deals that included both cost per thousand and
performance measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
