<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-TAKEOVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SPRINT BUYING WIRELESS FIRMS TO OFFER LOCAL PHONE, NET SERVICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DEBORAH SOLOMON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO -- Sprint Corp. said Monday that it is buying two
wireless companies with a major presence in the Bay Area, giving
consumers here a way to get local phone service and high-speed
Internet access from Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City, Mo., company said it has agreed to acquire
Videotron USA of Montreal and Transworld Telecommunications Inc. of
Salt Lake City for $210 million.
</P>
<P>
   Videotron and Transworld own a Mountain View company called
Wavepath, which provides wireless Internet access through various
Internet service providers in the Bay Area. Videotron owns 62
percent of Wavepath and Transworld Telecommunications owns 38
percent
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give Sprint a way to offer service to more than
6.4 million homes in the Bay Area; Seattle and Spokane, Wash.;
Tampa, Fla.; and Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has been searching for a way to get into customers' homes
and businesses so it can sell its Integrated-on-Demand network. ION
will let customers talk on the phone, receive faxes and access the
Internet simultaneously. Sprint plans to offer local, long-distance
and high-speed Internet service over ION, a $2 billion, digital
network the company is building.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Sprint had to lease telephone lines from the Baby
Bells, such as Pacific Bell, to get its service to the end-user.
Buying Videotron and Transworld will allow Sprint to bypass the
Baby Bells and avoid paying costly fees to link to their networks.
Instead, Sprint will offer most customers a wireless connection to
the ION network.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint bought two other wireless cable operators last month _
American Telecasting and People's Choice T _ which operate in other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this is we can supply a big pipe and get into
customers' homes while bypassing the local phone companies,'' said
Russ Robinson, a spokesman for Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Wavepath transmits data wirelessly through a
technology called Multipoint Multichannel Distribution Service.
MMDS uses a special radio frequency that allows customers to
wirelessly connect to the Internet at speeds of about 384 kilobits
per second.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area customers who want to use Sprint's ION network will
attach an antenna to the side of their house to connect to one of
Sprint's cellular towers around the Bay Area. The service will be
rolled out in the Bay Area in early 2000 and will cost between $100
and $150 for the entire package of local, long-distance and
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Wavepath currently operates in the Bay Area through various
ISPs, including Concentric Network and Slip.Net. Wavepath and its
ISP partners market primarily to corporate customers, but Robinson
said Sprint will sell the service to residential and small-business
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's Robinson said ION will appeal to customers who have
multiple phone lines, Internet service and more than $50 a month in
long-distance bills.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said Sprint's purchase is a defensive move
against AT&AMP;T and other telecommunications companies that are
planning their own digital, high-speed networks.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to offer local phone and high-speed Internet service
through TCI's cable TV lines. MCI is looking at wireless for part
of its network and bought a wireless company last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reflection of Sprint's desperate need to get to the
home,'' said Andrew Cole, vice president of Renaissance Worldwide,
a Boston consulting firm. ``They need to compete with AT&AMP;T and are
being forced to find a way around the Baby Bells. MMDS can
transport data and very often voice as well at high rates. It's a
good solution.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wavepath, a 50-person firm, Sprint's purchase is a
validation of the company's technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Wavepath managed to do is prove that voice and data can
be carried at high speeds on MMDS spectrum and can be done
economically,'' said Guy Beaudry, president and CEO of Wavepath.
``This is excellent news.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaudry said there should not be any layoffs as a result of the
acquisition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
