<SLUG> BC-US-POWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED SOLDIERS REJOIN FAMILIES IN GERMANY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
and DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSTUHL, Germany _ Three U.S. soldiers, declared fit and
flashing grins, were reunited with their families Monday at a U.S.
Army hospital a day after their release by Yugoslavian captors.
</P>
<P>
   As their families arrived from the United States, the three men
were given clean bills of health by doctors, although testing on
two of them turned up partly healed injuries from earlier in their
monthlong captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials said the injuries could indicate mistreatment by
the Serbs who captured them near the Macedonia border with Kosovo,
but said further investigation would be needed to clarify when the
injuries occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers put that matter aside Monday, happily traipsing
onto a balcony at about 10 a.m., their families beside them, to
wave and smile at gathered reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Spc. Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas, was flanked by
his parents, Rosie and Gilbert Gonzales, and his aunt, Rosalinda
Barrow. He flashed the ``thumbs-up'' sign and a grin when asked how
he felt.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., held
his 4-year-old son, Ryan. He was accompanied by his parents, James
and Edith Stone, his sisters, Deanna Stone and Dawn Reliford, and
his wife, Trisha, who has family in San Antonio, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, stood with his
parents, Andrew and Vivian Ramirez, his brother, Steven, his
sister, Nadine, and her 6-month-old daughter, Vanessa. It was the
first time Ramirez had seen his niece.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales appeared to be in the best medical condition, said
officials at Landstuhl Regional Medical Center, the largest
American medical facility outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a medical standpoint, Spc. Gonzales has no further tests
planned,'' said Col. Mack Blanton, deputy commander of clinical
services at Landstuhl. ``Everything has turned out fine as far as
initial laboratory and X-ray studies. He will not need any further
studies.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone had a scan Monday morning that revealed he had a broken
nose. Ramirez had swelling in his right lower leg and two broken
ribs, but doctors said he needed no further treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rested very well. Woke up this morning in good spirits,
eager to be reunited with their families,'' said Lt.-Col. Sharon
DeRuvo, chief of clinical nursing at Landstuhl.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said in Washington that the
three soldiers would undergo debriefings for two or three more
days.
</P>
<P>
   The initial interviews have reaffirmed U.S. officials' belief
that the soldiers were captured inside Macedonia, Bacon said. Serb
authorities have claimed the three were in Serb territory when
captured March 31.
</P>
<P>
   After taking 30 days of leave, the soldiers will likely return
to their units, which are based in Germany, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Clinton would
like to meet with the three servicemen when he visits other U.S.
troops in Germany Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of the soldiers began arriving in Frankfurt at
8:45 a.m. Monday (2:45 a.m. EST) and traveled by car to the medical
facility, which is located about 90 miles southwest. A major
traffic accident on the German autobahn delayed their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales' parents and an aunt arrived at the medical center at
about noon. They visited and ate dinner with Gonzales at the
medical base.
</P>
<P>
   DeRuvo said the soldiers had been watching television, listening
to the radio and reading newspapers since arriving by air Sunday
from Croatia, where they crossed over from Serbia by bus.
</P>
<P>
   DeRuvo said the soldiers were getting reacclimated to life on
the base. Just to make sure, each was assigned a ``buddy escort''
from their unit who knew them well and who could help them adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``They worked together, they trained together, they have spent
time together,'' DeRuvo said of the buddy escorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know each other in terms of what they like and what they
don't like, so they are there to help them repatriate,'' she said.
``They are there to give them a firm grounding into what their life
is normally like and get them back into that transition into their
home environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanton said the general health of the soldiers was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were generally taken care of adequately during their
period of captivity,'' Blanton said. ``I have no concerns in that
regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen David Grange, commanding general of the First Infantry
Division, said, however, that he suspected the soldiers were
treated poorly when they were first captured. Grange escorted U.S.
civil rights leader Jesse Jackson and the soldiers from Croatia to
Ramstein Air Base near Landstuhl on Sunday morning. Jackson and an
ecumenical entourage are credited with negotiating the release of
the prisoners of war Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think all the treatment was well,'' Grange said,
citing how the soldiers appeared on Serb television. ``It's obvious
there was a little bit of mistreatment. But the examinations will
determine that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone had visible injuries on his face when the three were shown
on international news broadcasts shortly after their capture.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton said it did not appear that Stone had suffered permanent
damage. Blanton declined to elaborate on how Stone was injured
because the circumstances surrounding the soldiers' capture is
being investigated. The soldiers were on a routine reconnaissance
mission on the border when captured.
</P>
<P>
   While in captivity, Ramirez received stitches for a laceration
on the top of his head, doctors said. It was not clear how that
injury occurred, but Blanton said the wound was healing well.
</P>
<P>
   DeRuvo said the soldiers' military training helped them maintain
physical strength and mental fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took excellent care of themselves,'' she said. ``They
were trained well. They knew what to do, and it shows that they had
the discipline to take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they've come out overall in good health, but the
training the military has provided them and the discipline they
chose to take to follow that training made a difference in their
physical and mental well-being. They look good. They feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the soldiers were eager to be reunited with their
unit at Schweinfurt Army Base about 100 miles northeast of the
military hospital. But they also were looking forward to going back
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they are looking at some well-deserved leave,''
Grange said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
