<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INHERITING STOCK IN AN IRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ARTHUR LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Q: In a recent column, you mentioned that when someone inherits
stock, that person's cost basis for capital gains will be the price
of the stock on the day the deceased died. Does this also hold true
for stock contained in an inherited Individual Retirement Account?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Inherited IRAs are a special case.
</P>
<P>
   The key point is that the taxable proceeds you get from an
inherited IRA are considered ordinary income, not a capital gain.
Therefore, the cost basis is irrelevant for your tax calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue spokesman Jesse Weller points out that IRAs are
a rare exception to the general rule that assets you inherit are
nontaxable. If the deceased were to leave you stock outright _
rather than in an IRA _ you wouldn't be taxed on the value of the
stock, although you would have to pay a capital-gains tax if the
value of the stock later rose and you sold it.
</P>
<P>
   If you inherit a traditional IRA from your spouse, you have the
choice of either removing the assets from the IRA or maintaining
the IRA as though you originated it yourself. If you choose to keep
the IRA intact, you can make your own contributions, according to
the usual rules and limitations, and you aren't compelled to
withdraw any assets until after you reach age 701/2. You won't be
taxed until the withdrawals begin.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not the spouse, you are not entitled to keep the IRA
intact. You have to take a distribution of the proceeds. With a
deductible IRA, all the proceeds are taxable. With a nondeductible
IRA, the amount that exceeds the contributions is taxable.
</P>
<P>
   (None of this discussion applies to Roth IRAs, which are tax
free.)
</P>
<P>
   When you receive the proceeds, you have the choice of either
taking the stock as stock or having it liquidated and receiving
cash instead. Either way, you pay taxes based on the value of the
stock at the time of the distribution.
</P>
<P>
   If you receive stock, any change in the value after the
distribution will be treated as a capital gain or loss. The date
you receive the stock would be the date you use in determining
whether the gain or loss is long-term or short-term.
</P>
<P>
   There are other, even more convoluted, rules about the tax
treatment of inherited IRAs that can't be covered in this space _
such as how quickly the IRA assets must be distributed and whether
you may deduct part of the estate taxes in figuring your income-tax
liability.
</P>
<P>
   For fuller details, take a look at IRS publications 590, 559 and
448.
</P>
<P>
   FINDING MISSING CASH
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a client of an online brokerage firm. On the latest
monthly account statement they sent me, a substantial amount `of
cash appeared to be missing. I called this to the attention of
three different client-support representatives, but they seemed
confused, and the situation has not been rectified. How should I
proceed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your next step should be to contact the top management of the
brokerage firm. No more fooling with subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   If you are correct about the amount of money that should be in
your account and if you haven't been deliberately defrauded,
management probably can clear up the matter to your satisfaction by
conducting a detailed review of your transaction record.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, file a complaint with the National
Association of Securities Dealers, the brokerage industry's
self-regulatory body.
</P>
<P>
   You can file your complaint electronically on NASD's Web site at
www.nasdr.com. Or you can complain by letter to NASD's district
office in San Francisco. Write to the attention of Elisabeth P.
Owens, the district director, at 525 Market St., Suite 300, San
Francisco, Calif. 94105-2711. The telephone number is (415)
882-1200.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING STOCK
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have just bought some stock and want to know what is the
record date for tax purposes. Is it the date the trade actually was
made on the stock exchange, or is it the settlement date three
business days later?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you report a capital transaction on Form 1040, Schedule
D, you enter the actual transaction date _ not the settlement date
_ under the heading ``date acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the next column, under ``date sold,'' you state
the actual transaction date of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   For your sale to qualify as a long-term capital gain (or loss),
the ``date sold'' must be at least one year and one day after the
``date acquired.'' If an asset is sold one year to the day after it
is bought, it is still a short-term sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
