<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AIMS GIBES AT HILLARY CLINTON AT AN UPSTATE DINNER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton supplied Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani with some of his best material Monday night as he drew
cheers from Republicans here with jabs at her as an interloper with
no connection to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``carpetbagger'' has crept into Giuliani's speeches as
he and Mrs. Clinton crisscross the state, each exploring a run for
the same U.S. Senate seat next year, and he used it again at the
Fulton County Republican Party's annual dinner in Amsterdam, which
is 30 miles northwest of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor reminded his audience that Mrs. Clinton, who grew up
in Illinois, has lived most of her adult life in Arkansas, and
signaled that he sees resentment of her as a powerful issue for New
York Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does make sense in New York to have somebody
representing us in the Senate, let's start off, who's from New
York,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may announce for the Senate in Arkansas,'' he joked. And in
an arch reference to that state's political scandals, he added,
``Given the experience of the last several years, maybe they would
elect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani gave his usual account of taming the untamable city,
cutting crime and shrinking welfare rolls, but his barbs at Mrs.
Clinton brought the most enthusiastic response from his audience of
200.
</P>
<P>
   His comments were even more pointed in a session with reporters
before the dinner, when he said that in a campaign, there would be
raised ``a very valid question of how do you represent a state in
which you have no connection at all,'' an issue that he said would
be particularly potent upstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of her being a carpetbagger in New York City does not
have the same impact as it does outside of New York City,'' the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that her candidacy would be ``a real plus'' because
``she would galvanize support for the Republican side in a way that
few people could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in central New York, one of the state's most staunchly
Republican regions, that may well be true. In Fulton County, 19 of
the 20 county legislators are Republican, and the other is an
independent.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he thought of Giuliani, Allen Bohne, a former
county party chairman, said, ``I can tell you one thing, I don't
think too much of Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people at Monday night's event said that they did not
know much about the mayor _ though what they knew, they said, was
positive _ and that they were reserving judgment about a possible
primary between Giuliani and Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island's
Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Lazio speak to us not long ago, and we really liked
him,'' said Dexter Risedorph, a county election commissioner.
``Tell you the truth, I'll go with whoever can win.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who takes pains to appear nonpartisan at home, where
most voters are Democrats, wears his party identification far more
proudly upstate. ``The things that New York City gets credit for
turning around all have to do with Republican philosophy and
Republican programs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also took swipes at President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, and said that any of the Republicans running for
president would be preferable to Gore. He also praised Gov. George
Pataki, a highly popular figure here but a fellow Republican with
whom Giuliani has clashed repeatedly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
