<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVES OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After many years of straight, smooth hair, it seems
to be time for a change to styles with a bit of texture. That
should be good news for women with curls or waves or anyone whose
hair gets unruly in summer humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lawrence of Louis Licari says that cutting long layers
into hair that is no longer than shoulder-grazing will encourage
any natural curl or wave. Layers also lighten the weight of hair so
it has gentle movement. She suggests using gel or pomade and
squeezing hunks of hair to lock in the desired shape.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Tavernise of the Peter Coppola Salon describes the change
as going from the look of satiny silk to nubby linen. To achieve
the effect on naturally straight hair, he suggests applying pomade
or gel to random strips of hair, twisting each one, and letting it
sit on the hair underneath, without combing or brushing. This will
work on any length hair, he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
