<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED IS BACK ON BOARD AS THE METS SPIN ALONG
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets' season has been a little like a
revolving door so far: The moment a player comes back into view, it
seems another one is gone.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of nagging injuries since spring training has prevented
Manager Bobby Valentine from using a set lineup every day. And it
is doubtful that Valentine, who loves to tinker, would have done so
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what lineup combination Valentine has put on the
field, the Mets have usually won.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at Shea Stadium, in a 5-3 victory over the Houston
Astros, Rick Reed made his return from the disabled list as the
Mets (17-9) were victorious for the sixth time in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had just completed their first three-game sweep of San
Francisco at Shea Stadium in 22 years, even though the Giants had
won six in a row and had the best record in the league coming in.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros then came into town on a four-game roll, in first
place in the National League Central, and boasting the best hitting
lineup in the league.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets made it easy on Reed, who was pitching for the
first time since April 11, by giving him a 4-0 first-inning lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno _ playing for Rickey Henderson, out with a sprained
right knee _ ignited the rally with a single and a stolen base. One
out later, John Olerud walked. Mike Piazza followed with a
run-scoring single off Chris Holt (0-4).
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura singled to load the bases. Mike Kinkade _ a late
addition to the lineup in place, this time, of Bobby Bonilla _ was
hit by a pitch to drive in a run. Brian McRae followed with a
two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who allowed five hits and three runs in six innings with
two walks and six strikeouts, needed every single run. A leadoff
walk to Ken Caminiti in the second led to a two-out, run-scoring
single from Holt. Richard Hidalgo followed a two-out bloop single
from Caminiti in the sixth with his sixth home run of the year to
cut the lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   But Cedeno hustled his way to a one-out double in the bottom of
sixth, stole third and scored on Edgardo Alfonzo's fly ball to
left.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell tossed two scoreless innings before John Franco
came on to record his 10th save in 10 attempts. So Reed, coming
back from a torn calf muscle, went to 2-0 on the year as the Mets
continued to apply pressure to the first-place Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Mets were without their starting outfield Monday
night. Henderson is out indefinitely with an injury he sustained
Sunday, and Bonilla, out since April 24 with a partial ligament
tear in his right knee, was scratched from the start when it rained
before the game. He wound up grounding out pinch-hitting for Reed
in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, General Manager Steve Phillips said: ``I think
we've played our full team only the first five days of the season.
That makes me hopeful that once we do get everyone back, we'll be a
pretty good team.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
