<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DULL SAYS HE WOULD MEND FENCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the most miserable time of Richard Dull's
life _ those months following the death of Maryland basketball star
Len Bias.
</P>
<P>
   Dull, the Terrapins athletic director at the time, was hounded
by reporters and wracked by guilt. Bias' death, induced by cocaine,
resulted in myriad investigations into the basketball program, all
of which embarrassed the university.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years later, Dull sat in the Cal State Northridge
athletic department conference room and admitted his mistakes. He
is one of four finalists to become CSUN's next athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we really had done was admit student-athletes that did
not have any chances of graduating,'' Dull said. ``My role in
encouraging their admission was a mistake. . . . It is one I'm not
going to repeat here.''
</P>
<P>
   After resigning from Maryland, his alma mater, in the fall of
1986, Dull worked in the private sector until July 1995, when he
became the director of athletics at the University of Nebraska at
Kearney. He moved on to his current post as director of athletics
at Moravian College in Bethlehem, Pa., in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the environment of college athletics,'' Dull said.
``The best time of my life was as a student-athlete at the
University of Maryland and as the athletic director at Maryland _
minus four months.''
</P>
<P>
   If hired at CSUN, Dull would be in charge of an athletic
department that needs to be rebuilt on a fundamental level. Dull
said the department is understaffed and needs to mend fences with a
faculty that feels alienated from athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be as active in the academic community as you
can,'' he said. ``Once people start to talk to each other, they
understand each other. There has been some unhappiness on the
faculty with the (sports) administration here. You take care of
your own house first.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as marketing CSUN athletics, Dull said he would reach out
to families, even though students would not be ignored. The goal of
the department, he said, is to capture the attention of a core
group that has roots in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Dull noted that when he took over as athletic director at
Maryland in 1981, about 3,000 students attended home football
games. By the mid-'80s, when the Terrapins became a nationally
ranked program, student attendance had increased to 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You build around families,'' he said. ``I'm not into
tailgaters or beer drinkers. People go to sports events to have
fun. You have to make it fun for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution to spreading the word, Dull said, isn't a mystery.
One of the jobs of the department is to speak directly to community
organizations and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is hard work,'' he said. ``There are no secret
plans out there anymore. A lot of people put ads in newspapers. I
regard that as the lazy man's way. Radio advertising, newspaper
advertising, TV advertising . . . that doesn't require much work.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Arias, the fourth and final A.D. candidate, is scheduled
for interviews and a public forum on Friday. The forum is scheduled
for 4:30-5:30 p.m. in the athletic-department conference room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-03-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
